<HEADLINE>
WIN WAS AS EASY AS 1-2-3 FOR CHIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ They knew what they wanted to do. It just
took them 30 minutes to get around to doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game against the Patriots, Kansas City coach
Gunther Cunningham demanded three things from his team.
</P>
<P>
   1) Run the ball successfully.
</P>
<P>
   2) Control the clock.
</P>
<P>
   3) Knock Drew Bledsoe down consistently.
</P>
<P>
   When it was all over, the Patriots left Arrowhead Stadium no
longer undefeated. The Chiefs had used their formula _ and a large
dose of luck when Adam Vinatieri's winning field goal attempt
bounced off the right upright with four seconds to play _ to claim
a 16-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe took a beating, climbing off the deck at least 16 times,
to rally his team to the verge of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   From the 29th minute of the game until the 55th, Bledsoe went
back to pass 14 times and had two completions for 28 yards. The
beating he took in that time took its toll. It was only when the
Chiefs' defense backed off in the final five minutes that he was
able to get it going.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Chiefs had put themselves in position to win by
controlling the clock for most of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played our game in the second half,'' said Chiefs general
manager Carl Peterson. ``We did what we do well. We ran the ball.
We put Bledsoe on the ground. In the first half we were fancy, and
we are not fancy.''
</P>
<P>
   This should have been a great win for the Patriots. Somehow,
after being pushed around for most of the second half, they nearly
won it, against large odds.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs are a tough team at Arrowhead. They orchestrate the
crowd of 78,000 well in the league's noisiest outdoor stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Patriots had six penalties and three
turnovers, yet they led, 7-3, at intermission. It should have been
more because Bledsoe missed Shawn Jefferson, who was wide open, on
a pass in the second period that would have put the Patriots ahead,
14-3, and made the Chiefs throw the ball to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   However, after gaining only 32 yards rushing in the first half,
the Chiefs pounded away on the ground in the third period. Their
big adjustment was to line up in a double tight end formation that
allowed them to overpower the Patriots along the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, they rushed for 108 yards in the final 30
minutes. This also enabled them to control the clock for 12:26 in
the third. Overall, Kansas City had the ball for 35:37, the most
for a Patriots' opponent this season.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Patriots defensive line coach Ray Hamilton
challenged his players to stop the run. They couldn't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs appeared to be putting the game away until they
started to back off of Bledsoe in the final four minutes. Then he
torched them for a touchdown and had New England set up for a
relatively easy field goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   He had taken a beating, but kept on competing.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to stop the Chiefs from getting a good pass rush in
Arrowhead. The noise makes it difficult for visiting offensive
linemen to hear the snap count. Patriots guard Heath Irwin jumped
two times in the first three plays. The Patriots were called five
times in the game for false starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs brought the heat all day. But Bledsoe held the ball
until the last instant on many pass plays, waiting for receivers to
come open, and paid the price.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the game, the Patriots outschemed the Chiefs, once
using a no-huddle offense, and Bledsoe still didn't have time to
get the pass away to an uncovered receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern for the Patriots after the game was their
run defense. Kansas City has a good offensive line and power backs,
but not much speed. The Patriots tackled poorly in the second half,
as bruising backs Bam Morris and Donnell Bennett broke tackles with
regularity.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots couldn't get the ball. And when they did, they made
more mistakes on offense (two fumbles, two interceptions) than they
did in the four previous games put together.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City started beating up the Patriots on both sides of the
ball in the second half. As the Chiefs rallied, the crowd got back
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they couldn't shake Bledsoe. Trailing by 9 points with 4:52
to play, he connected on 6 of 8 passes for 77 yards and an 8-yard
touchdown pass to Jefferson. Bledsoe got the ball back again with
30 seconds to play and moved his team 53 yards in 26 seconds
against one of the league's best defensive teams. But it wasn't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   After the game Cunningham told Bledsoe, ``You're as tough as
everybody said you were.'' Later, Cunningham said, ``That was one
hell of a performance. We beat the hell out of him today and he
kept getting up and making plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots lost, but they proved they could compete in one of
the most hostile environments in the league and still win. Even if
they lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
