<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HOPE TO STOP SLIDE AGAINST AVALANCHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's probably fitting that a team with the name
Avalanche is at the FleetCenter Monday as the Bruins attempt to
stop a four-game slide that has produced just one point this
season, Saturday's 1-1 tie against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get a lot better, I promise you,'' said Boston captain
Ray Bourque at Sunday's open practice at the FleetCenter where he
thanked a gathering of season ticket-holders and Corner Club
members for their support.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque and his teammates could take a big step toward keeping
that promise by improving their scoring (five total goals),
specifically on a power play that has gone 2 for 18 (including 0
for 6 against the Flyers).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of coaches are scratching their heads about their power
plays at this time of year,'' said Bruins coach Pat Burns. Indeed,
after Saturday's games, the Bruins ranked 18th in power-play
conversion percentage. ``We had some real good chances against the
Flyers. Sammy (Sergei Samsonov) hit a post there one time. And that
makes a difference between talking about it and not talking about
it. It's that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just something where there's a magic solution you put
out there and it works. You have to work at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns had his troops working at it Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time,'' he said. ``You don't want to
be too pretty. Sometimes, you just have to simplify it. Get the
shot on net and battle it out is sometimes the best way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   New Bruin Dave Andreychuk, the veteran left wing and career
533-goal man, along with Bourque, have been the team's power-play
scorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you want to play with regular linemates as much as
you can, and that was hard to do in preseason when we had a few
injuries,'' said Andreychuk. ``But I feel pretty comfortable here.
Sure, power plays are a big part of the game. There are a lot of
penalties being called and we have to get back to basics on our
power play.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk said the team has to generate speed through the
neutral zone. ``That's where it all starts,'' he said. ``I thought
at times we've had some good attacks, but I think at times we've
just been a little too fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your power play is struggling, the best thing to do is
just try to get some shots on goal. That's what we've got to go
back to. When Ray and Kyle McLaren get the puck on net, I've got to
be in front of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the talent on the power play. We just have to start to
work together a little bit more. Jason Allison was out most of
training camp (with an injured wrist) and we really didn't have
much time to practice it, and you have to practice the power play
as five guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns also is telling his team not to dwell on the slow start.
He pointed out Sunday that perennial power Colorado was 0-4 out of
the gate last season before getting on track.
</P>
<P>
   Burns reported defenseman Hal Gill, stunned by an accidental
John Grahame stick to the forehead in Saturday's game, was feeling
a little better but would be evaluated before game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a good challenge for us,'' said Burns. ``Colorado
is a good team, a top NHL contending team.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he believed the Bruins improved a bit in their 4-3
loss Thursday night to Ottawa, a game in which they squandered a
3-1 lead, ``but there are still some guys who have to be acclimated
more into our club, guys who don't have a lot of experience when it
comes to the way we play. I think the guys are OK. Everybody's
working hard to get out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we have to be more confident with the puck. We
started out strong again against the Flyers (scoring their only
goal 46 seconds after the opening faceoff). We have a lot of
confidence, but then we seem to wake the other team up and then we
seem to change our ways a little bit. We have to adjust to that.''
</P>
<P>
   One way, said Burns, is for the Bruins to get a little meaner.
``Sometimes putting the puck in behind their defense and going down
and running somebody over gets you into games,'' said the coach,
taking a page out of the ``Cam Neely How to Strike Fear Into an
Opponent'' Primer. ``We saw a little bit more of that in the first
period (Saturday night), but now we have to see it consistently
over 60 minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
