<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXOFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOUBLE JEOPARDY' BEATS `RANDOM HEARTS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Revenge edged out romance at the nation's
multiplexes as ``Double Jeopardy'' topped ``Random Hearts'' for the
top box office slot with an estimated $13.6 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,913
theaters during a healthy Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeopardy,'' starring Ashley Judd as a wife framed for her
husband's faked murder, racked up its third consecutive victory as
it lost only 20 &UR;  &LR; percent from the previous weekend. The Paramount
release has grossed $65.8 &UR;  &LR; million in 17 days and could hit
$100 &UR;  &LR; million by the end of its run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film is continuing to play very well throughout the
country,'' industry tracker Arthur Rockwell said. ``It's really
connected with Middle America.''
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing popularity of ``Double Jeopardy'' was a key in
keeping Sony's ``Random Hearts'' out of first place, where many
trackers expected it to open based on the appeal of leading man
Harrison Ford. ``Hearts,'' which also stars Kristin Scott Thomas,
took in $13.1 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,697 theaters as it debuted amid reviews
that were mixed at best.
</P>
<P>
   Sony reported the film played well in upscale markets in large
cities, including Los Angeles, and drew a predominantly adult
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opening for `Random Hearts' is not too shabby, but Ford's
core audience is action fans, and men were just not interested in
seeing him like this,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the
Reel Source forecasting service. ``It also had to compete for the
date crowd with `Double Jeopardy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said ``Random Hearts,'' in which the stars discover
their dead spouses were having an affair before dying in a plane
crash, has a somewhat limited audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie feels almost like it's from a different era,'' he
added. ``It goes to prove audiences do care about the material and
not just the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' second weekend of ``Three Kings'' came in third
with $11.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,942 theaters as the well-reviewed Gulf War
drama lost only 25 &UR;  &LR; percent from its opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Another critical favorite, ``American Beauty,'' followed in
fourth with $9.2 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,226 theaters as DreamWorks added 520
locations as it continued to maneuver the offbeat comedy as a
potential Academy Awards contender.
</P>
<P>
   Distribution chief Jim Tharp said the studio has no plans to
expand ``Beauty'' further for now, and Bucksbaum predicted the
film, which has nearly $31 &UR;  &LR; million overall, could play well into
next year and hit the $85 &UR;  &LR; million mark. ``I think they're keeping
the number of theaters low right now so the movie will stay fresh
in the minds of Academy voters,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's opening of ``Superstar,'' the latest in the long
line of ``Saturday Night Live'' spin-offs, posted respectable
returns in fifth with $9 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,943. The project, with Molly
Shannon playing her Mary Katherine Gallagher character, should
quickly move into the black since it cost a reported $14 &UR;  &LR; million
to make, a bargain-basement price.
</P>
<P>
   With five films taking in at least $9 &UR;  &LR; million, the overall box
office continued its impressive fall-season performance as it hit
$90 &UR;  &LR; million, up 20 &UR;  &LR; percent over the same weekend last year. The
year-to-date total has gone past $5.6 &UR;  &LR; billion and leads the same
period of 1998 by 8 &UR;  &LR; percent.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of solid holdovers took the sixth and seventh spots with
Disney's 10th weekend of ``The Sixth Sense'' grossing $5.9 &UR;  &LR; million
at 2,784 theaters and Sony's fourth weekend of ``Blue Streak'' with
$5.5 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,591. ``Sense'' has grossed $242.5 &UR;  &LR; million to
replace ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' as the 15th highest domestic
grosser of all time, and ``Blue Streak'' has hit $55 &UR;  &LR; million.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were 20th Century Fox's second weekend
of ``Drive Me Crazy'' with $3.8 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,234 theaters as the
romantic comedy dropped 44 &UR;  &LR; percent, followed by Sony's second
weekend of ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland'' with
$2.2 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,210 sites and Universal's fourth weekend of
``For Love of the Game'' with $2.1 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,414 locations.
Disney's second weekend of ``Mystery, Alaska'' nearly vanished in
11th with $1.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,704 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of art-house launches for well-reviewed dramas generated
strong returns, with Artisan's ``The Limey,'' starring Terrence
Stamp and Peter Fonda, earning $171,900 at 17 theaters and Fox
Searchlight's ``Boys Don't Cry'' with $66,000 at two sites. But
Miramax's expanded run of ``Happy, Texas'' was less impressive with
$160,000 at 39 screens.
</P>
<P>
   Business should remain at a solid pace during the upcoming
weekend with a pair of high-profile dramas opening _ Fox's ``Fight
Club'' with Brad Pitt and Universal's ``The Story of Us'' with
Bruce Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer. Bucksbaum predicted ``Fight
Club'' will easily win because of its strong appeal to young adults
and teen-agers and the memorable promotional icon of a ``Fight
Club'' bar of soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox has done a brilliant job of marketing,'' he noted. ``Women
want to see `Fight Club' because of Brad Pitt, and men want to see
it because of the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Final results for the Friday-Sunday period will be released
today.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
