<HEADER>
A2864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     10-11 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR PLAY FINALLY COST PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Your parents can tell you about the
consequences of your actions all they want, but you have to burn
your fingers in the flame at least once to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Your friends can tell you about the consequences of your actions
all they want, but you have to have your heart broken at least once
to understand.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell yourself about the consequences of your actions all
you want, but you have to end up in the woodshed at least once to
understand what the truth about consequences really is.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Patriots learned the truth. They got their fingers
singed. They got their hearts broken. They got taken to a woodshed
known as Arrowhead Stadium. Worst of all, they got themselves beat.
</P>
<P>
   They could have defeated the Kansas City Chiefs with a
late-game, 32-yard field goal Sunday but they didn't, losing a
game, 16-14, that they really never should have been in because
they persisted in the same erratic behavior that had dogged them
through a 4-0 September.
</P>
<P>
   For a month,the Patriots talked of how they had failed to play
up to their potential in victories over the wounded New York Jets,
inexperienced Indianapolis Colts, and just plain lousy New York
Giants and Cleveland Browns. They said, quite rightly, that they
knew they couldn't keep making these mistakes, missing these
opportunities and still winning these games at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday they learned they were right.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the snap wasn't quite right and the hold wasn't quite
right and so the kick wasn't quite right. It hit the right upright
and thus the Patriots lost on a glorious fall day when they turned
the ball over four times, committed six false starts, had their
quarterback sacked three times, and couldn't stop a running team
from doing what it wanted to do in the second half, which was grind
the clock to dust by doing the same to the Patriots' defensive
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned our lesson today,'' said defensive end Willie
McGinest after Adam Vinatieri's 32-yard field goal with four
seconds to play slammed into the top of the right upright and fell
to the ground the same way his team had.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't come into a hostile environment against a good team
and commit penalties and turn the ball over and not force turnovers
and still win. Good teams take advantage of that. We shot ourselves
in the foot too many times to win this time. It was all our fault.
Every one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was and so they lost. Lost as they secretly knew they would
if they continued to ignore the thin red, white, and blue line
they'd been walking week after undefeated week. Walking it until
they tripped over it because they tempted football fate one time
too many.
</P>
<P>
   They relied on Drew Bledsoe's magic, their own resilience, and
Vinatieri's reliability one time too often. So they are undefeated
no longer, victims of Vinatieri's foot, the Chiefs' legs, and their
own hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat's off to them,'' safety Lawyer Milloy said. ``We held
them in the first half and it seemed like we got satisfied with
that. We should have jumped on them, but instead we made it hard on
ourselves, and this time it didn't work out for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were saying we were the worst 4-0 team in sports but we
were very, very confident. We still are. Even with all our mistakes
we still had a chance to win with nine seconds left, but we'd been
saying this would get us if we kept playing like this and it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we didn't know we'd been beating ourselves and
then pulling the games out at the end. This time we bit ourselves
in the butt.''
</P>
<P>
   They did that by fumbling four times and throwing an
interception in the first half, thereby blowing an opportunity to
take control of the game away from a running team able to gain only
32 yards on the ground in the first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   They did it by letting an opponent linger too long this time,
linger until it took control of the game instead in the second half
by knocking New England's defense off the ball and Bledsoe on his
back before finally ramming it down the Patriots' throats. Although
the Chiefs would turn all that effort into only a 13-7 lead after
three quarters, they had controlled the ball for 12:26, leaving the
Patriots with only 2:34 to play offense.
</P>
<P>
   Then New England opened the fourth quarter with another long
drive that ended in a turnover. So by the time Bledsoe finally
threw a touchdown pass to Shawn Jefferson with 2:43 to play, and
followed up by getting the ball back with 30 seconds to play and
taking his team 53 yards in 21 seconds, it wasn't quite enough.
</P>
<P>
   Close, but not close enough this time to avoid finally paying
the price for cutting corners and tempting fate. Close but an
exploding cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give them credit,'' linebacker Chris Slade said of the
Chiefs. ``They stuck with their game plan. They didn't let us deter
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 30 seconds to go I had no doubt we'd win it. When Shawn
caught that pass (a 27-yard completion to the Chiefs' 14 with nine
seconds remaining) I believed it was automatic. But nothing's
automatic. You knew sooner or later the law of averages would catch
up with us. You can't keep skating by, skating by, skating by.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wakeup call for this team. I hate to see us lose to
get a wakeup call, but we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is do they wake up in time and go to work or do
they roll over and go back to sleep and miss the boat to the
playoffs they know they're well capable of boarding?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you keep doing the things we were doing _ the mistakes
and the penalties _ we were fortunate to be in a close game with a
chance to win at the end,'' Bledsoe said. ``We could have been
blown out by that point. We're too good a team to keep beating
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   So they keep saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CHIEFS-B     10-11 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CHIEFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSED FIELD GOAL HANDS PATRIOTS FIRST LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There were points handed out for bravery
(quarterback Drew Bledsoe) and for resiliency, for making Sunday's
game before 78,636 crazy red-garbed fans at Arrowhead Stadium so
close.
</P>
<P>
   None of those points added up to the 3 the Patriots needed with
nine seconds remaining in the game, however. Three points they
could, and should have, had when Adam Vinatieri missed a 32-yard
field goal attempt that clipped the right upright and didn't go
through.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe engineered another late fourth-quarter drive to put the
Patriots in position to win, but they lost, 16-14.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some of the luck had run out after four straight wins,
and they fell to 4-1, tied atop the AFC East with the Buffalo
Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it all measured and we had it measured well, we just
didn't do it,'' said Patriots coach Pete Carroll about the final
kick.
</P>
<P>
   The snap by Mike Bartrum and the hold by Lee Johnson weren't so
hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the ball off my thumb and I couldn't get the laces
around,'' said Johnson. ``It was a very poor hold. I couldn't get
the laces around in time and they were at 3 o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the kick looked as if it was going to sail through until it
took a sudden right turn and clanged away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could probably go out and hit about 100 of those, but I
didn't hit the one I had to hit,'' said Vinatieri, who has missed
his last three attempts after hitting his first nine, including
three that were crucial in first three wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible,'' added Vinatieri, who also missed a 48-yard
attempt. ``We needed it and I let them down. I thought it had a
chance, it was going right at it . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs coach Gunther Cunningham said, ``I never saw the ball hit
the upright, but Arrowhead is a great place. I know we're in
Missouri, but Dorothy's here, too. They have a heck of football
team. My hat's off to Drew Bledsoe. I don't know what other
quarterback would have survived that onslaught. He got hit I don't
know how many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was knocked down more than 10 times, was sacked three
times, and hurried endlessly. By halftime, he had stitches in his
chin, he had been pounded on the shoulder, and he was flexing his
knee. He threw two interceptions and fumbled once. He missed Shawn
Jefferson on deep routes three times, including one that seemed to
be a sure touchdown. In all, the Patriots had four turnovers to
Kansas City's two, and although it might have been Vinatieri who
missed the chip shot at the end, Bledsoe was more than willing to
accept the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam should never have been in the situation to have to make
that kick,'' said Bledsoe, who completed 23 of 45 passes for 334
yards and two touchdowns. ``My job as a quarterback is to hold onto
the ball, not give it to the defense. I turned it over three times,
and that makes it difficult to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe didn't complete a second-half pass until only 4:27
remained in the game. That pass was a 10-yarder to Lamont Warren
that started a 77-yard scoring drive and brought the Patriots
within 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive, Tony Simmons (7 catches, 107 yards), who was
filling in for the injured Troy Brown, caught passes for 13 and 39
yards. On a third and 8, Bledsoe made one of his best throws, an
8-yard pass to Jefferson in the left corner of the end zone with
2:43 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots elected not to try an onside kick. After the Chiefs
made one first down on the ground, the Patriots forced a punt. They
got the ball at their 33 with 30 seconds remaining. Bledsoe hit
Terry Glenn (8 yards), Ben Coates (18), then found Jefferson for 27
yards down the left side after he beat Eric Warfield. With nine
seconds left and the ball at the Chiefs' 14, the offense had set
the stage for the winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was not meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots guard Heath Irwin committed two false starts in the
first three plays and New England had six in the first half as the
crowd noise was incredible. The Chiefs threw all the blitzes they
possibly could at New England early. On the Patriots' second
possession, Bledsoe dropped back and was stripped of the ball by
Derrick Thomas, and it was recovered by KC's Chester McGlockton at
the Patriots' 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs settled for a 22-yard Pete Stoyanovich field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots followed with a 78-yard scoring drive, which
contained another false start by Irwin. Bledsoe also missed
Jefferson downfield, and a reverse lost 9 yards when Kevin Faulk
and Glenn muffed the exchange. But they muddled through and
Bledsoe, holding onto the ball as long as possible, lofted a
beautiful strike to Glenn, who turned James Hasty and went in from
49 yards away to give the Patriots a rare early lead this season,
7-3.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half, the Chiefs decided to go back to what
they do best _ run.
</P>
<P>
   They exploded for 108 yards, using four backs but mostly Bam
Morris, to keep drives alive and the keep the Patriots' offense off
the field. On two scoring drives in the second half, Kansas City
ate up 8:06 and 8:05. The Chiefs took the third-quarter kickoff and
scored in 14 plays, 11 on the ground, including Donnell Bennett's
1-yard TD run. They had a nine-play, 38-yard third-quarter drive
that set up a field goal that made it 13-7, in which six of the
plays were on the ground. In the fourth quarter another 14-play
drive, set up by Hasty's interception of Bledsoe, featured 10
running plays before Stoyanovich hit a 23-yarder making it 16-7.
What changed?
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the same things they did in the first half,'' said
the Patriots' Willie McGinest. ``There were no adjustments. It's
all of our fault. They just did what they set out to do and we
couldn't stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell said, ``They out-toughed us
in the second half. That's basically what it comes down to, but we
still had a chance to win a game in which we were minus-two in
turnovers in this place. Most teams don't come that close to
winning a game here.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest took offense to the suggestion the previous four games
had been more a matter of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're surviving nothing,'' said McGinest. ``We're fighting our
ass off every week. It's not like we're just surviving. We let them
score too many damned points, and that's why we lost the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
