<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-AR     10-11 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RED SOX FLATTEN THE INDIANS AND HOPE FOR MARTINEZ TO GET
BETTER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 27, 28, 29 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It rained all day and it stopped at night, and then
came the thunder and the lightning of the Boston Red Sox bats. Much
of it was from John Valentin, who had two home runs among his four
hits and seven runs batted in. But so many others contributed for
24 Boston hits in an astounding 23-7 thrashing of the Cleveland
Indians in Game 4 of the first round of the American League
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston run total broke a record for the most in postseason
history, beating the Yankees' output in an 18-4 victory over the
New York Giants in the 1936 World Series. Their hits total also
broke a major-league record for postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's barrage had the fans roaring in Fenway Park and
it left the Cleveland pitching staff stunned as these two
century-old rivals headed back to Ohio for a climactic Game 5 on
Monday night at Jacobs Field. Who knows who will pitch for Boston
against Charles Nagy of the Indians? Pedro Martinez, the Red Sox
staff ace who is due in the rotation, remains doubtful with back
pain that forced him to leave Game 1. Late Sunday night, with the
game well into its fourth hour, the 33,898 fans chanted ``We want
Pedro! We want Pedro!'' as if their voices could will him back to
health.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen, who failed in Game 2 for the Red Sox, is likely
to begin the game, but manager Jimy Williams refused to say for
sure before Sunday night's game. The winner of Monday's game meets
the Yankees in the best-of-7 American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   This game began with the American flag flapping outward in a
brisk breeze over the Green Monster, the big wall that dominates
left field in this lopsided park, as a man sang of bombs bursting
in air. Soon, Valentin and his teammates slammed balls against and
over the wall. They did the mash. They did the Monster Mash.
</P>
<P>
   They knocked out Bartolo Colon, Cleveland's best pitcher, in the
second inning. They made the Indians look foolish chasing their
rockets. Manny Ramirez, the big right fielder, ran into second
baseman Robbie Alomar with his knee and later used his leg to kick
a ball across the outfield. Ramirez, who led the major leagues with
165 RBI this season, has no hits or runs batted in this series.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, a 32-year-old third baseman, has had trouble with his
fielding, making two crucial errors in this series, one of them
decisive in Cleveland's Game 1 victory. But he had one home run and
three runs batted in during Saturday's 9-3 victory, setting up
Sunday night's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the lineup for Boston was shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, a
candidate for the league's most valuable player, who played in the
first two games of the series but missed the third on Saturday. His
right wrist, originally injured by a pitched ball a week before,
became too sore for him to swing the bat or throw the ball. In the
first lineup released by the Red Sox Sunday evening, Garciaparra
was not starting and Lou Merloni, who had two hits in Saturday's
game, was in his place. However, a second lineup was released a few
minutes later, with Garciaparra in and Merloni out.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Garciaparra told him he could play after swinging
the bat in a tunnel beneath the stands. Neither team took batting
practice on the field because of the rain, which began in the late
morning and continued throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hurt the kid,'' Williams said, referring to
Garciaparra. ``The trainer taped his wrist and he went out to the
tunnel and after he got done hitting he came back and said he could
play. So I changed the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Reed entered the game as Cleveland's relief pitcher
at the beginning of the fourth inning, he hit Garciaparra with his
first pitch, which appeared to brush the midsection of
Garciaparra's uniform. Later, after Boston's Jason Varitek homered
off him in the fifth, Reed hit Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hargrove, the Cleveland manager, was criticized for his
handling of pitchers in Saturday's defeat in Game 3. Sunday night,
he started Colon on three days' rest, instead of the usual four,
for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never done it,'' Hargrove said. ``I'm hoping for the
best.'' In words that might prove prophetic, he also said: ``Boston
has been very resilient all year. They are capable of winning three
straight. I don't think we can afford the luxury of holding back
our two best pitchers.'' Colon gave up seven runs on six hits.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Red Sox were starting Kent Mercker, a left-handed
pitcher, Sunday night, the Indians replaced two of their
left-handed batters with right-handers. Wil Cordero was in at
designated hitter for Harold Baines; Richie Sexson played left
field in place of David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians scored single runs in the first and second innings;
the Sox got two in the first, five in the second, three in the
third and five in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin hit his first home run in the first, driving in Jose
Offerman, who walked ahead of him. His second, also for two runs,
came in the third, a towering shot that disappeared between the
light towers into the night sky high above the screen that reaches
high above the wall. He also singled in the second and doubled in
the fourth, the double driving in three more runs to raise Boston's
lead to 15-2. Also homering was Offerman, a two-run bolt in the
second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
