<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC'S HASSELBECK, O'BRIEN STILL SORE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After navigating some extremely rough waters to win its
first four games of the season, Boston College's football team
appeared to be cruising toward a 5-0 start.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before BC's juggernaut sprang a leak in Saturday's
24-14 loss at Temple, which left the Eagles smarting from their
first loss of the season and starting quarterback Tim Hasselbeck
smarting from a mild separation of his right (throwing) shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom O'Brien said Hasselbeck was examined by team
physicians Sunday, and X-rays were negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no fractures, no dislocation, no sprain,'' O'Brien
said tersely. ``It's a mild separation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck did not complain about the injury when it happened _
``sometime in the middle of the first half, definitely in the first
quarter,'' the quarterback said. He wound up finishing the game and
completing 14 of 22 attempts for 146 yards and a 3-yard touchdown
pass to Ryan Burch that gave BC a 14-0 lead in the second quarter.
Hasselbeck threw one interception and was sacked three times.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said he was not yet ready to rule out Hasselbeck for
Saturday's Big East home game against Pittsburgh. ``The doctors say
there's a chance (he could play), but we'll see by Wednesday if he
can practice or not,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   If not, then redshirt freshman Brian St. Pierre will make his
first career start against the Panthers, who are coming off a 24-17
loss to No. 16 Syracuse last Thursday night. BC coaches have
prepared St. Pierre for this scenario by giving him time in all
five games this season.
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre has completed 14 of 20 passes for 175 yards and been
intercepted twice this season. Against Temple, he completed 6 of 9
attempts for 77 yards but was intercepted in the end zone in the
second quarter when Temple cornerback Fulton Fryar outleaped BC
redshirt freshman Jamal Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good throw, a throw he had to make,'' O'Brien said,
absolving St. Pierre of any blame for the interception. ``I put
that on the receiver, because if he can't come down with it, then
he's got to make sure that the man covering him doesn't come down
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   BC squandered its 14-0 lead when the Owls rallied for 24 points,
including 17 in the second half, to score their first victory of
the season after being shut out in three of their five previous
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, meanwhile, managed to generate minus-8 yards of
offense on their first three offensive series of the second half,
all resulting in three-and-outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was lost in the third quarter,'' O'Brien said. ``We
were never able to blunt their drives or to stop the bleeding . . .
We have no one to blame but ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien also was angry at the media over what he said was a
``perceived inference'' that he had not been forthcoming about
Hasselbeck's injury.
</P>
<P>
   In his initial postgame remarks, O'Brien told the media everyone
on his team had emerged physically sound. However, when he returned
to the locker room, the coach learned from team trainers that ``a
late injury was reported by Hasselbeck,'' he said Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   When Hasselbeck emerged from the locker room with his right arm
in a sling, reporters sought O'Brien for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Approached aboard the team bus afterward, O'Brien declined to
discuss Hasselbeck's injury _ or even to acknowledge that he was
aware of it _ deferring comment until his teleconference
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, at which point he lashed out at the media and
accused both Boston newspapers of calling him a liar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
