<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-VINATIERI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINATIERI KICKING HIMSELF AFTER CRUCIAL MISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Adam Vinatieri knows if you kick often enough
with the game on the line you end up feeling the way he felt
Sunday. Trapped.
</P>
<P>
   Pinned at his locker with his eyes glistening and the weight of
his team's failure on his shoulders, Vinatieri sat on a stool and
tried to explain why his latest kick, the one that could have won a
football game with nine seconds to play, failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri has won six such games with last-minute field goals
during his three-plus years as the Patriots' kicker. Until Sunday
he never had missed in such a situation, but if you kick long
enough the ball becomes a traitor. Sunday was Vinatieri's day for
that, which meant it wasn't his team's day.
</P>
<P>
   With nine seconds to go in a 2-point game, Vinatieri lined up a
32-yard field goal at Arrowhead Stadium that would beat the Kansas
City Chiefs if it went straight, as most of his kicks have. It was
a familiar position, a place he had in one sense or another been in
three times this season already without letting his team down.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the snap was off and the hold was poor and the
kick sailed an inch too far to the right, slapping into the upright
and falling to the ground. With it fell the Patriots, 16-14.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, Vinatieri sat in his locker surrounded by
notebooks and minicams, his voice choking in frustration and
disappointment as he tried to explain the unexplainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let the team down,'' Vinatieri said after missing two kicks
Sunday, including the potential winner. ``We needed it and I let
them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when it left my foot it had a chance, but it never
moved. I hit it hard enough but I just pushed it to the right.
Thirty-two yards? I need to hit every one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   As Vinatieri's voice choked with emotion, punter Lee Johnson
listened on the edge of a wall of humanity and finally leaned in to
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very poor hold,'' Johnson said. ``Make sure you write
about that. Adam won't say it, but it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he should make it, and I know he should make it, but
I didn't get the laces turned around. They were at 3 o'clock. The
laces were on the right side, and when that happens the ball tends
to go to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what happened as the ball sailed too far to the
right and slapped harmlessly into the upright as the Chiefs poured
onto the field knowing how lucky they had been.
</P>
<P>
   And how unlucky a reliable kicker named Adam Vinatieri had been
this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam has won a bunch of games for us in the past and he will
win a bunch of games for us in the future,'' coach Pete Carroll
said. ``We had a chance to win it and we didn't get it. That's all
there is to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you are Vinatieri, pinned in your locker with tears in
your eyes and the weight of your team's defeat on your shoulders.
Then there's a lot more to it than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
