<SLUG> BC-TEACH-AMERICA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM TEAMS RETIRED TEACHERS WITH NEW ONES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bernard Koblin returned recently to his old
stomping grounds, Pasadena's Muir High School, where he spent
nearly two decades teaching driver's education, general typing,
health and whatever else came his way.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a reunion that drew the 81-year-old and his wife,
Sadie, also a former high school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   They were there to serve as mentors to first-year teachers Judy
Hu and David Herman, both members of Teach For America, a national
nonprofit organization that recruits college graduates to become
teachers in underserved communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to draw on my experience,'' said Bernard, who will
be mentor to Herman, 22, a math and science teacher at Muir. ``If
it works I'll be happy. If not, we'll try something different.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple was paired with the new teachers through UCLA's
Center on Aging, which seeks retired teachers and administrators to
volunteer three or more hours each month in the Teach For America
program.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 32 volunteers are working with novice teachers in
five school districts _ Los Angeles, Compton, Long Beach, Lynwood
and Pasadena _ and more are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Compton, we have three or four people (volunteers are)
mentoring, so it's not the ideal one-on-one mentoring that we would
like,'' said Amanda Timberg, program director of Teach For America.
The organization has 109 new teachers in Los Angeles-area school
districts this year.
</P>
<P>
   A support system is available for teachers without mentors who
can attend special meetings, retreats and discussion groups
organized by Teach For America.
</P>
<P>
   The mentors aid new teachers by observing them in the classroom,
helping craft lesson plans and doling out advice on myriad issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadie's a godsend,'' said Hu, 25, an English teacher at Muir
who was paired with the former high school social studies teacher.
``She's my roommate over the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hu, who looks almost as young as her students, said she needs a
coach in a profession that already has been abandoned by two of her
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching is hard alone, and without support it's even
harder,'' said Hu, who delayed her entry into the profession for
two years after college so she could travel in Europe and Africa
and gain some needed life experience.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, she and fellow teacher Herman got the support they
were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   While Sadie observed Hu in the classroom, Bernard reviewed a
list of concerns with Herman. The new teacher's No. 1 worry:
classroom management.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's talking that I can't stop,'' said Herman, who already
has switched some students' seats to cut the chatter. He also is
struggling to make algebra interesting and relevant to students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a bunch who's in the middle, a bunch who I'm boring and
a bunch I'm losing,'' Herman said. ``Unfortunately, there's not 36
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard offered a few suggestions and sympathized with the
younger man who grew a beard to look older.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to do an efficient job teaching,'' Bernard said.
``My first year was difficult. I had no mentor, but I had a fellow
teacher to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Devastating'' is how Sadie recalls the first time she faced a
classroom of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what to expect standing in front of a group of
people,'' said Sadie, who taught social studies for 17 years before
retiring in 1988. ``Knowing you want them to learn something is
unnerving.''
</P>
<P>
   And being a mentor doesn't mean pointing out mistakes, Sadie
said, but serving as a confidante who can share ideas and help find
solutions to problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make you incompetent but competent,'' Sadie said of
having a mentor. ``I want her to feel good about being a good
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Koblins have retired from their high school
teaching jobs, neither one has given up the profession. Both teach
business courses part-time at Pasadena City College.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing to serve as mentors was an easy decision for the pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're either a teacher or not,'' Sadie said. ``If you're a
teacher, then you can help somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard views his turn as a mentor as returning a favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What goes around comes around, and the good I do will
return,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   To find out how to become a mentor, contact Mike Fong, education
coordinator at UCLA's Center on Aging at (310) 794-0676. To find
out more information about Teach For America, please call (800)
832-1230.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
