<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINDY MCCAIN RECALLS STRUGGLE WITH PAINKILLER ADDICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Cindy McCain bared her soul on national television
Sunday, telling how she was addicted to painkillers and stole pills
from the relief agency she founded.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a new admission for Cindy, the wife of presidential
candidate Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   More than frs ago, she spoke with handpicked reporters,
telling them that from 1989 to 1992, she was addicted to Percocet
and Vicodin and took drugs from the American Voluntary Medical
Team, which aided Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Cindy McCain told ``Dateline NBC'' that it was tough
to talk about her addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to relive a time in your life that you really
wish you never lived,'' she said. ``But it's also good for me to
talk about it, and I'm happy to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she admits she took the drugs from the relief
organization, she emphasized that no needy person failed to receive
medicine because of her addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that were suffering were never deprived of anything . .
. I took a good portion of (the drugs) but I didn't take all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   As John McCain makes his run for president, the issue of his
wife's addiction has remained in the background, though she has
been asked about it on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   For him, the ``Dateline'' interview served as a pre-emptive
strike against political opponents who might bring up the issue
during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, who also appeared on the show, said he should have
known about his wife's problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should've detected this earlier on,'' he said on the TV
program. ``Clearly there were signs. . . . I'd call almost every
day, and sometimes she would sound a little bleary or a little kind
of unconnected and I would think, `Well, she's just tired or
sleepy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He said he feels partially responsible for her problem, because
``maybe I was wrapped up too much in Washington and my ambitions to
pay as much attention as I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline'' skipped over some of the more gory details.
</P>
<P>
   The show failed to mention Tom Gosinski, a former AVMT employee
who accused Cindy McCain in a lawsuit of ordering him to conceal
``improper acts'' and ``misrepresent facts in a judicial
proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosinski had been fired from AVMT in 1993, and he alleged he was
let go because he knew too much about her drug use.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's attorney, John Dowd, charged that Gosinski was
extorting the McCains by offering to settle the case for $250,000.
That spawned an investigation by the Maricopa County Attorney's
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Gosinski's lawsuit was dropped and he was never
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The show also failed to mention Gosinski's charge that Cindy
McCain had asked him to lie to make it easier for her to adopt a
baby from Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, backed up by court documents, said at the time that
the adoption of Bridget McCain was ``proper in every respect'' and
saved the life of the child, who needed an operation in the United
States to correct a cleft palate.
</P>
<P>
   Gosinski also had credibility problems. In the county attorney's
report, several AVMT staffers said Gosinski had privately
threatened to blackmail the senator's wife if she ever fired him.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy McCain said she needed the extra drugs to deal with pain
from two back surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having difficulty walking and moving and doing all the
things, and with a young family that makes it very difficult,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The addiction also came during the toughest chapter in John
McCain's political career, the Keating Five scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that that had a very significant effect on Cindy,
because it was very terrible trial for us,'' her husband said.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of five senators who met with federal regulators on
behalf of Keating, a key figure in the nation's multibillion-dollar
savings and loan failure.
</P>
<P>
   The senator ultimately received a mild rebuke from the Senate
Ethics Committee for exercising poor judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she was worried about getting caught, Cindy McCain
said, ``When you're addicted, no, you don't think about things like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the addiction ended in 1992, where her parents
confronted her about her drug use.
</P>
<P>
   She told her husband about the addiction about a year later,
after she was contacted by the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration, which was investigating drugs missing from AVMT.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to know where the drugs were. . . . I told them
what I had done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed against her. She paid restitution and
performed community service, working in a soup kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his wife did something that was ``very wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't change the fact that she's a good mother and
she's a good person and she was a member of an organization who
went around the world and did many good things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy McCain said she still has something to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done good things,'' she said, ``and the best thing I've
done is go into recovery and stay drug-free.'' &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at (602) 444-8178, or at
bill.muller(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
