<SLUG> BC-RAC-JOCKEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN FOILS GOLD CUP FAVORITES 
</HEADLINE>
 CLUB GOLD CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rains washed away the hopes of the backers of
Behrens and Lemon Drop Kid Sunday, as long shot River Keen stole
the show in the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, the 4-5 favorite, is a Horse of the Year candidate, but
he could do no better than second after lagging too far back on a
sloppy, speed-favoring track. Lemon Drop Kid, vying for the
3-year-old championship, does not like a wet oval, and that was
further established Sunday as he finished fifth at 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   River Keen, a 7-year-old, was claimed at Hollywood Park Dec. 4
for $100,000 by trainer Bob Baffert on behalf of owner Hugo
Reynolds, who is in road construction, and the Irish-bred horse now
has earned more than $1.3 million for the pair. River Keen won the
Woodward at Belmont Sept. 18 at 5-1, yet he was given little chance
in the Gold Cup and was sent off at 12-1 ($26 to win) under Chris
Antley in the time of 2:01 2/5 for 1 1/4 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who has won 18 Grade I races this year, stayed at Santa
Anita to watch his top 2-year-old colt, Forest Camp, run in the
Norfolk Stakes, but he said River Keen nearly was scratched from
the Gold Cup. ``Seriously, we almost scratched this horse because
he was dead lame (Saturday) night,'' said Baffert. ``He popped a
quarter-crack (a tear in the hoof wall) last week, and we patched
it and it looked like he got a little bit of an infection in there.
They worked on it, and the crew did a really good job. I told them
that if he was still lame to scratch him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to put him into the race, and he was right there,
laying second,'' said Antley, whose own career was revived when he
rode Charismatic to triumphs in this year's Kentucky Derby and
Preakness. ``I found the best place I could for him on the track,
and he held smoothly and finished strong. I had a lot of horse the
whole way.''
</P>
<P>
   River Keen took over the lead turning for home and held off 7-2
chance Almutawakel, ridden by Jerry Bailey and owned by the
Godolphin Stable, through the stretch. Behrens, who was as far back
as sixth on a day during which few horses gained any ground, got up
in the last jump with Jorge Chavez to edge Almutawakel for the
place, but he was 3 1/4 lengths behind River Keen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behrens showed me that he's courageous,'' said his trainer,
Jim Bond. ``He didn't like the surface at all, and he still got
second. They won't beat him in the Breeders' Cup (Nov. 6 at
Gulfstream Park). He needed a race, so we weren't going to
scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   River Keen, who, like Lemon Drop Kid, will go on to the
Breeders' Cup, has a record of 9-3-4-1 this season and has been
first or second in five straight stake races. Can a reformed
claimer be Horse of the Year? If he wins the $4 million Breeders'
Cup Classic, why not?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful Pleasure, an outstanding 4-year-old, showed
Silverbulletday, the presumptive 3-year-old filly champion, her
heels as she led from wire-to-wire to capture the $500,000 Beldame
in a dazzling display. Ridden by Chavez, Beautiful Pleasure, who is
very comfortable over the slop, set withering fractions, including
6 furlongs in 1:09 1/5, and she kept going until she hit the wire 4
3/4 lengths ahead in 1:47 3/5 for the 1 1/8-mile race. Trained by
John Ward, Beautiful Pleasure returned $6.80 to win as the 2-1
second choice. Silverbulletday, trained by Baffert and the winner
of 11 straight races against fellow fillies, chased Beautiful
Pleasure every step of the way at 2-5 with Bailey, but could not
gain, settling for second. ``Jorge Chavez did a wonderful job
today,'' said Ward. ``At times, I thought he was going to let
Silverbulletday get to him. Beautiful Pleasure has such a big
stride that you just have to let her use it in the slop. The
interesting thing about this big filly is that she didn't slide at
all. We were going to run our race today, no matter what. We made
Silverbulletday commit to our style, rather than us committing to
her style. I thought Silverbulletday ran pretty good, considering
she had to do things she didn't want to do. Beautiful Pleasure has
earned herself a spot in that Breeders' Cup Distaff race, and I'm
really looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surfside, a beautifully bred 2-year-old filly, ran to her
bloodlines with a courageous victory in the $400,000 Frizette
Stakes. Darling My Darling, the 7-5 choice under Chris McCarron,
took over the lead from Surfside turning for home, but Surfside
surged back with Pat Day to prevail by a head at 9-5 ($5.90 to win)
in the time of 1:43 for a mile and one-16th. A daughter of Triple
Crown winner Seattle Slew, out of Flanders, who was a 2-year-old
filly champion, Surfside gave Hall of Fame trainer D. Wayne Lukas
his sixth Frizette winner. ``I was concerned about the mud, but it
turned out right,'' said Lukas. ``I give great credit to Pat Day.
When he has the right horse, he knows where he is at all times. Pat
always seems to save a horse for that extra jump or two. It was a
very, very positive sign for her to come back again; it bodes well
for her down the road. This will set her up for better efforts when
the races go two turns, such as at the Breeders' Cup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
