<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Oct. 11. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MCCAIN (Phoenix) _ Sen. John McCain's wife, Cindy, bared her soul
on national television Sunday, telling how she was addicted to
painkillers and stole pills from the relief agency she founded. It
was not a new admission for Mrs. McCain. more than five years ago,
she spoke with handpicked reporters, telling them that from 1989 to
1992, she was addicted to Percocet and Vicodin and took drugs from
the American Voluntary Medical Team, which aided Third World
countries. Though she admits she took the
</P>
<P>
   drugs from the relief orgon, Cindy McCain emphasised that
no needy person failed to receive medicine because of her
addiction. By BILL MULLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Phoenix) _ The last time Vice President Al Gore campaigned
in Arizona, he was jubilant because he and his boss, President
Clinton, were sweeping to an easy re-election that included a
historic victory in Arizona. Today, Gore will return as a
presidential candidate in his own right, making a brief swing
through Phoenix to scoop up campaign cash for his unexpectedly
tight Democratic primary battle against former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley. Gore, scheduled to arrive in Phoenix in the morning, will
tour a local school to highlight school overcrowding, then attend a
$250-a-person fund-raiser. Story by KRIS MAYES. Story will move in
the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   BIOSPHERE (Tucson, Ariz.) _ It's been a long, strange trip _
from desert ``eco-cult'' to reputable research center. But in eight
years, the massive glass-and-steel pyramid and eggshell-like
buildings of Biosphere 2 have emerged as a genuine educational and
scientific proving ground. ``I'm a very reputable scientist, and I
endorse 100 percent what's going on out there,'' said Wally
Broecker, a geochemist at Columbia University in New York. By KERRY
FEHR-SNYDER. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WATERPACT (Phoenix) _ If water is power _ and in the arid West,
water is everything _ the balance of power in Arizona is about to
shift. State and federal negotiators are working on an agreement
that could leave 10 Indian tribes in control of nearly half the
Colorado River water that flows through the Central Arizona Project
Canal. It's enough water to serve an urban population of more than
3 million, and someday it just might. The Clinton administration is
determined to see that the tribes get water. Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt has made it clear that he will use his authority to
take the water from the state if talks fail. Arizona officials
believe some sort of agreement is in everyone's best interest. The
tribes, which want the water to settle decades-old claims against
the federal government, likely would lease some of their bounty
back to farmers,who stand to lose the most in the deal, or to
cities thirsty to accommodate new growth. BY SHAUN MCKINNON. Story
will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
