<SLUG> BC-GORE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HOPES ARIZONA TRIP BOLSTERS CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The last time Vice President Al Gore campaigned in
Arizona, he was jubilant because he and his boss, President
Clinton, were sweeping to an easy re-election that included a
historic victory in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Today (MONDAY, OCT. 11), Gore will return as a presidential
candidate in his own right, making a brief swing through Phoenix to
scoop up campaign cash for his unexpectedly tight Democratic
primary battle against former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, scheduled to arrive in Phoenix in the morning, will tour a
locol to highlight school overcrowding, then attend a
$250-a-person fund-raiser at Eddie Matney's restaurant in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser is expected to push Gore's Arizona contribution
total over $250,000 _ compared with the $126,000 Bradley had raised
by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent Arizona poll, conducted by Arizona State
University pollster Bruce Merrill, Gore still led Bradley among
Arizona Democrats, 42 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's front-runner status appears increasingly shaky,
observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore still has a core amount of support here, and if you took
a poll you'd see him ahead, but I think you'd see Bradley closing
like he has all over the country,'' said Sen. George Cunningham,
D-Tucson, who has endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, recent surveys by pollster Earl de Berge have shown
just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that Gore has admitted this is a campaign has
attracted the interest of voters,'' de Berge said. ``And I think
many of them just have real doubts as to whether or not Gore can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, while still trailing Gore in polls, has planted a
foothold in the southern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   During a campaign swing in June, he wooed local Democrats in
Tucson, won the endorsement of that city's mayor, and raised more
than $15,000 for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a big hit,'' Cunningham said, noting that southern
Arizonans seem to like Bradley's cerebral, unapologetically liberal
style.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Gore's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the vice president say he will easily outstrip
Bradley's Arizona fund-raising totals. And he retains the loyalty
of most of the state's elected Democratic officials, they say.
</P>
<P>
   They expect voters to warm to his message, too, especially in
the wake of his high-profile makeover, which includes loosening the
stays on his once-rigid wardrobe and moving his headquarters from
Washington, D.C., to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no place to go but up,'' said state Rep. Ken Cheuvront,
D-central Phoenix. ``People have such low expectations of him right
now, they don't look at him as a great orator or speaker, when in
reality when you listen to him he does a great job. I think
people's attitudes will change when they see him in person.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Cunningham, Gore's face-off with Bradley is great
for Democrats, who get to pick the best of two quality candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both reek of substance, and they both are on the right
side of the issues most of the time,'' Cunningham said. ``And the
differences between the two are shades of gray rather than black or
white. I think that we could easily support whomever got the
Democratic nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Cheuvront suggested that Gore will grow stronger
fending off Bradley's challenge from the Democratic left-wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore was faltering, and this is making him become more
hardened,'' Cheuvront said. ``It will get him ready for a very
tough general election campaign.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
