<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS TRY TO MESH MISHMASH LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Apparently, the Sonics are serious about this.
</P>
<P>
   They really are thinking about going into the regular season
with guys who played last year in France (Emanual Davis), Argentina
(Lazaro Borrell), Turkey (Shammond Williams) and the Dominican
Republic (Fred Vinson). They join Russian-born Vladimir Stepania, a
one-year Sonic vet.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Seattle's team. This is Ellis Island's team.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics might finish in the bottom half of the Western
Conference, but they've already won the airline-miles championship
entering training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Stepania and Borrell (a Cuban refugee) are the only
foreign nationals. The rest of the guys are American, although
certainly not All-America in basketball, and not good enough a year
ago to stick on an NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that the bottom of a roster is rarely a factor
in a championship, it's also true that most championship teams
recruit internationally for the top stars, not for expatriates who
couldn't find work in the booming American job market.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer the Sonics found themselves combing the bazaars
of Istanbul and Buenos Aires, hoping to find someone (begin italic)
si habla (end italic) jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   After just a single display, Sunday's scrimmage at KeyArena,
it's hard to say whether the Sonics' shopping foray has added
merely a bunch of $5 Rolexes.
</P>
<P>
   What is apparent is that none of them are Scottie Pippen, whom
the Portland Trail Blazers recently acquired for a bunch of $5
Rolexes.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of deal-making that (begin italic) didn't (end
italic) go on in Seattle that puts a question mark on this season
bigger and more crooked than a Vin Baker free throw.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen makes the Blazers the third Western team that figures to
be almost unbeatable for the Sonics, behind the Los Angeles Lakers
and NBA champion San Antonio Spurs. Throw in Utah because Karl
Malone and John Stockton put the Jazz ahead 15-0 just by showing
up, and the Sonics for the 1999-2000 season are among many
undistinguished puppies attempting to get out from under the same
heavy blanket for the West's four remaining roster spots.
</P>
<P>
   As you may recall, the Sonics this summer in the free agent
derby struck out on plans A, B and C, then called a halt to
alphabetizing before they ran out of letters and had to borrow from
Cyrillic.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a mishmash, a collection of unproven youngsters
and vets on the downside, most of whom have never spent a moment in
the of Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   To suggest that there will be start-up problems this season is
to suggest that the New Carissa had a little trouble getting off
the Oregon coast.
</P>
<P>
   As it was put by forward Horace Grant, perhaps the premier new
acquisition, ``This is the first time in my 13 years in the NBA
I've started with a team that had only three or four guys from the
previous year.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the number is five, but three, Stepania, Jelani McCoy
and Rashard Lewis, were rookies. A fourth, Baker, was here but
proof came only via dental records on numerous scones.
</P>
<P>
   But tempting as it is to write off the season as Gary Payton and
the 11 dwarfs _ thereby setting a personal record of a complete
seasonal dismissal before the first exhibition game _ restraint
will prevail, at least for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   This roster is so convulsed that it is impossible to forecast an
outcome. Yes, it is a mishmash, but mishmashes make the playoffs in
the NBA all the time. They never win championships, but no one who
saw Sunday's unveiling, including the Sonics' brass, would offer up
the C-word sober.
</P>
<P>
   What the Sonics have a shot at is to be so completely different
than last year's team as to be moderately entertaining. They have
lost three respected elder statesmen in Hersey Hawkins, Detlef
Schrempf and Dale Ellis, but they have added a bunch of
streetballers who make up with youth and chaos what they lack in
elegance and two-handed chest passes.
</P>
<P>
   For what seems like the 15th consecutive year, the Sonics still
do not have a solid center. In fact, they really don't have a
center at all, figuring to share the pivot among forwards Grant,
Baker and Greg Foster, all of whom are mostly basket-facing jump
shooters.
</P>
<P>
   They don't even have a real front-line banger, although Grant
figures to have at least another year's rebounding and defense in
his 34-year-old body.
</P>
<P>
   What they have is a bunch of relatively little guys who like to
hoist and yap. A few of them even care about defense, which might
provide some drama until the ball is lobbed into the hands of
Malone, Shaquille O'Neal, Tim Duncan or Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, the Sonics appear to have assembled a bunch
of retreads who hope to hold the fort until McCoy, Lewis and
Stepania get mean and smart.
</P>
<P>
   In the little picture, without an acquisition the caliber of
Pippen, Mitch Richmond, Steve Smith or Penny Hardaway, the Sonics
are hoping for so much sizzle that few customers will notice the
kitchen omitted the steak.
</P>
<P>
   If you were thinking about going on a sports diet, the Sonics
might have a team for you.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
