<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BATHROOMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS TAKE AIM AT MESSY BATHROOMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Antoinette Reicheach visits the restroom at
Grant High School, she packs her own tissue and soap _ just in case
supplies run short.
</P>
<P>
   At San Fernando High School, student body president Natalie
Hernandez has made bathroom reform a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is never, ever soap,'' Hernandez said. ``The boys'
bathroom is bad, too. I just walk by, and it reeks of urine.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the state of campus restrooms in the Los Angeles Unified
School District.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by stopped-up toilets, empty paper towel dispensers
and graffiti-marred walls, some schools have declared war on messy
student bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how hard our staff works _ vandalism, clogged
commodes, paper towels thrown on the floor and put in the sink all
wet _ that takes staff time. That's a constant battle,'' said
Robert Hamm, deputy director of operations in the district's
Maintenance and Operations Branch.
</P>
<P>
   Although a small number of students vandalize restrooms, keeping
them clean at 532 schools districtwide is a Sisyphean task for
custodians whose ranks have been cut by 35 percent during the past
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   To have enough custodial staff to keep pace with the problem,
Hamm said the district would need to hire an additional 1,255
employees at a cost of $40.1 million in salaries, benefits and
supplies. The district now employs 2,300 custodians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody recognizes that we're drastically understaffed,''
Hamm said. ``The staff that we do have has a range of duties,
including restrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to Evan Smith, plant manager at Grant High School,
where graffiti and occasional trash fires keep custodians busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our toughest job, and it's the most important because
it's a health issue,'' said Smith, whose custodians clean school
restrooms after nutrition break, lunch and throughout the day as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Grant High School Principal Joseph Walker said he understands
the task facing school custodians. He would like to assign aides to
patrol the bathrooms and hallways in the school's two main
classroom buildings but said he doesn't have the budget to hire
more employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't maintain safety and maintain the bathrooms at the same
time,'' Walker said. ``I don't have aides to do both.''
</P>
<P>
   SMART RESTROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the district's Maintenance and Operations
Branch began a concerted effort to upgrade school restrooms by
outfitting them with ``smart technology'' _ sensors that
automatically operate urinals, commodes, sinks and hand driers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've really been a blessing for us,'' said Thane Opfell,
assistant principal at Monroe High School, which installed the
electronic sensors on urinals and hand dryers in two student
restrooms last year.
</P>
<P>
   Opfell said the automatic hand dryers eliminate the need for
paper towels _ the weapon of choice among vandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really makes a difference in appearance. You don't have
paper towels thrown on the floor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Funded by the district's maintenance budget, the improvements
also include new tile, paint, stall doors and partitions to
restrooms that need them. The cost to upgrade a restroom can range
from $7,500 for smart technology to $10,000 including paint, new
tile and other improvements.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the technology has been installed in 134 restrooms at 67
schools. This year, maintenance and operations officials want to
upgrade 100 restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe has also reduced vandalism by posting campus aides
outside the two refurbished restrooms during nutrition break and
lunch. Aides and administrators check other bathrooms throughout
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Opfell likens the task of patrolling student restrooms to
controlling air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get there regularly and on a set schedule to
monitor for graffiti and supply shortages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And to discourage graffiti, Monroe students are in the process
of painting colorful murals in restrooms throughout the school. The
newly refurbished boys' restroom sports an Aztec-themed mural.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has reduced tremendously the amount of graffiti,'' said
Liz Herrera, Monroe's student body president.
</P>
<P>
   GIVING CUSTODIANS A REAS
</P>
<P>
   At Taft, a series of vandalism incidents prompted school
officials to create an anonymous tip line that students could call
to report suspected hooligans.
</P>
<P>
   The approach has worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made all the difference,'' said Assistant Principal Jim
Szabo. ``We made it public to the kids that the only way to have
clean, safe restrooms that are well stocked with paper goods was to
eliminate students who have a different agenda than the rest of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   At San Fernando High School, students are keeping a close eye on
two new restrooms that have smart technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have been taking care of it,'' said Assistant
Principal Hewitt Hornbeck, who has staked out bathrooms to reduce
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day it was open, a small amount of graffiti was
found in one corner and toilet paper was heaped in a big pile in
the middle of the floor,'' Hornbeck said. ``The kids were so mad
because it was such a nice clean bathroom that they ratted on (the
vandal).''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, San Fernando's student body president, hopes other
school bathrooms will be refurbished if the two new restrooms are
kept in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to have dirty bathrooms,'' Hernandez said. ``With
the smart technology bathrooms, students see that it's clean and
they want to keep it clean.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, students and administrators said they will
continue fighting bathroom grime.
</P>
<P>
   The district's Maintenance and Operations Branch is considering
rewarding schools where restrooms sparkle. Some of the rewards
could include painting the restrooms and installing smart
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids feel like they need to vandalize the bathrooms.
Unfortunately we can't seem to eliminate the problem,'' Opfell
said. ``We have to manage it and take care of it with the resources
we have.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
