<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG PICTURE LOOKS FUZZY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Coaches always like to say after a game that they
won't know all the answers until watching the tape on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Well, USC coach Paul Hackett viewed the tape Sunday of the
Trojans' 31-24 loss to Arizona, and things didn't look much better
than the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think defensively, we missed a lot more tackles than we
normally do,'' Hackett said. ``It was our poorest tackling.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive tape was even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defensive front was more of a problem than we
anticipated,'' Hackett said. ``They had eight guys up on the line
and at times it confused us. We didn't block them particularly
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line after the video viewing? ``We just didn't play,''
Hackett said. ``Why? I don't know that (Arizona) is better. But
they were better on Saturday, clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   So where does USC go from here? The Trojans will travel to South
Bend for the unenviable task of facing Notre Dame (3-3) on a
two-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the big picture? Does USC fold it in, or can the
Trojans rebound after such an abysmal performance against Arizona?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get it together as a team and decide what to do.
As of now, we're not looking too good,'' freshman wide receiver
Kareem Kelly said. ``I know these guys don't want to go back and
play TCU (in the Sun Bowl).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing everything good in practice, but in the game we do
the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is flabbergasted that USC's offense could be, so, um,
pathetic. Especially when he looks around at the Trojans' wide
receiver corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the players, but we just can't get it together,'' he
said. ``Defenses cannot stop myself, R. Jay (Soward) and Windrell
(Hayes).''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly has a good point, but USC seems unable to turn its
reservoir of talent at receiver into touchdowns. Maybe they're too
hamstrung by the Trojans' anemic running game and woeful offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans ran for 45 yards against Oregon and 40 against
Arizona, if you take away quarterback sacks.
</P>
<P>
   It stands to reason they will be just as awful against Notre
Dame, which might be the most physical team on the schedule.
Hackett said no major lineup changes will occur in the backfield
this week, so the dreaded ``we must execute'' theory will have to
suffice.
</P>
<P>
   And there really is little hope in the short term that the
Trojans will improve offensively. The worst thing that may have
happened was scoring 62 points against Hawaii. It provided a false
sense that USC could move the ball.
</P>
<P>
   USC's offense has only outscored its defense 17-13 and 17-7 the
past two weeks. That's a major problem, and something has to be
done about it, or any bowl game might be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Soward underwent a CAT scan Saturday night and the
results were negative. He could undergo further testing this week.
Soward, who suffered a concussion, is expected to play this week.
</P>
<P>
   The news is not as good for right guard Jason Grain, who may
have torn ligaments in his knee and will undergo an MRI today.
``(The trainers) are nervous and concerned,'' Hackett said. Left
tackle Brent McCaffrey (sprained knee, ankle) is expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   Lineup change: Hackett said Windrell Hayes will start again at
wide receiver, now that he has recovered from his sprained ankle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
