<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE PLAY CALL ALMOST COST UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Emptying the notebook:
</P>
<P>
   When Oregon covered 84 yards in three plays on its opening
series, how many UCLA fans thought the Ducks were headed for 50?
</P>
<P>
   Questionable call: Had the Bruins lost, quarterback Cory Paus'
incomplete pass with just over a minute left would have been
costly.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it was third and 11. But with a 34-29 lead and 1:29 left,
UCLA was playing the clock, not Oregon. A running play would have
used 30 seconds, since Oregon was out of timeouts and couldn't stop
the clock. Instead, the incomplete pass to Danny Farmer stopped the
clock and gave the Ducks 30 precious seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt they thought we were going to run the ball,'' Bruins
coach Bob Toledo said. ``We tried to make a big play. We thought
they'd play for the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough for a ring: After a hapless opening series, the
Bruins played Rose Bowl-caliber defense.
</P>
<P>
   They held Ducks tailback Reuben Droughns to 43 yards. They
forced four turnovers. They unnerved quarterback A.J. Feeley with
two sacks and constant pressure. And with few exceptions, they had
solid coverage on Oregon's receivers. (Playmaker Tony Hartley had
one reception for 19 yards.)
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of Oregon's 29 points resulted from UCLA turnovers. The
Ducks scored one touchdown on Matt Smith's 81-yard interception
return and another after UCLA kickoff returner Lovell Houston
fumbled at the 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks went 84 yards on their first drive and 88 on their
last, which ended 1 yard short of the game-winning touchdown.
Otherwise, they gained a meager 271 yards, with one drive longer
than 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're developing an attitude, and we showcased that tonight,''
linebacker Ryan Nece said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes of brilliance: UCLA's offense scored 31 points and
operated at maximum efficiency for a 15-minute stretch late in the
second quarter and early in the third.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of the game, the Bruins sputtered. They did not run
consistently (2.5 yards per carry); two drives ended on Paus
interceptions and two on blocked field goals. The worst drive
started on Oregon's 20 _ courtesy of a Droughns fumble _ and ended
1 yard later, with a missed field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week: Paus was at his best in attack mode. When
throwing on first and second down, he completed 16 of 21 passes for
222 yards. When throwing on third down, he was 5 of 13 for 110
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week II: The Bruins have lost eight fumbles this
year, but only four by the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has fumbled once (Eric Whitfield after an
interception at Arizona State) and the special teams three times,
all Saturday: Houston's kickoff return, Ryan Roques' punt return,
and the blocked punt that bounced off Gabe Crecion.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Tailback DeShaun Foster aggravated his sprained
right ankle on his only carry of the game, in the second quarter.
He spent the rest of the night on the bench, his ankle on ice, and
is questionable for Saturday's game against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead: UCLA was the only Pac-10 team to play its first
two conference games on the road. It was a difficult task for a
young team with a new quarterback, but now the Bruins get rewarded:
Beginning with Oregon, four of the last six games are at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
