<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2920 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     10-11 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TRY OUT TRIANGLE OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ One week into its development, Project Triangle
finally was unveiled for the public Sunday night, albeit in its
embryonic stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, practicing behind closed doors since training camp
began Oct. 4, gave fans and media a glimpse of their training in
Phil Jackson's triangle offense, scrimmaging before a packed house
at UC Santa Barbara's Thunderdome.
</P>
<P>
   The starters looked sharp early on, but everyone looked sloppy
by the third 10-minute quarter, and Jackson called it a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hauled them off the court after three because we started
making turnovers, and that's a sign of fatigue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The purple team, led by starters Shaquille O'Neal, A.C. Green,
Glen Rice, Kobe Bryant and Derek Fisher, was especially effective
in the new offense early on. Rice and Bryant finished with 12
points each. O'Neal had 10 points and five rebounds but missed all
seven of his free-throw attempts, including an air ball. All
statistics were unofficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some real good things out there tonight,'' Jackson said.
``That doesn't mean that Shaq's foul shooting is included in
that.... I thought they organized their offense all right for a
week of training. They looked like they knew what they were doing
out there for a little bit at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Green had seven rebounds, and Fisher had seven assists and eight
points before leaving the game with left-knee tendinitis.
Second-year guard Sam Jacobson led the gold team with a game-high
13 points on 5-of-7 shooting, with a trio of 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Benjamin, trying to make the team as a backup center, had
six rebounds and five points. John Salley, attempting a comeback,
did not score and finished with two assists and no rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The learning curve is different for individuals,'' Jackson
said. ``I saw some very bright things out there that I liked from
some players, and other players bewildered me as to what they were
doing out there on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's major concern heading into the exhibition was not so
much whether his team was ready for prime time, but whether his
players could stick to the game plan and resist the temptation to
play to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's named the `Kobe Memorial Game,''' Jackson
quipped after the morning shootaround. Bryant shook his head and
smiled at the jab. ``I do that naturally,'' he said of his showboat
tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Almost here: It's not official yet, but Jackson expects Ron
Harper to sign a contract and report to the team by as soon as
Thursday, when the Lakers return to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The former Bulls guard has been rehabilitating his knee after
undergoing arthroscopic surgery this summer and considering
retirement. Jackson preferred Harper make it to camp but said he
didn't miss much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie doesn't need this. He's been doing this for about the
last seven years. He's got this stuff down,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Glen Rice's bout with knee tendinitis has been the
only significant injury in camp, but Jackson said the empty
trainer's room isn't necessarily a sign that players came to camp
in great condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might say ... that I'm kind of coasting with them, rather
than that they came in in shape,'' he said. ``I don't believe what
I'm reading in the paper about guys being in great shape. I've had
to nurse a couple guys through practices, and we're doing a lot of
teaching and a lot of conditioning ... so we're not running as hard
as a lot of teams run at the beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
