<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2935 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     10-11 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING NEW WITH USC WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's pass-happy edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   It's almost quaint the way Trojan forces annually find
themselves baffled and confused at mid-season.
</P>
<P>
   They wonder why they no longer dominate opponents, why they
can't beat a ranked team, why they can't win on the road, and why
they can't run the ball down the throat of foes like they did in
days of yore, when noble Trojans like Marcus Allen and Charles
White considered 1,000 yards a pit stop en route to a goal of
2,000.
</P>
<P>
   This no longer should be a surprise. USC has had two losses by
mid-October in 13 of their last 17 autumns, and gone on to lose
five games or more nine times since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   USC's negative yardage effort Saturday against Arizona (minus 20
rushing) was merely their third such game since 1996. They were
minus 23 rushing in last year's Sun Bowl against TCU, which hasn't
been a power since Davey O'Brien won the Heisman in 1938, and were
minus 14 against Washington at home in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   I can explain USC's problems in six easy steps, and the formula
isn't exclusive to the Trojans. A lot of the points apply to Pac-10
teams in general and explain why the conference looks to be in
decline.
</P>
<P>
   1. John Robinson left for the NFL after the 1982 season, on the
heels of NCAA probation.
</P>
<P>
   2. The NCAA leveled the playing field by limiting scholarships,
giving schools like Oregon, Arizona and Washington State access to
the best California prospects. And now those schools lose players
to Colorado and prominent Mountain West and WAC schools.
</P>
<P>
   3. The NCAA eliminated the source of many stud players by
implementing Proposition 48 test requirements. Schools like UCLA
and USC do not recruit Prop. 48 athletes. Others like Washington
and Colorado do.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prospects who normally would have limited their options to
the best Pac-10 schools had their eyes further opened to other
colleges via ESPN. Pac-10 basketball went through this phase in the
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   5. It became vogue to play defense. Skill players found
cornerback as much fun to play as quarterback or receiver. The
Bears' 46 defense was a cool attack defense, and it evolved into
the press defense (eight-in-the-box).
</P>
<P>
   6. Offenses turned to finesse systems, like the widely copied
49ers west coast offense, putting the seat of power in the hands of
the quarterback and placing the power tailback on the list of
endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the Pac-10 should be surprised by this. The conference
has been the predominant provider of quarterbacks for the NFL for
two decades. There are 17 former Pac-10ers on NFL rosters today,
and seven are starters -- Troy Aikman (UCLA), Drew Bledsoe
(Washington State), Mark Brunell (Washington), Chris Chandler
(Washington), Billie Joe Hobert (Washington), Akili Smith (Oregon)
and Jake Plummer (Arizona State).
</P>
<P>
   Seven others have started NFL games, too -- Steve Bono (UCLA),
Tony Graziani (Oregon), Rob Johnson (USC), Ryan Leaf (Washington
State), Chris Miller (Oregon), Rodney Peete (USC) and the ageless
Warren Moon (Washington) -- and Cade McNown (UCLA) may start next
week for the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, this group does not include the recently retired John
Elway (Stanford), Tommy Maddox (UCLA) and Mark Rypien (Washington
State), or Todd Marinovich (USC), who is in the CFL. ...
</P>
<P>
   While USC has been sending Peete, Marinovich and Johnson to the
NFL, it has been unable to produce a single running back of note.
Since Allen's 2,427-yard season in 1981, the Trojans have had only
five backs crack the 1,000-yard mark. The Trojan running game has
averaged less than four yards a carry in 13 of the last 18 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just USC with running problems. There's just one former
Pac-10 running back starting in the NFL, Washington's Corey Dillon
at Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The only other ex-Pac-10 backs finding even modest playing time
are UCLA's Kareem Abdul-Jabbar (Miami), UCLA's Skip Hicks
(Washington), Washington's Napoleon Kaufman (Oakland), and Oregon's
Derek Loville (Denver). Since 1987, the Pac-10 has produced just
one consensus All-American running back (Cal's Russell White in
1991). ...
</P>
<P>
   While USC muses on its problems running the ball, they might
also try to solve their problems defending the run. Trung Canidate,
not to be confused with Heisman Candidate, ran for 194 yards
Saturday. ...
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't be too quick to write-off the Rose Bowl chances of
any Pac-10 team with two losses. There's been four two-loss Pac-10
champs (1981, 1985, 1992, 1993) in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is 3-0, but it has road games at USC, Washington and
Arizona State left. Washington is 2-0, but it has back-to-back road
games versus Arizona and UCLA in November. Arizona is 2-1, but it
still has Oregon, UCLA, Washington and its annual brawl with ASU
left to play.
</P>
<P>
   USC (thanks to missing the Huskies) and Oregon both have the
difficult part of their schedules behind them. UCLA still has
Arizona and Washington left, but both games are at home and they
get a bye between them. They finish against USC, who they've beaten
eight straight times. ...
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of good seats are still available for the Nov. 26 USC
home game against Louisiana Tech. ...
</P>
<P>
   Is this the most exciting NFL season ever? Nine of 12 games
Sunday (not including Sunday night) were decided by three points or
less. On the season, 39 of 70 games (a percentage of .557) have
been decided by a touchdown or less. And 27 of those 39 (.692) have
been by a field goal or less. ...
</P>
<P>
   News item: Critics say Saturday's match between a woman and a
man was bad for boxing. Reaction: Oh yeah, like everything else
that's happened lately has been good for boxing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
