u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-WILLIAMS-B     10-11 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS HAS RISEN TO TOP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WILLIAMS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The announcement will come next month and, atypical of
any information associated with Jimy Williams, it will not be
surprising. Williams will be named the American League's Manager of
the Year. He will earn the award because he was able to do things
no one else expected.
</P>
<P>
   Most people would point to the Red Sox' 94 wins _ many of us
expected 20 fewer _ to illustrate Williams's unpredictability. But
that's only part of the story. The rest of it was on display Sunday
at Fenway Park. On a rainy day, Williams sat inside and talked
about his team. Well, not really. He was supposed to be talking
about his team. What he said, though, is what he wanted you to
know.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, not much. That's part of being a good manager in
the 1990s. The message seems to be simple. The less insight you
give to the public, the more successful you will be. Managers such
as Williams and Cleveland's Mike Hargrove have mastered this
unspoken rule. They are Artists of Misleading Information. Outside
of the park, that's called lying. But when you're here and you're
managing, it's called gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Take the tale of Nomar Garciaparra's wrist. On Friday, the
manager and the shortstop said the wrist was sore. They indicated
that Garciaparra would be given a day off and that it was not a big
deal. On Saturday, Garciaparra was out of the Sox lineup.
Williams's explanation was that the shortstop was hurt and couldn't
play. Sunday, the Sox distributed a lineup without Garciaparra's
name on it. Several minutes later, they revised the lineup, which
included their best player.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is he came into my office and said he was ready to
play,'' Williams said. ``He could play. So I changed the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have happened that way. But if I were you, I certainly
wouldn't bet on it. That's managing in the Internet Age. If you
aren't good at subterfuge, you won't survive in this game. Hargrove
has been with the Indians since 1991. He knows about misdirection
plays, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of this series, Hargrove announced his starting
rotation: Bartolo Colon in Game 1, Charles Nagy in Game 2, Dave
Burba in Game 3, and Jaret Wright in Game 4. The rotation was a
farce and Hargrove knew it. His hope was that the Sox didn't. It
was farcical because the manager knew Burba was injured (although
he never announced it) and was hoping that he could last six or
seven innings. He didn't. Before the game, Wright was told to be
ready in case Burba couldn't go. So Hargrove had no intention of
pitching Wright Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. His plan all along was to come back
with Colon.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the twang in his voice and the folksy tales he
presents, Williams is not given credit for being smart and clever.
I think the man is smart. Not only that, I think he controls the
media as well or better than media ringmaster Bill Parcells. As
Williams spoke in a room Sunday, Jose Offerman was sitting several
feet away, cracking up. Williams was in rare form, giving
monologues rather than inside information. And you know what? The
players love it. They trust Williams. They know Williams is that
friend of yours who holds onto a secret forever.
</P>
<P>
   So, predictably, this is what Williams said Sunday when he was
asked about Pedro Martinez's condition: ``See, we need to focus on
we only got one game here today. We only got (Kent) Mercker. You
know, we got our backs to the wall. We're in a one-game elimination
situation. That's where we are. That's all I can focus on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess, you know, when I was a little kid, I liked to play
marbles. You know, everybody has different games they like to play.
I liked to play marbles. A lot of you people think I've lost mine,
I don't know. I still got them at home in a big old brandy snifter.
I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   There was laughter, but no update on Martinez. That's the way
Williams likes it.
</P>
<P>
   As his marbles commentary echoed throughout the room, Williams
was asked to describe his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, is this finality?'' he responded.
</P>
<P>
   The questioner explained that, no, the query was not intended
that way. Williams then softened his stance and wound up talking
about talented speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we don't have that great orator in our clubhouse,'' he
said. ``That speaker, that spokesperson. But we've got a lot that
speak when they're on the field with the bat or their arm or glove,
you know? Kind of simple guys, but inside they're tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most telling comment the Manager of the Year would
make all day. His team is tough, smart, and misunderstood. So is
he.
</P>
<P>
   One day next season, Williams will be sitting in his office.
Someone who doesn't know better will ask him how he came to be
1999's best manager. He may talk about his team, marbles, and
people who know how to master English. Really, that would be the
most accurate response.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
