<HEADLINE>
STANLEY TERROR AT PLATE, AND ON BASEPATHS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-STANLEY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Historic baseball games offer all sorts of statistical
barometers. For the Red Sox, Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's 23-7 win over the
Indians was no exception. The number of runs, the number of hits,
and the number of players who contributed assigned Game 4 its place
in Boston lore and its rank among playoff games. But there are also
more subtle signs of historic success.
</P>
<P>
   How often, for instance, do you see the solidly built Mike
Stanley get a triple and infield single in the same game?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the stat of the night. I can't remember back to my last
triple,'' said Stanley. ``Eight years ago . . . was that my last
triple? Legging out a base hit, going first to third _ it's not
usually in my repertoire. It's just nice to be able to help
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Stanley finished his hitting spree, he had collected
five hits in six at-bats. The first baseman started with singles in
the second and fourth innings. The infield single came in the
seventh, courtesy of Indians third baseman Travis Fryman, who
stumbled trying to pick up Stanley's bouncing grounder.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Stanley was the beneficiary of poor judgment by
Cleveland right fielder Manny Ramirez. Stanley launched a fly ball
to the center-field gap. Center fielder Kenny Lofton and Ramirez
both chased the ball. Ramirez slid feetfirst to make the catch but
ended up kicking the ball deeper into the outfield, allowing
Stanley to arrive safely at third. The triple scored Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to continue to focus on what you're doing and go
out and have fun with it,'' said Stanley. ``You try to keep the
attack on.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final at-bat, the first baseman nearly had a home run. He
lofted a ball toward left field, came up a foot short of clearing
the wall, and settled for a stand-up double.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his Red Sox teammates, Stanley had respectable production
early in the series. The first baseman/designated hitter has played
all four games of the Division Series, posting a .625 average and
going 10 for 16. His series batting average leads all Red Sox
players who have batted more than once.
</P>
<P>
   He generated the most offense for Boston in Game 1, going 3 for
4 and driving in Nomar Garciaparra in the fourth inning. All of the
hits were singles off Indians' starter Bartolo Colon. But that
chilly night in Cleveland, Stanley suffered through questions about
an underthrown ball by John Valentin that he failed to scoop for a
crucial out.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley has seen a steady improvement throughout the series by
his Boston teammates as they have adjusted to the pressure and
excitement of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as a team guys got comfortable,'' said Stanley. ``That
game (Saturday) they started breaking out and feeling good about
themselves. Actually, I saw a lot of good swings in the second game
that we lost. You could sense and see and feel guys starting to
feel a little more comfortable at the plate. Obviously, the last
two games, they've been able to produce. You just see the steady
incline of people feeling better about themselves at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox finished their historic Game 4, the most
important, though unrecorded, measurement may have been the team's
comfort level. And fittingly, Stanley looked pretty comfortable
legging out the infield hit and standing at third after a rare
triple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
