<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-COLON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTLESS NIGHT FOR COLON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The second-guessing began as soon as the bottom of the
Red Sox order tattooed Bartolo Colon in the second inning
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. Colon already had given up a two-run homer to John
Valentin. Trot Nixon, the No. 9 hitter, had belted one off the wall
in center. So why was Colon still in the ballgame to give up a
two-run shot to Jose Offerman?
</P>
<P>
   Probably because Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove has known for a
couple of weeks what the rest of the world found out over the
weekend: The Indians have no bullpen. And with Dave Burba hurt and
Jaret Wright gone wrong, they have only two starters.
</P>
<P>
   So when Hargrove sent Colon to the mound on three days' rest for
the first time in his career, it was the inspiration for a
conflagration. ``Everything that we threw up there, they hit,''
Hargrove shrugged after the Red Sox had battered half a dozen of
his pitchers for a postseason-record 23 runs. ``When it came down,
it wasn't where we were standing.''
</P>
<P>
   League rules say fielders can't cling to the top of the
scoreboard or set up shop in the screen. That's where the Indians
would have had to be playing Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, as Boston teed off on
everybody from Colon to Steve Karsay to Steve Reed to Paul
Assenmacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing,'' said catcher Sandy Alomar, who kept
standing up and pulling off his mask to watch balls disappear into
the murk. ``It was humiliating.''
</P>
<P>
   No pitching staff in baseball history ever had given up 23 runs
in a postseason game. Cleveland's has conceded 32 in two. Now
Hargrove has to use Charles Nagy on three days' rest in Monday
night's all-the-marbles finale at Jacobs Field. And hope that he
can go at least seven innings. ``It's not really great to be in
this position,'' said Nagy. ``But there's nothing else I can do
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of a breezy summer, when the Indians were miles ahead
of the rest of the American League Central, they had a five-man
rotation. Now, with Doc Gooden off the postseason roster, Wright a
battered shadow of his former self, and Burba doubtful, Cleveland
suddenly has an empty cupboard.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove knew better than anyone that his pitching staff isn't
nearly as dominant as it might have looked while Cleveland was
shutting down Boston in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Indians won the division by 21 1/2 games, they were a
.500 club from September on. Gooden won only one game after May 18
and was put on the shelf. Wright went on the disabled list twice
and was 1-3 with a 6.65 ERA after Labor Day. And Burba, their best
pitcher down the stretch (7-3 from Aug. 1 on), was hurting.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Cleveland cruised through the first two games
with Colon and Nagy, Hargrove knew the next two would be rough
sledding. He knew Burba could offer only limited innings in Game 3.
And instead of starting Wright Sunday, which was the original plan,
Hargrove went with Colon _ and watched him implode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bart could not get his breaking stuff over and had to rely
heavily on his fastball,'' the manager said after Colon was tagged
for seven runs without getting an out in the second inning. ``I
don't care how hard you throw the ball, if you throw a lot of
fastballs and can't get your breaking stuff over, big-league
hitters are going to get to you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a hanging breaking ball to John Valentin in the first
inning that was the red flag. ``If you don't make a good pitch, the
guy's going to hit it hard the way Valentin did,'' Colon said.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove downplayed his starter's three days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the short rest had anything to do with it,'' he
said. ``You know, Bartolo's a good competitor, he's a strong young
man. And, you know, I think it was just one of those nights for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Colon get hammered, is Nagy worried about
starting Monday night's finale on short rest, too?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really,'' he said. ``I'm a different type of pitcher
than Bartolo. He's a power pitcher, so when he gets more rest he's
stronger out there. Myself, I'm a sinkerball guy. The less rest you
have, the better your sinker's going to be. That's what they say,
anyway. We'll see (Monday night).''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was the same in the Fens for this suddenly Lost Tribe.
``The good part about it is that none of these runs count
tomorrow,'' mused Alomar. ``Tomorrow is 0-0.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
