<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-CORDERO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORDERO HEARS IT FROM FENWAY CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at Fenway Park, Wil Cordero made his
first start of the Division Series. But despite considerably less
playoff time than his teammates, the designated hitter came to the
plate with a lot more history.
</P>
<P>
   The loud booing that followed the announcement of the fifth
player in the Indians' order had nothing to do with any at-bats
against the Red Sox. A pinch-hit performance in Game 1 was not
enough to encourage the crowd's intense displeasure. The fans were
not booing because of anything that happened on the field. The
vitriol related to a time when Cordero played for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On June 11, 1997, when he was an outfielder for the Red Sox,
Cordero was arrested on charges of beating his wife and threatening
to kill her. He eventually pleaded guilty to domestic abuse charges
and received a suspended sentence. The Red Sox released Cordero in
September. Ever since, he has been persona non grata in the Hub.
When he returned with the Chicago White Sox in 1998, he was lustily
booed. And until March, 1999, his baseball career suffered as a
result of his personal troubles.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the support of Robbie and Sandy Alomar, Cordero
has resurfaced with Cleveland and resurrected his career. Fellow
Puerto Rican Sandy Alomar spoke to Cordero after a Puerto Rican
League game and learned that the outfielder was jobless. Then the
elder Alomar brother talked with Indians' general manager John Hart
about bringing Cordero to the club. In February, the player with a
troubled Boston past signed a one-year, non-guaranteed contract.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove had his doubts about
Cordero, but the Alomar brothers eased his mind. Now, Hargrove is
an avid supporter of the 27-year-old designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wil's a baseball player,'' said the manager, addressing his
decision to start Cordero in Game 4. ``Wil has been good for us,
you know, obviously his problems here in Boston were publicized.
But that's _ that's hopefully behind him. I think he's taken steps
to remedy the situation. But it has no consideration as far as _ or
bearing on _ him either being in the lineup or not being in the
lineup. Wil Cordero is a very good baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, a productive season was cut short in June after
Cordero broke his left wrist against Milwaukee and was placed on
the 60-day disabled list. Before the injury, he earned the Tribe's
designated hitter/left-field assignment over Richie Sexson after he
hit .405 in spring training with 10 doubles, 4 home runs, and 20
RBIs. Cordero continued making contributions by hitting .319 in
April with 7 doubles, 2 home runs, and 11 RBIs. He was activated in
early September and apppeared in 14 games before the close of the
regular season, recording a .238 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero still harbors ill will toward the Red Sox, claiming the
organization caved in to public pressure when it dealt with his
arrest. In the Division Series, he has had two opportunities to
take his anger out on the team that released him two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He had a pinch-hit single with one out in the ninth inning of
Game 1. The hit put runners on first and second. And after a walk
to Richie Sexson, Travis Fryman hit the single to left to win the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the boos, Cordero had two singles and a walk through
five innings Sunday night, then hit a solo home run in the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
