<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2942 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EAGLES-HN     10-11 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EAGLES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Philadelphia Eagles went 18 consecutive
quarters without scoring an offensive touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 19th quarter, they crossed the goal line to beat the
Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   It took only one trip to the end zone for one of the worst teams
in the NFL to make laughingstocks of the previously undefeated
Cowboys. The Cowboys sat on a 10-point halftime lead, only to watch
their defense surrender 13 points in the fourth quarter for a 13-10
embarrassment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first victory for the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams would go out there and do it, close the deal
early,'' Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith said. ``So we've got a
ways to go as a ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is the only other team to watch the Eagles' offense
score, in the first quarter of the opening game. Tampa Bay, Buffalo
and the New York Giants shut out the offense that ranked next to
last in the NFL coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   But one large gap in Dallas' zone defense allowed Charles
Johnson to breeze 28 yards into the end zone with 1:07 to play. The
Dallas defense, which had dominated so thoroughly in the first
half, could only watch, dazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unspeakable and unthinkable,'' cornerback Deion Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly considering the early statistics:
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles didn't cross midfield until 3:19 remained in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia picked up its only first down of the first half
after the two-minute warning before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   That final drive of the first half was for a grand total of 10
yards. The Eagles' other five possessions in the half netted
minus-one, seven, two, six and one yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This win was badly needed,'' Philadelphia running back Duce
Staley said. ``(It) was almost like being in a desert with no water
and no signs of water. Coming out of the locker room I saw a spark,
and that's something I haven't seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (3-1) never even had a flicker. Their 10 points came
on halfhearted drives that totaled only 52 yards. They scored on
their second possession of the day thanks to field position,
getting the ball at the Eagles' 29. They essentially floundered for
three plays, then turned to Richie Cunningham for a 42-yard field
goal to go on top 3-0 with 7:07 remaining in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas didn't add to its lead until the second quarter, when it
drove 48 yards on five plays. Rocket Ismail caught a 17-yard pass,
and Smith sprinted for a 22-yard gain. Quarterback Troy Aikman then
connected with Smith on a nine-yard TD strike for a 10-0 edge with
11:35 remaining in the half.
</P>
<P>
   It proved to be all the scoring they would muster.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there were a couple of sustained drives. The Cowboys marched
73 yards to the Eagles' one, but Smith fumbled at the goal line at
the end of the first quarter. They trudged 32 yards on eight plays
early in the second period, but Troy Vincent leaped in front of
Ismail in the end zone for an interception. The rest of the
Cowboys' offense consisted of five punts and another interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a nice job of getting underneath our intermediate
stuff and forcing us to come underneath,'' Aikman said. ``We just
failed to establish anything as far as getting momentum going.
There were things that hurt each drive and kept us from getting
first downs on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they were playing without Michael Irvin, who suffered
trauma to the neck and spine after a first-quarter hit and spent
the night in a hospital. They were playing without Mark Stepnoski,
who left in the second quarter with a lower back contusion and did
not return. They were playing without Everett McIver, who was on
the inactive list with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, they were playing without that spark that
Philadelphia (1-4) somehow found at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my responsibility to get these guys ready, and we didn't
go out and play well enough to win the ballgame,'' Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey said. ``Entirely too sporadic. We could not sustain
anything, and that's what killed us today. We really struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' comeback began in the fourth quarter, when they
mounted back-to-back field-goal drives to narrow the gap to 10-6
with 5:42 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Following the second field goal, the Eagles forced the Cowboys
to go three-and-out. Smith gained eight yards on first down but was
hit at and behind the line on his next two carries, and Toby Gowin
punted from his 34.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles then moved from their 28 to the Dallas 28 in six
plays. Quarterback Doug Pederson, who had been booed since the
first half, hit a wide-open Johnson in the middle of the field. He
dived into the end zone just as the Dallas secondary converged on
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope we're hurt,'' Gailey said. ``I would hope we're
upset. But I don't think we're rock bottom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
