<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-11 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LARRY Dierker not only understands the second-guessing, he has
embraced it and even taken part over the years as an Astros
broadcaster and guest Chronicle columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Second-guessing is what makes baseball baseball, he says.
Baseball became America's pastime because millions have passed the
time cursing their favorite team, questioning the manager's moves
and talking about next year.
</P>
<P>
   But even Dierker was getting testy, a bit put out, when many
moves he made in the final two games of the Braves series were
questioned not just by you or me but by players and general manager
Gerry Hunsicker.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it would take to motivate his team after losing the
decisive third game of the Division Series, Dierker quipped sharply
about having a pep rally. After the clinching Game 4, Dierker
clearly was agitated over being questioned about how he handled the
pitching, saying starter Shane Reynolds didn't look as if he wanted
to be in the game anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds shot back with a few barbs directed at the skipper, and
star first baseman Jeff Bagwell called Dierker's comments ``weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Astros are talking about next year yet again. And if
you think it is only Bagwell and Craig Biggio whose legacy on this
team might hinge on the coming season, you're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If you think it's only Moises Alou's mysterious absence from the
bench during the playoffs or Derek Bell's absence of production
that might be addressed during the offseason, you're leaving
someone very important out of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, Dierker will be pushing the buttons yet again when
this gang takes its show to the Gashouse next season. And he should
be.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you can question Dierker's decision to pitch to the
Astro-killer, Brian Jordan, in Game 3. Maybe you didn't like much
of what you saw from Dierker in Game 4 or throughout the playoffs.
I didn't, either.
</P>
<P>
   But Dierker should be there next spring because he somehow
guided this team to a third division title despite so many setbacks
and injuries, including his own life-threatening condition. Over
the course of the season, Dierker made more moves that proved to be
right than wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He and pitching coach Vern Ruhle helped make the Astros' staff
one of the strongest in the league, and even if some in the
clubhouse quietly questioned his decision-making, it's difficult to
argue with the results.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because of the third straight early exit from the
playoffs, Dierker figures to have the microscope focused on his
moves more than ever in 2000. And that's the way it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Consider next season Dierker's most important as Astros manager.
</P>
<P>
   The division race figures to be as heated as it was this season,
considering the young and hungry Reds, a talented Pirates team, the
unpredictable Cardinals and perhaps even Sammy Sosa's Cubs, who
figure to be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting to the playoffs in 2000 will challenge Dierker. And
once there, if the Astros can make it for a fourth straight year,
it won't be just Biggio and Bagwell hoping to change their
postseason fate.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker must do more. He is the most likable of men and is
deservedly revered in this city. He is as much the Astros as
Bagwell, Biggio, Jimmy Wynn, Nolan Ryan, Mike Scott, Jose Cruz or
any figure in the franchise's history.
</P>
<P>
   The way Dierker came back from his ugly grand mal seizure in
June, becoming even more of a sentimental favorite and returning to
the bench long before anyone expected, enamored him to millions.
</P>
<P>
   He was there when the Astrodome opened, he was there when it
closed, and in some capacity he has been there throughout the
Astros' history.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell and Biggio have heard recent cries of the club having to
do something _ make a change _ if it ever is going to get over its
playoff frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the answer to get rid of Bidge and Bags?'' Bagwell said.
``I don't know. Maybe. But that doesn't mean you'll do better
without us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros frankly would be silly to move their cornerstone
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt as confident on my last at-bat, when I was
2-for-whatever, as I ever have,'' Bagwell said. ``I thought I would
do something big, but it just didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker surely felt as confident as ever with his playoff moves,
too. It just didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   Is the answer to get rid of Dierker? No. He has earned as much
of a chance as anyone to be there at Enron Field's opening next
year. But if the division race slips away or another playoff series
goes the way of the last three, surely more than a few fans will be
letting off some steam at the Gashouse.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes baseball baseball. And it's what will make the
2000 season probably the most critical of Dierker's managing
career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
