<HEADLINE>
RED SOX ATTACK ANCHORED BY LIGHTEST SWINGERS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-LINEUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A year ago, the postmortems of the Red Sox' Division
Series loss to the Cleveland Indians pointed a finger at the bottom
of the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   In that four-game series, Boston's Nos. 5 through 9 hitters went
a meager 10 for 74, a major power outage.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening two losses of this series in Cleveland, the
bottom half of the order _ along with the top _ was silent again.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change in Saturday night's 9-3 victory, in which
the lower half of the order banged out five hits.
</P>
<P>
   And in Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's 23-6 rout at Fenway Park, the Red Sox'
power surge was a sight to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Murder's Row of Troy O'Leary, Mike Stanley, Jason
Varitek, Darren Lewis, and Trot Nixon, which pounded out 14 hits,
drove in seven runs, and was a pivotal part of the explosion that
sparked Boston to a 15-2 lead after four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive was the 7-8-9 trio of Varitek, Lewis, and Nixon,
who had a batting line to die for: nine hits in 13 at-bats with
five extra-base hits, nine RBIs, and 11 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   By themselves, the lightly regarded bottom third of the batting
order contributed more offensive in one game than it did in an
entire series a year ago and out-hit the entire Indian lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way was Varitek, who went 4 for 5 with a single, two
doubles, and a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis had three hits and was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, batting in the ninth slot, had a two-run double in the
first inning, a run-producing sacrifice fly in the third, and a
two-out, two-run double in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 batter Stanley had five hits _ three singles, a double,
and a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Only O'Leary, who was hitless in four at-bats, failed to get on
base.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, the Red Sox ruled, and afterward the confidence
in the clubhouse was palpable. And much of the team's offensive
outburst (32 runs in two games) came from the part of the order
once called the Red Sox dead zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to be aggressive at the plate,'' said Varitek. ``We had
to take some of the pressure off our big guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a sense of optimism up and down the lineup. ``You
get in a groove and it does seem contagious,'' said Nixon, who had
five RBIs. ``Now we have to go out and do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
