<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-RANGERS-HNS &LR;      10-11 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ARLINGTON _ When the Texas Rangers were swept by the New York
Yankees in the first round of the American League playoffs a year
ago, the Rangers' frustration was tempered by the knowledge they
had lost to a team that was one of the best in recent years, if not
all time, and a sense their day would come.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being swept by the Yankees this season, the Rangers had a
harder time finding reasons to look on the bright side. This year's
postseason train wreck left the Rangers dazed, confused and
embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we just wanted to get to the playoffs,'' shortstop
Royce Clayton said. ``This year, getting to the playoffs was not
our goal. Getting to the World Series was our goal. It's very
disappointing, but we have to deal with it. We're going to have to
deal with it again next year, and that's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years without a postseason appearance, the Rangers
broke through in 1996 but were ousted in the Division Series in
four games by the Yankees, the eventual World Series champions.
Returning to the playoffs last year, the Rangers were swept in the
Division Series by a Yankees team that had won 114 regular-season
games and would capture another World Series.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers and Yankees were paired again this year,
conventional wisdom spoke of a tighter series. The Rangers had
enhanced a potent offense with one of the best hitters in the game,
Rafael Palmeiro, and had won 95 games, a franchise record. The
Yankees (98-64) had compiled the best record in the American League
but had not been the machine they had been the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers players talked openly of this being the year they would
beat the Yankees, but the outcome of Rangers-Yankees 1999 was
eerily identical to Rangers-Yankees 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Rangers hit .152 during the Division Series and scored
one run _ Juan Gonzalez's home run in the fourth inning of Game 2 _
pretty much duplicating what they did in '98, when they hit .141
and scored once.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Rangers produced even a hint of an offense, they might
have been competitive, because their starting pitching was
excellent.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that hit .293 during the regular season, best in the
majors, and scored 945 runs, second only to the Cleveland Indians,
the Division Series was an improbable, almost inconceivable, end to
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good hitting team,'' Palmeiro said. ``We ought to be
able to hit any pitcher. I can't explain what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is the Yankees' pitching is such that no team is
going to do much against them in the playoffs this year. The
Yankees got three terrific starts from Orlando ``El Duque''
Hernandez, Andy Pettitte and Roger Clemens. Closer Mariano Rivera
was as sharp as ever. Had the series gone to a fourth game, the
Yankees' starter would have been David Cone, who less than three
months ago threw a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said of the way
his pitchers performed against Texas. ``Last year, we did the same
thing, and I remember saying this was the toughest series for us
because you don't want to go through this ballclub again and think
you can hold them to one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that bothered me about our ballclub in the second
half (of the 1999 season) was that our pitching staff walked so
many people. If we went into this series the same way, we would
have been murdered. I felt these guys were ready to pitch, and it's
just a matter of good pitching stops good hitting. We have been
able to pitch in this series. Hopefully, we can continue to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he did not believe the Rangers' hitters had
approached the series any differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when they've had trouble beating us, you know
there's a psychological thing going on,'' he said. ``But I don't
think the approach is any different. Again, I know they scored a
lot of runs (during the regular season). But if you think back to
the All-Star Game in Boston this year, you had (Larry) Walker,
(Mark) McGwire, (Sammy) Sosa _ Pedro (Martinez) took care of all of
them. If you go out there and pitch the way you're capable of
pitching, even the good hitters don't hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates refused to say the series had been
a step backward for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in my eyes,'' he said. ``I know our goal is to move
forward and win a world championship, and I'm confident it will
happen here soon. I'll just sit back and take a few months to
analyze what went on in this series and see how it is we can score
most of the year and yet, when it comes to these three games, we
can't smell home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Yank sail onward, the Rangers face an interesting
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Although Oates and general manager Doug Melvin appear to have
the job security that comes with making three playoff appearances
in four years, they work for an owner, Tom Hicks, who has tasted a
championship with his other professional franchise, the NHL Dallas
Stars, and has played kingmaker with the football and basketball
programs at the University of Texas. Hicks indicated last week that
a quick exit from the playoffs by the Rangers would trigger an
evaluation of the franchise's personnel and philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have 11 players who are free agents, the most
prominent being second baseman Mark McLemore and third baseman Todd
Zeile. Before getting a single off Clemens in Game 3, McLemore, 34,
was 0-for-14 in the postseason, a slump dating to 1998. The Rangers
also might be tempted to move Gonzalez, who can become a free agent
after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   A look at Melvin's mindset came when he was asked during the
series if he would rather build a team that regularly makes the
playoffs or a team that makes one spectacular run to the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is you have to build _ get into the postseason, and
eventually it will happen,'' he said. ``Sort of use that Denver
Broncos theory. The Broncos did it enough times, (and) it
eventually happened. You have to focus on that. If you get there
enough times, eventually it will happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
