<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2949 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      10-11 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The offseason means rest and relaxation for some, surgery and
rehabilitation for others, and tee times, hunting excursions and
fishing trips for most.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And then there's Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker and his
band of decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Hunsicker might toss his golf bag into the trunk
of his car, but a briefcase and cell phone will be the only things
he'll be toting most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   A long season and short postseason are over, but the work is
just beginning for the Astros' brass. Hunsicker will review the
season and personnel with the coaching staff today, and similar
sessions with owner Drayton McLane Jr., president Tal Smith,
assistant general manager Tim Purpura and numerous scouts will be
held in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the process to improve, which is exactly what
the Astros hope to do in 2000. They have won the National League
Central an unprecedented three consecutive years, and improvement
means advancing beyond the first round of the playoffs _ something
the Astros have been unable to do following each of their
division-winning seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Plans were undermined in 1999 by an almost unheard-of rash of
injuries that saw the Astros use the disabled list 16 times. The
fact they managed to win the division was an accomplishment in
itself, but there's work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Holes could be created at shortstop and catcher because Ricky
Gutierrez and Tony Eusebio are free agents. The outfield situation
is unsettled because there are more bodies than positions. As
always, the budget will be an issue because of the uncertainty of
arbitration, particularly in the cases of Jose Lima and Carl
Everett _ both of whom will get significant raises.
</P>
<P>
   But the main focus might be on a pair of players who are signed
for 2000 but not beyond. Taking care of second baseman Craig Biggio
and lefthanded pitcher Mike Hampton are near the top of Hunsicker's
offseason to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first step is meeting with the staff (today), and then
we'll have some internal meetings with upper management,''
Hunsicker said. ``Once we get through that exercise, we'll begin
making decisions on what direction we're headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in a review-and-reflect mode over the next couple of
weeks, but once we get past the first few weeks of meetings and
planning, they (Biggio and Hampton) will be the first order of
business. That certainly is a priority. Biggio and Hampton are a
year away from free agency, and we want to explore the possibility
of extensions for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible long-term contracts might be in the future
for Lima and Everett, but at this point the focus is on Biggio, a
cornerstone of the franchise for the last 10 years, and Hampton,
who has the look of an ace after posting a 22-4 record in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``With arbitration-eligible players, I always give the player
and his representation the opportunity to talk about their desires
with regards to the possibility of a long-term contract,''
Hunsicker said. ``I'll do the same this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it figures to be a costly offseason for McLane, who
spent about $54 million on players in 1999. At this point, it's
unclear how much that figure will increase next season, but it's
worth noting the Astros' payroll has been on the climb over the
past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea yet until we go through the first round of
meetings,'' Hunsicker said. ``I don't see any significant increases
in the cards, but we're not in a situation where we have to cut
payroll, either. It's too early to answer that question, but I can
tell you we're not going to end up with a $70 million payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon completion of the World Series, Hunsicker can begin
negotiating with his own free agents. Eusebio, Gutierrez, reliever
Doug Henry and outfielder Stan Javier are key players in that
category. Javier, who was acquired from San Francisco in August,
indicated an interest in coming back to the Astros, although there
has been some speculation he will return to the Bay Area, where he
has spent the majority of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Astros' inexperience at catcher (Paul Bako and
Mitch Meluskey each have less than two full seasons in the big
leagues), re-signing the 32-year-old Eusebio would seem to be a
priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen,'' Eusebio said. ``They
haven't mentioned anything to me. I'd be happy to come back if they
want to sign me, but if not I'll have to find another place to
play. I think I showed them that I could catch a lot of games this
season and that my knees are fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play winter ball in November and get myself in
shape for spring training. I like Houston, and I like playing for
the Astros. I don't think we need to change too much. If we keep
this team together, and we stay healthy, I think we're going to do
better next season.''
</P>
<P>
   How the Astros will handle Gutierrez's situation is not as
clear. He's likely to command more than $3 million a year on the
free-agent market, and backup Tim Bogar is signed for another year
at $500,000. The Astros conceivably could pass on Gutierrez and
team Bogar with a low-priced veteran shortstop, or they could swing
a trade for another shortstop of every-day caliber. There won't be
much available through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have any power over that,'' Gutierrez said. ``I
love it here, but we'll have to see what our options are and see
what happens. It would be hard to walk away from a team like this,
but it's a business. We'll just have to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Henry, returning to Houston is his first priority, but he
knows the Astros may decide to make changes in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not knowing if I'm going to be back is the toughest thing,''
Henry said. ``I finished the year on a good note, but when you're
35 years old Gerry said they'll be talking to me in a couple of
weeks. Hopefully, I'm a part of their plans.''
</P>
<P>
   That, along with many other issues, will become clearer over the
next several weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2950 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GI-KOREAN-WAR-CRIMES-     10-11 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GI-KOREAN-WAR-CRIMES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUNDREL AMERICA'S TWO-FACED PURSUIT OF GLOBAL JUSTICE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Oct. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The soldiers herded hundreds of frightened men, women and
children out of their villages and on to the road. When the people
stopped to rest, planes swooped down to bomb and strafe them.
Panic-striken, the survivors hid in two culverts under a railway
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three days, the soldiers repeatedly fired machine
guns into the huddled mass from both ends of the culvert, killing
another 300 villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Too many such stories have been told this year. However, this
particular atrocity was not committed by Serbs. It was committed by
Americans, or so it is said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident took place in July 1950, when the United States was
fighting to save Korea _ and the Koreans who died _ from communist
tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   For years, survivors have sought in vain for an admission of
responsibility by the American government. But now an investigation
by the Associated Press has confirmed the survivors' account with
testimony from old soldiers still haunted by their role in the
killings, and documents showing that they acted under orders.
</P>
<P>
   Shamed by the revelations, the Pentagon has belatedly ordered
its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Although not forgivable, the desire of American officials to
ignore the incident is perhaps understandable. It was long ago. The
United States' armed forces are now far more assiduously schooled
in the laws of war than they used to be, and they pride themselves
on avoiding civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   In places like Kosovo, Bosnia and Haiti, the lives of American
troops are now more often put at risk protecting civilians than
trying to win all-out wars.
</P>
<P>
   And yet such a plea of mitigation makes even less comprehensible
America's continuing opposition to what could be the single biggest
step towards preventing future massacres _ the creation of a
permanent international criminal court.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has lobbied hard against the establishment of
such a court, even though dozens of countries, including all
America's NATO allies except Turkey, have indicated that they will
ratify the treaty setting up the court.
</P>
<P>
   America has no principled objection to the idea of supranational
bodies dealing with war crimes. Quite the contrary. It was the
prime mover behind the international criminal tribunals for
Yugoslavia and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   It refused to guarantee immunity from prosecution to leaders in
the Bosnian conflict even to get a peace agreement. Along with
Britain and France, it supplied information to the Yugoslav
tribunal that led to the indictment of the Serb leader, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to bring some belated justice to Cambodia, it has
actively supported the establishment of an international tribunal
to put Khmer Rouge leaders on trial.
</P>
<P>
   America clearly believes in building a system of international
justice, but on one vital condition: that any such system does not
apply to America itself.
</P>
<P>
   Its initial enthusiasm for a permanent court evaporated when
other countries rightly refused to tie the court's powers to the
veto of the U.N. Security Council, which would have made it a mere
political tool of the great powers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, America has pleaded that, as the sole remaining
superpower, its soldiers and officials would be the target of
politically motivated prosecutions, hampering its peacekeeping
efforts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   America's allies have similar concerns, so they have restricted
the powers of the court's prosecutor and given the court the right
to act only if national authorities themselves refuse to
investigate or punish alleged atrocities. This should be enough to
allay American fears.
</P>
<P>
   But the real objection of some officials, and of opponents in
Congress, is more fundamental and even less defensible: they cannot
tolerate any infringement of American sovereignty by an
international body over which the United States does not have
direct control.
</P>
<P>
   Such an absolutist version of sovereignty is rapidly becoming an
anachronism. America blew a huge hole through it by intervening in
Kosovo and bombing Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Its frequent denunciations of war crimes and other atrocities
abroad, and its promotion of internationally enforceable rules in
trade and arms control are based on the assumption that absolute
claims to sovereignty are no longer legitimate or useful.
</P>
<P>
   Judged in this context, America's opposition to an international
court is not only hypocritical, but misconceived. Even a superpower
would be safer in a world where the rule of international law stood
some chance of being applied.
</P>
<P>
   And the sad tale from Korea is a reminder that even Americans
sometimes commit war crimes and then try to cover them up. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
