<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2951 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      10-11 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ There have been times Rudy Tomjanovich has had to find the
bright side. It's part of the job. It makes sense, too. If a coach
can't find reasons to be optimistic after a week of training camp,
it's fairly certain he is headed for a miserable seven months.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not one of those times. As the Rockets broke camp and
headed to Houston on Sunday, Tomjanovich did not have to
manufacture enthusiasm. He could barely contain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited,'' he said. ``I'm telling you the truth
when I say that. Sometimes I try to be positive. I'm not trying. I
just am.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling permeated training camp. It would be wrong to say
the upbeat attitude is a marked improvement over last season, when
confidence was also high. But the good feelings of the week in
Austin have come almost as a happy revelation, or at least a
discovery in the wake of the widespread changes throughout the
team. It has become a topic of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to (Hakeem Olajuwon) about something completely
different,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He said, `Coach, man, this team.
Man, we've got some good guys. It's going great.' There is very
good morale, very good playing chemistry and interpersonal
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the team to get to know each other. We got some good
work done. We have a lot of work ahead, but I think we have a nice
foundation. The biggest thing is the positive enthusiasm about this
team. The older guys, Charles (Barkley) and Dream, have expressed
nothing but positive things about this team. They feel rejuvenated
and excited about the new mixture.''
</P>
<P>
   It should not be surprising the Rockets, new and old, enjoyed
their first steps together because those steps were taken at top
speed. Tomjanovich began developing the team by emphasizing its
running game and no matter how difficult the demands of training,
players usually prefer running to the discipline of half-court
drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're emphasizing running,'' guard Matt Maloney said. ``It's
early, but it definitely puts everyone's spirits high. If we came
out and worked on defense the first days, everyone would be worn
out. But there's a positive atmosphere, and there's good thoughts
about this year.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many established veterans on the roster, picking up the
pace has allowed for more offensive chances, and greater
opportunity for players to display their abilities to new teammates
and coaches. With 10 new players on the roster, providing immediate
opportunity to perform went a long way toward players feeling
comfortable with their new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets a chance to showcase skills in the open court,''
guard Shandon Anderson said. ``That's going to keep everyone happy.
At the same time, when we need a basket, we'll know we can go
inside and work our way from there.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, the Rockets said six days of practices
in Austin offered encouraging signs about the season. As much as
players might have been aware of each other, until they got on the
same floor, running the same offense they would have to beginning
with Wednesday's NBA exhibition in Seattle, they really could not
predict what sort of team they could become.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out how deep this team is,'' Barkley said. ``I'm very
impressed with the depth. It's going to be a fun season. We've got
good guys. But I think everybody is surprised at the level of
talent we have. Everybody is impressed with Steve Francis and
Shandon Anderson, but I think Carlos Rogers has been impressive.
It's just been a pleasant surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   For the holdover Rockets, checking out the newcomers has been
natural and to be expected, and now they have become the source of
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some great new guys,'' Olajuwon said. ``Players like
myself and Charles that were already here, we're excited to see all
these new guys. You have a situation where everybody is excited,
the coaches, the players. You have a concept that is very clear.
We're going to be a running team. That fits the players we have, so
everybody is very upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems so natural. It's very competitive but at the same
time, very friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   To the newcomers, the first week has been a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm loving this team,'' center Kelvin Cato said. ``I'm loving
the philosophy of this team. We'll go out there, run people into
the dirt and win ballgames. I'm loving it. We've got a lot of
scorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the league, you hear so much about what people can do
and can't do. Until you see it for yourself, you don't know. I
didn't know Shandon was this quick. I had never seen Steve play at
this level. I didn't know Bryce (Drew) and Matt shoot like they do.
All you heard about was Dream and Barkley. When Pip (Scottie
Pippen) was here, you heard about him. You don't know how good
Cuttino (Mobley) is until you watch him practice every day.''
</P>
<P>
   But making all those parts fit remains as important as
collecting them. There is still much more offense to put in and the
defensive drills will come. The week in Austin was only a start.
And a good start does not always mean a great finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good last year,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We can't make a
negative out of something that was also positive. We have to also
grow and stay on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, we really fit together well and some special
things could happen if we work hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
