<HEADER>
A2953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS &LR;      10-11 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ After only about 30 minutes of unbridled celebration
following their dramatic National League Division Series victory
over the Arizona Diamondbacks on Saturday, the New York Mets
focused their attention _ and their best shots _ on the Atlanta
Braves.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mets and Braves open the NL Championship Series on Tuesday
in Atlanta, and the Mets have not forgotten comments by Atlanta
third baseman Chipper Jones and relief pitcher John Rocker in late
September. The Braves beat the Mets five of six times during a
10-day period to gain control of the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it looked as if the Mets had fallen out of the
playoffs. They were one game behind Atlanta on Sept. 21 but fell
eight games back after going 1-8 in the next nine days. After an
11-inning loss at Shea Stadium to Atlanta, the Mets were two games
out of the wild-card lead with three to play. They roared back to
win their final four games, including a one-game playoff against
Cincinnati, and then beat Arizona 3-1 in the NL Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   After the Braves finished their season series against the Mets,
going 9-3, Jones said something to the effect that Mets fans had
better convert to the Yankees if they wanted to follow a New York
team in the playoffs. Rocker was more blunt, being quoted as
saying, ``I hate the Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, in turn, aren't fond of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next team we play,'' said Mets manager Bobby Valentine,
the master of the snide comment, ``is going to be playing ghosts
because they said we were dead. I don't know if they've ever played
against people coming back from the grave before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nice,'' said Mets reliever Turk Wendell of beating
Arizona, ``but I think it'll be even more special once we beat the
Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   About Jones, Wendell said: ``All I have to say is he stuck his
foot in his mouth. He's going to have to deal with it every game.
He's going to have to deal with the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   As the boisterous Mets fans left Shea Stadium after Saturday's
win, several chanted, ``We want Chip-pah! We want Chip-pah!''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets and their fans will have to deal with Jones, who
hit four home runs in three games from Sept. 21-23 when the Braves
swept the Mets and finished with a .400 average, seven homers and
16 RBIs in 12 games this season against New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets believe they'll be able to better deal with Jones and
the Braves in the NLCS because of the way they handled the pressure
of the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our heart's still pumping,'' said Mets left fielder Rickey
Henderson. ``They felt that when they left, we were no match for
them. They felt we were dead, and that we would not get the
opportunity to see them again. I'm real happy to see them again
since they thought we were dead. Now we can come back alive. The
Braves are a big challenge for this ballclub. Any time you get a
challenge, you get up for that ballgame. This team is going to be
more relaxed now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were giddy after reserve catcher Todd Pratt's home run
in the 10th inning Saturday gave them a 4-3 win in Game 4 and
finished the Diamondbacks. In their champagne-drenched clubhouse,
someone yelled: ``Bring on the Braves.'' Valentine heard the taunt
and answered: ``Yeah. Bring 'em on.''
</P>
<P>
   That's awfully big talk for a team that last season went into
Atlanta for the final weekend needing to win to stay alive in the
wild-card race and were swept in three games. And for a team that
lost five of six games to Atlanta down the stretch this year and
made the playoffs in part because Cincinnati lost two of three on
the final weekend in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets suddenly think all the pressure is on the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a get-back,'' Valentine said. ``I'd like to see what
we can do on the big stage. We'll try to be the underdogs that we
are and just see if we can play on the same field as them. A lot of
people don't think that we have this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics would seem to bear out those opinions. The Braves
outscored the Mets 63-40 in 12 games and hit 18 homers to the Mets'
seven.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta starting pitchers who will work in this series _
Greg Maddux, Kevin Millwood, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz _ were a
combined 7-2 against the Mets. Rocker had five saves, allowed no
runs in seven innings and struck out 11 of the 23 Mets he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The New York starters _ Masato Yoshii, Rick Reed, Al Leiter and
Kenny Rogers _ were 1-4 against Atlanta. If Orel Hershiser gets a
start in the series, that figure drops to 1-6. New York's staff ERA
was 5.23 against Atlanta; the Braves' was 3.17 against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that data, New York seems to believe it is the
reincarnation of the 1969 Mets, with a miracle lurking around every
corner. The Mets have had their share of exceedingly good fortune
in the last 10 days against Pittsburgh, Cincinnati and Arizona, but
playing Atlanta in October is another matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
