<HEADER>
A2954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     10-11 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA PUTS SELF BACK IN LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fenway Park press box attendant Guy Spina took the call
at 5:50 Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. There has been a lineup change, he was told.
Nomar's in. The new lineup will be up shortly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I was surprised,'' Spina said, who already had
distributed copies of a lineup that had Lou Merloni as the
shortstop and batting sixth, with no sign of his good buddy
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   An hour earlier, in the family room adjacent to the Red Sox
clubhouse, manager Jimy Williams had informed the team's beat
reporters that Garciaparra would not play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have Nomar in the lineup,'' Williams said. ``I didn't
ask him. He didn't swing yesterday, and I don't want to put that
kind of heat on the kid. Take it out of his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Garciaparra took it back into his hands, because by the
time Williams appeared at the pregame press conference, the
flip-flop had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally when he came to the park, I didn't have him in the
lineup,'' Williams said. ``But he wasn't here yet. Because in my
mind, yesterday he couldn't hit in the tunnel. I didn't want to put
a lot of added pressure on this kid, keep asking, `Can you play?'
Is it that monumental to hurt this kid? I don't want to hurt the
kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``So with that in mind, the trainer taped his wrist and he went
out to the tunnel. And after he got done hitting, he came back and
said he could play. So I changed the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra had a single in three at-bats, and scored a run
after being hit by a pitch in the fourth. He was lifted for pinch
hitter Merloni in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't suffer any setbacks,'' Williams said. ``I think he's
OK, you know, for tomorrow's game, hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 15 days since Garciaparra was struck in the right
wrist by a pitch by Orioles reliever Alberto Reyes at Fenway Park.
After the game, he had X-rays, which were negative, then played the
next day, collecting two singles in four at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   He sat out the next game, however. ``It really blew up on me,''
he said at the time, but dismissed the suggestion he might need to
have further tests. ``Whether it's really screwed up or not doesn't
matter,'' Garciaparra said. ``I'm still going to go out there. It's
irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of a rainout in Chicago, Garciaparra wound up with two
days off, and the next night hit a home run in Comiskey Park in the
victory that clinched a wild-card berth. That would be the last
time he would play in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Sept. 30, he was on his way back to Boston for a
magnetic resonance imaging exam. Team physician Arthur Pappas
diagnosed Garciaparra's injury as a bruised tendon (the extensor
carpi ulnaris) in the wrist, administered a cortisone injection,
and Garciaparra missed the last five games of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   He homered and doubled in his first two at-bats in the playoffs
Wednesday in Cleveland but went hitless in three at-bats in Game 2,
with third baseman Travis Fryman stealing a hit from him on his
last at-bat. By the time the series switched to Boston, he was
unable to work out with the club on the offday and was scratched
from the lineup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar could barely move his wrist,'' teammate Mike Stanley
said Saturday. ``He was having trouble putting on his jacket, for
crying out loud. We didn't go home saying, `Oh my gosh, we're going
to be without Nomar.' We said, `Lou's playing tomorrow; no big
deal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Having to play without Garciaparra, the American League batting
champion, was the worst roster loss the Sox had sustained since
1975, when Jim Rice, who hit .309 with 22 home runs and 102 RBIs,
was hit by a pitch by Vern Ruhle of the Tigers in the season's last
month and missed the playoffs and World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, on the eve of the World Series, the Red Sox were forced
to wait for the National League champion to be decided in a
two-game playoff between the Dodgers and Cardinals. To stay sharp,
the Sox scheduled three exhibitions at Fenway Park against a team
of American League all-stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day Mickey Haefner of the Senators hit Ted Williams
in the elbow with a pitch,'' said Sox vice president Dick
Bresciani.
</P>
<P>
   Williams played in the Series, the only one in which he appeared
over the course of his 19-season career, but batted just .200, with
no extra-base hits in 25 at-bats and one RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted never used it as an excuse,'' Bresciani said, ``but a lot
of people said it really affected his swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's teammate, Bobby Doerr, in an interview earlier this
summer, said Williams also had a bad case of the flu during that
Series and never told anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Roger Clemens was pitching against the Orioles in his
last start of the regular season and had a 5-1 lead when Orioles
catcher John Stefero hit a line drive off Clemens's pitching elbow.
There was some doubt whether he'd open the playoffs against the
Angels. He did, but was ineffective and lost, 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Later, of course, came the famous Clemens blister, which led to
his removal from Game 6 of the World Series against the New York
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra appeared in 135 of the Sox' 162 games this season
and made 133 starts. When he started, the Sox were 80-53, 27 games
over .500; they were 14-15 when he didn't. The Sox finished 94-68,
26 games over .500.
</P>
<P>
   He had more than his share of aches and pains this season,
beginning with spring training, when he had a strained right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   In April, he missed six games with a strained left hamstring. In
May, he missed a game with a bruised right index finger. He missed
two games with a strained left groin in the last week of June,
reaggravated it a week later, and missed the last nine games before
the All-Star break. He missed a game in Oakland Sept. 8 after
fouling a ball off his ankle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
