<HEADLINE>
FATE SMILES ON VALENTIN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-VALENTIN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It seemed that he was trying too hard not to smile. It
was as if John Valentin was auditioning for a spot in the
Buckingham Palace guards' rotation. Just after midnight, he stood
at his Fenway Park locker. He was shuffling through clothes,
pushing some aside and stuffing others into a duffel bag.
</P>
<P>
   And not smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll smile a little bit later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, you could see a slight grin appear. His team
needed to beat Cleveland Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in the fourth game of this
best-of-five Division Series. The Red Sox did that. They scored 23
runs and Valentin drove in seven. During one eight-at-bat streak in
Games 3 and 4, he had six hits _ three home runs, two doubles, a
single _ and 10 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   You could take the conservative approach and say the Sox beat
the Indians, 23-7. Or you could put it another way: Valentin drove
in as many runs as the Indians scored. He was 4 for 4 with two home
runs. He became the sixth Sox player to hit two homers in a
postseason game. He now finds himself next to Carl Yastrzemski,
Rico Petrocelli, and his buddy Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin is the team's last link to Vaughn. He has a key to the
Hit Dog's Easton home and sometimes goes there and takes some
swings in Vaughn's private batting cage. He sounded like No. 42
early Monday morning after he was reminded that some people wanted
a rookie, Wilton Veras, to replace him at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not he replaces me is the Red Sox' decision,''
Valentin said with a shrug. ``When they do that or if they do that,
someone else will benefit from my services. Until then, I play for
the Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   No one at Fenway Park was thinking about that Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
Valentin came to bat in the first inning and received a standing
ovation. He responded with a home run. He singled in the second. He
homered again in the third. By the fourth, it was a 10-2 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Val's a gamer,'' Sox center fielder Darren Lewis said. ``He's
obsessed with the game. He's into every pitch, every at-bat, every
inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis spoke some more about Valentin and then turned his
attention to the Boston crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I heard something about them having a lot of flights
available (to Cleveland),'' Lewis said. ``Is that true?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the morning flights to the city by Lake Erie are sold
out. But Sox fans will be relieved to know that Valentin is already
there.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to be fazed by his two-day run. ``It's just two
games,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the performance made you wonder. On Friday, the Sox and
Valentin were dismissed. Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, everyone got standing
ovations. What started this?
</P>
<P>
   You could almost imagine Valentin among teammates, presiding
over a late-night poker game. During a lull in the conversation,
maybe Valentin proposed that the team have a hitting contest
against the Indians in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dammit, let's do it,'' Valentin probably said as he began to
apply his eye black. And to prove how serious he was about it, he'd
be the one to start the Fenway hitting festival.
</P>
<P>
   If that actually happened, I wouldn't be shocked. In fact, the
Sox have desensitized me to sports stunners. It's so bad now that I
have come to expect the unusual. It's like watching your third
chase scene in an action movie. After a while, you just shrug when
you see the driver of a sputtering Hyundai maneuver his car on an
airport runway, shift into fifth gear, and pull even with the
Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox truly have me twisted. On Saturday, someone came up to
me and said, ``Did you hear about UMass? They were beating
Northeastern, 69-0.'' I nodded and said, ``Did Northeastern come
back?''
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Sox have done to New England. At the beginning
of the season, they were heroes to truck drivers and ditch diggers,
window washers and coal miners. Now their popularity has touched
everyone who ever has been underestimated and counted out. Students
who have received Cs for most of their academic careers are now
focused on the Honor Roll. Couples who once believed their love was
gone are now cuddling and listening to Barry White. The Los Angeles
Clippers even think they can win an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   And now, in this postseason of resurrection, it is Valentin's
turn to be featured. He said he feels the same as he did a month
ago. He also said he isn't doing anything different. He just looks
different. He explained all of this as he rifled more clothes into
his bag, zipped it, and headed for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   No one thought the team would be in Ohio Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope they score some runs for me,'' said Game 5 starter
Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it shouldn't surprise anyone if the Sox respond
with a 20-run night, Saberhagen throws a two-hitter, and Valentin
goes 5 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   Think about some of the things happening in this series. There
is the cult status of Valentin. Mike Stanley is hitting .625. Manny
Ramirez is hitless (as the fans reminded him _ several times _
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night).
</P>
<P>
   One of the most unusual teams the region ever has seen has a
game Monday night in Cleveland. Valentin will start at third base.
Maybe he'll manage a smile before the night is over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
