<HEADLINE>
SEASON RESTS WITH SABERHAGEN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-SABERHAGEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Next up: Bret Saberhagen. Not much at stake. Just a
season. Just a chance to continue what looked impossible only 48
hours ago, a chance to get into the American League Championship
Series against the Yankees beginning Wednesday night in New York.
</P>
<P>
   With Pedro Martinez's back still balky, Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams Sunday &UR;  &LR; night tabbed Saberhagen as the starter for Monday
night's fifth and deciding Division Series game against the Indians
in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good, without much discomfort,'' said Saberhagen, who
started and lost Game 2 in Cleveland Thursday night, giving up six
earned runs in 2 2/3 innings. ``Everybody will be well rested,
including myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who combined prayers and pitches to get through the
season, said his arm feels better than it has in some time. ``It's
the first time I've really felt this good in a while,'' he said.
``I've got to go out there, be relaxed, and see what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen said he won't push it. ``I won't do anything to
jeopardize the team's chances,'' he said. ``To me, the bottom line
is helping the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, he will get that chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
