<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S CALL THE WHOLE THING OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You say the Raiders; we smell invader.
</P>
<P>
   How 'bout the Vikings? Not to our liking.
</P>
<P>
   You want the Saints? Support 'em, we ain't.
</P>
<P>
   So that leaves the Cards...
</P>
<P>
   And there's probably a bunch of stupid rhyming words we could
find to finish off this little ditty, but to tell you the truth, we
pretty much lost interest when we started calculating the interest
the NFL owners would be making on Bob McNair's extortion payments.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: Once upon a time, when we were trying to
establish ourselves as something more than a place that made
movies, we actually used the NFL to help give us some civic pride.
We allowed Cleveland's first NFL team a long visit at the Coliseum,
then a visit to Anaheim, before the reality of the league's greed
was rammed home.
</P>
<P>
   After that, we embraced Brooklyn's lovable (but winning) bums.
We then took in Minneapolis' wayward (but winning) cagers. We
accepted the Raiders the first time when we felt two teams befitted
our standards, and they brought us a Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
   Then it got ugly. And this Ellis Island mentality didn't work in
the modern-day sports landscape of the City of Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Don't give us your tired, your weary, your deadbeat franchises
anymore. And, no, it's not because everyone around here is
!ital!apathetic to the NFL; we're only turned off by its pathetic
self-righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   Of those choices above, if we have to get someone's used team,
we'd just as well pass. Your L.A. visa has been rejected.
</P>
<P>
   We suggest trying the Salvation Army, if you're really looking
for a tax break....
</P>
<P>
   And, sure, it kinda irks us right about now to see the St. Louis
Rams kickin' some rear ends....
</P>
<P>
   By the way, while we were force-fed the Broncos-at-Raiders game
on TV Sunday, the home-bound Oaklanders didn't see it. It was
blacked out. For the 17th straight home game. Somethin' about the
Raiders failing to sell out again....
</P>
<P>
   To put into perspective Jackie Robinson's color-barrier-busting
feat in 1947, Time magazine includes it in a special ``Great Events
of the 20th Century'' issue _ not in the sports category with Jesse
Owens' Hitler-dissin' feat at the '36 Olympics, but under events
that affected society. It was, if you remember, the catalyst for
Harry Truman's ordering integration of the armed forces (1948), the
Supreme Court decision against segregated schools (1954) and the
Rosa Parks-inspired bus boycott in Montgomery, Ala., led by Martin
Luther King (1955).
</P>
<P>
   So with all that, Robinson will make the ESPN ``SportsCentury''
Top-100 athlete list at No.15. If you factor in what we just ran
down, he's bigger than Ali, Jordan and the Bambino combined. If you
consider him as a pure athlete _ and we're well aware of what he
did at UCLA _ Robinson hardly made the impact to put him that close
to the top....
</P>
<P>
   The wooden leg once attached to famed Chicago White Sox owner
Bill Veeck goes up for auction in Illinois next month. It's even
autographed _ he gave it to a Chicago tavern owner in 1977 as a
good luck charm after a new prosthesis had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Opening bid is $1,000, and speculation is it will go for
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't touch it....
</P>
<P>
   And then there's ``Strikeout,'' the book that's been out for a
while by former Detroit Tigers star pitcher Denny McLain.
</P>
<P>
   The big leagues' last 30-game winner has been holed up in a
Pennsylvania federal prison for all kinds of charges. He missed the
Tiger Stadium going-away party, but was hardly mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's Tuesday installment of ``Real Sports'' sent host Bryant
Gumbel to interview the man who insists he's been incarcerated even
though ``I had nothing to do with this... not one damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A snippet of the interview:
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel: ``(In your book) you admitted to giving and receiving
kickbacks, extortion, loan sharking and buying a plane to smuggle
and transport drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   McLain: ``No, that's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel: ``They are not my words, Denny, they're yours.''
</P>
<P>
   McLain: ``Well, it made a good book, I guess.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
