<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 BILLION _ ANYBODY COUNTING?
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The world takes aboard its 6 billionth passenger sometime
Tuesday. Come on, folks, squeeze together and make room for one
more.
<P>
   That's a humbling number. It makes one aware of one's
insignificance, if one needed awareness of that.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it. Six billion people, and how many of them will read
this column? Not more than half of them.
</P>
<P>
   Six billion, isn't that just about capacity? Maybe somebody
should install Bay Bridge-style metering lights in Heaven.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Please be patient, folks. You'll all get your turn. &LR; 
 &UR; We're killing 'em off as fast as we can down there. We've got &LR; 
 &UR; wars raging, genocides, ethnic cleansings, plagues, nuclear &LR; 
 &UR; goofs, now we're throwing earthquakes at 'em right and left. The &LR; 
 &UR; United States is doing a fine job resisting gun control. So &LR; 
 &UR; please stay in your line, either ``Nike Wearers'' or ``Nike &LR; 
 &UR; Makers,'' and the lines will be moving soon. Be sure to have &LR; 
 &UR; your boarding pass ready when your stork arrives. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To get the scoop on the population boom-boom, where better to go
than to the Boom Boom Room? At John Lee Hooker's blues place in the
Fillmore, business was, yes, booming.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing about a blues club is that everyone always seems
to be having a good time. Are they unclear on the concept? Just a
little earlier, many of these same people were moping and bitching
at some bar during happy hour.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the blues performers can give you the blues.
Lonesome Long-Gone Howlin' Muddy Blind Lemon Smith. My favorite
blues name is Magic Slim, because like I always say, you can never
be too slim or too magic.
</P>
<P>
   The song subject matter is hardly cheerful. My woman done run
off with the Webvan.com delivery guy. Took my Lexus and my Nokia.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there was no doom and gloom at the Boom Boom Room.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Let  &LR; her  &UR; make the Lexus payments. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WANT THE BLUES? Just cue up the tape of Sunday's 49ers game.
</P>
<P>
   The team that once boasted the most enlightened, generous
ownership in the game o' football got smoked by the Ramzzz, a team
that, until a couple weeks ago, was at the opposite end of that
spectrum, owned by a miserly, clueless ditz.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is nearing the end, Young might be toast, the new stadium
plans are a joke, the current 49ers owner has as much allegiance to
San Francisco as does Jerry Falwell. Dark days, fans.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young missed his appointment with the noggin doctor
Friday, and the 49ers would have fined him, but Steve forgot where
he buried his life savings.
</P>
<P>
   Old Genius (Bill Walsh) and the Apprentice Genius (Steve
Mariucci) didn't do the one thing they had to do this season:
protect their quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery caller known as Old Homeboy says the 49ers should
have done what Steve Young's ad agency did. In one of Steve's new
TV commercials (for cars? milk?), Young is sitting at his kitchen
table surrounded by cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 49ers should have surrounded Young with cows,'' Old
Homeboy moans.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 49ers opted for sleek, twinkle-toed interior
linemen who get tossed around like skunks crossing the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   The 49er fans aren't booing, they're saying, ``Mooooo.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST PERSON to be Y2K'd? It might have been the late Fred
Small.
</P>
<P>
   Fred was born in 1899, and in 1989, at age 90, he applied for an
additional credit card. The company denied Fred because he was
``not old enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer obviously thought Fred was five  &LR; 10 years short of
being born, and the unborn are notoriously bad credit risks.
</P>
<P>
   Fred died at 94, at an awkward stage: Too old to live but too
young for a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   TRUTH IN ADVERTISING? I hope so. I'm going to run to Macy's and
pick up a pair of Sandhurst clogs.
</P>
<P>
   Jeni Paltiel brought the Macy's ad to my attention. It says the
shoe has ``antigravity construction.''
</P>
<P>
   Won't the fellas at the gym be surprised when this old-timer
shows up in clogs and starts dunking in their faces?
</P>
<P>
   I have often walked down this street before, but the pavement
always stayed beneath my feet before.
</P>
<P>
   THE BLUE ANGELS dazzled again over the weekend, although it's
harder and harder for them to impress the fans with their routine,
since more and more commercial airliners are performing similar
stunts.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Howard was one of the thousands of oohers and aahers, but
she wonders: What do those Blue Angels pilots do after work to let
their hair down? After buzzing San Francisco rooftops at 600 mph,
what do these guys do for kicks? Drink a brewski and play pinball?
</P>
<P>
   I think what they do is screw up their courage and take a wild,
gut-wrenching ride with one of the city's infamous stunt cabbies,
the Yellow Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 03:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2999 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-REPUBLICANS-BUDGET-SF     10-11 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-BUDGET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GOP FEARS GAME OF BUDGET POKER AT CLINTON'S TABLE  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With time running out in the last session before a
presidential election year, congressional Republicans are once
again heading into a budget showdown with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Given Clinton's near perfect record in past confrontations,
including the  &LR; a 1995 government shutdown that deeply wounded the
GOP, many Republicans fear that this time the fight might cost them
their majority in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best Republicans can hope for is that no one is paying
much attention and it will have no effect a year from now,'' said
conservative publisher and GOP strategist Bill Kristol.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders find themselves falling into the trap they tried to
set for Clinton: the charge that the president is raiding Social
Security to pay for his new spending.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Republicans who are on track to tap Social Security
money first, because they cannot hold the line on their own
spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just could well be the straw that breaks the camel's
back,'' said Rep. Mark Sanford, R-S.C., referring to the cumulative
weight of repeated GOP failures to contain spending. ``Republicans
have been near indistinguishable from Democrats, and that ...
perception could have cataclysmic political implications for the
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   As the budget fight reaches its crescendo, Republicans find
themselves snared by their own appetite for spending _ from aid to
farmers to military pay increases _ and headed for a budget summit
with a president who knows they will do virtually anything to avoid
another government shutdown, including spending Social Security
money they have vowed never to touch, to pay for programs Clinton
wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're playing poker with somebody and you know at least
part of what's in their hand, you've got an advantage,'' Sanford
said. ``The one thing (Clinton) knows is in our hand is the fact
that we don't want a government shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly the endgame that GOP leaders planned when they
mapped out their political strategy last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tiny five-vote House majority that left no room for
error, Republicans vowed to stay within budget constraints that
were projected to produce a $161 billion surplus _ $147 billion of
it in Social Security revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to pass the 13 annual appropriations bills without
touching the surplus to force Clinton to drain Social Security
money to fund his spending programs. It would produce a stark
political contrast: responsible Republicans who protect Social
Security versus spendthrift Democrats who rob future generations.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, boasted in August that
this tactic would force Clinton to negotiate with the GOP ``on his
knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than three months later, Republicans are on their knees
scrounging in dark corners for ways to stuff $612 billion of
spending into a $580 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid tapping Social Security revenue, Republicans have
resorted to a host of accounting tricks, from ``score-keeping
adjustments'' that simply make red ink disappear to designating the
2000 census an ``emergency'' to stretching out payments of the
earned income tax credit to low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Observing the effort from a campaign stop in San Jose, GOP
presidential front-runner George W. Bush pointedly distanced
himself, blasting the last ploy as an attempt to ``balance the
budget on the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems began early this year, as spending pressure within
the GOP's own ranks, magnified by demands from congressional
Democrats and the White House (Clinton has threatened to veto bills
that don't fund his priorities), inexorably pushed this year's
appropriations bills over budget.
</P>
<P>
   With a five-vote margin that is so tight they do morning head
counts to ensure they have a majority on any given day, Republicans
simply did not have the votes to pass bills that restrain spending,
much less make controversial cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture was the first big item to break the budget, starting
with a mammoth $7.4 billion emergency farm aid package that has
grown to $8.7 billion. Both parties also agreed on a big boost for
the military, with added money for transportation, scientific
research, veterans hospitals and other items. But few were willing
to cut anywhere else to make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tom Coburn (R-Okla.) and I spent 14 hours on the House
floor with the (agriculture) bill trying to cut some things out _
which to both of us didn't seem to make a whole lot of sense _
nobody was willing to hold the line,'' Sanford said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Republicans continue to insist they will not dip into next
year's Social Security surplus. ``Our resolve to end the 30-year
raid on Social Security is total,'' House GOP leaders vowed in a
September 28 statement. ``We've drawn a line in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   They are about to cross that line.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the party announced a $5 million ad campaign to back
up its promise, the Congressional Budget Office issued a letter
saying Republicans were on course to overspend by $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a typical idea of cleverness by a congressional party,
which is too cute by half,'' Kristol said. ``We can inoculate
ourselves against Social Security by saying we're not going to
touch the Social Security surplus ... but then you realize, whoops,
well, the appropriations bills aren't going to be quite low enough
... so then they start looking at accounting gimmicks like a 13th
month, and then of course everyone comes down on them like a ton of
bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would spend even more than Republicans, but the
president claims not to be raiding Social Security because he
proposes to increase cigarette taxes by 55 cents per pack.
According to the Congressional Budget Office, however, that won't
cover all the added spending either.
</P>
<P>
   Fully aware that Republicans will do anything to avoid another
government shutdown, Democrats have stepped up their invitations to
Republicans to negotiate, perhaps in another White House budget
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, GOP leaders emerged from a similar powwow with
billions in fresh spending, their tough budget promises in a
shambles, conservative voters disgusted and the loss of six
precious House seats in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``For months, I have as an interested observer wondered and
worried what the endgame strategy is,'' said retired Napa
Republican Rep. Frank Riggs, ``and I believe it's become apparent
that they really don't have one.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  He added, ``It is somewhat amazing and perplexing because
we've been down this road before. We know that the president holds
most of the cards and that these last-minute, year-end
deliberations ... play right into his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreading another budget summit, Republicans are now floating the
idea of across-the-board spending cuts. Democrats are already
responding by charging that such cuts would eviscerate popular
programs ranging from education to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cal Dooley, a Central Valley Democrat, said the most likely
outcome is a replay of last year, in which ``they end up in a
situation where they have to negotiate an omnibus budget bill with
the president, who is then in a very, very strong position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 03:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3000 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SIXBILLION-POPULATION     10-11 2330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXBILLION-POPULATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AS POPULATION HITS MILESTONE, SCIENTIST WORRY ABOUT CONSUMERISM  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime Tuesday, the United Nations estimates, the world's 6
billionth person will be born. The event will probably occur on the
Indian subcontinent, and the baby's parents will likely be of
humble means.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they'll be subsistence farmers, woodcutters or
tradespeople. Maybe they'll own a small shop. Their ambitions will
not be overweening: weatherproof shelter, sufficient food and
adequate clothing.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely the world's 6 billionth inhabitant will grow
up to share its parents' modest aspirations. Given current trends,
the child may consume more than its parents _ much more.
</P>
<P>
   And not just rice and homespun cotton cloth. He or she will
want, and probably obtain, a wide array of sophisticated consumer
goods: a television, radio and refrigerator. Processed food and
drink. Perhaps even a motor scooter or car.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the problem, many scientists say. The population
crisis isn't just about more people, though that's certainly a big
part of it. The United Nations projects there will be 9 billion or
more living on the planet by 2050.
</P>
<P>
   It's also about the inevitable expectations of the billions of
people who will be born in the coming decades. Most will be born in
developing countries; most will aspire to the same energy-intensive
consumerism now promulgated in North America and Europe. And that
could have profound consequences for global ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   Already, scientists say, the expanding human population is
causing a mass extinction of other species _ only the sixth time
such a widespread eradication of life has occurred in the planet's
history. And skyrocketing energy use appears to be loading the
atmosphere with carbon dioxide and other trace gases, causing
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of these problems _ and whether humanity can avert
catastrophe _ is a matter of some dispute, but there's little doubt
about one thing: For the first time, human population is shaping
the planet's basic dynamics rather than the other way around. In
some ways, current population trends are heartening _ or at least
not as distressing as they were even a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Family planning programs begun in earnest 30 years ago have paid
impressive dividends. Worldwide, fertility has been more than
halved, down from around six children per woman in the 1950s to
2.06.
</P>
<P>
   In developed countries, the birthrate is even lower than the
global average. The fertility rate in the United States is 2.03.
And both Europe and Japan have rates of 1.4 _ meaning that they may
actually decline in population.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Sherman, director of communication for the population
office of the U.S. Agency for International Development, said birth
control accords reached during a 1994 international population
conference in Cairo are working.
</P>
<P>
   Birthrates have dropped, said Sherman, because women in
developing countries are obtaining the information and materials
they need to limit family size.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman recently returned from a visit to India _ a country that
is approaching 1 billion in population and that promises to
outstrip China as the world's most populous nation by 2050.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of our work is being done in Uttar Pradesh, a single
state in India that has a population of about 220 million, which is
close to that of the United States,'' said Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   Uttar Pradesh is an extremely poor state characterized by a
rural, conservative culture. Yet people are determined to control
the size of their families, Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually everyone we talked to wanted no more than two
children,'' she said. ``Reproduction is a politicized issue in
India, but (birth control) enjoys tremendous support at the village
level. The Cairo accords are working. There are very real
challenges ahead, but significant progress has been and continues
to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the average birthrate for most developing countries
hovers around 3.8, and many African nations post fertility rates of
6 to 7. That means human numbers are still spiraling upward.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the world's population continues to grow at close to
80 million annually because of ``population momentum.'' In other
words, the average woman is having fewer children, but there are
more and more women reaching child-bearing age each year.
</P>
<P>
   The future, in short, looks crowded.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has plotted three likely scenarios for global
population growth, with human numbers ranging from 7.3 billion to
10.7 billion by year 2050. Depending on a variety of factors,
population may or may not stabilize at these levels.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures are discouraging in light of current resource
trends. Desertification and deforestation are accelerating in many
countries, local water shortages are expanding into regional crises
and about half of the world's fisheries have been overharvested.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that there are about 740 million acres of
high-quality agricultural land in the world, and about
three-quarters of that amount is already exploited.
</P>
<P>
   To bring the rest into production would require vast monetary
investments for infrastructure and market development, and would
also exact a high environmental price in the form of obliterated
wildlife habitat, soil erosion and water pollution. So there are
clear limits to expanding agricultural production to feed the
billions of new mouths that are expected.
</P>
<P>
   The global marketplace may be creating unprecedented prosperity,
but it is also raising troubling questions about the capacity of
the planet to support such wealth, some scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble is that every villager in India and Pakistan now
has access to a television, perhaps even the Internet,'' said Paul
Ehrlich, a Stanford University biologist whose 1959 book, ``The
Population Bomb,'' is considered a seminal text on the modern
population dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, these folks are comparing themselves to Bill
Gates, not their parents or their neighbors,'' said Ehrlich.
``They're adopting the American model of consumerism. There are
twice as many people today as in 1960, but we're using five times
the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich said the new consumer paradigm comes at an infelicitous
time, conjoined as it is with a huge, rapidly expanding population
and strained natural systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the scientific community is worried sick,'' he said.
``In some ways, we know how to solve the population problem _ we've
seen some progress there. But we don't know how to solve the
consumption problem. We're basically mining our natural capital _
soil, water, biodiversity _ for transitory economic gain.''
</P>
<P>
   A big, hard and thoroughly unpleasant crunch is inevitable, said
Ehrlich. ``I think a good case can be made that we're already at
the edges of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich has many allies in the scientific community, but he has
been making dire predictions on resource depletion, famine and
epidemics for three decades. So far, few of his prognostications
have come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   While other population experts are hesitant to couch their
concerns in terms as apocalyptic as Ehrlich's, they nevertheless
have serious concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the risk of serious environmental problems is high
for the next century,'' said Robert Engelman, vice president of
research for Population Action International, an environmental
research and lobbying group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Engelman said many developing countries already face serious
food and water shortages. ``In terms of food, sometimes that's due
to production problems, sometimes to transport problems, but the
fact remains that many countries are incapable of feeding
themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Engelman, there has always been poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In and of itself, poverty is not unique,'' he said. ``What is
unique to our time is a combination of a population that is at an
all-time high and growing, coupled with rising affluence. What is
unique is that we now have a global model based on the U.S. model,
one that says that the good life depends on consuming large
quantities of natural resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Meat is emblematic of this model.
</P>
<P>
   Meat consumption is going up worldwide, and that demands
correspondingly higher per capita production of grain. It takes
about 7 pounds of grain to yield 1 pound of beef. Poultry takes 2.7
pounds of grain to produce 1 pound of meat, while swine eat 6
pounds of grain for every pound of pork.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States and Canada, each citizen consumes about a
ton of grain annually _ partly as bread or pastries, but mostly
indirectly, as meat. By contrast, developing countries have yearly
grain consumption rates of about 200 pounds per capita.
</P>
<P>
   Meat is esteemed as a luxury food _ indeed, a status symbol _ in
many developing countries, so demand for it  &LR; is acute and growing.
And with the desire for meat comes the demand for grain-based
livestock feed.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and 2030, grain consumption, primarily as animal
feed, is expected to grow by about 2.5 percent annually in the
developing countries. That may not seem like much, but a single
percentage point can represent millions of tons of wheat, corn,
sorghum and barley _ enough to feed millions of people if eaten
directly.
</P>
<P>
   And those millions of tons of grain represent, in turn, great
quantities of expended natural resources _ from water for
irrigation to the natural gas used to produce fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the environmental impact associated with both the
grain and the meat: rivers polluted with pesticides and nitrates,
exhausted aquifers, eroded soil. And ultimately, there is a wall
waiting to be hit: The quantity of arable land is all too finite.
</P>
<P>
   So should people in Chad, Bangladesh or Bolivia be denied the
chicken dinner they crave? Given the extravagant consumption in the
developed world, that hardly seems fair, population analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States, Europe and Japan created the model, and it
isn't a sustainable one,'' Engelman said, ``so we have to be the
ones to apply pressure to change it. We need to look at the way we
live. Is the quality of life really directly correlated to the
amount of stuff we consume? Do we really need the biggest house on
the block and the three SUVs in the driveway? Even if we stabilize
population where it is now, it won't matter much unless we address
consumption.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all experts are irremediably gloomy about population growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we should adopt a Pollyanna attitude, but
doomsaying isn't appropriate either,'' said Robert N. Stavins, a
professor at the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard
University who specializes in natural resource and environmental
economics.
</P>
<P>
   The world stands ``at the frontier of an enlightened policy to
turn things around, though I don't think we're there yet,'' Stavins
said. ``I don't suggest a laissez faire approach, but I think the
marketplace is sending signals that will ultimately improve the
environment and address natural resource issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Stavins said ``nonrenewable'' resources such as oil, coal and
metals are not a critical problem in the long run because the
marketplace will either find new ways to extract them profitably,
assuring steady supplies, or will discover substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, said Stavins, a more worrisome problem is
so-called renewable resources, such as fisheries and timber.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `tragedy of the commons','' he said. ``There are
generally no incentives to manage these resources, but there are
ample incentives for everyone to exploit them. So while they are
theoretically renewable, they are often exploited to the point of
collapse. And then environmental quality may not be adequate to
assure a recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are also ways for the market to address the plundering
of renewable resources, said Stavins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can put scarcity value taxes on fish landings, for
example,'' Stavins said. ``Or you can use a tradable permit system,
similar to what's being used to reduce acid rain. Say the
government wants to reduce the catch of a species 10 percent from
10,000 pounds a year. They issue permits for 9,000 pounds total,
and inefficient producers can sell their permits to more efficient
producers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, said Stavins, modern industrialization may
reduce rather than exacerbate pollution and resource waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industrialization can cause problems short-term, but studies
have demonstrated that after a certain point, rich, industrialized
societies demand tougher and tougher controls on pollution,'' he
said. ``Globally, it's getting harder and harder to buy dirty
technologies. The incentives are shifting away from them. That's
why I'm not as pessimistic as some people.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one _ not even moderate optimists like Stavins _ is
predicting a future without rough spots. Six billion people create
a great deal of stress, both environmental and social.
</P>
<P>
   Things, in short, could go wrong. Quickly. All the estimates for
population growth, says Engelman, are assuming ``no surprises''
scenarios. Unexpected catastrophes could cause the population curve
to angle sharply downward.
</P>
<P>
   A few back-to-back poor harvests in the world's grain-producing
regions could trigger global famine. AIDS and Ebola could pale in
comparison to the next unknown virus waiting to emerge from an
African or Amazonian rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very real risks ahead, and disease is one of them,''
said Engelman. ``We also don't know what the future climate will
be. If big surprises are in store, all bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Engelman, ``if we all work together, we can probably
dodge the bullet. And the real work is in the middle ground,
assuming neither the worst nor the best scenarios. We have to
address population growth and consumption simultaneously. Dealing
with only one or the other won't do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
