<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Oct. 10, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-REVIEW (Washington) _ Congress is rediscovering the
health care crisis _ which did not go away with the 1994 collapse
of the Clinton administration's effort at a comprehensive overhaul.
What often got lost in the partisan maneuvering and millions of
dollars of lobbying is now unmistakably clear: There was an
objective reality out there. This was not just a political
exercise. President Clinton all but snapped an `I told you so' last
week. `What has happened is exactly what we said would happen,' he
said. By Robin Toner. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-SEX-REVIEW (Alexandria, Va.) _ After GOP presidential
aspirant Gary Bauer was criticized for holding private meetings
with a female aide, other politicians and their consultants called
the incident unsurprising in a world of terrified male principals
and at least potentially penalized female aides, particularly in
the wake of the Lewinsky scandal. Bauer and other politicians are
wondering how to preserve their reputations without putting female
aides at a disadvantage in terms of legitimate yet confidential
conferences. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SHOPPING-REVIEW (Undated) _ As electronic commerce
moves into the mainstream, it has prompted a new appreciation for
old-fashioned business skills. Customers, it seems, still have
decidedly offline standards of service. They demand timely delivery
of goods and the ability to easily return merchandise that proves
disappointing, for example. The online retailers who come up short
on those fronts will be casualties in the coming consolidation
among online retailers _ a Darwinian winnowing expected to begin
during this Christmas shopping season. By Steve Lohr. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   HOMERUNS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Home runs have become a dime a
dozen. Like 100-point swings in the stock market, they don't mean
what they used to, their thrill diluted in an unparalleled flurry
of four-baggers. The last decade has seen such an increase in home
runs _ with almost all of them relived ad nauseam on ESPN _ that
the feat has become baseball's slam dunk, a once-sensational event
sabotaged by its own popularity. Yet somehow fans still delight in
each individual long ball as it happens. By Alan Schwarz. (also
moving in `s' category as BBO-HOMERUNS-REVIEW). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   DISEASE-WORRIES-REVIEW (New York) _ The region is in the midst
of outbreaks of E. coli bacteria and West Nile flu, and it is the
latter that most people are more concerned about. West Nile is
exotic to this area, and thus provokes fear and a sense that the
ecosystem is out of balance. E. coli is generally perceived to be
the result of human error _ undercooked meat or negligence with the
water supply _ and thus preventable. What is forgotten is that E.
Coli has killed far more people, including children. By Jennifer
Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FOREIGN-REVIEW (Washington) _ President Clinton's aides
say his chances of achieving a place in history as a master of
foreign policy don't look so bad. Many goals are near fruition. Yet
Clinton was recently forced to retreat on perhaps the longest of
his long-vision goals: ratification of the nuclear test-ban treaty.
It is being blocked by Republicans, who may be willing to pass it
only after Clinton leaves office. The incident speaks volumes about
the political atmosphere in which Clinton will have to operate if
he wants to accomplish great things and burnish his legacy in his
final 15 months as president. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-NAZIS-REVIEW (Vienna) _ A look at why fears of a revival
of Nazism in Austria are exaggerated. Austria is sometimes
criticized for failing to deal with its Nazi past, while Germany
has constantly apologized. Yet Austria doesn't have gangs attacking
Jewish cemeteries as Germany does. In Austria, non-Nazi
right-wingers and mainstream conservatives have both been offended
by cries that Jorg Haider is a neo-Nazi. By Donald G. McNeill.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-COMMUNISTS-REVIEW (Belgrade) _ In a way, communism still
lives in the former Yugoslavia _ both in patterns of power and
habits of mind. This failure of political and social transformation
helps explain why efforts to overthrow President Slobodan Milosevic
are faltering. While `reform Communists' are back running Poland,
for example, they are a younger generation, humbled and educated by
periods out of power. But in most former Yugoslav republics, the
same leaders still rule as they did 10 years ago in the name of the
Communist Party. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S.-REVIEW (Washington) _ With the Colombian
government facing its most serious crisis in years, the Clinton
administration is scrambling to assemble a package of military and
economic assistance that could reach dimensions not seen in the
hemisphere since the Cold War. But administration officials are
struggling to reassure anyone who will listen that Colombia today
looks nothing like El Salvador once did. By Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Photo-Graphics editor is Deborah Marchand
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 603-1036
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: marchand(at)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECHNICAL PROBLEMS: &LR;  Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
</P>
