<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5829 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-DISEASE-FEARS-REVIE     10-11 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DISEASE-FEARS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S INFECTIOUS: FEAR THAT'S OUT OF PROPORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As public health threats go, they could not have been
more different. The West Nile-like encephalitis virus, which broke
out in New York City in August, travels by mosquitoes that feed on
infected birds and then bite humans. It tends to sicken elderly
people the worst. The E. coli epidemic, which happened
simultaneously in upstate New York, was food-borne. E. coli strikes
the elderly too, but more often makes children the most ill. One
disease, never before been seen in the Western Hemisphere, is in
fact generally quite benign. The other is somewhat common, with the
potential to greatly sicken many people under the right
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ask around pediatricians' offices and the New York City
Department of Health, and what do people fear the most? Hands down,
West Nile. In recent weeks, the region seemed close to hysteria
over the virus: Phones lit up in record numbers at the health
department, parents in areas where there was not a single case kept
their children indoors, TV reporters talked in stern tones about
the plague among us. The E. coli outbreak, one of the worst the
nation has ever seen, got scant media coverage and provoked little
public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, this seems understandable. West Nile is exotic to
the New York region, and therefore stirs fear of the unknown. E.
coli is generally perceived to be the result of human error or
oversight _ undercooked meat or negligence with the water supply _
and thus preventable. Perhaps more important, the E. coli outbreak
occurred upstate, off the radar screen of city media, in a rural
area that may be perceived to have lower public health standards
than the city. (Untreated well water at a county fair was tainted
with cow manure from a nearby farm.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet the West Nile virus is the lesser peril, especially to
children, the focus of so much parental worry lately. It generally
produces very mild symptoms, especially in healthy, younger people.
Six older people have died _ the youngest was in her 60s _ but more
typical are the dozens of people suspected of having contracted
mild to semi-serious cases of the illness, including one child. In
contrast, infection with E. coli bacteria can escalate quickly from
diarrhea to dementia to death, and the outbreak upstate sickened
hundreds and sent 10 children to the hospital, killing one. At
least eight were on kidney dialysis early on, fighting for their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The two outbreaks affirm that what arouses fear and loathing in
the disease world often defies epidemiological logic. In fact,
hair-raising though little-publicized epidemics happen all the
time, hurting far more people, including children, than the West
Nile virus has. Last week, officials in upstate Chautauqua County
announced a whooping cough epidemic, with over 250 confirmed cases.
Unlike West Nile, that disease does not depend on mosquitoes to
carry it south to the city.
</P>
<P>
   But herald an illness that has never before passed American
shores and watch the panic ensue. ``We know from past experiences
that people get frightened by things that are new and different,''
said Dr. Stephen Ostroff, the acting deputy director for science
and public health at the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. Ebola, bird virus, hantavirus _ all have
caused great fear in recent years. But worldwide what kills more
people, especially children, than all of these? Respiratory
illnesses, Ostroff said. ``You don't hear anything about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Public health policy often unwittingly accompanies panic. For
instance, New York will almost certainly devote huge efforts to
mosquito control next year (critics say they're long overdue) even
as vaccination programs for seemingly outdated diseases are
neglected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know why there is a single case of whooping cough
in New York state,'' said Dr. Charles Calisher, a professor of
microbiology at Colorado State University. ``That means to me that
that vaccine hasn't been given to everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that if someone comes into New York with West Nile
fever, they are a huge danger to the rest of the population,''
Calisher added. ``But the same thing is true about whooping cough
upstate. That illness is a threat to New York City unless vaccine
coverage is 100 percent, which it never is.''
</P>
<P>
   Government and the media often unwittingly conspire to keep the
focus on certain illnesses. While New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
took pains to present West Nile as largely benign, he and the
health department also held frequent, urgent press conferences on
the matter. One such event was called hastily at 6 p.m. on a
Friday. The agenda? To announce a few new confirmed cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tough,'' admitted Maria Mitchell, a former city health
commissioner who is now president of AMDEC, a biomedical research
consortium. ``You have to have an appropriate level of concern
without creating panic and hysteria. AIDS was a perfect example.
There were all sorts of worries about forms of transmission that
simply didn't exist. We worked hard on that. But now, in some
populations, there isn't enough fear again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes government officials find themselves in the
uncomfortable position of having to play epidemiologists, a hat
they do not wear as well as, say, that of politicians. Members of
the media often do the public a disservice with errors in reporting
about who is most vulnerable, how the illness manifests itself, and
even how many cases are reported. At one point, television
newscasters insisted that there were two totally different
outbreaks in New York.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile has also caused fear because its carrier, mosquitoes,
can be found anywhere, causing people to fear that they can get
sick just walking out the door. ``But if you look at nine people
dying compared to the amount of mosquito bites we have all
gotten,'' said Ms. Mitchell, ``it doesn't seem like the plague.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 0846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
