<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-HOMERUNS-REVIEW-ART     10-11 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-HOMERUNS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING, GOING, YAWN: WHY BASEBALL IS HOMER-HAPPY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (duplication notice: also sent in `s' category as
BBO-HOMERUNS-REVIEW)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major league baseball teams have padded their considerable
coffers in recent years by linking corporate sponsors to almost
every play in the game, from the ``AT&AMP;T call to the bullpen'' to a
``National Arbitration and Mediation umpires lineup.'' (No kidding;
it's a dispute-resolution business.) If baseball wants a perfect
corporate match, however, it should call the folks over at Anbesol
and pitch a tie-in for home runs, because we're getting a little
numb to it all.
</P>
<P>
   Like 100-point swings in the stock market, home runs don't mean
what they used to, their thrill diluted in a unparalleled flurry of
four-baggers. The last decade has seen such an increase in home
runs _ with almost all of them relived ad nauseum on ESPN _ that
the feat has become baseball's slam dunk, a once-sensational event
sabotaged by its own popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Even the homer-happy news media have fallen asleep to home runs'
metronomic regularity. Major leaguers slammed a record 5,528 home
runs this season, a 10 percent increase over last year's previous
high of 5,064, and barely anyone cared. ``Last year kind of
desensitized everybody,'' said Peter Schmuck, baseball columnist
for the Baltimore Sun. ``I guess nobody noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, of course, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa captivated the
sports world with their 70 and 66 home runs, respectively, capping
modern players' long climb to grab the crowns of Roger Maris and
Babe Ruth. This season's reprise failed on two counts. With McGwire
hitting 65 and Sosa 63, they neither made a serious run at the new
record nor fell short enough to reaffirm how amazing last year
truly was. Instead, their unremarkable sequel only helped
underscore how current home run totals, like Canadian dollars, have
less value than at first glance.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs are a dime a dozen now. (Or, if you're McGwire, about
$2 million a dozen.) Even the hitters themselves have to
acknowledge it. Doug Glanville, the center fielder for the
Philadelphia Phillies, said: ``When I was growing up, if a guy hit
20, I was like, `Twenty! Wow, he's good!' Now, it's like,
`Whatever. No big deal.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, 20 major leaguers hit at least 36 homers, a total that
a decade ago would have led the American League. The grand slam
once was the most delectable of home runs; now more than 100 of
them get hit every year, sating even the most voracious fan. This
season Robin Ventura of the New York Mets hit two in one
doubleheader. Fernando Tatis of the St. Louis Cardinals hit two in
one  &UR; inning. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The paradox here is that while home runs as a whole mean less,
fans still delight in each individual long ball as it happens. (The
frenzy receives a steroid-like boost when rock music immediately
gets blared through the stadium speakers. ``Whoomp! There It Is!''
is Yankee Stadium's injection of choice.)
</P>
<P>
   Team owners have built smaller ball parks, shrunk the strike
zone _ yes, it's now smaller than a bread box _ and allowed
aggressive hitters to don suits of armor at the plate (arm pads,
shin guards and the like) to facilitate more and more home runs,
with each of these moves validated at the ticket office.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal is clear: Americans love anything big, from big
biceps to big drives to big scores, and prefer brute force to
cunning. The home run is indefensible. The pitcher can only watch
the ball's persistent arc, and must stand in shame as the hitter
saunters around the bases. The triple remains baseball's most
exciting play, but excitement involves risk. It requires strategy.
Why go to all that trouble when you can simply beat the other
side's brains in?
</P>
<P>
   This predilection was embodied in New York City's feelings
toward how its Yankees and Mets reached the playoffs this year. The
Yankees essentially hit a home run, enjoying a cozy lead in their
division for the entire summer. The wild-card Mets, meanwhile,
staged an old-fashioned rally, drawing a walk, hitting a single,
getting another single, getting foolishly caught in a rundown, then
extricating themselves and finally scoring with a dust-flying slide
into home. Safe! Ask most New Yorkers and they'll probably say they
prefer the Yankees' commodious approach, when the Mets' journey was
far more thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is moving toward an all-or-nothing culture, to its
detriment. As home runs skyrocket, so do strikeouts. Fewer stolen
bases and hit-and-run gambits make for less strategy and
second-guessing, and before you know it the sport will dovetail
into a dressed-up homer-hitting contest. That's essentially what
fans got in the final weekend of this season _ Fox TV disguised the
McGwire-Sosa longball showdown as the ``Game of the Week,'' even
though the players' teams were a combined 50 games out of first
place while the Mets, Houston Astros and Cincinnati Reds were
locked in a marvelous pennant race. The Cubs' manager, Jim
Riggleman, put it best: ``I'm embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no more embarrassed than the modern player who doesn't
hit home runs. A Nike commercial this year featured Greg Maddux and
Tom Glavine of the Atlanta Braves, two of the decade's most
successful pitchers, taking extra batting practice because, they
claimed, ``Chicks dig the long ball.'' For how long is the
question. All home runs, even McGwire's, fall to earth eventually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
