<HEADER>
A3036 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-CLINTON-FOREIGN-REV     10-11 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-FOREIGN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTIAL WISH LISTS SEEKING GLORY FAR FROM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From inside the White House, Bill Clinton's chances
of carving out a place in history as a master of foreign policy
don't look so bad. The White House, in fact, has a wish list of
fairly spectacular goals, and at least some of them seem
tantalizingly reachable.
</P>
<P>
   A lasting Middle East peace deal that ends the hostilities
between Israel and the Palestinians and Syrians? A better
understanding with China? An opening to Iran? Restoring U.S.
prestige at the United Nations by paying Washington's overdue
bills?
</P>
<P>
   Well, wait a minute. Clinton may want to do all this, but this
is the same president who was forced last week to back down on
perhaps the longest of his long-vision goals: ratification of the
nuclear test-ban treaty. Faced with a Republican phalanx of nays in
the Senate, Clinton buckled; he said he was ready to see a vote put
off for a year or more. That sounded a lot like what the Republican
leadership had in mind: to allow ratification _ if it is allowed at
all _ only on a new president's watch.
</P>
<P>
   The incident speaks volumes about the political atmosphere in
which Clinton will have to operate as he tries to burnish his
legacy in his final 15 months in office.
</P>
<P>
   When presidents enter office, the record shows, they usually
find that a foreign policy masterstroke is the easiest way to
establish their stature as the nation's leader. But as presidents
enter their last year they often find themselves more
circumscribed; election year politics, a weary bureaucracy and, in
Clinton's case, an ever more hostile Congress, are closing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain irony that as an administration nears its
end, foreign policy becomes much more difficult because of the
political context,'` said diplomat Winston Lord, who has served in
both Republican and Democratic administrations. ``Either the
president wants to get re-elected or his party wants to get
re-elected and in the Congress you've got partisan juices flowing
as well. That means the White House, the press, the national
political committees, whether Republican or Democratic, view
everything through the political prism.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is more irony in Clinton's case, because this
president came to office with nary a thought to foreign-policy
initiatives. Then he lost control of Congress, and has spent most
of the time since mired in one partisan battle after another.
</P>
<P>
   He has, of course, had accomplishments, among them placing his
signature on the test ban treaty back in 1996. But now, instead of
being able to build on them, Clinton finds himself again ambushed
by domestic politics. The president's supporters were left
lamenting that Clinton had failed to press Congress for
ratification much earlier, because he feared a confrontation with
the Senate's Republicans over the Democratic domestic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Not all presidents, faced with a hostile Congress, have suffered
on foreign policy like Clinton. President Harry S. Truman launched
the Marshall Plan and the Truman Doctrine in the first years of his
administration, when Republicans controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a major difference between then and now, said
James Chace, a biographer of Dean Acheson, who was one of Truman's
secretaries of state. ``Unlike in Truman's time, there is no
overwhelming threat and Congress can afford to deny Clinton
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``History,'' he added, ``judges by results, and the results
under Clinton show that no overall architecture has emerged. There
are no building blocks like the Marshall Plan or the establishment
of NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   So the wish list remains long. Here, according to Clinton
administration policy- makers, is the rough condition of the
wishes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A comprehensive Middle East peace settlement would be prize
No. 1. But Syrian President Hafez Assad so far has turned away the
administration's inducements, while Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat have agreed to try for a
framework by February that outlines the final agreement to be
achieved by September. Clinton is on the phone two or three times a
week with Arafat and/or Barak, trying to build trust between the
pair, White House aides say. But even if a deal is completed,
Clinton will be under pressure to be modest about his role in it,
because Barak has made a point of insisting that he and Arafat are
in charge _ and not the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Making China a `strategic partner' was a major objective. But
now the administration is struggling to restore relations to where
they were a year ago; allegations of Chinese nuclear spying aren't
helping, nor are China's internal political rivalries.
Administration officials acknowledge that Clinton lost an
opportunity last April when he refused to bend in talks with China
about terms for its entry to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   _ The new U.S. delegate to the United Nations, Richard
Holbrooke, has taken on the job of lobbying Congress in a last
ditch effort to get U.S. arrears to the United Nations paid. But
meanwhile, U.S. standing at the United Nations has become so dicey
that Washington had to lobby tiny New Zealand to give up its
candidacy on the budget committee so that the United States could
seek the role unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a near-perfect world, Clinton is said to very much desire a
rapprochement with Iran and Cuba. But Iran is still not ready,
administration officials say. And competition for the votes of
Cuban immigrants in Florida in the 2000 election make a gesture
toward Fidel Castro all but impossible.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the column marked accomplishments, Kosovo looms large. But
while the war Clinton led last spring took Kosovo out of the
clutches of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, many of those
who favored the intervention remain angry that Milosevic remains in
power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
