<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Art in the news
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some news stories so delicious in their idiocy that
commentary is superfluous. I will try to restrain myself.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution reports that public school
educators in Muscogee County, Ga., had teacher aides touch up 2,300
copies of a social study text containing the famous painting
``George Washington Crosses the Delaware.'' It seems someone
noticed that if you looked at it from a certain angle, George's
watch fob could be mistaken by a fifth-grader for tiny, misplaced
genitalia. No compliment, that, to the purported Father of Our
Country. (Kids will actually wonder what a watch fob is.)
</P>
<P>
   It took two weeks for teacher aides to paint out this lurking
menace, which has gone undetected in the long history of both the
painting and the republic. Educators explain they fear
fifth-graders will see what they have seen.
</P>
<P>
   The painting is in the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York
City. Maybe Rudy Giuliani ought to have a go at shutting them down,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
