<SLUG> BC-R-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSONAL HEALTH: WHEN GOOD INTENTIONS BACKFIRE AND CREATE FOOD
AVERSIONS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing from file of 10/4.)  By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you think your toddler or preschooler is living on thin air?
Has mealtime become a battle of wills? How many of these
admonitions are familiar to you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Finish your dinner! The children in (unfortunate country) are
starving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't eat your broccoli, there'll be no dessert
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I ask is that you taste it. Just one bite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go out to play until you've finished your lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The (food) is delicious. Just try it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan B. Roberts, an expert on childhood nutrition at Tufts
University, says that each statement, along with many others to
cajole small children into eating what's good for them, is more
likely to establish a food aversion than a desire or willingness to
consume the food in question.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and Dr. Melvin B. Heyman, professor of pediatrics at the
University of California at San Francisco, with Lisa Tracy, a
writer, have produced an excellent guide, ``Feeding Your Child for
Lifelong Health'' (Bantam, $15.95). It offers strategies that mesh
with children's changing stages and foster interest in foods that
are the essence of good nutrition. The strategies are intended to
keep meals and snacks from becoming battlegrounds and to prevent
children from learning to refuse the foods that parents most want
them to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The book also offers menu suggestions and recipes and lists
caloric needs and reasonable portions for children to age 6. You
may think your 2-year-old is not eating enough, but experts will
reassure you that a third of a cup of cereal, 10 ounces of milk and
two grapefruit segments make a good breakfast, and that half a cup
of noodles with butter and cheese and a quarter of an apple are
adequate for a toddler's lunch.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to leading them to what they need, children are
like horses. You can choose what foods to offer, but it is your
child who decides what and how much to eat. Children instinctively
resist foods forced on them. You should never resort to bribery or
threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telling your child, `You can have ice cream only if you finish
your spinach,' sends the clear message that dessert is nice and
spinach is an unpleasant chore,'' the authors say. ``Over time he
will come to hate it.'' Instead, offer food opportunities _ ``Would
you like to try some salad?'' _ and be prepared to take no for an
answer. Or try reverse psychology: ``I'm glad you didn't eat your
peas, because I want them.'' Then eat them yourself (unless, of
course, the child decides to eat them first).
</P>
<P>
   Children instinctively resist persuasion, Roberts and Heyman
write. ``Preferences for less healthy foods are actually reinforced
by pressure to eat healthy ones, coupled with the absence of
pressure to eat the less healthy ones.'' Avoid making a child
suspicious of a food by pushing it. If a child refuses to eat
things like green beans, bring them back every week or two (for a
total of 15 times, Roberts suggests) and let the child know he
doesn't have to eat them.
</P>
<P>
   Forbidding less-than-healthy foods can foster an intense desire
for them. When a child eats at someone else's home or at a party,
whatever is served should be permissible. By not keeping less
desirable foods and beverages in your own home, you will reduce the
opportunities to eat them.
</P>
<P>
   When my sons were small, we never had soda, candy, chips, cake
or rich cookies in the house, but all were allowed on occasion.
Fresh fruits were always available, along with homemade muffins and
quick breads made with fruits or vegetables. As a result, they
never clamored for overly sweet or fatty treats, and even now
rarely eat them.
</P>
<P>
   Take advantage of what the authors call ``a window of
opportunity'' for introducing many kinds of vegetables. The ages of
1 and 2, when children put everything in their mouths, are good
times to offer a variety of foods, including vegetables, fruits and
fish. I used to buy packages of mixed frozen vegetables, defrost
them and sprinkle them on the boys' feeding trays as finger food.
In those days, they ate every kind, from cauliflower to lima beans.
Even if some vegetables are later refused, children will often go
back to them after this early introduction.
</P>
<P>
   But even children who start out with an appetite for a range of
foods will suddenly, at 2 or soon after, become conservative and
resist anything unfamiliar, often insisting on the same foods day
after day until you're convinced they'll soon turn into peanut
butter and jelly on white bread.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts says you can encourage acceptance of new foods by
creating ``bridges of familiarity''; for example, by substituting
sliced banana for the jelly, or by replacing one slice of white
bread with whole wheat. If your child likes breaded chicken
nuggets, introduce fish as breaded sticks or fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to like a variety of fruits and vegetables is extremely
important to your child's growth and future health. But telling a
child that a food is delicious or good for her is a sure-fire way
to make it undesirable. Offer a small amount of the food, eat it
with obvious pleasure yourself, but don't insist that the child try
it.
</P>
<P>
   If your child tends to fill up by eating pasta, potatoes or meat
first, leaving no room for vegetables, try offering cut-up raw or
steamed vegetables and dip before the meal is served. Children love
to dip, and low-fat salad dressing or a simple dip of reduced-fat
mayonnaise or yogurt and ketchup can be all the encouragement a
child needs to eat vegetables. Try flavored yogurt as a dip for
fruit. Keep in mind that children usually prefer crisp vegetables.
For those vegetables my sons categorically refused, I often grated
or pureed them in tomato sauce or soup, or incorporated them into
quick breads and muffins, which the boys sometimes helped to
prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the issue of participation. When a child helps
to make a food _ whether it is adding cherry tomatoes to the salad,
tearing the lettuce, mixing the batter or growing vegetables in a
garden or window box _ the child is far more likely to want to eat
it. Research has shown that when children become familiar with a
food, like beans in chili, by preparing it in class, they are much
more likely to choose it and eat it in the lunchroom.
</P>
<P>
   But don't insist that every new food be tasted. ``Tasting rules
are hard to enforce, lead to arguments and in the long run don't
work,'' the authors state. Instead, casually offer a part of the
food that may have special appeal, like a crispy crust or tasty
sauce, or have someone else at the table say how good the broccoli
or beans are.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid preparing separate meals for children and adults. (If a
dish is to be highly spiced, however, it would be wise to remove
some for the child before the hot seasonings are added.) If a child
refuses to eat a main course, make no comment about it. Simply
offer a plain alternative, like cereal and milk or a cheese
sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts has unkind words for food tricks, such as cutting
sandwiches into fancy shapes or making faces on hot cereal. I am
not so sure: people's appetites are whetted by their eyes as well
as their taste buds, and my sons got a kick out of the simple
decorations I made on their oatmeal and French toast. Early on we
dubbed broccoli ``baby tree,'' and 29 years later our sons still
enjoy this healthful vegetable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
