<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3116 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN12-COX     10-11 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reliving the good times
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI, Fla. _ This is my hometown. I grew up here back in the
'50s when gasoline cost 19 cents a gallon, and the only ``runners''
anybody'd ever heard of were the rum kind who flourished on the
Florida coast during prohibition. Life was good, but try to
convince a kid of that.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1947, I met a girl named Ann Marie Anderson at
school. We
</P>
<P>
   started doing stuff together. We joined the choir and learned to
sing harmony _
</P>
<P>
   sort of. ``Whispering Hope'' was our favorite. Our mothers made
us circle skirts to wear under the choir robes. Annie's was green.
Mine was white.
</P>
<P>
   We partnered in home ec class. Once we cooked up a prune whip
that was so nasty looking at it gave us a bad case of the giggles.
Once we got in trouble for
</P>
<P>
   frying potatoes when we were supposed to be baking apple crisp.
</P>
<P>
   When my mother had an operation, Ann Marie's mother, a
no-nonsense Swedish
</P>
<P>
   lady, took me in and saw to it that I cleaned up my oatmeal
every morning
</P>
<P>
   before Mr. Anderson drove us to school.
</P>
<P>
   That same year we went steady with two guys named Bill. Once we
danced with
</P>
<P>
   them at a school dance. Both romances lasted a week.
</P>
<P>
   In 10th grade, Ann Marie met A.B., and pretty soon they were a
twosome. A.B.
</P>
<P>
   had a friend named Harry who had a cool '40 Chevy and no
girlfriend. The
</P>
<P>
   fix-up was in. We doubled on Saturday night. I wore a blue dress
and a flowered silk scarf around my neck. Harry had on a tweed
jacket. We went to the Jamboree at school, kind of an in-house
talent show. The Taylor twins tap-danced. Later we wheeled into
Kelly's Drive-In for hamburgers, 25-cent milkshakes, and to see and
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two years, the four of us spent a lot of time
together, just like we're doing this afternoon, 50 years later in
Ann Marie and A.B.'s living room. Annie and I are giggling and the
guys are telling stories _ same as we did all those years ago _
before three marriages, two divorces, a couple of bypasses, and
bifocals.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night beach parties at Crandon Park were a mainstay of
our social
</P>
<P>
   life. Ann Marie reminds Harry how we had to keep the fire going
until midnight
</P>
<P>
   so he could have a hamburger without having to confess on
Saturday that he'd
</P>
<P>
   eaten meat on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we got crazy _ like the night Harry raced Jerry
Gregory across the
</P>
<P>
   Rickenbacker causeway to Key Biscayne. We jumped the median _
twice. Once to
</P>
<P>
   pass Jerry, and once to get back on our own side of the bridge
and out of the
</P>
<P>
   way of oncoming traffic. Ann Marie and A.B. were in the back
seat. Later, when
</P>
<P>
   I asked Harry why he was acting funny, he said he was thinking
about what a
</P>
<P>
   stupid thing he'd done and how close he'd come to flipping the
four of us into
</P>
<P>
   Biscayne Bay.
</P>
<P>
   I went to my first prom with Harry. He showed up looking mighty
fine in a
</P>
<P>
   white dinner jacket and his dad's new ``step down'' Hudson. It
was on loan for
</P>
<P>
   the special occasion. I was feeling fairy tale gorgeous as Harry
helped me
</P>
<P>
   into the car _ until I tried to ``step down'' and got tangled up
in 20 yards of
</P>
<P>
   ice-blue tulle and went sprawling across the front seat. I wasOK, but my
</P>
<P>
   gardenias were smashed. Ann Marie and A.B. were in the back
seat.
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday morning we all went for a sail on George Mauer's
boat. The girls
</P>
<P>
   brought food, and the guys brought drink. Four grueling hours
later, with
</P>
<P>
   little help from wind or tide, we waded ashore on a tiny island
in Biscayne
</P>
<P>
   Bay, spread out the picnic and sent Harry to reclaim the jug of
cider we'd
</P>
<P>
   been dragging behind the boat to cool. We were desperately
thirsty, and as it
</P>
<P>
   turned out, doomed to another four dry hours. The boy geniuses
had bought a gallon of apple cider vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Which just happens to be what Annie and I are ragging them about
this
</P>
<P>
   afternoon. But hey, isn't that what old friends, and memories,
are for?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
