</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3117 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX     10-11 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cats, dogs, kids, lizards and roots, what more?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I can't completely empathize with what Lori St.
John had to worry about. Every morning in my house we have to check
to see what the cats spit up. For a day or two, St. John was hoping
not to have to tell her guest python, ``Now, spit up the cat.''
</P>
<P>
   That cat can release from the ceiling. The python is gone _
reclaimed by its owner.
</P>
<P>
   Most every reader of the Waco Tribune-Herald felt the old
epidermis expand and contract at the front-page story about St.
John finding the 9-foot, one-eyed python in the parking lot of the
Bill Logue Juvenile Justice Center and carting it home.
</P>
<P>
   And talk about story placement. Right above the picture of St.
John holding the snake was a teaser to an inside story on how to
``keep your home from becoming a rodent haven.'' A python would do
that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one obvious problem for St. John was the event that
the python might classify her cat as a rodent.
</P>
<P>
   I can almost relate to this. I don't have any 9-foot pets
slithering around my house. I do recall a hairball nearly that
large.
</P>
<P>
   The average American house is an ecosystem _ many lives entwined
in eco-confines. We have the children. We have house plants. We
have the pets. We have what buggers the pets bring in, and others
uninvited.
</P>
<P>
   If you take away kids, who commonly come with pets, you dispatch
with most of the standard nuclear ecosystem. But you never live in
an eco-vacuum. When I was single, I had no children, no house
plants, no pets. But I did have things growing in my refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   As a bachelor, I thought I was insulated, apart from nature's
forces. Then I found that mice had been convening to nibble through
take-home packets of ketchup I'd been storing for the winter. We
are all somewhere on the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   Having children and pets really accents the home-as-wilderness
experience. This ranges from Wild Kingdom rituals around the
refrigerator _ teen-agers hunt in packs _ to house cats waiting for
a june bug to be introduced to their bio-dome.
</P>
<P>
   I've written before about the imported-to-Waco Mediterranean
geckos that hang upside down on our windows, their see-through
bellies showing their last dinner. I've lobbied my wife to allow
them to hang out inside. They're known to control bugs like, for
instance, the ear mites that pester the cats.
</P>
<P>
   The other day (my wife's sworn vow to leave me also factored in)
I finally holstered my interest in giving geckos the run of the
house. I watched in dyspeptic horror as one of our cats chased down
a gecko and made like a python, digestive-wise. Maybe the window
screen is best for see-through lizards.
</P>
<P>
   And lest we assume that the extent of the home-sweet ecosystem
is that which walks and stalks afoot, the other day we faced up to
an invasion under our feet.
</P>
<P>
   In a summer where fire ants were burrowing all the way to the
China Sea for moisture, roots from the Arizona ash in front of our
house gradually and inexorably had strangled off our sewer line,
carving into the pipe like lifers in Shawshank Prison. After
repeated visits from the rooter industry, which may one day prove
more lucrative in Waco than giving allergy shots, we gave in and
gave up our front yard to professionals with a backhoe.
</P>
<P>
   As the plumbers replaced our rusted line, they hauled out roots
big enough to serve with rump roast.
</P>
<P>
   I came home after the deed was done to find a gaping wound from
the house to the street, the roots flayed out from the incision. It
was like thorasic surgeons had left a patient unstitched on the
table. The next morning they ``closed up'' _ in O.R. terms _
leaving a scar the size of the Mojave Desert.
</P>
<P>
   But at least we could flush. Last time I checked.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, it's scary, all the life forms out
there trying to share inner domains. Wish I didn't have to think
about it.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
