</P>
<P>
   THE PATH TO ABUSE OF THE FIRST AMENDMENT ISN'T A ONE-WAY STREET.
``Here we go again,'' writes columnist Vernon Jarrett. ``This time
the holier-than-thou sinner is the management of the Brooklyn
Museum of Art, which is willing to publicly trample the feelings of
millions of religious human beings simply because it believes that
all art is sacred.'' This week, Jarrett offers a hard-hitting
commentary on the controversy concerning Chris Ofili's work ``The
Holy Virgin Mary.'' Jarrett's take: ``Don't ask the taxpayers who
are insulted by the art to finance the promotion of (Ofili's)
ideas. And one need not be impressed by New York's mayor, Rudolph
Giuliani, to feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   NO RESPECT, NO MONEY _ Political campaign financing season has
arrived once again. This year, however, will be different.
Candidates may have a harder time getting donations from
Asian-American supporters. ``Asian-Americans, who have been stung
by the 1996 campaign contribution scandals, will be shutting doors
and taking the phones off the hooks,'' writes columnist Amy Wu.
Many Asian-Americans feel that they were placed under a cloud of
suspicion after two Chinese-Americans were accused of campaign
finance violations. The media and Democratic political opponents
also helped to tarnish the image and reputation of the
Asian-American community.
</P>
<P>
   GAY REPUBLICANS AND DEMOCRATS HAVE THEIR WORK CUT OUT FOR THEM.
Is there really a change in the attitude of GOP presidential
candidates toward gays? On the surface it would seem so, now that
they are on the campaign trail. Rich Tafel, Executive Director of
the Log Cabin Republicans, says George W. Bush has ``laid the
philosophical groundwork for supporting federal nondiscrimination
policies and legislation.'' Columnist Chuck Colbert couldn't
disagree more. GOP presidential hopefuls, Colbert writes, ``fall
very short of fully supporting and wholeheartedly embracing gay
civil rights as shown by their Democratic contenders,'' who favor
passage of a gay civil-rights employment bill, (the Employment
Nondiscrimination Act), hate-crimes legislation, lesbian and gay
adoptions and political appointments.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON ... MARGARET CO. This week, we have transmitted the
first installment of New America News Service's ``Spotlight On...''
entertainment feature. ``Spotlight On ...'' is a lively Q&AMP;A
interview series with noted individuals whose achievements, stature
or influence put them in ``role-model'' positions. Celebrities from
the worlds of academia, entertainment, politics, science and sports
give readers a glimpse of their interests, hobbies, latest
accomplishments and some not-so-known facts _ like their plans for
ringing in the year 2000 _ in this short, fun feature. First up:
Comedian Margaret Cho.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION ABOUT NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE -- AND TO
RECEIVE THE SERVICE FOR 30 DAYS FOR FREE -- please contact sales
representative Ana Pena by phone, (212) 499-3333, or fax, (212)
499-3382.
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks!
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
