<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Operating system upgrade will enhance multiple-user features
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Oct. 23, Apple will release the latest upgrade to
its Mac operating system, or OS.
</P>
<P>
   This latest upgrade, dubbed OS 9, represents evolutionary change
in Apple's venerable software that controls the look and feel of
all Macs.
</P>
<P>
   With OS 9, users will for the first time be able to create and
keep several individual configurations on one Mac. That is, two
people can share a computer but use desktops and configurations
customized to their specific tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer officially announced OS 9 on Tuesday, but reports
about the project, code-named Sonata, and its key features have
been proliferating across the Web for months. To check out the
latest reports, visit such sites as Apple Insider, MacIntouch and
Webintosh.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a summary of OS 9's biggest new features.
</P>
<P>
   Sonata's biggest change will be an expanded ability for Macs to
handle multiple users. With Sonata, several people will be able to
share a Mac and keep separate work environments. Those individual
working environments will be password-protected.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no one but you _ or a system administrator if
your Mac is on a network _ will be able to change your setup. Among
the things you'll be able to customize will be look, file access
and Internet configuration.
</P>
<P>
   You can sign onto a Mac configured for multiple users via a
written password or through voice recognition. Sonata will include
a new control panel called Voice Password Assistant.
</P>
<P>
   With Voice Password, you select a spoken code word, then say it
until the system understands your voice and the code word. Then a
user can sign onto a Mac by selecting his or her name and saying
the correct password.
</P>
<P>
   Another OS feature getting an overhaul is Apple's new Sherlock
search technology. Sherlock lets users search not only their hard
drive but the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sonata will add two new important searches to Sherlock. The
first is for people. Sherlock will search out via the Web telephone
numbers and e-mail addresses. What it finds will be listed on your
computer in the Sherlock window.
</P>
<P>
   The second new search is for e-commerce. Type the name of a
product into Sherlock. It will then search the Web for varying
prices and availability of the product, listing the results on your
computer.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more changes coming with Sonata, many of which
are minor enhancements and bug fixes.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about this upgrade, check out Apple Insider at
www.appleinsider.com
</P>
<P>
   /macos8.7.shtmlreports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
