<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plug/no play weekend frustrating experience
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It looks as if it may be time to lighten the load on
the old Pentium 166.
</P>
<P>
   I took it with me and looked into the maw of the circuit-board
abyss. I made it back relatively OK, but I'm not sure the P166 did.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long, headache-inducing, frustration-filled trip.
Somewhere along the way, the P166 took a near-fatal hit. In fact,
its brains are still a little scrambled and it gets a faraway look
in the monitor. It all started innocently enough.
</P>
<P>
   About a week after putting in the Intel NIC, or network
interface card, which I wrote about in the last column, weird
things began to happen, and my modem started acting goofy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a U.S. Robotics 56K Winmodem, your basic generic Windows
95 plug-and-play hardware. It developed the strange habit of
answering incoming phone calls after one ring with a fax tone. So,
on a Friday afternoon, I went out and bought a Diamond Supra
voice/fax modem for $60. Late Sunday night I was looking at a dead
computer and a Win 95 CD that wasn't even useful as a coaster
because it has a hole in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   I actually enjoy opening up my P166 _ a Toshiba Infinia _ to
tinker and install new hardware. Also, I hoped to rectify my
increasingly poor MindSpring connection. In the past few weeks, the
number of disconnects has jumped from none to frequent, and when it
does stay connected, the download speeds drop to less than 200
bytes!
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the modem wasn't the answer, and slow, overloaded ISP
servers quickly became the least of my problems. I popped the top
on the P166, swapped out the USR modem for the Supra, stuck in the
CD-ROM with the new modem's drivers and turned on the juice _
waiting for Win 95 to do that magic plug-and-play trick and
discover my new hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Now, plug-and-play is really a wonderful thing (you Mac users
stop snickering). Win 95 finds your new piece of hardware, asks for
the drivers, copies them off your CD, restarts itself, and you're
plugged and you're playing.
</P>
<P>
   So I didn't expect any surprises when I opened up the Properties
on my computer and looked in the device manager. Egads!
</P>
<P>
   There were several problems. The most confusing thing was having
two COM1 ports and an unnamed COM port along with the COM2 serial
port and the LPT1 printer parallel port. On top of that, the Intel
NIC had one of those alarming yellow exclamation points Win 95 uses
as a hardware conflict alert.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm no greenhorn in the device manager. I've done several
modem upgrades, and have added a TV tuner card, scanners, printers
and NICs.
</P>
<P>
   So I knew all about removing conflicting devices and letting the
Win 95 plug-and-play feature find them again to reinstall the
drivers. So I did ... to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I played plug-and-play for the rest of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, I got into the IRQs, DMA channels, reinstalling drivers,
removing devices, you name it. I was swapping cards around into
different PCI and ISA slots _ a trick I had used successfully in
the past. I was in the Setup program, using DOS commands I forgot
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I was doing a lot of plugging but no playing.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba was no help. Support wanted $35 to even let me ask a
question. Forget that. I already paid them $2,200 for the machine.
They weren't getting any more of my money.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I reached a point where trying to dial the modem
resulted in the famed Windows ``fatal exception'' and the blue
screen of death. Then it deteriorated to where I couldn't even boot
into Windows without the machine turning blue.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I decided I had to reformat the hard drive _ after a
three-hour timeout to back up my 8-gigabyte disk.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't throw in the towel until I ran the Windows set-up
program and got a message that a CAB file was corrupt before the
setup program terminated itself. I had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I have managed to restore my computer to a shadow of
its former self. It works fine, except that I apparently have a
conflict with my USB serial bus. And I still have that gnarly
unnamed COM port.
</P>
<P>
   I have not yet figured out what the deal is. All I can figure is
that my motherboard _ built for the first-generation Pentium chips
_ wigged out from having too many devices installed. I suppose I
will take the P166 to a pro and see what's what.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, if anyone needs a new modem, I have one for
sale cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
