<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: How do the networks create the yellow
first-down marker that appears across the field during NFL games?
Is there some kind of object on both sides of the field for a
current or reflection to run between? Why don't the players ever
trip over the yellow marker? _ Tom N.
</P>
<P>
   A: The mysterious yellow line is generated in computerland; in
all, eight computers are used. The folks at Fox Sports said the 1st
&AMP; Ten system, which allows television viewers to see a first-down
line as the goal in a series of downs, does the work. A virtual
line begins with a central computer receiving input from several
cameras. Another computer translates the information into a
graphic. Yellow is used unless it is a team color or used in the
field palette. Yet another computer sends it on to be superimposed
on the program video. To synchronize the computerized first-down
line with the game's program feed, the 1st &AMP; Ten system delays
program video and audio a fixed number of frames.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a fifth-grader at Noble Elementary in Ohio. I have been
working on a project about your state. I need some help from your
readers. I would like them to send me picture postcards from your
area. The class is trying to collect as many postcards as possible.
I thank you for your help with this project. _ Harleigh Butler A:
OK, Texas, show this enterprising Buckeye what ``many postcards''
means. Send the youngster a Texas scene in care of Mrs. Joan
Ledwedge's Class, Noble Elementary School, 130 Minerva St., Tiffin,
OH 44883. I will let you know how well Texas stacks up in her
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a monastery in South Texas that allows
people to stay in their rooms and take a vow of silence during a
retreat. I stayed a few days years ago and want to get in touch
with them again. Is this too vague? _ Robin M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Best guess? The Corpus Christi Abbey located on Lake Corpus
Christi, near Mathis. A vow of silence is not required, but is
respected. This 97-acre site is ideal for a weekend (or more) of
reflection. The monks of Arkansas' Subiaco Monastery came to Texas
in 1927 to staff a new high school. Originally located in Corpus
Christi, the monastery moved to its present location after the
destructive 1970 Hurricane Celia. To book the Benedictine Retreat
Center for a group retreat or an individual, call (361) 547-9797 or
write to Retreat Director, Benedictine Retreat Center, HCR 2, Box
6300, Sandia 78383.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ A reader has found relief in various climates (Belize to
Newfoundland) from mosquitoes with Bounce fabric softener sheets.
Pin one to the back of a shirt collar to discourage those pesky
critters.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697 or e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
