<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International radio spins a unique, charming web
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I'm an analog guy in a digital world.
</P>
<P>
   At home, when I escape the two computers that sit on my desk
here at work, I slide into a more comfortable seat. It faces a
sight that would make any 13-year-old quivery inside. On an
8-foot-long table there are shortwave receivers, ham radio
transceivers, antenna tuners, power meters, and even more
mysterious black boxes that have names and functions too esoteric
to try to explain.
</P>
<P>
   About once a year, I take a break from writing about computers
and spend a few minutes talking to you about shortwave listening
and ham radio.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when I first proposed writing one of these columns
about an analog technology so old and basically unchanged that
Marconi would still feel at home sitting at that table with me, my
editors were aghast. No one cared about shortwave radio, they said.
But each time I've written about it, readers from all around the
country have responded with memories and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   My own theory is that there is a magic in the ghostly voices and
music that we hear directly from the source amongst the static. The
first question my friends have when I brag about talking via ham
radio to another operator in some far-off country is about what I
can do with ham radio that I can't do Internet.
</P>
<P>
   After all, anyone with a computer and $20 a month for an
Internet service provider can instantly exchange e-mails and even
voice messages with folks all over the world. And with ham radio _
unlike the good-buddy world of citizens band radio _ fairly
demanding tests are required to get a license from the Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   So why go to all that trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I tell my friends. Some of them understand
immediately; others look at me as if I had confessed to a
fascination with collecting matchbook covers. You'll have to decide
for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The way the world is today, most of the information we get is
filtered.
</P>
<P>
   If you read newspapers, and I hope you do, the words you read
have been selected by a reporter and edited by several editors
before they reach your eyes. When you see and hear a big shot on
television, those words and seconds of video have been selected
based on an army of opinions and prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   With ham radio, I am able to talk directly to people in
countries that are in the news. Unlike with an e-mail, I can hear
the tone of voice, sometimes even the family dog barking in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   And even when I use my radio to simply listen to the commercial
broadcasts from these countries _ something you can do yourself, no
license required, with a $100 shortwave from Radio Shack or other
retail outlets _ I can linger for hours. I don't just hear
headlines on these foreign broadcast stations. I can hear the
music, hear the commentary (most of the stations have English
language services), hear the comedies, listen to the radio plays.
... I get a more complete picture than I would ever have from
newspapers or television alone.
</P>
<P>
   All I can do here, because space is limited, is tell you what to
do next, if any of this strikes a chord in your heart. If ham radio
interests you, there's an excellent Web site maintained by the
American Radio Relay League at www.arrl.org where you can get
licensing information free. And, if shortwave listening appeals to
you, look in your favorite bookstore for Passport to World Band
Radio. It has reviews of commercial radios and frequencies of
foreign radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Radio isn't the sort of hobby that will make you rich and
famous, but _ if you are wired just right inside _ it will enrich
your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
