<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-TOOLS12-COX     10-11 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mad magazine slips into CD-ROM realm
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A couple of years ago, I hailed the issuance on CD-ROM
of every page of every issue of National Geographic magazine. I
called it a milestone in software publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, I found the publication of every National Geographic
foldout map only slightly less monumental.
</P>
<P>
   This year we have every page of every issue of Mad magazine. My,
how the publishing pendulum doth swing.
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to say, surely, that somewhere in the pages of all
the National Geographic magazines ever published, there is
something for everyone. It is not, however, safe to say that about
Mad magazine.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember, dimly, the days when I looked forward to the
appearance of each new issue, with trenchant and hilarious parodies
of current films and radio programs.
</P>
<P>
   Television, for those of you whose parents weren't even born
then, was in its very infancy. It wasn't available in many areas
and even when it was, not many people had a set.
</P>
<P>
   It has probably been 40 years since I looked at a copy of Mad.
The old issues I so enjoyed seem pretty silly now. I don't even
understand much of the newer issues. This is only to be expected,
since in my view television humor, for instance, has been in a
steady decline since the halcyon days of Sid Caesar and Ernie
Kovacs.
</P>
<P>
   As with the National Geographic productions, the Mad magazine
compendium is achieved by scanning in the pages of each issue. Thus
the early ones are displayed on realistically yellowed paper and
faded colors, the later on bright white stock and rich color.
</P>
<P>
   One can also find a certain degree of fascination in the gradual
loosening of publishing taboos over the past 50 years. But of
course, one could find that in the complete page-by-page compendium
of every issue of Playboy, too _ and I suspect that is not far
away.
</P>
<P>
   The interface is reasonably simple but not without problems, at
least on my system. When I select a title within any of the
magazines, it appears in the form of illegible stripes of color.
After zooming in on the pages, they suddenly straighten out and
everything is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Page-turning is just slow enough to be mildly annoying.
</P>
<P>
   If you remember something about the old issues that you
particularly enjoyed, you can enter key words and find the issue in
which it appeared, and the CD-ROM on which it resides. There are
various little side features of mostly sophomoric humor not
directly taken from the magazine, but certainly within its spirit.
</P>
<P>
   This magnum opus of comic-book parody is brought to us on seven
CD-ROMs courtesy of Broderbund.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot in good conscience recommend it to everyone. If it has
been many years since you've seen Mad magazine, I would suggest you
invest in a current issue of it as a kind of test drive before you
lay out $70 for the whole ferschlugginer mess.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
