<P>
   EDIT-POPULATION _ Greetings to the planet's 6th billionth
inhabitant, born today accoring to U.N. estimates. World population
crisis seems to have abated slightly, but that's no reason to let
up on global effort to promote family planning, economic
development and education and empowerment of females, all fo which
have salutary effet on brith rates. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
8.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Public school educators in Muscogee
County, Ga., had teacher aides touch up 2,300 copies of a social
study text containing the famous painting ``George Washington
Crosses the Delaware.'' It seems someone noticed that if you looked
at it from a certain angle, George's watch fob could be mistaken by
a fifth-grader for tiny, misplaced genitalia. No compliment, that,
to the purported Father of Our Country. (Rosenfeld, Cox News
Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ MIAMI, Fla. _ This is my hometown. I grew up
here back in the '50s when gasoline cost 19 cents a gallon, and the
only ``runners'' anybody'd ever heard of were the rum kind who
flourished on the Florida coast during prohibition. Life was good,
but try to convince a kid of that. (Schuett, Cox News Service)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ When you think about it, it's
scary, all the life forms out there trying to share inner domains.
Wish I didn't have to think about it. (John Young is opinion page
editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
