<HEADER>
A3153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     10-11 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL APPEALS COURTS IN CRISIS _ JUSTICE IS DELAYED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to Alliance for Justice, a nonprofit public interest
advocacy group in Washington, D.C., five of the 11 federal circuit
courts of appeal are facing judicial emergencies because of
unfilled vacancies on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   Judges in those federal appellate courts with a number of vacant
judgeships must take up the cases that would be given to new
appointments _ if they were ever confirmed. The increased workloads
mean decisions on cases in those overloaded federal appellate
courts take more much time. Justice is delayed _ as much as three
years or more.
</P>
<P>
   Some of President Clinton's nominations to the federal bench
have taken even longer than two years to be confirmed or denied
confirmation by the Senate after hearings before the Senate
Judiciary Committee and the committee's recommendations. And some
of the president's nominations to fill a judgeship have come only
after more than two years of a vacancy. Justice is delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan Citizens for Independent Courts, an offshoot of
The Century Foundation's Constitution Project headquartered in the
nation's capitol, blames both the president and the Senate
Judiciary Committee for the delays that have created this judicial
crisis. After a task force studied the situation, Citizens for
Independent Courts issued a report in September entitled ``Justice
Held Hostage: Politics and Selecting Federal Judges.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, judicial nominations have slowed down
considerably since President Carter's term in office. He took an
average of 240 days to nominate a federal judge; President Reagan
took 254 days; President Bush took 296 days; Clinton takes an
average of 315 days. Justice delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The report also points out that same tardiness from the Senate
Judiciary Committee, which must recommend confirmation or not, and
the Senate, which votes on the nomination. During the 96th Congress
(Carter was president), it took an average of 90 days to confirm or
deny a nomination. During the 100th Congress (Reagan), it took an
average of 144 days to confirm a nomination; during the 102nd
Congress (Bush), it took 138 days. But for the 105th Congress
(Clinton), it took an average of 201 days to confirm or deny a
nomination to the federal judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   From vacancy to nomination to confirmation in Carter's day took
an average of 330 days _ less than 11 months. In the last session
of Congress, it took Clinton and the Senate an average of 516 days
to fill a vacancy on the federal bench _ approximately 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the number of federal lawsuits filed in a 17-month
period. And there aren't sufficient numbers of federal judges to
handle the workload. It means delays. It means it is likely that
clerks, not judges, are doing a great deal of the work and
analyzing cases they don't have the experience or the legal
foundation to bring to bear.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting phenomenon came to light while the data was being
gathered and analyzed for the report: It takes the Senate nearly a
month longer to confirm female nominees than male nominees. And it
takes two months longer to confirm or deny judicial nominees who
belong to racial minorities. Those figures shouldn't surprise
anyone _ the Senate Judiciary Committee and the Senate itself are
very nearly ``white male only'' clubs. Is it any wonder then that
fewer than 20 percent of federal judges are women? And less than 17
percent are from minorities?
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be a new litmus test working in the Senate. It
has nothing to do with judicial philosophy or judicial temperament;
it's based upon gender and race.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Senate rejected the nomination of Missouri
Supreme Court Judge Ronnie L. White to a federal district court in
his state. His credentials are impeccable. He was the first black
to be named to the Missouri high court. In June 1997, Clinton
nominated White to a federal judgeship. White waited over two years
to be denied. The vote was down party lines: 54 Republicans against
confirmation, 45 Democrats for confirmation. Sen. John Ashcroft,
R-Mo., led the opposition to White's confirmation, complaining that
law enforcement groups in Missouri were against White because he
dissented too often in capital punishment cases.
</P>
<P>
   If race wasn't the reason the Senate rejected White's
confirmation to the federal bench, and his dissent in capital
punishment cases was the reason, it is still the wrong reason _ the
incredibly wrong reason. We cannot have an independent judiciary if
senators let law enforcement groups determine how they will vote on
the confirmation of judges.
</P>
<P>
   If judges were to become the stooges of police departments, it
would be the end of freedom as we know it. In those countries where
the judiciary is the servant of the police or the military, a
dictatorship exists or is in the process of arising. Civil rights
and civil liberties are clubbed and shot down in the streets. And
die there.
</P>
<P>
   We can hope that the report and recommendations issued by the
Citizens for Independent Courts are read and thoughtfully
considered. We've had enough of making the federal judiciary a
political football, to be kicked around by senators and presidents.
</P>
<P>
   There are citizens waiting for some relief from the federal
courts, waiting for money owed to them, waiting for a corporation
to clean up its pollution, waiting to get the rights guaranteed to
them under the Constitution _ waiting for some sense of justice.
</P>
<P>
   There are many judicial nominees waiting to be confirmed or
denied. The Senate needs to pressure the Senate Judiciary Committee
to hold hearings and move on the nominations. The people are
waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
