<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3160 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-ART-OF-HANDWRITING-LI     10-11 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-OF-HANDWRITING-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOST ART OF HANDWRITING
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color graphic of handwriting) 
 By ALLISON CLARK 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With computers taking over more and more of our written
communication, perfect penmanship may be going the way of spoken
Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Technologies such as e-mail, voice mail, pagers and cell phones
dominate the realm where pen and paper once ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Students are still practicing rote handwriting exercises in
elementary school, but they're learning to type on PCs at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We write a lot less by hand now,'' says Kate Gladstone,
director of the Annual American Handwriting Competition. ''The good
side of that is that we are less fatigued, so when we do write, we
can give a little more attention to that nominal handwriting we do.
But the bad side is that we get less practice. It's almost as if
our hands don't work when they start to write.''
</P>
<P>
   So what are the consequences of becoming a nation of illegibles?
Does it matter if our descenders dip too low or if our t's are
improperly tilted? Gladstone says yes.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of computer information originates as writing _ phone
numbers, messages, faxes,'' she said. ''We write down the stuff
that has to be super quick, but it also has to be super accurate.
Try writing down a Web page address with a sloppy letter _ you miss
just one letter and you've lost the information.''
</P>
<P>
   Another side effect comes into play when children are learning
to write, Gladstone said. Youngsters learn in part by watching
their older siblings and parents form letters. When typing replaces
longhand in the home, that example is missing.
</P>
<P>
   ''To make an `o,' you start at 12 o'clock and go
counterclockwise. You don't start at 6 o'clock or 3 o'clock. But
you'll see kids doing that now,'' she said. ''It used to be
something you only saw in kids with a perception disability, or
from houses that were illiterate. Now teachers see it with every
kind of background, especially from the top socioeconomic classes
where they're more likely to have computers.''
</P>
<P>
   But extra attention to penmanship in the classroom, say
teachers, would come at the expense of other, perhaps more worthy,
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ''Compared to 15 years ago, handwriting is less emphasized,''
said Wanda Rentfrow, a curriculum resource teacher at Archer
Elementary outside Gainesville, Fla. ''As a parent and a teacher,
you have to pick your battles. Some children simply do not have the
physical ability to have really nice penmanship. Why cause them
that frustration when you could be teaching them how to read?''
</P>
<P>
   Good penmanship has always been founded on conformity, historian
Tamara Plakins Thornton says in her book, ''Handwriting in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the industrial age, the uniform strokes of the Palmer
method were the norm, and the concept of expressing individuality
through handwriting was unheard of. After all, no one was demanding
flexibility in subtraction or spelling.
</P>
<P>
   Even left-handedness was seen as wayward, associated with
''criminals, insane persons, imbeciles, epileptics, vagrants and
social failures of various sorts,'' as one 1913 magazine article
reported. Today's penmanship allows a slightly wider spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not like when I was in school, where you sat up straight
with the paper at a certain angle and someone patrolled the aisles
to reposition you,'' said Nancye Childers, director of the
Gainesville, Fla., Country Day School, where children from
preschool to fifth grade learn the Zaner-Bloser method, a
combination print-script style.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of the fifth-graders have very classically perfect
handwriting. But there is more individuality in their writing,''
Childers said. ''They practice writing in terms of fluency more
than the perfect form.''
</P>
<P>
   If standards have relaxed across the board, it may be out of
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time teachers can spend on handwriting is increasingly
less, but the demands are the same,'' Gladstone said. ''They may
not have time to do more than pass out a work sheet and collect it
and put a check on it if it's remotely acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequences may arise on standardized tests, where essay
portions are graded outside of the school by people unfamiliar with
the students' writing.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the writing is legible, messy penmanship can detract
from how information is received on a subconscious level, Gladstone
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A more attractive paper gets a better grade,'' she said.
''Studies have shown that the same paper written in a different
hand can vary by almost a letter grade, and these are people who
have been told not to take handwriting into account,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gladstone believes the problem is in how children are taught to
write.
</P>
<P>
   ''You never see writing on a shopping bag or logo that looks
like the script we teach kids. Yet we tell them that's how adults
write,'' she said. ''The basis of the handwriting we teach them _
the vertical line and the circle _ are the hardest shapes for a
person to make. A professional draftsperson needs tools to do this.
So of course we make 5-year-olds do it freehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the speed and neatness of typing, along with the cushy
spell-checking and editing functions of computers, the keyboard may
ultimately prove to be mightier than the pen.
</P>
<P>
   Take the science projects at Country Day, where fifth-grade
students were given the choice of writing or typing their papers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every single one of them came in typed,'' Childers said. ''The
students thought they looked more official.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Childers believes good penmanship has a place in a
point-and-click world. ''There's still a lot of writing that goes
on,'' she said. ''I don't think it will disappear completely _ I
hope not.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we still have a sentimental attachment to script. What
else could account for all those handwriting fonts on word
processing programs? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Alisson Clark writes with The Gainesville Sun in Florida.)
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
