<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-UNITED-NATIONS-QUIZ-L     10-11 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-NATIONS-QUIZ-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST-YOUR-KNOWLEDGE-OF-THE-UNITED-NATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  By NORMAN ZIEROLD 
 c.1999 Norman Zierold 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The need for an organization like the United Nations was
recognized 200 years ago by Napoleon Bonaparte who said, ''If we
want peace, nations should avoid the pinpricks that precede
cannon-shots.'' In the half century since its establishment, The
United Nations has not always been able to forestall wars, but it
has defused a great number of incipient conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the purposes of our annual observance of United Nations
Day on October 24 is to look back at what this international
organization has accomplished over its lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dealing with disputes between nations, the United
Nations has played a valuable role in many other areas: setting up
the International Atomic Energy Agency, for example, and drafting
the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and three sponsoring
treaties on the peaceful use of outer space and the seabed.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quiz to test your knowledge of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   1. Q. Was the United Nations the first organization of its type
in modern times?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. The League of Nations, founded after World War I, was its
precursor. The League, however, was unable to prevent World War II
and was formally dissolved in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   2. Q. When was the United Nations founded?
</P>
<P>
   A. In April 1945 at the Conference on International Organization
which met in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   3. Q. Was this the first time the term was used?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. As early as 1941 the United States and Great Britain
signed the Atlantic Charter, which served notice that they would
set up a world organization when peace was restored. The following
year, 26 nations signed the Declaration of the United Nations in
Washington, D.C., the first use of the term. President Franklin
Delano Roosevelt coined the name to describe the countries fighting
the Axis powers in World War 11.
</P>
<P>
   4. Q. At the founding conference in San Francisco an American
diplomat who later became very controversial served as executive
secretary. Can you name him?
</P>
<P>
   A. Alger Hiss.
</P>
<P>
   5. Q. How many nations participated in the founding conference?
</P>
<P>
   A. 50. All 50 agreed to adopt the Charter. Poland, not present,
signed later, making 51.
</P>
<P>
   6. Q. What are the purposes of the United Nations?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Charter lists four major purposes: (1) to maintain
international peace and security; (2) to encourage friendly
relations among states based on the principle that all have equal
rights; (3) to promote international cooperation in solving social,
economic, and cultural problems; and (4) to serve as the agency
through which members can act to achieve these goals.
</P>
<P>
   7. Q. Can you name the major organs set up by the Charter?
</P>
<P>
   A. The General Assembly, the Security Council, the Economic and
Social Council, the International Court of Justice, the Trusteeship
Council, and the Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
   8. Q. The Secretariat handles all administrative matters and is
headed by its secretary general. The first three occupants of this
post all became quite well-known. Who were they?
</P>
<P>
   A. Trygve Lie of Norway, Dag Hammarsksjold of Sweden, and U
Thant of Burma.
</P>
<P>
   9. Q. Of the six major organs set up by the Charter, which has
the most clout?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Security Council was so designed. It is composed of five
permanent members _ China, France, Great Britain, Russia, and the
United States _ and 10 nonpermanent members elected by the General
Assembly for two-year terms. It can investigate disputes and
recommend means of settling them, including breaking off diplomatic
relations, economic sanctions, and collective military measures.
</P>
<P>
   10. Q. What is a significant weakness in the power of the
Security Council?
</P>
<P>
   A. Permanent members have the right to veto virtually any
decision, often blocking action. As a consequence, the General
Assembly's role has expanded to meet repeated challenges. In
emergencies where the Security Council fails to act, it can
recommend U.N. action, including use of armed force.
</P>
<P>
   11. Q. How is the General Assembly structured?
</P>
<P>
   A. It is a highly visible forum, with each nation, large or
small, having a single vote. A small island nation of 10,000
exercises an equal vote with 1-billion-strong China. While current
issues tend to grab public attention, the Assembly also supervises
activities of the Economic and Social Council, the Trusteeship
Council, and the specialized agencies.
</P>
<P>
   12. Q. What are some of the specialized agencies?
</P>
<P>
   A. Among the better known are the World Health Organization
(WHO), the International Labor Organization (ILO), the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), and the United Nations
Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
   13. Q. What is UNICEF?
</P>
<P>
   A. The United Nations International Children's Emergency Fund.
It helps children and adolescents worldwide, especially where the
need is greatest, in devastated areas and developing countries. For
its wide-ranging efforts, UNICEF was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize
in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   14. Q. How is the United Nations secretary-general chosen?
</P>
<P>
   A. He is appointed by the General Assembly upon the
recommendation of the Security Council for a term of five years,
and he may be reelected. He is in charge of a group of civil
servants whose loyalty is expected to be to the world community at
large. His role as the embodiment of the UN as a whole gives him
considerable diplomatic influence.
</P>
<P>
   15. Q. Who is the current secretary-general?
</P>
<P>
   A. Kofi Annan of Ghana is the seventh to hold the post.
</P>
<P>
   16. Q. How has the composition of the United Nations changed
since its inception more than half a century ago?
</P>
<P>
   A. At the outset, Western nations predominated. Today, with a
constantly rising membership, the majority of nations are nonwhite
third-world countries.
</P>
<P>
   17. Q. How many members are there today?
</P>
<P>
   A. The membership, at 185, is edging up toward the 200 mark.
Since there are numerous Territories or Protectorates which may
eventually become states, the prospect of 200 may not be that far
off.
</P>
<P>
   18. Q. The World Almanac tells us that there are 192 independent
countries in the world. That means there are seven which have not
joined the United Nations. Who are they?
</P>
<P>
   A. Kiribati, Nauru, Tonga, Tuvalu, Taiwan, Switzerland, and
Vatican City. Some small lands eschew membership expenses; Taiwan
incurs China's veto; and spunky little Switzerland, it seems, is
just not a joiner.
</P>
<P>
   19. Q. Can you name the official languages of the UN?
</P>
<P>
   A. Arabic, Chinese, English, French, Russian, and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   20. Q. Only one nation has ever withdrawn from the United
Nations. Can you name it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Indonesia withdrew, but rejoined less than two years later.
</P>
<P>
   21. Q. Where is the U.N. headquarters?
</P>
<P>
   A. In New York City on land donated in large part by John D.
Rockefeller, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   22. Q. What is the origin of the quote: ''Since wars begin in
the minds of men, it is in the minds of men that the defenses of
peace must be constructed?''
</P>
<P>
   A. The constitution of UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Norman Zierold is a North Carolina-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
