<HEADER>
A3173 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MUSIC-COOPER-KANSAS-K     10-11 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-COOPER-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICE COOPER TEES OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TIMOTHY FINN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's 51 and he can do what he wants, which means Alice Cooper
plays lots of golf and lots of loud rock music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially I don't have to do this,'' he said. ``I choose to
do it. When I'm off tour, by the time eight or nine months go by, I
want to be back on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper is finishing up the latest leg of what he called his
``Rock 'n' Roll Carnival Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing this show for two years now,'' he said.
``It's time to put it to bed. Next summer we'll start a whole new
show based on a new album that will be called `Brutal Planet.'
It'll be Alice's new-century address: very pessimistic, very
apocalyptic, very hard rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this current show is for the Alice fans. We do all the
hits plus some deep album cuts, gems that only the hard-core fans
will know.''
</P>
<P>
   From Washington last week, Cooper (born Vincent Furnier) talked
about his hometown, golf and Goth rock at the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You must have noticed that several performers are still doing
what you started almost 30 years ago _ Marilyn Manson, Rob Zombie.
What do you think about that?
</P>
<P>
   A: I admire anyone who goes out of their way to do a show. I may
not agree with everything they say or do, but at least they are
doing a show. Even Cher, I've heard, puts on a real extravaganza.
Now that's obviously not my kind of music, but you've got to
appreciate her making the effort to do a real production for her
audience.
</P>
<P>
   I think some of this is a backlash against the Seattle//slacker
stuff where bands were withdrawn and boring. Why be boring? Have
some fun. Rock shows should be like movies: I don't go to a movie
hoping it'll change my life. When I saw ``Jaws 3,'' it wasn't a
great movie, but it was worth the seven bucks to see the shark eat
the helicopter. It was a wonderful waste of time. ...
</P>
<P>
   I like to think I was responsible for knocking some barriers
down in the late '60s. Back then, you weren't allowed to say ``show
biz'' and ``rock'' in the same breath because rock was anti-show
biz. Everyone was like James Taylor, very into peace and love and
``I wanna change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Alice Cooper came around, and it scared everyone. It was
like Busby Berkeley meets ``A Clockwork Orange.'' There was
violence, but it was choreographed, a la ``West Side Story.'' I
don't like real violence, of course; this was theater, a show.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You come from Detroit, like a lot of other hard-core rockers
and shockers: Iggy Pop, the MC5 and now the Insane Clown Posse, Kid
Rock and Eminem. How has your hometown influenced you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Alice Cooper actually broke out of Detroit. We tried to get
started in L.A., but they hated us. The only bands who would take
us out on tour were the Doors and the Mothers of Invention. So we
moved back to Detroit, where they ate us up. We'd play gigs with
the Stooges and the MC5 and fit right in with that.
</P>
<P>
   The difference? In L.A., people go, ``Hmmm. Let's see, who's
playing tonight: Oh, Iggy and Alice.'' Then they go home from work,
change out of their nice work clothes into Levi's, a black T-shirt
and black boots and then drive to the show. In Detroit, they show
up straight from work in jeans and boots. And in Detroit you never
see anyone plugging their ears. In fact, they'll kill you for not
being loud enough.
</P>
<P>
   The other difference: Detroiters are viciously loyal. I'm still
a huge Lions and Tigers fan because I'm a dyed-in-the-wool
Detroiter. It has totally infected my music. I'll never be in a
band unless it has at least two guitars. I don't go for the
keyboard//horns thing. I want big, loud guitars. And that's pure
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have become an accomplished golfer. How did Alice find
golf?
</P>
<P>
   A: I started 17 years ago, when I stopped drinking. My wife says
I traded one bad habit for another, but I had to fill my time with
something. Time is the enemy for an alcoholic: You sit around
watching TV and you think, ``I'd love a beer.'' So for two years or
so, I played 36 holes a day. I got hooked and I got really good. I
was playing with pros every day. My handicap went from like 39 to 9
in one year. Now it's 3, and I can pretty much play 3 anywhere. ...
</P>
<P>
   I keep Alice and golf separate though. I never impose golf on
Alice. Or him on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-PERSON-CHANGE-KANSAS-     10-11 1715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSON-CHANGE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHOICE TO CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new Tracy Allen glances back at the old one and shakes her
head at the sorry picture. Given to angry outbursts or the silent
treatment. Always finding somebody else to blame. Feeling miserable
and reveling in it.
</P>
<P>
   The old Tracy Allen drove people away. They never knew what to
expect from her. When her supervisors tempered a generally
favorable job evaluation with concerns about her angry outbursts,
Tracy faced the depths of her problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew right then that this can't continue,'' Allen says. ``I
realized it was going to destroy my life. I realized I'd better do
something about this right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That was two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Allen subsequently joined a support group for people disabled by
their anger. She began to talk to a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she says, ``I realize that life isn't peaches and cream. It
isn't fair. We can cross our arms and stick our lips out and become
angry and get into the blame game, or we can learn to deal with
what life's thrown at us. We have a choice to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Choices. Along with genes and neurochemicals and environmental
factors such as the way we were toilet-trained, they have a lot to
do with who we are. Science has long grappled with the question of
our makeup _ physical, emotional, mental. With how much of us is
fixed and how much of us is elastic.
</P>
<P>
   Every few weeks it seems another gene is found and identified,
our fate further sealed. The early-to-bed, early-to-rise gene. The
gene that determines how much trouble one is likely to have
quitting smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But there remains much that under the right circumstances, given
effective guidance, driven by enough desire, can be altered. Panic
disorder, pessimistic thinking, depression and sexual dysfunctions
are notable examples, according to Martin Seligman, a University of
Pennsylvania psychology professor and author of the book What You
Can Change &AMP; What You Can't.
</P>
<P>
   Julienne Thomas, an Overland Park pastoral psychotherapist who
consults with patients mostly about their marital and family
difficulties, puts it this way: ``I wouldn't be in this business if
I didn't think it was absolutely possible to generate change.''
</P>
<P>
   Will to change
</P>
<P>
   Charles Welsh is also in the change business. He's the clinical
director for psychiatric services at Research Mental Health
Services. He knows people can remake parts of themselves. He's done
it. Remade himself at midlife from minister to graduate student to
psychologist. From one who smokes to one who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Change can happen, he'll tell you. But within certain parameters
and grounded in certain prerequisites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some features of personality are more changeable than others.
Some people are more willing to change than others. Some are more
interested than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Most amenable to change, he says, is ``the person who values
learning, change and growth ... who wants to find better ways to
live ... who wants to read a lot, learn a lot and associate with
others for positive causes.'' And, it should be noted, who can
relate to the old light-bulb joke: How many psychiatrists does it
take to change a light bulb? Just one, provided the bulb wants to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I address with people is, `Are you willing to
change?' If you're willing to consider other ways, if you're
willing to attempt it, to experiment _ and that requires an act of
commitment _ that can surmount what one would call deficits in
ability. Change takes place more as an act of will than as an act
of being able.''
</P>
<P>
   Journey man
</P>
<P>
   Ben Worth was on schedule and on target for the good life. He
was just waiting for the satisfaction to kick in.
</P>
<P>
   He'd followed the prescription. He'd racked up a law degree and
an MBA. He was a lawyer in general practice, working hard, working
Saturdays, bringing home lots of money. He'd purchased a big house
in Johnson County and filled it with lots of stuff. He'd been
married to the same woman since 1968. His daughter was on the
high-school tennis team.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for the big emotional payoff. He kept waiting. Then
he started to wonder: Why didn't it feel better? He began looking
for answers in marriage counseling, in men's groups, in a search
for a spiritual life.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I looked more deeply at things, I saw that this isn't what
I want to do with the rest of my life,'' he says. Gradually he left
law practice. He and his wife divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Worth says he made a 180-degree turn from Type A to ``laid back,
easygoing, spiritually oriented,'' from focused on work to focused
on people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very goal-oriented. Now I'd say I'm process-oriented. I
enjoy the journey now. I didn't before.''
</P>
<P>
   He married a woman on the same spiritual path and moved to
Raytown. Three years ago he established the American Buddhist
Center at Unity Temple on the Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   In his mission to remake his life, Worth, 53, sought out many
resources, such as counselors and support groups. Meditation was
one of the primary tools that he says helped him to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Those who would remake themselves must have ``the courage to
look deep within, to shift your focus from the outer world and what
everyone else is telling you you should want and examine your
belief system in light of what works for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Another powerful strategy, Worth says, is ``associating with
like-minded people. Rather than continuing to sit around having a
drink with friends and bitching about life, you associate with
people who want to share the challenge of looking inward.''
</P>
<P>
   The cartography of character
</P>
<P>
   Jack Mayer has for years studied the structure of personality
and the interplay of thought and emotion. An associate professor of
psychology at the University of New Hampshire-Durham, Mayer has
concluded that our personality traits are pretty well entrenched.
But here's the good news: He says that ``almost any trait... can be
changed through learning and creating better mental models.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that learning for most people is rather flexible,'' he
says. ``We know we can change people through education.''
</P>
<P>
   Say, for example, that an introvert wants to become more
sociable at parties, but her mental model of her social environment
_ her mental map _ has always told her that people ignore her at
parties. By observing and learning from a morlly skilled
friend that when people at parties are engaged in conversation they
often appear to be ignoring other people, our introvert can, in
effect, redraw her mental map. She can, Mayer asserts, learn to see
her social interactions more objectively.
</P>
<P>
   Growth factor
</P>
<P>
   The event that launched Mary Jane Hart's journey was the death
in 1988 of her son, Tyler. It unleashed lots of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to find out who I was and what I came here to do. I
felt I had to find some answers. I had grown up doing what
everybody told me to do, but I felt there was something not right
with that. I think I totally lost touch with myself and my views.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 she joined a group aimed at bolstering self-esteem. It
lead her to conclude that she had subjugated her needs to those of
her husband and six children, that she had learned subservience and
dependence and needed to unlearn them.
</P>
<P>
   She began to say no. She learned how to deal with the car
mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you do that, you're defining who you are,'' the
Independence woman says.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, at 54, she began working outside the home for the
first time in 25 years. In May she divorced her husband of 27
years.
</P>
<P>
   Change is scary, she says. And in her case, it involved a fear
of being rejected by people she loves. When she felt herself in the
grip of fear, she would ask herself: ``Where is this fear coming
from? What's it stopping me from reaching?''
</P>
<P>
   And she would remind herself of her counselor's constant
admonition: Growth is choosing to act in a different way in the
face of the same old feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Note to self
</P>
<P>
   When Tracy Allen decided to master her anger, she got a little
green notebook and kept it with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I'd start getting angry or irritated, I would take
this notebook out. I'd start thinking, `What are my body signs?'
For me it was chest pounding and tension in the neck and shoulders.
I'd get fidgety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask myself questions like, `What's my mind talk?'
There were comments in my mind like, `I don't like you. Why can't
it be done right? I just want to give up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then Allen, who lives in Overland Park, would jot down what she
wished for at that moment: Peace. Not to be judged. Respect.
Support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used that little green notebook. That was the beginning
stage to help me think about, `Why am I angry?' ''
</P>
<P>
   With help from Jerry Medol, who leads several anger-management
groups, Allen concluded that much of her hostility was a response
to her feeling abandoned as an adolescent by her mother, when her
mother became seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   A natural introvert, Allen, 37, says the notebook helped her
begin talking to people, telling them how she was feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing I've learned is ... you need to ask yourself,
`Is this a hill I want to die on?' Whenever you feel you have to
prove a point or get back at someone, you have to think if you want
to suffer the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the assist she got from her anger support group
and Medol, Allen says her faith in God reinforced her efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me a lot about who I am and who he is. God loves me
and has a great plan for me. That doesn't mean God is going to let
everything good happen in my life. There's been a lot of good, but
there's been some not-so-good. But he still loves me.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen also developed an appreciation for what she has, and she
began to shed the cherished image of herself as a downtrodden,
miserable victim. That meant giving up the attention it had
garnered for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got too many people walking around as victims. You have
a choice to pick up and go on. I'm excited about my life, the
direction it's going. I'm not saying I have completely forgotten
what's taken place in my life, but I don't let my past dictate my
present or future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
