<HEADER>
A3181 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-GRIFFITH-AND-BANDERAS     10-11 1454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIFFITH-AND-BANDERAS-IN-ALABAMA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRAZY' FOR EACH OTHER: MELANIE GRIFFITH AND ANTONIO BANDERAS TRY
SOMETHING NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Ina color slide of Melanie Griffith in a scene from ``Crazy
in Alabama.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Listening to Melanie Griffith's distinctive little-girl voice,
it's easy to take her lightly.
 &HT;    She may be a 42-year-old veteran of a quarter-century in the
movie business, with a resume that includes an Oscar nomination as
Best Actress, four marriages and three children by three different
fathers.
 &HT;    But when she starts talking, she could say the nastiest things
and it would be, well, cute.
 &HT;    Don't be fooled.
 &HT;    ``Melanie Griffith breaks your heart,'' says actor Antonio
Banderas, her husband of two years. ``But I don't think people
should be fooled into thinking she is weak. She is one of the
strongest women I know. She is a survivor, and I've never seen her
more sure of herself.''
 &HT;    After two years of marriage, Griffith and Banderas are still
acting like googly-eyed newlyweds. Just ask Griffith about their
recent weekend getaway to Paris.
 &HT;    ``We made love six times in one day and then flew home,'' she
says with a giggle.
 &HT;    Recently, Griffith lost a significant amount of weight, and
Banderas congratulated her with a massive diamond.
 &HT;    ``He's so romantic,'' she says, giggling again. ``I can't say
enough about my man.''
 &HT;    But Banderas' best gift may be Hollywood's taking her seriously
as an actress. In his first stint behind the camera, the
39-year-old Banderas directed her in ``Crazy in Alabama,'' a new
comedy/drama about women's rights and racial tolerance that's being
hailed in advance reviews as her best work in years.
 &HT;    The film has brought the two to an early-morning breakfast at
New York's Regency Hotel. Both are casually dressed _ she in
skintight blue jeans and a white T-shirt, he in blue jeans, a red
T-shirt and a matching baseball cap turned backward. Both are
smoking cigarettes, despite a hotel staffer's reminded that it's a
no-smoking floor.
 &HT;    ``Please,'' Griffith purrs in that unique voice, ``it's the only
vice I have left.''
 &HT;    The rule is waived, and the two puff on.
 &HT;    It was Griffith who first came across ``Crazy in Alabama,'' Mark
Childress' novel about a glamorous, eccentric Alabaman who kills
her abusive husband, chops off his head and sticks it in a
Tupperware container. Then she takes off for Hollywood to pursue
her dream of television stardom.
 &HT;    She engaged the author to write a screenplay for Green Moon
Productions, the production company she and Banderas recently
floated, and convinced Banderas to make it his directorial debut.
 &HT;    Marriages have foundered over one partner directing the other,
but both deny any special strain on their relationship.
 &HT;    ``We had a great time,'' Banderas says. ``But it was difficult
for me in my head, because I know we actors are very insecure. We
are very sensitive. I didn't want to touch a nerve within her that
would hurt our personal relationship. So we put it all on the table
and talked about it.
 &HT;    ``By the time she got on the set, she was ready to go.''
 &HT;    ``The best part is that we had this time to spend together,''
Griffith adds. ``And as a director, he's so fun and cool. When he
would watch a take, everyone would be waiting to see how Antonio
reacted. If he liked your acting, he would throw his hands in the
air and scream, `Yes! Yes!' It was very passionate on the set.
 &HT;    ``The worst part is that he knows me too well,'' she says. ``He
would know if I wasn't giving him everything he wanted. He would
say, `Do it again.' But I didn't get upset. I did as I was told. We
didn't fight for one minute.''
 &HT;    Which, she adds, was a good thing.
 &HT;    ``Temper-wise we really are different,'' Griffith explains. ``I
react in a flash _ I'm very emotional. He's the type that holds it
in there and then explodes.''
 &HT;    Banderas can understand the actor's point of view because he's
been a star for more than a decade _ first in his native Spain,
where he won acclaim in Pedro Almodovar's ``Women on the Verge of a
Nervous Breakdown'' (1988) and ``Tie Me Up! Tie Me Down!'' (1990),
and then in an American career which peaked in 1998 with ``The Mask
of Zorro.''
 &HT;    ``I had a plan to become a huge movie star,'' he says candidly.
``I felt like I had this empty space just waiting to be filled up.
I craved the fame.''
 &HT;    Griffith laughs. Born into the movie industry _ her mother is
the actress Tippi Hedron, best known for Alfred Hitchcock's ``The
Birds'' (1963) _ she never saw Hollywood from the outside, as her
husband did. In fact, she actually set out to be a model, only to
find that what she thought was a modeling audition was actually
casting for the film ``Night Moves'' (1975). She got the part and
was on her way, more or less in spite of herself.
 &HT;    ``It's like my entire career beginning was this big mistake,''
she says. ``I wanted to act, but I didn't like all the attention
that goes with it.''
 &HT;    Despite her share of hit movies _ most notably her
Oscar-nominated role in ``Working Girl'' (1988) _ that attention
has focused primarily on her private life. At age 14 she fell in
love with 22-year-old Don Johnson on the set of her mother's movie
``The Harrad Experiment'' (1973). They married when she turned 18,
only to divorce a year later. Next she married actor Steven Bauer
at 24, had a son and got divorced. She later remarried Johnson, had
a daughter and got divorced again.
 &HT;    By comparison, Banderas' life has been uneventful, involving
only a single divorce.
 &HT;    Griffith's second marriage to Johnson, which she declines to
discuss, was on the skids when she and Banderas were cast together
in ``Two Much'' (1996).
 &HT;    ``We fell in love while shooting,'' Banderas recalls. ``It was
unavoidable. Our love was like a big fire.
 &HT;    ``At first it seemed like this type of love was an illusion,''
he says. ``We were filming a movie. It was movieland, but once the
film ended, I found out that it was real. I needed her and she
needed me.''
 &HT;    Griffith got a quick divorce, and almost immediately Banderas
proposed.
 &HT;    ``I get down on my hands and knees on the beach of North
Carolina where I was filming a movie,'' he says. ``And Melanie
started laughing. Can you believe it? I thought she'd be crying,
but she was giggling.''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``And then Kim Basinger and Alec Baldwin walk up to us on the
beach in the middle of the proposal,'' he adds. ``They were also in
town filming a movie. I'm like, `Get out of here! I'm proposing!'''
 &HT;    Today the two live in a Spanish-style mansion in Brentwood,
Calif., with their 2-year-old daughter Stella and Griffith's other
two children, 9-year-old Dakota and 13-year-old Alexander.
 &HT;    ``I think the key to this marriage surviving is that you have to
love the person you have in front of you first thing in the
morning,'' Banderas says. ``I love her during the worst moments.
Yes, there are moments when love disappears, but then you find
yourself falling in love with your own wife again.''
 &HT;    Chances are their family will be expanding soon _ Griffith says
they'd like to have another baby next year.
 &HT;    ``We're working all the time on getting pregnant,'' she says
with that sugar-sweet voice and a roll of her eyes. ``We're
practicing all the time to meet our goals for the millennium.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
