<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-X-FILES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSING ENCOUNTERS? `THE X-FILES' BEGINS WHAT MAY BE ITS FINAL
SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of David Duchovny and Gillian Anderson in a
scene from ``The X-Files.'') 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the biggest cliffhanger of all for ``The X-Files'': Will
the show return after this, its seventh year?
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure: David Duchovny, who as FBI Agent Fox
Mulder made paranoia sexy, most likely won't be back. As he entered
the final year of his contract on the show, the actor sued Fox
Television, alleging that it had deprived him of syndication
profits to which he was rightfully entitled.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps it's just as well, because Duchovny is clearly
running out of patience with the show, as witness his response to a
question about fans' most popular topic, the relationship between
Mulder and Agent Scully (Gillian Anderson).
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell you how uninterested in that I am,'' he says.
``I could not make it clear enough.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the grand conspiracy that is the show's underlying
story?
</P>
<P>
   ``I care as little about that as I care about the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a done deal. But wait: Anderson is signed for
another year, and series creator Chris Carter admits that, while
he's writing this year as the show's final go-round, his mind could
still be changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd consider anything,'' Carter says. ``I would have to feel
good about the kinds of stories we were telling. I know Rod Serling
was very upset when they turned `Twilight Zone' into an hour show
from a half-hour show _ he felt that it wasn't right for the
stories, and that's when he bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it didn't feel right to me and it was just being done as a
commercial venture, I would be less interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox Television president Doug Herzog sees no need to make an
immediate decision on an eighth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything's possible,'' Herzog says. ``Ultimately, if everybody
wants to do it, I'm sure we'll figure out a way to do it. If not,
it won't get done. We'll have to cross that bridge when we get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny, who also wrote and directed last season's acclaimed
episode ``The Unnatural,'' stresses that if he leaves it will be to
pursue other career paths, not because he feels, as some fans have
complained, that the show lost its edge last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe four or five shows that we did were some of
the best that we've ever done,'' the actor says. ``We did some
clunkers _ we always do. I mean, we have the kind of show that
reaches further, in terms of story and execution, than any other
show on TV. So when we succeed we're better than any show on
television, and when we fail we can be worse than a lot of pretty
bad shows on television.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't return, Duchovny adds, Anderson could certainly
carry on without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I was indispensable at one point, I'm no longer
indispensable,'' he says with a shrug. ``Nobody is. It's a brand
name _ it's Crest, it's Menudo. Look at `NYPD Blue' _ I'd be an
idiot to sit here and say, `It's not going to go on without me.'''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, and then admits that it isn't that easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want it to,'' he concedes. ``I mean, there would be
a part of me that would be sitting at home wishing fervently that
it would fail. You know, I feel like it's mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Duchovny's eyes are on the big screen. Other than
the 1998 ``X-Files'' movie, his films _ ``Kalifornia'' (1993) and
``Playing God'' (1997) among them _ haven't done as well as his
television roles, which have also included a cross-dressing federal
agent on the cult favorite ``Twin Peaks'' and a turn as himself on
``The Larry Sanders'' show, where his flirting with Sanders caused
the host (Garry Shandling) to go into a panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My television history is really cool,'' Duchovny says,
``because I did `The X-Files,' `Twin Peaks' and `The Larry Sanders
Show' _ those are three great TV shows.''
</P>
<P>
   His next attempt to conquer the big screen will be ``Return to
Me,'' a romantic comedy written by and starring comedian Bonnie
Hunt, with whom he appeared in the movie ``Beethoven'' (1992). The
film was made during this past summer's hiatus from ``The
X-Files,'' and Duchovny admits that it was sometimes hard to keep
them separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple times when Bonnie would say, `This is
encroaching on `X-Files' a little bit,''' he admits. ``I don't know
_ that character is so much a part of me, and the differences can
be subtle. Sometimes you lose track.''
</P>
<P>
   But making the film got him thinking about ``what it is I want
to do with the rest of my life,'' he says. ``I'll turn 40 next
August, so I think it's a really good time to ask that.''
</P>
<P>
   The path ``The X-Files'' will follow, Duchovny thinks, is that
blazed by ``Star Trek,'' whether the series ends after this season
or in a year or two. So fans shouldn't expect a final episode that
will tie up all the loose ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show's going to continue on in movie form,'' he says, ``so
I don't think that we'll have to have any kind of end _ you know,
we're not going to blow the place up or have it all be a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll just keep teasing them,'' he says. ``The
interesting thing about everybody's interest in the relationship
between Mulder and Scully is that they want some kind of resolution
with that. But look at our show _ each week, something happens to
Mulder and/or Scully that is completely life-changing, and yet we
come back the next week as if nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be just as well, the actor adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `We want resolution, we want closure,''' Duchovny
says. ``But when you give them answers, they go, `That's not as
exciting as not knowing. Why did you tell me?'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The X-Files,'' consult the
official Website at www.thex-files.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
