<HEADER>
A3183 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-HILARY-SWANK-IN-BOYS-     10-11 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILARY-SWANK-IN-BOYS-DONT-CRY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT JUST ONE OF THE BOYS: HILARY SWANK AND `BOYS DON'T CRY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Hilary Swank with Chloe Sevigny in a
scene from ``Boys Don't Cry.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Boys don't cry, perhaps, but Hilary Swank does.
 &HT;    The tragic story of Brandon Teena brings tears to the young
actress' eyes, just as her breakthrough performance as the doomed
Teena is doing to many of those who see the film ``Boys Don't
Cry.''
 &HT;    The $1.4 million, reality-based drama, written and directed by
Kimberly Peirce and starring Swank and Chloe Sevigny, is currently
in limited theatrical release. It's a controversial story, all the
more so because it happens to be true.
 &HT;    Teena was no ordinary young man, mostly because he was a she _ a
Nebraska woman named Teena Brandon who pretended to be a man. Teena
fell in love with a woman (Sevigny) in 1993 and befriended her
family and pals, but was ultimately raped and murdered by those
same friends when they discovered her secret.
 &HT;    ``This had to be the most challenging role I've ever done, and
it could be the most challenging role I'll ever get to play,'' says
Swank, previously best known for her roles in ``The Next Karate
Kid'' (1994) and ``Beverly Hills, 90210.'' ``Knock on wood, this
won't be the best role I ever play, because I'm only 25.
 &HT;    ``I had plenty of doubts,'' she admits. ``There was a lot to do.
It was really important that I pass as a boy. And, any time you
play a real person, you've got trepidations because you want to
honor that person's memory in a respectful way.
 &HT;    ``Also, just in general, you want to rise to the challenge of a
good role.''
 &HT;    Pulling a De Niro, Swank worked out, underwent vocal training to
deepen her voice and cut off her long hair. She also went out on
the town, venturing into bars and other public places dressed and
behaving like a male.
 &HT;    The experience fascinated the actress.
 &HT;    ``I learned a lot about myself and a lot about humanity,'' says
Swank _ who, sporting a skintight halter sweater and a skirt during
a conversation in the bar at New York's Rihga Royal Hotel, is
unmistakably a woman. ``There were fun times, when people saw me
and treated me like a young boy, and there were other times when
people couldn't figure out what I was, and those people made me
feel very uncomfortable.
 &HT;    ``I found that very lonely,'' she says. ``People didn't want to
talk to me or even deal with me. Most of the bars I went to were
gay and lesbian bars, and there I was just another person. So I
found places where I fit in and places where I felt uncomfortable
and the people around me felt uncomfortable.
 &HT;    ``I'm glad I did it, though,'' she concludes, ``because it was
important for me, in terms of playing the character, to understand
even just a little of what Brandon experienced.''
 &HT;    The transformation into a boy was fascinating, the actress
reports.
 &HT;    ``Once I saw myself with my hair cut and looking completely
different, I thought, `Wow, what a wonderful thing to be able to
do,''' she says. ``It amazed me that I could be such a chameleon,
that my face could look so different.
 &HT;    ``That's a very exciting thing for an actor to find out.''
 &HT;    Swank also believes she came to understand Teena.
 &HT;    ``He only lived 21 years, but in those 21 years his life was so
full,'' she says, her eyes welling up. ``He lived every moment so
fully.
 &HT;    ``He had the courage to follow his dream,'' she says, ``and
there's nobody in the whole world who doesn't have a dream. Anybody
can relate to that. We all have dreams. That's why everyone can
relate to the film.
 &HT;    ``Some people may not want to see a movie about a transgender
person or a gay character,'' Swank adds, ``but to me the film
transcends all of that. It transcends gender and gets to a deeper
issue. It's about something that happened in our society, and
hopefully the film will make people think about how and why it was
allowed to happen, and also how we can stop it from happening
again.''
 &HT;    Though the film has already garnered stellar reviews, some
people are taking writer/director Peirce to task for fictionalizing
elements of Teena's saga. Given the brouhaha over the fictional
elements historian Edmund Morris has introduced into his Ronald
Reagan biography, ``Dutch,'' a ``Boys Don't Cry'' backlash may have
been inevitable.
 &HT;    Swank appears to be caught a bit off-guard by the issue, but
quickly jumps to her director's defense
 &HT;    ``What can be hard about telling a true story as a movie is that
it has to be a movie,'' she says. ``Kim puts it so well, but a
movie has to hit dramatic arcs and you have to tell so much in two
hours ... Kim had to squash Brandon Teena's story together and tell
whatever she felt were the most important parts. You can't touch on
everything unless you want it to be some epic film.
 &HT;    ``My feeling is we tried to be very loyal to Brandon and his
story,'' she says. ``Ultimately, it's public domain _ if someone
wants to take it and, like Kim did, tell it as she felt it
happened, that's her right.
 &HT;    ``I feel she did a great job. She told a story in an hour and 40
minutes that really does justice to it.''
 &HT;    Swank discovered her own passion for telling stories through
acting at an early age. Born in Lincoln, Neb. _ not far from where
``Boys Don't Cry'' takes place _ and raised in the state of
Washington, Swank was 8 when a teacher asked her to write a skit
and perform it before her classmates.
 &HT;    ``I remember standing up there and something in me came to
life,'' she says, a smile crossing her face. ``It felt so good and
so exciting. I ran home and said, `Mom, I want to be an actress.'
 &HT;    ``She said, `That's fun. Go play.'''
 &HT;    Undaunted, Swank became a regular in school plays and local
repertory theater. Eventually her mother came around.
 &HT;    ``When I was 15,'' she recalls, ``my mom _ who was separated
from my father and at a crossroads in her own life _ said, `You're
really serious about this, aren't you? Do you want to go down to
Los Angeles and give it a try?'
 &HT;    ``My mom has been a huge supporter and a driving force in my
career.''
 &HT;    In 1994, the 20-year-old actress had her first experience with
Hollywood's star-making machine. Her performance in the title role
of ``The Next Karate Kid'' was expected to put her on the map _
until the film flopped.
 &HT;    ``Looking back, I can say I'm glad it didn't happen,'' she says.
``I don't know what choices I would have made, because I was so
young. I didn't know what kinds of movies I wanted to do, and I
might have gotten myself pigeonholed. Now I'm doing what I love.''
 &HT;    In other words, now Swank acts only when she feels compelled to
do so. In fact, since wrapping ``Boys Don't Cry'' nearly a year
ago, she hasn't worked. Instead, she's been reading scripts, taking
meetings, traveling and relaxing at home in Los Angeles with her
husband of two years, actor Chad Lowe.
 &HT;    ``Hopefully `Boys Don't Cry' will just give me more choices and
let me do the work I respond to,'' she says. ``Then, if I have a
short career, at least I did it doing work I'm proud of.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Boys Don't Cry,'' consult the
official Website at www.boysdontcry.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
