<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MOVIES-DEADMEN-KANSAS     10-11 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DEADMEN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD MEN TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a dead guy starts talking, we tend to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Provided, of course, that we realize he's a dead guy.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Not if you've been going to the movies lately, where
dead guys have been doing a lot of talking. (Warning: If you
haven't seen ``Jakob the Liar'' or ``The Sixth Sense,'' you may not
want to read farther.)
</P>
<P>
   See if this sounds familiar:
</P>
<P>
   - In ``American Beauty,'' the disembodied voice of suburban
husband Lester Burnham (Kevin Spacey) guides us on a tour of his
life. Lester introduces himself by telling us: ``I'm 42 years old.
In less than a year I'll be dead. In a way, I'm dead already.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Lester is talking to us from beyond the grave.
</P>
<P>
   - In `the Liar,'' Robin Williams portrays a Jew who
entertains his fellow ghetto residents while awaiting the arrival
of Nazi troops who will take them to their deaths. Jakob narrates
the story; we don't realize until the end, when he's shot, that
he's been dead the whole time.
</P>
<P>
   - In ``The Sixth Sense,'' Bruce Willis plays a child
psychiatrist treating a boy plagued by the ghosts of people who
don't realize they're dead. In the end the shrink (and the
hoodwinked audience) realizes that he is himself one of those dead
people.
</P>
<P>
   - In ``Stir of Echoes'' the ghost of a murdered girl seeks
revenge on her killers by communicating first with a little boy and
later with the child's disbelieving father (Kevin Bacon).
</P>
<P>
   Right now we're experiencing a sudden pileup of loquacious
corpses, but the dead-man-talking is part of a long tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roman playwright Seneca used the device of a ghost seeking
revenge in his `Hercules Furens,' '' said Robert Wilson, professor
of English at the University of Missouri-Kansas City. ``And it has
been employed ever since. The most obvious example is Shakespeare's
`Hamlet.' Another Elizabethan play, Thomas Kidd's `The Spanish
Tragedy,' is also about a ghost seeking revenge. In that instance
the ghost is the play's narrator.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many religions and cultures around the globe entertain
the possibility that the recently deceased may not realize they're
no longer alive, it seems to be a fairly recent arrival in Western
literature.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more dramatic depictions of this circumstance was
Ambrose Bierce's 1891 short story ``An Occurrence at Owl Creek
Bridge.'' In that Civil War tale, a Southern spy is being hanged
from a bridge by Union troops. The rope snaps, he falls into the
stream below, escapes and makes his way to his home. Just as he
embraces his family, he finds himself once again dangling from a
rope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much later a French director made it into a short film which
played on TV's `Twilight Zone' in 1962,'' notes John Tibbetts,
assistant professor of film at the University of Kansas. ``Lots of
baby boomers vividly recall that telecast.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years after Bierce, the horror author H.P.
Lovecraft wrote the short story ``The Outsider,'' which might be
viewed as a prototype for the setup of ``Sixth Sense.'' Tibbetts
says: ``It's a first-person narrative about a man who emerges from
an underground bunker and wanders around before realizing he's dead
and has left his own grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Another example is the film ``Jacob's Ladder'' (1990) in which a
Vietnam veteran (Tim Robbins) finds himself tormented by hellish
visions. At the end of the film we realize that Jacob was killed in
the war and never returned home. The entire experience has been
either a depiction of the afterlife or a hallucination experienced
at the moment of Jacob's death.
</P>
<P>
   In this century Thornton Wilder's Pulitzer-winning play ``Our
Town'' depicts a graveyard in which the village's dead continue to
dwell, observing the living and little by little drifting away from
their earthbound existences.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous example of a dead narrator is
screenwriter Joe Gillis, played by William Holden in 1950's
``Sunset Boulevard.'' That film begins with a shot of Joe's corpse
floating in a swimming pool. The dead man becomes the teller of the
tale, often delivering sardonic comments on what we're witnessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll admit I don't really see the advantage of that
approach,'' Tibbetts said. ``It's the one thing about `Sunset
Boulevard' that really bothers me. Same thing with `American
Beauty' _ it seems like a cop-out. To me it indicates there's flaw
in the whole first-person narrator thing. Either you're dead or
you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, though, views the device as an effective
attention-getter: ``Talk about speaking with authority ... the
character is dead and still talking. Who's not going to pay
attention to what he has to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Both men agree, though, that there's no mystery as to why we're
all of a sudden getting so many movies about the chatty deceased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's both millennial _ as 2000 approaches lots of people are
getting nervous _ and a result of the fact that the baby boomers,
who are running Hollywood, are in their 50s,'' Tibbetts said.
``More than half our lives are gone, and that's what it's all
about. We're aware of our own mortality and are trying to deal with
that fact in our popular culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Movies and TV shows about individuals whose intellects survive
death offer reassurance, Tibbetts said. ``Also, films like
`American Beauty' may reflect the idea that many of us feel like
we're walking ghosts. In this new technological age, we're not sure
what our identities are any more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the recurring themes of Renaissance culture is memento
mori, or `remember me,' '' said Wilson. ``When you see paintings of
the saints in their cells, there's usually a skull on the desk. The
idea is to remind us that you will become this. It plays into the
idea that death is the great leveler. Doesn't matter if you're a
king or a commoner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
