<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDDIE-FISHER-LOOKS-BACK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC, MEMORIES AND REGRETS: EDDIE FISHER LOOKS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Eddie Fisher at a recent
book-signing.) 
 By MICHAEL J. BANDLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    When Eddie Fisher sees what's going on with Ricky Martin, pop
music's hottest heartthrob of the moment, he can relate. Back in
the 1950s, the same kind of spotlight was on him.
 &HT;    In 1951, for example, soon after he arrived at Fort Hood, Texas,
for basic training as a newly drafted private, Fisher turned out
with the other soldiers for his first mail call.
 &HT;    ``One guy got two letters, another got four,'' he recalls. ``I
got 4,500. I felt like I was almost the only person in the world _
everything was happening to me.''
 &HT;    Post-Sinatra and pre-Elvis, the Philadelphia-born singer's
records regularly topped the charts in the years immediately after
World War II. Today, however, he's best known for a series of
high-profile marriages _ to Debbie Reynolds, Elizabeth Taylor and
Connie Stevens _ that produced four children, including Tricia
Leigh, Joely, Todd and ``Star Wars'' heroine Carrie Fisher.
 &HT;    In retrospect, Fisher says, his is a story of missed
opportunities and unnecessary failures.
 &HT;    ``I get an A+ in poor judgment,'' he says. ``I should have paid
a thousand percent more attention to my music. I don't know if it
was laziness or the fact that everything came so easily to me.''
 &HT;    Behind the headlines, the marital and extramarital relationships
and the drug addiction that straitjacketed him for nearly four
decades was a golden-throated lyric baritone who had waves of
bobby-soxers swooning at New York's Paramount Theater and in movie
houses across the country. Crooning what he calls ``bubble-gum
songs'' _ among them ``Dungaree Doll,'' ``Lady of Spain'' and ``Oh
My Papa'' _ he was Frank Sinatra's heir apparent. But it wasn't to
be.
 &HT;    ``I didn't pay much attention to my career and my singing,''
Fisher admits. ``It looks like I did if you listen to the work, but
I certainly paid more attention to women and drugs.''
 &HT;    Fisher's voice was his ticket out of a dysfunctional immigrant
family buffeted by the Depression. First singing at services in a
local synagogue, he moved on to Philadelphia radio programs and
then into New York ballrooms and Catskills resorts, all before he
was 20. Soon recordings and then television beckoned.
 &HT;    Those days are long gone for the 71-year-old singer, who lives
with his fourth wife, Betty Lin, in a sun-drenched, 18th-floor
aerie overlooking San Francisco Bay. He no longer performs live,
but is at work on a new CD due in 2000, and has recently published
a memoir, ``Been There, Done That'' (St. Martin's Press, 1999),
co-written by David Fisher, who's no relation.
 &HT;    A previous autobiography, ``Eddie: My Life, My Loves,'' appeared
in 1981. But Fisher admits that it wasn't the whole truth.
 &HT;    ``I wrote that first book scared,'' he says. ``I was still under
the influence of drugs _ I began stories and they never ended. What
I wrote was true, but it didn't tell the complete story.''
 &HT;    In the new book, which has provoked controversy for its
kiss-and-tell accounts of his amorous adventures, Fisher is
anything but evasive.
 &HT;    ``I was truthful to the nth degree,'' he says.
 &HT;    Affable yet a bit hesitant in some of his responses, the singer
makes no excuses for his checkered past. Even today, six years into
a ``devoted'' marriage to Lin, a former graphic artist and
restaurateur, and nearly a decade after ending his drug dependency,
he admits that he's ``not completely comfortable'' with himself.
 &HT;    ``I don't think I ever was or ever will be,'' he says. ``But I'm
as comfortable as I can be.''
 &HT;    Wearing dark glasses and a hearing aid, Fisher admits that he
can't claim to have considered himself strong in any area of his
life.
 &HT;    ``I guess you would call me weak,'' he says hesitantly. ``I just
wanted to be a nice guy. I didn't want to be tough _ I think I was
a gentle man. I just gave in. I could have been a lot stronger than
I was.''
 &HT;    If he could reverse anything in his life, he adds, it would be
his involvement with drugs, which began in April 1953 when Max
Jacobson, a well-known Manhattan doctor popular with the stars,
injected him with a ``vitamin cocktail'' that actually contained
methamphetamine.
 &HT;    ``At one point, I thought I was smart enough to ask him, `Max,
what's in there?''' he recalls. ``And he said, `If I told you,
would you know?'''
 &HT;    In time, Fisher became dependent on cocaine.
 &HT;    His 1955 marriage to singer/movie star Debbie Reynolds made them
America's reigning sweethearts for a while, but Fisher says that
even before his notorious involvement with Elizabeth Taylor the
marriage was in trouble.
 &HT;    The end began when their good friend, producer Mike Todd, was
killed in a 1958 plane crash. Fisher's consoling of Taylor, Todd's
widow, soon turned into a liaison and then marriage _ which, in
turn, was shattered by Taylor's affair with Richard Burton during
the making of ``Cleopatra'' (1963).
 &HT;    In Fisher's conversation, as in his book, Taylor emerges as the
most unforgettable, if elusive, person in his life.
 &HT;    ``It was magical,'' he says. ``She had great humor. She was mad
about me, as much as I was mad about her. But it's hard to define
our relationship _ it's an experience that I couldn't completely
put into words.''
 &HT;    Fisher's children have reacted angrily to the book, and while
he's clearly proud of them, plugging Joely's current tour as Sally
Bowles in ``Cabaret'' and showing off the song Tricia wrote for
him, he admits that he wasn't much of a father, even compared to
his own father, whom he calls ``a nasty, abusive man, a tyrant.
 &HT;    ``He was better than I was, much better,'' Fisher says. ``He
came home every night. I was never there. There's a bond, but it
isn't built on anything, except that they're my children and I see
them now and then _ mostly then.''
 &HT;    His fans' disillusionment over his romantic entanglements
hastened Fisher's career decline in the 1960s, but he blames
himself more than anyone else.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't smart enough to know that when you're on top, or near
the top, it's tougher to stay there than get there,'' he says. ``I
thought I was a kind of god. I was there and I was going to remain
there.
 &HT;    ``Sinatra, on the other hand, seemed like he wasn't paying
attention to his career, but he built a repertoire unlike anyone
else's,'' Fisher adds. ``And he worked at his singing. No one ever
told me to do so. No one dared, because I was doing so well _ when
everything you put out is a hit, they don't want to interfere with
success.
 &HT;    ``But they should have,'' he says. ``The songs I made into hits
were not songs that belong in a repertoire for life. Anything I
would have recorded in that period would have been a hit.''
 &HT;    Many what-ifs swirl around Fisher's story _ what if he hadn't
met Max Jacobson? What if Mike Todd had lived? What if Fisher
hadn't picked up the ``Cleopatra'' script from a pile and suggested
to Taylor that she consider playing the title role?
 &HT;    Fisher generally isn't inclined to speculate, but he does wonder
how he might have fared if he'd come along today, growing up in a
world of music videos, strong multicultural sounds and new
directions in pop?
 &HT;    ``I wasn't as handsome as Ricky Nelson or Ricky Martin,'' he
muses. ``Maybe Ricky Nelson. But good talent finds a way. I don't
know to what level I would have risen.
 &HT;    ``But I think I would have made it at any time. It would have
worked out.''
 c.1999 Michael J. Bandler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael J. Bandler is a Silver Spring, Md.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
