<HEADER>
A3190 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-PETS-ORANGUTAN-KANSAS     10-11 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-ORANGUTAN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC ZOO GETS BABY APE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've probably heard about the recent birth of the baby
orangutan at the Kansas City Zoo. And you probably know how
important it is for the endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   But you probably haven't heard the story behind the story.
</P>
<P>
   You haven't heard about the pudding and the PVC pipes. You
haven't heard about the frozen raspberries or the ultrasound tests.
And you haven't heard about the groundbreaking behavior
modification work that made this birth more than just cute and
cuddly.
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of the one-of-a-kind relationship between the
baby's mother and the humans who take care of her.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years zoologist Beth Moore and senior staff
veterinarian Kirk Suedmeyer have worked countless hours to get the
mother, named Jill, to trust them. In the end, using positive
reinforcement, they trained her do a combination of things that no
other zoo in the world has been able to get an orangutan to do.
</P>
<P>
   They trained her to voluntarily stick her arm into a PVC pipe
with a hole cut in the top so Suedmeyer could regularly draw blood.
They trained her to urinate into a cup and hand it over for
analysis. And, almost unbelievably, they trained her to waddle to
the front of her cage, grab the bars over her head and allow
Suedmeyer to rub gel on her swollen tummy for ultrasounds.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed caretakers to monitor the health of the baby
orangutan like never before _ a critical step considering Jill's
last baby was stillborn.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wourms, Zoo director, was thrilled. Not only did the
accomplishment reflect well on the Kansas City Zoo, but it also
provided researchers with ``invaluable information about
reproduction in an endangered species.''
</P>
<P>
   Among zoo people the story is nothing short of remarkable.
That's why researchers are writing professional papers on it.
That's why Kansas City Zoo staffers are being asked to speak at
conferences. And that's why an international film crew flew here
from England to record the birth _ and the events leading up to it
_ for a National Geographic television series on great apes.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted in London, series producer Jan Euden said she was so
impressed that the Kansas City Zoo's work with Jill has become a
major part of the first episode, to be aired next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen this anywhere else,'' Euden said ``I think it
is absolutely remarkable what they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's why.
</P>
<P>
   As long as anyone can remember, if zoo staff needed to draw
blood or perform an ultrasound on orangutans and other great apes
they had one choice: Immobilize the animals first.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason for that. Orangutans are extremely strong _ six
to seven times stronger than humans. Getting close to them can be
dangerous. Which makes the prospect of giving them shots, drawing
blood and rubbing ultrasound goo on their bellies all the more
dicey.
</P>
<P>
   So how did the Kansas City zoo manage it?
</P>
<P>
   Suedmeyer just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is ask them,'' he said. ``We just never
asked them before.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, why go to the time, trouble and expense of
shooting them with a tranquilizer dart when you can earn their
cooperation with positive reinforcement?
</P>
<P>
   Enter the pudding and frozen raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   Orangutans love pudding and frozen raspberries. They also love
gelatin, frozen blueberries and yogurt. You can see it in their
faces as they lift their heads and pucker their lips _ the
universal orangutan symbol for ``more.''
</P>
<P>
   With time, training and big spoonfuls of favorite treats,
Suedmeyer and Moore learned orangutans would do almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   The program of behavior modification _ called ``operant
conditioning'' _ began almost seven years ago with another
orangutan. It started with changing the animal's feelings about the
vet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before,'' Suedmeyer said, ```every time I would come up it was
a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he changed his approach. He decided to come to the bars and
just sit. No tranquilizer gun. No nothing. He just sat.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, through training, the animal learned that if he came
close to Suedmeyer, he would be rewarded _ with pudding,
raspberries or something else.
</P>
<P>
   They trained Jill the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Come here, get a treat. Put your arm through the pipe, get a
treat.
</P>
<P>
   Let them stick you with a needle, get a really, really BIG
treat.
</P>
<P>
   Since zoo staff members knew they would need to see the infant
orangutan, Moore even used positive reinforcement to train Jill to
show her the baby.
</P>
<P>
   They practiced with a stuffed orangutan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with her touching the baby outside bars,'' Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually we gave her the little stuffed animal inside the
bars. And we were teaching her things, like to hold it up in case
we needed to give it a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when she had her own baby, I thought: `Oh my gosh. There's
just no way she's going to let us see it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Jill surprised Moore by showing her the baby _ which was
recently named ``Pendamai,'' an Indonesian word meaning
``peacemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She came up to the bars, and I told her it was really a
beautiful baby,'' Moore said. ``I said `Gosh, Jill, you did such a
beautiful job.' And I said `Can I see your baby?' And she just sort
of leaned forward and let us look at the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoo spokesperson Denise Rendina saw the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That animal absolutely presented the baby for Beth to see,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just like `That is just the sweetest thing I have ever
seen.' It was phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you want an animal to show you her baby or let you give
it a shot, the key is patience, trust, training and rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Orangutans can't reason like humans, Suedmeyer said. But they
can make a simple cost-benefit decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, `Yeah, that's going to hurt. But it won't hurt that
badly, and really like those raspberries.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Suedmeyer, Moore and the staff already are talking about the
next stage of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already discussing doing possible artificial
insemination down the road by collecting semen samples from Doc
(the baby's father) and inseminating Jill when Doc has passed
away,'' he said. ``It will take us years, but I know we can do
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
