<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3191 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-PETS-BOOK-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      10-11 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-BOOK-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORS' ANIMALS ARE GOOD FOR WHAT AILS YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARJEAN BUSBY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many times last week did you sneak a moment for yourself and
think about life's good things? Don't laugh yet. What you needed,
of course, was an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   But this week (Oct. 11) you can read Chicken Soup for the Cat &AMP;
Dog Lover's Soul.MDSD/.MDNM/, a just-released collection of true
stories about pets, people and their remarkable bond. Designed as a
day brightener, it's warm, uplifting, sometimes poignant or
amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Each selection is only two to four pages long, so you could
finish several stories while waiting for your ride or your wash to
finishing drying.
</P>
<P>
   California authors Jack Canfield and Mark Victor Hansen
previously worked with Idaho veterinarian Marty Becker and Iowa
free-lance writer//editor Carol Kline on a litter mate called
Chicken Soup for the Pet Lover's Soul.
</P>
<P>
   The first book has sold 1.8 million copies since April 1998,
says Kline, a dog rescue volunteer and self-esteem facilitator.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first book I personally read close to 3,000 stories
submitted by people all over the world,'' she recalls in a phone
interview. ``But for this one I had some help in reading. I'd
screen out stories, particularly if they were not uplifting or were
too journalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Becker, a popular television figure, have stories in
both critter books. Her work enhances the ``On Love'' chapter and
``The Magic of the Bond'' pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Kline also helped Jim Kerr of the Colorado Boys Ranch
horsemanship program produce ``Sweet Pea's Mama,'' a story for the
pets-as-healers section. He had plenty of proof that animal
interactions are therapeutic and can mend broken spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Many stories are reprinted from other publications. Barbara
Bartocci of Overland Park gave permission for ``Mighty Hercules''
to appear. Earlier, Reader's Digest featured her account of a
family picnic, three snakes and her son's soaring confidence as he
cared for them.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonist Charles Barsotti of Kansas City shows a
physician-patient drawing in the healers' section. Doctor dog
prescribes: ``Eat some grass.'' Other humor typifies Bil Keane of
``The Family Circus'' and Jonny Hawkins, who has provided humor for
more than 175 publications.
</P>
<P>
   This Chicken Soup edition ($12.95, Health Communications Inc.)
names on the cover five celebrity writers: Sarah, Duchess of York;
James Herriot; Dave Barry; Cleveland Amory; and Roger Caras, a
leader in the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals.
</P>
<P>
   Kline and her co-authors will use their store visits and media
opportunities for a personal crusade: public awareness that 6
million pets a year are euthanized after they lose their home,
although their behavior problems are treatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people give up too fast, but I'd like to inspire them to
go the extra mile,'' Kline says. ``They can learn behavior
techniques, ask experts and take a small amount of time to analyze
the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
