<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3192 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FASHION-BEAD-KANSAS-K     10-11 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BEAD-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A BEAD ON THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To bead or not to bead. It's not much of a question for people
on the fashion trend track.
</P>
<P>
   So-called power bead bracelets, said to impart such gifts as
health, courage and fortune, are selling out everywhere, from
mainstream department stores to New York street vendors.
</P>
<P>
   On another level, embellished sweaters, jeans, shoes and bags
are surfacing in retail stores. At the recent New York spring
designer shows, bead-splashed voiles, silks and chiffons for day
and night flooded the runways. And closer to home, bead stores are
seeing a rush of people who want to create their own bracelets and
decorated jeans.
</P>
<P>
   So much for austerity. Adornment is having a run.
</P>
<P>
   Millennial movement
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the most visible beading right now is empowerment or
feng shui bead bracelets, which took off in recent months with the
speed of a space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The empowerment is said to vary with the type of bead. For
example, a card attached to a black onyx bracelet promises that the
gem boosts willpower. According to accounts from Milk &AMP; Honey Inc.,
which makes bracelets, rose quartz is the bead of love. Amethyst
brings serenity. And on it goes.
</P>
<P>
   They range from $5 at New York street stands to $20 at
department stores and as much as $80 at specialty stores such as
New York's Henri Bendel. At the New York fashion shows last month,
the press corps was sharing vendor locations thought to have the
best deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a block north from the tents, on the, uh, southwest
side of the street. I bought 10 for $20 ...'' was how the
conversation went.
</P>
<P>
   The idea started with American jewelry designer Stella Pace, and
as celebrities started wearing them, consumer demand began to rise.
The idea proliferated to a range of craftsmen, jewelry companies
and loving hands at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody hated them when I first brought them in,'' says
Marlo Thornton, the accessories buyer at Halls, a Kansas City
specialty store where Carol Dauplaise bracelets are $15. ``But
we've had to reorder several times.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Hodak, the fashion director for the parent company of the
Jones Store, echoed the success story. ``We've reordered them many
times,'' she said, recalling how she had seen them just the day
before on fashion professionals in New York designer showrooms.
``It's all different age groups, not just the young,'' who are
embracing the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Many think the appeal is more in the meaning of the beads than
the look. Ann Zbryk, the manager of Nomadic Notions bead store in
Overland Park, says a young man was in recently asking for a bead
of courage.
</P>
<P>
   When Janet Bloom, the owner of D'Bronx Pizza in Kansas City, was
given the beaded bracelet for health and a Buddha prayer bracelet
for happiness and well-being, she was sure they were all she
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to disturb the balance,'' she says. ``How could
you ask for anything more?''
</P>
<P>
   But then she started buying them as gifts for friends and
family. ``It makes them feel good,'' she says. And she believes so
strongly in the power of her own, she stores them in her evening
bag when she goes to a formal event so they will never be too far
away from her.
</P>
<P>
   Irenka Jakubiak, editor of Accessories magazine, says the
jewelry represents a millennium-inspired ``movement toward
spiritualism'' and a movement away from the impersonal. ``It's back
to finding something to believe in,'' she says, ``a hope for the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparel apparent
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile beads also are flooding the apparel scene. The idea
was boosted by Gucci designer Tom Ford and his fall homage to the
flash and splash of Las Vegas glitz. Since then, we've seen the
light meter punched up about 1,000 watts on clothes and other
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Spade's new shoe line includes beaded thongs. In his recent
spring show, Tommy Hilfiger fringed his jeans with Swarvorski
crystal beads. A woman standing in the crowd at a fashion show in
Times Square was wearing slipperlike flip-flops embroidered with
jeweled beads.
</P>
<P>
   In the home decor market, beads are showing up on lamps, pillows
and gifts, says Tom Julian, a New York-based trend tracker for
Fallon McElligott Advertising. And for do-it-yourselfers, Nomadic
Notions has had a ``huge increase in volume'' of business in all
kinds of beads and how-to classes, Zbryk says.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly at a time when the fashionables were consumed by
simple minimalism of tank tops and Gap T-shirts, a new decorative
motif seems a natural evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Steele, the fashion historian and curator at New York's
Fashion Institute of Technology, says it's the ``pendulum effect,''
in which fashion swings from one extreme to another.
</P>
<P>
   To her it's reminiscent of the bohemian and hippie movement of
the late '60s, when beads, embroidered mirrors and other ethnic
adaptations replaced the severely austere, modern lines of
Frenchmen Courreges and Cardin.
</P>
<P>
   The 1920s, when fashion took a turn toward straight-lined
flapper silhouettes and exuberant textiles, is the historical
analogy for Kathleen McDermott, a Boston-based fashion historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``When shapes simplify, clothes become more ornate,'' she says.
Beading provides ``a place for the eye to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
