 &HT;    With E-COMMERCE. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-SERVICE REMAINS LESS THAN IDEAL
</P>
<P>
   E-consumers who were satisfied with service they got on line ...
52%
</P>
<P>
   E-consumers who found telephone customer service easily
available ... 47%
</P>
<P>
   E-consumers whose online questions got answered within an hour
... 16%
</P>
<P>
   E-consumers who asked a question and got no answer at all ...
23%
</P>
<P>
   Source: Data collected in August and September 1999 from 692
online shoppers by e-BuyersGuide.com of Burlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   SANTA'S WORKSHOP MOVES TO THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   People who will shop online for the first time this year ... 10
million
</P>
<P>
   Projected consumer online spending for November and December
1999 ... $6 billion
</P>
<P>
   Amount Americans will spend online for holiday travel services
... $1 billion
</P>
<P>
   Projected online sales for holiday season 2003 ... $78 billion
</P>
<P>
   Source: Jupiter Communications of New York
</P>
<P>
   WHERE ONLINE BUYERS SAY THEY WILL LOOK FOR HOLIDAY GIFTS
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com ... 68%
</P>
<P>
   CDNow.com ... 45%
</P>
<P>
   eToys.com ... 43%
</P>
<P>
   ToysRUs.com ... 28%
</P>
<P>
   LLBean.com ... 20%
</P>
<P>
   Macy.com ... 10%
</P>
<P>
   Source: July survey of 4,849 Americans with Internet access by
Greenfield Online Inc. of Westport, Conn.
</P>
