<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3232 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-NUTRITIONIST-TO-STARS     10-11 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTRITIONIST-TO-STARS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD DISH  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE of Carrie Latt Wiatt is available FREE OF CHARGE
to purchasers of this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY
by e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when you order the
article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By LOUISE FARR 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``I love food,'' Matt Damon says. ``Everything bad _ I love
pizza, beer, chocolate and spaghetti.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a case for Carrie Latt Wiatt, nutritionist to the
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, the founder of Diet Designs, is Hollywood's most
high-profile calorie counter. Her custom-made meals have been
delivered to Jennifer Aniston, Julia Roberts, Dennis Quaid, Neve
Campbell, Reese Witherspoon, James Cameron, Danny DeVito and dozens
of other Hollywood types who've needed help staying svelte between
movies.
</P>
<P>
   When Alicia Silverstone couldn't get into her catsuit for the
last ``Batman'' extravaganza, Wiatt was the one director Joel
Schumacher called on for help.
</P>
<P>
   But Wiatt's most recent coup was adding Damon to her list of
dieters. Last year, the actor packed on the pounds as he waited to
begin shooting ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, who usually works out of an immaculate headquarters in
Culver City (complete with a stainless-steel kitchen and a staff of
nine), helped him slim down in time for the shoot. But he worried
about how he'd fare on the movie's set in Rome, surrounded by all
that pizza and pasta.
</P>
<P>
   So she hopped on a plane to Italy, toting a supply of what she
describes as Damon's ``fun food'': his favorite turkey jerky.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival, Wiatt instructed Italian chefs to expand their
repertoire with her low-fat meals for Damon, including creamy
polenta lasagna, crab cakes and chicken with Marbella sauce. She
also plowed her way through the city's fashionable restaurants,
where, she says, she taught Damon that he could lose weight without
being afraid of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have the thin-crust pizza, but only two or three
inches,'' says the earnest but glamorous Wiatt, 41. ``Pasta, but
two or three ounces at a time. He didn't think he could eat pasta,
and all of a sudden he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most people would wince at the prospect of a three-inch
slice of pizza _ why even bother? _ Damon pronounces himself happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrie helped me get through the movie,'' he says. ``I'm not a
person who diets well. She gave me food that I actually liked, and
I didn't feel like I was depriving myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly Wiatt's goal. As part of her mission to teach
America that less is more, she has written a book called ``Portion
Savvy'' (Pocket Books: $24), illustrated with cardboard pop-outs of
little chicken breasts, scoops of rice, undersized apples and
minimuffins.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt is horrified by the national obsession with super-jumbo
plates of fries, overflowing boxes of buttered popcorn, eight-ounce
bagels and 60-ounce soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do they get the idea that we need this kind of food?''
she says. ``It's ridiculous. It's obscene.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from her skill at preparing restaurant-quality,
nutritionally balanced food in moderate but satisfying portions,
Wiatt's secret lies in tailoring her 1,000- to 2,000-calorie daily
menus to suit individual tastes.
</P>
<P>
   (An editor at W magazine who tried her food for two weeks lost
six pounds completely painlessly on a 1,600-calories-a-day regime.)
</P>
<P>
   Everything is fresh; she even refuses to go mass-market because
she doesn't want to freeze her food. And she takes into account the
dieter's sweet tooth, providing lemon bars, butterscotch chip
brownies and dainty servings of tiramisu, mousse and chocolate chip
meringues.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing the frequent smile of a true believer, Wiatt describes
herself as ``part therapist, part scientist, part motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   She schedules regular appointments with clients, asking probing
questions about eating habits, medical problems and food
preferences. Then she finishes with a weigh-in on the unforgiving
scale that looms in a corner of her otherwise cheery office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is so intimate, and sometimes people make it their
intimate friend and get too close,'' Wiatt moans. ``Aaargh! Think
of how we're codependent in certain relationships. They don't work.
They're dysfunctional. And why would food be any different? I can
get people to think about establishing a healthier relationship,
establishing boundaries. ''
</P>
<P>
   For people who can't stay away from their refrigerators, it
helps to have breakfast, lunch and dinner prepackaged and
delivered, because there's no need to think about eating until it's
time to open one of Wiatt's boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The meals are never predictable: There's sea bass with tamarind
sauce and couscous; corn cakes with black-bean salsa; artichoke
pizza with goat cheese. Wiatt's list goes on and on, her menu
changing to incorporate seasonal foods.
</P>
<P>
   Local clients pay $200 for the first consultation and four
follow-up visits, plus $230 a week for 15 meals. (The meals can be
shipped to some other cities at an additional charge.)
</P>
<P>
   But price is not an object for most of Wiatt's clients, who also
appreciate her cheerleader sunniness (``Oh, you're so cute,'' she
says when she's complimented on the food).
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, who received her master's degree in nutrition from
California State University at Northridge, began her business in
her home kitchen about 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At first she was cooking for friends of her parents in the San
Fernando Valley, but she'd already picked up a handful of
show-business clients _ including her now best buddy Sela Ward _ by
the time Ward's agent recommended her to her future husband, ICM
agent Jim Wiatt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I committed the cardinal sin _ I married my client,'' she says
with her great guffawing laugh. ``I said, `Wait a minute. I can't
date you. You're my client.' He said, `Well, I'll fire you, then.'
So he married me instead.''
</P>
<P>
   The wedding was in 1992, and the divorce came two years later,
by which time Wiatt's business had skyrocketed, fueled by her new
husband's connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``You meet people for reasons; I believe that,'' she says,
adding that, Hollywood being Hollywood, she feels ``blessed'' to
have kept most of her clients after the split.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if someone said, `Don't go to her,' people respected and
knew that I was doing a good job.'' She reflects for a minute. ``It
was an important time in my life. He was my husband. He wasn't just
an agent who introduced me to people. Would I go back and marry
someone else in the business? Not a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, however, Wiatt has gone into ``the business'' herself.
In her syndicated TV show, ``Living Better with Carrie Wiatt,'' she
visits farmers' markets and yoga classes, dispenses health and home
advice and comes across as a high-energy, low-fat Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt's own increasing celebrity has made her more aware of the
pressures that her clients have to endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actors in the past have done some real extreme dieting and
used some very dangerous methods,'' she says. ``Everything from
diet pills in the '70s to ... I don't want to say this, but who
knows who snorted coke?''
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt also worries about ultra-thin actresses being judged too
harshly by the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not anorexic,'' she says. ``You'd know. Their teeth
would be gray. They'd be in the hospital. I've seen bulimics and
anorexics and they're not. I think women are becoming much more
focused on being fit and having a positive body image.''
</P>
<P>
   As a nutritionist, Wiatt's goal is to teach people her methods,
then set them free. But as much as she believes in herself, she
stops short of fanaticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ways to cheat within the structure,'' she says.
``For me, life without chocolate would not be worth living.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Louise Farr is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
