<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Oct. 12:
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN:
</P>
<P>
   INHOFE-TREATY (Washington) _ Interview with Sen. James Inhofe,
R-Okla., who opposes the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta) _ Attorney general drops key part of
corruption case against former President Suharto. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-PEACEPKEEPERS (Dili) _ Australians accuse Indonesians of
firing on one of their troops. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Grozny) _ Wide-ranging interview with Shamil
Basayev, a top Chechen commander. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PROTEST-HERO (Montredon, France) _ On the sudden fame of
Jose Bove, who became a national hero when arrested for vandalizing
a McDonald's construction site. ``There have been three
totalitarian forces in our life time,'' he says: fascism, communism
and now capitalism. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-OPPOSITION (Luzembourg) _ Milosevic's opponents drop plans
to meet with the European Union, which has sought their help in
eventually turning over the Yugoslav president to war crimes
tribunal. Foreign ministers also affirm support for winter heating
oil for Yugoslavs, despite U.S. opposition. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-KGB-SPIES (Rome) _ Latest in spy scandal, from KGB
archives. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CABINET (London) _ Prime Minister Tony Blair brings
Peter Mandelson, former trade minister, back into government, 10
months after Mandelson was forced to resign in a financial scandal.
Mandelson will be minister to Northern Ireland; the current
minister, Mo Mowlam, is expected to take the role of Cabinet
``enforcer.'' By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TIANANMEN (Hong Kong) _ Pro-democracy leader says
territory's leader put pressure on him to stop holding vigils on
anniversary of Tiananmen crackdown. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL:
</P>
<P>
   HIGHWAY-IMPALINGS (Miami) _ ``There has been another impaling on
I-95.'' So goes the news in South Florida, where the interstate
highways have become notorious for the rubble and trash on them
that occasionally kicks up and skewers cars and their drivers. By
Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   SMITH-MINORITIES (Los Angeles) _ Called the Jackie Robinson of
higher education when she became the first black woman to head a
top-tier college or university in 1995, Dr. Ruth Simmons, the
president of Smith College hrked on what she calls a
personal crusade to bring more disadvantaged students to her campus
and similar institutions nationwide. She is stepping out of the
ivory tower to recruit personally at big urban public high schools,
a rarity for a college president. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON:
</P>
<P>
   D.C.-HITECH-BOOM (Washington) _ A new, outside-the-beltway
culture has grown up in and around Washington. The city and its
suburbs are now home to far more businessmen and entrepreneurs than
federal workers and the assorted private companies and institutions
connected to the government. By at least one measure, Washington is
now the technological capital of the United States. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, map and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS:
</P>
<P>
   AFLCIO-ENDORSEMENT (Los Angeles) _ The AFL-CIO convention;
seeking to determine how the Gore campaign locked up the union's
endorsement. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ His stump style and how it
plays. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL:
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE-STEWART (Undated) _ Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia
is the latest entry in a Wall Street celebrity parade that
stretches at least back to the 1950s. But Ms. Stewart, who is 58,
cannot ultimately cash in on her empire unless she can find a way
to push her highly personal ``brand'' out beyond the borders of her
own daily schedule _ indeed, beyond the limits of her own lifespan.
By Diana Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-BASEBALL (New York) _ What the prospects of the Yankees
and Mets bode for the market. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-CROSSING (London) _ Global Crossing Ltd. takes a big step
toward its goal of creating a worldwide telecommunications network
by snatching Racal Telecom of Britain from under the nose of
Energis PLC for $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-TELECOM (Sao Paulo) _ MCI Worldcom Inc.'s planned
acquisition of the Sprint Corp. could send a jolt through Brazil's
telecommunications industry, which has emerged as a battleground
for many of the world's largest communications companies. By Simon
Romero.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MINORITY-BUSINESSES (Washington) _ Long united in the struggle
to maintain special breaks for non-white entrepreneurs, liberal
civil rights leaders and minority business groups have become
divided over a basic concept: what is a minority-owned company. By
Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Looking at recent cuts by big airlines
in the commissions they pay travel agents, who are also being
pressured by Internet sales of tickets. By Edwin McDowell.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Dr. Guenter Blobel, a cellular
and molecular biologist at Rockefeller University, is awarded the
Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for discovering that proteins
carry signals that act as ZIP codes, helping them find their
correct locations within the cell. The research has had an
``immense impact'' on studies of the cell, the assembly said, and
helps explain the molecular mechanisms behind diseases like cystic
fibrosis. Dr. Blobel, 63, was born in Germany and earned his Ph.D.
at the University of Wisconsin. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY:
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Dateline to come) _ ``Public Interests'' by Gail
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Dateline to come) _ ``Abroad at Home'' by Anthony
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
