 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2582 -- Oct. 11, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. FOR WORLD SECURITY, RATIFY THE COMPREHENSIVE TEST
</P>
<P>
   BAN TREATY During the 1990s, the United States has made a vital
contribution to arms control and non-proliferation. Thanks to the
common resolve of the world's powers, we have achieved a
substantial reduction in nuclear arsenals, the banning of chemical
weapons, the indefinite and unconditional extension of the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty and, in 1996, the conclusion of
negotiations on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. The decisions we
take now will help determine, for generations to come, the safety
of the world we bequeath to our children, write Jacques Chirac,
Tony Blair and Gerhard Schroeder. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
THE BIZARRE WORLD OF MATTHEW BARNEY When Matthew Barney came onto
the world art scene in 1991, with his surreal sculptures and
videos, he was instantly successful. Since then, his work has only
got better and stranger. He has mostly been making a series of
increasingly elaborate films, called ``Cremaster.'' Now 32, Barney
is the most important American artist of his generation. By Michael
Kimmelman. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (5,100
words) + edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
THE VIRUSES ARE COMING As the earth grows warmer, and as pathogens,
aided by increased global trade, political chaos and the
destruction of rain forests, find new hosts, people who have never
set foot in Africa will be contracting malaria, just as last month
Americans who never set foot in Africa contracted the West Nile
virus, which was discovered in Uganda in 1937 and had never been
seen in this hemisphere. What it means is what we already know :
pathogens have no borders. By Jeffrey Goldberg. From The New York
Times Magazine. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
THE NEXT CARDINAL Because of the prominence of the position, New
York's next archbishop will not only most likely be named a
cardinal. He will also characterize the church's leadership well
into the next century. And 40 years after John F. Kennedy became
the first Catholic president of the United States, the church in
America is becoming an immigrant church all over again. Hispanic
Catholics, 24 million and counting, are quickly becoming the
largest ethnic group in the 62-million-member church. By Paul Elie.
From The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words. 5. FROM NATURE NEWS
SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo : 19h00 BST October 13)
</P>
<P>
   (a) Do-It-Yourself Climate Modelling All you need is a little
time and space on your PC. NASA has a scheme in which you can use
your desktop computer as part of a program in the Search for
Extraterrestrial Intelligence (SETI.) By Eleanor Lawrence. 500
words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) The Brain Bank You'd never guess that the rolling parkland
of Belmont, a leafy Boston suburb, is home to shelves of pickled
and frozen brains. This 'brain bank' has existed for over 20 years.
Each year it receives around 350 brains (each brain must reach the
bank within 24 hours of death,) and sends out more than 6,000 bits
of brain tissue to researchers. By Sara Abdulla. 500 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES SCIENCE TIMES
</P>
<P>
   (a) Scientists Unmake Diet ``Myth'' Willpower
</P>
<P>
   To attribute dieting success or failure to willpower,
researchers say, is to ignore the complex interaction of brain
chemicals. By Jane Fritsch. 1,500 words
</P>
<P>
   (b) Of Mice, Men and a Gene That Jumpstarts Follicles There is a
sudden ray of hope for balding people. The new herald of
hirsuteness is no mere cream or chemical but a gene with the
strange and potent name of Sonic hedgehog. By Nicholas Wade. 1,500
words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM PROSPECT MAGAZINE (N/A U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   (a) Meeting Megawati Megawati Sukarnoputri carries the hopes for
reform in Indonesia, but she opposed East Timor's independence. By
Barbara Schwepcke. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) It's A Snip Ian Hargreaves writes that his wife had already
bled for modern reproduction so it was his turn. But vasectomies
are not always simple. 1,500 words.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I am
interested in story no. ______ from summary 2582
