 Monday, Oct. 11, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Senate Republicans' defeat last
week of the nomination of Missouri State Supreme Court Justice
Ronnie White to the federal bench was a blatantly unfair and racist
act. GOP senators simply deferred to Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft's
opposition to White, who is the first black to serve on the state
high court. But the Senate action could well hurt the right-wing
Ashcroft, who is running for reelection next year. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3288 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      10-11 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Oct. 12. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FORFEIT. We have a copy of the Claire McCaskill report on
forfeitures that's finally been completed. It's being released
Tuesday at the beginning of another legislative hearing. Bottom
line: Cops can send much more seized money to education than they
have been. 35-40. Karen Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT (with FORFEIT). A lot of agencies and prosecutors just
stiffed the auditor's office, refusing to return a survey she sent.
12. Karen Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   SHOTS: Immunization rates are way down in all five metro
counties, but drastic drops have been recorded in Jackson and
Wyandotte counties, according to statistics to be released Tuesday
by the Partnership for Children. One big reason is that education
efforts have faltered because of high turnover at the health
departments. But health officials say they're also fighting a
growing anti-vaccination movement, fueled by alleged misinformation
on the Internet. (Complete report card story is embargoed for
Wednesday) Photo. Graphic. Donald Bradley. 20.
</P>
<P>
   CREME. Creme de la Creme, a new nursery and preschool in
Leawood, looks like nirvana for little kids. There's the Beauty and
the Beast soundtrack wafting throughout the 21,000-square-foot
building, the Trike Autobahn on the manicured playground outside,
the model train rolling around a track near the ceiling of the faux
Victorian streetscape. And that's just the trappings. Every 30
minutes, preschoolers are moved to a different activity, from
French to math to creative movement. Tuition at Creme runs almost
twice as high as the area average _ it's $12,000 a year for
preschoolers _ but satisfied parents say their children's happiness
is worth it. Yet child development experts warn that high cost does
not equal high quality. Kate Beem. Photo. 45.
</P>
<P>
   EDBD. The Kansas Board of Education meets in De Soto. The
members won't take up revisions to the science standards until
Tuesday, but the public comment session is today. Diane Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   IBC _ Interstate Bakeries Corp., one of the area's few remaining
Fortune 500 companies, is looking like a tempting takeover target
these days. By Jennifer Mann
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   ALGAME. The Red Sox and Indians fight it out in Game 5 to see
who'll advance to the ALCS. 3:09 p.m. start. Steven Rock. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   CHIEFS. Folo from the Chiefs' improbable win over New England on
Sunday. Adam Teicher. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   NLCSADV. Just 10 days ago, the Atlanta Braves were beating the
heck out oew York Mets as Subway Series hopes faded into the
Manhattan sunset. Now, they square off again, this time for a shot
at the World Series. Dick Kaegel. 25.
</P>
<P>
   POZ. Joe Posnanski column on Alexi Lalas, now in the second day
of his surprising retirement.
</P>
<P>
   NFLREVUE. Jonathan Rand's NFL Week in Review.
</P>
<P>
   RAMFOLO. Who could have ever believed that the St. Louis Rams
would be the only undefeated team in the NFL after five weeks?
Jonathan Rand. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-BEAD _ To bead or not to bead. It's not much of a
question for people on the fashion trend track. So-called power
bead bracelets, said to impart such gifts as health, courage and
fortune, are selling out everywhere, from mainstream department
stores to New York street vendors. 813 words. By JACKIE WHITE.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ALICE _ He's 51 and he can do what he wants, which means
Alice Cooper plays lots of golf and lots of loud rock music.
``Financially I don't have to do this,'' he said. ``I choose to do
it. When I'm off tour, by the time eight or nine months go by, I
want to be back on stage.'' 740 words. By TIMOTHY FINN.
</P>
<P>
   PERSON-CHANGE _ Choices. Along with genes and neurochemicals and
environmental factors such as the way we were toilet-trained, they
have a lot to do with who we are. Science has long grappled with
the question of our makeup _ physical, emotional, mental. How much
of us is fixed and how much of us is elastic? Every few weeks it
seems another gene is found and identified, our fate further
sealed. The early-to-bed, early-to-rise gene. The gene that
determines how much trouble one is likely to have quitting smoking.
1,500 words. By KAREN UHLENHUTH.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-DEADMEN _ When a dead guy starts talking, we tend to pay
attention. Provided, of course, that we realize he's a dead guy.
Confused? Not if you've been going to the movies lately, where dead
guys have been doing a lot of talking. (Warning: If you haven't
seen ``Jakob the Liar'' or ``The Sixth Sense,'' you may not want to
read farther.) 910 words. By ROBERT W. BUTLER.
</P>
<P>
   PETS-BOOK _ How many times last week did you sneak a moment for
yourself and think about life's good things? Don't laugh yet. What
you needed, of course, was an excuse. But this week (Oct. 11) you
can read /{Chicken Soup for the Cat &AMP; Dog Lover's Soul/}, a
just-released collection of true stories about pets, people and
their remarkable bond. Designed as a day brightener, it's warm,
uplifting, sometimes poignant or amusing. 400 words. By MARJEAN
BUSBY.
</P>
<P>
   PETS-ORANGUTAN _ A baby orangutan was born recently at the
Kansas City Zoo. You may know how important it is for the
endangered species. But you haven't heard about the pudding and the
PVC pipes. You haven't heard about the frozen raspberries or the
ultrasound tests. And you haven't heard about the groundbreaking
behavior modification work that made this birth more than just cute
and cuddly. 935 words. By JAMES A. FUSSELL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
