<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3320 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-LAUNDERING-BOS     10-11 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-LAUNDERING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM WILD WEST TO `KLEPTOCRACY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, observers proclaimed Russia as a Klondike of oil,
gold, and promise and predicted that the old communist giant would
head into the new millennium looking like a Western-style market
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the decade that began with sanguine visions of a frontier of
opportunity is closing with a fin de siecle fear of corruption and
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   As an investigation into Russian money laundering through the
Bank of New York gained momentum last week, Russia seemed further
than ever from the heady assessments of years past, when headlines
touting ``reform'' hung over the country like a halo in a medieval
icon. Now Russian banks, firms, immigrants, and even the Kremlin
stand accused of tainting the global money system by moving
billions of dollars in ill-gotten gains out of Russia and into
Western banks.
</P>
<P>
   The change in image is dramatic, if only because corruption in
the vast country is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   But neither is mischaracterization of Russia a novel recent
phenomenon. From ``wild west'' and ``land of robber barons'' to
``free market economy'' and, now, ``Indonesian-style kleptocracy,''
the analogies and categories used to explain the country's tortured
transition from central planning to something not unlike a command
economy, yet not a traditional market, have widely missed the mark,
according to seasoned Russia watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Holmes, a professor of political science and Russia
specialist at Princeton University, says decision-makers, scholars,
and journalists have used familiar names and images ``as an
anesthetic, because it's too painful to say we don't understand the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   In a land where people are not paid wages yet continue to work,
where living standards have plummeted yet starvation and riots are
rare, and where barter, not cash, is the currency of domestic
business, comparisons to the familiar fail to capture a very
strange system indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear words like chaos used to describe things, it
means we haven't been able to identify the form of order; it's not
recognizable to us,'' says Holmes, who also teaches at New York
University Law School. ``It says more about our cognitive
disabilities than about Russia per se.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern observers are not alone in their perceptual shortcomings.
In his famous pronouncement that Russia was ``a riddle wrapped in a
mystery inside an enigma'' _ perhaps the most worn cliche ever used
to describe a nation _ Winston Churchill articulated the
bewilderment outsiders felt in attempting to fathom an unfamiliar
order. Indeed, the newest image of Russia as a ``gangster
economy,'' with tentacles in the global money network, is a dark
incarnation of Churchill's idea that Russia is unlike the orderly
and transparent West.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so long ago that the West viewed Russia's
post-communist odyssey as a messy version of American history.
</P>
<P>
   After the Soviet Union came apart at the seams in 1991,
observers took to calling Russia a ``wild west.'' Take heart, US
and European advisers told foreign investors: Today you haul in
bags of cash to set up joint ventures; tomorrow you will see Wall
Street on the Moscow River.
</P>
<P>
   Flourishing street trade and brisk privatization inspired books
with titles like ``How Russia Became a Market Economy'' and ``The
Coming Russian Boom.'' Dazzled economists declared curious
phenomena like barter and nonpayments a side show to the grand
transformation. The International Monetary Fund preached tight
monetary policies as it doled out $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Others saw a land of nascent Rockefellers and Carnegies.
Russia's new industrial titans, flush with assets acquired through
cozy deals with the government, would follow their 19th-century
robber-baron cousins and instinctively heed capitalism's call to
turn enterprises into profitable outfits that invested in
themselves and in their country's future.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, with dead executives piled up outside
Siberian aluminum smelters and privatization officials gunned down
in St. Petersburg, the country was branded a Chicago of the 1920s,
a gangland steppe.
</P>
<P>
   August 1998 ended the conceit that Russia had been following the
``laws'' of capitalist development. As the ruble collapsed and
Moscow underwent an unprecedented debt default, ``It destroyed the
last credibility of those who defended the West's assessments of
and policies for Russia,'' says Jerry Hough, professor of political
science at Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no surprise that when money laundering charges surfaced
exactly one year later, the West was in no mood to see a reflection
of its own development. At House Banking Committee hearings in
Washington last month, Republican congressman Jim Leach of Iowa
declared that Russia was ``one of the world's most virulent
kleptocracies.''
</P>
<P>
   A stark assessment, considering Washington's strong support of
President Boris Yeltsin and his ``reformist'' efforts this decade.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Russia's freshly tarnished image reflects a growing
sense that the West's recipes for revival have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Russia may have free elections, a lively, independent press, and
bearable inflation, but the greater part of its 147 million
citizens live in what may be the greatest economic depression in
history. Critics like Holmes blame not crime but crippling fiscal
austerity prescriptions, and argue that Washington should have
orchestrated a Marshall Plan of humanitarian aid rather than trying
to micro-manage an economy and society it poorly understood.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Moscow has made many mistakes in the last nine years.
Capital flight and tax evasion have impoverished state coffers.
There is little rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   But such flaws are not the same thing as organized crime and
money laundering. While organized crime is rampant in Russia, far
from all Russians are crooks. And as a growing number of scholars
argue, far from all phenomena that cannot be labeled ``market'' or
``reformist'' are criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money laundering is the wrong term to describe what has been
going on in Russia,'' Hough says.
</P>
<P>
   So what is going on?
</P>
<P>
   David Woodruff, a political scientist at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, argues that the West got so mesmerized
with its prescriptions for capitalist changes that it missed the
real story: the development of what may be the world's largest
non-cash economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever its virtues, or its vices, the progress of market
reform is a dangerous narrative frame for anyone trying to make
sense of the course of Russian politics and economics,'' Woodruff
writes in ``Money Unmade: Barter and the Fate of Russian
Capitalism.'' Instead, he argues, the focus should be on the use of
barter and non-cash payments by Russia's 89 regions and large
industrial enterprises to conduct ordinary business.
</P>
<P>
   But getting economists and policy makers to analyze why oil
refineries pay workers with sausages, instead of analyzing exchange
rates and balanced budgets, is tough.
</P>
<P>
   The current climate of angst about ``dirty'' Russian money won't
help matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West was overly romantic in its expectations of what would
happen in Russia,'' said Jeremy Azriel of the Rand Corp., a think
tank. ``But now there is a real danger that the Russian business
community will be so thoroughly tarred and feathered that a lot of
honest people will be put out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Lynnley Browning, who covers financial services for the Globe,
spent six years in Russia.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1456EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
