A3321 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CHILANGOS-BOS &LR;      10-11 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHILANGOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A NAME BECOMES SLUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For eons, it seems, the residents of this massive
metropolis have lived grudgingly with the colloquial label of
``chilango'' _ an encapsulation of the gruff, arrogant, whiny, and
world-revolves-around-us attitude that makes them widely disliked
beyond their polluted and crime-ridden city limits.
</P>
<P>
   But now, a new edition of a prominent Spanish-language
dictionary has, for the first time, elevated ``chilango'' into
Latin America's official lexicon. In its entry for Mexico City, the
Orthography of the Spanish Language, which is compiled by the Royal
Spanish Academy, includes a reference to its inhabitants as
``chilangos'' for males and ``chilangas'' for females.
</P>
<P>
   To many people here, though, the name _ and its appearance in a
hardcover reference book _ is equivalent to a slur, and has sent
tremors through the city's intellectual and talk-radio circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that it's not an appropriate name, but there
is no other,'' Gonzalo Celorio, a writer and professor at the
National Autonomous University told the Mexico City daily La
Jornada, which broke the story last week in a lamenting article
that took up almost a full page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chilango'' has historically been used in a negative context,
and most often by people from other parts of Mexico who love to
complain that the capital _ which holds roughly 20 percent of the
country's 96 million residents _ gets too much attention and money
at the expense of the poorer provinces.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find a US equivalent to this Mexican moniker.
Americans gripe about pushy New Yorkers, provincial Bostonians, or
laid-back Californians, but ``chilango'' takes all the best and
worst qualities of a population _ aggressive, demanding, slimy, and
calumnious _ and wraps them into one word.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike racial, ethnic, or religious labels, which can
reflect a cultural attitude, a ``chilango'' can be someone from
just about any origin, so long as he was born in or acts like
someone from Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the social competition between the provinces and the
capital, but it is a type of insult,'' said Homero Aridjis, a poet
and president of PEN, an international writers group, who, despite
having lived here for the past 40 years, doesn't consider himself a
``chilango.''
</P>
<P>
   There are varying theories for the name's origin. Some say
``chilango'' is loosely rooted in a Mexican profanity that is used
to describe everything from sex, rape, or a conquest, or that it
refers to Mexicans' love of spicy food loaded with chile peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation, offered by the Mexican writer Carlos
Monsivais, is that the name came from fishermen _ sometimes called
``huachinangos'' _ from Veracruz state who, beginning in the
mid-1800s, gave their city-slicker clients the same name they used
to refer to their slippery and sometimes dirty catch.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the controversy over ``chilango'' may be more about
age than place. Most older people _ like those who aired their
complaints on radio shows last week _ bristle at the label, while
today's younger generations proudly wear the name like a defiant
badge.
</P>
<P>
   But like it or not, Monsivais said, ``chilango'' is here to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people should be so upset, especially because
there's no other word that better describes us,'' he said. ``It's a
name that has become indispensable and won't be substituted for
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard Chacon is chief of the Globe's Latin America bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
