<P>
   SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Dr. Guenter Blobel, a cellular
and molecular biologist at Rockefeller University, is awarded the
Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for discovering that proteins
carry signals that act as ZIP codes, helping them find their
correct locations within the cell. The research has had an
``immense impact'' on studies of the cell, the assembly said, and
helps explain the molecular mechanisms behind diseases like cystic
fibrosis. Blobel, 63, was born in Germany and earned his Ph.D. at
the University of Wisconsin. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   TIGER-REVIVAL (Undated) _ Like a furred phoenix rising from the
ashes, or a creature cognizant of its nine-lifetime warranty, the
tiger has come back. Far from disappearing, the tiger in some parts
of its range in Asia is practically thriving, its numbers
measurably greater today than just a few years ago. And though
conservationists who have long battled to save the tiger warn
against complacency and emphasize that the tiger is still
endangered, they admit to an unusual sensation these days:
optimism. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ANNIVERSARY (Undated) _ The Internet revolution began
quietly 30 years ago this month. With one scarcely noticed
milestone after another, the planetary nervous system envisioned in
the early '60s _ cyber rhetoric is as old as a Beatles tune _
unceremoniously began insinuating itself into society. A strange
amalgam of Defense Department money, engineering expertise, and
even a dab of countercultural idealism, slowly brought on the Net
we know today. By By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   WAVE-OBSERVATORY (Undated) _ A whisper from one of the most
exotic events in the universe could be among the first detections
when a new, $350 million gravity wave observatory begins operating
next year. The event is the violent merger of a pair of black
holes, a cataclysm that throws off ripples in the fabric of space
called gravitational waves or, more simply, gravity waves. It was
to detect such waves that physicists designed the Laser
Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory, or LIGO, which will
be dedicated on November 11 and begin a shakedown period of initial
operations in January of next year. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Fears of breast cancer are now
distorting the reality of the disease, which should be put in
perspective. Heart disease and lung cancer are far more deadly for
women. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-REACTIONS (Undated) _ Doses of prescriptions recommended in
the Physicians Desk Reference may be too high for many people and
may cause adverse reactions, ranging from dizziness and nausea all
the way to death, according to an article published last month in
the journal Postgraduate Medicine. For many drugs _ including
Viagra, Prozac and some medicines used to treat high blood
pressure, allergies, insomnia and high cholesterol _ smaller doses
would work just as well as the standard ones, with far less risk of
bad reactions, said the author of the article. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   ATWATER-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Conversation with Dr. Tanya Atwater, who
early in her career discovered how the western United States had
been developed and determined the role of tectonic plates. Now, she
is working on an animated film explaining earthquakes to children.
As for living with quakes, she explains that good roofs protect
people from rain and good construction can protect them from
earthquakes. By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY-FLU-SEASON (Undated) _ Health officials have been
surprised by early cases of the flu in several spots around the
nation, but say that it's very hard to predict just how difficult
this flu season will be. By Randi Hutter Epstein.
