<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-REFORM-PARTY-BOS &LR;      10-11 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORFUL CAST GATHERING FOR REFORM PARTY SCRAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Minutes after Boston lawyer Robert LaMarca
strolled into the Reform Party's state convention the other day, he
was minted as a member of the party and a delegate to its national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Casting an eye over the delegates milling about a hotel
conference room, it didn't him take much longer to sum up the
movement he'd joined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's chaos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chaos with consequences _ and characters. Born of H. Ross
Perot's willpower and wealth, the Reform Party, with its claim on
millions in federal matching funds and the potential to alter the
outcome of the 2000 presidential race, already has attracted one of
the oddest arrays of political personalities in the history of
American democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the players already in the fray or preening at
ringside.
</P>
<P>
   In the far corner glowers Jesse ``The Mouth'' Ventura, the
Minnesota governor and former boa-feathered wrestler who says he
wants to be reborn as a bra and scorns organized religion as ``a
crutch for weak-minded people.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the canvas glares Patrick J. Buchanan, the Catholic
conservative who promises that his ``pitchfork brigade'' will
return the Lord's Prayer to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   And here comes Donald J. Trump, the deep-pocketed developer who
has long considered politics too dirty because it meant shaking
germ-laden hands.
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this in Perot's dream of a third-party
juggernaut: The Mouth, The Christian Soldier, and The Donald are
ready to rumble for the soul of the party, a free-for-all that
could have life-or-death implications for the movement.
</P>
<P>
   To the distress of Republican front-runner George W. Bush,
Buchanan is poised to bolt from the GOP and defy Ventura by chasing
the Reform presidential nomination. In his quest, Buchanan may win
the help of a startling new soul mate _ Lenora B. Fulani, a
self-described New York leftist who controls a pivotal bloc of
Reform activists, even as she fends off criticism that she is,
among other things, ``a Marxist crackpot.''
</P>
<P>
   As Buchanan and Fulani broke bread last week at a restaurant
facing Central Park, Trump was around the corner on Fifth Avenue
answering Ventura's call to plan an exploratory campaign in pursuit
of the Reform nomination. And Perot was home in Texas with his own
untold intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The list doesn't end there. The lineup of other possible
contenders or draftees for top spots on the Reform ticket includes
actor Warren Beatty and actress Cybill Shepherd, and US
Representative James A. Traficant Jr., an Ohio Democrat renowned
for his ``Made in America'' tirades on the House floor. Traficant
has been mentioned as a possible vice presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Speaker,'' Traficant thundered in 1996, ``I say it is time
for American consumers to tell Nike to take a hikey.''
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over the party's presidential contest will be
Ventura's personal choice for party chairman, Jack Gargan, a
68-year-old poker-playing, pool-shooting maverick who makes no
secret that he has ``an eye for the ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And those are my good points,'' said Gargan, who will play a
key role in determining who wins the Reform nomination and its
$12.6 million ``honeypot'' of matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan, in an interview, said he worries about the party's
survival. Because Perot faltered in 1996, securing only 8.4 percent
of the presidential vote after seizing 19 percent in 1992, the
Reform movement risks lurching toward irrelevance with a lackluster
performance in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to say this, but all the factions in this party that
I was hoping to bring together are just getting spread further
apart,'' Gargan said. ``I feel like I'm riding a tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the party's treasure trove of federal funds is likely to
keep the Reform candidate viable until the November election, long
after all but the final Democratic and Republican candidates have
left the national stage. And if the Reform candidate fares well, he
could influence the outcome of the presidential race, if not win
it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those prospects, some of Buchanan's fellow conservative
commentators have sounded the alarm, warning him not to leave the
GOP fold. The Reform Party is ``a dysfunctional fringe movement in
the midst of an identity crisis,'' Oliver North wrote last week in
his syndicated column. ``The net effect of Pat throwing his lot
with this cast of characters will be to finish, at best, in second
place in the 2000 presidential contest, and to commit himself to
the political equivalent of a padded room.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, evidence abounds that this will be a wild season in
Reform politics. Ventura figuratively bared all in the November
issue of Playboy, defending the Navy in the Tailhook
sexual-harassment scandal (``much ado about nothing'') and
advocating the decriminalization of drugs and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   He has ignored a letter from Perot's leadership team asking him
to leave the Reform movement because his Playboy comments ``about
religion, sexual assault, overweight people, drugs, prostitution,
women's undergarments, and many other subjects do not represent the
values, principles, and ethics upon which this party is built.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Buchanan ``is in the bunker,'' aides said, fending
off charges that his new book shows him to be soft on Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Trump rushed onto ``Larry King Live'' Thursday to muse about
Oprah Winfrey as his possible running mate: ``She's popular, she's
brilliant, she's a wonderful woman. . . . She'd be sort of like me.
I mean, I have a lot of things going, and she's got a lot of things
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulani has been on CNN and other news outlets, talking up the
Reform Party and talking down assertions by the Anti-Defamation
League that she springs from a cult-like movement that has espoused
anti-Semitism. Fulani ran for president in 1988 and 1992 as leader
of the New Alliance Party, which merged with the Reform Party in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Fulani said she is focused on party-building
rather than ideology, although she called Buchanan's overtures to
her ``a funeral for social conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulani also bristled at assertions stemming from her association
with the New Alliance Party. ``I am not an anti-Semite,'' she said.
``I feel very uncomfortable with how people throw those things
around. Basically, I feel hurt and misjudged, and people don't know
what the hell they are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is going to be an interesting year for those tracking
the Reform Party. Just ask Frank Coppinger, a former state
representative from West Roxbury who recently abandoned his
Democratic roots and joined the party of Perot, Ventura, and
company.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the Massachusetts chapter's Worcester gathering
last Sunday, Coppinger offered his prediction: ``This is going to
be one of the craziest elections you'll ever see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
