<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DO FISH SLEEP? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do fish sleep at night?
</P>
<P>
   G.W. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bailey, Curator of Fishes at the New England Aquarium,
says that fish don't sleep they way we think of sleep. In the
fish-eat-fish underwater world, the challenges of survival require
more creative ways of resting than just shutting down for eight
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish usually rest for just minutes at a time, kind of like cat
naps,'' Bailey says. And most species don't zonk out into a deep
sleep. They'll find a protect somewhere and slow their
metabolism down.
</P>
<P>
   How can you tell when a fish is sleeping, since they never close
their eyes? (They don't have eyelids. Sharks have membranes they
roll down over they eyes, but only to protect them while they're
feeding.) Parrot fish find a sheltered spot in the reef they
inhabit, and secrete a mucous cocoon around themselves, to keep
their scent in so they won't be attacked while resting.
</P>
<P>
   Trigger fish back in to a crack in a reef or between some rocks,
and trigger a set of spines to shoot out, wedging themselves in to
the crack. Then they can safely turn down their metabolism, since a
predator can't pull them out without ripping the rocks out of place
too.
</P>
<P>
   Brightly colored reef fish, like angel, goat, butterfly, or
surgeon fish, turn their colors down when they rest. ``Their brain
generates those colors, stimulating chromatophore cells. They use
the color to communicate during the day,'' Bailey says. ``They
don't need to communicate when they rest, and they're safer if they
blend into the environment, so they just shut that off at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fish are nocturnal, active at night, and do their resting
during the day. Moray eels, soldier fish, and squirrel fish, use
their large eyes to do their feeding at night, then drop to depths
of 2-300 feet during the day and find caves and crevices to rest
in.
</P>
<P>
   Some fish go to school when they rest. Mackerel, cod, and
haddock ``normally don't have much use for each other during the
day,'' Bailey says. But at night they form into schools. Bailey
says these groups don't behave the way schools of fish do when
they're awake, actively swimming about.
</P>
<P>
   ``They join together because when their individual sensory
systems are turned down, the overall protective sensory power of
the group is greater than that of any one individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fish that school when they're active, swim off as
individuals to find tiny nooks and crannies in the rocks or reefs
for protection while they rest.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the ``grabber sleepers.'' Remoras attach to their
host, go into a resting state while riding along wherever their
host goes, and, as Bailey says, ``they're on the train to breakfast
when the host starts feeding,'' providing the scraps the remoras
feed on. In New England's turbulent ocean waters, some small fish,
and juveniles, attach to sea plants that are rooted to the ocean
floor, or to rocks, to keep from drifting off.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a bit about the myth that sharks never sleep. Wrong.
Some,urse sharks and reef tip sharks, reach very deep
metabolic slowdown. They'll find some sheltered place and reach
such a deep state of rest that predators can attack them easily.
</P>
<P>
   The ``ram ventilators,'' sharks that have to keep swimming to
force oxygenated water over their gills so they can breathe,
include the great white, mako, blue, whale, and basking sharks.
Bailey says they rest by shutting down one or two systems at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   How do they keep swimming? ``They're designed to keep that
system operating all the time. It's like our heart. It slows down,
but it never stops,'' Bailey explains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
