<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN POLITICS HELPS DERAIL A JUDGE'S NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was ugly _ as all displays of raw, purely partisan politics
in the Senate are.
</P>
<P>
   It was even more ugly because it was tinged by race _ not the
overt insensitivity that is easy to shout about, but the subtle
kind to which all white people remain prone and which forms the
real foundation of the country's continuing shame.
</P>
<P>
   With New England's six Republican senators in a crucial role
without apparently realizing it, a partisan 55-45 vote last week
rejected the first African-American judge on the Missouri Supreme
Court for a US district court vacany after more than two years of
unconscionable limbo and two approving votes by the Senate
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ronnie White's nomination was headed for approval as
recently as last week, when Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi used his weekly party caucus lunch to launch a party
loyalty crusade on behalf of embattled Senator John Ashcroft of
Missouri, a prominent social issue conservative who is pushing
every divisive hot-button on the issue console to save his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the New Englanders aren't worth attention. Judd Gregg
(Republican) and Bob Smith (newly Independent) of New Hampshire are
pretty consistent partisan and ideological go-alongs; some days
they act like the same person.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Jeffords of Vermont, John Chaffee of Rhode Island, and
Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins of Maine have richly deserved
reputations for thoughtful independence, well-maintained relations
across the aisle, and dilligent work. When they go along, it's
worth paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Their votes were key because they helped provide cover for a
decisive fifth vote from a far more culpable moderate, Arlen
Specter of Pennsylvania, who had twice voted favorably on Judge
White in the Judiciary Committee, as had chairman Orrin Hatch and
Strom Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   None of the New England Four had so much as a syllable to utter
before, during or after the Senate's highly publicized action.
Later, when asked for reasons, only Collins' office was silent.
</P>
<P>
   The one common reason they cited was a tradition of deference to
the position of the senators from the state involved, especially
when the senators are from their political party. Given the chaos
of legislative life, this is a position that deserves respect.
</P>
<P>
   This point was especially well made on behalf of John Chaffee,
whose policy it also is not to let the judicial philosophy of a
particular nominee (even if the senator disagrees with it) affect
that deference.
</P>
<P>
   His position, however, is fatally undercut by the role played in
this fiasco by Ashcroft's Missouri colleague, Christopher Bond. In
his re-election campaign last year, Bond worked hard in the black
community to get a third of its vote, in part by trumpeting his
highly favorable view of Judge White. And Bond appeared in person
to introduce the judge with appropriate encomiums when he appeared
before the Judiciary Committee two years ago, and his support was a
matter of record when President Clinton renominated Judge White
after the current Congress commenced work last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ashcroft did not actively oppose Judge White until this
summer, at which point Bond began to waver publicly. This flagrant
flip-flopping should have been a red flag for senators to put aside
their usual deference to inquire more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, although deference to home-state senators is
appropriate, there should be greater deference to the actions of
the Judiciary Committee, which not only did the leg work on Judge
White's background but twice sent his nomination along in
bipartisan votes of support.
</P>
<P>
   The word from Jim Jeffords is that he had no idea the judge is
African-American until after vote. If Jeffords said he had seen
extra-terrestials in Burlington, my first impulse would be to
believe him, but he should have known it, given the last-minute
eruption of controversy driven by Lott and Ashcroft. Even casual
inquiry would have disclosed the judge's race.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact is, tellingly, that minority judicial nominees in
this Congress have been more than twice as unsuccessful as whites.
And the vote to reject Judge White was going to be the first to
reject a nomination in a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   Only Olympia Snowe took a shot at the judge. She said she was
``particularly concerned'' about two cases where he ``refused to
uphold jury verdicts even in the most egregious cases.'' This
dovetails with Ashcroft's more flamboyant assaults on him as
``pro-criminal'' and ``insufficiently supportive'' of the death
penalty, which border on defamation.
</P>
<P>
   The counterpoint is not simply that he has supported capital
punishment in nearly three-fourths of the supreme court cases he
helped decide, nor that a majority of his votes to overturn death
sentences were part of court majorities. The real point is that it
is never fair comment to judge an appellate decision on the
brutality of the underlying crime.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is not Judge White's record but the extent to
which the Ashcroft and Bond political flip-flops should influence
other senators.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever an incident happens that picks at the scab over
America's deep racial wound, the big question is rarely about what
bad people or no-count people do; it's what good people do that
matter most.
</P>
<P>
   And in this ugly mess, the New England Four didn't help; they
enabled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
