<HEADLINE>
KNOW YOUR BMI , THEN YOU CAN FUDGE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you know your BMI? No?
</P>
<P>
   On Friday I asked 10 people if they knew their own BMI. Not one
of them did. Five of them didn't know what a BMI is. The other five
knew, but didn't know theirs. Two of the five said they'd prefer
not to know their own BMI. I can't blame them. I'm not exactly
thrilled to know mine.
</P>
<P>
   A BMI isn't a new kind of luxury automobile. BMI doesn't stand
for Barely Making It, although in certain cases, my own for
example, it might apply.
</P>
<P>
   BMI stands for Body Mass Index. It's the latest thing in
diet-speak, a fancy way of indicating how fat you are. Instead of
saying, ``I need to lose 15 pounds,'' you say, ``My BMI is reaching
crisis levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about your BMI sounds impressive because instead of just
whining about your weight, you're taking a serious interest in your
health.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the BMI was much in the news. A study of more than 1
million Americans by the American Cancer Society, reported in the
New England Journal of Medicine, found ``compelling and
irrefutable'' evidence of a link between excess weight and a higher
risk of dying from heart disease or cancer.
</P>
<P>
   According to this study, 55 percent of Americans are overweight.
More of us are fat now than ever before. But we knew that. All we
have to do is look around to see that we've become the super-size
nation. Which brings us back to the BMI.
</P>
<P>
   The higher your BMI, the grimmer your prospects. The study
reported a gradually increasing risk of death beginning with a BMI
of 25, except among black women. For reasons as yet unknown to
science, black women with sky-high BMIs were at no more risk than
their slimmer sisters. Researchers are looking into it. Meanwhile,
55 percent of the rest of us are on the old treadmill to oblivion,
and the pace picks up with every pound.
</P>
<P>
   You may ask: Why do I need to find out my BMI? I know I'm fat.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's only a matter of hours before everybody's BMI
becomes crucial conversation fodder. You'd better determine what
yours is pretty quickly, so you'll be prepared to lie about it.
Knowing your BMI probably won't make it any easier to lose weight,
but being able to talk knowledgeably about your BMI will give the
impression that you're making a serious, informed effort to get
fit, even if you're not.
</P>
<P>
   Determining your BMI is simplicity itself.
</P>
<P>
   Step one: Convert your weight in pounds to kilograms.
</P>
<P>
   Got that? No?
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it's done. Divide your weight in pounds by 2.2. The
resulting figure is your weight in kilograms.
</P>
<P>
   Step two: Convert your height from inches to meters.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this easy? It's not?
</P>
<P>
   OK. First determine your height in inches. Then divide that
figure by 39.37. Presto. Your height in meters.
</P>
<P>
   Step three: Square your height in meters, then divide your
weight in kilograms by your height squared.
</P>
<P>
   That's all there is to it. You should have your BMI. Those doing
the figuring by hand may want to take a doughnut break. You've
earned it.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, your calculations will have produced a BMI
somewhere between 1 and 50. Lower is better, health-wise. A figure
between 15 and 25 is normal. Between 25.1 and 30, you're
overweight. Anything over 30 is obese.
</P>
<P>
   Now what? You may want to do something about lowering your BMI.
Or you may just want to talk about it. Either way, you're prepared.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
