<HEADER>
A3349 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-11 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEX FUNDS SHOULD HELP PAY OFF STUDENT LOAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 49-year-old single woman who recently finished
graduate school. Currently I earn $32,000 a year. I live in an
apartment, and the only debt I have is $20,000 in student loans
that have interest rates between 7.66 percent and 8.26 percent. I
have a combined amount of $2,200 in my savings and checking
accounts. Recently I received a $60,000 inheritance, which I was
considering using to pay off my entire student loan. I can save at
least $400 a month. I would like to know where and how to invest
this inheritance and future moneys. I would like some ideas to
insure a comfortable life in retirement. My Social Security is
estimated at $7,000 a year, based on my past employment.
</P>
<P>
   M.B., Northampton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You'll have to save pretty aggressively to achieve that
comfortable retirement, but the $60,000 inheritance certainly gives
you a nice leg up. Given that building your retirement account
should be your primary focus, I'd abandon the idea of prepaying the
student loans. If you invest the money for long-term growth, the
returns should exceed the interest level on the student loans.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to put the money in Vanguard index funds.
I suggest you explore two avenues. The first is direct ownership of
funds in taxable accounts, and the second is using variable annuity
accounts, which will defer the taxes on the growth within the
account. Thinking about taxes is important, because if you invest
the money now and embark upon a program of adding $400 a month to
your retirement savings, you would amass $456,164 by age 65, a
projection which assumes 10 percent average annual portfolio
growth. In the final year of that projection, you would be
contributing the same $400 a month as now, but more than $41,000
would be added through internal growth.
</P>
<P>
   If your portfolio growth is taxed each year as it is realized,
you could well reach a point that you would have to withdraw money
from the fund accounts to pay the taxes they generate. But with the
variable annuities, you'd face tax liabilities (only on the
internal growth of the account) only when it is withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to divide your investments 50-50 between
variable annuities and taxable accounts. I suggest a portfolio made
up of 50 percent Vanguard Index 500, and 16 2/3 percent each in
Vanguard Mid-Cap Index, Vanguard Small-Cap Index, and Vanguard
Balanced Index.
</P>
<P>
   As for your additional savings, I suggest you start by putting
$166 a month of your extra income into a Roth IRA invested in
Fidelity Health Care fund. While Roth IRAs do not provide you with
the tax deduction you can get from traditional IRAs, they
compensate for this by allowing withdrawal of all funds --
including the growth within the account -- on a tax-free basis once
you reach your retirement years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the remaining $233 to be saved, Id suggest a good proven
value-oriented stock fund such as Vanguard Windsor II or Vanguard
Index Value.
</P>
<P>
   A few final pointers: Since winning your graduate degree should
propel you into as higher earning capacity, calculate your current
retirement savings as a percentage of your income, and then
increase the dollar savings level by applying the same percentage
of your earnings each time you get a raise. If you become eligible
to participate in a 401(k) or 403(b) plan or any other tax-deferred
savings plan, join it, whether or not your employer matches your
contributions. Like the variable annuity accounts, this will defer
the taxes on this money until you are in your non-earning
retirement years.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, treat the retirement savings program as a discipline --
you are starting pretty late, and you can't afford to miss a
payment or two from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've been tempted to invest in high-yield uninsured
certificates such as are advertised in the enclosed clipping. They
pay between 8.5 percent and 10 percent interest. I've received the
companies statements and still cant decide if its safe enough. I
have a large amount of money in Vanguards Prime Money Market fund,
which pays 4.9 percent interest, but that is also not insured,
although I don't lose sleep about it. What do you think of the
offers represented in the clip?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Saylorsburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think much of it, to be honest. When you read the
fine print, you see that the advertised rates are teasers. For
example, in the ad you sent, the company offered a 7.79 percent
yield if you invested $50,000 or more, or a 7.25 percent yield if
you invested as little as $5,000. But the catch is that this rate
only applies until Jan. 15, 2000 -- after that the rate will be
adjusted weekly.
</P>
<P>
   So while the headline on the advertisement proposes that you
lock in the high rates, the lock quickly comes off and you then
will have a variable-rate certificate. If you invested the $5,000
minimum you would be only $30 ahead of the yield on the Vanguard
money market fund, assuming it held at the level it was at when you
wrote. Actually, it would probably be less than $30, since the
Prime Money Market funds yield has risen to 5.07 percent as this is
written.
</P>
<P>
   What I suggest you do is go through the literature you have been
sent, seeking to determine first what yields these certificates
have actually paid after the lock in period has expired, and
second, what is the credit quality of the ultimate borrowers. My
guess is that the closer you look, the less attractive these
instruments are.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are beginning a retirement savings plan. We are
40 and 37 years old and earn $80,000 combined. We bought our house
two years ago. We invest $791 a month which is evenly divided
between Mainstay Growth and Equity and Fidelity Contrafund II
funds. We put $166 a month into a Roth IRA invested in Mainstay
Capital Appreciation fund, and $250 a month each into Janus Twenty
and Dreyfus S&AMP;P Index funds. We have about $7,000 in a Vanguard
Index 500 account. Finally, we have an emergency fund to which we
contribute $250 a month. In two months, we will be able to raise
our savings level to $2,000 a month. Is our portfolio too heavily
weighted with aggressive growth funds? Should we include a midcap
and an international fund. How will out net worth look in 15 years?
</P>
<P>
   S.S., Orange, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. To begin with the punch line, if you raise your monthly
savings level from $1,707 to $2,000 after two months and if you
achieve average annual portfolio returns of 10 percent, you would
amass $826,866 in 15 years (and $1,485,008 after 20).
</P>
<P>
   I think the relative lack of diversification in your portfolio
is more troublesome than the concentration of growth funds. I'm not
sure what you refer to as Mainstay Growth and Equity; perhaps you
mean Mainstay Growth Opportunity and Mainstay Equity Income or
perhaps Mainstay Equity Index.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever way it goes, it adds up to too much reliance on
large-cap domestic stock funds. So you should indeed look for
mid-cap and international positions, and if I were you I'd also
establish positions in a small-cap and a health care fund, keeping
each of these minor themes in the overall portfolio limited to
about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I based the estimate of 10 percent long-term portfolio growth on
the idea that within a year or two you will feel that youve
established enough in that emergency fund and will then divert
those savings into the stock funds which form the core of the
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   I am hoping that the account to which you contribute that $791 a
month is a 401(k) or some other tax-deferred savings plan. If not,
I would look beyond the Roth IRA for more tax-advantaged saving
vehicles. If neither of you have tax-deferred savings plans
available at work, I suggest you consider putting a sizable part of
your retirement savings in variable annuities, which are available
from most major mutual fund companies, and which tend to be modeled
on and track the results of the more popular retail funds.
</P>
<P>
   There is a small amount of insurance involved in the variable
annuity contract, which is what qualifies these instruments for tax
deferral. The cost of this insurance generally tends to reduce the
variable annuity account performance to a level about 1/2 percent
lower than that of the corresponding retail funds. In my opinion,
that 1/2 percent is an attractive price to pay for the tax
deferral.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
