A3351 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-FASHION-BOS &LR;      10-11 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FASHION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF FASHION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  The Mass Marketing of the Clothing Business 
By Teri Agins 
Morrow, 320 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has the concept of fashion gone out of style? Certainly
magazines are no longer dictating wardrobe choices for the masses.
And the idea of paying full price for a new designer creation is,
for many people, laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Just what happened to the influence of the elite designer? Wall
Street Journal reporter Teri Agins contends that kind of fashion
has given way to the power of mass marketing from retailers like
the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The End of Fashion,'' Agins chronicles the industry over
the last century, from the golden years when elitist Parisian
designers and their wealthy socialite customers set the standards
for style around the world and the masses followed their lead. She
writes that in the 1980s and '90s, a fundamental power shift
occurred: Suddenly the general public, not designers, was
determining the styles it wanted and the prices it was willing to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Agins attributes this shift to the social changes in the lives
of consumers. For one thing, women ``let go of fashion'': ``By the
198lions of baby-boomer career women were moving up in the
workplace, and the impact of their professional mobility was
monumental. As bank vice presidents, members of corporate boards,
and partners at law firms, professional women became secure enough
to ignore the foolish runway frippery that bore no connection to
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Men and women alike stopped dressing up, even at work. Thanks in
part to the computer nerds in the Silicon Valley, Agins writes,
casual day was born, creating a huge market for the likes of khakis
and knit shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Agins points out that consumers' values were altered at the same
time. ``Most people used to put `fashion' on a pedestal,'' she
writes. But that changed when stores like Ann Taylor, Gap, Banana
Republic, and J. Crew ``turned out good-looking clothes that
deflated the notion that fashion belonged exclusively to the
elite.'' As a whole generation of people under 40 grew up wearing
these comfortable, affordable clothes, high-fashion designer labels
became less relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Agins says, top designers _ many of whom had taken
their companies public _ stopped gambling on fashion whims and
instead produced wearable apparel, as well as accessories,
cosmetics, and home furnishings. These items may appear lesscreative, but they sell _ which is what shareholders want.
</P>
<P>
   ``The End of Fashion'' is a fascinating read for anyone who
loves the industry, its players, or clothing itself. Through
interviews with high-placed sources throughout the business, Agins
tells interesting stories about the fierce rivalry between Ralph
Lauren and Tommy Hilfiger; how Giorgio Armani developed a publicity
machine to get his clothes on Hollywood's A-list of celebrities;
and how Donna Karan struggled after taking her company public.
</P>
<P>
   Agins also traces the history of the French couture industry
from its triumph in the 19th century through the years when its
influence began to wane. The cultural and sexual revolution of the
1960s brought major change, she argues: With the advent of the
miniskirt, suddenly shopping in small boutiques with low prices was
``in.'' To keep up, French designers like Emanuel Ungaro and Yves
Saint Laurent introduced ready-to-wear collections for their own
shops, causing even rich clients to get accustomed to more
affordable quality clothing _ and presaging the wider changes of
the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Agins writes, creativity in fashion is expressed more in
marketing than in apparel. Designers have learned to circumvent the
fashion press by taking their message directly to consumers via
multiple-page advertising inserts in magazines. ``Today's
`branding' of fashion has taken on a critical role in an era when
there's not much in the way of new styling going on _ just about
every store in the mall is peddling the same styles of clothes,''
she says. ``That's why designer logos have become so popular; logos
are the easiest way for each designer to impart a distinguishing
characteristic on what amounts to some pretty ordinary apparel.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's era of Gap-like uniformity, Agins's book helps
readers figure out what happened to American style. Her insightful
analyses are well documented by industry experts. And her
conclusion _ anything marketed well will sell _ hits home to those
who have witnessed dramatic cultural changes over the decades but
never really thought about their impact on the closet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
