<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-GALBRAITH-BOS &LR;      10-11 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GALBRAITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COMPANY THEY KEPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
From F.D.R. On 
By John Kenneth Galbraith. Houghton Mifflin. 194 pp. $26. 
 
MEMORIES OF THE GREAT &AMP; THE GOOD 
By Alistair Cooke. Arcade. 277 pp. $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the attributes of two aging men of accomplishment and
letters like John Kenneth Galbraith and Alistair Cooke, this may be
the greatest: They look back, but not in anger. Nor in resentment.
Nor in envy.
</P>
<P>
   This publishing season (and this season of the century) brings
an especially happy harvest, twin volumes of reminiscences by
outsiders who became American insiders, and who in time also became
American icons. And in two brisk little volumes, Galbraith and
Cooke speed lightly through lives lived well _ not their own,
though they were lived uncommonly well, but the lives of men and
women who touched them and who helped shape the century.
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith was reared in Canada, Cooke in England, but their gift
is their understanding of the United States, and though they are
not strictly American characters, they have enormous insight into
the American character. And so our understanding, for example, of
Franklin Delano Roosevelt and Eleanor Roosevelt (treated in both
volumes), and of Lyndon Johnson (memorably sketched by Galbraith)
and Barry Goldwater (masterfully portrayed by Cooke), is
immeasurably enhanced and enriched.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is our understanding of both Galbraith, the Harvard
economist and popularizer of the phrase ``the affluent society,''
and Cooke, the BBC broadcaster popular for his ``Letter from
America'' that is one of the staples of the century's culture.
(Cooke has filed his ``Letter'' every week for 53 years, a landmark
in radio.) The two men are representatives of a dying breed, the
detached observer from abroad who brushes past the great and the
good of the era (plus a few of the bad and the ugly) and then
paints them in spare but illuminating brush strokes.
</P>
<P>
   They are ironists, too. Galbraith points out that he and Ronald
Reagan (``the first wholly uninhibited Keynesian president'') were
both founders of the Americans for Democratic Action, a leading
liberal interest group. Cooke, in a brilliant essay about Winston
Churchill, points out that one of the British prime minister's
virtues was ``the acceptance of humiliating defeats as episodes
natural to the wielding of power.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do these two men have to say for themselves, or about
other people? Let's start with the people they cover in common:
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Roosevelt. First Galbraith: ``The United States he saw
as a vast estate extending out from his family home at Hyde Park,
N.Y. For this he had responsibility, and particularly for the
citizens and workers thereon.'' Then Cooke: ``To a Europe bereft of
notable leaders who were not tyrants, here was a man who, defying
the current totalitarian models and denouncing them, was
reinvigorating the largest democracy by democratic means and with
the enthusiastic consent of the mass of his people.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Roosevelt. Galbraith: ``We do not think of her as a
presidential artifact, nor did she so think of herself. She existed
independent of the president.'' Cooke: ``(S)he simply listed in the
`Who's Who' entry only three or four offices she filled on her own
account. She might have recorded the sum of her great life with
nothing more than her vital statistics and the single entry:
`Created the 32nd president of the United States.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In those two paragraphs alone rest four insights capable of
jogging any reader's sense of the Roosevelts, and of history. But,
thankfully, there is more.
</P>
<P>
   General George C. Marshall ``was a man whose inner strength and
secret humor only slowly dripped through the surfaces of life, as a
stalactite hangs stiff and granity for centuries before one sees it
beneath a pool of still water of marvelous purity'' (Cooke). Robert
F. Kennedy ``was the principal moral force both in the White House
inner circle and the larger administration'' (Galbraith).
</P>
<P>
   Robert Frost was ``an outdoor Emily Dickinson'' (Cooke). Lyndon
Johnson ``was accomplished in using fiction as a cover for
plausible fact'' (Galbraith). And: ``Goldwater's flaw as a
practicing politician of high principle was a streak of naivete
which allowed him to embrace as allies shabby people and malicious
people who simply said aloud they were against the things he was
against. He assumed they shared the principles when all they shared
was a gross prejudice'' (Cooke).
</P>
<P>
   Along the way there are irresistible anecdotes galore, like the
time Galbraith brought Angie Dickinson to meet Jawaharlal Nehru,
then the prime minister of India, or the time Cooke, at Dwight D.
Eisenhower's farm in Gettysburg for a television interview, tried
to explain to the former supreme allied commander why the camera
crew sometimes took an hour to change the lighting. (Ike's
observation, testimony to his great gift for understatement: ``It's
a weird business.'')
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably but gratifyingly, these books reflect the authors'
respective strengths. Galbraith's is in devising immutable laws of
behavior, whether economic or political: ``In all politics one
needs an enemy and preferably an incompetent, misguided or socially
adverse one.'' President Clinton has profited from that advice
handsomely. Cooke's strength is in the very act of observation:
``It was a splendid day in Vermont when they buried Robert Frost,
the sky without a cloud, the light from the white landscape making
every elm and barn as sharp as a blade, and the people crunching
quietly through the deep snow and squinting in the enormous sun.''
Not even Frost could say it better.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-page reminiscence that Cooke wrote about John Nance
Garner, FDR's first vice president, is the single best evocation of
the first four decades of the century in Texas and Washington ever
composed. I read it twice and then, when I finished the book, I
read it yet again _ two more times. Consider this small excerpt:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon he was in the Texas legislature and in 1902 he
went to Congress, a small farmer's, railroad-hating Populist who
burrowed his way into power through the channels he knew best: the
back room, the small office, the poker game, the little chat with
worried men. All his life he distrusted orators, `crooners' as he
used to call them. Politics was doing the best you could for the
people you knew best; and that meant wheedling bills through a
reluctant Congress. He was a tireless wheedler, and he once said
that `a snort of bourbon is a better persuader than the Twelve
Apostles.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That was a different time. In two different volumes, Cooke and
Galbraith remind us how different it was, and they pass along some
of the richness of it. Their ultimate achievement is to remind us
that some of that richness, of course, is these two themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is chief of The Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
