<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3358 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-YEARS-BOS &LR;      10-11 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-YEARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE TOLD FOREVER AND AGAIN BY DIFFERENT WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE STORY OF A MILLION YEARS 
By David Huddle. Houghton Mifflin. 190 pp. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   However much gentle readers may enjoy being told the way the
world works, the benevolent tyranny of the omniscient narrator has
been under assault for years. Experience is fractured! cried the
moderns, then the postmoderns; Only the interior point of view is
sacrosanct. So there went centuries of now-suspect bird's-eye
narration, too often replaced in contemporary fiction by teensy
insights from myopic visionaries. But the greater point was well
taken in a universe that was, we now had to admit, governed by
relativity. On the personal and literary scale, this meant that if
I looked out the window and saw morning sunshine, you were just as
likely to see smog, traffic, and atmospheric traces of the
emotional tempest you'd borne the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Handled well, this new humility of vision actually opens up the
world a bit, and it's used to beautiful effect in poet and essayist
David Huddle's accomplished first novel. Although its focus is the
intersection of a few primary stories through several connecting
lives, the title of ``The Story of a Million Years'' is both ironic
and just _ capturing the kaleidoscopic infinity of a tale told
twice, or forever and again, by the different people who were there
to witness its unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   Huddle has imagined and reimagined his story with understated
precision, and the novel benefits from slow reading: The longer you
spend in the company of each of these narrators, the more deeply
identified you become with each of their dissonant perspectives.
This prismatic richness is cumulative, so that only near the end of
the work does the story expand outward to reveal new insights about
its beginning. Crosscutting among seven voices, ``The Story of a
Million Years'' has the still-life quality of a domestic drama
glimpsed through a picture window _ then explained by each person
you saw weeping, or laughing, in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Crandall, nee Bunkleman, is the obvious focal point of the
novel, and the first chapter (included in ``Best American Short
Stories 1996'') belongs to her, looking back on the affair she hada family friend, a man named Robert Gordon, the summer she was
15 _ and he was 41. It's a weird, Lolita setup waiting to happen,
and yet Huddle mostly pulls it off, in part because Marcy is a
dynamite character who keeps her heart to herself. By the end of
``Past My Future,'' Marcy's first story, we know that she will only
half-love and then leave Gordon, marrying the high-school
sweetheart she had the good sense to prefer. What we realize
immediately in ``Past Perfect,'' her husband Allen's version of
events, is how skewed and circumscribed this chain of events is
going to be _ marked by secrets and interpretations, deceits that
don't matter and private emotions that do.
</P>
<P>
   The overlapping central story of the novel belongs to Marcy and
Allen and their friends Jimmy and Uta Rago, all of whom hung out
together as students at the University of Virginia. Marcy and Uta
went on to nursing school; Allen, the arrogant bigshot who adored
Marcy because she never feared him, started off on a baseball
scholarship and wound up a lobbyist in D.C. Yet another man dazzled
by Marcy's sang-froid, Jimmy never had a chance with her, and so
married her best friend instead. Now an intensive-care nurse, Uta
possesses her own qualities of cool; she also has the unique
advantage of seeing Allen for the frail blowhard he really is.
Together and apart, these people face the usual hurdles of
parenting, aging, coming to terms with memory and reality. Their
collective saga has the feel of James Salter's ``Light Years,'' or
some of Updike's Maples stories _ satiny and sad, inflicted with
wisdom and resurrected only by self-knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the power of ``The Story of a Million Years'' lies in
its disparate revelations, so I won't diminish that punch here. But
the wistfulness of the novel (and its thematic intent) comes from
its tributaries of homage to the form of story itself _ the way it
shapes our lives, organizes our memories, allows us to live with
what we have done or failed to do. Thus Uta has her recollections
about a morning in New York when she had a chance at human
goodness, and took it; Jimmy, remembering his sister's childhood
death, can see the way her life and then absence made him who he
was. Even Robert Gordon _ the dark prince who in some ways has the
most interesting ``role'' in the story _ has a tragic grasp of what
you might call ordinary grace: the translucent quality you may or
may not see if you turn away from darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally this high-gloss literary sheen feels
self-consciously fluent and therefore a bit precious; the novel
veers once or twice toward metaphorical overkill. And Huddle's
empathic imagination, for all its reach, falters in certain
territories: a mother's split consciousness between passion and
parenting; a girl's choices about desire during a perfect
interlude. But these stumbles stand out because most of the novel
is so quietly and generously realized, from Marcy's splendidly
impenetrable life to the equally opaque enigmas of ``Summer
Afternoon.'' Over and over again, the voices of ``The Story of a
Million Years'' inform us of the chiaroscuro of the modern world _
a place of light and shadow and endless possibility, where things
are never, merely, as they seem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
