<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Bedrooms and Hallways'' Lively, mostly gay, and pretty
broadly drawn sex farce that leaves plenty of room for gender
confusion. It represents a sort of backhanded breakthrough: It
makes available to gay characters a form that's pretty moribund,
even on TV. Although slicker than Rose Troche's debut film, ``Go
Fish,'' it's not nearly as personal and endearing. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Happy, Texas'' Winning populist froth, with just enough spin
put on a storyline that might have been lifted from a silent movie
_ two prison escapees are mistaken for beauty-pageant organizers in
a Texas town that's hungering to send its schoolgirls to the state
finals. Flavorful acting, especially from Steve Zahn as the funny
con on the run and William H. Macy as a very proper sheriff whose
heart is on fire. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The Limey'' Stylish performances from '60s icons Terence
Stamp and Peter Fonda. Stamp is a British career criminal who comes
to LA after the death of his only daughter, gunning for the sleazy
record producer who's responsible; Fonda is his slick but shallow
target. Director Steven Soderbergh adds snazzy visuals, emphasizing
LA's sunny isolation. But they can do only so much to divert us
from a perilously slight story. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Random Hearts'' A-list soap opera, with Harrison Ford as a
stoical D.C. cop and Kristin Scott Thomas as a poised New Hampshire
congresswoman. They're thrown together when he learns that their
respective spouses, victims in an air crash, were having an affair.
It's dignified, intelligent, and handsomely crafted, but you never
believe the way these two come together. It seems to proceed from
the script's need for a star coupling, rather than from the
characters' natures. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``Romance'' This French film about a woman who throws herself
into a round of sexual activity when her self-esteem is shattered
by a lover's rejection could have been the film ``Eyes Wide Shut''
wasn't. But it isn't. Although Catherine Breillat's movie is more
sexually explicit than any other recent film that wants to be more
than porn, it's got the sexual energy of a dead battery. And
because the sex proceeds from the central character's self-directed
anger, it's acted out under a pall of morose self-abasement.
(Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Superstar'' A slender but nevertheless winning one-joke
comedy. Molly Shannon beats the odds by extending her ``Saturday
Night Live'' character _ tightly wound Catholic parochial
schoolgirl Mary Katherine Gallagher _ from skit to movie and making
it work on the strength of her tunnel-visioned intensity. It helps
that her SNL colleague Will Ferrell is on hand to play the dim bulb
she lusts after. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
