<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARRICK' HEISMAN HOPES STOLEN AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending for all needed)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Peter Warrick blew it.
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman Trophy, for all intents and purposes, was his to
lose. The star wide receiver of the No. 1 Florida State Seminoles
had no peer, really, when it came to the Heisman race. He was atop
everyone's list.
</P>
<P>
   Until, that is, Warrick suffered a precipitous fall from grace
when he and teammate Lavernaues Coles were arrested last Thursday
for grand theft.
</P>
<P>
   Coles, a recalcitrant receiver already on double-secret
probation, was kicked off the team, and Warrick was suspended
indefinitely after the players, abetted by a star-struck,
19-year-old Dillard's department store clerk, took $412.38 worth of
clothing from the store after plunking down only $21.40.
</P>
<P>
   Both players are due in court Monday, but even if Warrick plea
bargains his felony charge down to a misdemeanor, there is no
minimizing the devastating impact it has had on his teammates,
school, coaches, family, and, quite possibly, his future in the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   While Warrick issued a nationally televised apology to the
aforementioned parties during Florida State's 31-21 victory over
Miami Saturday, he should just forget the Heisman. He blew it. Big
time.
</P>
<P>
   That should be _ and probably is _ Bobby Bowden's counsel to his
troubled star player.
</P>
<P>
   If Warrick is given a reprieve _ and there is a strong
possibility he could return in time to help the Seminoles to a
national championship once his matter is adjudicated _ Bowden said
he would advise Warrick ``to take a very back seat, a very back
seat. You go out there and just play the best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Bowden wants Warrick back in the fold. But the
Florida State coach needs to make sure Warrick pays a price _ and
not just $21.40 _ for his sins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so a nation of Heisman voters turns its lonely eyes toward
you, Joe Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake _ if Hamilton wins the Heisman, it will not be
by default. So far this season, the Georgia Tech quarterback has
staged an impressive Heisman campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Hamilton led the Yellow Jackets on a game-saving drive
for the fifth time in 12 games in a 31-24 overtime victory against
North Carolina. He completed 14 of 26 passes for 273 yards and had
touchdown passes of 47 and 59 yards while rushing for 77 yards,
including a 14-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's leader in passing efficiency (191.24), Hamilton so
far this season has passed for 1,347 yards and 12 touchdowns and
has thrown just four interceptions. He now becomes the leading
contender for the Heisman. Although Wisconsin's Ron Dayne is slowly
gathering steam for consideration after the Dayne Train apparently
was derailed in a loss to Michigan three weeks ago, it is clear the
Heisman is now Hamilton's to lose.
</P>
<P>
   All he has to do now is avoid going on any shopping sprees with
Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, which leapfrogged from No. 11 to No. 5 in the
Associated Press ratings, cracked the Top 5 for the first time in
32 years after its impressive 34-31 victory over archrival
Michigan, which plummeted from No. 3 to No. 10 after dropping to
5-1. The victory was especially sweet for the Spartans, one of
eight undefeated teams remaining in the AP Top 25, who have run
their overall record to 6-0 for the first time since 1966.
Quarterback Bill Burke set a school record with his 400 yards
passing, while junior receiver Plaxico Burress set another school
record with his 10 catches for 255 yards, highlighted by long
receptions of 39, 49, and 68 yards. Burress also had a 15-yard
touchdown pass from Burke. ``We've got 365 days until they get
another chance,'' said Michigan State's Amp Campbell. ``We can go
anywhere we want to and brag about it. We can walk into an Ann
Arbor mall wearing our Michigan State hats and be proud.'' . . .
Notre Dame probably was filming a sequel to ``Rudy'' when coach Bob
Davie inserted sophomore tailback Tim O'Neill, a 5-foot-5-inch
nonscholarship player from Troy, Mich., in the waning moments of
Saturday's 48-17 romp over Arizona State. O'Neill carried twice for
4 yards on consecutive handoffs in Notre Dame's penultimate
possession . . . One supposes Wisconsin's Barry Alvarez, coaching
his team from his hospital bed while awaiting knee surgery in a
hospital 75 miles away in Rochester, Minn., must have required
cardiac care after his Badgers had to go into overtime to beat
Minnesota, 20-17, on Vitaly Pisetsky's 31-yard field goal . . .
Division 3 Mount Union won its 47th consecutive game _ a 66-0 rout
over Heidelberg _ to match the nation's longest winning streak, set
by Oklahoma (1953-57). Mount Union has won three consecutive
Division 3 national championships and four this decade . . . We
hate to dogpile on the Huskies, but Northeastern's 77-0 loss at
UMass Saturday ranked as the most lopsided in the country that day.
Only Oberlin's 71-0 loss to Wooster came close. There were only
three other teams who won Saturday by scoring 70 points or more:
Nebraska-Kearney over Fort Lewis, 79-13; Sterling over Ottawa,
Kan., 70-42; and Cortland State over New Jersey City, 73-7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
