<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF SPINES AND DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the difference between a doctor of osteopathy and a
medical doctor?
</P>
<P>
   A: Osteopathic medicine, developed by an American, Andrew T.
Still (1828-1917), in 1874, originally held that conventional
medicines were poisonous and that manipulation of the
musculoskeletal system could overcome abnormalities that led to
disease, even in organs like the heart and lungs.
</P>
<P>
   While doctors of osteopathy (who use D.O. after their names)
still use osteopathic manipulative therapy and while their training
includes up to 300 hours of training in manipulation, they now alsoe techniques of medical doctors, including drugs and surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The two kinds of doctors have similar four-year medical schools
with similar accreditation, followed by hospital training, often in
conventional hospitals. All states and the military allow
osteopaths to practice medicine, including prescribing drugs,
delivering babies and performing surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The main split between the two schools is now often seen as one
of philosophy; osteopaths, about half of whom are primary-care
physicians, are more likely to use hands-on treatment and see
spinal links to more diseases. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Medical doctors often regard the osteopathic approach as having
been less less rigorously tested than conventional medicine and are
especially skeptical of the efficacy of manipulation for ailments
other than spine problems.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
