<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-PYTHON-ANNIVERSARY-BO     10-11 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PYTHON-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW FOR SOMETHING COMPLETELY FAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ They're not dead yet.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, one of them is. But the other five men who make
up the Monty Python comedy troupe are feeling much better, well
enough to reassemble this weekend to mark the 30th anniversary of
the first showing on the BBC of ``Monty Python's Flying Circus.''
</P>
<P>
   That television show produced 45 episodes, spawned a cottage
industry of books, recordings, and films, and in the process
redefined British humor, finding an eager audience not just here
but in the United States, where the shows were broadcast on public
television and became cult classics.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the BBC devoted 3 1/2 hours of air time to Monty
Python retrospectives, including a screening of the 1979 film
``Life of Brian,'' a spoof on a Christ-like character that was
denounced by some as blasphemous.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Python was politically incorrect long before the term was
coined. They sang about cross-dressing lumberjacks, portrayed
Scotsmen as kilt-wearing automatons, and staged a mock Olympics for
the mentally disabled that would never get on the air these days.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Monty Python is part of the establishment. Michael
Palin does a BBC travel show. John Cleese, whose series ``Fawlty
Towers,'' about a bumbling innkeeper, became another cult classic,
does commercials for a British supermarket chain. Eric Idle lives
in California with his American wife and stars in the Brooke
Shields sitcom ``Suddenly Susan.'' Terry Jones and Terry Gilliam,
the American animator who produced the surreal animations for the
show, have directed Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the reasons Monty Python's satire of the British
establishment was so cutting is that the troupe was a product of
that establishment. Cleese and Graham Chapman, a member of the
troupe who died 10 years ago, met at Cambridge University. Idle,
Palin, and Jones appeared in revues at Oxford University together.
</P>
<P>
   All five of them graduated from Britain's two most prestigious
universities and began writing and performing for television and
radio. The BBC threw them together on a lark, a new show to fill a
void. Gilliam, whom Cleese had met in New York, was thrown in for
good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Took, an adviser to the BBC who devised the idea for the
show, said the title came from one of his bosses' dismissing him as
being like ``Baron Von Richthoven and his Flying Circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleese said that it was initially going to be called ``Gwen
Dibley's Flying Circus'' after Palin found that name in a newspaper
article, but that one of the group _ no one can say for sure who _
suggested Monty Python.
</P>
<P>
   Cleese said they just thought it sounded funny.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC agreed, up to a point. Monty Python had to go to court
on more than one occasion to prevent its skits from being edited.
In one case, one of Gilliam's animations had a voiceover in which
the narrator explained that a young prince found a spot on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foolishly he ignored it,'' the narrator said, ``and three
years later he died of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The BBC changed ``cancer'' to ``gangrene.''
</P>
<P>
   On the TV show, they sang about the virtues of Spam, satirized
randy clerics in ``The Dirty Vicar'' sketch, and routinely dressed
in women's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In their first movie, ``Monty Python and the Holy Grail,'' they
made fun of King Arthur, portraying him and his Knights of the
Roundtable as a bunch of morons. In one scene, Idle wheels a cart
through a village during the bubonic plague and calls for people to
``bring out your dead.'' Cleese emerges with an old man flung over
his shoulder and tries to dump him on the cart. But the old man
protests, saying, ``I'm not dead yet. I'm feeling much better.''
After haggling with Idle, who says he can't take the old man alive,
Cleese persuades Idle to wallop the old man on the head and take
him away.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, four of the five remaining members of the troupe
attended a screening of ``Life of Brian'' at the Empire Theatre in
Leicester Square to raise money for cancer research in memory of
Chapman. Idle did not show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is not playing with us at the moment,'' quipped Jones.
Idle is still smarting over the troupe's decision to cancel a 30th
anniversary touring show.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all that's eating at Idle. He laments that they all
have become part of the establishment they once savaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss people hating us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Kevin Cullen heads the Globe's London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
