<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      10-11 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THERAPIES: Hope for the Snorer's Suffering Spouse &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For millennia _ or maybe just sleepless nights that felt that
long _ people with serious snoring problems could rely on only
their spouses for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's referred to as `elbow therapy,''' said Dr. John W.
Shepard Jr., a specialist in sleep disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers have established not only how disruptive serious
snorers (usually men) can be to their partners _ costing them about
an hour's sleep per night _ but have also shown that the problem
can be greatly eased with a special nose mask.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, working at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn.,
had 10 couples sleep in the lab, each wired to the gills with
monitoring equipment, and measured the couples' sleep patterns.
They reported seeing far fewer ``arousals'' when the mask was used.
</P>
<P>
   The study is reported in this month's Mayo Clinic Proceedings.
Shepard, the director of the sleep disorders center at Mayo, said
it showed just how serious a problem snoring can be for the
well-being of the spouses and the health of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, he said, asked him whether it really mattered if a
snorer's partner lost some sleep. He told them, ``Set your clock
one hour earlier than you're used to getting up for the next week,
and call me and let me know how you feel.''
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on couples in which the man was being
evaluated for obstructive sleep apnea, a serious condition in which
the muscles at the back of the throat relax during sleep, briefly
cutting off breathing.
</P>
<P>
   The couples spent one night being studied. Monitors were
attached to the men to assess respiration. Among numerous other
devices, electrodes were placed on the women's scalps to measure
brain activity, letting doctors know when _ and how deeply _ they
were asleep.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of the night, the men were given no
treatment. But for the second, they were fitted with
oxygen-mask-like gear known as continuous positive airway pressure
devices. The apnea episodes decreased to an average of 7, from 26.
And the percentage of time the women spent sleeping increased to 87
percent, from 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREVENTION: For Athletes, a Consensus on Concussion &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely to lay a divisive issue to rest (indeed, even
its authors urge much more study), but new guidelines are making
their way to schools around the country with advice on how to
handle head injuries on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been disagreement over when, or whether, to
return a player to the game if the athlete suffers what appears to
be a concussion, a common injury in sports that involve either a
lot of impact or sudden, swift changes in posture.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines, published in the current issue of The American
Journal of Sports Medicine, were developed after a 1997 conference
attended by representatives of a wide array of medical and sports
organizations. The recommendations are described as a consensus and
are not endorsed by every group. Some believe they go too far;
others, not far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines recommend that an athlete who appears to have
received a head injury be immediately evaluated on the field. If
there is a loss of consciousness or symptoms that last longer than
15 minutes, or recur, the player should be taken out of a game and
seen by a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   When symptoms last less than 15 minutes, the report advises,
athletes can usually return to play, but only after being made to
perform increasingly difficult physical tasks, like sit-ups, to
make sure the symptoms do not return.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being kept out of the game, athletes whose
symptoms take longer than 15 minutes to subside should be gradually
reintroduced to physical activity only over the next week or so.
</P>
<P>
   If they ignore the caution, said Dr. Edward M. Wojtys, a surgeon
and associate team physician for the University of Michigan, they
are in danger of seriously reinjuring themselves. For a period of
time after a concussion, the brain remains more susceptible to
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies have reported that nearly 63,000 high school
athletes a year suffer mild concussions, and that two or more
significant blows can harm a teen-ager for years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PATTERNS: The Right Place for a Heart Attack &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Having a heart attack in an integrated neighborhood may offer a
better chance of getting cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published in this month's Annals of Emergency
Medicine, a team of researchers associated with the University of
Chicago examined 4,379 heart attack cases and found that in
neighborhoods where there were more heart attacks, residents were
most likely to be ready to offer aid.
</P>
<P>
   That was not surprising, but for reasons they were at a loss to
explain, the researchers also made this discovery: People were most
likely to receive CPR in neighborhoods that were integrated. People
were next most likely to receive CPR in neighborhoods that were
predominantly white, and least likely to receive such aid in
neighborhoods that were predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
   The researches theorized that the CPR response rate may be
higher in integrated neighborhoods because those communities often
have stronger institutions, like churches, that sometimes offer CPR
training, said Theodore J. Iwashyna, one of the authors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIDE EFFECTS: Relax! Stress May Harm the Prostate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Further indication about the health benefits of relaxing: a new
study suggests a link in men between stress and a chemical in their
blood that has been associated, at high levels, with a risk of
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the medical school of the State University of New
York at Stony Brook discovered the link in a study of 318 men.
</P>
<P>
   The men received digital rectal exams and blood tests for
prostate specific antigen, a protein that, when found at elevated
levels, may indicate prostate cancer. (Another recent study
suggested that the protein might not only serve as a marker of
cancer but also might help the body fight cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   The men were also asked to complete standard psychological
screening tests measuring their levels of anger and nervousness,
their ability to cope with daily life and their satisfaction with
their relationships with families and friends.
</P>
<P>
   When they analyzed the results, researchers found that men with
higher stress levels were three times as likely to have high levels
of prostate specific antigen.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur A. Stone, the psychologist who led the study, said
the finding might be another example of weakening of the immune
system's ability to fight disease caused by stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what the immune system does is keep things under
control,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers said they could not be sure whether stress
caused the higher antigen levels or was simply associated with
them.
</P>
<P>
   It was also possible that the stress was caused by the men's
concern over the possibility of having a medical problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WITH JUST A SPOONFUL OF LICORICE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If the candy industry is not careful, it may end up having to
contend with a twist on the old temperance movement poster
campaign: ``Lips that touch liquor shall not touch mine.'' For
liquor, substitute licorice.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter in the current issue of The New England Journal of
Medicine, three physicians in Italy contend that licorice root may
impede sexual performance and may even cause loss of sex drive in
men.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors _ Decio Armanini and Guglielmo Bonanni of Padua and
Mario Palermo of Sassari _ gave seven men ages 22 to 24 0.28 ounces
a day of a commercial licorice tablet. The doctors found that the
men's testosterone levels decreased during the period they ate the
licorice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amounts of licorice given to these men are eaten by many
people,'' the doctors wrote. ``Thus, men with decreased libido or
other sexual dysfunction, as well as those with hypertension,
should be questioned about licorice ingestion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
