<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EARLY-FLU-SEASON-     10-11 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EARLY-FLU-SEASON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY FEARS ABOUT THE FLU 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla., Texas, Okla., La., Alaska) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By RANDI HUTTER EPSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The flu season does not usually start before November, so health
officials in the state of New York were startled last week when the
influenza A virus raced through Monroe Community Hospital, a
chronic-care center in Rochester, N.Y., infecting many elderly
patients before they had received flu shots.
</P>
<P>
   In Great Neck, N.Y., a month-old baby was hospitalized with
influenza A on Sept. 27. (No one died at the care center and the
baby recovered within three days.) And while the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta does not yet have
national statistics for this year, there have been reports of
outbreaks in Alaska, Louisiana, Florida, Oklahoma and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these early cases, health experts and officials say,
predicting the severity of this year's flu season is about as
reliable as predicting the amount of snow this winter. There are
indications, gathered by monitoring flu epidemics around the world,
but there are no guarantees that the same strains will strike here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot predict how much flu you'll see, the timing or
intensity of the flu season,'' said Lynnette Brammer, an
epidemiologist with the influenza branch at the CDC. ``People
continually look for ways to make predictions, but the flu is
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, early reports have been reassuring. ``The one thing we do
know from the U.S. and international surveillance is that there are
not any influenza viruses that look terribly unusual,'' Ms. Brammer
said. ``All the viruses look like they will be sensitive to the
available vaccines, which is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that complacency is in order, officials say.
The elderly, children with asthma and people with chronic illnesses
should still get flu shots before November. Waiting until the virus
is widespread might be too late because the vaccine takes one to
two weeks to become effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are just gearing up to do their vaccine
programs,'' said Dr. William Barker, a professor of preventive
medicine and gerontology at the University of Rochester School of
Medicine. ``People don't generally anticipate you need protection
this early.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the outbreak at the hospital in Monroe County, Barker said:
``It really is a wake-up call that flu is in the community and you
should not delay getting a vaccine. Seeing an outbreak so early in
the season is a reminder that we could see more like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Influenza is a wily virus that changes frequently, a maneuver
that helps the virus avoid assaults by the body's immune system and
by drugs. It comes in several strains, usually named for the region
where they were first spotted, and three types, A, B and C.
Influenza A, the kind that hit the care center and the Long Island
baby, tends to be the most severe. Influenza B is usually milder
and influenza C has never caused an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   As long as changes from year to year are subtle, the same
vaccine will continue to be effective. Major changes, called
shifts, require new vaccines, but it can take months for a new
vaccine to get approval from the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for whatever reason, the first few people who get infected
are struck by a very different strain, that would be a signal that
we could be in for an outbreak,'' said Dr. Stephen Friedman,
director of the immunization program at the New York City
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   This year's vaccine is called a trivalent shot because it should
work against the three types of flu that are expected to circulate
this winter: the Sydney and Beijing strains, both influenza A, and
the Yamanashi strain, influenza B.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the common cold, which causes runny nose and sore throat,
the flu affects the entire body, causing coldlike symptoms, high
fever, muscle aches and headaches. Most people recover within seven
to 10 days, but those with chronic illness may suffer complications
that can be severe, if not fatal. Children with asthma are
susceptible to dangerous flare-ups, and pregnant women can also
suffer severe symptoms. Experts recommend the vaccine to pregnant
women during the second and third trimesters, not during the first
12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides flu shots, there are three drugs that are available by
prescription. Symmetrel (amantadine) and Flumadine (rimantadine)
are pills used against influenza A. Relenza (zanamivir) is an
inhaled medicine used to fight both influenza A and B. A fourth
drug, Tamiflu (oseltamivir), has not yet been approved by the drug
administration, but studies have indicated that it may work against
both A and B.
</P>
<P>
   While the vaccine can prevent the flu, the prescription drugs
are intended to ease symptoms after its onset. They are effective
only if taken within the first two days of the illness, health
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials said the prescription drugs would be most
effective in helping control outbreaks at group centers.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
