   LITTLE ROCK-MEMORIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For months, the black teen-age boy could enter Little Rock
Central High School only when escorted by federal troops,
sidestepping the angry mobs and ducking their spit. The white girl
driving her '49 Chevrolet to school could only stare incredulously
at the spectacle surrounding her classmate. ``It was all so stupid,
so asinine,'' she remembers thinking. ``I mean, what was the
problem? I had no objection to going to school with blacks.'' It
was autumn of 1957, and although they didn't realize it, the boy
and girl were part of a major flash point in American history that
would foreshadow the end of legal racial segregation. One of a
series of occasional stories about the Twentieth Century. By MILES
MOFFEIT. Story will move in ``a'' general news category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
