<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3411 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WAVE-OBSERVATORY-     10-11 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WAVE-OBSERVATORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OBSERVATORY IS DEDICATED TO WATCHING THE RIPPLING WAVES OF
SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Wash., Calif., Mass., N.M., Ill.)   (Science Times)  
(DW) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new calculation suggests that dense star clusters, which are
sprinkled throughout galaxies in Earth's cosmic neighborhood, act
as assembly lines for tightly orbiting pairs of black holes, and
then spit them out of the cluster, where they eventually fall
together and merge into one. Next year, if all goes well,
scientists will be able to take the first steps toward testing that
theory with a new, $350 million instrument, a gravity wave
observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, a cataclysmic merger of black holes should throw
off ripples in the fabric of space called gravitational waves or,
more simply, gravity waves. It was to detect those waves for the
first time that physicists designed the Laser Interferometer
Gravitational-Wave Observatory, or LIGO, which actually consists of
two separate stations, one in Louisiana and one in Washington
state. LIGO will be dedicated on Nov. 11 and begin a shakedown
period of initial operations in January of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, astrophysicists had assumed black hole pairs were so
rare it would be almost impossible to detect them. The scientists
preparing to work at LIGO assumed that their first capture of
gravity waves will come from less powerful events in the cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   The new calculations, by Simon F. Portegies Zwart of Boston
University and Stephen L.W. McMillan of Drexel University, suggest
that detectable mergers of black holes could be as much as a
thousand times more common than the events LIGO had set its sights
on. As is customary in astrophysics, the calculations have been
posted on a Web site managed by Los Alamos National Laboratory
(www.lanl.gov/abs/astro-ph/9910061) as they are being submitted to
the journal Astrophysical Journal Letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge difference,'' McMillan said. ``When you start
making these things in clusters,'' he said, referring to the black
hole pairs, ``the conditions are very favorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barry Barish, a physicist at the California Institute of
Technology who is the director of LIGO, said that if the
calculation was correct, its implications for the observatory's
first five to six years of operation were striking. The LIGO
detectors that will be in place during that time are much less
sensitive than those to come later, and the black hole pairs could
make the difference between seeing gravity waves or not seeing them
at all during that first phase.
</P>
<P>
   If the new calculations prove true, improvements might boost
LIGO's later detection rate from several events a year to as many
as one or two a day, said Stuart Shapiro, an astrophysicist at the
University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign who is involved in
calculating those rates. ``That's when you can do real science,''
Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Gravitational waves, ripples in the fabric of space itself, have
teased physicists for decades, because they have announced their
presence only indirectly. For example, when Joseph Taylor and
Russell Hulse of Princeton University observed a pair of neutron
stars caught in a tight orbit around each other, work for which
they won the Nobel Prize in 1993, they theorized that they should
produce gravity waves. The whirling neutron stars, superdense
cinders that sometimes remain when an ordinary massive star
collapses and explodes as a supernova, slightly stir the
four-dimensional fabric of space and time around them. According to
relativity theory, that stirring action should send out a weak
signal of gravitational waves.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor and Hulse could not measure those waves directly. All
they could do was show, with years of work, that the rotation of
the two-star or binary system was gradually speeding up as the
stars spiraled closer and closer together _ exactly what would be
expected because if energy were being carried away by the gravity
waves.
</P>
<P>
   Even LIGO, which is being built by Caltech and the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and will measure the minute stretching and
shrinking of space caused by such disturbances, will not be capable
of picking up such a faint spray of gravity waves. But when a pair
of neutron stars get so close that they crash together and merge,
the resulting burst of gravity waves should be detectable if the
smash-up occurs within one of the thousands of galaxies that are
within about 50 million light years of Earth.
</P>
<P>
   That process relies on ordinary stars occasionally being born in
pairs, exploding as supernovas and leaving behind neutron stars
with masses of about 1.5 times that of the sun. Black holes contain
the mass of ten or more suns and are even more exotic, having
collapsed behind a gravitational shroud called an ``event horizon''
from which nothing can escape _ not even light. The chances that
pairs of black holes could form as neutron star binaries do is
vanishingly small.
</P>
<P>
   So McMillan and Portegies Zwart looked at the possibility that
black hole pairs might, in effect, be manufactured inside the tight
knots of stars called globular clusters. In the clusters, which can
contain millions of stars, individual black holes fall to the
middle because of their great mass, the team realized.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, the black holes attract each other gravitationally
and pair off, forming binaries. The binaries carom off other black
holes and eventually pick up enough speed to escape from the
cluster. Out in the dark wasteland of space, the black holes spiral
inward just as neutron stars do, and finally merge in a spectacular
collision.
</P>
<P>
   Because the black holes are more massive than neutron stars,
said Barish of LIGO, more gravity waves are emitted and the events
are easier to see from far away. ``We see something that happened
deeper into the universe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The greater range adds up to a much bigger volume of space that
LIGO can monitor, said Barish.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the new work stress that an imperfect knowledge
of clusters and black holes means that their estimates are
uncertain by a factor of ten or so. ``We still have no
guarantees,'' said Dr. Kip Thorne, a LIGO collaborator and a
physicist at Caltech. Still, he thinks the new calculation suggests
`that we are likely to see a very large number of black hole
mergers.`
</P>
<P>
   Because gravity waves are a central prediction of relativity
theory, physicists would hail their detection as a major coup. The
possibility that LIGO will see gravity waves from black holes
brings an additional bonus, said Shapiro. Because of their terrific
gravitational fields, spacetime is warped around black holes more
strongly than anywhere else in the universe, according to
Einstein's equations of relativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gravitational wave is a direct messenger of that
spacetime,'' Shapiro said. ``The upshot will be the first
confirmation of Einstein's theory of relativity'' where the fabric
of spacetime is twisted almost beyond recognition, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
