<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEVADA-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     10-11 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVADA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IN NEVADA': FLITTING THROUGH A REALM OF DICE AND TUMBLEWEED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you think of Nevada, you probably think of Las Vegas:
Hunter Thompson's Day-Glo metropolis of fear and loathing, Bugsy
Siegel's vision of gangster glamour in the desert sands: that
giddy, glittering gulch of 24-hour slot machines, glitzy floor
shows and miles and miles of neon. As David Thomson points out in
his entertaining new book, however, there is another Nevada as
well, a rapidly vanishing Nevada of deserted desert vistas, rickety
ghost towns and empty roads, a remnant of the old frontier
seemingly forgotten by the modern world, a place so devoid of
habitation that ``you feel the human thing has hardly got a hold.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact the state that emerges from Thomson's book ``In Nevada''
is a place of blatant contradictions, a place where the beautiful
and the grotesque, the primitive and the futuristic dwell side by
side. The state has been a magnet for loners, libertarians and
anarchists, outlaws, gangsters and ``X-Files'' paranoiacs, but it
is also ``a playground of the federal government,'' which has used
its remote desert reaches as a testing ground for nuclear weapons
and secret reconnaissance aircraft. It is a region of extreme
weather and inhospitable conditions, but it is also home to the
Hoover Dam, one of the world's most daunting testaments to man's
mastery of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevada,'' Thomson writes, ``is on the edge, on the wire, off
to one side, in the empty quarter, or even in the rest of the
country's head as an idea, a possibility, an alternative. It is an
experiment, or a kind of theater. Yes, that's somewhere nearer to
the answer, for America has used Nevada as a testing ground, and
not just for weapons and their destructiveness but also for new
social ideas, and their explosiveness. What happens if you allow
divorce, prostitution, gambling? Can there be community and purpose
if you encourage things deep in human nature yet supposedly alien
to order and togetherness?''
</P>
<P>
   To address such questions, Thomson leads the reader on a
rambling, idiosyncratic tour of Nevada, taking us to Las Vegas, of
course, but also to small, abandoned mining towns and the barren
northern outposts of the state, where it is inadvisable to travel
without an extra stash of water and gas. He takes us along on a
government-conducted tour of the Nevada Test Site: a highly
circumscribed tour, it must be said, that nonetheless offers
glimpses of radioactive waste management facilities and the
infamous Sedan Crater, a 320-foot-deep, 1,282-foot-wide hole left
by the 1962 test of a 104,000-ton nuclear device.
</P>
<P>
   By cutting back and forth between descriptions of the test site
and a history of Las Vegas, Thomson tries to draw parallels between
the sort of gambling that goes on in casinos and the higher-stakes
gambling that has gone on with nuclear weapons. It's not a
particularly profound or well developed point, but the reader
doesn't really care, so engaging is Thomson as a tour guide. He
uses his novelistic powers of description, honed in three works of
fiction, to give the reader a palpable sense of what he sees. He
describes one hotel as having a ballroom ``of cut-rate 1980s
design, attempting to imitate the 1880s,'' a boxing ring as looking
``as poised and sinister as a Magritte painting.'' He also uses his
vast knowledge of movies, honed in half a dozen books about
Hollywood, to show how films like ``The Godfather,''
``Goodfellas,'' ``Casino'' and ``The Misfits'' have shaped and
played upon our preconceptions about Nevada and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   As his quirky, highly opinionated book ``A Biographical
Dictionary of Film'' attests, Thomson is also a master portraitist,
and in this volume he enlivens his narrative with sketches of such
disparate Nevadan figures as the explorer John Charles Fremont, one
of the first white men to see Lake Tahoe, and Steve Wynn, the
creator of the Mirage and Bellagio hotels, the flamboyant
entrepreneur who once quipped that he had tried to produce the sort
of marvel God might have made ``if He'd had the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra is described as a ``split personality standing
astride plenty and pain'': a poet having ``within him some ultimate
sad eloquence,'' a gifted artist but also an ``angry runt,'' who
seemed ashamed, in front of his pals, of the forlorn tenderness in
his voice. Howard Hughes, who bought the Desert Inn after he was
asked to check out of his rooms, is described as ``a Monopoly
player who regarded Las Vegas as a board game he had to cover''
with his own hotels. And Bugsy Siegel, the gangster who became one
of Las Vegas' founding fathers, is described as ``a truly Las Vegan
mix of good and bad luck,'' a man who ``saw the desert and the
great game of transforming it,'' and who ``like the first citizens
of the place,'' knew ``the virtue of moving a little farther out
into the desert and starting again.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the 50-odd years since Siegel's Flamingo Hotel
opened in the desert, Las Vegas has been transformed again into
something new. While Siegel helped turn a sleepy collection of
roadhouses into a film noir dream of swanky and slightly
disreputable glamour, today's Vegas moguls, like Wynn, are turning
the city into a family-friendly theme park filled with
world's-fair-like attractions, ``another kind of Disneyland,'' in
the opinion of many old-timers, ``too damn slick and organized for
its own good.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the state of Nevada has gone from being one of
the emptiest quarters of the West to being the most rapidly
expanding state in the union. Jet Skis and tourists (about 1
million a year) have invaded Lake Tahoe even as suburbs, malls and
highways have colonized the desert. In 1950, Thomson notes, the
entire state had a population of 160,000, about the number of hotel
beds estimated for Las Vegas by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IN NEVADA: THE LAND, THE PEOPLE, GOD AND CHANCE '
</P>
<P>
   By David Thomson
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 330 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
