<SLUG> BC-NEWTON-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOAST TO NEWTON AND A LONG-LIVED `PRINCIPIA' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new paperback of an old book may not seem like a big deal,
except when its author is arguably the greatest scientist of all
time and the book was first published 312 years ago. So the Dibner
Institute for the History of Science and Technology, on the campus
of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, is giving Isaac
Newton a book party to celebrate the publication of the first new
translation in 270 years of his landmark work, ``Philosophiae
Naturalis Principia Mathematica,'' first published, in Latin, in
1687.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Principia,'' as the work is commonly calwton
laid out the concepts of space, time, force and motion that defined
physical science for two centuries and established the law of
universal gravitation. The first publication was underwritten by
Edmond Halley, who used Newton's laws to discover the orbit of the
comet that bears his name. The book has seldom been out of print
since.
</P>
<P>
   The new translation, published by the University of California
Press, was done by the Harvard University science historian Dr. I.
Bernard Cohen and by Anne Whitman, with assistance from Julia
Budenz.
</P>
<P>
   The Dibner Institute is taking advantage of the occasion to call
attention to the splendors of its Burndy Library, which holds more
than 40,000 books, scientific instruments, photographs and other
artifacts, including a first edition of Euclid from 1482.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
