<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-FORESTS-NYTR &LR;      10-11 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FORESTS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 CLINTON PUSHES NEWS LIMITS ON NATIONAL FORESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Through proposed new regulations and directives,
the Clinton administration is trying to curtail development in
national forests, a move that has heartened many environmental
groups but infuriated commercial timber interests and conservative
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, the U.S. Forest Service unveiled a set of
proposed regulations on how to manage its lands with a new emphasis
on ecological health. The regulations, now open to review and
public comment, would essentially give environmental concerns
priority over economic goals.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman described the plan as a
``fundamental change in policy.'' Mike Anderson, a senior resource
analyst with The Wilderness Society, called the proposed
regulations a ``good step ... toward environmental protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics are calling them unfair and shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another step toward turning the national forests into
national parks,'' said Bob Slocum, executive vice president of the
North Carolina Forestry Association in Raleigh. He fears the
Clinton administration wants to eliminate logging and road
construction from the national forests.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is also considering a plan to place
millions of acres of national forests off-limits to commercial
development. That initiative has not yet been released, but rumors
of its existence began circulating in Washington in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that next week at some level the Clinton
administration will announce that it is pursuing better protection
for roadless areas of the national forests,'' said Nathaniel
Lawrence, a senior attorney with the Natural Resources Defense
Council, which closely follows forestry issues. ``I think it
remains to be seen whether it's more show than substance.'' Some 40
million acres of forest land are expected to be included in the new
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental advocates are pressing the administration to ban
road building and logging in vast swaths of the national forests,
which currently support a variety of activities, including logging,
recreation and wildlife preservation. They also want the
administration to include the Tongass National Forest in the
expected initiative. The Alaska forest is the nation's largest.
</P>
<P>
   The vast bulk of national forest land is out West. But some
eastern states, including North Carolina, have national forests
that could be affected by the Forest Service's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to hurt the economy and I believe the
environment in the long run,'' said Slocum of the North Carolina
Forestry Association.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, western North Carolina has already seen protests by
loggers upset over a halt in logging in the Nantahala National
Forest because of the presence of a rare bat. Slocum said he
expects that the new initiatives by the White House will only
further galvanize timber interests in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of federal activity has critics charging that the
Clinton administration is trying to revamp federal conservation
policies through executive fiat, without any congressional input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the impression that people in this administration may be
trying to rush things along, fearing that time is running out,''
said W. Henson Moore, president and CEO of the American Forest &AMP;
Paper Association.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, who chairs a key Senate subcommittee
on public lands management, said he supports the notion that
ecological sustainability ought to be a key goal of the U.S. Forest
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how do you achieve better health,'' Craig
said. ``That's where the argument lies.'' The administration is
hostile to the idea that logging can and should be part of an
overall plan for healthy forests, he said. Logging, he said, helps
eliminate diseased trees and cuts down on fire hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Craig also questioned the administration's recent approach,
saying it appeared unwilling to work with the Republican-controlled
Congress on forestry issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 11th hour of this administration, in the dark of night,
are they going to toss out some regulations?'' Craig asked.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, conservative lawmakers have turned to the annual
spending bills to achieve their goals. For example, the
appropriations bill for the Interior Department includes language
that would give the Forest Service and the Bureau of Land
Management more discretion in deciding whether to conduct wildlife
population surveys before deciding on road-building permits and
logging.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that move would open the door to more road
construction and logging and threaten wildlife. But supporters say
it would simply allow federal agencies to make decisions without
getting bogged down in endless studies.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior appropriations bill still faces votes in the House
and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is a Washington correspondent for the New York
Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
