<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV17-NY     10-11 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF MAKES A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Self'' used to be a dirty word. ``The wretch, concentered all
in  &UR; self &LR; ,'' wrote Sir Walter Scott in 1805, might get ``power and
pelf'' but would wind up ``unwept, unhonored and unsung.'' Not so,
said Walt Whitman a half- century later. ``I celebrate myself,'' he
sang in his ``Song of Myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the notion of  &UR; self &LR;  as something to be
celebrated has been taking a beating; Scott's sneer at  &UR; self &LR; 
reverberates through the language. It is bad to be  &UR; selfish &LR; , good
to be  &UR; selfless &LR; . People who are smug are  &UR; self-satisfied &LR; ,
narcissists are  &UR; self-absorbed &LR;  and often  &UR; self-indulgent &LR;  and
braggarts are  &UR; self-serving &LR; . You can find a few uses that reflect
well on  &UR; self &LR;  _ like  &UR; self-reliant &LR;  and  &UR; self-possessed &LR;  _ but
most praise is lavished on the rejection of self, as in
 &UR; self-sacrifice &LR; . And  &UR; selflessness &LR;  is next to godliness.
</P>
<P>
   Then  &UR; self &LR;  made a comeback. Showing some self-confidence, it
became the name of a Conde Nast magazine aimed at women interested
in their own bodies and minds. Its 20th-anniversary issue, out this
month, faces some of the bad  &UR; self &LR; s (``self-love, self-pity,
self-delusion, self-aggrandizement'') but dwells more on the good
 &UR; self &LR; s (``self-help, self-governing, self-made, self-respect,
self-denial'' and, for ovens, ``self-cleaning'').
</P>
<P>
   Though a bit self-conscious about a decline in their
publication's circulation, Self's editors gutsily reprint a Mike
Twohy cartoon showing a timid fellow writing in his diary, ``Dear
Diary, Sorry to bother you again,'' captioned ``Low Self-Esteem.''
In that regard, what to do about  &UR; myself &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   This reflexive pronoun requires reflection.  &UR; Reflexive &LR;  means
``turned back on itself,'' and a reflexive pronoun turns the action
back on its subject: ``I ((pronoun as subject)) perjured ((verb))
 &UR; myself &LR;  ((reflexive pronoun pointing back to the subject `I')).''
</P>
<P>
   The correct use of  &UR; self &LR;  or  &UR; selves &LR;  attached to  &UR; my &LR; ,  &UR; your &LR; ,
 &UR; him &LR; ,  &UR; her &LR; ,  &UR; them &LR;  or  &UR; our &LR;  is to turn the action back on the
other pronoun in the sentence. The subject and the object are the
same thing. But too many writers are using  &UR; myself &LR;  in an orgy of
false modesty, fearing to make the squeakily assertive sound of the
first-person singular accusative and dative  &UR; me &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter did it in his farewell address (a speech
he concluded with the word  &UR; farewell &LR; , which is the proper way to
end a farewell address). He said, ``I will work hard to make sure
that the transition from  &UR; myself &LR;  to the next president is a good
one.''
</P>
<P>
   When I popped him on this, E. Ward Gilman, editor of
Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage _ ``Dr. Roundheels''
himself _ cited the use of  &UR; myself &LR;  instead of  &UR; me &LR;  by
grammar-conscious authors from Dr. Samuel Johnson to E.B. White. He
even found the abomination in a sentence _ ``No longer were Price,
Buchanan and  &UR; myself &LR;  part of the innermost circle'' _ written in
1974 by me, and in no way ``written by myself.'' Even Homer
noodled.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Myself &LR;  is being used incorrectly in place of the first-person
singular nominative. (I'm too shy to write  &UR; I &LR; .) The new Uriah
Heeps, wallowing in phony humility, eschew the use of  &UR; I &LR; .
Sometimes, blushing shyly and digging a toe in the dirt, they
substitute  &UR; yours truly &LR; . More often, they replace the
``perpendicular pronoun'' with the horizontal pronoun,  &UR; myself &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, I was astounded when my predecessor as a
conservative New York Times columnist, Arthur Krock, titled his
memoirs about growing up in the 1890s ``Myself When Young.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until I plunged into the philological scholarship required
for this article did I discover that he bottomed the title on
Edward FitzGerald's translation of a quatrain in the ``Rubaiyat of
Omar Khayyam'' ( &UR; ruba`i &LR;  means ``quatrain'';  &UR; rubaiyat &LR;  is the
plural): ``Myself when young did eagerly frequent/Doctor and Saint,
and heard great argument/ About it and about: but evermore/Came out
by the same Door wherein I went.'' Poets can get away with
anything,  &UR; myself &LR;  included.
</P>
<P>
   If you hate to begin a sentence with  &UR; myself &LR; , as in `` &UR; Myself &LR; ,
I could not care less,'' try  &UR; as for me &LR;  or  &UR; for my part &LR; . A
reflexive pronoun is fine, however, as an emphasizer. I used one a
moment ago, as ``Dr. Roundheels  &UR; himself &LR; ,'' above.
</P>
<P>
   Americans use  &UR; myself &LR;  to underscore a pronoun as often as the
British use the superfluous  &UR; indeed &LR; , which means ``you bet; hear,
hear,'' and the emphatically reflexive ``If I do say so  &UR; myself &LR; .''
Let us not become the  &UR; Myself &LR;  Generation. If you want to show
submission, sew a large sign on the seat of your pants that reads,
``Kick me.'' Avoid ``Kick  &UR; myself &LR; .'' The latter lacks
 &UR; self-esteem &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Gypsy Run-Through
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall the `Music Man'  &UR; gypsy run-through &LR; ,'' writes Stuart
Ostrow in his new book, ``A Producer's Broadway Journey.'' He
defines the phrase as ``a private performance of a new musical
attended by the cast members' family and friends on the last day of
rehearsals before the out-of-town tryout.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Run-through &LR; , or ``hasty rehearsal,'' was coined by P.G.
Wodehouse in his 1923 ``Inimitable Jeeves.'' And  &UR; gypsy &LR;  was
defined in the 1973 ``Language of Show Biz'' as ``a chorus member
in a musical,'' specifically a dancer. But  &UR; gypsy run-through &LR;  was
a new one to me, so I called Ostrow at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the origin of  &UR; gypsy &LR;  _ ``Egyptian'' _ but was gypsy
dancing the metaphoric source of calling members of a chorus line
 &UR; gypsies &LR; ? No. ``Bob Fosse once told me,'' Ostrow said, ``that
dancers are the best soldiers. You tell them to jump into the
orchestra pit and they ask only, `How many counts?' We call dancers
 &UR; gypsies &LR;  because  &UR; gypsies &LR;  are known for always moving from place
to place _ and a dancer has to be constantly on the move.''
</P>
<P>
   Real  &UR; Gypsies &LR;  rightly resent the use of the verb  &UR; to gyp &LR;  as an
ethnic slur, but mobility is no derogation, and I (myself!) wish I
had a dancing relative to invite me to a  &UR; gypsy run-through &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
