<HEADER>
A3432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BARCELONA-OPERA-HOUSE     10-11 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARCELONA-OPERA-HOUSE-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVOS FOR THE RETURN OF A DIVA: BARCELONA'S OPERA HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARCELONA, Spain _ If the destruction of the Gran Teatre del
Liceu by fire on the morning of Jan. 31, 1994, was a nightmare, the
reopening of the legendary opera house at performance
Thursday evening was like awakening to find that nothing had
changed. As the curtain went up on a new production of Puccini's
``Turandot,'' the red-and-gold auditorium looked much as it did
when the Liceu was inaugurated in 1847 and when it was rebuilt
after the last fire in 1861.
</P>
<P>
   It could not have been otherwise. Such has been the Liceu's
importance in Barcelona's cultural and social life since the
mid-19th century that the idea of replacing the burned-out opera
house with a modern building was never mooted. The only way of
healing the wounds caused by the fire, it seems, was to pretend
that it had not happened. The choice of ``Turandot'' was not
accidental: It was the next opera on the program when the Liceu
(pronounced lee-say-OOH) went up in flames.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all the emotions stirred by the reopening on
Thursday, attended by King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia along with
much of Spain's political and economic elite, the Catalans are ever
practical. Thus, while discreet modern paintings on ceiling panels
are about the only changes in the auditorium, the rest of the opera
house has been transformed, with the addition of new rehearsal
rooms, a new foyer below the orchestra seats and, most
significantly, a state-of-the-art back stage, with extra space to
store production sets.
</P>
<P>
   Complex negotiations were needed for this to happen, though. The
opera house's entrance stands on the elegant tree-lined Paseo de
las Ramblas, but the rest of the Liceu was enclosed by old
apartment and office buildings that had to be acquired from their
private owners before the expansion could go ahead. The area
occupied by the Liceu has now doubled in size.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, while the opera house had been managed by the local
government since 1981, it was still owned by 400 heirs of the
wealthy families that built, and rebuilt, it in the 19th century.
Now, with only $14 million available from insurance, they could not
afford to rebuild it again. In exchange for priority to buy a
limited number of tickets in perpetuity, they therefore ceded the
property to a foundation run by the Spanish, Catalan and Barcelona
governments, which assumed most of the $120 million cost of
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for a new Liceu to rise from the ashes in less than six
years is all the more remarkable given the recent troubles of some
other European opera houses. La Fenice in Venice, destroyed by fire
in January 1996, has seen its reconstruction delayed until at least
2002 by judicial investigations and political squabbling. London's
Covent Garden, which reopens in December after a $367 million
expansion, has had its image muddied by charges of mismanagement
and elitism. Madrid's Teatro Real, which reopened in 1997 for the
first time since 1925, has yet to win a place among Europe's top
opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Liceu is in many ways starting afresh. It has a
loyal audience that remembers when Maria Callas sang here and takes
pride in the opera house's role as cradle for such great Spanish
singers as Victoria de los Angeles, Montserrat Caballe and Jose
Carreras. But even before the fire, the Liceu was living more off
its name than the quality of the performers and productions on its
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Liceu's general director, Josep Caminal i Badia, has put
together a new team with a mandate to create a program on a par
with the new building. Joan Matabosch, the house's artistic
director, already has experience in organizing recitals, operas in
concert and occasional full-scale operas in other city theaters
over the last three years. Bertrand de Billy, the 34-year-old
French conductor who was appointed music director last year, has in
turn been holding auditions in order to build the Liceu's orchestra
and chorus back to full strength.
</P>
<P>
   For their first season, apart from ``Turandot,'' they have
scheduled Janacek's ``Makropulos Case,'' Donizetti's ``Lucia di
Lammermoor,'' Verdi's ``Don Carlo,'' Wagner's ``Lohengrin,''
Mozart's ``Nozze di Figaro,'' Ermanno Wolf-Ferrari's ``Sly'' and
Bellini's ``Beatrice di Tenda'' in concert version. Along with a
full program of concerts and recitals, they will also present the
Frankfurt Ballet, the Compania Nacional de Danza and the Bolshoi
Ballet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The house has already adopted the common European practice of
preferring co-productions to assuming the full cost of new
productions. ``Turandot,'' for instance, will travel to the Theatre
du Capitole in Toulouse, France, while ``Don Carlo'' is being
co-produced with the Teatro Bellini in Catania, Italy, and Robert
Carsen's production of ``Le Nozze di Figaro'' will be coming from
the Grand Theatre de Bordeaux in France.
</P>
<P>
   The new Liceu hopes to present as many as 12 operas per season
within a few years, but it is starting cautiously. ``This season is
considered a dress rehearsal every night until next July,'' said
Adela Rocha, the Liceu's spokeswoman, noting that it would take
time to break in the new building, with all its high-tech
equipment. Indeed, teething problems were all too evident at the
final dress rehearsal for ``Turandot'' when de Billy had to stop
the orchestra after a few bars because the curtain did not rise.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's gala, however, everything went off smoothly. The
lavish sets and costumes in Nuria Espert's production of Puccini's
``Chinese opera'' seemed appropriate for the occasion, while the
warm applause for the orchestra and chorus suggested that de Billy
had begun well at the Liceu. Among the singers, Giovanna Casolla as
Turandot and Jan Blinkhof as Calaf performed solidly, although only
the Spanish soprano Maria Bayo as Liu stirred excitement.
</P>
<P>
   No one was in a mood to be critical. The real stars of the
evening were the new building and those who had made it possible.
In time, expectations of excellence onstage will no doubt rise. But
for the moment, it was not arias but the rebirth of a cherished
theater that had many in the audience damp-eyed. For Barcelona's
opera lovers, the nightmare was over: the Liceu was back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
