<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JOHN-RIDLEY-ART-2TAKE     10-11 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-RIDLEY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WRITER WHO TAKES ZIGZAGGING PATHS ALWAYS BUSY ON FILMS, TV
SCRIPTS AND NOVELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Nev. Japan)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It was, in some ways, a typical day for John Ridley.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours the other morning at his home in Hollywood Hills,
Ridley worked on a nearly completed novel for Knopf. Then he drove
to Santa Monica to meet with the producer Jerry Bruckheimer on his
film script for a ``Beverly Hills Cop IV'' for Eddie Murphy. By
afternoon, Ridley was driving to Warner Brothers to look at scenes
from ``Third Watch,'' the NBC series about paramedics, firefighters
and the police. He is a top writer on the show.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, he was at home to work on a new film script,
a psychological thriller, for the director Michael Bay
(``Armageddon''). That night, he picked up a yellow note pad to
revise a ``Third Watch'' script in time for a 10 a.m. meeting with
the producers the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of how my day spills out,'' Ridley said. ``I love
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would dispute that.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one of the most prolific writers in Hollywood, Ridley,
34, is credited with the story for the new George Clooney film
``Three Kings,'' a dark comedy about a group of soldiers in search
of a fortune during the Persian Gulf war. Ridley said he had
created the idea and written the initial screenplay, which was
later revamped and credited to the director, David O. Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so uninvolved in that movie,'' he said glumly. ``I read in
the trade papers that I was off the movie. No one called me. You
make good money, but let's just say they don't treat writers well
in Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley is unusual in numerous ways. He studied East Asian
languages and culture at New York University, worked as a stand-up
comedian at clubs in New York and Los Angeles, is married to a
professional gambler and spends most weekends in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   He is also one of the few black television and film writers
whose work is often unrelated to racial issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a unique voice,'' said Ed Bernero, co-creator of
``Third Watch.'' ``The writing is very lyrical, beautiful to read,
unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernero said that when he had initially discussed the show with
the producer and co-creator, John Wells (``E.R.''), Ridley's name
was almost the first on the list of writers to sign on. ``His voice
was the kind of voice we wanted on this show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ridley began writing for television in 1993 for sitcoms
with largely black casts, like ``Martin'' and ``Fresh Prince of Bel
Air,'' as well as ``The John Laroquette Show,'' he later moved to
series like ``Trinity,'' about an Irish family in New York, and
then ``Third Watch.''
</P>
<P>
   His first novel, ``Stray Dogs,'' a tale about a drifter on his
way to Las Vegas to pay off a Mafia loan shark, was later turned
into an Oliver Stone film, ``U Turn,'' starring Sean Penn, Nick
Nolte and Jennifer Lopez. His third novel, ``Everybody Smokes in
Hell'' (Knopf), deals with what his favorite writer, Raymond
Chandler, once called the ``degraded community'' of Hollywood,
which includes small-time talent agents, drug dealers, strippers
and some not-so-beautiful women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things I do are not what you would expect out of a
young black guy _ and that was part of the problem,'' said Ridley,
a tall, bearded and figure in jeans and a sweatshirt, in the
commissary at the Warner Brothers studio in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of the predominantly black television shows he
worked on, like ``Hangin' With Cooper'' and ``Martin,'' left him
somewhat indifferent because of their lack of sophistication.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's another level of show that I would have loved to have
been on,'' Ridley said. ``Like `Seinfeld' or `Frasier' or something
like that. I would have loved to have a show like that with a mixed
cast or an all-black cast. Unfortunately, those shows don't
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley grew up in the suburbs of Milwaukee; his father, John, is
a doctor, and his mother, Terri, a teacher. After being voted the
funniest student in high school, he moved to New York in his late
teens to perform in clubs as a comedian but attended NYU (to please
his parents) and took up Asian studies. After graduation, he lived
and traveled in Japan for a year before returning to New York to
work in clubs like Catch a Rising Star. (He appeared on ``The
Tonight Show'' with Johnny Carson.)
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ridley moved to Los Angeles in 1990 _ ``I needed a
change of pace'' _ he had completed a novel called ``Straight
Odds,'' which helped him get a talent agent. This led to television
work and his first published novel, ``Stray Dogs'' (Ballantine),
which earned strong reviews.
</P>
<P>
   His second novel, ``Love Is a Racket'' (Knopf), a gritty drama
about a failed screenwriter turned con man, was also well received
by critics. His writing was called ``smart and edgy and even
moving'' in The New York Times Book Review, and The San Francisco
Examiner has said his fiction ``brings to mind Raymond Chandler and
Elmore Leonard.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Sonny Mehta, president and editor in chief of Knopf,
who is also Ridley's editor, compared him to both Chandler and
Dashiell Hammett.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's voice is both hard and soft, gritty and urbane,'' Mehta
said. ``It's also a very contemporary voice. You see a lot of
Chandler because of the subjects he writes about, and a lot of
Hammett because of the stripped-down nature of the writing, and the
morality of it.'' He added, ``John and his subjects seem to have a
love-hate relationship with Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   What also fascinated Mehta about Ridley, he said, was that his
novels are populated by blacks as well as whites. ``You can read
Ridley for a while before you realize that many of the people he's
writing about are black,'' Mehta said. ``He doesn't wear it on his
sleeve. And what you realize is that he's writing about a black and
white underclass. It makes it kind of original.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley has completed the draft of another novel for Knopf,
tentatively called ``A Conversation With the Mann,'' about a black
man's life from the 1930s to the '90s, set mostly in New York, Los
Angeles and Las Vegas. ( Ridley's favorite writers, besides
Chandler, are Jim Thompson, Chester Himes, Walter Mosley and Norman
Mailer.)
</P>
<P>
   His ability to switch back and forth between projects is
enviable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually carry a note pad with me,'' he said. ``If I'm
waiting for a meeting to start, I'll write. If I'm on an airplane,
I'll write. Whenever there's a second to write the book, I'll do
it. I love it. I usually write in longhand first and then put it in
the computer. It kind of gives you two passes at the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have a problem switching back and forth. I know it
sounds kind of weird, but I write as much as I can, whether it's
the book or a movie, and then I move on to something else. For a
while I had two computers _ I was writing things simultaneously. I
love to write. I could write all day and all night. Ask my wife _
she'll tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley's wife is Gayle Yoshida, who was a script superviser on
``Martin.'' ``She doesn't like to be called a professional gambler
because she thinks it has a bad connotation, but she makes a living
gambling _ and I love it,'' said Ridley, who acknowledged that,
unlike his wife, he loses more than he wins. The couple are now
looking to buy a house in Las Vegas, a city that fascinates him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I could take you places in Las Vegas that would just
break your heart,'' Ridley said. ``Whatever your addiction is,
there's a place for it. It's so sad to see those 24-hour pawn
shops, people pawning their stereo equipment because they're either
desperate or have stolen it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not all his work has been successful. Ridley's effort to direct
his screenplay ``Cold Heart,'' about a pair of jewelry thieves,
starring David Caruso and Kelly Lynch, flopped, partly because,
Ridley said, the film's financiers kept getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the idea came up for ``Three Kings,'' Ridley gave a
response that was typical of the way he writes. He said he had long
had this idea for a contemporary adventure similar to the classic
John Huston film ``The Treasure of the Sierra Madre''(1948), about
gold and greed. Ridley decided to set his story during the Persian
Gulf war. In the movie, soldiers secretly hunt for a treasure in
occupied Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote it on the fly,'' Ridley said. ``I took my wife to
Vegas. We were there for a week. We'd gamble for a while, and then
I'd say: `Honey, I'm going up to the room for an hour. I'll be
back.' And that's how I wrote that story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
