A3439 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;     10-11 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT ON CRIME? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Anyone remember Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft's
short-lived campaign last year for the 2000 Republican presidential
nomination?
</P>
<P>
   Really inspiring, eh? The senator fashioned himself the voice of
the far right _ tough on pregnant teenagers, tough on church
backsliders, tough on immorality and dishonesty, tough on crime.
But above all, big on defending the Bible Belt's white male
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   That message didn't sell beyond the narrow confines of the
religious right. So in January Ashcroft retreated to seek
re-election to the Senate instead. That's proving to be heavy
lifting, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now his focus is on painting his popular rival, Democratic Gov.
Mel Carnahan, as the personification of those moral evils he railed
against as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The first victim of this strategy is not Carnahan but an
appointee of his _ Missouri Supreme Court Justice Ronnie White,
whose nomination to the federal bench was defeated by Senate
Republicans last week strictly as a favor to Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial nominations, as with everything else in the nation's
capital, are buffeted by the political winds. But dumping on
Justice White was a particularly crass example of a bunch of
partisans doing a bad thing to help a buddy hang onto his Senate
seat.
</P>
<P>
   And, aha, there's a catch. This may turn out to have hurt
Ashcroft more than it helps him. It should.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court nomination of White, the first African
American to serve on the Missouri high bench, had been pending for
two years. Ashcroft's state colleague in the Senate, Christopher
Bond, initially urged the Judiciary Committee to approve White, and
three Republicans on the panel voted for him. But when the vote
came to the Senate floor, all three as well as Bond reversed
themselves and joined the GOP stampede against him.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 12 years that the full Senate has
rejected a judicial nominee. Normally, controversial nominations
are stopped procedurally before reaching a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft had made a special last-minute plea to his Republican
colleagues to give him this one. He called White ``pro-criminal''
and an ``activist'' jurist, GOP code for a liberal who hands down
decisions they don't like. He accused White of insufficiently
applying the death penalty to bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   White's judicial record does not support such charges, but the
Republican senators didn't care. What Ashcroft wanted, Ashcroft
got. Afterward, several Republican colleagues said they didn't know
anything about White, including the fact that he is black.
Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch, campaigning for president on the
grounds he has more wisdom in picking judges than anyone, observed
lamely, ``I don't think I had a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   White's judicial performance was not really the point anyway.
Capitol Hill politics are so unstable that President Clinton has
begun predicting the Republicans will lose the Senate next year as
well as the House _ rather a stretch, but no longer inconceivable.
Ashcroft's seat suddenly matters a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is not an originial thinker, as his doomed presidential
campaign demonstrated. This is a politician behind the curve. His
timing was off regarding the clout of the far right. Now he's
recycling Richard Nixon's old anti-black, law-and-order mantra,
pretty much left in the dust of overt racist politics years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty is a minor item on the national agenda. It is
useful mostly as a symbol of those bad old days when liberals
imposed their moral qualms about the state's right to take any
human life on the judicial system. No more. The liberals lost that
one, and capital punishment is now commonly accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft claimed that his sole objection was that White is
overly anxious to reverse death sentences against convicted felons.
We are supposed to believe the judge's color had nothing to do with
the senator's hostility.
</P>
<P>
   But White's record shows he upheld the imposition of the death
penalty in 41 of the 59 cases that came before him. In 10 of the 18
cases in which White voted against the death penalty, he was joined
by a unanimous court. Three justices appointed by Ashcroft himself
when he was governor concurred on votes to reverse death penalties
more often than White.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft cites two cases, one involving an accused cop-killer
and another a drug courier, in which White reversed the death
penalty for legal improprieties. That's what judges are supposed to
do.
</P>
<P>
   And so, inevitably, we come back to race. Could Ashcroft have
persuaded his Republican colleagues to make partisan fools of
themselves by doing him such a transparent favor with no
intellectual underpinnings if the nominee being rejected were a
white male? The answer, sadly, is probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is now positioned as the champion of white innocents
against a black judge who would let murderers go free. But once
again he seems behind the political curve.
</P>
<P>
   Crime, although always a concern, is down almost everywhere.
Professional blacks have been moving steadily into prominent public
roles since Ashcroft entered government service some two decades
ago, and they are handling those roles well. Stirring up racial
tension is a nasty game that is now more subtle and uncertain than
in the past days of open confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leaders are furious at Ashcroft and are vowing to
campaign against him. Revenge is in the air. In an era of rapidly
expanding Hispanic voting rolls and black concerns about a
Republican GOP White House, minorities are likely to be energized
next year in Missouri and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   And those in Missouri won't be voting for Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
