<SLUG> BC-MAFIA-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRONTLINE': HOCKEY SUSPICIONS AND TIME FANTASIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York and Connecticut; see local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beware! Two provocative-sounding programs from those two premier
PBS documentary series, ``Frontline'' and ``Nova,'' fall flat
Tuesday night. ``Nova,'' says a press release, reveals
``fascinating secrets of time travel,'' but there are no
revelations except that an hourlong program can stall in a wormhole
of theorizing. As for the ``Frontline'' offering, about the
supposed corruption of Russian star players in the National Hockey
League, it doesn't score at all.
</P>
<P>
   To begin on the ice, ``Mafia Power Play'' is an exercise in
suspicion by association. We are told, for example, that one
Vyacheslav Ivankov, a convicted extortionist, is in business with
Slava Fetisov, who helped win the Stanley Cup for the Detroit Red
Wings in 1997 and now coaches for the New Jersey Devils. But has
Fetisov done anything illegal? Inferences are rampant, but evidence
is lacking.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the relationship between Anzor Kikalishvili,
billed as a boss of an organized crime organization, and Pavel
Bure, a star of the Florida Panthers? Has Bure been a victim of
extortion of some sort? He says, ``Nyet,'' and no facts are offered
to back up contrary allegations.
</P>
<P>
   And is it a crime for Valery Kamensky of the New York Rangers to
consort with a dubious character named Vyacheslav Sliva? Who knows?
Not the program's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia,'' the narrator says, ``where there's money, there's
mafia.'' That's easy to believe, and perhaps the producers were
counting on the bad reputation of Russian operators to get away
with an hour filled with speculation. The program can't even decide
whether the players are victims of the Russian mafia or
accomplices. Somebody seems to have lost sight of the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will traveling back through time ever be more than just
fantasy?'' asks the ``Nova'' narrator, introducing what began as a
lighthearted though not unserious conversation between Carl Sagan
and his friend Kip Thorne, an expert on black holes. They
confronted a theoretical paradox: in Thorne's words, ``the danger
that I may go into the time machine, go back in time, kill my
grandfather before my mother is conceived so that she can't
conceive me.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to figure out whether time travel can ever be
something more than a popular staple of science fiction, Thorne
invented the notion of a ``wormhole,'' a sort of tunnel in space
through which humans might travel back in time. ``If I now go into
this wormhole mouth today,'' Thorne fantasizes, ``I will come out
of that mouth yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an engaging notion, but his ruminations can be hard to
grasp as the program drifts around in an atmosphere of quantum
foam, negative energy, photons and other concepts troublesome for
the nonphysicist. Finally, Thorne, who was distressed by the
publicity given to his imaginings by overeager reporters, resolved,
``I will talk about anything else but not time travel.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of what begins as an enterprising journey, you may
understand why.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``FRONTLINE: Mafia Power Play''
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. Tuesday on PBS (Channel 13 in New York, Channel 49 in
Connecticut)
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Neil Docherty; Linden MacIntyre,
correspondent; Leslie Steven Onody, editor; Michael Sullivan,
executive producer; David Fanning, senior executive producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
