<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Oct. 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous jet stream will push numerous weak fronts across the
northern part of the country over the next several days. These
fast-moving systems will bring doses of clouds and showers,
followed by brief periods of cooler weather. Sunny skies and cool
air will cover the Middle Atlantic States Tuesday, with afternoon
highs near seasonal levels. In New England, the day will begin
sunny, however, high clouds will spread over the area by the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, the central Plains will have readings near
summertime values as temperatures rise into the 80s ahead of a weak
cool front. On the heels of this front, much of the northern
Rockies and northern Missouri Valley will turn noticeably cooler as
another surge of chilly air pushes southeastward.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeastern states, a stationary front will provide a
focus for showers and thunderstorms to develop from southern
Alabama to South Carolina. Some of the showers will bring heavy
rain, as they will be slow moving. Showers will also develop along
the western Gulf Coast with clouds from the showers spilling into
the southeastern sections of Texas and southern Louisiana. A few
thunderstorms are also possible in southern Florida, although much
of the peninsula will remain dry.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southwest, abundant sunshine will allow temperatures to
rise to well above normal levels. The coast of California will also
remain warm as offshore flow persists. Meanwhile, isolated showers
and a shield of clouds will reach the coasts of Washington and
northwest Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Fog Season
</P>
<P>
   The season for fog has arrived. Early on Monday, patches of
dense fog filled many valleys from Missouri to the interior
Southeast. Fog forms when when air near the ground is cooled enough
for the water vapor in the atmosphere to condense into visible
water droplets. In early autumn, the moist air of the summer season
lingers near the surface of the earth. Meanwhile, the lengthening
hours of darkness allow more of the day's heat to dissipate. The
cooled air at the ground is dense and therefore drains into low
spots in the terrain, making valleys prone to fog while nearby
hilltops often remain in the clear. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
