<SLUG> BC-NEW-CDS-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
 
NEW CDS FROM THE GOOD (bECK), THE BAD (A SPICE GIRL) AND PRINCE 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Music lovers, prepare to be crushed by a landslide of new CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the biggest names in pop music have released or are
on the eve of releasing new records _ just in time, obviously, for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: Mariah Carey, Sting, Rage Against the Machine, LeAnn
Rimes, Stone Temple Pilots, Fiona Apple, David Bowie, Beck and The
Artist Whom We Can Now Call Prince Again.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an A-to-B look at the 15 artists who are vying for ink on
your Christmas wish list, how each artist has done thus far and
what you can expect from his or her new effort: ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Fiona Apple
</P>
<P>
   The disc: I didn't want to type this all out, but my editor made
me. The full title _ most people are referring to it by using only
the first four words _ is When the Pawn Hits the Conflicts He
Thinks Like a King What He Knows Throws the Blows When He Goes to
the Fight and He'll Win the Whole Thing 'Fore He Enters the Ring
There's No Body to Batter When Your Mind Is Your Might So When You
Go Solo, You Hold Your Own Hand and Remember That Depth Is the
Greatest of Heights and If You Know Where You Stand, Then You Know
Where to Land and If You Fall It Won't Matter, 'Cuz You'll Know
That You're Right... It's a 90-word title. I hate my editor.
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Nov. 9
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Has yet to stumble.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: Young, beautiful and opinionated, Fiona Apple stirred up
quite a bit of commotion with her read-my-diary debut, Tidal, and
the edgy, somewhat erotic video for her hooky single, Criminal,
which earned her a Grammy for Best Rock Performance. She's talented
but annoying.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Theinded title of her second disc _ a
poem Apple wrote _ should give you a good idea: It's gonna be
pompous. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: The Artist
</P>
<P>
   The disc: Rave Un2 the Joy Fantastic
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Nov. 2
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Spotty but respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: One of the most prolific voices in pop music, Prince
(we're allowed to call him that again) has released more than 20
records, some of them pure genius, some of them pure nonsense.
Despite not being able to duplicate the success he had in the '80s
any time this decade, he has remained incredibly productive,
releasing the two-CD Mirror Ball set last year while working on his
newest disc, his first one for a major label since settling legal
wrangles with his former record company, Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Fantastic, his debut for Arista, features The
Artist's New Power Generation band, so expect more of the same
funk-laced pop he's been putting out lately. Guest appearances
abound, from Sheryl Crow, Chuck D, Ani DiFranco, Gwen Stefani and
Maceo Parker. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Beck
</P>
<P>
   The disc: Midnite Vultures
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Nov. 16
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Not a smudge on it.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: In 1994, Los Angeles transplant Beck Hansen might have
been regarded as a one-cool-hit wonder. But Loser was Page 1 of a
new chapter in pop music's history book. Tongue always millimeters
away from poking through his cheek, Beck has since taken his
slacker poetry and unique fusion of hip-hop and, well, just about
every other genre of music to countless heights, influencing not
only new bands, but also new musical trends. He very well could be
the Dylan of today.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Midnite Vultures promises to be a far more
dance-oriented disc, but with Beck's trademark lacings of country,
folk, punk and, this time around, swing. Of course it'll be
brilliant. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: David Bowie
</P>
<P>
   The disc: `hours ...'
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Out now
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Up and down.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: During the past several decades, Bowie has reinvented
himself not only to change with the times but sometimes to change
the times. If his past few efforts are any example, his days of
furthering pop music's evolution are behind him, but his love for
pushing pop music's envelope _ sometimes way over the edge _ still
result in, at the very least, intriguing records. Which is more
than you can say for the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: A better title for this would have been After
Hours, this is such a low-key affair. Very little of this is rock
'n' rollish. It's more meditative, like Bowie himself is now. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Bush
</P>
<P>
   The disc: The Science of Things
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Oct. 26
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Unfortunately, pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: The first two CDs from this UK Nirvana clone sold
millions, catapulting them to the forefront of Generation MTV _ the
lost generation?
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: At some point, all rock bands dabble in
electronics, except for, like, AC/DC. It's Bush's turn. Science is
the first Bush disc to feature drum loops, samples and other
digital nuances. But this is no surprise: Singer Gavin Rossdale's
girlfriend, No Doubt babe Gwen Stefani, sings backup on a track,
Space Travel. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Mariah Carey
</P>
<P>
   The disc: Rainbow
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Nov. 2
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: R&AMP;B singer Mariah Carey sells more records in a year
than most bands do in their entire careers. Unfair, yes. A
surprise, no. For years now, Carey has been making unemotional,
disposable pop songs, the kind of music that has plagued pop radio
for years but is still powerful enough to make people wanna buy it.
A true phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Harmless, inoffensive pop songs united by drum
machines; mechanical, angelic choruses; and thumping R&AMP;B beats. See
ya in line to get one.
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Who: Counting Crows
</P>
<P>
   The disc: This Desert Life
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Nov. 2
</P>
<P>
   Track record: So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: Five words have been a plague and payoff for San
Francisco's Counting Crows: ``Gonna be a big star,'' which singer
Adam Duritz mumbles at the end of the band's first hit, 1993's Mr.
Jones. Dreams may come true, but so do nightmares: As they were
selling millions of records, pop music critics were shooting down
the Crows, not for their rustic rock but for Duritz's often
over-the-top comments. Duritz has since mellowed, probably because
he realizes success can leave him as easily as it found him.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Judging from the tag-team production of David
Lowery (front guy of pleasantly loud Cracker) and Dennis Herring
(producer of Lowery's old band, oddball rockers Camper Van
Beethoven), expect the Crows' third studio album to be both
predictable and experimental. It probably won't be their best
record, but it may be their most diverse. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Eurythmics
</P>
<P>
   The disc: Peace
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Oct. 19
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Erratic.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: A walking VH1 ``Where Are They Now?'' special, the
Eurythmics _ singer Annie Lennox and partner/guitarist Dave Stewart
_ vanished as soon as they appeared, torn apart by the success
brought on by a string of '80s singles like Sweet Dreams and Here
Comes the Rain (Again). Peace is their first album in nearly a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Your guess is as good as ours. The band's
publicists clam up and hang up when the subject is brought up. Our
guess: It's kind of like when movie companies won't screen their
flicks for critics _ it's a good sign that it's junk. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Foo Fighters
</P>
<P>
   The disc: There Is Nothing Left to Lose
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Nov. 2
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: Led by ex-Nirvana drummer Dave Grohl, the Foo Fighters
have released two terrific discs of punk-pop gems. Turmoil inside
and outside the band (several players have come and gone; Grohl had
a nasty split with Veruca Salt gal Louise Post) has given Grohl
plenty of Nirvana-type angst to elegantly write and ferociously
scream about.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Like Kurt Cobain, Grohl is torn between two
loves: pop and punk. So don't let Learn to Fly, a midtempo rocker
and the album's first single, fool you. For every Fly, there will
be a noisier tune. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Melanie C.
</P>
<P>
   The disc: Northern Star
</P>
<P>
   Street date: November
</P>
<P>
   Track record: She's a Spice Girl. 'Nuf said.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: Mel C. is the latest Solo Spice, although she says she
has not left the band, as did Geri Halliwell _ and, wow, her solo
career sure did take off!
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Tweaked by several producers, including Beastie
Boys cohort Rick Rubin, Northern Star has an innocuous techno-pop
flair. It's Garbage, in both senses of the word. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Rage Against the Machine
</P>
<P>
   The disc: The Battle of Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Nov. 2
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Honorable.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: How appropriate that Rage Against the Machine picked
Nov. 2 as the release date for its latest opus _ it's Election Day.
For the past several years, the California-based act has smartly
blended social/political lyrics with an insanely loud and addicting
hybrid of rock and rap, becoming one of this decade's most
important and influential bands.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Judging from Los Angeles' first single, the
savage Guerrilla Radio, not much has changed in Rage's camp. And we
wouldn't want it to. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: LeAnn Rimes
</P>
<P>
   The disc: LeAnn Rimes
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Oct. 26
</P>
<P>
   Track record: She's Blue, all right.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: Local country sensation LeAnn Rimes blew everyone away
with her 1996 debut effort, Blue, which was cut before she was even
old enough to get a driver's permit. As success rushed in, though,
so did image and sound makeovers. Last year, she was wearing
leather pants and singing Prince's Purple Rain. It scared us.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: LeAnn Rimes is a back-to-basics collection of
country covers. The disc features Rimes singing Your Cheatin'
Heart, Me and Bobbie McGee and Crazy, as well as at least one new
track, Big Deal, which she may or may not be anymore. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Sting
</P>
<P>
   The disc: Brand New Day
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Out now
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Hit and miss.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: Ever since he cut away from the Police in the mid-'80s,
Sting has released consistently fair solo outings; they're tuneful
but sometimes way too pompous. The multi-instrumentalist should be
commended, though, for slipping hints of jazz and world beat into
his music.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Sting's latest disc is, by far, his most
unpretentious. He still toys with different styles _ from classical
to country _ but he does so naturally, not forcefully. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: Stone Temple Pilots
</P>
<P>
   The disc: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Oct. 26
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: STP's problems started way before singer Scott Weiland's
drug problems. In the mid-'90s, the band was ridiculed by critics
for sounding like Pearl Jam, and even when they won a best-new-San
Diego-band award, music fans in San Diego blushed, ashamed that a
band so hated lived right down the street. Weiland's drug problems
have only made matters worse. He'll be in jail until next year,
keeping the band off the road until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: A combination of aggressive and gentle, an
unintentional image of Weiland's chaotic life. ___
</P>
<P>
   Who: 311
</P>
<P>
   The disc: Soundsystem
</P>
<P>
   Street date: Oct. 12
</P>
<P>
   Track record: Strong but underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Primer: Before Kid Rock and Limp Bizkit stole their sound and
ran up the charts with it, 311 was merging rock and rap for a small
but devout following. Even though they had a mild hit in '96 with
Down, they're still overlooked as one of rap/rock's inventors. It's
catch-up time.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Hip-hop mixed with ruthlessly loud guitars. But
unlike Limp Bizkit's shallow deafenings, 311's music explores other
genres, such as reggae and R&AMP;B. Too bad it won't sell as well.
</P>
