<HEADER>
A3446 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-HAPPY-RESCUE-TEX     10-11 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAPPY-RESCUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW FILM EDITING RESCUES A UNHAPPY MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ You'd think with a film called ``Happy, Texas,'' the
hometown connections would be somewhat obvious. But despite the
fact that the story is set in a small Texas town (the real Happy is
in the Panhandle north of Lubbock), it was shot almost entirely in
Piru, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But according to director Mark Illsley and co-screenwriter Ed
Stone, one Fort Worth native had ``an extremely important impact on
the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Buckley _ brother of Betty Lynn, son of Betty Bob and
Illsley's college roommate _ stepped in to re-edit the movie when
``Happy, Texas'' was not so happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had already cut the film together with another editor and
the film was in terrible trouble, it was not working at all,''
Illsley says. ``So I fired that editor and hired Norman, and I can
with all honesty say that the only reason we're here today is
because Norman Buckley cut my film. So here we are, in Norman
Buckley country.''
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the lobby of Dallas' Adolphus Hotel is close enough to
discuss the long, strange journey of this little film about a pair
of escaped cons (Jeremy Northam and Steve Zahn) who pose as gay
pageant planners in a remote Texas town in order to elude police.
``Happy'' opened last week in Dallas and opens Friday in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know this movie was gonna get made,'' Illsley says.
``We were just a couple of unemployed guys sittin' at a kitchen
table writin' a screenplay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then after we shot it, we never knew if anybody was gonna see
it,'' Stone says.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax Pictures' Harvey Weinstein saw it, and his studio
eagerly snatched up the film at Sundance this year. Weinstein
gushed about the movie at ShoWest in March, even offering the
gathered theater owners an unusual advance screening of the film.
</P>
<P>
   But when the picture dropped from the pop radar, Illsley
badgered the studio for edits and reshoots. The difference was
dramatic, with Northam's budding relationship with local bank owner
Ally Walker given the most tweaking. But one element remained
entirely untouched.
</P>
<P>
   (Be warned that reading further may give away important plot
points!)
</P>
<P>
   William H. Macy's turn as the town sheriff, Chappy Dent, remains
the film's strongest character, and Illsley and Stone make no
secret that he's their favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best human being in the movie,'' Stone says. ``And
straight or gay, if Chappy Dent isn't a role model for every person
living, then there aren't any role models at all.''
</P>
<P>
   You can probably guess that Macy's tough-talking, redneck
sheriff has a secret. And when Northam and Zahn show up, he starts
questioning his own feelings, particularly his new-found affection
for Northam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't have a political agenda,'' Illsley says. ``I
mean Ed and I are both straight, but we were making a movie about
people wanting to be in love, and you know, I think anybody should
be able to relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy wasn't exactly their first choice for the role, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part was originally written for a 300-pound man,'' Illsley
says. ``His agents called us and there was a moment where we
thought, `Bill Macy's not right for this part, he's so skinny, what
are they thinking?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And then we were like, `What are WE thinking? It's Bill Macy!'
''
</P>
<P>
   Illsley says that any doubts they may have had disappeared after
meeting with Macy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him, `We're just so flattered that you could read a
script that was describing the character as this big 300-pound man
and that you could see yourself in the part.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And Bill would look at us and say, `Oh no, I'm gonna play it
as a 300-pound man. Now I'm gonna be in my body, but when I walk
into a room, I'm gonna walk into the room like a 300-pound Texas
sheriff.' And he did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's an American treasure,'' Stone says.
</P>
<P>
   Their giddiness about the film is infectious, and after raving
about almost every cast member, it's clear that Zahn is another
favorite. They already have another script in the works with a
noncomedic role designed, they say, to show off Zahn's acting
chops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is a very talented man,'' Illsley says. ``He's got a
little bit of a baby face, though. He's 31, 32?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 67 years old,'' Stone deadpans. ``He's amazing. He worked
with John Huston.''
</P>
<P>
   The two share a belly laugh that turns the heads of several
folks walking through the lobby. No wonder their movie is so
``Happy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
