<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-AFL-CIO12-COX     10-11 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFL-CIO12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFL-CIO PRESIDENT VOWS TO TURN GOP OUT OF HOUSE
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With an endorsement of Vice President Al Gore
virtually assured, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney convened his
labor federation's annual convention Monday with a vow to sweep the
Republican majority from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Sweeney's battle cry _ ``clean out the House,'' he declared
in his convention keynote address to 700 delegates _ and the
lingering reluctance of key unions to endorse Gore raised the issue
of whether organized labor's top political priority in 2000 is
winning the White House or restoring a Democratic majority in the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign chairman Tony Coelho, pausing in an endless series
of convention center hallway conferences with labor leaders,
rejected the suggestion that labor could abandon a faltering Gore
in the general election in order to concentrate on targeted House
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all understand that if we win the White House, we also win
the House of Representatives,'' Coelho said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chip Roth, communications director for the Brotherhood of
Teamsters, the key AFL-CIO member still holding out against
endorsing Gore this week, said a Democratic majority isn't
necessarily in the interest of union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about passing legislation that helps working families,''
Roth said. ``And in this era, where you have razor-thin majorities
in the House, you have to have a more bipartisan approach.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Teamsters abstain when the presidential endorsement comes
up for a vote Wednesday, ``it is still a meaningful endorsement,''
Roth added. ``It would be more meaningful, though, in a united
house of labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over as president of the 68-union federation in
1995, the year after Newt Gingrich led the GOP to a takeover of the
House, Sweeney has made it a priority to restore a pro-labor
majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear Monday that he is committed to building on
recent electoral gains, lashing out at the Republican congressional
majority in unusually harsh terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pounding in the heart of every trade unionist in this
country as our perverted United States Congress continues to boost
those who are up and kick those who are down,'' he said. ``It is
time, way past time, to clean out the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said the House is controlled by ``an ugly, anti-poor,
anti-working family majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rosenthal, the political director of the AFL-CIO, said the
federation's endorsement of Gore will unleash hundreds of campaign
workers for the vice president in the early primary states of Iowa,
New Hampshire, New York, California, Ohio and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to produce a vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said the presidential primary effort on behalf of Gore
will piggyback on organizing already under way in some states to
help pro-labor congresssional candidates in next year's general
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our priority is to have a president and a working majority in
the House that stands with workers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said he is not concerned that Gore could become a drag
on labor's congresssional campaign. Gore continues to trail Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, the overwhelming favorite in the Republican
presidential contest, by wide margins in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think the early polls mean a heck of a lot,''
Rosenthal said. ``Voters and union members don't know Al Gore and
they don't know George Bush.'' One of the reasons for an early
endorsement of Gore, he added, is ``to begin the education process
to insure that George Bush isn't elected next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, organized labor poured $35 million into a
campaign against GOP members of Congress, about $15 million of it
into expensive TV ads. But the campaign fell far short of its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, however, labor shifted tactics and went back to the
basics of politics. It spent less than $5 million on TV, but put
$23 million into a ``ground war'' of old-fashioned grass-roots
organizing, door-to-door canvassing, telephone banks and
get-out-the-vote campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The result was an historic off-year gain of House seats by the
incumbent president's party. And it came on the heels of the
impeachment of that president, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO plans to spend about $40 million in next year's
election, most of it, again, at the grass roots. It is assessing
its 13 million members $3 each to pay for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's only opponent for
the Democratic nomination, had aggressively lobbied AFL-CIO members
to delay an endorsement until after the primary voting begins next
January.
</P>
<P>
   But Sweeney, during the three days leading up to the labor
federation's convention, pressured some of reluctant unions for an
endorsement of Gore when the convention ends Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to Bradley, Sweeney noted in his keynote address that
``it is fortunate that we have two candidates from one of the
parties who are right on our issues more than they are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the AFL-CIO had invited the Republican
presidential candidates to meet with the federation's political
committee, but none had accepted. ``Not one of them had five
minutes for working families,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Teamster President James Hoffa has cautioned labor
leaders against automatically supporting Democrats, Roth
acknowledged that none of the major GOP candidates had made any
overtures to Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   When the AFL-CIO votes to endorse a presidential candidate, the
Teamsters are likely to abstain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an anti-Gore thing,'' Roth said. ``It's just too
early in the process. We know a lot about Vice President Gore, but
we don't know enough about candidate Gore and where he stands on
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
