<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3470 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-LITTLEROCK-MEMORIES-T     10-11 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLEROCK-MEMORIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO RECALL THE HISTORIC DAYS OF THE LITTLE ROCK NINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MILES MOFFEIT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, the black teen-age boy could enter Little Rock
Central High School only when escorted by federal troops,
sidestepping the angry mobs and ducking their spit.
</P>
<P>
   The white girl driving her '49 Chevrolet to school could only
stare incredulously at the spectacle surrounding her classmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all so stupid, so asinine,'' she remembers thinking.
``I mean, what was the problem? I had no objection to going to
school with blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   It was autumn of 1957, and although they didn't realize it, the
boy and girl were part of a major flash point in American history
that would foreshadow the end of legal racial segregation.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court order called for the desegregation of Little
Rock Central High School, but Arkansas Gov. Orval Faubus snubbed
the order, commanding the National Guard to block senior student
Earnest Green and eight younger black students from entering the
school.
</P>
<P>
   A standoff over the students dubbed the ``Little Rock Nine''
dragged on for weeks with federal authorities. Eventually,
President Eisenhower outmuscled Faubus by sending in the 101st
Airborne Division, wielding bayonets, to ensure the students'
entry. The whole scene riveted a national TV audience as one of the
early chapters of the tumultuous equal rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, just about everything in Little Rock, as in many
Southern cities, came neatly packaged by race: neighborhoods, lunch
counters, restrooms, buses. Blacks and whites rarely spoke to one
another, even at school, said Betty Finley, a Little Rock native
who now is a retired schoolteacher in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Finley was the white girl who watched the actions of her fellow
white citizens in disbelief. The day Green was finally admitted
into Central, she defied the long-standing social taboos, walked up
to him and handed him a bundle of class notes she had kept from the
previous weeks, so he could catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not patting myself on the back, but my thought was, `If I
were in his shoes, I would appreciate anything I could get,' ''
Finley said, adding that she fondly remembers his courage and his
soft voice.
</P>
<P>
   Green did catch up, and in a big way. Despite the profound
barriers to his education, he went on to earn a diploma and two
college degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is a successful investment banker with Lehman Brothers
in Washington, D.C., and an outspoken voice for civil rights. He's
a hero to many and is scheduled to receive the Congressional Medal
of Honor during the next year.
</P>
<P>
   He admires Finley and the other fellow students who secretly
extended a helping hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty was one of the students who tried to reach out,'' Green
said. ``The organized resistance really intimidated any white
students that tried to befriend us. They wanted to keep us
isolated. Their view was that we'd all drop out eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine black students who integrated Central High were
passionate about pursuing the best education possible, Green said.
Admission to the campus, which was at that time deemed one of the
top schools in the nation academically, was a crucial step.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was early enough in our lives that we all knew that this
(Central High education) was not going to be enough to sustain us
for the rest of our lives,'' Green said. ``We all wanted to go to
Central primarily for the educational content. We wanted to use
that as a building block to do other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, though. It was like going to war every day. We
had guards for the first three months, and then, after the
Christmas break, the Army removed the guards from inside the
school, and we went on our own to our individual classes. That's
when the harassment really increased significantly. It was an
organized, orchestrated group of students who tried to make certain
it was a very unpleasant existence for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Green and Finley went their separate ways after high school. But
both continue to share their stories with friends and students,
educating scores of people about one of America's most rancorous
civil-rights showdowns and about what integration has meant to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that fascinates the kids the most is what it was
like to live in a segregated community, where the restrooms were
marked `white' and `colored,' where there were black porcelain and
white porcelain water fountains,'' Finley said. ``They just can't
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green and Finley describe the experience as almost surreal. They
covet their yearbooks not only for sentimental reasons but as a
record of the history that they lived.
</P>
<P>
   The pages are packed with strange images: shots of the sprawling
brown-brick campus juxtaposed against those of soldiers flashing
bayonets; pictures of the general who boomed to the students during
an assembly, ``We're here for a job, and it's going to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Green made an appearance in Little Rock in 1997 for the 40th
anniversary of the standoff. Feelings were mixed about the event
because many blacks at Central still lag whites academically. But
Green and others took the opportunity to dwell on the progress
that's been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one young person out there has seen the story of the Little
Rock Nine and can take from it a belief that he or she can open a
door, succeed against the odds, dream the impossible dream, turn
`no' into `yes' or navigate uncharted waters,'' Green told the
crowd, ``then the Little Rock Nine become the Little Rock Ten, the
ten hundred, the ten thousand, the ten million.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley didn't make the commemoration, but during recent Central
reunions, she stayed late, keeping her eyes peeled for Green in the
hope of congratulating him on his success. She kept missing him.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, she finally reached him by telephone. It was
the first time in 42 years that the two had spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really good to talk to him,'' she said. ``I recognized
his voice right away. I think it's appropriate that he's going to
get the Medal of Freedom with the other Little Rock Nine. They're
more deserving than most anybody. They were kids. They faced an
awful lot of hate and anger. It takes a special courage to do what
they did.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
