<HEADER>
A3472 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SANTANA-POPULARITY-2T     10-11 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTANA-POPULARITY-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT MUST BE BLACK MAGIC. AFTER 30 YEARS, SANTANA'S HOTTER THAN EVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here in the fall of 1999, Santana's most recent CD,
``Supernatural,'' has sold more than 2 million copies, and its
flagship single, ``Smooth,'' is holding steady as the
third-most-popular single in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Are we SURE this isn't 1971? Or 1972?
</P>
<P>
   Back in those days, after all, Mexico-born Carlos Santana and
his buddies were fusing rock, blues and Latin rhythms into a funky
entity that sounded unlike anything else on rock radio. His blazing
guitar work and the band's roiling percussion and ability to jam
made them a hit at Woodstock and with rock audiences worldwide as
Oye Como Va, Black Magic Woman and Evil Ways became FM staples.
</P>
<P>
   The band had gone from obscurity in their home base of San
Francisco to becoming (besides the Grateful Dead) the city's
hottest local act, to arena-filling superstars in less than five
years.
</P>
<P>
   And now Santana's star has risen again. Released this spring,
``Supernatural'' finds Santana paired with a host of young rock and
hip-hop artists, including multiple Grammy winner Lauryn Hill,
Wyclef Jean, Cee-Lo, former House of Pain leader Everlast, Mexican
rock band Mana, matchbox 20 lead singer Rob Thomas (who sings on
``Smooth),'' Eagle-Eye Cherry and jam-rock-goes-pop king Dave
Matthews _ plus Eric Clapton and production on one song by the Dust
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   It's this ultra-smart generation- and genre-merging that has
made young rock fans sit up and take notice; after years of steady
but declining sales, Santana is currently outselling Ricky Martin
and the Red Hot Chili Peppers, though both released CDs around the
same time as Supernatural and have received far more press.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Santana is the only active ``veteran'' rock band in the
Top 20 on the Billboard album chart, outselling young metal/hip-hop
acts Kid Rock and Limp Bizkit and sugary popster Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that more than a few times Alex Valentine, music
director for a local rock station, has received phone calls from
teen-agers asking who this Santana guy is, and is this his first
CD, and do you think he'll put out another one? Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger demographic thinks he's a new artist _ he's this
guy that plays guitar and knows all these cool people,'' says
Valentine with a laugh. ``Smooth has been in power rotation for us
since we signed on a month ago, and we've been playing the cuts
with Everlast and Dave Matthews, too. You take a genius like Carlos
Santana _ whose music sounds fresh in any year _ and combine him
with these young, hip artists, and that equals success.''
</P>
<P>
   The pairing of Santana, man and band, with the younger artists
is being seen as a stroke of marketing genius, and it rests on the
bald head of Clive Davis, head of Arista Records. Thirty years ago,
it was Davis who signed Santana to Columbia Records, where they
quickly became stars with such LPs as ``Abraxas'' and
``Caravanserai.'' Davis left Columbia, while Santana stayed and
kept on keeping on and putting out numerous CDs.
</P>
<P>
   There were some singles that did OK: A cover of Buddy Holly's
``Well All Right,'' which peaked at No. 69 in 1978, and a Russ
Ballard song, ``Winning,'' which hit the Top 20 in 1981. But in
general Santana was stagnating commercially and, to an extent,
artistically: Subsequent CDs, such as ``Freedom'' and ``Milagro,''
didn't come close to the Top 50, much less the Top 20.
</P>
<P>
   Davis founded Arista 25 years ago, and he re-signed Santana in
1997. Both Davis and Santana agreed that they needed to update the
band's sound and image for the '90s, and Davis came up with the
idea of pairing him with younger artists. Phone calls were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was definitely driven by Clive,'' says Adam Sexton,
Arista's vice president of artist development. ``And when we
started contacting people, we were overwhelmed by the response. We
just tapped into something.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime fan and local drive-time personality Jon Dillon says
that Santana had received scant support from Columbia in the past
several years, which is often the fate of aging rock acts past
their commercial peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put out a couple albums there that I didn't even know
about,'' says Dillon, a classic rock station DJ who first saw
Santana in 1971. ``He put out some great stuff, but it was
overlooked. He got pushed under the carpet with Columbia. They just
figure he's peaked, and they just work on the newer acts who they
figure will make them the most money.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, outside forces were also shaping Santana's
re-emergence. Santana was elected to the Rock 'n' Roll Hall of Fame
in January 1998, and his guitar work graced Lauryn Hill's 5
million-selling ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' which was
peaking in popularity (sold-out shows, Grammy awards) just about
the time Supernatural was released.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the boom in Latin music in general, thanks to Ricky
Martin's success during the spring with Livin' La Vida Loca.
</P>
<P>
   Also, people were looking back at the first Woodstock festival
in preparation for this summer's version _ and, thanks to an
intense rendition of Soul Sacrifice, Santana was one of the
performers who got the most notoriety out of the 1969 show.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in fact, perfect timing, and Arista positioned Santana
just right to be rediscovered.
(MORE)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
