<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3473 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SANTANA-POPULARITY-TE     10-11 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTANA-POPULARITY-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: xxx be rediscovered. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We were looking at three groups _ people who always buy his
stuff, older fans who don't buy his record anymore, and young
fans,'' Sexton says. ``And one of our advantages is that Santana
tours all the time, record or no record.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step was to get Santana in front of those youngsters
who had never seen him. And so Santana opened seven East Coast
stadium dates for the Dave Matthews Band in late May, playing to
more than 300,000 fans over seven nights.
</P>
<P>
   The CD began to sell, bolstered by Arista offering two tracks
for downloading to both Amazon.com and America Online. That, plus
numerous TV appearances, increased his visibility. Santana
continued to tour and was now drawing more teens and
twentysomethings than ever; pairing him with Ozomatli and Mana also
helped draw the younger fans. As did a ``Hard Rock Live'' special
that has aired on VH1 several times since it debuted in August.
</P>
<P>
   In Santana, younger rock fans found a man who could lead his
band through torrid performances _ and if they dug just a little
deeper, they'd find a spiritual, gentle soul who embraces all types
of music and all cultures and is a serious devotee of highly
regarded jazz artists such as John Coltrane and Miles Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like the Grateful Dead _ older fans came out of
the woodwork to see him,'' says Leo Saenz, leader of Fort Worth's
popular Latin Express, who performs many types of Latin music but
always features Santana songs in the group's sets. ``He stayed true
_ he didn't change his format or go disco like other bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an icon in the Latin community _ I've seen people from
Mexico, Brazil, Puerto Rico and Tejanos at his shows. He's
world-renowned. Some of the kids in the neighborhood are talking
about the same thing we knew all along.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Santana phenomenon shows no sign of letting up.
According to Sexton, last week was the most successful ever for
Supernatural _ 160,000 copies sold. The video for Smooth was the
most popular on VH1, and Santana's current tour _ sorry, no Texas
shows _ is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to have a vision to put Carlos and Rob Thomas
and Carlos and Everlast together,'' says Dillon. ``You think, `How
is this going to work? How will this sound?' But it works. This is
the BEST album. I think it's a continuation of his talent _ it's a
commercial comeback, but he's just so good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers the pop music scene for the Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7839 or e-mail him at
dfer(AT)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
