A3475 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-11 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLET-DODGING TOUGH GUYS SHOOT FIRST, SPEAK LATER ON `STRIP'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In all its empty-headed glory, the spectacularly
testosterone-filled The Strip has the distinction of being the TV
version of the action-saturated blockbusters we've witnessed in
theaters recently.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the degraded subculture of Las Vegas, a world of crime
and sex nestled within a world of glitzy capitalist, shopping-mall
kitsch, The Strip (8 p.m. CDT Tuesdays, UPN) follows the adventures
of a pair of former Las Vegas cops-turned-undercover security team
for a wealthy casino owner.
</P>
<P>
   Created and produced by Joel Silver, who brought us the Lethal
Weapon and Die Hard franchises, the UPN drama is, as expected,
heavy on car chases, shootouts and fistfights while on a shootout
during a car chase. (In the opening episode, these at least look
nicely choreographed.) I also like the move by one of our heroes,
actually ducking out of the way of a bullet. Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   The, uh, story line: Elvis (Sean Patrick Flanery) and Jesse (Guy
Torry) risk their lives only to be made scapegoats for a failed FBI
sting. They storm off, quitting the force and eventually aligning
themselves with casino tycoon Cameron Greene (Joe Viterelli), who
gives them an assignment to retrieve a kidnapping victim. An offer
of full-time employment arrives at episode's end.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, we learn about these two guys, although you've
already seen them if you've watched any of Silver's films, or
anything with Chris Tucker attached. From the leads to the
supporting characters, there's nothing new here.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis is the typical shoot-first, speak-second hero, so burned
out and bummed out that he rarely cares about the consequences of
his actions. ``I need a Slurpee,'' he announces seconds after
beating a guy to a pulp. He dresses like he's homeless and throws
half-eaten sandwiches into the back seat of his car.
</P>
<P>
   This unnerves Jesse, who wears suits, has a gorgeous real-estate
agent wife (Stacey Dash), and actually moved to Las Vegas for the
opportunity to better his family. I wouldn't be surprised if we
learn that he's a _ no way _ Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Torry, bless his comedic heart, is a stand-up comedian whose
stylistic aggressions of black urban macho are just what the script
ordered. He skulks, swaggers and spews out lines in a rapid-fire
bluster, except when he's not stretching his mouth into a big,
horsy grin, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse to crook: ``I ought to slap you silly for even saying
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry that I can't recall what was said to him, which shows how
much it matters. Dialogue is kept at a minimum here. Better to see
that bullet coming at your head.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
