<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers pull double-duty as baseball fansBy Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ray Ferraro spent Monday night in front of the
television, rooting for his beloved Boston Red Sox. Tonight, he and
about a half dozen Thrashers teammates will be at Turner Field,
cheering on the Braves against the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball's always been my favorite sport,'' said Ferraro, who
has 346 goals in a 16-year NHL career. ``It was when I was growing
up, and it still is. I picked hockey when I was about 16 because
that is the sport I thought I had the best future in. But I never
stopped loving baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans are wrong if they think most NHL players from Canada
grew up playing hockey year-round. The summers might be short, but
they do exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us played baseball, too,'' said Nelson Emerson, who
was born in Hamilton, Ontario. ``I've always been a big fan. I had
this little Expos uniform I loved when I was real young. Then I
switched over to the Blue Jays when Toronto got its team. Now I've
got to root for the Braves. They're my home team now. It's amazing
how good they have been in the 1990s. I think it will be the Braves
against the Yankees in the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Emerson, 32, loved baseball, he always knew that
hockey was his sport. That wasn't the case with Ferraro, who played
second base and shortstop in the Little League World Series as an
11-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro's all-star team from Trail, British Columbia, won the
Canadian championship in
</P>
</TEXT>
