u p BC-BUSH-WELFARE-HNS &LR;      10-11 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WELFARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANNOUNCES $500,000 IN GRANTS IN EFFORT TO HELP POOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, the front-running
presidential candidate who calls himself a ``compassionate
conservative,'' announced nearly $500,000 in grants Monday to
Christian groups that help the poor stay off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Bush announced the first five of some 17 grant finalists after
touring a church-run health clinic where a priest lamented a 300
percent spike in demand for services during three years of welfare
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Some 103 organizations around the state have applied for the
state grants, offering various ideas on how to offer practical
support to the poor as they move from welfare to work. The Texas
Legislature has authorized the Texas Department of Human Services
to spend $7 million over two years in Temporary Assistance for
Needy Families on such projects.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who says government should rally the ``armies of
compassion,'' toured a health clinic at El Buen Samaritano
Episcopal Mission in south Austin, where he announced the finalists
for the welfare ``innovation'' grants.
</P>
<P>
   DHS plans to award this year at least 17 such grants to
religious and community organizations offering creative approaches
to help the poor become self-sufficient. The charitable programs
include car repair, drop-in day care, literacy training, help in
obtaining work uniforms, life skills, English classes, computer
training and mentoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``America will be changed because people of faith and good heart
are willing to help people in need,'' Bush said. ``I believe
rallying the armies of compassion, thanking the soldiers in the
armies of compassion, is the next bold step in welfare reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as welfare rolls have dropped 57 percent in Texas since
peaking in 1994 at roughly 800,000, the demand for the church's
services has soared, said the Rev. Jaime Case. The health clinic's
budget, supplied mostly by the Episcopal Church, grew from $250,000
in 1994 to $1 million today.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of growth, though, can't be sustained as you can
imagine,'' Case said. ``Facilities are falling down around us. The
load we're carrying is getting a little burdensome.''
</P>
<P>
   Case said he's uncertain whether ever-growing demand for his
church's prenatal and well-baby clinic for the uninsured are partly
a result of welfare reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so, but what do I know? I'm just a priest,'' he said.
``But I would say they seem to be very coincidental timing-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that the problems of the poor have likely
been there all along and the clinic's growth is also the result of
outreach efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The church clinic has not applied for one of the welfare
``innovation'' grants, but Case said it might consider doing so.
</P>
<P>
   DHS Commissioner Eric Bost and Bush said the grant finalists
include Methodist churches in Beaumont and Smiley, Lutheran Social
Services in San Antonio, the Good Shepherd Mission in Huntsville
and the Salvation Army in Smith County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the course of the last two years, we have more
faith-based and public sector relationships, I believe, than any
other state in the country,'' Bost said.
</P>
<P>
   DHS spokesman Mike Jones said no needy citizens are forced to
use the government-backed programs offered at churches and other
religious institutions. The agency also insists that participation
in religious activities cannot be a condition of receiving the
help.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``nothing in the contract restricts them from talking
religion,'' he added. ``You're going to a church so obviously
that's a part of their services.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
