u i BC-MEXICO-FLOOD-1012-COX     10-11 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FLOOD-1012-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEADLY MEXICAN FLOODS AND LANDSLIDES PROMPT CALLS FOR BETTER
PREVENTION
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Bodies are still being unearthed from mud and
thousands are scrambling for food and water.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexicans are already debating whether nature _ or man _ is
most to blame for a week of disastrous floods and mudslides that at
last count have killed at least 344 and left 200,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Although record rainfall has drenched southeastern Mexico,
critics are also blaming alleged government corruption and
negligence for allowing homes and other structures to be built in
flood plains, on steep hills and other potentially dangerous areas.
</P>
<P>
   Infrastructure, especially drainage systems, critics are also
claiming, is woefully inadequate and poorly maintained in
vulnerable regions where hurricanes and tropical rainstorms are
frequent. And efforts to get relief to stranded flood victims have
been slow and disorganized, according to angry victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start making very big changes in Mexico to avoid
these kinds of disasters, or they will only get worse,'' said
Estrella Vasquez, a member of Mexico's federal Chamber of Deputies
who belongs to the center-left opposition Democratic Revolutionary
Party, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, president of the Chamber's new Committee on Civil
Protection, said Mexico needs better disaster preparedness laws and
programs or the country will continue to suffer more unnecessary
deaths and costly damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge scandal,'' agreed Homero Aridjis, one of Mexico's
leading environmentalists. ``No one is responsible for rain. But we
are responsible for the inefficiency of civil protection in
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested angrily that the government funnel money to the
flood victims from some of the $80 billion it has earmarked for
taking over bad bank loans from the nation's banks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials fear that the death toll from floods could claim as
many as 600 lives. Parts of the city of Villahermosa in Tabasco
state are so inundated the city's streets look like canals.
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst tragedies confirmed so far struck in Puebla
state east of Mexico City, where a mudslide engulfed a poor
neighborhood and buried an estimated 100 people alive on Thursday
in the city of Teziutlan.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood, which was not established under proper
building codes, consisted of mostly flimsy houses built in a ravine
below a cemetery. As is frequently the case in Mexico, the homes
were slapped up quickly by poor people, some of whom had migrated
to the town for jobs in clothing-assembly factories.
</P>
<P>
   A zoning plan called for the homes to be removed from the
ravine, but the mudslide struck first.
</P>
<P>
   A second village, Acalana, was also believed to have been buried
in mud, perhaps killing as many as 150 to 200 people. Only 30 were
able to escape, area residents said Monday, in what could be the
single deadliest tragedy of a week of flooding and mudslides across
southeastern Mexico. Acalana is a small farming village 90 miles
northeast of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo visited Teziutlan on Monday and
announced that the government would help families rebuild homes.
The poorest families whose homes were destroyed will receive 88
days in wages, $2,000 in construction material and land. Families
whose homes were damaged will receive $200 to $600 worth of
material, while higher-income families were eligible for subsidized
credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this (disaster) can be blamed on poverty,'' said
Salvador Rivero Laborde, a Mexico City civil engineer who said
building codes are routinely ignored in many cities where the poor
are desperate to find a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   Corrupt authorities, too, are to blame, Vasquez claimed, because
they fail to enforce building codes or take bribes to ``give''
people unoccupied land to squat on.
</P>
<P>
   That's what people said happened in the Pacific resort city of
Acapulco, where three years ago a similar landslide killed dozens
of people. Poor residents of the city said local political leaders
told them they could build shacks at the top of a hillside that
later gave way under the rushing waters of a swollen river.
</P>
<P>
   That landslide occurred while Mexico's Pacific coast was under
siege by Hurricane Pauline, which killed at least 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who cancelled a trip to Europe to supervise rescue
efforts, said that the damage from last week's floods may surpass
Hurricane Pauline.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, rain continued to fall in some of Mexico's
rain-drenched Gulf states. Tamaulipas state was put on alert for
flooding adents were already complaining that prices for
basic goods were climbing as much as 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Flood victims in Veracruz state complained about price gauging
and a slow response for help when Zedillo ventured there last
Friday. He told a man who was interrupting him to ``shut up,'' or
that he might ``have to pay,'' according to a Mexican reporter who
published an account of the confrontation in Reforma newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo and the man later both apologized. But the president has
been under sharp criticism for his outburst, as well as for his
administration's lack of investment in public works and protecting
Mexico from disasters such as Hurricane Pauline and 1998's
wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedies during this administration have underscored
institutional abandonment,'' said Reforma newspaper columnist
Roberto Zamarripa. ``A drastic change in social policies has lead
to a selective and tardy distribution of resources, which has made
some of these communities unable to protect themselves from the
forces of nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
