u a BC-MILLION-MARCH-COX     10-11 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-MARCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Million Family March plans announced
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First he called on black men. Now Minister Louis
Farrakhan is calling on all Americans to take their families to the
nation's capital next year for a Million Family March.
</P>
<P>
   The Nation of Islam announced Monday that it will hold a Million
Family March in Washington, D.C. next year on Oct. 16 to inspire
Americans' commitment to their families and communities.
</P>
<P>
   The march, which will come five years after the Nation's Million
Man March, is open to all races and religions, said Ray Muhammad, a
Nation spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This call for a Million Family March is because the 20th
century has directly focused on the destruction of the family
unit,'' Muhammad said during a press conference. ``Minister
Farrakhan believes that the 21st century must focus on the
restoration of a God-centered family unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Million Family March is scheduled for the fifth anniversary
of the Million Man March, which boosted Farrakhan's national
profile _ though the Nation's leader is still viewed as a demagogue
by many for his fiery rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Including some black clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Many black pastors in Atlanta, such as Bishop Eddie Long of New
Birth Missionary Baptist Church, refused to support the Million Man
March. The Concerned Black Clergy of Atlanta backed it, saying the
issues it raised were larger than Farrakhan or any particular
religious group.
</P>
<P>
   The group is taking the same approach to the new Million Family
March, said its president the Rev. Timothy McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that's about the business of elevating and helping
black men is a friends of ours,'' McDonald said. ``This is not
about the Nation of Islam. It's about God, our nation and our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
