<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3490 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-KIDS-LUNCHES12-COX     10-11 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-LUNCHES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prepackaged lunches gaining in popularity in area schools
 &HT;    By Diane Lore and Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lauren Myrick slowly peeled back the plastic from her
pizza Lunchables and laid the large cracker on top. Then she
squirted tomato sauce on the wafer and meticulously spread it
around. Next, she sprinkled on shredded cheese, and finally, with a
flourish, topped the masterpiece with a pepperoni.
</P>
<P>
   Does it taste good? ``Uh-huh!'' Crunch. Crunch. Crunch.
</P>
<P>
   The kindergartner is too busy eating to offer a full critic's
review. After all, it's lunch time at Vaughan Elementary School in
Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it should be called Lunchables time.
</P>
<P>
   More children are bringing pre-packaged lunches to school and
going for grab-and-go snacks after school than ever before. For the
kids, the attraction is fun foods in fun packages. For parents,
it's convenience. But for nutritionists, the trend is a measured
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``These products can have a place in children's diets, but not
every day and not all of them,'' said Kathleen Zelman, a Marietta
(Ga.) nutritionist and spokesperson for the American Dietetic
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: many of the new pre-packaged foods for kids are
high in sodium, fat and sugar. And health experts say feeding
children processed convenience foods _ instead of nutritious
hand-prepared lunches and fresh fruits and vegetables _ may
shortcut their dietary needs and even promote childhood obesity.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 dietitians, nutrition researchers and
government and industry leaders will gather in Atlanta next week
for the ADA's annual meeting. And one of the key topics will be
childhood nutrition and obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Snacks and lunchtime can be trickiest for ensuring children are
eating healthy diets, because parents often aren't there to
actually see what their children eat.
</P>
<P>
   Kids are notoriously picky when it comes to school lunches, and
parents are increasingly pressed for time to pack healthy lunches
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the ready-to-go lunch. ``The pre-packaged lunch meals is a
$660 million annual industry,'' said Lisa McCue, spokesperson for
the Grocery Manufacturers of America. ``This is yet another one of
those items that speaks to the convenience trend.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's no question that Oscar Meyer is the all-star here.
Sales for Lunchables totalled more than $500 million in 1998. Since
the product was introduced 10 years ago, 1.6 billion Lunchables
have been sold, with sales steadily increasing by 15 percent each
year.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Lunchables were simply meat, cheese and crackers
packaged together. Now they include mini-pizzas, tacos and hot
dogs, and they come packaged with candy bars and fruit punch.
</P>
<P>
   Grab-and-go snacks also are growing in the industry, McCue said.
Go-Gurts, or tubes of yogurt kids slurp without a spoon, are the
latest hit. Only now being introduced nationally, Go-Gurts have
already earned $37 million in sales in a year of limited
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Other individually-packaged snack and drink products are
Coolcuts carrots and ranch dip, which feature Bugs Bunny on the
package, and cute little chocolate milk jugs called ``chugs'' by
Mayfield. Parents looking for ways to save time are more than
willing to pay for these convenience items. A Lunchables meal, for
example, costs $2.29 at Publix. Compare that to about $1.50 for the
average school lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything wrong with (Lunchables) as an occasional
thing,'' said Jennifer Myrick, Lauren's mother. ``She eats
something substantial; she likes them and I would rather give my
time and attention to her instead of spending it in the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Myrick said she usually sends a sandwich to school with her
5-year-old, but once a week, Lauren takes a pizza Lunchables.
Myrick usually packs sliced apples with it (though Lauren's front
teeth are missing so lately she's been getting pudding instead.)
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the right approach to take, nutritionists said.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting Lunchables or similar products (there are a few generic
brands) to once a week or less is important. So is packing
additional fruits and vegetables with them or making sure the
breakfast and evening meal balance out nutritionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the pre-packaged lunches are loaded with fat and
sugar. It's a lot of cheese, a juice drink that's not really fruit
juice and then a candy bar,'' said Margo Wootan, a senior scientist
at the Center for Science in the Public Interest. ``So they've got
a lot of the wrong things in them and they are missing a lot of the
right things.''
</P>
<P>
   For lunches, Zelman suggested going with the smaller snack-size
Lunchables that don't have punch or candy.``Then you can pack the
fruit and carrot sticks and some real juice with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents find their kids often snub the home-packed lunches as
much as cafeteria lunches. At Vaughan, third-grader Danny Borske
was happily eating his pizza Lunchables while his classmate Eric
Dawkins was ignoring his homemade peanut butter and jelly sandwich
because it was ``smooshed.'' Another friend, Jeremiah Dickson,
wasn't eating his sandwich because it had cheese on it, which he
didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's essential parents and kids plan the lunches
together each week, said Chris Rosenbloom, a nutrition professor at
Georgia State University. ``Start by looking at the school menu
each week and seeing which days they'd like to eat there. Kids
usually are willing to eat the cafeteria offerings sometimes, like
on taco day or pizza day.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools, like Vaughan, are now packing meals similar to
Lunchables. One day last week, nearly half of a third-grade class
chose the cafeteria's pre-packaged lunch. The lunch had cheese and
ham cubes, crackers, fruit, a box of raisins, a choice of side
dishes and a low-fat cookie. Everything but the raisins (many boxes
were tossed) seemed to be a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   Next designate a ``Lunchables'' day, and then talk about what
kinds of lunches they would like to pack at home. ``Give them a
voice in what you pack and they'll be more likely to eat it,'' said
Rosenbloom. She also suggested dressing things up a bit _ use
cookie cutters on sandwiches, find whimsical containers and cut up
fruit rather than sending it whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the kids involved in planning, offer a variety and offer
only the best of the convenience foods,'' Rosenbloom said.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker and Diane Lore write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
