u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-535&AMP;A     10-11 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PARTY LEADER IS BARRED FROM NEXT ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian ultranationalist leader, Vladimir
Zhirinovsky, suffered a setback Monday when his party was barred
from participating in December's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   With his anti-American diatribes, Zhirinovsky has become well
known for his strident nationalism. He reached the height of his
influence in the early 1990s, when he emerged as the
third-most-popular politician in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, his popularity has waned as critics
charged that his Liberal Democratic Party simply sold its votes to
the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   His latest troubles seem to have occurred because his party had
become too much of an embarrassment for Russian authorities, who
insist that they are engaged in a fight against corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Under Russian law, the Central Election Commission must approve
a party's list of candidates. The entire slate must be disqualified
if any of the top three aspirants is rejected.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what happened Monday, said Artyom Golev, a
spokesman for the commission. The second- and third-ranking
candidates on Zhirinovsky's slate _ Anatoly Bykov, an aluminum
magnate from the Siberian region of Krasnoyarsk, and Mikhail
Musatov, the deputy head of the parliamentary defense committee _
were rejected for failing to disclose some of their assets.
Specifically, they failed to report the ownership of some cars and
of a house that Bykov owns in Krasnoyarsk, Golev said.
</P>
<P>
   Banning Zhirinovsky's party from the parliamentary race would be
expected to help two key political groups that are vying for places
in the 450-seat Parliament: the coalition between former Prime
Minister Yevgeni Primakov and Mayor Yuri Luzhkov of Moscow, and the
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's action, however, may not be the end of the
matter. Zhirinovsky vowed to take the issue to the Supreme Court,
and suggested he might try to get the party back on the ballot by
registering a new and less ostentatious bloc of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the country needs hungry people in ragged clothes who do
not have the money to buy nice suits,'' Zhirinovsky said, ``we
shall find such people.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Zhirinovsky's current list of candidates was anything
but inconspicuous. In addition to Bykov, who has often been accused
of corruption, the party list included Sergei Mikhailov, the
reported leader of one of Russia's most powerful organized-crime
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates on the list included Dmitry Yakubovsky, who
served a four-year prison term for stealing valuable manuscripts,
and Ashot Yegiazaryan. Yegiazaryan's brother owned the apartment
where Russia's former prosecutor, Yury Skuratov, was filmed
cavorting with two prostitutes _ a tape that was then broadcast on
state television.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian analysts assert that Zhirinovsky understood that
his popularity was declining and sought to raise as much money as
he could by selling spots on his party ticket to corrupt
businessmen. Members of the Parliament have immunity from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``His career is coming to an end, so he is just trying to
extract the maximum financial dividend,'' said Andrei Piontkovsky,
a political analyst. ``Everybody knows he is just selling his
name.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky had boasted that his party would receive 20 percent
of the vote, but some analysts questioned whether it would obtain
the 5 percent needed to qualify for a place in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhirinovsky's list of candidates was something of an
embarrassment for Russian authorities _ particularly at a time when
the Kremlin is trying to demonstrate that it is fighting
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhirinovsky went too far,'' said Sergei Markov, the director
of the Institute of Political Studies. ``The Kremlin and the
political elite drew a distinction between appropriate and
inappropriate political behavior. They defined the rules of the
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
