<HEADLINE>
NEW CHOICES IN TRAVEL INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)  
(lb) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travel insurance is entering another period of change. Beth
Godlin, senior vice president of Access America, said companies
like hers were always looking for new products to sell, and one is
an annual policy, which is expected to be widely available early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   These annual policies do not provide reimbursement for trip
cancellation or interruption _ a big source of claims _ which keeps
premiums low. Trip-cancellation policies can still be bought
separately under the usual terms, which are linked to the length
and cost of a trip _ about $6.50 for each $100 for short trips.
</P>
<P>
   The annual policies, with an overall premium of roughly $150 a
year, provide benefits in the event of loss of life or limb _
insurance jargon for this is ``accidental death or dismemberment''
or ``A.D.D.'' _ a minimal amount for lost or delayed baggage, and
treatment costs for illness or injury, all usually for incidents
100 miles or more from home. These are familiar benefits,
frequently provided by regular life insurance or property
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The part of the annual policy probably most important to the
traveler is medical evacuation. Costs for medical evacuation are
steep, and a benefit of $50,000, typical of an annual policy, would
not always be sufficient. But it can help, since costs of $100,000
for evacuation are common. Experts in the field say 20 percent of
travelers who buy insurance want such medevac coverage.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. embassy officials say that although many travelers think
the government will get them home if they are injured, this is not
the case. Despite images of the injured being lifted out by
helicopter, evacuations usually involve the purchase of multiple
seats on a scheduled airline for an attendant, casts or medical
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Annual policies are worth a look for people who probably will
take more than two trips a year at their own expense. Adventure
travelers, hikers and people who go to remote places by car also
might find one useful, as might those who have little or no regular
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Annual policies are sold by only a couple of companies now, but
the majority of big names, including Access America, say they plan
to introduce such a policy in the first three months of 2000. While
the existing policies are sold to individual travelers, they are
really intended for professionals who travel a lot _ travel agents,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Access America has been selling its annual policy to
professional groups since 1997 and, Ms. Godlin says, will be
selling a similar one to the public early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Access America, Box 90315, Richmond, VA 23286; (800) 284-8300;
www.accessamerica.com.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Directly
</P>
<P>
   Travelex Insurance Services of Omaha, Neb., sells what it calls
Annual Travel Accident Protection, on Land, at Sea, in the Air. It
is not sold through travel agents, but directly to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The company's basic offering costs $149 a year. The package
program _ there are many conditions on all of these specified on
the leaflet _ covers the traveler for up to $50,000 in
medical-evacuation costs or for transportation home of a body;
$25,000 for loss of life, two limbs, both eyes, or a limb and an
eye during a trip, other than in a plane crash; up to $10,000 in
treatment costs for illness or injury; $1,000 for lost baggage, and
$500 for baggage delay, or $100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The baggage benefit is never very big, but even a small benefit
like this might help someone whose luggage was stolen or destroyed
in a situation not involving an airline. A benefit of $300,000 is
paid in the event of death, loss of a limb or loss of eyesight in a
plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   This policy, like all of those involving medical treatment or
evacuation, involves the use of an assistance company with an 800
phone line; that company controls when and to where an evacuation
takes place. The underwriter is TIG Insurance Co. in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While this policy is sold to individuals, it is not available in
New York state. Shannon Lofdahl, a Travelex spokeswoman, said the
company had filed an application with the state, and a spokesman
for the state Insurance Department said that it was under review.
The policies are available at self-service boxes in a number of
airports in other states, where the applicant fills out the
brochure, giving a credit-card number, and then folds, stamps and
mails it.
</P>
<P>
   An Important Limitation
</P>
<P>
   The ins and outs of these policies require careful reading.
Although most trip-cancellation policies have provisions that
permit policyholders to apply for benefits when an existing
condition like heart disease or diabetes acts up, the Travelex
annual policy, like other annual policies, has no such provision.
This means that no treatment benefit is available to people who
fall ill from something that they have recently been treated for.
The evacuation portion, however, remains in effect.
</P>
<P>
   California tries to keep people from buying duplicate coverage,
and to meet California law, the Travelex leaflet says, ``Note: In
California, the pre-existing conditions limitation is waived for
medical expense.''
</P>
<P>
   But further down, under ``What Is Not Covered,'' is this: ``In
California, benefits are not payable if during the 60 days prior to
the effective date, a legally qualified physician advised you not
to travel due to a sickness or injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelex, 11717 Burt St., Suite 202, Omaha, NB 68154; (888)
407-5404; www.travelex-insurance.com.
</P>
<P>
   For a Group
</P>
<P>
   Globalcare Insurance in Massachusetts is offering a similar
annual plan, with benefits underwritten by American International
Group in New York. Edmund Cocco, the president of Globalcare,
acknowledges that this policy is really designed for a small office
or group: A premium of $500 for each sale is the minimum, meaning
that four people pay $125 each.
</P>
<P>
   This would buy $250,000 benefit for each person in the event of
loss of life or limb. The policy has no medevac component, so it
looks a lot like the travel policies that employers take out on
their workers. But for small companies with no coverage, it has a
value. The addition of a medevac benefit is being discussed, he
added. Cocco's policy is available through travel agents in all
states, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Globalcare Insurance Services, 220 Broadway, Suite 201,
Lynnfield, MA 01940; (800) 821-2488.
</P>
<P>
   All but four states _ Alabama, Iowa, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin
_ and the District of Columbia require that travel agents have a
license to sell insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes New York travel agents complain about the state's law,
but Wayne Cotter, a spokesman for the New York State Insurance
Department, said that the fee for travel agents to sell trip
insurance was $40 for two years. Insurance companies may pay the
fee for agents who agree to sell their policies. Commissions to
travel agents are 30 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The companies listed above, and many others, sell regular travel
insurance with a trip-cancellation benefit. But keep in mind that
this coverage must be bought promptly after the initial deposit on
a trip _ seven to 14 days usually _ to include coverage for an
existing condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
