<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WEB TRAVEL  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPPING SOFTWARE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget these days, but a computer does more than
connect to the World Wide Web. You can use it to write an actual
letter inquiring about room rates, print it out and, if you
remember how, put it in an envelope, attach a stamp and drop it
into a mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy software with information on destinations,
descriptions of hotels, parks and resorts, or maps that you can
make for yourself. The software, like a printed article, is fixed
in place when it is published, unlike a Web site, which can be
constantly updated (theoretically, anyway).
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest mapping programs, DeLorme's Street Atlas
USA, came out on CD-ROM in 1991. The seventh version of the program
was published this fall, and it is almost too rich with
possibilities: There are 8 menus across the top of the screen, 19
icons under the menus and 6 additional icons to the right of the
windows where you type in the start and finish of your trip. A full
installation of the Atlas takes up around 256 megabytes of
hard-disk space, and you still must have the CD in its drive.
</P>
<P>
   I punched in New York City as my starting point and the New
Jersey town I live in as my destination. Detailed maps appeared on
the screen, taking me through the Holland Tunnel and along a
reasonable path, though the Lincoln Tunnel would have been my
choice. I had to scroll through many maps on a 15-inch screen
before I got home.
</P>
<P>
   There the town was, with little blue rectangles marking such
points of interest as Dunkin' Donuts. (Version 7.0 adds almost 3
million ``points of interest,'' most of them more interesting than
that.) I entered my address, and a little ``home'' symbol appeared
in what seemed to be the right place, although without the street
name.
</P>
<P>
   Going into one of the icons at the top of the screen, I typed in
the ZIP code of a friend who lives in San Francisco. In a moment, a
map of that part of the city appeared. I typed in his full address
and the ``home'' snapped onto the map on the correct block.
</P>
<P>
   Street Atlas USA 7.0 is compatible with the global positioning
satellites used for navigation systems in cars, and will work out a
new route if the driver goes off track (and is traveling with a
computer). If you have a Palm or Windows CE handheld computer, you
can transfer maps and routes to them. The program works with
Windows 95, 98 or NT 4.0 and should be widely available for less
than $45. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION PLEASE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.gogoinfo.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can go on the Web for travel information without getting
bogged down in making reservations. Gogoinfo has names, phone
numbers and often links to Web sites of airlines, cruise lines,
lodgings, trains and buses, as well as destinations, attractions
and travel publications.
</P>
<P>
   The Attractions section contained casinos, museums, parks and
ski areas. Other sources included phone numbers for the Federal
Aviation Administration consumer hot line and the Thomas Cook
Currency Service. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OFFICIAL SITES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every state, and virtually every city, has an official Web site
that provides the ABC's for travelers. Since I was in gogoinfo
anyway, I linked to several of them from there. The San Diego
Convention and Visitors Bureau, www.sandiego.org, was typical, with
listings of lodgings, shopping, dining spots and maps.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin, Texas, Convention and Visitors Bureau,
www.austin360.com/acvb, describes the city as the ``live music
capital of the world'' and, appropriately enough, quotes Willie
Nelson as saying ``it's a great place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   All these sites provide an easy entry to trip planning as long
as you bear in mind that their purpose is promotion, not objective
information. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
