<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSPHERE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOSPHERE: DESERT GREENHOUSE RISES FROM `ECO-CULT' TO RESEARCH
CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORACLE, Ariz. _ It's been a long, strange trip _ from desert
``eco-cult'' to reputable research center.
</P>
<P>
   But in eight years, the massive glass-and-steel pyramid and
eggshell-like buildings of Biosphere 2 have emerged as a genuine
educational and scientific proving ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very reputable scientist, and I endorse 100 percent
what's going on out there,'' said Wally Broecker, a geochemist at
Columbia University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Broecker has been a driving force behind Columbia's involvement
in Biosphere 2 ever since he was tapped in 1991 to stem the loss of
oxygen inside the once-hermetically sealed structure.
</P>
<P>
   That was nine months into the first experiment, run by the
controversial and now-defunct Space Biosphere Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Four men and four women, known as Biospherians, were cloistered
in the $200 million facility to determine whether they could live
solely off the structure's man-made ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Among the goals was to determine whether Space Biosphere
Ventures ultimately could colonize the moon or even a distant
planet, ``which I thought rather bizarre,'' Broecker said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``You wouldn't transport something the size of the
biosphere to the moon. You size up the weight and forget it; it's
too heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, traditional agriculture used inside Biosphere 2
would never work outside the Earth's atmosphere, Broecker said.
Instead, hydroponically grown crops would have been the best hope.
</P>
<P>
   But Broecker disputes reports that Biosphere managers ``were
cheating'' when they pumped oxygen into the vacuum enclosed
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``To their credit, it was extremely well engineered,'' Broecker
said. ``Despite media reports, they were not cheating. They were
too directed. They sacrificed those eight (people) in there to get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Biospherians also were charged with conducting experiments
and coping with a ``Gilligan's Island'' existence, marooned inside
the massive structure in the shadow of the Catalina Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were being starved for oxygen, and they had a lot of
things to do in there,'' Broecker continued. ``Plus, one group of
four didn't get along with the other group of four. They were
skinny, their faces were pocked, they looked unhealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegations also surfaced in published reports that the
Biospherians faced further duress at the hands of Space Biospheres
Ventures co-founder John Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The report accused Allen of running a cult in which he ruled by
fear and intimidation. Allen vehemently denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   But they persist even today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a religious cult, but an eco-cult,'' Broecker said.
</P>
<P>
   An unpaid consultant, Broecker tried to convince Space Biosphere
Ventures to rethink its experiments. In 1994, halfway through the
living experiment with a second group of Biospherians, the
project's financial backer, Texas billionaire Edward Bass, pulled
the plug entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bass' financial people decided to give the cult the
heave-ho, and it was a cult . . . they then put the Biosphere in
the hands of a management company,'' Broecker recalled. That firm,
he added, spent 1{ years trying to stabilize it and turn it over to
more stable leadership. &QL; 
TAKES OVER FACILITY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which is where Columbia came in.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia, which formed a science partnership with Biosphere 2 in
1994, expanded its role by taking over the facility two years
later, turning it into a research and teaching facility.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover added a much-need air of legitimacy to Biosphere 2.
</P>
<P>
   Guanghui Lin, an associate scientist who joined Biosphere 2 in
1996, recalled when he submitted his first research paper to a
peer-reviewed scientific journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came back to me like it wasn't worthy research because it
was from Biosphere 2,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But subsequent papers were met with far less resistance, and
were soon published in such journals as ``Oecologia and
Biodiversity and Allelopathy.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's crowning achievement came earlier this year with
the publication of research on how increases in carbon dioxide in
the atmosphere is hurting the ocean's coral reefs. The findings
were published in ``Science,'' one of the top scientific journals
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a very nice study there, which is absolutely
scientifically valid,'' said Steven Wofsy, an atmospheric scientist
at Harvard University. ``They didn't answer all the questions, but
you never do in science.'' &QL; 
CLIMATE ZONES STUDIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the research being conducted at the Biosphere 2 is being
done in one of three biomes, or climate zones: an ocean, a rain
forest and a managed forest.
</P>
<P>
   Wofsy, who studies global change, said Biosphere 2 is unique in
its ability to run studies to answer questions, such as what the
ecosystem might look like in 50 or 100 years with the increasing
buildup of carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone could say you could legitimately criticize it (the
coral reef study) by saying that's just a big pot of water with a
wave machine,'' he said. ``But that will be true with any
environmental study.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the ecosystems in Biosphere 2 is designed to replicate
the natural environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these systems are perfect analogs to the outside
world,'' John Adams of Biosphere 2 said.
</P>
<P>
   But the artificial nature of the glass-dome structure is what
makes the Biosphere 2 a giant lab that allows researchers to tinker
with various aspects of the environment and measure the results
more precisely than in nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's valid,'' Wofsy said, ``and in some respects, it's
an elegant place to do these experiments.'' &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at (602) 444-8975 or
kerry.fehr-snyder(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3501 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      10-11 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is Anne Stephenson's ``New &AMP; Notable'' column forthe week
of Oct. 10:
</P>
<P>
   ``PHYSIOGNOMY: THE MARK SELIGER PHOTOGRAPHS'' &QL; 
(Bulfinch, $75) &QL; 
   You have not lived until you've seen Brad Pitt in an evening
gown and goggles. Better yet, look at Drew Barrymore dancing nearly
naked with a sumo wrestler. Or Aerosmith's Steven Tyler with his
lips spread just as wide as they will go (that is to say shockingly
wide _ Tyler can look like a contortionist just by opening his
mouth). Or Keith Richards playing dominoes. Or Howard Stern wearing
a crown of thorns (think about it). On the cover _ the stunned
look, we assume, is from the makeup session _ is Jerry Seinfeld as
the Tin Man. Just inside is a perplexed-looking Tom Hanks
scratching his brow with ape hands. Trust us _ you will look at
this picture for a long, long time. In fact, if you pull this book
out in public, a crowd will gather _ it's that big a draw. Maybe
it's the celebrity factor. Maybe it's Seliger's unpredictable way
with his subjects, who seem willing to do the oddest things at his
request. As chief photographer for ``Rolling Stone,'' he has put
famous faces in the most surreal and unusual circumstances. The
photos go largely unexplained, and we found that to be irritating.
Also, the subjects remain unidentified until the very back of the
book, which makes for some confusion because it's really hard to
tell who some of them are. But those are quibbles. The book is
pricey but fun. With an introduction by Eric Bogosian. &QL; 
``SHE SAID YES'' &QL; 
By Misty Bernall (Plough, $17) &QL; 
It's at issue whether 17-year-old Cassie Bernall said anything at
all before she was shot to death in April at Columbine High School
in Littleton, Colo. Did Dylan Klebold ask her whether she believed
in God and did she say yes before he pulled the trigger? Her
parents choose to believe she did despite reports to the contrary,
and her mother has now written this book _ proof that grieving
people need to impart some meaning to the death of a child and that
the attention of strangers is oddly comforting. Beyond religious
fervor and parental sorrow, however, Misty Bernall tells another
important story. Three years ago, Cassie was a difficult
ninth-grader whose conversations with friends touched on drugs,
sex, self-mutilation and violence toward teachers and parents.
Misty discovered this when she read letters Cassie had written to a
friend, whereupon the stunned Bernalls did what Misty calls ``the
hardest thing you can ever do as parents: to put your foot down and
say, `This stops right here.' '' They immediately put Cassie into
another school, regularly searched her room, tapped the phone and
forbade her to see her old friends even though they knew it might
backfire and drive Cassie further away. When Cassie's friends
vandalized their house, they moved to another neighborhood to keep
her away from them. Cassie eventually got better, but it's
impossible to read about this troubled girl at war with her
desperate parents and not think of the boys who later murdered her.
What Cassie Bernall said that day is not as important as what two
other parents wrote to the Bernalls a month later: ``We will never
understand why this tragedy happened,'' Sue and Tom Klebold said,
``or what we might have done to prevent it. We apologize for the
role our son had in your Cassie's death. We never saw anger or
hatred in Dylan until the last moments of his life when we watched
in helpless horror with the rest of the world. . . . May God bring
peace and understanding to all of our wounded hearts.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``WHAT IF?'' &QL; 
Edited by Robert Cowley (Putnam, $27.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What if, in the summer of 1941, Adolph Hitler had made his major
attack not into Soviet Russia but into Syria and Lebanon _ would he
then have won a strategic position that could have brought him
eventual victory? Or what if, early in his invasion of the Persian
empire, the young King Alexander had been dealt a second blow with
an ax (the first had damaged Alexander's helmet and left him
disoriented and unable to defend himself) by a Persian noble named
Spithridates? What if Alexander's bodyguard had not speared
Spithridates before he could strike again and destroy Alexander's
chance of becoming ``great''? If you feel your blood pounding, the
goose bumps rising, your heart soaring with the thrill of it . . .
then you must be a historian. If you dozed off before the first
question mark, you are a civilian and should refrain from looking
at this book lest you asphyxiate on the futility of it all. This is
an expansion of the the 10th anniversary issue of ``MHQ: The
Quarterly Journal of Military History,'' in which the editor asked
historians to write about the most important ``might-have-beens''
of military history. They had so much fun that many came back for
more. Contributors include John Keegan (who explores the
aforementioned Hitler scenario), David McCullough, Stephen E.
Ambrose and James M. McPherson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE LONG PROGRAM'' &QL; 
By Peggy Fleming (Pocket, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Figure-skating champion Peggy Fleming is too nice to write a
book. She didn't get angry at her son when his girlfriend turned up
pregnant. She doesn't blame her mother for being a control freak.
She has been married to the same man for a million years. She went
into a depression during her recent treatment for breast cancer,
but that was caused by a drug _ she stopped taking it, and her
sadness disappeared. We ask you: Where's the dirt? Where's the
trouble? The answer is that there is none. Fleming is as nice as
she appears to be and then some (she calls Nancy Kerrigan ``a very
ungracious loser'' for her behavior after Oksana Baiul beat her in
the 1994 Olympics _ for Fleming, that's like hurling obscenities).
This memoir, which covers her career and personal life, is not
exactly scintillating reading, but Fleming is so likable that we
decline to say more. &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net,
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
