<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AIRLINE-FARES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMISES, PROMISES FROM THE AIRLINES  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: (AT) should be replaced with the symbol) 
(af) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Government reports show that fewer planes are arriving on time,
more middle seats are occupied and more bags are arriving late or
damaged. But not to worry: the 14 domestic passenger airlines that
belong to the Air Transport Association announced on Sept. 15 that
within 90 days their policy will become ``customer first.''
</P>
<P>
   The similar policies adopted by the 14 airlines are aimed at
staving off support for a passenger bill of rights in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The new policies include promising to tell customers the lowest
available fare, do a better job of telling people when and why a
flight is delayed or canceled, respond in writing to complaints
within 60 days and clearly explain the limits on the use of
frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines also said they would make ``reasonable'' efforts
when planes are stranded on taxiways to provide passengers with
food, water and restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who co-sponsored legislation for a
passenger bill of rights, called the new airline policies, which
were offered in lieu of the legislation, ``nothing but legalistic
gobbledygook.'' Wyden recently included two amendments to a
Department of Transportation bill that direct the inspector general
of the department to investigate any ``unfair and deceptive''
airline practices regarding information on the lowest fare and the
status of flight overbooking.
</P>
<P>
   One airline promise is intended to help people shop for the best
fare, but it will cost some passengers. Some airlines say that
customers must pay for a ticket to guarantee a quoted price but
that the reservation can be canceled within 24 hours with a full
refund, even on otherwise nonrefundable tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But customers who carry a balance on their credit cards will
have to pay interest on the amount of the fare until the refund is
processed.
</P>
<P>
   While all 14 airlines pledged to tell callers the lowest
available fare, only Alaska Airlines included its Web site in that
promise.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines also said they would devise consistent policies to
determine who gets bumped when a flight is overbooked. They also
promised to pay attention to passengers who are disabled or have
special needs, such as children traveling alone. Some airlines now
charge fees of up to $30 a flight segment for children traveling
alone, even on nonstop flights.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Berger, editor of the Consumer Reports Travel Letter,
said that she was not impressed with the promises, many of which
she said are vague and all of which lack the teeth that government
regulations would include.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the marketing department's hand in this, but not the
customer service department's,'' Ms. Berger said. ``There is a lot
of hype and marketing speak about how we care about you. Over all
this is same-old same-old.''
</P>
<P>
   One indication of how seriously each airline regards its
promises of improved customer service may be how the policies are
treated on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Aloha, Continental, Northwest, United and TWA put a link on
their home page to their new policies. To find US Airways' plan,
you have to click on ``Travel Information''; on ATA's home page,
you go to ``About ATA,'' and for Delta's you click on ``The
Gateway.''
</P>
<P>
   American and Hawaiian posted their new promises in places where
few passengers are likely to look: on Web pages with corporate
information for shareholders or journalists. Alaska put it on its
employee Web site, www.alaskasworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   America West, Midwest Express and Southwest had not posted their
new customer policies more than a week after the Air Transport
Association announced them.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Brobeck, executive director of the Consumer Federation
of America, an independent, nonprofit group in Washington, said
that ``some airlines will try harder than others to deliver
improved customer service and some airlines will slip below the
standard thinking that they won't get caught and, if they do, that
the penalties will be insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can file complaints with the government by e-mail at
airconsumer(AT)st.dot.gov, by calling (202) 366-2220 or by writing
to the Aviation Consumer Protection Division, Department of
Transportation, C-75, Room 4107, Washington, D.C. 20590.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints should include a brief description of the problem,
the airline and flight number and the itinerary, as well as
information on how you can be contacted. Don't expect much for your
trouble, though. The Transportation Department just tallies
complaints _ and only about customer service, not safety _ and does
not arbitrate.
</P>
<P>
   Both Brobeck and Ms. Berger said that a customer-service crisis
of the gravity of the one at the Detroit airport last winter, when
Northwest passengers sat for hours on jets mired in snow just a few
hundred feet from the terminal, would determine the value of the
new promises.
</P>
</TEXT>
