<TEXT>
<P>
   (nk) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Oct. 12. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-BAN-TREATY (Washington) _ The outline of a deal emerges
that would postpone a Senate vote on a nuclear test ban treaty
until after President Clinton leaves office. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-NURSE-RATIOS (Los Angeles) _ Over the objections of the
state's health care industry, Gov. Gray Davis has signed a bill
backed by the state nurses' union that will make California the
first state to require hospitals to meet fixed nurse-to-patient
ratios, in an effort to force higher quality care and combat
cost-cutting measures in the place where managed care was born. By
Todd S. Purdum. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   D.C.-HITECH-BOOM (Washington) _ A new, outside-the-beltway
culture has grown up in and around Washington. The city and its
suburbs are now home to far more businessmen and entrepreneurs than
federal workers and the assorted private companies and institutions
connected to the government. By at least one measure, Washington is
now the technological capital of the United States. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   Special Report: 2,700 words; with photo, map and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ The government of
President B.J. Habibie announces that it is dropping an
investigation of possible corruption by former President Suharto,
defying public sentiment days before an assembly is to choose the
next president of Indonesia. By Seth Mydans. 1,000 words. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PROTEST-HERO (Montredon, France) _ Since he was arrested
in August for vandalizing a nearby McDonald's building site _
though his principal complaint is over American taxes on luxury
food _ Jose Bove, a wiry, 46-year-old union leader and sheep
farmer, has become something of a national hero. By Suzanne Daley.
1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   AFLCIO-ENDORSEMENT (Los Angeles) _ A reconstruction of how the
White House and the Gore campaign engineered the early endorsement
from the AFL-CIO. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Dr. Guenter Blobel, a cellular
and molecular biologist at Rockefeller University in New York City,
is awarded the 1999 Nobel Prize in Physiology of Medicine for
discovering that proteins carry signals that act as ZIP codes,
helping them find their correct locations within the cell. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-OPPOSITION (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Leaders of the Serbian
opposition to President Slobodan Milosevic find themselves
criticized on two fronts. They angered the European Union by
boycotting a meeting to protest its demand to extradite Milosevic
for war crimes, while Milosevic called them cowards, sycophants and
traitors. By Steven Erlanger. 1,300 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
