<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-KEYES-COX     10-11 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campaign 2000: Keyes serves as headliner
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An auditorium full of conservative
Republicans had laughed at Steve Forbes' jokes, applauded Gary
Bauer's sentiments, and risen to its feet in passionate support for
the beleaguered Pat Buchanan. Then it was time for Alan Keyes to
fulfill a familiar role: show stopper.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced as the only speaker who could follow Buchanan at
Saturday's National Federation of Republican Assemblies straw poll,
the 49-year-old former Reagan administration official and radio
commentator did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Unpacking a tool kit full of rhetorical devices, Keyes first
praised Buchanan as ``a man of courage and integrity,'' then
painted Forbes as a socialist for his support of NAFTA and GATT.
</P>
<P>
   His hands flashing in quick, precise gestures, Keyes called for
the end of the income tax and the federal Education Department in
words that reached back to the abolitionist speeches of the last
century. His voice rising in disdain, he warned against those he
said are selling out their party's principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You focus on victory and you will be manipulated into
defeat,'' he said, drawing a regular cadence of applause from an
audience hostile to their party's frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point I'm supposed to talk about voting for me and
stuff,'' he continued, his voice lowering by degrees into a stage
whisper as he asked listeners merely to search their beliefs and
see if they concur with his.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes finished third in the straw poll, ahead of Bauer, but the
results don't seem very relevant to his campaign. He has become
familiar with getting some of the biggest applause lines at
Republican gatherings, while gaining few votes.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes actually won a straw poll last August in Birmingham, after
being only one of two candidates to show up (Orrin Hatch was the
other). He delivered a thunderous anti-Clinton, anti-abortion
message to the Alabama GOP, but he left the convention before the
vote was announced and has made little of the victory since.
</P>
<P>
   This nonchalance about his standing has caused some to question
why Keyes is mounting his second bid for the Republican nomination,
if he isn't running to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the question. I know there are people who
hire their pollsters and consultants and hold their focus groups to
figure out what people want to hear. And then they stand before
audiences with jury-rigged speeches that have tag lines to make
people think that they believe what they do whether they do or not
... and if that's what it means to run in order to win then of
course, I won't do that,'' Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation away from the speaker's rostrum, Keyes doesn't
attain the same ringing decibel level, but retains a mixture of
dapperness and intensity. A practicing Roman Catholic, he wears a
crucifix on a gold chain underneath his tie.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed as ``nonsense'' the charge that he's running just
to raise the money, saying he has passed over more lucrative
ventures to be involved in politics. What he wants to do, he said,
is to present his view about the moral decline of the nation ``with
dignity'' and let audiences respond to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Americans now being pushed into a condition of slavery.
It'll be of a different kind in its outer manifestations than the
slavery my ancestors suffered but it will be slavery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to nearly all-white audiences, Keyes often evokes the
black experience of slavery, whether denouncing abortion or calling
for the end of the income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not free people, we're a people on parole,'' he told the
Kansas City audience.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an Army sergeant, Keyes said he has ``vague
memories'' of being marched to the back of a bus when the family
was stationed near Augusta, Ga., but was insulated from the worst
aspects of racism by a protective family and the integrated life of
military bases.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, he was struck with the ``emotional truth'' that
he was descended from slaves. He remembers reading Lerone Bennett
Jr.'s ``Before the Mayflower,'' a history of Africans in America,
with tears in his eyes. But from that point he diverged sharply
from those black liberals, such as Jesse Jackson, of whom he would
later be so critical.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes got his undergraduate and doctorate degrees at Harvard,
where he was influenced by the late Allan Bloom, author of ``The
Closing of the American Mind.'' He formed a philosophy, later
expounded in two books, which blends deeply conservative social
views with the belief that slavery has given African Americans a
special moral vantage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I fight the same battle when I speak on behalf of
the unborn that Frederick Douglass and Martin Luther King Jr. were
fighting,'' Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes served in the State Department seven years, including a
stint in India where he met his wife and a posting as ambassador to
the United National Economic and Cultural Council. Later, he was an
interim president at Alabama State University, ran an unsuccessful
race for the U.S. Senate in Maryland and became host of the
syndicated radio program, ``America's Wake-Up Call.''
</P>
<P>
   The first suggestion that he run for president in 1996, Keyes
said, came from Georgians who heard him speak for former Waycross,
Ga., Mayor John Knox in the 1994 governor's race. Knox today
praises him as the best speaker in the Republican Party, and ``the
most intelligent man I've ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   The most bizarre moment of the 1996 race for Keyes came when he
was detained by police for trying to gain entry at a candidates
debate in Atlanta. Keyes was led out to the street, then picked up
by Mayor Bill Campbell and driven to his hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird, but you know what else it was? Proof of how
frightening the truth is for some people,'' Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled his first campaign as a kind of ``pickup basketball
game,'' with supporters working as long as they could, then passing
the ball to others. The current campaign has tried to be more
systematic, he said, without losing its grassroots connections.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes has no campaign or finance chairs, and no headquarters.
The candidate's home base is the Washington area, his campaign
manager, Dan Godzich, works out of Phoenix, Ariz., and his
scheduler, Carla Michele, directs traffic from her home in a Dallas
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grassroots. We're true grassroots,'' Michele said of the
small organization which supports Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   A volunteer at Keyes' booth outside the convention in Kansas
City, Barbara Betterman, said his identification of moral decay as
the fundamental problem afflicting the country was what attracted
her to his campaign. And also, the way in which he delivers his
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes me jump to my feet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes said a steady stream of small contributions will enable
him to continue his current campaign, if not in the high style of
Forbes or Texas Gov. George W. Bush. And while he can't expect to
win many straw polls, he takes satisfaction in the influence he
believes his fiery speeches have had on the other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compare their speeches last time, and their speeches this
time, and see if there isn't Alan Keyes in almost all of them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
