<HEADER>
A3512 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-MOWLAM-BOS &LR;      10-11 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MOWLAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOWLAM LEAVES NORTHERN IRELAND POST IN CABINET SHUFFLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair shuffled his Cabinet
on Monday, replacing Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam with
Peter Mandelson, the mastermind of the 1997 Labor Party landslide
who resigned from the Cabinet in disgrace last December.
</P>
<P>
   The move, while designed to reward Blair loyalists, may have a
distinct impact on the sluggish Irish peace talks by making the
Protestant unionists more willing to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Mowlam, the first woman to hold the job as Britain's top
official in Northern Ireland, was given what is ostensibly a
promotion, to chief of the Cabinet, a position known as ``Cabinet
enforcer.'' But the move comes just three months after Mowlam
persuaded Blair not to make her take a new job similar to the one
given to her Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The reshuffle served two key purposes for Blair, who wanted to
give Mowlam, the most popular member of his Cabinet, a more
high-profile position in Britain, and to get Mandelson back in his
inner circle. Mandelson, 45, is given the most credit for helping
Blair seize power by moving the traditionally left-wing Labor Party
to the center, ending 18 years of Conservative government and
giving Labor the biggest parliamentary majority in nearly two
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Blair also moved three close aides into the defense, health, and
treasury ministries, firming up the presence of ``New Labor''
advocates in the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   In her new position, Mowlam, who consistently tops polls as the
most popular Cabinet member, will be in the British public eye more
regularly, appearing on television and radio to defend the
government's policies. Mandelson, meanwhile, appears to be
politically rehabilitated just 10 months after resigning as trade
secretary for failing to disclose he took a $615,000 loan from the
government paymaster general whose office he was investigating.
Mandelson used the money to buy a home in the trendy Notting Hill
section of London.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ancram, chairman of the opposition Conservative Party,
criticized Mandelson's relatively swift return to power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He only resigned 10 months ago in disgrace. This shows that as
long as you're a crony of Tony Blair, it doesn't matter what you've
done,'' said Ancram.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and his top aides, meanwhile, hope that moving Mowlam out
of Belfast will make the Ulster Unionists, the biggest party in
Northern Ireland, more willing to compromise in the ongoing dispute
that has prevented the creation of a local government and stalled
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble suggested that
Mowlam be replaced by Mandelson, and there were senior aides to
Blair who wanted him to make the move in August. But Mowlam
resisted the suggestion that she be made the Labor Party's
chairwoman or the government's chief whip, the first time anyone
could remember a Cabinet member refusing a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Mowlam told friends and associates that she was not
totally opposed to changing of jobs, but was uncomfortable with the
vague leadership jobs on offer and wanted something ``more
hands-on.'' She was also reluctant to leave when some unionists
were crowing that they were forcing her out. Unionists accused
Mowlam of being biased toward nationalists, a charge she rejected.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Blair at Downing Street on Monday, Mowlam appeared
alongside Mandelson, telling reporters, ``It's never an easy time
to go, but everyone has to go some time.'' But, she insisted, ``I'm
very pleased with the job I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said there was ``nothing more important'' to finding a
solution to the current impasse, in which unionists refuse to form
a local government with Sinn Fein, the political allies of the
Irish Republican Army, until the IRA begins turning in weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, who had bristled at Mowlam's informal style, said he
welcomed Mandelson's appointment. Nationalists were less
enthusiastic, but said the appointment of one of Blair's closest
advisers underscores the prime minister's commitment to
implementing the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, the political
settlement aimed at resolving the Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's reshuffle was the first major change that Blair has
made in his Cabinet since his landslide election in May 1997. It
was prompted by the departure of Defense Secretary George Robertson
to become the general secretary of NATO, and the decision last week
by Health Minister Frank Dobson to resign to run for mayor of
London. Robertson was replaced by Geoffrey Hoon, a junior foreign
minister, while Dobson was replaced by Alan Milburn, who was chief
secretary to the treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cunningham, the most senior member of Blair's Cabinet,
resigned as the Cabinet enforcer, opening the job for Mowlam.
</P>
<P>
   Besides giving Mowlam a higher profile in Britain and getting
Mandelson back inside 10 Downing St., Blair has succeeded in
bringing in more of his New Labor peers, according to political
observers. Cunningham was an old hand who served in the last Labor
government 20 years ago, while Hoon and Milburn are known as
``Blairites'' who helped modernize the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
