r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     10-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE CLOTHESHORSES STRUT THEIR STUFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sophia Loren &LR; , often seen in the front row of leading
designers' fashion shows, has been accused of being paid big bucks
to be there. Her going rate is $50,000 per show, reports
 &UR; Neil Travis &LR;  of the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   Travis says many young actresses not particularly ``noted for
their love of high style'' pick up extra change and/or extra
clothes by showing up for the their &LR;  shows.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at a  &UR; Tommy Hilfiger &LR;  fashion show last week,
 &UR; Debbie Harry  &LR; was in the audience and the grunge rock group  &UR; Bush &LR; 
provided very loud music. According to fashionwiredaily.com, Harry
``started ripping pages from her Hilfiger program and stuffing them
into her ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Her representative denied that this meant she didn't like the
music. ``She thought Bush was great. I don't know why she stuffed
paper in her ears.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION STATEMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - South Korea-based LG Fashion makes scented men's suits,
reports GQ magazine. A Los Angeles outlet for the company's Maestro
line sells scented golf shirts, and &LR;  as well as formal and casual
suits with lavender and pine aromas.
</P>
<P>
   The technology employs microcapsules that pop on contact. The
scent is said to last through 20 dry cleanings and/or three years.
The first shipment of the suits, which cost $400, sold out in a
month, says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - Vogue reports on uniforms newly designed by Viktor &AMP; Rolf for
the staff of the Centraal Museum in Utrecht, Holland, featuring
Levi's jeans, a shirt and a sash worn diagonally across the chest,
embroidered with the wearer's name and job. ``They are embroidered
in Holland by the same firm that makes vestments for the pope,''
says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - The last word in tattoos is not ``Mom'' or ``Death Before
Dishonor''; it's the color white. Details magazine says that
tattoos filled with white, so-called ``ghost tattoos,'' appear
lighter than skin, and eventually fade when the skin's natural
pigment take over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE POWER OF SLACKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, two San Diego schoolteachers,  &UR; Constance Bowman  &LR; and
 &UR; Clara Marie Allen &LR; , spent their summer vacation on a B-24
production line at a bomber plant. Their book about the experience,
``Slacks and Calluses,'' was published the following year;
Smithsonian Institution Press has just reissued it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't think there's a difference'' between women who
work in slacks and women who work in skirts, wrote the authors,
``just put on a Consolidated uniform and try to get service in your
favorite store, make a reservation at a ticket office or get
information at the post office. Either the clerks have no concept
of the position of a customer in a buying and selling economy _ or
they don't consider aircraft workers customers.''
</P>
<P>
   As to men, ``we were not women at all, as far as they were
concerned., &LR; '' Making their way to and from work in slacks every
day, the women stood in crowded buses while men sat. ``Two women in
skirts who got on at the same time we did were always offered
seats.''
</P>
<P>
   On their first Sunday off, the authors got dressed up and went
for a bus ride, ``just to reassure ourselves that it was the slacks
and not us.'' Seven men gallantly rose.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman, who later married and became writer  &UR; Constance Reid &LR; ,
lives in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - ``Do you still feel like you're fighting for respect in the
industry?'' the Cable Guide asked  &UR; Melissa Etheridge &LR; . ``No,'' she
said. ``I feel a lot of respect. It's funny; I've been gone for a
couple of years and I've come back and I kind of feel even more
respect. It's kind of disconcerting. I'm not that old; don't
respect me too much. I don't feel a problem for being a woman or
being gay. I think music has gone further than that.''
</P>
<P>
   - Meanwhile, MSNBC says that in the middle of taping a
`` &UR; Roseanne &LR; '' episode last week, the star started screaming and
cursing and using four-letter words in front of a live audience.
She was led off the set, and the rest of the week's shows were
canceled. A spokeswoman said Roseanne ``was ill.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever see those stools? You haven't been on a chair that
high since you were 2. Seventy-three-year-old Jews are climbing and
climbing to get to the top of the chair. And when they get to the
top of the chair, they can't even drink the coffee because there's
12 people around one little table.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Jackie Mason  &LR; on seating at Starbuck's, quoted in a Wall
Street Journal story about restaurants with high chairs.
Restaurateurs think sitting high ``cranks up'' the dining
experience and makes it easier for strangers to meet; restaurant
analysts say sitting high makes for rapid customer turnover.
</P>
</TEXT>
