<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BIRM-MAYOR-COX     10-11 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRM-MAYOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mayoral vacancy splits black communities
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Today when city voters cast their ballots for
mayor, Richard Arrington won't be one of the choices for the first
time in 20 years. The first black mayor in city history retired
this summer, saying he had done all he could, had exhausted all
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not to say his administration won't live on.
</P>
<P>
   The top candidate in a field of 14 is City Council President
William Bell, a faithful supporter of the mayor through the years.
Arrington left office early and appointed Bell as the interim
mayor, giving the council veteran the chance to run as a
pseudo-incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   The move helped solidify the black constituency that kept
Arrington in power so long. But it's also troubled some black
professionals, who say two decades under Arrington helped little in
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Former Birmingham Municipal Judge Emory Anthony, a black man
appointed to his judicial post, ran strongly in the past against
Arrington, drawing from some of the same people who put Arrington
in office.
</P>
<P>
   After running against Arrington, Anthony lost his judicial
appointment. Today, he works in private practice and supports city
council member Bernard Kincaid for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bell leading Kincaid 2-1 with nearly 40 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony is among those fearful that an extension of Arrington's
power would be bad for the city as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was good at playing the race card,'' Anthony said. ``That
was a good card for him to play because he could say you're just
trying to keep a black mayor down'' to white council members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything became a black-white issue. But you can't divide
the people one day then come back the next day and try and put the
city back together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Cleage runs the Five Points Ace Hardware in the city's
chief entertainment district. The city's cultivation of growth
outside of downtown, which won Arrington's approval, has worn thin
with him.
</P>
<P>
   He said the vitality that once made downtown merchants jealous
of Five Points South has peaked because of developments on the edge
of town like the city-conceived Summitt, a $100 million mix of
hotels, offices, shops and apartments. Such projects also are seen
as development that leaves out blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburban town of Hoover, shoppers flock to the Riverchase
Galleria, an area that gives rise to a haven of strip malls next to
the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's never going to get anywhere economically because
all of it is going to the suburbs,'' Cleage said.
</P>
<P>
   John's Restaurant once stayed open till 10 p.m. But the inner
city is so deserted after dark that closing time was moved back an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   The brick building where the city's power lawyers lunch at a
round table with a split white laminate top sits downtown on
Richard Arrington Jr. Boulevard. By nightfall, the locals are gone.
They need incentive to come downtown, which means businesses need a
reason to set up shop, said Jodie Stanfield, the general manager at
John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need someone who's going to bring Birmingham back,'' said
Stanfield.
</P>
<P>
   All around the financial and legal district that dominates
downtown, vacant buildings abound. Plate glass windows display For
Sale signs. Loft apartments are beginning to move in but
businessmen like Stanfield are waiting to see if they really take
root.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the convention people drive through here to get to some
of the livelier spots, they see a ghost town,'' Stanfield said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Arrington never accomplished was moving Birmingham
forward as a region, not a conglomeration of satellite communities
moving at cross-purposes to a municipal behemoth. Like Atlanta,
Birmingham as a region is faced with the complex issue of
delivering services and expanding business in a managed fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Arrington was just never able to be a mobilizer in
that,'' said Edward LaMonte, a political scientist at Birmingham
Southern College and formerly the senior staff member of
Arrington's administration the first two terms. ``The next mayor
has to be a more skillful metro area leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
