<SLUG> BC-ALA-LOTTERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama polls open as state lottery hangs in balance
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Whether Alabama voters today approve a
statewide lottery referendum may depend on Chevy church vans and
BellSouth phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're suggesting our churches run their vans and pick up
people that want to vote,'' Joe Bob Mizzell, director of Christian
ethics for the Alabama Baptist Convention, said Monday. He then
joined a prayer vigil on the steps of the state Capitol to oppose
the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The key for both sides is voter turnout, forecast at a
remarkable 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking church members to divide their rolls and call 10
people each and remind them to vote,'' Mizzell said. ``I don't have
any polling that supports this, but my gut feeling is that it's
dead-even _ we may even be ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls consistently have shown voters favor the lottery in
Alabama, a state surrounded by lotteries. Don Siegelman was elected
governor last November on the promise of starting an education
lottery that would fund HOPE scholarships similar to Georgia's.
</P>
<P>
   Barraged by advertising for and against the lottery, more
election-eve poll respondents are saying they haven't made up their
minds. In a survey Thursday by the Alabama Education Association,
which favors the lottery, 49 percent said they'd vote for the
lottery, 35 percent said they are against and 15 percent said they
are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Johnson, pollster for the AEA, reasoned the undecided
numbers have climbed because of the advertising deluge. He said
``undecideds'' typically drop by election eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really tells me that some folks are just hopping on
`Don't Know' because they don't want to say,'' Johnson said. ``They
don't want to be verbally punched by both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   For lottery advocates, black voters may be the most critical
group. The anti-lottery faction will be relying on white,
Protestant churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Johnson there is strong pro-lottery sentiment
across gender, race, party and income lines. Alabamians who said
they go, those who went to church frequently represented the only
demographic group that opposed the lottery.,.
</P>
<P>
   In AEA polling last week, 30 percent of those surveyed said they
went to church more than once a week. Of that group, 51 percent
opposed the lottery while 44 percent approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an upset if the lottery lost,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
