u i BC-YUGO-OPPOSITION-745&AMP;A     10-11 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-OPPOSITION-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB OPPOSITION BOYCOTTS EUROPEAN UNION SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Leaders of the Serbian opposition to
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia found themselves
criticized on two fronts Monday. They angered the European Union by
boycotting a meeting to protest its demand to extradite Milosevic
for war crimes, while Milosevic himself called them cowards,
sycophants and traitors.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, already facing dwindling turnouts at its nightly
rallies, is used to harsh criticism from the Milosevic government.
But some opposition leaders said privately Monday night that they
were upset that the European Union had put them in such a difficult
political position by demanding that they support a resolution that
would call for the extradition of Milosevic, who has been indicted
for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition leaders say they want to concentrate on trying to
oust Milosevic rather than being asked to hand him over like a war
trophy to the countries that bombed Serbia less than six months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need for the Hague tribunal issue to be imposed as
a priority,'' said a leader of the Alliance for Change, Vladan
Batic. ``This nation still cares about its national identity.
Milosevic should be tried in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   But discussions with European Union diplomats in Belgrade on
Sunday night did not achieve an acceptable compromise, so leaders
of the main Serbian opposition parties refused to go to a meeting
Monday in Luxembourg. Officials from Serbia's sister republic,
Montenegro, attended, as did Vuk Obradovic, head of the small
opposition Social Democracy Party, and Nenad Canak, who runs an
opposition party in Vojvodina, the northern province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In Luxembourg, European Union foreign ministers hoped to make
``a new beginning'' with Serbia by providing about $5 million in
heating oil, despite American reservations. The first shipment
would be to two opposition-run towns in southern Serbia, Nis and
Pirot.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of this ``Energy for Democracy'' program is to try to
show Serbs that the West is opposed to the Milosevic government but
not to ordinary citizens, who face a very cold winter with few
resources.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration fears, though, that Milosevic will
siphon off the aid or claim credit for it. Privately, some U.S.
officials say a cold and hungry population is more likely to try to
overthrow Milosevic, which remains the United States' top policy
goal in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But European leaders think that the U.S. approach is too crude
and that a faltering opposition here needs to show voters that it
can provide the fuel and food they need with Western support _
benefits that the isolated Milosevic cannot match.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders helped come up with the Energy for Democracy
plan to demonstrate that they are likely to be able to deliver
prosperity if Milosevic is removed from power. The opposition
favors a wider lifting of sanctions against Yugoslavia, arguing
that Milosevic uses them as an alibi for the increasing poverty and
desperation of ordinary life here.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Milosevic did Monday in a rare speech in Leskovac,
as he presided over the reopening of a railway station on a line
badly damaged by NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in the last decade was refugees, sanctions,
earthquakes and floods,'' Milosevic said in a speech shown often on
Monday on national television. ``Still, we remained on our feet and
showed the whole world how to defend the fatherland, how the
country can be defended and rebuilt.''
</P>
<P>
   His government has contrasted its efforts to reconstruct the
country with the rallies by the opposition, which state media call
``the Alliance for NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are mainly cowards, blackmailers and
sycophants,'' Milosevic said. ``They do not take part in the
reconstruction, but with rocks in their hands and with words they
learned in the offices of our murderers, threaten to destroy what
we have defended from NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic accused the opposition of wanting ``civil war'' in an
effort to create a pro-Western colony led by ``a local traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   And he challenged the opposition to prove its support in federal
and local elections that are to be held next year _ elections that
would not affect his own position.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, with its rallies faltering, is moving toward a
demand for early elections in the next three months, but under
conditions that would include international supervision and open
access to television and radio.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The European Union meeting was something of an embarrassment
because of the boycott of the opposition leaders the Europeans were
trying to help. The British foreign secretary, Robin Cook, said,
``The decision, as I understand it, is not theirs but imposed on
them by Milosevic, who has told them they will be guilty of treason
to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Batic and other opposition leaders, including representatives of
the Democratic Party of Zoran Djindjic and the Serbian Renewal
Movement of Vuk Draskovic, had objected to the draft European Union
declaration in the meetings over two days, saying it would be
politically damaging to agree to it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western diplomats here suggested that it was at the United
States' insistence that the European Union made such a point, in
the draft declaration, of cooperation with the International
Tribunal in The Hague. This was a way of getting the United States
to go along, however grudgingly, with the Energy for Democracy
program, one diplomat suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is also trying to press the democratic
opposition in Serbia to be bolder and more outspoken in its
resistance to Milosevic _ ``to prove that they really are a
democratic opposition,'' a NATO-country diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   But another Western diplomat here, not from a NATO country,
said: ``The demand to commit to extradition puts the opposition in
a totally false position, especially when they are so divided and
weak. They have a lot of other problems to worry about, without
being made to seem unpatriotic or craven.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Zivkovic, mayor of Nis and a vice president of the
Democratic Party, said: ``Thirty hours before the meeting, a
document is circulated which is supposed to be the result of a
meeting with us. This is a principle which is unacceptable.''
Zivkovic is considered one of the opposition's most effective
leaders, and his city, Nis, would be one of the first beneficiaries
of the oil deliveries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
