<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vanity Fair puts new spin on Rockwell
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks of the Saturday Evening Post illustrator as a
portrayer of corny Americana may see him in a new light after
reading the Vanity Fair ($3.95) excerpt from ``Norman Rockwell:
Pictures for the American People.'' Published to coincide with the
touring Rockwell exhibit that opens at Atlanta's High Museum in
November, writer Dave Hickey explains that Rockwell was a more
important and complex artist than his detractors will admit. His
paintings were not intended to be nostalgic, Hickey notes, but
rather moments captured in time before they faded. ``The kids in
Norman Rockwell's America always grow up,'' Hickey writes. ``I
imagine the `Girl With Black Eye,' who sits grinning outside the
principal's office, a decade later burning her bra. I imagine the
kids in `After the Prom' sitting around the campfire in some
commune in New Mexico trying to recapture the golden glow of that
night at the soda fountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Other articles of note are Judith Newman's insightful profile of
Viacom chief Sumner Redstone, who took a handful of movie theaters
and turned them into a media empire; Tom Hanks' tribute to Gary
Cooper; Steve Daly's attempt to get inside Jim Carrey's head; and
Annie Leibovitz's photographs of four decades of Bond girls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kid stuff: They're too old for sandboxes but too young to be
called teens. Newsweek ($3.50) labels them Tweens in an interesting
cover story about the generation of kids ages 8 to 14. A retailer's
dream, these are the repeat moviegoers who kept ``Titanic'' afloat
for months, snap up CDs by the Backstreet Boys and Ricky Martin,
and spend 300 percent more than their group did a decade ago. A
helpful sidebar explains how parents can cope with mounting
pressures on their Tweens.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More kid stuff: Some Tweens and former Tweens are wildly
successful before their time. In its Next Generation issue, The New
Yorker ($3) profiles 29-year-old Tennessee congressman Harold Ford
Jr., 11-year-old soccer prodigy Vincenzo Sarno, 8-year-old chess
whiz David Howell, 19-year-old golf sensation Sergio Garcia and six
other up-and-comers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Terminator talks: Part of the reason for Tina Brown's
success at Vanity Fair and The New Yorker was her ability to mix
celebrities and politics with culture and gossip in the same
magazine. She's attempting the same formula at Talk ($3.50) with
some degree of success. The November issue features a lengthy cover
story on Arnold Schwarzenegger, in which the action film star hints
at a political future; an assessment of John McCain that praises
him as a man and damns him as a candidate; and a conversation with
Oliver Stone about his new film, ``Any Given Sunday.'' The most
shameless piece of puffery in the magazine is Douglas Brinkley's
profile of Al Gore. Lauding the vice president for his decision to
go to Vietnam, Brinkley attempts to make Gore's stint as a
journalist seem as dangerous as being a helicopter tail-gunner.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  True hominy: Grits, that ubiquitous Southern breakfast staple,
have gone uptown. In a tasty history of grits, Smithsonian ($3)
writer Tim Warren found them served with spicy shrimp and tasso
gravy at elegant restaurants such as Magnolias in Charleston, S.C.
Warren, however, prefers his the old-fashioned way _ mixed with
bits of over-easy eggs and sausage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Influence List: In compiling a list of the most powerful
people in the media, the editors of Brill's Content ($3.95) make an
interesting point: Three decades ago, when there was no CNN and no
Internet, such a list would have included the editors of a few
major newspapers, Time and Newsweek, and perhaps the editor of
Vogue or Cosmopolitan. So who's on the list this year? Not
surprisingly, CNN correspondent Christiane Amanpour, New York Times
executive editor Joseph Lelyveld, and talk-show host Oprah Winfrey
are among the Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His Bradness: No, Brad Pitt is not in drag in the new Rolling
Stone ($3). He's just, well, wearing dresses. It was Pitt's idea to
do the photo shoot as a contrast to his shaved head and
chipped-tooth appearance in his film ``The Fight Club.'' Says
photographer Mark Seliger: ``With Brad, you can't get strange
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
