<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAMSEY12-COX     10-11 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Authorities, media waits for Ramsey grand jury decision
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ The JonBenet Ramsey grand jury reconvenes
today, and with expectations high that a decision could come at any
time, a media storm is blowing into this place.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are scrambling,'' said CNN producer Betty Anderson,
predicting that when the eight women and four more walk into the
Boulder Justice Center today, they will pass through a gauntlet of
more than 100 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   It may or may not happen today, she said, but speculation says
this time will be remembered as ``The Week That Was.''
</P>
<P>
   That thinking is backed by the fact that the grand jury that has
met for over a year on a nearly three-year-old murder, ends its
term Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels are filling up with news crews; reporters who arrived in
town Monday had to find rooms outside the city. The networks have
had crews stationed here for months, but now they've set up
elaborate command centers in the local Marriott Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   NBC-NET is hold up in the top of a bank building. ABC, NBC, FOX
have all been ``wiring'' the place for some time, finding the best
sites for live shots, building sources - all for the murder of one
little blond girl in an otherwise small, quiet hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   The mass popularity and undying attention to the story confounds
many residents of the town. Many want to put the whole thing behind
Boulder, believing it has not portrayed the city in a good, or even
accurate light.
</P>
<P>
   ``JonBenet put Boulder on the map, but it's a sad way to be put
on the map,'' said Julia Wrapp, who works in a small book store on
Pearl Street, a quaint stretch of shops and cafes.
</P>
<P>
   That anxiety may well peak today with a grand jury decision.
Talk around Media Town is that the grand jury may not wait until
the last day to issue its verdict. It can either chose to indict
one or more people, chose not to and issue a report on their probe,
or simply do nothing, say nothing and walk away from the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous, to spend all this time on a story about these
wealthy people,'' said John Putnam, 39, who owns a local car
dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the media has rarely strayed from its coverage of the
JonBenet murder mystery. It has defined a new kind of story that
appeals both to the tabloids as well as the mainstream media. If
the O.J. Simpson story was the first block buster of this kind,
then JonBenet is its steam roller.
</P>
<P>
   The news has sometimes made Boulder look bad. The accusations of
blunders in the cases, as well as the well-publicized infighting
between the police and the District attorneys office, have been
harsh. Meanwhile, the media has noted that since Dec. 26, 1996
murder, the leadership level of the Boulder Police Department has
turned into a black whole. The police chief and several top
investigators on the case have left the department.
</P>
<P>
   The slightest hiccup of news has drawn media out of the Boulder
woodwork. JonBenet has been on scores of tabloid magazine covers,
and four times the story has appeared on the cover of People
magazine. The 6-year-old with the China Doll face and the cascades
of blond curls, a former Miss Colorado, has fueled debates on child
abuse, the controversy over tiny-tot beauty pageants, and the
treatment of the wealthy when they come under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The media attention will flare again today in Boulder, a
community tucked between the Rocky Mountains and the yellow plains
where little grows, between a rock and a hard place.
</P>
<P>
   City officials are bracing for a wave of reporters and satellite
trucks. Even Monday, a holiday when the jury stayed at home, CNN
made sure to have one crew in front of the Justice Center and
another outside the front door, just in case. This morning, the
yellow tape will go up to mark off the parking spots for the grand
jurors and security staff will remind the camera crews to stay at
least 25 feet away from the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's disgusting,'' said longtime Boulder resident Ed
Amarant, 54. ``The media these days. They blow everything out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Schneider writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
