<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SMITH-MINORITIES-ART-     10-11 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-MINORITIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH COLLEGE PRESIDENT'S CRUSADE: MORE MINORITY STUDENTS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Texas, N.H., N.J., Miss.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At Hamilton High School, a grand old building in a
gritty slice of West Los Angeles, Ruth J. Simmons surveyed a
roomful of 35 black and brown female faces and saw her own.
</P>
<P>
   Striding through the Hamilton library, with its posters of Oprah
Winfrey and Whoopi Goldberg announcing ``Reading is Power'' in
Spanish and English, Simmons shook each hand and introduced herself
as the president of Smith College. ``You're the president?'' one
girl asked, incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Jackie Robinson of higher education when she became
the first black woman to head a top-tier college or university in
1995, Simmons has embarked upon what she calls a ``personal
crusade'' to bring more disadvantaged students to her campus and
similar institutions nationwide. The 12th child of a sharecropper
turned factory worker who grew up in a Houston home with neither
books nor desk, Simmons is stepping out of the ivory tower to
recruit personally at vast urban public schools like Hamilton, a
rarity for a college president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in the door, I thought, `This is home,' I
recognized where I was,'' she said of Hamilton, a place with bars
on the windows and where SAT scores average 944 (Smith students'
are typically in the 1200s). ``One of the reasons I talk to
students is because I want them to know a president looks like
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies suggest that graduates of elite universities like
Smith have formed the backbone of the black and Hispanic middle
class, but administrators at such schools have largely hit a wall
in their efforts to lure more minorities. Now, even as the legal
and political attacks on race-based admission have intensified,
leaders of private colleges and universities are seeking innovative
ways to attract not only the most successful minority students but
also those from low-performing schools who lack the traditional
preparation for competitive campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a struggle,'' said Gregory S. Prince Jr., the president
of Hampshire College and the head of a five-college coalition in
Western Massachusetts that includes Smith. ``What you have to do is
find ways to make them aware that you exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the number of African-American and Hispanic students
pursuing higher education has swelled in recent years, their
presence in selective schools has remained flat. At Smith, about 4
percent of the 2,800 undergraduates are black, 4 percent Hispanic,
and 12 percent Asian-American. The faculty is even less racially
mixed, with just seven Asian-Americans, nine African-Americans and
three Hispanics among 244 full-time instructors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are trying, but it just hasn't worked so far,''
said Tory Shelley, 19, a sophomore who is one of two Hamilton High
graduates enrolled at Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Still trying to overcome a reputation as a finishing school for
the future wives of the rich and powerful, Smith, founded in 1871,
faces multiple barriers to recruiting minority students. Many are
put off by the notion of a single-sex school (someone at Hamilton
used the word ``convent''). Tuition, room and board total $30,442
(56 percent of students get financial aid). Its pristine campus is
nestled in Northampton, Mass., a tiny town where black churches _
or hairstylists who know how to care for African-American hair _
are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   So Smith has tried to sell itself to minority applicants with
special campus visits, it has started a scholarship for inner-city
students in Springfield, Mass., and it has admitted a dozen
first-year students with lower-than-normal grades and test scores,
bringing them to campus a month early for extra help. To prime the
pump, it has also established partnerships with the Harlem School
for Girls and with community colleges in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Other top-flight schools are taking similar steps. Princeton
University has replaced student loans with extra grants for
families whose incomes hover below the national average (this year,
$42,000). Hampshire created the James Baldwin scholarships for high
school dropouts who have earned their GED. The former president of
Dartmouth College, James O. Freedman, said he tried to send a
message by giving honorary degrees to prominent black and Hispanic
scholars _ one recent recipient was Ruth Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   At Smith, students and professors say the president's presence
is as effective as any program. The class of 2003 has 32
African-American women, up from about 20 in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't have to be speaking about diversity,'' said
Katrina Gardner, 22, the president of the Smith student government.
``You look at her, and it's like, wow, that's who she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Elisha Smith, a 20-year-old junior from Tupelo, Miss., who is
president of the Black Student Alliance, said it could be
uncomfortable being the only nonwhite person in a class, ``and you
try to answer questions, and people automatically think you're
wrong, or act like they didn't hear you.''
</P>
<P>
   The small cadre of black students often feels pressured to
educate the white majority on issues of race, she said, but many
have sought refuge in Simmons' weekly office hours, and have become
frequent dinner guests in her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is a matter of national interest, a matter of
national salvation,'' Simmons said of her efforts, which include
convening a conference on race this fall and starting a journal,
Meridians, focusing on minority women. ``Bringing poor people from
the margin into the mainstream is what we're best at, what we're
known for.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said she focused on fund-raising and pure academic
programs during her first four years at Smith to win over alumnae
who were quietly skeptical of the prospect of a black president.
She has garnered national attention by establishing the first-ever
engineering program at a women's college, instituting a
curriculum-wide focus ic speaking and providing a paid
internship for every undergraduate. In March, she spoke at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's profile has swelled alongside Simmons', as has its
endowment, to $862 million from $507 million. Now, with her smart
suits and fat Smithie pearls, Simmons skates seamlessly through a
sea of white faces at alumnae events, receiving kudos from
well-coiffed older women and tattooed young feminists alike.
</P>
<P>
   At a reception at the Jonathan Club here, whose wood-paneled
walls are as much an Ivy League atmosphere as Los Angeles has to
offer, a woman from the class of '38 exulted that the college
president back then had a white beard, and ``now we have this
beautiful woman.'' A 1990 graduate said she was thrilled with
Simmons' appointment because she, too, had been a scholarship
student. A member of the class of 1998 embraced her like a favorite
aunt, then proudly said she was working at the Rancho Santiago
Community College District in Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send us some students,'' Simmons replied.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   At Hamilton, where about 60 percent of the 2,850 students pursue
higher education, the vast majority at two-year schools, Simmons
spoke of the glories of a liberal arts education, urging the girls
to seek exotic opportunities rather than staying close to home and
taking classes at a community college.
</P>
<P>
   She told them that when she was their age, she did not see
herself as college material. She acknowledged that she had been
terrified to leave her family when she went to Dillard University
in New Orleans (and later to Harvard).
</P>
<P>
   She told the students they were beautiful, and she begged them
not to be afraid to ask for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize in them what I was as a child,'' she said later.
``Somebody comes along and says to you one day, `Guess what, I see
something in you.' I remember when that happened for me as if it
were yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls, who are enrolled in a program called College
Pathways, which helps students less likely to go to college chart a
course to higher education, responded with a mix of wide-eyed hope
and new confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a colored woman,'' Tia Smith, 15, said simply, ``and I
can relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the bell had rung and the school buses pulled away,
Aleshia Williams remained in the library, pondering her prospects
for attending Smith, a leafy campus 3,000 miles away that she had
not even heard of an hour before.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old sophomore had exchanged phone numbers with the
president and vowed to keep in touch. They were two black women
whose parents never finished high school, one dreaming of becoming
what the other was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going to go to college. I want to go, I want to
make a change,'' Aleshia said. ``Maybe I can be president of a
college one day. Maybe I can take her place.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
