<HEADER>
A3582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDIT-POPULATION-COX     10-11 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-POPULATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crowded world for No. 6 billion
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the 6 billionth inhabitant of planet Earth, born today
according to U.N. estimates, a hearty welcome to our world, and
good luck!
</P>
<P>
   You will need lots of the latter. U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan symbolically picked a baby in Sarajevo to be No. 6 billion,
but you could have just as easily been born in any one of scores of
impoverished nations, since that's where population growth remains
most explosive. That puts you at a disadvantage from Moment One of
your life.
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to be born in Sierra Leone, your life expectancy
will be less than 40 years. If you start life as an Afghan, you
will be vulnerable to disease from a lack of safe drinking water
and sanitation. If you're a girl in Yemen, you probably will get no
schooling. If you're a Bolivian, you're likely to grow up
malnourished. In fact, 3 billion people get less protein in their
daily diet than the average American house cat.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for scarce resources will be keener as you grow up.
Demographers worry that today's billion-plus crop of young people
ages 15-24, the largest of its kind in history, could make past
baby booms pale by comparison, and your group, ages 0-15, is larger
still, numbering 1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   You and your brothers and sisters have to strike a balance with
nature. More and more of you are competing for freshwater supplies
that have remained relatively constant for the last 5,000 years.
Most land that is suitable for farming is under cultivation. All
the world's fisheries are being exploited at or beyond sustainable
levels. Every 20 minutes, another species of plant or animal
becomes extinct.
</P>
<P>
   What's to be done if you and your generation are to have a
chance at a decent life? Today's adults have to make wise
decisions. Make family planning information and materials more
widely available. Invest more in economic development and public
health. Give girls the same chance at education as boys. All of
these are proven methods to promote population stability.
</P>
<P>
   You should know the richest, most powerful country in the world
is frittering away its leadership on this crucial issue because
many in its Congress don't think spending public funds for family
planning overseas is a priority matter. Oh, Congress did pass a
scaled-down $25 million contribution to the U.N. Population Fund
for that purpose, but even that could be lost in end-of-session
maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   Pray, little one, that the world's decision-makers come to
understand the gravity of your plight, and please scoot over a bit
to make way for No. 6,000,000,001.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial originally appeared in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
