<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3588 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CHURCHILL-ROOTS-BOS &LR;      10-11 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHILL-ROOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY QUEST BRINGS A CHURCHILL TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Plimoth in 2nd graf is correct)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH, Mass. _ A British man with a crisp accent, loafers,
khakis, Oxford shirt, and navy crewneck sweater stood questioning a
Wampanoag Indian accessorized with animal skins, bear claw
necklace, and soapstone pipe. The British man fingered the other's
necklace and posed such questions about tribal life as ``how common
is intermarriage?''
</P>
<P>
   Although he appeared to be just another European tourist
strolling blithely through an American historical site Monday,
Winston S. Churchill was on an oddly personal journey when he
peppered Native American staff with questions at Plimoth
Plantation. The grandson of the great prime minister was peering
into dark huts and ship cabins in search of clues to his own family
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Sir Winston Churchill before him, Churchill clings to
an old family belief that the clan has Native American ancestry.
Churchill has also recently concluded that his family tree boasts
three ancestors who sailed on the Mayflower.
</P>
<P>
   Historians cast a skeptical eye on both notions, but Churchill's
quest on ``this side of the pond,'' as he put it, offers insight
into a colorful trans-Atlantic family and the question of how it
produced one of the century's most influential men.
</P>
<P>
   Like his grandfather, the 59-year-old former Conservative Party
member of Parliament has an attachment to the United States that is
both pragmatic and romantic. Sir Winston, who lived from 1874 to
1965, needed American help to fight Nazi Germany. Young Winston, as
the British press still calls him, wants to sell copies of ``The
Great Republic: A History of America,'' his just-published
compilation of the prime minister's writings about America.
</P>
<P>
   The two Churchills have both loved the United States for its
youthful vitality, the spirit that arguably saved the world from
tyranny in World War II. The elder Churchill, historians say,
cherished his American heritage as much as his British blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather would have been enormously proud to think he
had in his veins the blood of those who founded America,''
Churchill said. ``The whole theme of his life was the unity of the
Anglo-American peoples.g as we stand shoulder-to-shoulder
together, there's no trial we can't survive and overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchill scholar Scott Steward suggests that, ultimately, the
Winston who is alive today is seeking to explain Sir Winston's
genius as genetic destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elder Winston Churchill felt he'd gotten a tremendous
boost from the mixture of his American and English ancestry,'' said
Steward, editor of NEXUS, a journal published by the New England
Historic Genealogical Society. ``There was this idea that tired,
old Europe could use a boost from these American heiresses who were
coming over to Europe to produce a new race of stronger, better
Europeans.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchill belongs to a noble line of Englishmen descended from
the first duke of Marlborough, an 18th century war hero. Sir
Winston's mother, the glamorous and beautiful Jennie Jerome, came
not from nobility but from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``On his father's side, Winston Churchill is from a very grand
family, so it's interesting that they are quite enthusiastic about
the American ancestry,'' Steward said. ``The reason has to be that
they are finding in it an explanation for the achievements of
Winston Churchill.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Winston still inspires awe: indefatigable, Cassandra-like in
his warnings to a complacent Britain about the danger posed by the
Nazis, able to unite the free world in wartime with his graceful
words and bold vision.
</P>
<P>
   Was Sir Winston's greatness an accident of birth or just a
function of his time? It is tempting for his family, Steward said,
to believe his mixed-up genes coded for genius, just as
horsebreeders believe that crossing breeds creates a special horse.
</P>
<P>
   The theory ``is a very simple way to lay claim to, if not
destiny, then sense,'' Steward said. ``It's coherent. It's hardly
surprising that there's always a search for meaning and the simpler
and more elegant, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   That Jennie Jerome had Iroquois blood is ``a long and deeply
entrenched family tradition,'' Churchill said Monday. Her mother
and grandmother had dark, exotic features, and the younger
Churchill offers a portrait of Sir Winston's grandmother as
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got red Indian written all over her face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill is ignoring birth records, tombstones, and other
documents that discount the theory, said historian Elizabeth Snell,
author of ``The Churchills: Pioneers and Politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These ideas are romantic, and, I think, politically correct,''
Snell said.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not historically verifiable, she said. ``It's
timely to believe in this Native American connection. What young
Winston is trying to do here, he's trying to make every American
connection there is. Any author would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchill traces his family lineage back to the Mayflower
through Elizabeth Cooke, granddaughter of a Mayflower voyager, who
married Daniel Wilcox, one of Jennie Jerome's ancestors. According
to Snell and Steward, however, Cooke was Wilcox's second wife,
while the Jeromes descend from his first wife.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Jerome-Churchills come to the Mayflower, Snell
said, is probably through an ancestor, Arthur Howland, whose
brother is recorded as a passenger. Howland himself is not known to
have been on board that famous vessel.
</P>
<P>
   It is known when the great prime minister himself first crossed
the Atlantic. It was 1895, and a 21-year-old Churchill developed an
instant admiration for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great, crude, strong, young people are the Americans, like a
boisterous healthy boy among enervated but well-bred ladies and
gentlemen,'' he wrote in a letter, according to William
Manchester's biography, ``The Last Lion.'' ``What an extraordinary
people the Americans are! . . . They make you feel at home and at
ease in a way that I have never before experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Winston shares his grandfather's enthusiasm,
remarking in his memoirs, ``It is one of the nicest qualities of an
American, that he is easy to make friends with.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his grandfather, the younger Churchill has been a
journalist, writer, and politician. He served as a Tory member of
Parliament from 1970 to 1997, though he never achieved high office.
Both had to contend with famous, if remote, parents. Young
Winston's were Randolph Churchill, a tempestuous alcoholic, and
Pamela Harriman, former US ambassador to France.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill, by all accounts, lacks his grandfather's spark of
genius. Politically, he is best known for embarrassing his party in
1993 when he called for a halt to ``the relentless flow of
immigrants to this country'' and contended, erroneously, that some
British cities had a minority population greater than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his concerns about immigration, Winston S. Churchill
believes, like his grandfather, that America can only enrich his
own country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, President John F. Kennedy awarded Sir Winston Churchill
the rare distinction of an honorary American citizenship. In reply,
Churchill wrote of his great satisfaction with ``the interwoven and
upward progress of our peoples,'' even ``in this century of storm
and tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We stood together,'' Churchill continued, ``and because of
that fact the free world now stands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
