<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ADVANCE-CO     10-11 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let the banter begin! Braves, Mets talk it up
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been three years since the Braves had their
hearts stomped on in New York City. They surrendered the World
Series to the Yankees in 1996 after taking a 2-0 lead as commanding
as they come.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't been back to the World Series since. And they won't
this time, if this other team from New York fresh from the point of
no return has anything to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets blaze into town for the start of the National League
Championship series tonight on the momentum of their wild-card
revival and the bravado of their manager.
</P>
<P>
   The latest from Bobby Valentine is that the Braves haven't shown
the Mets the proper respect.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox, for one, considers Valentine's
contention to be ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a joke, the lack-of-respect angle,'' Cox said. ``Of
course they are a great team. Of course they've got our respect.
They're good guys. I like them _ I don't post anything on our
board. You either come to play baseball or you come to talk. And
you better come to play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have done that against the Mets all season, winning
nine of the 12 meetings. By beating them in five of six games in
the final 10 days of the season, the Braves broke open an otherwise
tight NL East race and left the Mets scrambling for a wild-card
berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets came back from two games down with three to play in the
season by sweeping the Pirates. Then they beat the Reds in a
one-game playoff and took the Arizona Diamondbacks in the Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   They're back.
</P>
<P>
   But so are the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   They have made eight consecutive trips to the National League
Championship Series. They have met seven different teams there.
Asked what they had learned from back-to-back NLCS losses to the
Marlins and the Padres, Chipper Jones responded, ``It (stinks) to
lose that early.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been hearing a lot from the Mets' fans, who have been
blistering him with off-color language every trip to the plate.
They had grown to hate Jones those three days in Atlanta when he
homered four times during the Braves' sweep to nearly ended the
Mets' division title hopes single-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of Shea Stadium after the Braves won two out of
three in New York a week later, Jones shot some parting words back
at the Mets fans. He suggested that they go home and put on their
Yankees gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a very mature statement,'' Valentine said
sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more of a shot at the fans than it was their ball
club,'' Jones said. ``Bobby can turn it around any way he wants.
The last thing I want is to get in a newspaper-reading war with
Bobby Valentine.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's what Valentine is looking for, maybe he's going after
the wrong guy. Young Braves closer John Rocker already had some
words he thought were said privately _ that he hated the Mets _ run
across the top of a New York tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in a news conference Monday about his thoughts on the
Mets, Rocker said: ``There are a few. Which ones I should voice,
I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   So he began politically with talk of the seven .300 hitters in
the Mets lineup. Then he covered their overall talent, how he
thought it was superior to the Braves and how he was surprised the
Mets had to squeak into the playoffs. And then it seeped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat them nine out of 12 games,'' Rocker said. ``I don't
see how Valentine can say a word.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rocker had something to say about respect as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of respect for the Mets,'' Rocker said. ``All
the games were hard fought games, 2-1, 3-2. I think just as we have
respect for them, I don't think Bobby Valentine has much respect
for us. You may not like us, you might think you can beat us, but
at least have respect for the other team. I don't see that kind of
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in all of the talking are the usual October questions for
the Braves about pressure, about going to eight National League
Championship Series in a row and winning only one World Series
ring. Ironically, it might be just the mental diversion the Braves
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel any pressure,'' Jones said. ``The way I see it,
we've been playing the role of underdogs all year, since all the
injuries came up. People expect us to be here, but they don't
expect us to win. So we'll go out, play hard, keep our mouths shut
and play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
