<HEADLINE>
WALKING TOURS OF BERLIN  
 RENTING A WARDROBE TRUNK  
 QUANTAS OF MADEIRA  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: (AT) should be replaced with the symbol) 
(af) 
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I expect to be in Berlin this fall and would like to find a
walking tour that focuses on architecture. It could be in a group
or self guided, but must be in English. _ Marjory A. Simon, Rye
Brook, N.Y. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  A: There are at least a couple of ways to get a tour of the
architecture of Berlin, where building has been booming since the
nation's reunification and the city's designation as the new German
capital.
</P>
<P>
   One way to see much of this change is with Berlin Walks, a
company run by an expatriate Briton, Nick Gay. He uses a team of
seven guides, he said, all of whom are native English speakers who
have been living in Berlin for some time. Berlin Walks offers four
regular tours, and Gay said the one that would probably best suit
you is ``Discover Berlin.''  &UR;  &LR;  This three-hour tour visits sites of
historical importance, Gay said, but it also takes note of new
development. Among the stops are the New Synagogue, the TV tower on
Alexanderplatz, Museum Island, Unter den Linden, the War Memorial,
the Brandenburg Gate, the Reichstag, the Wall and the Museum at
Checkpoint Charlie. The tour takes public trains twice and covers
about two and a half miles on foot, Gay said.
</P>
<P>
   This tour is offered daily at 10 a.m. and, from April through
October, again at 2:30 p.m. It leaves from the taxi stand at the
Zoo Station; look for the sign over the taxi stand and the guides
wearing Berlin Walks badges. The cost is $10, or $7.75 for ages 25
and under, at the rate of 1.8 marks to the dollar. The train
tickets _ about $2.15 _ can be bought from the guide. Reservations
are not needed.
</P>
<P>
   The other standard tours offered by Berlin Walks are ``Infamous
Third Reich Sites,'' ``Jewish Life in Berlin'' and ``Discover
Potsdam.'' The company also will put together custom tours, on foot
or by car. Contact Gay at (49-30) 301-0104 or at
berlinwalks(AT)berlin.de.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is a customized tour by Culture Trip, which
designs tours and outings, mainly for museum or university groups,
primarily from the United States. Virginia G. Shulte, a former New
Yorker who runs Culture Trip, said she uses specialists in the
pertinent subjects, not traditional guides. She could arrange to
hire an architect to lead a small group or an individual on an
architectural tour of the city. The cost is $135 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Culture Trip at 56 Mommsenstrasse, 10629 Berlin,
Germany; (49-30) 305-3890, fax (49-30) 345-1596. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a company on Long Island that rents cruise wardrobes
and delivers them to the ship? _ Susan Niego, Nesconset, N.Y. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: A company that has provided this service for years is Liberty
Moving and Storage, 17 Central Ave., Hauppauge, N.Y. 11788.
</P>
<P>
   According to Christina Squicciarini, a spokeswoman for Liberty,
the company can deliver what is properly called a wardrobe trunk _
essentially a portable closet and chest of drawers _ to your home
and pick it up locked after you have packed. It will be delivered
directly to the ship so you can board without most (or any) of your
luggage in tow. When you return, the company will return it to your
home and pick it up after you unpack.
</P>
<P>
   The fee for this service depends on the length of the cruise,
Ms. Squicciarini said, but it is generally $300 to $500. She
suggested reserving a wardrobe at least two weeks ahead of sailing.
To do so, call Liberty at (516) 234-3000 or (212) 223-6440. Ask for
Mary Zuliani, extension 232. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are planning a trip to Madeira and are looking for
recommendations for moderate nonchain hotels in Funchal. Also how
can we find out about tours of wineries? _ Susan Gish,
Philadelphia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: The island of Madeira is known for wine, but tourism is the
major industry of this popular vacation destination. So there are
no shortage of hotels on the island, especially in the capital,
Funchal, but most of them are conventional chainlike
establishments, travel agents acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   A comfortable yet more authentic Madeiran experience is probably
best found at one of several quintas _ former manor estates _
according to Maria Joao Ramires, a spokeswoman for the Portuguese
National Tourist Office in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best known is the Quinta da Bela Vista, about two
miles west of downtown Funchal. It has 67 rooms and suites in three
buildings set amid 37 acres of gardens; some have sea views, and
all are individually decorated with antiques. There is a pool and a
restaurant. Rates, which include full breakfast and tax, range from
$170 to $225, at 185 escudos to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The quinta is represented in the United States by Marketing
Ahead, 433 Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y 10016, (800) 223-1356, and
Pinto Basto Tours, 24 South Main Street, New City, N.Y. 10956,
(800) 526-8539.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto Basto also represents the Penha da Franca, a quinta within
easy walking distance of downtown Funchal, according to Margaret
McGlade, the agency's manager. This inn has 40 rooms costing $80 to
$160, depending on size and season (high season starts around the
end of November), including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms are in small Madeiran-style two- and three-story
houses, with red tile roofs and green shutters, set amid lawns and
gardens. They are individually decorated and have a variety of
views. There is a heated pool.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is a bed-and-breakfast like Quintinha Dalia, 54
Rua dos Ilheus, 9000 Funchal, Madeira. About a mile from the city
center, it offers six rooms with private baths, a terrace and
garden, a sitting room with TV and free parking. The house is
behind Quinta Magnolia, now a school with public recreation
facilities, including jogging paths, squash and tennis courts and a
large pool. Rates are $38 to $65 a night; reservations and
information from (351-91) 774-844 or at www.madeira-island.com
(which includes photos).
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Ramires, all the wine houses on the island _
including four in Funchal _ have regular visiting hours, and you
don't have to visit in a large tour group. You can obtain
inforon these at hotels, or contact the Instituto do Vinho
da Madeira, 78 Rua de 5 Outobro, 9000 Funchal, Madeira; (351-91)
204-600, fax (351-91) 228-685.
</P>
<P>
   Booklets listing hotels and wine houses and other information
about Madeira are available from the Portuguese National Tourist
Office, 300 Fifth Ave., New York, N.Y. 10036; (800) 767-8842, fax
(212) 764-6137.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
