<HEADLINE>
`THE STRIP' TAKES US TO `VEGA$,' BUT WE'VE BEEN THERE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, mouthbreathers. For the scoop on ``The Strip,'' have someone
read Tuesday night's punchlist to you.
</P>
<P>
   _Fiery explosions: 2
</P>
<P>
   _Fistfights: 2
</P>
<P>
   _Gunfights: 2
</P>
<P>
   _Women in peril in T-shirts: 1
</P>
<P>
   _Women in thong bikinis: 3
</P>
<P>
   With expensive production and cool (read: barely intelligible)
movie-style dialogue, ``The Strip'' is UPN's latest attempt to
attract males who aren't likely to be watching ``Party of Five,''
``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' or ``Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   To do it, the network got filmmaker Joel Silver (``The Matrix,''
``Lethal Weapon'') to produce this slick homage to ``Vega$,''
featuring a pair of wisecracking cops name Elvis and Jesse (Sean
Patrick Flanery and Guy Torry), who trade in their badges to work
as outside security men for a casino owner. The plot is standard
private-eye genre, the stunts nothing we haven't seen before, and
the women are lacking the usual amount of apparel and meaningful
lines. The saving grace ``The Strip'' is high-gloss production, but
a ``Baywatch'' made by a pro is still a ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Strip. Hourlong drama series about two former police
officers who leave the force to work as security guards for a
wealthy casino owner. Starring Sean Patrick Flanery, Guy Torry and
Cameron Greene. Series premiere Tuesday on UPN. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+ (for mouthbreathers)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C- (for everyone else)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
