<HEADER>
A3601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-KEYS-COX     10-11 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-KEYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keys for the Braves to win
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. No Micro-Chip this time.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Chipper Jones could match his mid-September madness
here, when he hit four home runs in a three-game sweep of the Mets.
But with the resurgent Brian Jordan back hitting cleanup, Jones
must carry another big stick and talk, well, softly.
</P>
<P>
   2. On his Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker was dominant against Houston, escaping that no-out,
bases-loaded jam in Game 3 and saving Game 4. He must keep
dominating and, with help from his fellow relievers, offset one of
the Mets' strengths, their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   3. Rotate this.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a decided edge in their starting rotation. Use
it. You make the call: Maddux-Millwood-Glavine-Smoltz or
Yoshii-Leiter-Reed-Rogers?
</P>
<P>
   4. Get to the heart of the matter. Again.
</P>
<P>
   In winning five of six from the Mets last month, Atlanta cut out
three of the four chambers of the heart of the Mets lineup. Edgardo
Alfonzo was 4-for-25 (.160), John Olerud 3-for-26 (.115) and Robin
Ventura 4-for-23 (.174), a combined 11-for-74 (.149). And cleanup
man Mike Piazza (7-for-23, .304) is still nursing a sore thumb.
</P>
<P>
   5. First things first
</P>
<P>
   Win tonight. Since the Braves lost the NL Championship Series
opener in 1991, every Game 1 winner since '92 has gone on to win
the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
