<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY INTO SUHARTO CORRUPTION IS HALTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA _ Indonesia's acting attorney general announced Monday
that he was halting a yearlong investigation into alleged
corruption by former president Suharto, saying there was not enough
evidence to prosecute the longtime autocrat whose wealth is
estimated in the billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is likely to undermine the credibility of Suharto's
successor, B.J. Habibie, as a reformer, just nine days before
Indonesia's National Assembly decides whether to retain Habibie as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's move to shelve the investigation into alleged misuse of
public monies by two Suharto-run charitites outraged many
Indonesians who had raised a rallying cry last year against 32
years of ``corruption, cronyism, and nepotism,'' sparking riots
that forced Asia's longest-serving leader from power.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie, Suharto's vice president and protege, had vowed to
stamp out corruption and promised to spare no one. Suharto's
fortune dwarfed his $1,764-a-month presidential salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people forget that this government is really an
extension of the previous regime,'' said political commentator
Wimar Witoelar. Prosecuting Suharto would be ``like a snake trying
to eat its tail. . . . Habibie has paid lip service to popular
demands (for justice), but it's been a stalling game.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's reputation has already suffered from a banking scandal
that implicates him and his party in siphoning funds for campaign
use and from the crisis in East Timor _ two issues, along with the
Suharto probe, that he will have to address in his accountability
speech before parliament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the ruling Golkar Party is expected to announce
whether it will continue to back the beleaguered Habibie for
presidnext week's race, and the Suharto decision will hurt
his standing among party reformers, said Marzuki Darusman, deputy
chairman of Golkar and leader of the anti-Habibie faction.
</P>
<P>
   The unpopular decision could also spark public unrest and
possible violence in the lead-up to the volatile race for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the nail in the coffin for Habibie,'' predicted
Jusuf Wanandi, chairman of the Jakarta-based Center for Strategic
and International Studies. ``By doing this a few days before his
accountability speech, he is waving a red flag in front of students
and other protesters. They're going to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrevian, a 37-year-old driver who like many Indonesians uses
only one name, said he was disappointed and surprised by the
decision, ``because we had 32 years of Suharto and many of us know
he is very corrupt. Indonesian people want Suharto and his family
in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrevian echoed the popular view that Suharto bought his way
out of prosecution, but even Suharto's political opponents
acknowledge they have no evidence to support that accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Former General Suharto, 78, and his six children were estimated
last year to have amassed $30 billion in assets across some 260
companies, much of which was allegedly acquired through kickbacks
and sweetheart deals. Suharto _ who recently suffered a stroke,
bringing to a halt his questioning by investigators _ has denied
any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Wanandi said the investigation made a mockery of public demands
for accountability. ``You cannot go over the evidence for 15 months
and then interrogate him for a couple of days and then he becomes
sick and it's over. In 15 months, they've had time to conceal
everything and take their money abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanandi asserted the investigation by the Habibie government _
which includes many former Suharto loyalists _ was ``half-hearted,
because Suharto said, `If you do it to me, I'll do it to you.'
They're all in this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's lawyer Monday praised the recommendation to drop
charges, saying the charges were politically motivated. ``The case
of former President Suharto has more of a political nuance than the
legal aspects,'' Juan Felix Tampubolon said in a television
interview.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the investigation was a scheme that required
state-owned banks to donate 5 percent of profits to charities
linked to Suharto. Acting Attorney General Ismudjoko said his
investigation uncovered irregularities, but no evidence that
Suharto had broken the law to enrich himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ismudjoko said investigators found the charities had lent money
to commercial enterprises, but that the money was ultimately
returned to the charities. Suharto critics say the funds were
tapped by Suharto's children as free lines of credit to fund their
commercial empires.
</P>
<P>
   The government did not declare Suharto completely innocent,
however, saying that if corruption exists in other cases, the
public should come forward with proof. Witoelar called this a
hypocritical strategy by the Habibie regime to ``cover themselves''
from criticism that they are protecting Suharto's family.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's children are estimated to be worth hundreds of
millions of dollars each, though many of their assets are being
held by the national debt restructuring agency for non-payment of
debts. The only criminal proceedings launched so far are against
Suharto's youngest son, Tommy Hutomo Mandala Putra.
</P>
<P>
   A verdict on a multimillion dollar land deal that the
prosecution alleges cost the government $10.8 million could be
issued as early as this week. If found guilty, Suharto's son could
be imprisoned for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ismudjoko said the results of a separate investigation into a
controversial national car project that exempted Suharto's youngest
son from taxes would be announced by another minister, but he did
not say when.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, police questioned two senior ministers over the PT
Bank Bali scandal, in which the bank paid a $77 million fee to a
firm run by a senior ruling party official _ money that opponents
charge was funnelled into Habibie's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank have delayed
critically-needed bailout loans to Indonesia until the issue is
resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0337 </DOCNO>
