<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dream team: Gordon crew two-for-two
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Jeff Gordon was rewarded with a lifetime
contract last week. Maybe Hendrick Motorsports should do the same
for the No. 24 team's new crew chief, Brian Whitesell.
</P>
<P>
   The tandem has been together for two races and has won both.
Gordon took the checkered flag at Monday's UAW-GM Quality 500 to
become the first driver to post back-to-back victories this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are really supporting Brian, they're supporting me
and they're supporting one another,'' Gordon said. ``The chemistry
is there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really should consider retiring now,'' joked Whitesell, who
is 2-0 after taking over for long-time crew chief Ray Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon leads all drivers with seven victories, and moved from
fourth to sixth in the Winston Cup points standings after Monday's
race, which was postponed on Sunday because of rainy weather.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte finished second and gained 29 points on Dale
Jarrett, who now leads the points standings by 222 with five races
remaining. Mike Skinner was third, tying his career-best finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray helped built that organization to where it's at and
(Whitesell) obviously got a great team,'' Labonte said. ``I think
to carry on like they have really isn't surprising in (a) way.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dale Earnhardt, ``Ray must've forgotten his notebook (when
he left Hendrick). That 24 team looked really good today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's win was not in his usual dominating fashion. He
struggled in qualifying, and was forced to start in the 22nd
position, which later helped Gordon tied an event record for
rallying up from the most spots to win.
</P>
<P>
   For most of race, Gordon simply hung around the top of the pack.
He patiently waited for his opportunity to pass Labonte, and saw it
with eight laps remaining. Gordon ended up leading only 16 of 334
laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an amazing week,'' Gordon said. ``There were times
we were great in practice and there were times we were horrible.
When we were at or worse, I was still having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was enjoying it more than I ever had before just because I
felt like I'm more part of this team today than I have ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   By guiding Gordon to victories at Martinsville and Charlotte,
Whitesell has become the sport's newest celebrity. He signed a
three-year contract with Hendrick about a month before his
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm breaking even becamuch pressure as it
(victories) takes off, it puts it right back on,'' Whitesell said.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome allowed owner Rick Hendrick and Gordon to be
reunited in victory lane for the first time since the '96 season.
Hendrick, who has been battling with luekemia for three years, has
attended only two races this season.
</P>
<P>
   TOP 5
</P>
<P>
   1. Jeff Gordon, Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bobby Labonte, Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mike Skinner, Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   4. Mark Martin, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   5. Ward Burton, Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
