<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BASEBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MIDEAST, 2 RED SOX FANS KEEP THE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ David Forman and Nadim Khoury are among the
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Forman, a rabbi born in Belmont, Mass., and Khoury, a
Palestinian brewer of beer who lived in Brookline, Mass., count
themselves part of a community of believers who see Fenway Park as
a holy place and who believe in the Red Sox' promise of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   They may come from different religions and opposing sides of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, but they both proclaim allegiance to
Red Sox Nation. And they are part of its diaspora _ countless
thousands worldwide with connections to Boston who understand the
longing and the suffering that comes with another autumn and
another shot at the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, these two men found themselves in the predawn
darkness following the game on the World Wide Web, hoping that this
year might be different.
</P>
<P>
   Forman, a 55-year-old pillar of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations and a founder of the group Rabbis for Peace, was born
into the Fenway tribe. He grew up in Belmont and remembers the
first game he attended, in 1950, when he sat in the bleachers and
watched in awe the signature swing of Ted Williams and the pitching
of Mel Parnell. He is now an ``orthodox Red Sox fan'' and a
``Reform rabbi'' who immigrated to Israel in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that time of year again,'' said Forman. ``I can feel it.
The tension is rising, the nervousness. Through it all, you keep
the faith somehow. I guess that is what defines being a Red Sox
fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Khoury, the 40-year-old Christian Palestinian owner and general
manager of Taybeh Brewing Co., became a Sox fan, like many others,
as a college student. In 1979, he moved from the West Bank to
Brookline to take business courses at Boston University and to work
at Foley's Liquors, a store owned by his family that sits in the
Whiskey Point section of Brookline, within sight of the Fenway Park
light towers. Waves of Fenway faithful would sweep down the streets
on their way to the games, and soon he was caught up in a tidal
pull toward the great American game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand it for a long time. But then you get it,
and it makes its way into your soul,'' said Khoury. ``We were
fairly warned about what we were in for as Red Sox fans. But for
us, the Red Sox were about more than baseball. They are our
connection to Boston, and because of that very important to our
family.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges as a fan living in the Middle East is
keeping up on the games in a region where ESPN is harder to find
than water in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Since Forman came in 1972, he has tried desparately to stay
abreast of the scores and the standings. Through the 1970s and
1980s, he got his baseball news from the International Herald
Tribune, which publishes scores a day late. Sometimes he'd call his
brother in Framingham for updates. He said there were many
occasions late at night when he would resort to calling directory
assistance in Boston and asking operators if they had the game on.
The arrival of CNN changed that. And now he even finds himself
surfing various Web sites for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Khoury returned to his hometown in the West Bank in 1994 after
the signing of the historic Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement and
founded a very successful brewery. His 8-year-old, Brookline-born
son has inherited a passion for the Red Sox that he shares with a
group of cousins from the family's village of Taybeh. Their rooms
are covered with Red Sox banners and memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Forman and Khoury don't know each other. But they share a common
language and a family of patriarchs with names like Williams,
Yastrzemski, and Martinez. They measure history in a timetable
marked by 1967, 1975, and 1986. They share a hope in the future.
And both see in the Red Sox a reflection of their ethnic
identities.
</P>
<P>
   Forman discusses the Red Sox in terms of his Jewish faith and
the ``olam haba,'' which is Hebrew for ``the world to come.'' He is
painfully aware that the idea of Red Sox victory in the World
Series anytime soon is a wish not grounded in reality. As a rabbi
and Talmudic scholar, he said, ``There is too much reality with the
Red Sox to believe that it will come in this world. But I hope for
another place, a transcendent place where a World Series title
could happen. And that belief has to sustain us.''
</P>
<P>
   Khoury compares the resiliency of Red Sox fans to that of the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox story is like the Palestinian story,'' said
Khoury. ``It is taking too long, and there are a lot of
frustrations along the way. But the point is to keep trying, to
never give up. And then it will come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Insh'allah,'' he said in Arabic. ``God willing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2023EDT &QL; 
