<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DUKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gimmick leads to win for Duke to build upon
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The play that's making all the highlight shows allowed
Duke coach Carl Franks to get his first career victory after four
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 17-10 with time running out against Virginia on
Saturday, the Blue Devils were at the Cavaliers' 9. The call was
for tailback Letavious Wilks to pitch to receiver Scottie
Montgomery, who would pass to quarterback Spencer Romine.
</P>
<P>
   Got that? The Blue Devils didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Wilks was hit and fumbled, but the ball bounced to Montgomery,
who threw a desperation pass across the field that Richmond Flowers
grabbed for a touchdown with six seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After Duke scored a touchdown in the second overtime, Virginia
had one nullified when the officials ruled the receiver caught the
ball out of bounds. TV replays appeared to show otherwise. The Blue
Devils improbably won 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We screwed up every way we could,'' Franks said. ``But I guess
four wrongs makes a right.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the wrongs mattered to Franks on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``An exciting win for our team,'' said Franks, a former Duke
player and assistant. He was Florida's offensive coordinator for
Steve Spurrier the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was very excited in the locker room,'' he said.
``Now we need to make sure we continue to build upon that just like
we had talked about building from the second half of the Florida
State game.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks arrived in Durham to inherit a program that returned 20
starters, including both kickers. But the Blue Devils were 4-7 in
Fred Goldsmith's last year as coach, after seasons of 2-9 and 0-11.
</P>
<P>
   Having been groomed under Spurrier, first at Duke and then at
Florida, Franks brought all the nuances of the Gators' ``Fun `n'
Gun'' fancy passing attack with him to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for him, the Duke players spent their Goldsmith
years running the ball more than throwing it.
</P>
<P>
   The transition was hampered by a first-game shoulder injury to
Romine, who missed three games before the breakthrough at Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really played a lot better than I expected,'' Franks said.
Romine completed 16 of 35 passes for 246 yards, two interceptions
and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what his confidence level would be, how well he
would be able to make audibles, but he changed plays very well,''
Franks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gutsy guy. He took some shots. I think now he'll
continue to get better. Hopefully, we can keep him healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2023EDT &QL; 
