<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARTHA-STEWART-ART-2N     10-11 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHA-STEWART-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: previous season.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the prospectus, Ms. Stewart plans to focus on
building her burgeoning but still unprofitable Internet business,
with guidance from Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, the Silicon
Valley venture capital firm, which has a 5 percent stake in Ms.
Stewart's company. Together, merchandising _ through Kmart and
other outlets including her ``Martha by Mail'' catalog _ and online
commerce accounted for 22.5 percent of the company's six-month
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, she got a salary and bonus of slightly less than
$4.7 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Her company is taking no chances that she will suddenly decide
on a life of quiet contemplation in the Maine woods: employment and
licensing agreements give the company the exclusive right to use
her image and services, and even her private residences, for as
long she is associated with the business.
</P>
<P>
   Her new employment contract guarantees her a salary and bonus of
at least $1.2 million. The company will also pay her $2 million a
year for the use of her colonial estate in Westport, Conn. and her
two vacation homes: one in East Hampton, one on the coast of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Stewart's most crucial role in the new public company
will be as controlling stockholder. After the offering, the Martha
Stewart Family Limited Partnership _ Ms. Stewart is the only
partner listed in the prospectus _ will control 96 percent of the
company's voting stock.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, this famously attentive _ some say ``controlling'' _
entrepreneur will be able to determine the outcome of any matter
that comes before shareholders, from takeover bids to the selection
of the company's accountants. Even the stock certificate is being
designed in-house, one of her advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   Her control is rooted in the two-class stock structure her
underwriters and lawyers designed for her.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to sell 7.2 million to 8.28 million shares of
class A common stock to the public. It will distribute an
additional 7.1 million class A shares to the company's current
investors. Besides Ms. Stewart, those investors include Time
Warner's Time Publishing Ventures unit, which acquired its stake as
part of the agreement that gave Ms. Stewart control of her domain
in 1997. Of the $91.7 million Ms. Stewart hopes to raise with the
stock offering, she hopes to use $41.7 million to buy out Time's
remaining stake.
</P>
<P>
   But the company will also issue roughly 34.1 million class B
shares, each of which can cast 10 votes, compared with a single
vote for each class A share, and all of which will be owned by Ms.
Stewart's family partnership.
</P>
<P>
   If the initial offering fetches the estimated $13 to $15 a
share, as the underwriters expect, the company would have a value
of about $680 million and Ms. Stewart's partnership would control
stock theoretically worth more than $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   Given the company's current dependence on Ms. Stewart, however,
those millions may be ephemeral: the moment she tried to sell any
substantial part of her shares, they would plunge in value in
response to fears of life without Martha.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that risk, several experts said, Ms. Stewart has the
biggest stake in reducing her dominance at the company.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, she has some strong directors who could make sure she
yields a bit of the limelight: L. John Doerr, a partner with
Kleiner Perkins; Charlotte L. Beers, the chairwoman of J. Walter
Thompson Worldwide and chairwoman emeritus of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
Worldwide; and Naomi O. Seligman, a co-founder of the Research
Board, a prominent information technology research group.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Stewart herself must be an active and willing
participant in the effort to confer stardom on her potential
successors, warned Mark Rubin of the Metropolitan Group, a
consulting firm in Leonia, N.J., that specializes in closely held
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got some very talented people in that company,'' Rubin
said. ``What is key is having her participate in developing the
succession, or there could be a backlash or resistance to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, of Lippincott &AMP; Margulies, said Ms. Stewart was on her
way to becoming a brand, rather than a person: ``If she's not all
the way there, she is still more than just an individual _ she has
come to represent a way of life, a specific vision, a level taste.
The question is, how well can that be institutionalized?''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``That's a very fair question _ and I'm not sure I
would be rushing to be the first investor to find out the answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
