<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-BIO-CATEGORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN BOOK ENTERS LISTS AS NONFICTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Dutch,'' the biography of Ronald Reagan whose
author, Edmund Morris, inserts a fictional version of himself in
the narrative, jumped onto the best-seller lists last eekend _ in
the nonfiction category.
</P>
<P>
   And, although there was little debate over how to classify the
work, its unusual and heavily debated blending of fact and fiction
did make some book review editors pause before including it in the
nonfiction category.
</P>
<P>
   Charles McGrath, the editor of The New York Times Book Review,
said the Morris biography would make its debut at No. 2 on the list
Sunday. ``No matter what you did people would complain,'' he said.
``It is a big can of worms. There have been other things on the
nonfiction list that have been, in retrospect, as least as
fictional as this.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' by John
Berendt, who has said that he simply ``rounded the corners'' in
inventing dialogue and stretching the facts surrounding a murder in
Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said that in the best-seller list, the customary
one-line description is used to flag the fact-versus-fiction
controversy surrounding ``Dutch.'' The line reads, ``The authorized
biography of Ronald Reagan, bedecked with fictional passages.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times' book review, where ``Dutch'' also ranks
No. 2 on the nonfiction list, chose a similar approach, using a
one-line description that reads, ``This long-anticipated official
biography of President Reagan features a fictionalized narrator.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wasserman, the book editor at the Los Angeles newspaper,
said: ``It does disturb that the boundaries between the realm of
the fact and the republic of the nonfact are increasingly blurred.
For much of the public, this may be a distinction without a
difference.'' But, he added, for journalists, they matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dutch'' was also classified as nonfiction on Amazon.com's
list, where it ranked No. 1. The book is published by Random House,
a division of Bertelsmann AG.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
