<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3617 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-11 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MY BOY SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My favorite Ronald Reagan story involves the false Lassie. Once
when he was president, Reagan invited the White House press corps
to his ranch in California. One of the reporters noticed the family
collie and, in an effort to make conversation, asked what the dog's
name was.
</P>
<P>
   After an almost imperceptible pause, the president smiled and
said ``Lassie.'' Later an aide on the press plane explained that
Reagan had, as they say, misspoken. He didn't remember his dog's
name, and had simply come up with something that sounded
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   There are all sorts of ways you can interpret this anecdote _ as
a hint of the Alzheimer's disease that was to come, or an example
of Reagan's tendency to recast reality with characters from
Hollywood movies. I suspect, though, the real moral was simple. The
president didn't care enough about the dog to bother to learn its
name. If he returned to the ranch one weekend and found an Irish
setter waiting for him at the gate, he would probably never have
noticed the switch.
</P>
<P>
   This easygoing indifference to the world around him extended
beyond the animal kingdom. Reagan had trouble identifying his
children too. His son Michael once recounted a blood-curdling story
of his boarding school graduation, at which his father failed to
recognize him and genially stuck out his hand and introduced
himself. When Maureen Reagan discovered that her 7-year-old
half-sister, Patti, had not been told they were siblings, Reagan
hedged: ``Well, we just haven't gotten that far yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend both Patti and her brother, Ron, went public with
their defenses of Edmund Morris' controversial biography of their
father. Patti, writing in The Washington Post, said it was a relief
to read that Reagan had not shut just her out of his inner life,
but also the entire universe. Ron told ``60 Minutes'' that his
father treated ``everybody the same way,'' whether you happened to
be his gardener or his child.
</P>
<P>
   In middle age, the Reagan offspring are still the walking
wounded, yearning for an emotional acknowledgment they're doomed
never to receive. Ron Reagan laughed nervously, in a stab at
easygoing indifference, as he explained that he could tell Reagan
had himself written that letter to the nation announcing that he
had Alzheimer's, ``because there's no mention of his children.''
(Actually, the former president offered a generic reference to
``family.'')
</P>
<P>
   As a group, presidents have never been particularly successful
at parenting _too busy, maybe, or too large. John Quincy Adams,
whose children called him ``The Iron Mask,'' raised a couple of
suicidal alcoholics, but so did the hyper-attentive Theodore
Roosevelt. On the other hand Bill Clinton, who has set records for
unsatisfactory private performance as president, seems to have done
a great job with Chelsea. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it's strange to be listening to the Reagan
children bare their wounds while so many Republican presidential
candidates who wrap themselves in the Reagan mantle are sniping at
the opposition for less-than-pristine personal behavior. ``People
love Ronald Reagan because he was a strong family man with Nancy,''
said Charles Jarvis, who deserted the Gary Bauer campaign for Steve
Forbes because Bauer had been having unchaperoned meetings with a
young female aide.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that no American voter, even those of the Christian
right, actually picks a candidate according to private conduct.
Most of them understand that they're lucky to find a candidate
whose policies they agree with, let alone someone whose behavior
they'd want to emulate. ``It would be different if they discovered
somebody had committed murder,'' said Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia, the
twice-divorced champion of the Defense of Marriage Act. Barr, who
once licked whipped cream off two women's breasts at a charity
fund-raiser, has good reason to set the bar somewhere around
homicide.
</P>
<P>
   If social conservatives actually tried to choose candidates by
the state of their souls, Jimmy Carter, that born-again family man,
would have had two terms. Ronald Reagan, the divorced
non-churchgoer and remote parent, might, as his son suggested over
the weekend in a different context, have ended his career as the
host of ``Unsolved Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
