<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-TREATY13-1STL     10-11 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TREATY13-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ASKS SENATE TO PULL NUCLEAR TREATY
 &HT;    Eds: New throughout with Helms reaction.
 &HT;    710&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Senate Republicans girded for
a high-stakes showdown Tuesday over the fate of an international
treaty banning nuclear weapons tests.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to Republican demands, Clinton formally asked Monday that
the treaty be withdrawn from a scheduled Tuesday vote in the
Senate, aiming to salvage the accord from certain defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proceeding to a vote under these circumstances,'' Clinton
wrote in a letter to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
``would severely harm the national security of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plea was immediately rejected, though, by one of the
treaty's most powerful opponents. Senate Foreign Relations
Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said he would block any
effort to delay the Senate vote unless Clinton gives up entirely on
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
   ``His letter, while a step in the right direction, was still
insufficient to avert a vote on the CTBT tomorrow,'' Helms said in
a statement late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be made clear that this CTBT is dead and that the next
president will not be bound by its terms,'' said Helms. ``Without
such concrete assurances, I will insist that the Senate proceed as
planned and vote down this treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratification of a treaty requires a two-thirds majority vote
in the Senate. Members of both parties estimate that only half of
the Senate, and perhaps less, supports the test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Helms and other foes of the treaty said last week that a vote
could be avoided only if Clinton asked Lott to pull it from
consideration and agree not to bring it back up for the duration of
his term.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's five-sentence letter to Lott was silent on the second
condition, however, and the issue of how to move forward remained
unresolved late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This withdrawal request is merely a first step,'' said Lott's
press spokesman, John Czwartacki. ``Not only must the treaty be
withheld from consideration at this time, agreement must be reached
that it not come up again at any time this Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House responded that any such promise amounted to
undue constraints on the president's ability to conduct foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply can't put a sign on our door that says 'closed for
business' during an election year,'' said National Security Council
spokesman David Leavy. ``Who knows what the international
environment will be like over the next 18 months?''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the contentious rhetoric, moderate senators from both
parties were quietly seeking a way to put off the vote with an
agreement to delay further consideration of the treaty until after
the 106th Congress adjourns late next year.
</P>
<P>
   Such an agreement needn't involve Clinton, Czwartacki said, but
could be reached among Democrats and Republicans in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the president to reverse himself,'' said Czwartacki.
``Now it's up to the Senate _ D's and R's _ to agree that it not
come up again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, such an arrangement could be the best
Clinton could hope for at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a decision for those guys to make,'' said Leavy. ``But
the president has made clear that he wouldn't bring this treaty up
unless he had the votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to Tuesday's outcome, however, appeared to rest with a
handful of the treaty's most outspoken critics, particularly Lott,
Helms, Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., and Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Helms's objections could prove lethal.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, under Senate procedures, canceling the treaty's
scheduled vote Tuesday would require the unanimous consent of the
senators. A single dissident could force a vote, even if Lott
decides he wants it pulled.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on the treaty, which calls for the United States and
153 other countries to renounce nuclear weapons tests, could be
delayed until Wednesday, however, due to scheduling matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate doesn't return from its Columbus Day break until
midday Tuesday, and both parties have caucus meetings scheduled
into the afternoon. An important agriculture spending bill is up
for a floor vote late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several hours of debate remain on the Senate time
clock before the treaty vote can take place.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who became the first national leader to sign the treaty
in 1996 and asked the Senate to approve it two years ago, was
unhappy when the Senate scheduled a vote less than two weeks ago.
He claimed the schedule didn't allow sufficient time to discuss the
treaty and work out assurances for the accord's Senate opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton says the treaty would help reduce the threat of nuclear
weapons proliferation by prohibiting signatories from conducting
tests essential to the development of such arms.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents such as Helms argue, however, that the ban would tie
the hands of U.S. weapons developers, potentially undermining the
U.S. nuclear arsenal. Further, critics allege, the provisions of
the treaty would be impossible to verify, and that would enable
some nations to cheat.
</P>
<P>
   The United States stopped conducting nuclear test explosions in
September 1992, under the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
