<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CABINET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR GIVES ULSTER JOB TO AIDE BRUSHED BY SCANDAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair brought his closest political
confidant, Peter Mandelson, back into government Monday, putting
him in the strategically crucial position of Northern Ireland
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson, 45, who was forced to leave the Cabinet in a
financial scandal last December, replaced Mo Mowlam, 50, who became
head of the Cabinet Office, the so-called ``government enforcer''
responsible for keeping programs on track and officials in line.
Jack Cunningham, 60, resigned from the job.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Cabinet changes, Geoff Hoon, 45, a deputy foreign
secretary, succeeded Defense Secretary George Robertson, 53, who is
becoming secretary general of NATO, and Alan Milburn, 41, a
treasury minister, replaced health secretary Frank Dobson, 59.
Dobson resigned to fight for the Labor nomination for the position
of London's first elected mayor against the Conservative candidate,
Jeffrey Archer, the millionaire novelist.
</P>
<P>
   In her two and half years in the high-profile position of
Northern Ireland secretary, Ms. Mowlam muscled the strong-willed
politicians of the conflicted province into dealing with one other
while she herself was undergoing treatment for a brain tumor. She
earned approval ratings even higher than those of Blair, 46, the
most popular British prime minister in history.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, however, with progress in the Northern Ireland
peace settlement stalled, she had come under criticism from the
Ulster Unionists, the province's largest party, which has become
increasingly divided over whether to continue to support the
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's decision to replace her and name his most trusted aide
to the post will be seen as an indication of his persistence in
driving home a solution at a time of deepening gloom in Ulster.
George Mitchell, the former American senator, is conducting a
formal review, now in its sixth week, to try to salvage the April
1998 accord he helped broker as chairman of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the feeling of the Ulster Unionists that Ms. Mowlam
had become unsympathetic to their cause, Ken Maginnis, the party's
security spokesman, said Monday, ``There will be huge relief,
particularly among unionists, that there is a change in secretary
of state at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, the head of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic
and Labor Party and a winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, praised her
for the ``superb work she had done, particularly in these difficult
times.'' He said the people of Northern Ireland owed her a ``deep
debt of gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Unionist is the term used to describe those people, largely
members of the province's Protestant majority, who want to see
Northern Ireland remain British. Opposing them are those people,
called nationalists or republicans, and predominantly Catholic, who
are interested in seeing the province become closer to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the terms of the accord into place has become deadlocked
over the unwillingness of the Irish Republican Army to begin
disarming and the refusal of the Ulster Unionists to let the
members of the IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, take their seats in
a new Northern Ireland government until weapons are turned over.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson, a shrewd political strategist, is credited with
having planned the modernization of the Labor Party that saw it
shed its socialist past, overcome the distrust of the business
class and get back into power after 18 years of Conservative rule.
In the first year of the Blair government, he was regularly
demonized by the Tories and by large parts of the press as a
shadowy behind-the-scenes figure in his job as minister without
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, Blair named him trade and industry secretary, a
post he invigorated by championing greater investment in
information technologies, praising American entrepreneurship and
furthering Labor's new attentiveness to the leaders of British
business and finance.
</P>
<P>
   In a development that rocked British political life last
December, he was forced to quit when it emerged that he had failed
to disclose he had received a $625,000 low-interest home loan from
a millionaire colleague in government whose finances had come under
investigation by his department.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's farewell letter to his close colleague suggested the
likelihood, if not the speeded-up timing, of what took place
Monday. ``I want you to know that you have my profound thanks for
all you have done,'' the prime minister wrote in December, ``and my
belief that, in the future, you will achieve much, much more with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party chairman, Michael Ancram, deplored the
appointment, saying, ``It is wrong to bring back a disgraced
minister who was forced to resign only 10 months ago.'' He said it
``shows how arrogant this prime minister has become.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
