<SLUG> BC-MAXIM-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maxim Group loss at $19.2 million
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maxim Group Inc. on Monday restated its loss for
fiscal 1999 to $19.2 million, or $1.08 a share, before items. The
company originally reported a loss before items of $2.6 million, or
15 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1998, the company reported a profit before items of
$16.2 million, or $1 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The downward revision results from vendor support revenues,
expense accruals and asset write-downs that were incorrectly
recorded last year, said Tom Leahey, executive vice president of
finance. They will be booked in future quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The company originally reported revenue of $684.4 million for
fiscal 1999. The restated figure is $664.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   In its press release, the Kennsaw, Ga.-based flooring retailer
also said it expects auditors to question the company's ability to
continue as a going concern. The auditors' concern relates to a
previously announced default. The default was triggered when the
company exceeded limits on the repurchase of stock in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim said it is negotiating a waiver to the default.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has been conducting an
``informal inquiry'' of the company's financial records, but it is
unclear whether the commission is considering formal action. The
SEC does not comment on informal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim plans to file its annual report with the SEC on Monday and
quarterly reports for the first two quarters of 2000 within several
weeks, Leahey said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed at $7.18 3/4 Monday, up 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
