<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ HITS RECORD BUT HOLIDAY TRADING IS LACKLUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The NASDAQ composite index rose to a record high
Monday, propelled by a handful of telecommunications and
semiconductor stocks. However, with banks closed many traders were
off for Columbus Day, leaving most stocks little changed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, traders and analysts said the run-up in the NASDAQ
index, its sixth straight daily advance, should be viewed with some
caution.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was trading volume light, but the bond market, which
often acts as a governor on stock prices _ particularly high-priced
technology issues _ was closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of a few stocks in the technology sector,
it was a lackluster, listless day,'' said Bill Allyn, head of
listed trading at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``With the bond market being
closed, I would not put too much stock in the NASDAQ hitting a
record. Tuesday will be a much better barometer.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by big gains in Qualcomm and MCI/Worldcom, the NASDAQ
composite index rose 29.38, or 1 percent, to 2,915.95. The gain
eclipsed the index's previous record of 2,887.86 set on Sept. 10.
Since the start of the year, the NASDAQ composite is up 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most other major market averages barely budged.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average dipped 1.58, or 0.01 percent,
and closed at 10,648.18. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index dipped
0.81, or 0.1 percent, to 1,335.21. But the Russell 2000 index of
small company stocks rose 2.48, or 0.6 percent, to 430.19.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume was light, reflecting the holiday conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 655.4 million shares changed
hands. On the NASDAQ, volume was 862.3 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism about upcoming earnings reports helped to move big
semiconductor stocks higher.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, a component of the S&AMP;P 500, gained 3 5/8, to 96 5/8.
Intel, a NASDAQ component, gained 13/16, to 76 1/2. Both companies
are expected to announce their third-quarter results after the
market closes on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm posted the biggest point gain among NASDAQ stocks. It
was up 8 9/16, at 222 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of cellular phones and semiconductors said it expects
Globalstar Telecommunications Ltd., the satellite telephone
operator that it is supplying with equipment, to have 600,000
customers by the end of its first year in business.
</P>
<P>
   Of the NASDAQ composite stocks, Yahoo! was the biggest loser.
</P>
<P>
   The leading Internet directory company fell 10 3/4 to 181 3/8
after restrictions on certain of its executives expired, freeing
them to sell shares.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, bank and airline stocks retreated Monday following a
few sessions of solid gains.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan dropped 1 3/4 to 73 13/16. J.P. Morgan, a Dow
stock, fell 2 9/16 to 115 9/16. And Bank of America dropped 1
11/16, to 54 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Among airline stocks, UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines,
slipped 1 3/4, to 68. AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines, lost
2 7/16, to 60 7/16. And Delta Airlines fell 1 11/16, to 52 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. gained 7/8 to 53 after the automaker reached a
tentative agreement on a new four-year contract with the United
Auto Workers. The agreement averted what could have been the first
nationwide UAW strike at Ford in more than two decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
