<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO SELL GHANA MINE IS IN LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Every silver lining has a cloud.
</P>
<P>
   A recent surge in gold prices has tarnished Pioneer Group Inc.'s
plan to sell its loss-making African mine, after a wrong-way bet on
bullion left the would-be buyer short of cash for the deal, sources
familiar with the matter said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ashanti Goldfields of Ghana had teamed up with Gold Fields Ltd.,
a leading South African miner, to bid jointly for Pioneer's
Teberebie Goldfields operations, also in Ghana. Industry analysts
have said the once-profitable mine is worth from $50 million to
$100 million, even with the $40 million or so in debt it carries.
</P>
<P>
   But sources said talks, near completion last month, had come to
naught, as a troubled Ashanti sold itself Monday to a competitor,
Britain's Lonmin PLC. Ashanti's struggle to meet creditors' demands
following a surprise spike in gold prices made it vulnerable to a
takeover and in no shape to finance an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling of the Teberebie sale is a blow to troubled
Pioneer, which has struggled for years to get rid of its
money-losing mine and has frustrated investors in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely a setback,'' said Michael S. Beall, who
covers the Boston-based investment management company for Davenport
&AMP; Co. ``But things are not over yet.'' He said Pioneer could sell
Teberebie to a joint venture grouping Ashanti-Lonmin and
Gold-fields in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   A Pioneer spokesman, Timothy Frost, declined to comment. Hours
after questions from The Boston Globe, Pioneer issued a statement
saying it would wind down its operations at Teberebie, cutting back
mining in coming months and ceasing gold-processing entirely in the
first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The moves would cause Pioneer to report ``a substantial
write-down of its investment'' in the mine for the third quarter,
the statement said. Pioneer said it was still in negotiations to
sell the mine. It expects to report third-quarter earnings in early
November.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer is an eclectic mutual fund company with an unusual
collection of other operations, including a Siberian timber farm,
Moscow real estate, and fund operations in Eastern Europe, India,
and Taiwan. In the past, Pioneer's nonfund businesses made a lot of
money, but they have since become a major drag on the company's
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Once a high-flier, Pioneer has upset investors by posting losses
for several straight quarters. Pioneer lost $25.2 million in the
second quarter, most of it from the gold mine, and has all but
closed down its Russian investment operations. The company lost
$41.2 million in 1998, half from the mine, which has been plagued
by production glitches and low commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   Under president John F. Cogan Jr., 72, Pioneer has undergone
several management shakeups and restructurings in recent months and
has vowed to be more selective about its noninvestment operations.
</P>
<P>
   But other factors have conspired against the company. Mirroring
an industrywide trend, Pioneer's assets under management shrank to
just under $21 billion at the end of August, according to Financial
Research Corp. Pioneer had net redemptions, or withdrawals, from
its mutual funds of $114 million in August.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer shares surged briefly last month when precious metal
prices rose, but they have since fallen back. The company, one of
about two dozen publicly traded investment management firms, is
down 26.6 percent so far this year. It now trades at around 14 1/2,
barely one-third of its August 1997 high.
</P>
<P>
   Ashanti had staked its immediate financial future on a flat gold
market, taking out contracts betting that prices would stay low.
The agreements, some written earlier this year when gold was at a
20-year low, were designed to protect against losses and ensure the
firm made money even in a limp market.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, gold suddenly soared to a two-year high of $338
an ounce as central banks across Europe promised to limit sales to
boost prices. The surge left Ashanti vulnerable to banks' requests
that it put up cash as collateral for the contracts. The demands,
known as margin calls, left Ashanti struggling to find more than
$250 million to pay creditors and led to its takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer has been trying to get rid of part or all of its gold
mine for nearly five years. A 1995 plan to float shares in the
operation on exchanges in London and Ghana collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Beall said Pioneer's board was keen to see results improve
quickly. ``It's kind of sad to say,'' he said, ``but they ought to
just think about selling the whole company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
