<HEADER>
A3630 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE-AR     10-11 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in research. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the time, his brother, Hans, was on the faculty of the
University of Wisconsin on a Fulbright Scholarship. Hans advised
Gunter that his medical training was insufficient to do research,
that American universities were ahead of their German counterparts
because of the war, and that he should come to Madison. Gunter
Blobel did, and earned a Ph.D. there in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Blobel moved to Rockefeller University as a
post-doctoral fellow largely because he wanted to work with Dr.
George E. Palade, a pioneering cell biologist. ``My work was a
direct extension of the work Dr. Palade had started at
Rockefeller,'' Blobel said of Palade, who went on to win a Nobel
Prize in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, scientists had used the electron microscope and
other techniques to describe the structure of the cell, Blober
recalled. They learned that a cell contains many different
structures known as organelles that carry out different functions.
Each organelle is surrounded by a membrane.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists did not know how the cell worked. A particular
mystery was how large proteins could get through the tightly sealed
membranes surrounding the organelles.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel reasoned that proteins have to be transported either out
of the cell, or to the different organelles. Such transport had to
be highly regulated, or the cell would be wide open to damage from
things entering from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Blobel and Dr. David D. Sabatini, who now heads cell
biology at New York University School of Medicine, proposed a bold
idea known as the signal hypothesis. It was that ``proteins
secreted out of a cell contain an intrinsic signal that governs
them to and across membranes,'' the Nobel Assembly said in its
citation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 30 years, with support from the National
Institutes of Health and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute,
Blobel and his team have conducted experiments to prove the
existence of programmed steps that allow molecules to move from one
part of the cell to another, and directed to their proper location.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel Prize was awarded not for a single major discovery,
but for the series of findings in the decades that it took to prove
the hypothesis, Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Blobel's team found the intrinsic signal they were
seeking, in a protein found in one organelle known as the
endoplasmic reticulum.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel found that each newly made protein has an
organelle-specific address, a stretch of the protein called a
signal sequence, that is recognized by receptors on an organelle's
surface. His team showed that in the endoplasmic reticulum, the
binding of the signal sequence to its receptor opens a watery
channel in the membrane through which the protein can travel.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel also characterized in detail the molecular mechanisms
underlying the processes and showed that they were universal,
operating similarly in yeast, plant and animal cells.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at Rockefeller University on Monday, Blobel
said there were many disappointments in the 30 years of research
``such as when your grants and papers are rejected because some
stupid reviewer rejected them for dogmatic adherence to old
ideas.'' His remarks drew thunderous applause from sympathetic
colleagues and younger scientists who packed the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``What keeps you going are the little blips of excitement every
three to four years,'' Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists know that the cell works because it sorts its
proteins and directs them to the right places to carry out various
functions. Some proteins become building blocks for constructing
the cell. Others function as enzymes catalyzing thousands of
specific chemical reactions. Without the little signals Blobel
hypothesized, the cell would cease to function. Scientists alw that a number of hereditary diseases are caused by errors in
these signals and transport mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel is still working, trying to unravel the trafficking of
signals between the cell's nucleus and cytoplasm. A knowledge of
how such communication goes on in normal cells is necessary to
understand what goes awry in cancerous cells, Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   His research has contributed to the development of a more
effective use of cells as ``protein factories'' for the production
of important drugs such as erythropoeitin. It helps stimulate the
production of red blood cells in the bone marrow and is used widely
in many kidney and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel said that with more research he expected that scientists
would unravel the mysteries of how brain cells are damaged by
Alzheimer's disease, blood cells are destroyed by the AIDS virus
and other infections, and normal cells become malignant.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``As long as we do not know how the cell works we don't know the
kind of havoc the AIDS virus creates in the cell,'' Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel said his work has not found any cures and that there will
not be specific treatments for many cancers and other diseases
until scientists gain that fundamental understanding. ``We are very
far from it,'' Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel credited Rockefeller University's focus on basic research
for the last century in providing him the teaching and work
environment to make his discoveries. He thanked his his wife, Laura
Maioglio, for ``tolerating my long hours in the lab.'' ``Our
schedules meshed because she worked late at the restaurant and that
gave me the opportunity to come home late from the lab.''
</P>
</TEXT>
