<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-BROWNS-COUCH-COX     10-11 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-COUCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns-Bengals matchup played second fiddle to Couch-Smith drama
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio_ Sounding defiant but looking a bit shellshocked,
Tim Couch returned to work Monday winless as a starting quarterback
after Sunday's bitterly disappointing 18-17 loss to the Cincinnati
Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Couch did not play horribly, but against the backdrop of draft
classmate Akili Smith's heroics and subequent theatrics, he
definitely played second fiddle in his own stadium _ and it hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks ago, the expansion Browns, not to mention their fans,
identified the Bengals as a team that easily could become their
first victim. And if Smith, a rookie, were to make his first NFL
start, then so much the better, many thought. They didn't count on
Smith doing his best John Elway impersonation and marching the
Bengals 80 yards in the last two minutes for the winning score, a
two-yard TD pass to Carl Pickens. They didn't count on being 0-5
going into Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to tough it out,'' said Couch, at the helm of an
offense that has scored 43 points this season. ``I feel like I'm
learning a lot, but just not getting a lot of results. I'm not
shaken. I'm not going to just give up. I knew it was going to be a
tough deal and I'm just going to go out and prepare like I always
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, motivated by what he regards as a draft-day injustice
committed by the Browns, completed 25 of 41 passes for 221 yards
and two touchdowns. Couch, selected two spots ahead of Smith with
the No. 1 overall pick, connected on 15 of 27 for 164 yards and was
intercepted once.
</P>
<P>
   Not wasting an opportuity to pour salt into any wound he could
find, Smith danced around and gestured toward the Browns' bench
afterward, infuriating Couch, who all week had made a point of
staying above the fray as others built up the rookie quarterbacks'
first encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough. You want to fire back at him for the little things
that he's said and done,'' Couch said. ``But you've just got to
stay out of it. I don't think he means anything personal toward me
or anything. I don't really care about it, to be honest with you.
He can do all he wants and say all he wants. I'm just going to keep
playing football.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Couch benefit from sitting out a game? He doesn't think
so. More importantly, neither does head coach Chris Palmer. Nor,
for that matter, does Ty Detmer, the man Couch supplanted as the
starter in Week 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel they need to stick with Tim,'' Detmer said. ``He's your
guy. He needs to learn. You can't beat game experience as a
learning tool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns moved the ball well at times Sunday. Then there were
those other times. Count Couch among those baffled by the offense's
inability to convert on third down, especially in short-yardage
situations. ``I don't know what the deal is with that,'' he said.
Three times Sunday they failed on 3rd-and-1. The last and most
devastating of these directly preceded Cincinnati's winning score
as running back George Jones went off tackle for no gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no specific problem,'' fullback Marc Edwards said. ``It's
one guy breaking down here, one guy there. It's extremely
frustrating. Tim didn't have a bad day. It was the offense in
general. It makes you sick to your stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the offense needs to adopt a ``more vicious''
attitude on third down. ``If you need one yard, you've got to get
the damn thing,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter if they have 20 guys
trying to stop us, it's up to us to get that accomplished. It's one
damn yard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Browns' case, the longest yard.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McClelland writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
