u a BC-OHIO-FOSTERCARE-COX     10-11 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-FOSTERCARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio legislation aims to improve foster care system
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Children languishing in unsafe, dirty or
dilapidated foster homes may finally get help from state lawmakers
who have littered the General Assembly with legislation that
targets the flawed foster system.
</P>
<P>
   Five foster care bills have already been introduced, and now a
state lawmaker has vowed to create additional legislation that
would force state or local governments to conduct random
inspections of both private and county-run foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tolerated abysmal conditions that no child should be
living in, just because they are foster kids doesn't make them
throw-aways in society,'' said state Rep. Jeff Jacobson,
R-Phillipsburg. ``The government needs to make sure those foster
homes are being inspected, it's something we should have been doing
all along.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal follows a series of articles in The Dayton Daily
News detailing problems in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, for instance, no public body inspects foster homes
offered through private placement agencies. The state doesn't
conduct random inspections. And counties that place a child through
a private agency will typically follow up on a placement, but do so
by appointment and concentrate on the care of the child, not the
living environment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the New York-based Council on Accreditation, the
principal accrediting organization for foster care agencies, does
not normally also does not perform routine inspect ions of homes as
part of the accreditation process. Council officials, however, say
they are now considering new standards for accrediation that would
include random foster home inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson said his legislation would require the Ohio Department
of Human Services to create a system that ensures both private and
county-sponsored foster homes are being checked randomly. The
actual inspections would be conducted by either state or county
social workers or private inspectors depending on which system the
state chooses. Under Jacobson's plan, private agencies would pay
for the inspections of their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government needs to be accountable for these kids and
where they are living,'' Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson has also introduced legislation that would force
non-profit agencies, including private foster care agencies, to
separate their public and private funds. All records of public
funds would be considered public records and open to inspection.
The bill would also increase penalties for the misuse of public
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Problems in foster care have also caught the attention of Ohio
Gov. Bob Taft who called for the state to do more for foster
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an area that has been ignored for a long time and the
state needs to do much more than it's doing now,'' Taft said in a
recent meeting with Daily News reporters and editors.
</P>
<P>
   Taft cited the current efforts of the Department of Human
Services and state Auditor Jim Petro to crack down on and monitor
the operations of private agencies. Some of the state initiatives
include:
</P>
<P>
   Auditing about 25 private foster care agencies, which account
for about 80 percent of all children placed with private agencies
in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing a Shareholders Group, which includes nine
subcommittees that, with the Department of Human Services, will
lead a sweeping review of the current foster home licensing system.
Department officials estimate that more than 400 people are
currently working on correcting the state's foster care system.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a foster care tracking system that's designed to better
monitor complaints about foster care providers and what is being
done to solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of kids and the severity of their problems are
overwhelming us,'' Taft said. ``That's not an (excuse) for thestate. It's more proof that much of this goes back to the break
down of families.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft said he supports one proposed law introduced by Ohio House
Minority Leader Jack Ford, D-Toledo, that would require criminal
background checks of foster parents and increase trair
family foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   Other pending bills would establish a team that reviews the
death of any Ohio foster child; require case workers to make at
least one unannounced visit every six months in protective
supervision cases; and set up a system for regular state audits of
private agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is one of many states scrambling to reform foster care
systems in desperate need of reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News found that private foster care agencies across
the country operate with little government oversight and have
little financial incentive to run quality homes. With a nationwide
shortage of foster homes, children may be taken from abusive or
neglectful families only to be moved from foster home to foster
home, or placed in filthy homes in run-down neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foster care systems are a mess all over the country, I don't
think there is a single state that does this well,'' said Ben Wolf,
an ACLU attorney in Chicago, who represented the state's foster
children in a lawsuit against Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children are voicless and often helpless to tell the right
people when they are living in rat holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
