<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALILEO-MISSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galileo gets past tricky time in Jupiter orbit
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMISBURG, Ohio _ Launched a decade ago, the Galileo spacecraft
and its locally built nuclear generators survived their riskiest
moment yet Monday in the spacecraft's mission around Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Galileo passed within 380 miles of Io, Jupiter's innermost large
moon, just after 1 a.m. Eastern Daylight Time Monday, braving a
region of such intense radiation that mission controllers feared
the craft might not survive.
</P>
<P>
   No problems were reported, however.
</P>
<P>
   It was good news for Gary Morris, project manager for isotope
power systems at the Mound plant in Miamisburg. The Department of
Energy Plant, operated by contractor Babcock and Wilcox of Ohio, is
where Galileo's nuclear generators were assembled, fueled and
tested in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said his program's work on Galileo is long since
finished, but he and others still follow the mission on the
Internet and in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're getting pictures and signals back, it says
the RTGs (radioisotopic thermoelectric generators) are doing their
jobs,'' Morris said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   RTGs convert the heat from decaying plutonium fuel into
electricity. Space probes to the outer solar system use RTGs
because their missions are too long for batteries and are too far
from the sun for solar cells to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.5 billion spacecraft was launched in 1989 and reached
Jupiter in 1995. It completed its primary mission in 1997, but the
Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., has been operating
it for NASA on an extended mission that runs out in January.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, JPL spokeswoman Jane Platt said the spacecraft
was still functioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still talking to (mission controllers,)'' she said.
``They worked around the radiation and made some science
observations.''
</P>
<P>
   Io interests scientists because it is the most volcanically
active body in the solar system, but Jupiter's powerful magnetic
fields bathe the satellite in radiation that can interfere with
sensors and damage electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Back on earth, Morris' program at Mound has survived periodic
attempts by the Energy Department to relocate it from the Mound,
which is being converted to a high-tech industry park.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the Energy Department recently decided to keep the
RTG program at Mound and plans to build new RTG facilities there.
NASA is working on plans for space probes to Pluto and one to study
Jupiter's moon Europa. Morris said both would use RTGs.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
