<SLUG> BC-SOUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION MAY TAP GULATI FOR FRONT OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Revolution are on the verge of announcing the appointment of
Sunil Gulati as director of soccer operations. Gulati, 40, was
deputy commissioner of the MLS and was in charge of acquiring most
of the league's players from 1995 until he was fired before this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution owner Jonathan Kraft would not confirm Gulati's name
but said a decision will be made soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to fix our soccer operation and to do that we want to
get the best soccer people we can,'' Kraft said Monday. ``We always
thought we were hiring the right people but it hasn't worked out
that way and it hasn't been fair to the fans. The fan support
proves there is a market for the product. We have had four years of
losing teams but if you look at the crowd (21,335) for our last
game, there is a real interest out there, and it is incumbent upon
us to get it right. Whoever we bring in will have international
ties and the ability to do deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution concluded their fourth season with a 1-1
regulation-time tie and shootout win at D.C. United Saturday night.
They have failed to advance to the playoffs in three of four
seasons and have an all-time record of 36-75-17. Walter Zenga was
fired as player-coach after 30 games this season and Steve Nicol
was interim coach the final two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in final discussions,'' general manager Brian O'Donovan
said. ``This person would make soccer decisions. The coach would be
like a general manager and would set the tone for the team, make
personnel decisions, travel plans, be responsible for how the team
looks _ basically like it happens in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not afraid to make moves that will put us in the best
position to accomplish what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulati would hire the coach and be involved in personnel
decisions. Gulati, a former financial planner for the World Bank
and economics professor at Columbia University, likely would retain
his New York residency.
</P>
<P>
   As a US Soccer Federation executive, Gulati was a prime mover in
the US Cup competitions and was a member of the 1994 World Cup
Organizing Committee. When the MLS began, Gulati recruited players
such as Leonel Alvarez, Jorge Campos, Roberto Donadoni, Marco
Antonio Etcheverry, Giuseppe Galderisi, Doctor Khumalo, Hugo
Sanchez, Carlos Valderrama, and helped arrange for most of the top
American players to return to the US. Through contacts with agents
such as Giovanni Branchini, Gulati brought in young players such as
Brazilian forward Welton.
</P>
<P>
   Gulati has negotiated contracts for most of the players in the
league. But he was dismissed after a conflict with MetroStars'
investor Stuart Subotnick in February after signing Tab Ramos to a
contract extension at maximum salary.
</P>
<P>
   But Gulati also clashed with coaches and reporters in being
essentially player personnel director for 10 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution players will meet Tuesday, then return to training
camp in January. A preseason visit to Trinidad is likely before
camp opens Feb. 6-20 in Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
