<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-11 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: CHEFS PROTEST TAX
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of French chefs and restaurant owners, many wearing
tall white hats and banging pots, converged on Parliament to demand
lower taxes. When riot policemen blocked their way, the shouting
marchers fought back with eggs and flour before being dispersed
with tear gas. The restaurateurs want a reduction in the 20.6
percent value-added tax, or VAT, they must charge their clients.
They say it is too hard to compete with fast-food chains, which can
charge only a 5.5 percent tax.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: TRAIN TOLL REDUCED
</P>
<P>
   The death toll in a train crash outside Paddington Station,
London, has been scaled down from 70 to ``nearer 30,'' the police
said, after the delayed search of a badly burned car of the
intercity express that collided with a commuter train turned up
only one body. ``We may never know exactly now many people were on
that train,'' Deputy Assistant Commissioner Andy Trotter said.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: WOMAN AT NEWSPAPER JAILED
</P>
<P>
   Pressure on Iran's reformist newspapers tightened with the
disclosure that a female editor had been arrested on charges of
publishing ``outrageous'' articles offending ``public morality and
decency,'' The official news agency, reporting the arrest of Jaleh
Oskui, the editor of Penj-Shanbeh-ha, a weekly, said she was the
first female editor to be jailed in a sequence that has seen dozens
of papers closed by the conservative-controlled courts, and a
growing number of male editors jailed, fined or banned from
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: U.N. AIDS FIGHT ON CRIME
</P>
<P>
   The government has joined forces with the United Nations to
fight corruption in the criminal justice system here, officials
said. At the ninth Annual Anti-Corruption Conference, which was
held in Durban, the officials announced that the United Nations
would help train local policemen and investigators to combat
bribery, theft and other crimes by public officials.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: SLAIN BY LEFT AND RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   More than a score of people have been killed in separate attacks
by left-wing guerrillas and right-wing paramilitary groups in the
strategic northwest province of Antioquia. In the largest of the
assaults, 13 men were taken from their homes, bound, shot and their
bodies dumped along a highway. Local authorities said right-wing
gunmen appeared to be responsible for the massacre, which followed
three guerrilla strikes that left at least a dozen people dead
elsewhere in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: 3 CAPTIVES FREED
</P>
<P>
   A heavily armed band that kidnapped a dozen foreigners and
killed an Ecuadorean soldier last month has freed three of its
captives. The European tourists released over the weekend brought
letters from the remaining hostages, oil workers from the United
States and Canada who are reported to be unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: PREMIER APPOINTED
</P>
<P>
   President K.R. Narayanan said he was satisfied that the
coalition led by the Bharatiya Janata Party had the parliamentary
majority to govern and appointed Atal Behari Vajpyaee as prime
minister. Vajpayee has pleaded with his coalition partners to act
like allies, not opposition parties as the government makes some
``hard decisions'' in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: CONGRESS AIDES QUIT
</P>
<P>
   At least five senior officials in the Congress Party have
resigned since the party had its worst showing ever in the
elections just concluded. The party's newly elected members of
Parliament will meet Tuesday to choose a leader. The question was
whether Sonia Gandhi, the party's president, will lead the
opposition in the lower house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: BEIJING AIDE ACCUSED
</P>
<P>
   One of Hong Kong's most prominent pro-democracy leaders, Szeto
Wah, has accused the territory's Beijing-appointed chief executive,
Tung Chee-hwa, of pressing him to stop holding annual candlelight
vigils to mark the June 4, 1989, Tiananmen Square crackdown. Szeto
said Tung told him that if he wanted to improve ties with Beijing,
he should cancel the commemoration. Tung denies he told the
democrats to end the vigils. But he makes no secret of his chagrin
at this display of political protest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
