<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-PATRIOTS-NOTES-BOS &LR;      10-11 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS REVEALED PATRIOTS' WEAKNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The blueprint for beating the New England Patriots
has been drawn and future opponents surely will try to follow it.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a Frank Lloyd Wright creation. There is nothing fancy
or exotic about it. You run the ball and you run over their
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Do that and you may not win but you will have a chance to win. A
very good chance, in fact, if the Patriots play the next 11 games
the way they've played the first five. If you can rush the ball and
you can rush Drew Bledsoe like the Kansas City Chiefs did, you can
give these Patriots the bum's rush or at least be in position to,
and that may be the only way to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   You don't beat Bledsoe very often any more in shootouts. His arm
and his arsenal of weapons are too lethal. To beat him you must
engage in guerilla warfare. You must avoid direct confrontation
with New England's air force. You must keep its top gun grounded or
on the ground, both of which the Chiefs succeeded in doing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will do the rest. They will commit the penalties or
the crucial turnover or be unable to run the ball consistently or
find some odd way to make their lives difficult.
</P>
<P>
   These are failures they got away with for a month but kept
publicly acknowledging. They admitted they had not played
consistently very often during their 4-0 run to start the season.
They said this could not go on and then duplicated it the very next
Sunday until they finally ran into a team that could reduce 60
minutes of football to less than half that by pounding a weak
defensive front until it wore out. After it did, the Chiefs kept
pounding away, controlling the ball and limiting Bledsoe to seven
minutes and 12 seconds of offense in the final 30 minutes of a
tight game.
</P>
<P>
   When he did get the ball, the Chiefs went after Bledsoe hard and
got to him too often for him to play as well as he had in the four
victories. Not that he played poorly Sunday because he did not. He
played well enough to give his team a chance to win again at the
final gun as it had done three times this year. But the Patriots
are 19-1 in games in which Bledsoe has a rating of 100 or better
and Sunday it was 71.8, which was good but not good enough to
overcome Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Patriots were still in position to win on the
road with four seconds to play after committing six false starts,
turning the ball over four times, and allowing their quarterback to
get mugged spoke volumes about the team's abilities in general and
Bledsoe's in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Patriots lost on a missed field goal with four
seconds on the clock on a day when they could have won speaks
volumes as well, however, and they need to recognize that or they
will face the same fate whenever they engage teams that are their
equal or nearly so.
</P>
<P>
   The way to beat the Patriots is to not get into a beef with
Bledsoe. If you do, you lose, unless your quarterback is someone
like Brett Favre, in which case you still might lose but at least
you have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   If your quarterback is a mortal, say a Kent Graham or a Rick
Mirer or an Elvis Grbac or a Tim Couch, you almost always will
lose. That's true even for young Peyton Manning, the future fastest
gun in town, who lost a close one to Bledsoe this year after
playing about as well as a quarterback could.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs offensive coordinator Jimmy Raye understood this and did
not try to buck it. He chose to run and his defense allowed him to
get away with it by doing the only thing you can to keep Bledsoe at
bay. It knocked him down.
</P>
<P>
   Sacked three times and bowled over 10 times three, Bledsoe's
effectiveness and accuracy slipped slightly. He had completed 70
percent of his second-half passes in the previous four games. In
this one he completed 50 percent. His team could not survive that.
</P>
<P>
   Twice he missed Shawn Jefferson open deep because he had to
unload the ball before he wanted or was less than comfortable when
he did because he was about to be decapitated. Had he hit those
plays instead of been hit, the Patriots lead by two or three
touchdowns and the Chiefs cannot run the ball 43 times and hence
they become the fifth victim of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't hit them because the Chiefs hit him. When they
finally stopped, Bledsoe hit back. After a second-half start in
which New England's first nine passes resulted in seven
incompletions, an interception, and a penalty, the Chiefs unwisely
decided to go soft for a time, dropping men into coverage and
rushing only four linemen. The result was Bledsoe completed nine of
his last 11 passes and led his team to a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to keep somebody in his face at all times,'' said
Chiefs free safety Jerome Woods. ``Safety, linebackers, everybody,
so he wasn't able to see his target.''
</P>
<P>
   This worked. Not by much but by the 4-inch width of an upright,
which is what Adam Vinatieri hit with his 32-yard field goal
attempt with four seconds to play. It was the thinnest of victory
margins but it was enough for the Chiefs. Their strategy had
succeeded. They had limited Bledsoe's chances and hence the
Patriots' by running over their defense with 43 rushes and running
over Bledsoe with an assortment of blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rushing for only 32 yards in the first half, the Chiefs
were able to persist in their approach because they had gotten
after Bledsoe just enough that he missed those two bombs to
Jefferson that would have forced Kansas City out of its strategy.
Had Bledsoe hit them or had Terry Allen not fumbled at the 12-yard
line, the score easily could have been 14-3 or even 21-3 by
halftime, a situation that would have destroyed the Chiefs' plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots so consistently have given themselves no margin
for error this season that with just one or two miscues they were
undone. In large part that was because the massive Chiefs offensive
line and powerful four-pronged rushing attack destroyed New
England's defensive front.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were on offense for only 7:12 in the second half
but perhaps the most significant stat was one other teams now will
try to duplicate. New England's four starting defensive backs made
24 tackles against a team that completed only 18 passes. Worse, the
starting defensive line made only nine tackles against an opponent
that rushed 43 times. Even in a defense designed for linebackers to
make plays, too often the Chiefs' big backs got into the secondary
with a full head of steam. What resulted was 140 yards rushing,
more than 35 minutes of Chiefs' offense, control of the clock and
of the game's tempo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision at halftime to play defense and run it
right at the heart of their defense,'' Chiefs coach Gunther
Cunningham said. ``They wilted in the third quarter when we marched
downfield and set the tone for what we were going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple, brutal blueprint for victory. The Patriots can
expect to see a lot more of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
