u s BC-ISRAEL-HEAT-1012-COX     10-11 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HEAT-1012-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA HEAT OVERPOWERS MACCABI TEL AVIV IN TRANSATLANTIC HOOPS
CELEBRATION
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ The Miami Heat used superior speed, power and
size Monday to overwhelm Israel's best basketball team 126 to 91,
but the game still looked good from where Ovi(CQ) Ben-Chaim sat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful, it's great,'' Ben-Chaim said from his
courtside wheelchair. He was shot in the head by a sniper during
Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon. Now, with his legs paralyzed, he
plays wheelchair basketball for Israel's Wounded Soldiers' House.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see a team like this in Israel, it's great. It's like
someone says, OK, now you are good . . . not equals, but good
enough to play with,'' said Ben-Chaim, 38. ``The Americans are like
brothers, family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat came for an exhibition game against Maccabi Elite Tel
Aviv, which they agreed to play three years ago in order to win the
rights from Tel Aviv for 1996 draft pick Martin Muursapp, now
playing in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time an NBA team played here in 21 years and it
melded NBA glitz with distinctly Israeli elements.
</P>
<P>
   There were extra spot lights installed for pre-game
introductions, an appearance at courtside by celebrity sportscaster
Ahmad Rashad and the presence of league Commissioner David Stern,
watching from a seat beside U.S. Ambassador to Israel Ned Walker.
</P>
<P>
   There were also security guards posted by Heat huddles during
time-outs, war veterans at courtside and in-your-face crowds that
sent cheers and heckles toward both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans kind of reminded me of NBA fans on the road, hostile,
chanting,'' said Heat star center Alonzo Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   While he said it was ``flattering'' to see many fans wearing
jerseys with his name and number (33), he noted that they also
taunted the team with chants of ``first round knockout'' in
reference to the Heat's play-off departure last season.
</P>
<P>
   But, with a sampling of dunks, ally-oops that brought the
raucous crowd to standing ovations and just overall dominance, the
Heat's premier players fulfilled their roles. Guard Tim Hardaway
lead scoring with 24 points. Heat coach Pat Riley pointed out that
the Heat were ahead 23-5 when he gave Hardaway a rest and saw Tel
Aviv tie the score in the second quarter at 36. Hardaway re-entered
the game and the Heat were leading by 23 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning lead the Heat with 11 rebounds and forward Mark
Strickland had 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Tel Aviv coach Pinhas Gershon said he should have forced the
game to end when it was tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' he said. ``Not everything in life is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat appeared to have periodic trouble figuring out the Tel
Aviv's zone defense _ prohibited in the NBA. And, two fellow
Americans playing for Tel Aviv _ foreign players are allowed on
Israeli teams _ gave them problems in streaks. Former Stetson and
Continental Basketball Association guard Mark Brisker had 19 points
and former University of Minnesota guard Arriel(CQ) McDonald had
14.
</P>
<P>
   Riley and Hardaway agreed after the game that Tel Aviv center
Nat Huffman, who had 14 points, is probably NBA caliber.
</P>
<P>
   Tel Aviv has won Israel's championship for six straight years
and also frequently plays European teams. Basketball is the No. 2
sport here, after soccer, but the top players only make about
$400,000 a year _ cheap by NBA standards.
</P>
<P>
   By the start of the fourth quarter Monday, Hardaway and
guard-forward Dan Majerle were resting on the bench and pointing in
mock anger at fans calling their names.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,700 attended, short of selling out the 10,000 seat Yad
Eliyahu(CQ) Sports Palace, Israel's largest arena. Games often
sell-out for Tel Aviv's European League games, but ticket prices
for the exhibition _ ranging from about $15 to $80 _ were double
the normal cost.
</P>
<P>
   When the game was over, the Heat headed for the airport and back
to Miami, after spending less than three days here. The trip
allowed time for just a short tour of Jerusalem Sunday between
practices and meetings. Riley said he was haunted by stories of the
Washington Bullets, who lost to Tel Aviv in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one game, anybody can beat you,'' Riley said. ``It was
really a business trip. We were concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
