<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3662 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-AFLCIO-ENDORSEMENT-2T     10-11 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFLCIO-ENDORSEMENT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE WORKS BEHIND SCENES TO GET LABOR ENDORSEMENT FOR GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the AFL-CIO's endorsement hanging in the
balance, President Clinton did his vice president a big favor
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   According to Douglas Dority, president of the Food and
Commercial Workers Union, Clinton telephoned a friend of Dority's
to make one last nudge to assure that Dority's union would provide
the crucial swing vote needed to secure the labor federation's
important endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called John Sweeney, the labor federation
president, over the weekend. While it is unclear how much Clinton's
calls ultimately affected the outcome, they were the final steps in
an intense effort by the Gore campaign _ and the White House itself
_ to win labor's support for the vice president with an endorsement
that the AFL-CIO is expected to approve on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To line up labor's support, Clinton appeared at a dinner last
Thursday honoring the Teamsters' president, James Hoffa. And in
recent weeks the White House has moved to limit imports of
low-priced steel, part of an effort to placate the powerful United
Steelworkers of America.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Clinton and four Cabinet members traveled to Chicago
to address the concerns of eight union presidents worried about the
loss of factory jobs. Clinton told them that on the recommendation
of Gore he was setting up a task force to determine how to save
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's full-court press is one of several factors
that have put Gore on the verge of grabbing the the biggest plum so
far in the early months of the 2000 presidential campaign. Equally
critical, many labor leaders said Monday, were the vice president's
record on labor issues as well as the need for Sweeney to prove
that he could unite the federation around Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Gore and his rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley, have battled
over the labor endorsement, with Bradley urging union leaders not
to rush to make an endorsement so early.
</P>
<P>
   The labor endorsement is a boon to candidates because the
AFL-CIO has 13 million members, prints millions of leaflets and
mobilizes thousands of union members to get out the vote and
operate phone banks.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Dority said the Food and Commercial
Workers' Union decided to back Gore for a reason that was haunting
many of Gore's labor supporters: If Gore did not gain an
endorsement from the labor federation it would be construed as a
devastating setback to the vice president at a time when Bradley's
strength seems to be growing each day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's most outspoken supporter in labor, Gerald McEntee,
president of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees, said, ``There was a real fear that if we didn't have an
endorsement here for Gore, it would have cut him off at the
knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of endorsing Gore at the AFL-CIO convention this week,
some union leaders were pushing for a delay, in hopes of wresting
more concessions from Gore and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last week, Sweeney was so discouraged that he told
aides he might not put an endorsement up to a vote at the
convention because several pivotal unions weren't making the
movement toward Gore that he expected.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime early on Friday, AFL-CIO officials said, Sweeney
decided to stick his neck out and push hard for an endorsement even
though he was uncertain he could muster the needed two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Sweeney said he decided to work hard to line up
backing for the vice president because he believed that Gore has
been a good and loyal friend to American workers and that Gore was
going to be the Democratic presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, union officials said, saw that Gore nearly had the
two-thirds needed, and he was confident that if he pushed for an
endorsement, that would move several fence-sitting unions toward
backing Gore, enabling the vice president to clinch the two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after Sweeney spoke out for an endorsement on Friday,
several fence-sitting unions other than the Food and Commercial
Workers announced that they would back an AFL-CIO endorsement of
Gore. Those unions were the Office and Professional Employees
International Union, the Laborers International Union of North
America and the National Treasury Employees Union.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of the largest unions in the AFL-CIO, the
Service Employees International Union, gave Sweeney assurances this
past weekend that it would back an endorsement if its vote was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   For many union leaders, there was another big concern, that the
AFL-CIO and Sweeney would be weakened and embarrassed if the labor
federation did not endorse Gore at the convention, when Sweeney was
such an outspoken supporter of the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there wasn't an endorsement, it would have hurt John,''
McEntee said. ``The guy worked so hard for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many union leaders interviewed said that the question always was
not whether they were going to endorse Gore, but when. Several
opposed an early endorsement because they said their members were
not yet paying attention to the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members weren't mentally prepared to talk about the
presidential election,'' said Dority of the Food and Commercial
Workers' Union. ``We thought it would be better to wait until
closer to the election. But we saw that not endorsing at this time
might send a message that we're against Gore, and we didn't want to
be seen that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The stepped-up involvement from the White House and the Gore
campaign came only after many labor leaders had complained that
Gore had not given them enough one-on-one attention. At the same
time, Bradley was calling the leaders two or three times a day,
union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Some union officials said that they were receptive to the
argument Gore has been making recently that he has fought for union
issues for a long time while Bradley quit the Senate in 1996 and
has been viewed as doing little for labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley's been out of the Senate now for how long?'' asked
William Burga, president of the Ohio affiliate of the AFL-CIO.
``Gore stayed in there. I think that means something.''
</P>
<P>
   But several union officials, most notably the presidents of the
Teamsters and the autoworkers, said there should be no rush for the
AFL-CIO to make an endorsement because they thought holding off
might wrest more concessions from candidates. Other union officials
argued against an early endorsement because the Gore campaign was
in disarray and Bradley was coming on strong.
</P>
<P>
   Shea, the Sweeney aide, said, ``Because it was early, because of
the atmosphere _ is the Gore campaign falling flat? _ because
Bradley was doing a good job of reaching out, people got into this,
maybe we should just hang back. Why rush? Nobody was saying we
prefer Bradley over Gore. John's reaction was: That's not a
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   For labor officials like Sweeney, loyalty is an important
factor, and they have seen Gore speak out for years on labor's
issues, ranging from the minimum wage to a patients' bill of
rights. At two recent meetings of the AFL-CIO's executive
committee, the vice president won rave reviews for defending
workers' right to organize and for condemning corporations that
violate the law by firing workers who support unionization efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been very much in the fray with us, on education,
on health, on children's issues'' said Sandra Feldman, president of
the American Federation of Teachers. ``Over the years he's been
with us very steadfastly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MINORITY-BUSINESSES-N     10-11 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-BUSINESSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS A MINORITY-OWNED BUSINESS? SOME SAY 51 PERCENT OWNERSHIP.  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla., N.Y., Ariz.)   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Long united in the struggle to maintain special
breaks for nonwhite entrepreneurs, some civil rights leaders and
minority business groups have become divided over a basic concept:
what is a minority-owned company.
</P>
<P>
   Many black and Hispanic owners of large businesses are arguing
that the traditional definition _ a company in which members of
minority groups own 51 percent _ limits their ability to raise
capital by selling stock. But leaders of large civil rights groups
and minority small-business owners say that changing the definition
will further erode the whole idea of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a proposal by the National Minority Supplier
Development Council to relax the definition of what would be
considered a minority company. The council, based in New York, is a
private organization that certifies whether companies can be
considered owned by minorities. Many large corporations rely on the
council's evaluation process to determine whether companies they
are contracting with are, in fact, owned by African-American,
Hispanic or Asian-American entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 26 in Phoenix the council's 80-member board will vote on
a resolution that would allow minority companies to sell stock and,
in some cases, retain the council's certification, even if the
stock sale results in minorities owning as little as 30 percent of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the change say it is needed to allow minority
companies to grow and to compete against larger white-owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our commitment is to assist the development of minority
business,'' said Harriet Michel, president of the council, which is
made up of Fortune 500 corporations. ``Minority firms must be
allowed the same opportunity to grow in this global economy, to be
competitive and not to be continually defeated because they don't
have access to capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Larger minority-owned companies say they need access to capital
without losing the council's certification, without which they
might not be eligible for a company's minority contracting program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you an introduction,'' said Joe Arriola, who is
Cuban-American and chairman and chief executive of Avanti-Case
Hoyt, a graphics arts company that does nearly $160 million worth
of business and has offices in Miami, Chicago and Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Arriola said he would like to expand his business by buying a
small graphics arts company. But while his competitors could do
that by selling stock, ``I got to pay with cash and, for me, cash
only comes from borrowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of some civil rights groups, including the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the National
Urban League and the U.S. Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, say the
change will open the door to so-called front companies, in which
minority executives have prominent positions but the companies are
owned and controlled by whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``For as long as there has been black enterprise, when you said
black ownership that has always meant 51 percent,'' said Earl G.
Graves Sr., publisher of Black Enterprise Magazine, who has led the
opposition to the proposal. ``If you have 51 percent, you have
control; less than 51 percent, it is not control, you have an
ownership stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents worry that any increase in front companies would
discredit the concept of special breaks for minority companies at a
time when affirmative action programs are under assault. They are
also concerned that a change by the council might prompt the
federal government to re-examine its definition of what constitutes
a small ``disadvantaged'' company _ currently 51 percent ownership
by minorities or some whites _ that are given breaks in bidding for
government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the change say they understand the concerns of
civil rights leaders given the setbacks in the courts and the
passage of ballot initiatives like Proposition 209 in California,
which outlawed government programs that extend ``preferences''
based on race and sex in employment, college admissions and
contracting. But they say the proposal has a number of safeguards
built in.
</P>
<P>
   For example, companies must already be 51 percent owned by
minorities and have a stock deal with a venture capitalist worked
out before they can apply for a waiver of the 51 percent rule. The
council will also examine the future makeup of the board, the issue
of who holds voting stock as opposed to common stock, and who will
be in charge day to day.
</P>
<P>
   The change is being pushed by several large corporations,
particularly the Big Three automakers. In recent years, General
Motors, Ford Motor and DaimlerChrysler have been consolidating
their supply operations, buying more from larger and larger
suppliers and scaling back contracts with small suppliers. In the
process, the car companies and several minority suppliers say that
unless minority suppliers grow, they will soon be shut out of the
industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
