<HEADER>
A3669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-FURNITURE-SALE-BOS     10-11 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FURNITURE-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFETT COMPANY BUYS NEW ENGLAND FURNITURE COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Eliot and Barry Tatelman, known to New England shoppers
for their goofy yet memorable television ads for Jordan's Furniture
Co., said Monday they have agreed to sell their business to
Berkshire Hathaway Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement with Berkshire Hathaway's chief executive,
Warren Buffett, the brothers said they would continue to have free
rein in running the four-store furniture chain founded by their
grandfather in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Jordan's Furniture was unexpected. The Tatelmans had
had no thoughts of selling, they said. But after being contacted by
Buffett, the second richest man in the world, the brothers
negotiated a deal that would allow them to run Jordan's. And by
selling, the brothers said, they can give their children the
freedom to choose any career _ not necessarily the family business.
</P>
<P>
   Each brother has two children, all of whom are either in college
or recently graduated. Eliot's oldest son, Josh, is the only one,
so far, who has been attracted to the furniture business.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have family businesses and force their kids to
go into it,'' Barry Tatelman said in an interview. ``Mine and
Eliot's goal is to have happy kids who can do exactly what they
want to do when they want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   While neither party involved in the deal would disclose the sale
price, analysts said furniture stores typically sell for at least
one year's revenues. Jordan's expects to sell about $250 million
worth of furniture this year, putting the sale price at $250
million or more.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, who in May flew all their employees to Bermuda for
a day, plan to share the sale proceeds with the company's 1,200
workers. Each employee will be paid 50 cents for every hour worked
at Jordan's _ for long-time employees, that could mean bonuses of
up to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   It remains a mystery why the store was named Jordan's when it
was incorporated in 1928 by Samuel Tatelman. In 1973, Barry and
Eliot Tatelman took over the family business from their father, who
had taken it over from his father.
</P>
<P>
   There are now four Jordan's stores, in Avon, Waltham, Natick,
Mass., and Nashua, N.H. While rooted in tradition, the stores are
anything but conventional.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its acres of furniture, the Avon store has a
flight-simulated ride that might be found at Disney World. The main
floor of the Natick store has a recreation of New Orleans' Bourbon
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers have expanded carefully. The Natick store is the
newest and biggest Jordan's, covering 130,000 square feet. Opened
in April 1998, it was the first Jordan's to open in 11 years. With
backing from Berkshire Hathaway, the brothers said they hope to
have more freedom to open more of the ambitious _ and expensive _
theme stores. The first planned is on the North Shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ability to expand and do unique things, and it's not
personal investments anymore _ that's a nice feeling,'' Eliot
Tatelman said.
</P>
<P>
   For Berkshire Hathaway, the Jordan's deal follows other
purchases of small or family-owned furniture stores. Buffett's
investment company in 1992 purchased 55-year-old Nebraska Furniture
Mart after a family rift. Berkshire Hathaway also owns
Houston-based Star Furniture Co., and R.C. Willey in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett started his company in 1965 and transformed it from a
textile firm into an investment holding company now estimated to
have nearly $60 billion in investment assets. On the strength of
his world-renown financial savvy, Buffett has amassed a personal
fortune worth $36 billion, making him second only to Microsoft
chairman Bill Gates on Forbes magazine's list of the world's
wealthiest individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire Hathaways' holdings include insurance giants Geico and
General RE Corp., as well as a quirky mix of small firms ranging
from the Buffalo News to a candy company and shoe maker Dexter Shoe
Co. Buffett's company has also purchased large stakes in such
corporate giants as Coca-Cola Co., Gillette Co., and American
Express.
</P>
<P>
   The Tatelmans said Monday they were approached by Berkshire
Hathaway about doing a deal through mutual friends at Nebraska
Furniture Mart. ``We took him (Buffett) through our Natick store,
and he loved it,'' Eliot Tatelman said. Prior to that, the brothers
said, they had turned down numerous offers to take their company
public, a move that would have meant a loss of control.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers said Buffett has given them a free hand in
overseeing Jordan's _ ``as co-presidents or something,'' Barry
Tatelman said. They said they didn't feel the need to get that in
writing, because they trust Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with Warren and his company, and the way he does
things, is exactly in line with what we want,'' Eliot Tatelman
said. ``We're going to run the company tomorrow exactly as we have
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Berkshire Hathaway did not return telephone calls
and referred questions to Jordan's. Buffett, in a press statement,
called Jordan's ``unique'' and a ``gem.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's advertisements are distinctive. Featuring the Tatelman
brothers, they are typically silly and sometimes spoof ads for
other products. In one, for example, the brothers dropped a ball
bearing on a couch to mimick a Lexus ad that did the same to
highlight the luxury car's sleek lines and precision engineering. A
newer Jordan's ad featured a woman sitting on a couch, spewing
uncomplimentary remarks _ in Swedish _ about the two brothers, who
were clueless about what she was saying.
</P>
<P>
   Among furniture retailers, Jordan's is known for moving huge
amounts of merchandise rapidly. Though Jordan's never has sales,
its revenues per square foot of showroom far exceed the industry
average. In a rare criticism, the company was charged with
exercising a virtual monopoly on some furniture lines provided
solely to Jordan's by distributors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
