<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG10-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baylor's Steele finds fault with Bears' mistakes vs. A&AMP;M
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Kevin Steele has sounded like a broken record,
constantly reiterating ``the long process'' he and his staff are
going through to establish credibility for the Baylor football
program they inherited this season.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the rookie head coach has preached patience and
positive thinking. Practicing those traits, though, becomes
increasingly difficult when he keeps seeing the kinds of mistakes
that the Bears made Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, even if it had played a perfect game, undermanned
Baylor would have had a difficult time attempting to derail No. 13
Texas A&AMP;M in College Station. But Steele, for all his positivism,
was peeved at the mistakes the Bears made en route to the Aggies'
45-13 victory.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for starters, sophomore Andra Fuller's decision to
drift back from his 10-yard line to catch Shane Lechler's 62-yard
punt at the 2. Fuller got back to only the 10, and three plays
later quarterback Jermaine Alfred threw a pass that A&AMP;M safety
Michael Jameson intercepted and returned 20 yards for a touchdown
to put A&AMP;M up 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't ever do that,'' Steele said of Fuller's decision to
retreat to the 2 to field the punt. ``You just don't do it. You put
your heels on the 10-yard line and you never back up. Never. That's
something we'll have to settle this week. But I know this: I bet
you nobody catches the ball inside the 10 again.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was the blocked punt off the foot of Kyle Atteberry,
leading to A&AMP;M's first offensive touchdown in three games;
cornerback Daniel Wilturner's failure to reach the end zone after
an interception, getting knocked out of bounds by quarterback Randy
McCown, who chased him down; Atteberry'smiss on a 27-yard gimmee on
the final play of the half after the interception, which would have
swung momentum back to the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a good enough football team to be doing some of the
things we did,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't think he's still not accentuating the positive despite
the Bears' league-worst 1-5 record (0-3 in the South).
</P>
<P>
   ``I always want to paint the picture for the best, whether you
know in your own heart that, hey, long-term, it's going to be a
dogfight,'' Steele said. ``But you want to pump things up and
breathe life into it as fast as you can. People say, 'That's not
right, because it's false.' But when things have been down you need
to give people hope. When reality does strike, you assess it and
keep on plugging. This thing's going to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Block that kick
</P>
<P>
   When Texas was sunk by three blocked punts in its opener against
North Carolina State, many coaches had an explanation _ or they
thought they did.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams are always ragged early in the season, the coaches
noted, because it's difficult to simulate full speed special-teams
action in practice. But at the midpoint of the season, they are
being forced to re-evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   Kicks are being blocked at an astonishing pace in games
involving Big 12 teams. Already this season, league teams have been
a part of 12 blocked punts, six blocked field goals and three
blocked extra points. By comparison, for all of last season, league
teams were involved in 13 blocked punts, six blocked field goals
and six blocked PATs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very interesting year in that regard,'' Nebraska
Coach Frank Solich said. ``Why it is, I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Solich speculated that the rash of blocked punts might be
because many teams have gone to a spread formation, with players
split out to get downfield coverage rather than staying in to
block.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of pluses to that formation, but it takes
tremendous coordination,'' Solich said. ``All it takes is one guy
not doing his responsibility to get the ball blocked. I don't
really have an answer for it, though. All I know is most coaches
just hold their breath when it comes time to kick the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Game within the game
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is a 32 1/2-point underdog going into Saturday's game at
No. 13 Texas A&AMP;M, but Coach Terry Allen knows a good showing could
reflect more than on the Kyle Field scoreboard. It could show up in
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks heavily recruit in Texas, with 22 Texans on their
roster, including star running back David Winbush of Killeen
Ellison. There currently are four Killeen products at Kansas,
including standout freshman RB Reggie Duncan of Ellison, who is
redshirting after picking the Jayhawks over A&AMP;M. Part of the reason
for that might be that KU assistant head coach Darrell Wyatt is a
Killeen native.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question a good performance on Saturday would be a
real bright spot for us,'' Allen said. ``We'll be fanning out
Friday night to go to high school games, and we know there are a
lot of kids we're anxious to recruit who will be at the game
Saturday, so a good performance could really help.''
</P>
<P>
   Flag day
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State led the league last year in both penalties (118)
and penalty yards (993), so it's not like the Wildcats aren't used
to seeing flags fly in their direction. But Coach Bill Snyder isn't
so sure someone wasn't overdoing it Saturday, and it wasn't
necessarily his players.
</P>
<P>
   K-State was whistled 18 times for 162 yards in penalties in its
50-9 victory over Kansas, both school records. Snyder, though,
wasn't sure all the penalties were valid, especially some of the
five infractions for pass interference _ three on backup cornerback
DeRon Tyler and two on starting corner Dyshod Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, not eager to incur a Big 12 fine for criticizing
officials, danced around the subject Monday. But he did hint that
he didn't agree with some of the pass interference calls.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the calls came despite Tyler and Carter playing
coverage the way they had been taught, Snyder responded, ``By and
large, that's the case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a major concern for me,'' he added. ``Nobody is
ever going to be pleased with penalties to any degree. When you end
up with 18 of them, it can put you over the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the league
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's victory over Missouri last week was its first
overtime game ever, and the four-hour affair also was the longest
game in Buffs' history.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Davis' 107 rushing yards against Nebraska marked his
sixth straight 100-yard game, second-most in Iowa State history. He
has a long way to go before reaching the school mark for
consecutive 100-yard games, held by his brother Troy Davis (17).
</P>
<P>
   Nobody should be surprised Texas Tech lost at Oklahoma State
last week. In the games immediately following their encounters with
Texas A&AMP;M, the Raiders are 3-10 under Coach Spike Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M TB Dante Hall remains questionable for the Kansas game while
continuing to rehab a strained muscle in his back. Players of the
week
</P>
<P>
   Offense: Texas TB Hodges Mitchell, who rushed for a career-high
204 yards and one TD in the Longhorns' 38-28 victory over Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Defense: Kansas State LB Mark Simoneau, who won the award for
the second straight week after 11 tackles, a sack and two stops
behind the line in the Wildcats' victory over Kansas
</P>
<P>
   Special teams: Colorado KR Ben Kelly, who returned the opening
kickoff 100 yards for a score in the Buffaloes' 46-39 overtime
victory over Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Riggs writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
