<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-     10-11 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING ABOUT BRADLEY IS VERY LIKEABLE, AND THAT COULD BE THE
PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fletcher Lokey drove 90 minutes to hear former Sen.
Bill Bradley, a Democratic candidate for president, speak at a high
school in southern New Hampshire last week, and he was not
disappointed. ``I was electrified,'' he said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked which of Bradley's policy positions he liked
best, Lokey, 50, paused, then conceded that he could not think of
one. He said he liked Bradley, a former basketball star, mainly
because of his personality, which struck him as honest and sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sensibility, a gut feeling,'' Lokey, a maintenance
worker, said. ``But a real strong one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lokey and others like him are both the central strength, and
potential Achilles' heel, of Bradley's insurgent campaign,
particularly in the flinty state of New Hampshire, site of the
nation's first primary next February.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, the endorsement of voters like Lokey _ disaffected
Democrats and independents who care deeply about character and are
attracted by Bradley's folksy style _ has propelled his campaign
from near obscurity into real contention.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bradley's sole Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore,
the inability of such voters to pinpoint accomplishments, or even
policy positions, of Bradley's indicates that the challenger's
support remains skin-deep. A steady dose of criticism against
Bradley, Gore's aides say, will move those voters toward Gore, or
at least away from Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people know what this guy's record is, they'll realize
Bradley's not what he claims to be,'' said one senior official in
the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Guided by that strategy, Gore and his surrogates have stepped up
their attacks on Bradley's character, integrity and voting record.
In Iowa on Saturday, before 3,000 Democrats at the
Jefferson-Jackson Day Dinner, Gore accused Bradley of being a
disloyal Democrat for having retired from the Republican-controlled
Senate in 1996 and for having voted for President Reagan's budget
cuts in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Newt Gingrich took over Congress and tried to reinforce
Reaganomics to try to force deep cuts in Medicare and Medicaid, I
didn't walk away,'' Gore said. ``I decided to stay and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has also tried to brand Bradley as a political
panderer who has shifted position on an array of issues to win
votes. One example: they say that Bradley voted against ethanol
subsidies and other farm support programs when he was a senator
from New Jersey, only to endorse some of those policies when he
started campaigning in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Gore campaign's strategy is focused on appealing to
core Democratic voters who may have been slipping slowly into the
Bradley camp. It may have already paid dividends: on Sunday, John
Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, said Gore would win the
endorsement of the powerful labor federation this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's response to Gore's aggressive new campaign has been
carefully measured, making him appear, oddly, more like a
front-runner than Gore. When, for instance, reporters asked Bradley
last week to respond to the assertion that he was a quitter, he
removed an imaginary dart from his shoulder, and said, ``I don't
think the American people want the politics of the dart board.''
</P>
<P>
   Such high-mindedness reflects a core belief of the Bradley
campaign: that voters will be drawn to him because they view him as
having integrity and strong moral character. Nowhere is that
clearer than in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In more than three dozen interviews with New Hampshire
Democratic voters in recent days, a majority expressed approving
assessments of Bradley's character, commonly describing him with
words like ``authentic,'' ``regular guy'' and ``real.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Bill Duschatko, 55, an Internet consultant who
came to hear Bradley speak at a middle school in Bedford, N.H.,
last week. Though Duschatko could not name policy positions that he
liked, beyond Bradley's support of abortion rights, he said he
respected the candidate's straightforward nature. ``Not so much
hucksterism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Duschatko, Bradley's decision to quit the Senate after three
terms actually demonstrated a strong character, showing that he did
not need a comfortable Congressional perch to run for president.
``I admire the way he handled himself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, New Hampshire looms as a crucial proving ground.
Many political analysts say he must win or finish a close second in
the state to stay alive as the campaign speeds into a dense clump
of March primaries, when the vast majority of delegates will be
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show that Bradley has pulled even with, or ahead
of, Gore in New Hampshire. Exhilarated by this initial success, his
campaign has opened a second field office in the state and begun
using hundreds of college volunteers to do weekend canvassing.
Bradley himself has visited New Hampshire almost every other week,
usually for several days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests that Bradley's anti-establishment campaign
could play well in New Hampshire, where voters have a reputation
for contrariness, having handed victories to underdogs like Pat
Buchanan, a Republican, in 1996 and Sen. Gary Hart, a Democrat, in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly aware of New Hampshire's independent streak, Bradley has
tried to cast himself as a reform-minded upstart. He calls Gore
``an establishment politician'' who travels in Air Force 2, ``while
I arrive in a van.'' He has made a central issue of weeding ``the
corrupting influence'' of big money out of American politics, a
line that almost always draws loud applause from New Hampshire
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   But more than his policy positions, or even his Hall of Fame
basketball career, it is Bradley's plain-Joe manner that seems to
attract voters in New Hampshire and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   He often slouches in his chair. He slams his hands into his
pockets as if they were pesky appendages that should be hidden.
When he speaks, he usually sucks on throat lozenges, which, when
amplified through a microphone, make loud clacking sounds when he
rolls them against his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Harris, 53, of Peterborough, N.H., said Bradley's lack of
polish made him seem warm. ``Even though Bradley is not a
charismatic speaker, he's honest, he's genuine,'' she said. ``It
feels like he just connects with people.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Alice Bruning, 34, a friend of Ms. Harris', said
the vice president seemed too well packaged.``He's too well
trained,'' she said. ``I don't feel that he's lived a regular
American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might expect Al Gore to ask what a scanning machine at a
grocery store is,'' she added, remembering President Bush's
campaign gaffe in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign has become adept at underscoring his rough
edges. In Iowa last week, he was introduced by a local supporter,
John Tapscott, who noted that just before the event, a strap on the
back of the candidate's tie had fallen off, causing the two ends to
dangle apart.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, Bradley fixed it with a piece of Scotch tape, which he
then proudly showed to the crowd as he took the podium to speak.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, the inability of many New Hampshire voters to identify
Bradley's positions on major issues could loom as a vulnerability.
In the recent interviews, few of the people who said they admired
Bradley knew much about his platform. Many were not even aware that
he had recently outlined a plan to make health insurance available
to almost all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Several who said they liked Bradley's homespun style expressed
doubts about voting for him when they learned about some elements
of his philosophy, which compared with Gore's, favors a more
expansive government role on a variety of issues, like gun control
and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Maryellen House, 42, the owner of a collectibles shop in
Concord, N.H., said she had little interest in Gore because, ``once
you're in office a long time, you forget the people.'' She said she
liked the way Bradley's campaign used hand-painted signs, which
indicated to her a more grass-roots style that might attract her
vote.
</P>
<P>
   But told that Bradley _ like Gore _ supports strong gun-control
measures, she paused. ``I kind of like John McCain,'' she said,
referring to the Arizona senator seeking the Republican
presidential nomination.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
