<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ RISES TO A RECORD AS DOW AND S&AMP;P 500 SLIP
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose to a record, propelled by a
handful of telecommunications and semiconductor stocks. However,
many traders were off for the Columbus Day holiday, leaving most
stocks little changed. The Nasdaq rose 29.38 points, or 1.02
percent, to 2,915.95. Meanwhile, most other major market averages
barely budged. The Dow Jones industrial average dipped 1.58 points,
to 10,648.18. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped 0.81
point, to 1,335.21.
</P>
<P>
   REVERSAL FOR GENERIC-DRUG MAKERS
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, generic versions of popular drugs were coming to
market with relative ease, and investors were clamoring for shares
of the tiny companies. But the group has had a rapid descent
recently. A raft of legal troubles from lawsuits to inquiries by
the Federal government have spooked investors, while the number of
drug introductions has stalled.
</P>
<P>
   COMMISSIONS CUT FOR TRAVEL AGENTS
</P>
<P>
   Three more airlines cut travel agent commissions to 5 percent
from 8 percent, following the lead of United Airlines and American
Airlines. Despite the loss in revenue from previous cuts, most
travel agents have demonstrated surprisingly strong survival
skills. The shares of most airlines declined. For example, AMR, the
parent of American Airlines, fell $2.4375, to $60.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines joined other large carriers in raising
leisure fares 3 percent to 6 percent after Continental Airlines
increased prices because of higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   DISPUTE OVER MINORITY BUSINESSES
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leaders and minority business groups have become
divided over what constitutes a minority-owned company. Many black
and Hispanic owners of large businesses are arguing that the
traditional definition _ a company in which members of minority
groups own 51 percent _ limits their ability to raise capital by
selling stock. But civil rights leaders and minority small-business
owners say that changing the definition will erode the idea of
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL CROSSING PUSHES INTO EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing made an aggressive push into Europe, acquiring
the telecommunications business of Racal Electronics of Britain for
1 billion pounds, or about $1.65 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET MAKER WARNS ABOUT PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Knight-Trimark, the biggest Nasdaq market maker, said that its
third-quarter income would rise less than analysts had forecast
because of fewer trades from Internet brokers, its main customers.
The company said earnings will be 17 cents to 19 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   3 COMPANIES IN LINUX ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   Trying to nudge Linux software into the mainstream of computing,
three companies are joining in an unusual collaboration to promote
Debian, a Linux operating system. Two computer makers, VA Linux
Systems and Silicon Graphics, and the specialist book publisher
O'Reilly &AMP; Associates are linking up to sponsor a broader
distribution of Debian. The use of Linux _ a free version of the
powerful Unix operating system created by a Finnish programmer,
Linus Torvalds _ has grown significantly in the last couple of
years because of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGES CONSIDERED IN BANK RULES
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, told bankers
that regulators were considering changes to deal with the huge
banks being formed by mergers.
</P>
<P>
   STAKE IN RUSSIAN FACTORY REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   A court in St. Petersburg renationalized a Russian porcelain
factory, annulling a majority stake held by an investment fund that
was backed by Congress and included the buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL EXPRESS CHIEF TO RETIRE
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Weise, the 55-year-old president and chief executive of
Federal Express, will retire in January and be replaced by David
Bronczek, the executive vice president and chief operating officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
