<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HISS-NIXON-TESTIMONY-     10-11 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISS-NIXON-TESTIMONY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSCRIPTS REVEAL NIXON'S ROLE IN HISS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Dec. 13, 1948, Richard Nixon, then a young congressman,
appeared in New York before a federal grand jury that was
investigating communist infiltration of the government. Two days
later, the grand jury indicted Alger Hiss, a former State
Department official, in a perjury case that became one of the most
divisive issues of the Cold War and thrust Nixon into the national
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Historians have only been able to speculate about what Nixon
actually told the grand jury, testimony that most believe was
pivotal in the jury's decision to indict Hiss and not to pursue
charges against his chief accuser, Whittaker Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than 50 years later, newly released transcripts of
Nixon's appearance before the grand jury show that Nixon, as his
critics have maintained, blatantly lobbied grand jurors to indict
Hiss, yet was more subtle and sophisticated in his approach than
his critics have ever given him credit for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been very close to this Chambers case from the
beginning,'' Nixon told the jury at one point, ``and my only
interest in it has been in attempting to get to the truth of the
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts help explain Nixon's reasons for wanting to
testify, suggesting that he believed he had to take a dramatic step
to protect the broad investigations of espionage within the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts of Nixon's testimony, which run to 51 pages, are
part of a larger trove of grand jury records, totaling about 4,200
pages, released by the Justice Department last week to a coalition
of scholars and historical groups that had sued for access to the
materials based on their historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   Many scholars now believe that Hiss was a Soviet spy, but other
questions remain, such as the extent of Soviet espionage in the
United States, the relationship between the House Committee on
Un-American Activities and the Justice Department, the use of grand
juries to indict dozens of people for perjury in the McCarthy era
and Nixon's role.
</P>
<P>
   David Vladeck, director of Public Citizen Litigation Group,
which represented the scholars, said the entire set of records is
to be released in Washington on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Peter Leisure, of U.S. District Court in New York, who
ordered the release after reviewing detailed summaries of the
transcripts, had ruled that an exception to traditional grand jury
secrecy should be made for the archive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court finds the public has a significant interest in
disclosure of Nixon's testimony,'' Leisure wrote. ``Grand jury
testimony by a congressional official allegedly attempting to
influence a grand jury's charging decisions is of inherent and
substantial historical importance.''
</P>
<P>
   A copy of Nixon's testimony was given to The New York Times by
someone who reviewed the transcript.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Craig, the historian who had initially filed the petition
to release the records and who has read the full set, said both
sides in the Hiss-Chambers debate are likely to find support for
their positions in the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But Craig said the significance of the records is in the way
they illuminate the other issues, ``and give a richness to the
historical record.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig characterized the Nixon grand jury testimony as ``the
speech that the American people never were able to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Another historian who has reviewed the archive, Sam Tanenhaus,
author of a biography of Chambers, said: ``You see the brilliant,
conniving, calculating but also the masterly Nixon. He knows where
to draw the line and he never crosses it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's arrival at the grand jury, whose term was to expire in
two days, was well chronicled. News accounts described Nixon, then
35, as entering the grand jury at about 1:40 p.m., clutching a new
calfskin briefcase, inside which were several canisters of film
negatives.
</P>
<P>
   The film was known as the ``Pumpkin Papers,'' photographs of
confidential Navy and State Department documents that Chambers
claimed Hiss had secretly passed to him about 10 years earlier.
(Chambers had turned them over to investigators for the House
committee after hiding them in a pumpkin on his farm in Maryland.)
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had been warned by a fellow congressman that the film
belonged to the House and should not be given to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon saw the film as crucial evidence of Hiss' guilt, was
convinced the Justice Department was not taking the investigation
seriously and feared the grand jury might seek to indict Chambers
for perjury instead of Hiss, Nixon later wrote in his book ``Six
Crises.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars have speculated that Nixon had pleaded with the jury to
indict Hiss, and not Chambers. He did neither, the transcript
showed, but rather, more subtly, built a case that sought to leave
the jurors with no alternative but to indict Hiss.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon declared that he did not intend ``to make a speech to the
jury,'' the transcript showed. But then he did make such a speech.
</P>
<P>
   He told the jurors that he had come ``solely as a messenger for
the House,'' thad the film, and that they could inspect it.
</P>
<P>
   Of Hiss' testimony before se committee, he said:
``Technically, he may not have committed perjury. He did lie.''
</P>
<P>
   And he offered a road map of how the jurors might find a way to
indict Hiss, suggesting names of witnesses they might subpoena,
questions they might ask, even advice on how to interrogate Hiss,
whom he called ``a very persuasive witness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that Mr. Hiss can be cross-examined,'' Nixon
explained, ``is by obtaining basic information and then confronting
him with that information and then cross-examining him
relentlessly, and I mean relentlessly, until the truth comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The individual jurors, who are not identified in the transcript,
emerged as an active and assertive group.
</P>
<P>
   When Nixon said he was barred from leaving the rolls of film
with the jurors, one reminded him that they and he are both working
for ``committees of the American government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't one help out another by leaving them here,
regardless of those laws?'' the juror said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon still refused. ``I will not part with the films,'' he
said later. ``If the fiinto evidence, I go with them.''
</P>
<P>
   A deal was later struck that allowed the jury to have copies of
the film.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon recounted the findings of the committee's investigation,
and suggested that the committee had been faced with exactly ``the
same conundrum'' as the grand jury in sorting out the statements.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Nixon laid out ``two lines of inquiry'' that the
jurors might take. One was to trace the State Department documents,
which were available to only four people _ Hiss, his boss, and both
of their secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that the grand jury would want to hear all four
of them on that point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also challenged the jury to closely examine Hiss' denials
that he was a communist, suggesting that it investigate Hiss'
``provable contacts'' with two suspected communists, ``both of whom
have rather extensive records.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the grand jury ``a very great American institution,
certainly as great as the Congress,'' Nixon said that if the
Justice Department ``does a proper job'' in presenting the case, he
was confident the jury would reach the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   But he also warned that if the jury was unable to indict because
of ``legal technicalities,'' allowing the guilty to ``go
scot-free,'' the committee would continue to pursue the case.
</P>
<P>
   Hiss was indicted two days later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
