<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3702 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     10-11 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Keeping Retirement Cash Safe 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: I am 44 years old and would like to retire within five years. I
have $250,000 invested in stocks, $400,000 in stock mutual funds in
my 401(k) plan, and a paper profit of $250,000 in fully vested
company stock options. Should I switch some of this money to
something safer to prepare for retirement?
<P>
   &QL; 
A: To answer with confidence, I would have to know more. Most
important is whether you have other significant sources of income _
a spouse's salary, for example _ and how much you think you will
need for living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, I am going to take a shot at this question because I
get many like it, and even a hypothetical answer might show people
how to think about this kind of problem.
</P>
<P>
   I am going to assume that you are single, that you will have no
other sources of income once you give up your salary, and that you
need about $50,000 per year to maintain a satisfactory standard of
living.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, you have little choice but to keep your funds
invested in the stock market. That will be risky _ the market
doesn't necessarily go up every year _ but anything less risky
won't pay you the return you need to retire so early.
</P>
<P>
   Your investments currently total $900,000. History suggests that
you can expect an average annual return of about 10 percent from
the stock market, including reinvestment of dividends. So your
expected annual return starting out would be $90,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   However, assuming that your $900,000 becomes $990,000 at the end
of one year, you would be imprudent to withdraw the entire $90,000
gain. Instead, you should leave extra money in the pot to guard
against inflation and large, unexpected expenses. (Speaking of
which, I hope you plan to maintain medical insurance because
without it, these calculations become extremely iffy.)
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of withdrawing 10 percent annually, you might want
to limit yourself to 6 percent. In that case, at the end of the
first year, you might withdraw as much as $59,400 (6 percent times
$990,000). That's plenty if all you need is $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   All this reasoning goes down the drain, however, if the United
States enters a long period of stagflation, such as it suffered
starting in the early 1970s. The cost of living soared, with annual
percentage gains in the Consumer Price Index eventually reaching
double digits. Meanwhile, the stock market hit some bad bumps and
went essentially nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   At age 44, you could have four decades or more of life ahead of
you. Anything could happen to the economy during that time _ and
probably will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Liquidating Stock
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My mother, who lives in a retirement home, has much of her
assets tied up in General Electric stock inherited from my father,
who was a longtime GE employee. Her stockbroker thinks that she
should sell some of the GE and diversify her holdings. However, the
cost basis for this stock is only half the current price, so the
capital-gains tax would be high. Mom doesn't need to liquidate any
assets now, but that might become necessary in two or three years.
When it does, should we sell the GE, or some other asset that would
leave her with a smaller tax bill?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: It's usually a good idea to diversify your investments, so I
can't fault your mother's stockbroker for suggesting it, even
though I have this irrational suspicion that he (or she) may just
be looking for commissions on the GE sale and on whatever you buy
to replace GE.
</P>
<P>
   The tax bite is not necessarily that big a deal. You don't
indicate how much money is involved, but if your mother sells, say,
$150,000 of GE stock and half of that represents a long-term
capital gain, she could be left with proceeds of somewhat more than
$125,000 after federal and state taxes. If she reinvests that
amount in stocks paying the same dividend as GE _ currently 1.1
percent of the stock value _ her dividend income would be reduced
by roughly $300 per year to $1,400 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Tax considerations always should take a back seat to investment
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   If you think GE is going to perform much better than anything
else in your mother's portfolio, then it might be a terrible idea
to sell it, even though this would provide greater diversification.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you think GE is going to be an inferior
performer, then you should sell it and taxes be damned. If GE was
about to tank, you'd be foolish not to sell it. Better to pay taxes
on a gain than to have no gain.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't consider yourself qualified to judge GE's
prospects, then you are taking too much risk by letting it dominate
your mother's portfolio. You might as well diversify the portfolio
and let her broker have those commissions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Y2K Safeguard
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the impending Y2K crisis, I am thinking of transferring
my employer-sponsored retirement account from a stock fund to a
government-security fund. When the crisis is over, I would just
transfer it back. What do you think of this plan?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: What Y2K crisis?
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, how certain can you be that whatever happens after
midnight on New Year's Eve will reduce drastically the value of
your stock-market investments?
</P>
<P>
   The present value of the stocks in your fund includes a
consensus of everybody's best estimate about the potential impact
of Y2K. If Y2K turns out to be significantly worse for these stocks
than the consensus believes, then yes, your stock fund will suffer,
at least temporarily. And yes, under those circumstances, a fund
invested in something safer like U.S. Treasuries probably will
perform better.
</P>
<P>
   But if Y2K turns out to be no more than a minor glitch and you
are holding a highly conservative portfolio, then you might lose
out on some growth in your assets.
</P>
<P>
   There is no definitive answer to your question, so do whatever
helps you sleep most soundly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
