<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3703 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INVEST-INVEST_SFCHRON     10-11 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INVEST </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Publishers Mine the Internet  
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
If you want to get a book published these days, it helps to include
the word ``Online'' in the title.
<P>
   Amazon.com, the Internet retailer, lists 1,090 such books for
sale. Among them are 15 whose titles include the phrase ``Online
Investing,'' and seven more with ``Online Trading'' in the title.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, ``Online'' is in: It helps to sell books. But in the
case of investment books, the ``Online'' titles often are
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   These books don't teach you the magically profitable techniques
you can use when you buy or sell securities online _ as
distinguished from trading over the phone with a live broker or
through an automated telebroker system.
</P>
<P>
   That's because there aren't any magical techniques. When it
comes to investing, your computer is simply another tool for
sending orders to your broker. You click a mouse instead of
fingering a touchpad or (God forbid) talking to someone.
</P>
<P>
   Online investing is a good thing for investors because they pay
lower commissions than they do with other types of order placement.
Brokers can charge less for an online transaction because it
entails minimal labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   That's about all there is to say about online investing _ and it
doesn't take long to say it.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, we have all these books.
</P>
<P>
   Before you buy one, thumb through it carefully, read all the
chapter headings, even read the first paragraph of each chapter. If
you are going to plunk down $25 (give or take), make sure you get
something you need.
</P>
<P>
   You can't always tell a book by its title.
</P>
<P>
   What you will find, more often than not, is a lot of general
investment advice that would be useful _ or, perhaps, useless _
regardless of whether you own a computer.
</P>
<P>
   If you want investment advice, you might as well buy the
classics, rather than these upstart efforts. If you have to read
just three, make them the following: ``The Intelligent Investor,''
by Benjamin Graham; ``One up on Wall Street,'' by Peter Lynch; ``A
Random Walk Down Wall Street,'' by Burton Malkiel.
</P>
<P>
   The new online investing books do have an online angle of sorts.
Many of them contain lists of Internet Web sites, such as
Microsoft's MSN MoneyCentral Investor (http:/
/moneycentral.msn.com/investor), Yahoo (www.yahoo.com) and
TheStreet.Com (www.thestreet.com), that can help you research
potential investments.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those Web sites are well known to investors with
Internet access. However, if you are behind the learning curve, go
ahead and buy a book.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that investment-research Web sites are
something to sneeze at.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many of them are extremely valuable _ light years ahead
of the resources available to individual investors before the
Internet caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   They are also infinitely easier to use. It no longer is
necessary to trudge to your broker's office, the public libraries
or the nearest Securities and Exchange Commission filing room. You
don't even have to leave your den.
</P>
<P>
   You can use research Web sites to dig out a company's financial
statements, create charts of its stock performance, read the latest
news about the company and keep abreast of analyst opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most remarkable and useful of all, some Web sites _
among them MSN MoneyCentral Investor _ allow you to run computer
screens on all the many thousands of publicly held companies, to
find the ones that fit your investment criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Using a computer screen _ which can sort through millions of
pieces of data in a few seconds _ you can cull companies by their
rate of earnings growth or price movement, by the ratio of their
prices to their book values, and scads of other criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Let's consider three online investing books at random. They
happen to be the three most recent ones to cross The Chronicle's
transom.
</P>
<P>
   _``Online Investing the Smart Way,'' by Stephen Littauer,
Dearborn, $19.85.
</P>
<P>
   This book, by a much-published financial writer, discusses the
features of some of the leading Internet research sites.
</P>
<P>
   It also contains some technical tips that could be useful to
investors who haven't previously bought or sold stocks through
their computers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it warns that brokerage Web sites have an
unfortunate tendency to crash on heavy trading days. To get around
this problem, it suggests that you open accounts with more than one
online broker. It also suggests that you sign up with more than one
Internet service provider, because ISPs also have their down days.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, however, the book drifts away from the online scene
and lapses into general investment advice that will seem familiar
and obvious to all but the greenest investors.
</P>
<P>
   Example: ``In buying stocks, select companies that appear to
offer the greatest chance for future earnings expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   This book ought to be renamed ``Investing for Dummies.''
However, that title has been taken.
</P>
<P>
   _``Online Investing,'' by Jon D. Markman, Microsoft Press,
$24.99.
</P>
<P>
   Markman is a former business editor and writer with the Los
Angeles Times, currently managing editor of Microsoft's MSN
MoneyCentral Investor Web site. He is a solid, sophisticated
thinker, and the book provides even veteran investment buffs with a
lot to chew on.
</P>
<P>
   Markman devotes the first part of his book to explaining his
proprietary method for screening stocks, using MSN MoneyCentral's
data-crunching capabilities. He favors so-called momentum stocks _
those whose prices are appreciating faster than the market in
general _ on the theory that ``stocks in motion tend to stay in
motion.''
</P>
<P>
   While you need to go online to use a stock screener and
experiment with Markman's stock picking criteria, it doesn't much
matter whether you place your trades online.
</P>
<P>
   He says his method works just fine if you initially buy a
portfolio of three to 10 stocks, then leave them untouched for one
year. He calls this technique ``yeartrading.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before the midpoint, Markman declares: ``If I've persuaded
you to become a dedicated yeartrader ... you have to go no further
in this book.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who choose to plow on, he launches into detailed
descriptions of just about every useful investment site on the Web
and how to use them to analyze stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Markman brings the discussion back time and again to his
Microsoft Web site, which he plugs unabashedly, describing it as
superior in various ways to other sites.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the interests of accuracy, the book should perhaps be
renamed ``Microsoft Rules.'' But no doubt the publishing company _
like its proprietor, Bill Gates _ was too modest to use that title.
</P>
<P>
   _``Day Trade Online,'' by Christopher A. Farrell, Wiley, $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   This is the oddball of the lot. It isn't about online research
and it doesn't offer a lot of warmed-over investment generalities.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it describes the author's own day-trading system.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, a New York hedge-fund operator, claims that he makes a
good living by trading in-and-out all day in New York Stock
Exchange stocks, grabbing a succession of tiny profits that add up
to hefty totals by the closing bell.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to follow his system, you can do it. His methods are
described in full, unambiguous detail.
</P>
<P>
   One catch: Farrell points out that you need at least $50,000 in
capital to start, because you will be buying and selling 2,000
shares of stock at a time.
</P>
<P>
   He also recommends that you use a broker that charges
commissions no greater than $10 per trade, because the profits (if
any) on each trade will be small _ only 6.25 cents per share. On
2,000 shares, that would amount to $125 _ minus commissions on both
the purchase and sale.
</P>
<P>
   You also need access to real-time stock quotes, including
current bid-and-ask prices and the amount of stock being bid for
purchase or offered for sale.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many brokers with commissions no higher than $10
per trade that provide this information, but there is at least one
_ Datek Online.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed bid-ask information is crucial, because Farrell's
system is designed to exploit the difference between what the Big
Board specialists are bidding and asking.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he might step in and bid slightly more than the
highest bid for 2,000 shares of a stock, then turn around quickly
and sell it for slightly less than the lowest asking price.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that method will only work with stocks that
aren't fluctuating. If the bid-and-asked prices suddenly move lower
while you are holding 2,000 shares of a stock, you are going to
lose money on that trade.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Farrell advises those who follow his method to
buy only the least volatile stocks, such as utilities and
closed-end investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this book should be renamed ``Buy and Pray.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
