<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEOPLESOFT-PEOPLESOFT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   PeopleSoft to Buy Vantive 
 &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
PeopleSoft Inc., a maker of business software, has agreed to buy
Vantive Corp., a struggling provider of customer service software,
for about $433 million in stock.
<P>
   Both companies have been hit hard this year by management
turmoil, a slow-down in sales and increased competition.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that while the deal will not solve the problems of
the two companies, it should leave them in a position of greater
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasanton's Peoplesoft _ which makes financial, human resources
and manufacturing software _ has lost ground of late to competitors
Oracle Corp., SAP, and J.D. Edwards. Company founder Dave Duffield
recently stepped down as chief executive, following the departure
of many longtime executives.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft today also preannounced third-quarter revenue of
about $300 million, or $50 million less than the $351 million
reported for the year-earlier period. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara's Vantive has consistently lost money, despite the
fact that it competes in the red-hot customer relationship
management (CRM) market. AMR Research predicts the market for CRM
software will grow from about $2 billion last year to $11 billion
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals such as Siebel Systems and Clarify Inc. have soared as
companies look to automate their sales force, call center and field
service operations.
</P>
<P>
   But Vantive has not kept pace. The company today reported
preliminary third-quarter revenue of approximately $42 million, as
well as a net loss for the quarter of between $0.16 and $0.18 per
share. The company lost nearly $5 million in the six months ended
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts questioned whether the PeopleSoft-Vantive merger will
lead to a dramatic reversal of fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination makes sense for both companies, although
announcing it under more positive circumstances a year or two ago
would have provided a lot more bang for the buck,'' said Charles
Phillips of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``PeopleSoft needed a
product suite in the CRM area since demand (for its other software
products) has stagnated.''
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft chief executive Craig Conway said customers were
constantly asking the company to add customer service and sales
applications to its core software offering. ``The value proposition
is greater for customers the more integrated your solution
becomes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Dobrin, an analyst with software advisory firm
Benchmarking Partners, noted that PeopleSoft and Vantive have been
partners for several years, so it's unlikely the companies will
have trouble merging the two product sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I think PeopleSoft will now be able to go to market
with more conviction,'' he said. Many of PeopleSoft's competitors
began adding CRM capabilities to their software suites more than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said Vantive chief executive Tom Thomas will become
general manager of PeopleSoft's new CRM division. He said Vantive,
which employees 600 people, would remain in its Santa Clara offices
and that he did not foresee a major reduction in staffing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not taking the approach of achieving immediate
financial gain through the elimination of redundant positions,''
Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in PeopleSoft yesterday fell 88 cents, or 5 percent to
$16.38. Vantive shares jumped $3.06, or 34 percent, to $12 on the
merger news.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
