<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAMSEY-1STWRITETHRU-C     10-11 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-1STWRITETHRU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grand jury in Ramsey case finds itself in eye of media storm
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ The JonBenet Ramsey grand jury reconvenes today
and, with expectations high that a decision could come at any time,
a media storm is gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are scrambling,'' said CNN producer Betty Anderson.
When the eight women and four men on the grand jury walk into the
Boulder Justice Center this morning, she predicted, they will run a
gantlet of more than 100 news reporters, photographers and media
crews.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury, which has met for more than a year to hear
evidence in the slaying nearly three years ago of a 6-year-old
girl, ends its term Oct. 20. So while it may or may not happen
today, Anderson said, the speculation mounts that this will be
remembered as ``The Week That Was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotels are filling up with news people. Reporters who straggled
into town Monday had to find rooms outside the city. Network news
shows such as ''The Today Show'' and ''Good Morning America'' are
calling local officials for interviews. But the TV networks have
had crews stationed here for months, setting up elaborate command
centers in places like the local Marriott and the top of a bank
building.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, NBC, FOX and CNN have all been ``wiring'' the place for
some time, finding the best sites for live shots, building sources
_ all in covering terious death of one little blond girl in
an otherwise quiet hamlet that is increasingly irritated by the
unwanted attention.
</P>
<P>
   The town's anxiety may peak today with a grand jury decision.
Talk around here is that the jurors may not wait until the last day
to issue their verdict. They can choose to indict one or ore
people, or not charge anyone and issue a report on their
investigation _ or simply do nothing, say nothing and walk away
from the case.
</P>
<P>
   Many townsfolk want to put the whole thing behind them,
believing it has not portrayed Boulder in a good, or accurate,
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``JonBenet put Boulder on the map, but it's a sad way to be put
on the map,'' said Julia Wrapp, who works in a small bookstore on
Pearl Street, a quaint stretch of shops and cafes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous, to spend all this time on a story about these
wealthy people,'' said John Putnam, 39, who owns a local car
dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the national news media has rarely strayed from the
JonBenet murder mystery. It has defined a new kind of story that
appeals as much to the tabloids as to the mainstream media. If the
O.J. Simpson story was the first blockbuster of the genre, then
JonBenet is the steamroller.
</P>
<P>
   The news coverage has sometimes made Boulder and its
institutions look bad. Accusations of blunders in the
investigation, accounts of vicious infighting between the police
and the district attorney's office, have left their bruises on the
town's image.
</P>
<P>
   Since the morning after Christmas of 1996, when JonBenet's body
was found, the media have chronicled the self-destruction of the
leadership of the Boulder Police Department. The police chief and
several top investigators have left the department.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been arrested or charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   John and Patsy Ramsey, the girl's parents, have been the primary
focus of speculation, but they steadfastly maintain their
innocence. Police do not suspect the girl's older brother, Burke.
Since the murder, the Ramseys have moved to Atlanta where they
remain close to other family members and JonBenet's grave in
Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Family members say the media attention has been a whole separate
tragedy for the Ramseys. In one moment of angst, Patsy Ramsey's
sister, Pam Paugh, exclaimed to a reporter: ''If Geraldo Rivera
calls my sister a murderer one more time, I will probably lose my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The slightest hiccup of news, or rumor of news, has repeatedly
drawn reporters of all stripes out of the woodwork. JonBenet's
beauty princess features have been pictured on countless tabloid
magazine covers; four times the story has made the cover of People
magazine. The death of the 6-year-old with the china doll face and
cascading blond curls, a former Little Miss Colorado, has fueled
debates on child abuse, on tiny-tot beauty pageants and on the
treatment of the wealthy when they come under suspicion of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this community tucked between the Rocky Mountains and the
Plains, between a rock and a hard place, is braced for yet another
wave of reporters and satellite trucks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Columbus Day holiday that kept the courthouse
closed, CNN made sure to have camera crews outside, just in case
somebody showed up and had something to say. This morning, yellow
tape will go up to mark off parking spots for the grand jurors, and
security staff will remind the camera crews to stay at least 25
feet away from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's disgusting,'' said longtime Boulder resident Ed
Amarant, 54. ``The media these days _ they blow everything out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Schneider writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
