<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-HOLY-LAND-2TAK     10-11 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HOLY-LAND-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFTING BODY AND SPIRIT  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first cable car in Israel was a makeshift contraption built
during the country's war of independence in 1948. Strung 160 feet
high across a valley below the walled Old City of Jerusalem, it
connected isolated Israeli fighters on Mount Zion with an outpost
to the west, and was used to ferry out wounded and lift in
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The car was a crude rectangular metal box long enough to carry a
stretcher, and it was cranked across the valley at night on a cable
that was dropped during the day to avoid detection by Jordanian
troops.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 years later, state-of-the-art cable car rides whisk
visitors in comfortable gondolas to five historic and scenic points
in Israel and Palestinian-ruled Jericho in the West Bank. Gliding
to spectacular cliff-side and mountaintop locations, the rides
provide easy access to some of the most popular tourist sites in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The newest ride, which began operating in July, is in Jericho,
the sleepy desert oasis about 15 miles northeast of Jerusalem that
was the first West Bank town handed over by Israel to the
Palestinian Authority five years ago under the 1993 Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   The cable way is part of a new tourism complex that will include
restaurants at the base and top, souvenir shops and a 55-room
three-star hotel. The upper restaurant is scheduled to open at the
end of the month, the lower one in November and the hotel in
February.
</P>
<P>
   A major goal of the project is to attract more tourists to the
historic sites of Jericho, which bills itself itself as the oldest
and lowest city in the world, 10,000 years old and 800 feet below
sea level. The private venture is financed by Palestinian
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The cable way, built by an Austrian company, climbs 547 feet to
a cliff-side monastery on the Mount of Temptation, where according
to Christian tradition, Jesus fasted for 40 days and was tempted by
the devil. The 19th-century Greek Orthodox monastery, a row of
stone structures perched on the cliff, was built on the site of a
Byzantine chapel and medieval church, among caves that housed
Byzantine monks from the fourth to seventh centuries.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, pilgrims have toiled up a steep path to the
site from the foot of the mountain. Now it's a five-minute ride,
and as many as 625 people can be ferried to the monastery every
hour. That prospect was unsettling at first to a 65-year-old monk
known as Father Gerasimos, who after 15 years at the monastery is
the longest serving of the four Greek Orthodox monks still there.
He guides visitors to a rock revered as the place where Jesus
fasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that people should walk up, as Jesus did,'' recalled
Kamel Sinokrot, vice president of the firm running the cable way.
``I told him that if Jesus were here today, he would prefer the
cable car.'' After trying the ride, the monk relented, Sinokrot
said.
</P>
<P>
   An account in the Book of Matthew (Chapter 4) makes it clear
that Jesus, led into the wilderness, did not need a cable car.
``The devil taketh him up into an exceeding high mountain and
sheweth him all the kingdoms of the world and the glory of them,
and saith unto him: All these things will I give thee if thou wilt
fall down and worship me.''
</P>
<P>
   A stunning panorama greets riders at the top: Jericho, with its
date palms and banana groves, the arid expanse of the Jordan
Valley, the northern end of the Dead Sea and the mountains of Moab
in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   New stone terraces and a small amphitheater furnish the heights,
and visitors can walk through small, empty cliff caves once used by
the Byzantine monks. The terrace restaurant will serve Middle
Eastern food during the day and French cuisine by night, when the
lights of Jericho glitter below.
</P>
<P>
   The ride up offers a bird's-eye view of two other historic
sites: Tel al-Sultan, an excavated mound opposite the base station
that contains the ruins of ancient Jericho dating back to the
eighth millennium B.C., and the remains of sugar mills built by
Crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   Amir Dajani, operations manager of the cable way, said that with
the expected tourism surge of the approaching millennium, he
anticipates as many as half a million visitors a year. In the
future, visitors will be able to combine the cable-car ride with a
trip to the neighboring Israeli-managed site of the Qumran caves,
where the Dead Sea scrolls were discovered.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 miles south is Israel's best-known cable-car ride, at
Masada, the rock fortress where Jews rebelling against Roman rule
made their last stand after the destruction of the Temple in
Jerusalem in A.D. 70. A sleek new cable car system was inaugurated
in Masada National Park in August in an effort to accommodate the
swelling numbers of visitors, replacing a smaller one installed in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   A fortified palace stronghold of King Herod, the Roman-appointed
ruler of Judea, the mountain, flanked by sheer cliffs dropping
1,300 feet to the Dead Sea, was where 967 Jewish rebels held out
against a Roman siege, taking their own lives before their refuge
was overrun in A.D. 74.
</P>
<P>
   The site was excavated in the 1960s, yielding extensive finds,
including palaces, bathhouses, vast storerooms and a synagogue,
mosaic floors and frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1972, it has drawn more than 10 million people from Israel
and abroad, and forecasts of more than a million visitors annually
have prompted an ambitious plan to upgrade the site. Besides the
new cable-car system, the plans call for a visitors center,
reconstruction of ruins and conservation of the frescoes and
mosaics.
</P>
<P>
   The new Swiss-built cable-car system, which can transport 1,200
people an hour in cars holding 80 people each, posed a challenge to
the preservation of Masada. The Israeli Nature and National Parks
Protection Authority held public hearings on how best to provide
access from the upper station, by bridge or tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bridge said it would be an eyesore, while
supporters argued that tunneling into the ancient mountain would
violate the integrity of a national landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was to build a wood-and-steel bridge to the summit
plateau from the upper station, which was bolted into the side of
the cliff to preserve the profile of the mountaintop. The result is
visible for miles around: the massive gray steel of the upper
station on the side of the rock, the struts of the bridge giving it
the appearance of a giant centipede.
</P>
<P>
   The ride up is dramatic. In the space of three minutes,
passengers are swung 928 feet up to a sweeping view of the Dead Sea
and the badlands of the Judean Wilderness in a vast depression that
is the lowest place on earth.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But there are still Israelis who, like the monk at the Mount of
Temptation, are uncomfortable with the notion of riding up to
Masada in a cable car instead of climbing the ancient Snake Path
that winds up the side of the mountain. For many Israelis, the
hourlong hike up was a pilgrimage, an initiation rite passed by
pupils, members of youth movements and soldiers who took their oath
of service on the summit. Legions of tourists have also climbed the
path, often before dawn, to witness sunrise over the hills of
Jordan to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Even the environment minister, Dalia Itzik, at the inauguration
of the new cable way, said: ``I prefer that twisting path. There's
something in that walk that makes you feel history every step of
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the northern port city of Haifa, a cable-car ride up biblical
Mount Carmel is also infused with history. At a promontory rising
steeply from the Mediterranean, globe-shaped gondolas climb 454
feet in three and a half minutes. Ascending from a promenade and
restaurant at the water's edge, they reach a commanding point at
the northwest corner of the Carmel range, an area revered since
antiquity as a holy place.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian inscriptions name it as a hallowed site, the Bible
describes a confrontation on Mount Carmel between the prophet
Elijah and priests of the Semitic weather god, Baal, and Greek
writings describe Cape Carmel as a place of worship of Zeus.
</P>
<P>
   Built by an Austrian company and run by a restaurant chain, the
cable car has been operating since 1985. As the gondolas glide up
the mountain, they pass Elijah's Cave, which according to a
fourth-century Byzantine tradition was the prophet's place of
refuge. The cave was first venerated by Christians, then also by
Jews and Moslems, and is now mostly visited by Jewish pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   Dominating the palm-studded summit is a monastery of the Roman
Catholic Carmelite order, which was founded in the 12th century by
monks who settled in Carmel caves and revered Elijah. Today, there
are 10 monks at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The imposing 19th-century structure, crowned with a dome and
bell tower, contains a hostel for pilgrims and an ornate church,
whose soaring cupola is decorated with paintings of Elijah, other
prophets and saints.
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of the promontory stands a lighthouse built in 1928
on what was the 19th-century villa of an Ottoman governor. Now an
Israeli military installation, the lighthouse building is called
Stella Maris, Latin for Star of the Sea, a name also commonly used
for the monastery.
</P>
<P>
   From a terrace above the top station, there is a view of Haifa
sprawling down the slope of Carmel and of the entire northern
coastline, stretching past Haifa Bay and the walled Old City of
Akko (also known as Acre) to white coastal cliffs on Israel's
border with Lebanon. The same scene, or a night view of Haifa, can
be enjoyed from two eating establishments superbly situated next to
the upper station: The Lighthouse cafe and the China Ribs
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   From a promenade stretching south along Stella Maris Road, the
pine and scrub-covered mountainside drops away against the vast
blue backdrop of the sea. Standing out against the Mediterranean is
a small white domed chapel along a half-mile walking trail that
winds down to Elijah's Cave, providing views of the sandy beaches
south of Haifa.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 miles north of Haifa, Israel's coastal road ends at
Rosh Hanikra, whose white cliffs are visible from the Stella Maris
lookout. There, a short, steep cable-car ride, down this time,
takes visitors to sea grottos on the border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Carved out of the chalk cliffs by pounding waves, the grottos
used to be accessible only to skilled swimmers who could make their
way around the bluffs, fighting currents and the pull of the tides.
Since 1968, visitors have been able to reach the grottos by cable
car on what its operators call the steepest and shortest cable way
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Narrow cars, which can carry 15 people each, gently descend a
60-degree incline, bringing visitors down the 224-foot cliff in
little more than a minute. A walkway through a tunnel hewn into the
rock provides changing vistas of the grottos, where sunlight is
reflected in the blue-green water.
</P>
<P>
   The cable way, owned and operated by the neighboring Kibbutz
Rosh Hanikra, was originally built by a Swiss company and upgraded
in 1987 by an Austrian firm _ the latest of a long line of
conveyances over the coastal cliff.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping off to the sea at the western edge of a high ridge, the
headland has served throughout history as a crossing point to and
from what is now Lebanon. Stairways carved into the rock were used
by travelers more than 2,000 years ago, and during World War II,
British forces built a tunnel and railway through the rock, the
remains of which can be seen near the lower cable-car station.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a gate across a road at the top of the cliff marks the
border between Israel and Lebanon. Although in recent years there
have been more than a dozen incidents in which guerrillas in
southern Lebanon have fired rockets into northern Israel, the
cable-car site has not been targeted and usually remains open, even
in times of tension.
</P>
<P>
   A drive 40 miles east and north along that border leads to the
longest and highest cable-car ride in Israel, at Qiryat Shemona in
the upper Galilee. From the southern entrance to town, the
French-made Manara Cliff cable way lifts passengers 2,374 feet from
the Hula Valley to the Naftali Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   A private enterprise financed by an Israeli investor, the ride
opened in August 1998, the brainchild of Kibbutz Manara members and
partly owned by the kibbutz. The seven-and-a-half minute ride
carries visitors past sheer cliffs and pine-covered slopes,
revealing views of Qiryat Shemona and the fields and fish ponds of
the Hula Valley, an expanse of farmland dotted by kibbutzim that
was once a swamp. The view from the gondola extends across the
valley to the Golan Heights and the looming Mount Hermon,
snow-capped in winter.
</P>
<P>
   The upper station is at Kibbutz Manara, where visitors can pick
apples in its orchards, swim in its mountaintop pool and have a
meal in the communal dining room, all for a fee. The biggest
attractions, however, are on the mountain itself.
</P>
<P>
   There are hikes on the wooded summit, following trails that loop
through stands of oak to dramatic cliff-side views of the valley.
There are bicycles for rent for a ride down the paved and rough
dirt roads that traverse the mountain. At the middle cable-car
station, you can rappel down a 135-foot cliff or scramble up an
artificial climbing wall.
</P>
<P>
   But even without the frenzy of activity, the swift, scenic ride
from the warm valley floor to the cool mountaintop is exhilarating
enough, ample proof that the geographic contrasts and rich history
of the land below can be appreciated anew from the lofty heights of
a cable car.
</P>
</TEXT>
