<HEADLINE>
ON FLORIDA HIGHWAYS, IMPALEMENT IS A THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (Eds: The word ASTERISK in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT26 and NYT27 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Some drivers here fear Interstate 95, for schizophrenic
traffic that plummets from 75 and 80 mph to tire-smoking zero,
without warning. They fear the long trains of bumper-to-bumper
drivers who speed just a few feet apart with no hope of stopping in
time.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, they fear trash.
</P>
<P>
   Every few months news anchors announce, with gravity but not the
least surprise, ``There has been another impaling on I-95,'' from
the debris that lies in wait, like booby traps in this concrete
jungle, for the unsuspecting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most recent drivers impaled on Interstate 95 and its
South Florida connectors was Chazz Campbell. He was driving home on
Sept. 18 when he saw a blur of metal flying at his car. The debris
hit the northbound lane, bounced and gouged through the floorboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a hot, burning, numbing sensation in my leg,'' Campbell
said. When he glanced down, he saw he had been skewered. ``I had a
2{-foot metal rod sticking in my leg, pinning me to the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dread that highway,'' he said. ``I've seen everything go
flying into traffic, everything from mattresses and lawn chairs to
car parts and large stones.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, three people have been impaled by flying
debris _ iron reinforcing rods, glass and other projectiles _ on
I-95 and its connectors between Miami and West Palm Beach. So far,
no one has been killed.
</P>
<P>
   It happens, drivers here say, because Interstate 95 and its
connectors have become a dumping ground, by accident and on
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual to be traveling at 75 mph down Interstate 95
and to see, smack-dab in the middle of four lanes, part of a
washing machine, a surfboard, a lawn mower or a twisted iron
reinforcing bar pointing like a spear at oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Although national statistics on impalements are difficult to
come by, South Floridians are convinced that the
Miami-to-West-Palm-Beach corridor must surely be the Impalement
Capital of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   James Hoffman, a limousine driver, was impaled while driving on
an I-95 connector, I-595, in April, when a 4-foot iron rod
shattered his windshield and bored into his right arm. Larry
Humphrey had to have glass flushed from his eyes when it came
flying into his face on I-595 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in one of the more terrifying accidents, 13-year-old
Stephanie Murray was traveling in the front passenger seat of her
mother's minivan when a reinforcing rod flew through the van's
windshield, passed through her chest and through her car seat. It
came within an inch of her heart, and it punctured her lung. She
survived, but she still coughs up blood and has trouble breathing,
said her father, James Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have thought that people would have taken this kind
of thing seriously when it happened to Stephanie,'' said her
mother, Denise Murray. ``It breaks your heart to see these things
happen again, month after month.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics responding to Stephanie's accident could not remove
her from the van, so they drove the van to the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel it, between my bones,'' Stephanie said. ``I
thought, `This can't be happening to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie still sees trucks with their tailgates down, nothing
but gravity holding down their cargo, and she cringes. ``No one
should have to go through what I went through,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The impalements are more dramatic, but debris has been blamed
for other bloody accidents here. They are usually not the big story
of the day, because they happen too often.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it has been one near-impalement after another on
South Florida expressways. In August, a Coral Springs woman escaped
serious injury when a metal rod struck her windshield, and in July,
an abandoned refrigerator door caused a three-car pileup. In June,
another metal rod went through the windshield of a car, landing in
the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Florida Department of Highway Safety and Motor
Vehicles counted 121 accidents in which cars collided with
``movable object on road'' along interstates in Miami-Dade, Broward
and Palm Beach counties, resulting in 73 injuries.
</P>
<P>
   When such accidents occur, television reporters announce that
``there has been another near-impaling.'' The most frightening this
year was the case in May of Debbie Tejeda, who was pregnant when a
metal rod lying on I-95 was struck by another car and flew into her
windshield. It narrowly missed her.
</P>
<P>
   The debris does not fall from the sky, but from the backs of
trucks traveling the densely packed lanes, said police officers who
investigate the crashes, and highway workers whose job it is to
clean up that mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do take it very seriously,'' said Delrish Moss, a detective
with the City of Miami Police Department. ``We have established a
phone line _ (ASTERISK)FHP _ where commuters can call and report
road debris. We have crews that try and get to it _ before anyone
else does.''
</P>
<P>
   In a part of the country where building codes are often regarded
as mere suggestions, it is little wonder that construction crews
ignore most safety precautions when loading the trucks that rumble
along the interstates. They pile concrete, reinforcing rods and
other building materials haphazardly on pickups and larger trucks,
say the drivers who share the road with them and wince and swerve
every time a brick comes hurtling off the bouncing truck beds.
</P>
<P>
   Murray thinks his daughter might not have been so terribly hurt
if the driver of the truck hauling the iron rod had taken a few
extra minutes to make sure his load was secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disgusting, it's frustrating, and you know it can be
prevented,'' Murray said. ``I feel like going out and picking up
every single piece myself. I wish I could.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the debris appears to have fallen off trucks or
to have been left along the highway by drivers working on their own
broken-down cars, some of it has been intentionally dumped.
</P>
<P>
   Work crews respond quickly to clean up such messes, but often
not quickly enough. ``They find just about everything,'' said Paul
Blanchard, resident maintenance engineer for the Florida Department
of Transportation in Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items routinely spotted on the interstates here,
besides the too-common construction equipment, are sofas, chairs
and mattresses _ there are a lot of mattresses. But there have also
been kitchen appliances, sinks, whole automobile engines and
transmissions, brake drums, bumpers, 5-gallon buckets, wheels and
tires _ not pieces of shredded rubber, but the whole thing _ and
dead buzzards. (Buzzards, common here, have a wing span of several
feet, and hitting them is at least as intimidating as striking a
dead dog.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, after the little girl was injured,'' said Pembrook
Burrows, a lieutenant with the Florida Highway Patrol, referring to
Stephanie Murray, ``we established a program called Roads, or
Removal of All Debris Safely,'' a joint operation of the Highway
Patrol, Department of Transportation and police departments from
Dade, Broward and Palm Beach counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We patrol the interstate to make sure that there isn't any
loose debris,'' Burrows said. ``If we see any on a moving vehicle,
we will pull them over and ticket them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the police and motorists take the hazards seriously,
some here in South Florida take an almost perverse pleasure in the
dangers, calling them ``Miami Moments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to laugh at,'' said Campbell, who manages a clothing
store in Sunrise Mall in the Fort Lauderdale area. ``It's mentioned
on the evening news, and people are amazed and shocked, for about
two minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
