A3717 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-ART-NYT &LR;      10-11 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BROKEN RIB MAY KEEP O'NEILL OUT FOR LEAGUE SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo NYT24 is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A distraught Paul O'Neill learned Monday that he has
a fractured rib on his right side and has been advised by his
doctors to bypass the American League Championship Series and wait,
hope and pray he has healed sufficiently to play if the Yankees
advance to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill underwent a magnetic resonance imaging exam Monday at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center that showed he has a
nondisplaced fracture of the 10th rib on the right side. Nevalee
O'Neill, Paul's wife, said the Yankees cannot give her husband a
cortisone shot because he has some internal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who admitted that the pain in his rib has remained
constant for several days, called his wife after receiving the
disturbing news. She took the call while waiting for O'Neill with
the couple's three children in the parking lot at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors told him that he should take this series off and
try to play in the next series,'' Nevalee O'Neill said. ``If he
tries to play, they said that he's going to feel the same way that
he did the other night. He's going to have trouble breathing when
he runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Dr. Stuart Hershon, the team physician, declined to
comment and the Yankees were typically quiet about O'Neill's
injury, General Manager Brian Cashman conceded for the first time
that there is a possibility the outfielder will not be on the ALCS
roster. But the possibility seems more like a definite, with Shane
Spencer likely to replace O'Neill, leaving the Yankees without
their regular No. 3 hitter and without the only outfielder whose
most comfortable position is right field. The roster is due to be
filed with the American League at 10 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Cashman was asked to comment on Nevalee O'Neill's remarks
about her husband's being advised to skip the ALCS, the general
manager did not dispute them and simply said:
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be able to play or he may not be able to play.
Tomorrow's a big day. We have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill injured himself Oct. 2 by crashing into a low wall while
pursuing a foul fly ball at Tropicana Field in St. Petersburg,
Fla., in a game against the Devil Rays, and he has shown minimal
improvement since. X-rays initially showed no injury, but he
aggravated the problem while running in the outfield in Game 2 of
the division series and did not play in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   He muttered ``lovely news'' when approached by reporters at
Yankee Stadium Monday after the exam but retained slim hopes that
he would recover in time to play in Game 1 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last four days I've done nothing,'' said O'Neill, who is 2
for 8 in the post-season. ``Tomorrow is going to be a day where I'm
going to have to go out and see if it's possible to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman had said that O'Neill's rib injury would not force him
to miss the ALCS, but the general manager revised his opinion even
before he knew that O'Neill's rib was fractured. The Yankees would
most likely play Ricky Ledee in right field, a position he played
for only seven innings during the season, with Chad Curtis and
Spencer sharing time in left. Both were nonfactors late in the
season as Spencer had 34 at-bats and Curtis just 25 in the final 31
games. While O'Neill had 19 home runs and 101 runs batted in for
the season, Spencer and Curtis combined for 13 and 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that with him in there we have a better chance of
producing a lot of runs,'' Darryl Strawberry said. ``That's the
most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee added, ``We're better with him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill will probably not be out there. As long ago as
Saturday, the 36-year-old O'Neill had questioned his availability
and said he might be out a ``long while'' if he did not get better
in 24 hours. Monday, O'Neill reported no improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I wake up and I feel it,'' O'Neill said. ``It
doesn't go away. I don't know if it's something I'll work through
or if it won't allow me to play.''
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neill first arrived at Yankee Stadium before noon and
before going to the hospital, he bumped into Manager Joe Torre in
the lobby and spoke ominously about his chance of playing. Before
O'Neill knew that he had a fractured rib, O'Neill told Torre that
he had to ``just go out there and see if I can play with it.'' The
two spoke briefly, and Torre ended the conversation by saying:
``We'll keep our fingers crossed. Maybe throw in a prayer or two.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Hours before O'Neill found out he had a fractured rib, it had
already been an exasperating day because he took his mother to
visit his ailing 80-year-old father in a hospital in Manhattan. His
father, Charles O'Neill, underwent a heart procedure last week, but
he developed a staph infection afterward and has had to remain
hospitalized longer than the family expected, creating more cause
for concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess those things happen when you're 80,'' said O'Neill.
``This can get pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have not announced their starting rotation for the
American League Championship Series, but it seems probable that
they will use the same alignment they used in the division series.
That means Orlando Hernandez would start Game 1, followed by Andy
Pettitte, Roger Clemens and David Cone. If Cone starts Game 4, it
will be his first start in 15 days. But Cone said, ``Joe can slide
me in anywhere that he wants.'' Hernandez was one of four players
at Yankee Stadium Monday, but he bolted by reporters and said,
``Tomorrow, tomorrow.'' Since the Game 1 starter has a news
conference Tuesday, Hernandez could have unwittingly offered a clue
that he will start the opener.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
