SUB-D.C.-HITECH-BOOM-3, 10-11 -- Construction cranes and a bicycle
are part of the scenery adjacent to the headquarters of America
Online where the company is expanding. A new, outside-the-beltway
culture has grown up in and around Washington. By at least one
measure, Washington is now the technological capital of the United
States. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- D.C.-HITECH-BOOM-2, 10-11
-- Melissa Moss, head of Women's Consumer Network, in her
Georgetown office. Moss, who has held senior positions in politics
and government for 20 years, says ``I wanted finally to run
something of my own.'' So she started the network, which offers
advice and special deals to its members, primarily through a Web
site. A new, outside-the-beltway culture has grown up in and around
Washington. By at least one measure, Washington is now the
technological cap the United States. (Shana Raab/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DULLES, Virg. -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- D.C.-HITECH-BOOM-1,
10-11 -- George Vradenburg 3d, a senior vice president for America
Online, outside his office. When Vradenburg drives downtown for
meetings, quite often he is asked: ``So, when did you fly in?'' A
new, outside-the-beltway culture has grown up in and around
Washington. By at least one measure, Washington is now the
technological capital of the United States. (Shana Raab/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- MARTHA-STEWART-2, 10-11 --
From left, Martha Stewart's book ``Healthy Quick Cook,'' her brand
of house paint, and one of the items produced under the Martha
Stewart Everyday label of bed and bath goods sold at Kmart.
Stewart's company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, which she hopes
to take public this fall, is the latest entry in a Wall Street
parade that stretches back at least to the 1950's, when Minnie
Pearl's Fried Chicken came to market on the strength of the country
singer's Dogpatch charm. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WESTPORT, Conn. -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- MARTHA-STEWART-1,
10-11 -- Martha Stewart with flowers in her office in January,
1998. Ms. Stuart bought control of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia,
from Time Warner, for $53.3 million in 1997. Her company, which she
hopes to take public this fall, is the latest entry in a Wall
Street parade that stretches back at least to the 1950's, when
Minnie Pearl's Fried Chicken came to market on the strength of the
country singer's Dogpatch charm. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TAMA, Japan -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- JAPAN-YOUTH-CRIME, 10-11
-- An exercise session at the Tama Juvenile Training School, a
reform school for boys an hour west of Tokyo by train. Youth crime
is one of the fastest growing criminal categories in the country.
And as schools across Japan, and towns large and small,
increasingly become the theaters for attacks by gangs, sexual
crimes and theft, Japanese authorities are sounding the alarm.
(Howard French/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- DISPUTED-SCHIELE, 10-11 --
In January the Manhattan District Attorney, Robert M. Morgenthau,
obtained a grand jury subpoena keeping two Egon Schiele paintings
once confiscated by the Nazis here pending his criminal
investigation into their ownership. Many of Morgenthau's peers are
wondering if his well-known rivalry with the United States
Attorney's office in Manhattan, now headed by Mary Jo White, right,
lead him to champion the popular cause. (Angel Franco, Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) FOXBORO, Mass. -- Oct. 11, 1999 --
FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-B&AMP;W, 10-11 -- Bill Parcells, then coach with
the New England Patriots, talks with Tom Coughlin of the
Jacksonville Jaguars during a game at Foxboro Stadium in September,
1996. Now in his fifth season as the Jaguars' only coach, Coughlin
is a graduate of the Parcells School of Design and Motivation. (Jim
Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- COLUMBUS-DAY-PARADE, 10-11
-- Mayor Rudolph Guiliani of New York, center, shakes hands with
members of the Veterans Corps of Artillery before marching in the
Columbus Day parade on Monday. The Columbus Day Parade stepped off
Monday with a lineup of officialdom, ethnic pride and kitsch.
Giuliani is expected to run for the U.S. Senate against first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- BBN-METS, 10-11 -- New York
Mets fans outside Shea Stadium on Monday hoping to get a chance at
buying Mets playoff tickets. Tickets for the New York Mets' home
games against Atlanta in the National League Championship Series
next weekend will go on sale Tuesday at Shea Stadium and by
telephone, team officials said. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE-2, 10-11
-- Dr. Gunter Blobel and his wife Laura Maioglio, walk from his lab
to the auditorium at Rockefeller University on Monday. Blobel was
awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine on Monday for
discovering that proteins carry signals that act as ZIP codes,
helping them find their correct locations within the cell. Blobel,
63, was born in Germany and earned his Ph.D. at the University of
Wisconsin. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE, 10-11
-- Dr. Guenter Blobel, a cellular and molecular biologist at
Rockefeller University on Monday. Blobel was awarded the Nobel
Prize in Physiology or Medicine on Monday for discovering that
proteins carry signals that act as ZIP codes, helping them find
their correct locations within the cell. Blobel, 63, was born in
Germany and earned his Ph.D. at the University of Wisconsin. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HOLLYWOOD -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- JOHN-RIDLEY, 10-11 -- John
Ridley at his Hollywood Hills home; an image of the singer Sade
fills the wall behind him. Certainly one of the most prolific
writers in Hollywood, Ridley, 34, is also credited with the story
for the new George Clooney film ``Three Kings,'' a dark comedy
about a group of soldiers in search of a fortune during the Persian
Gulf war. (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- EPHEDRA-DEBATE, 10-11 --
Sales of ephedra-based dietary supplements, like Metabolife 356, on
sale at the Port Authority Bus Terminal in Manhattan, are steadily
on the increase. Critics are concerned the nutritional supplement,
used by dieters, athletes, students and late-shift workers, not to
mention others simply looking for a jittery high, is a form of
``legal speed'' and say the herb, ephedra, is too easily abused.
(Aaron Lee Fineman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- MEDICINE-BALL, 10-11 --
Wendy Seyb, 27, a choreographer in Manhattan, works out with
trainer Jason White using various types of medicine balls. The
medicine ball, darling of the trimming and toning crowd before its
exile to six decades of exercise Elba, has bounced back. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAN DIEGO, Calif. -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- DRUG-REACTIONS,
10-11 -- Dr. Jay Cohen, who has written about the use of
perscription drugs, at home in his office. Doses of prescriptions
recommended in the Physicians Desk Reference may be too high for
many people and may cause adverse reactions, ranging from dizziness
and nausea all the way to death, according to Cohen's article
published last month in the journal Postgraduate Medicine. (Robert
Burroughs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- ATWATER-Q&AMP;A,
10-11 -- Tanya Atwater, professor at the University of California
Santa Barbara, in the Santa Ynez Mountains where she is touching a
portion of ancient seabed which folded up vertically following
pressure from the San andreas fault. Prof. Atwater, who early in
her career discovered how the western United States had been
developed and determined the role of tectonic plates. Now, she is
working on an animated film explaining earthquakes to children.
(Michael Tweed/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- EARLY-FLU-SEASON-2, 10-11 --
Flu vaccine is administered at the Manhattan offices of the New
York City Health Department last Friday. Health officials have been
surprised by early cases of the flu in several spots around the
nation, but they say that it is very hard to predict just how
difficult this flu season will be. (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- EARLY-FLU-SEASON-1, 10-11 --
An injection of flu vaccine is prepared at the Chelsea Immuniztion
Clinic in downtown Manhattan last Friday. Health officials have
been surprised by early cases of the flu in several spots around
the nation, but they say that it is very hard to predict just how
difficult this flu season will be. (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- INTERNET-ANNIVERSARY,
10-11 -- Dr. Leonard Kleinrock, a pioneer in the development of
Internet technology, standing next to the first Internet switch, an
interface message processor, in his laboratory at U.C.L.A. The
Internet revolution began quietly 30 years ago this month. A
strange amalgam of Defense Department money, engineering expertise,
and even a dab of countercultural idealism, slowly brought on the
Net we know today. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 11, 1999 -- TIGER-REVIVAL, 10-11 -- One
of the Bronx Zoo's Siberian tigers. Like a furred phoenix rising
from the ashes, or a creature cognizant of its nine-lifetime
warranty, the tiger has come back. Far from disappearing, the tiger
in some parts of its range in Asia is practically thriving, its
numbers measurably greater today than just a few years ago.
(Wildlife Conservation Society)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
