<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-ART-NYT &LR;      10-11 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATS, BALLS AND BARBS: METS AND BRAVES ARE READY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York Mets had not even arrived on Monday
afternoon, and the Atlanta Braves were already dismissing them,
flicking Manager Bobby Valentine's provocative remarks away like so
many foul tips.
</P>
<P>
   With Game 1 of the National League Championship Series still a
day away, the Braves warmed up to meet a team they dominated during
the regular season _ winning 9 of 12 games _ by smoothly assuming
the bemused air of the detached.
</P>
<P>
   If Chipper Jones had ignited much of Valentine's ire when he
tweaked Mets fans three weeks ago _ suggesting they drag their
Yankee gear out of the closet because the Mets were finished _ then
Valentine's comments Sunday about the Braves' perceived lack of
respect for the Mets, and then his rebuke of Jones for prematurely
predicting the demise of the Mets, seemed only to tickle the
Braves. It provided a pleasant diversion until the games begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves may have won the World Series only once in a decade
in which they have won eight division titles, but they have surely
learned how to win the war of words. As any child dealing with the
loudmouth in school knows, just hit him where it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his thoughts on Valentine, the voluble reliever John
Rocker, who once said he hated New York, responded with the
innocent smile of an altar boy and said: ``I look at the Mets team.
Seven of their nine hitters are .300 hitters, they have the best
infield in the history of the game, great bullpen, veteran starting
pitching. I'm really shocked to see how they had to squeak into the
playoffs with a one-game playoff. I thought they would beat us out
for the division, just looking on paper, at talent, theirs versus
ours. For us to still beat them 9 out of 12 times, I don't see how
Bobby Valentine could say a word.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. ``He's a pretty good talent evaluator,'' Valentine said in
response to Rocker. ``I guess he feels we underachieved.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more sober moments. Mets catcher Mike Piazza took
batting practice with his left thumb heavily taped, but said he is
likely to play Tuesday, because the swelling and stiffness caused
by a cortisone shot had subsided.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, the Mets will start Masato Yoshii, who allowed two
runs on four hits in six and two-thirds innings in the Sept. 30
game the Mets lost to the Braves by 4-3 in 11 innings. He will
oppose Greg Maddux, whom the Mets unbelievably clobbered for eight
runs on 11 hits in a 9-2 victory on Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves said that their regular-season dominance means
nothing in this series, that, despite the Mets' struggle, they had
always expected them to make the post-season. And the Braves say
they may do better than they did in the two previous league
championships _ losses to the Marlins and the Padres, respectively
_ precisely because they were challenged down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the season, there was not much time between the
clinching and when the playoffs started,'' Jones said. ``Everybody
might have gotten a little rusty before. You had to play for 150
games, then relax for 10 days and then have the biggest series of
the year coming up. You had to flip that switch on. We haven't had
to do that this year, and hopefully that will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that he was not as hot at the plate as he was when he
single-handedly clobbered the Mets three weeks ago, that all the
teams pitching around him had thrown his rhythm off, explaining his
slump _ he batted .231 with one run batted in against the Houston
Astros in the division series. Someone asked Maddux whether any Met
in particular gave him trouble. ``No,'' he replied, not immodestly.
Later in the day, Valentine found it within him to call Jones a
``super talent.''
</P>
<P>
   But if baseball was still the lead story, then the more
interesting subtext was the frisson of tension between the two
clubs. The Braves have not had a true rival since moving to the
East, Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox said, but their rival is whoever
challenges them each year in the division. That team this year was
the Mets, and Cox was quick to dismiss the notion Valentine had
proffered that the Braves somehow did not respect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a joke, a joke, the lack-of-respect angle,'' Cox said.
``I don't know where that came from. They've got our respect. They
have a lot of good players on that team and they're good guys. I
like them.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about Valentine, who three weeks ago leveled this
devastating critique of Cox, ``This year he had to manage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know Bobby Valentine that well,'' said Cox, who
is thought to disdain Valentine, though he has never said so
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine, who arrived hours after the Braves finished their
workout, seemed perplexed by all the fuss his comments had caused.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, he seemed to be conceding that perhaps he had gone
too far, saying ``things are said and sometimes all of us don't
think before we speak.''
</P>
<P>
   So, was Valentine conceding that he had gone too far in his
attack on the Braves? Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard them say anything other than we
underachieved,'' he said. ``Animosity? Our guys are loving, caring,
good fellows who just go about their business and just love to play
the game. I don't think there's any animosity on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves could finally agree with something Valentine said.
This should make things much better. It's not the players the
Braves dislike, it's the Mets' fans, they explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they weren't done; they came back from the dead, I
guess,'' Jones said of the Mets. ``I always say things in the heat
of the battle. At that particular time it was more of a shot at
their fans than their ball club. Bobby Valentine can turn it around
any way he wants. The last thing I want to do is get into a
newspaper war with Bobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feed off the crowd,'' Jones said. ``If the fans of
New York can't get you pumped up for a game, nobody can. You hear
things about your mom, about your wife, about your kid. It's pretty
rude. Without a doubt, they're the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The games cannot begin soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
