<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AHEAD AS 2 BIG UTILITIES CONTINUE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., N.H., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Consolidated Edison Co. reaches a deal to buy Northeast
Utilities, the combined company would have 4.7 million customers
stretching as far north as New Hampshire and would eventually be
able to sell cheaper power in the New York metropolitan region,
analysts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the two companies are continuing, a person close
to the discussions said Monday. But the negotiations could still
break down. Neither company would confirm the talks Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of both companies moved sharply last week on speculation
about a possible deal. Shares of Con Edison dropped by 7 percent on
concern that a merger with Northeast would depress Con Edison's
strong earnings. Shares of Northeast, meanwhile, rose more than 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Con Edison fell $1.875, to a 52-week-low of $37.1875.
Northeast rose 56.25 cents, to $21.125.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison, based in New York, had 1998 sales of $7.1 billion.
Northeast Utilities, which is based in Berlin, Conn., had 1998
sales of $3.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the utilities are in some ways very different,
analysts said that they were pursuing similar strategies and could
complement each other's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would make a nice fit,'' said Barry Abramson, a utility
analyst with Paine Webber Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison has pursued a cautious path under its chairman and
chief executive, Eugene McGrath, but is under pressure to expand in
the fast-paced environment of deregulation, where growth and size
are thought to be important.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Con Edison acquired Orange and Rockland Utilities
in New York state for $1.5 billion, adding to its customer base and
expanding its reach northward. It now has 3 million customers, many
of which need special high-quality power and require reliability.
An acquisition of Northeast, which sells power to 1.7 million
customers in Connecticut, New Hampshire and Massachusetts, makes
sense geographically.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if McGrath does not act quickly, another large utility,
like the National Grid Group of Britain, could snap up Northeast.
David Jones, the group chief executive of National Grid, said last
week that he wanted to make more acquisitions in the Northeast, a
statement that may have spurred Northeast and Con Ed to enter into
more serious talks.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Abramson said, the deal would combine Con Edison,
which has had steady and strong earnings and has been paying a
steady dividend, with a utility that has had large losses in recent
years and had to suspend its dividend four years ago because of
financial pressures caused by problems with its nuclear plants.
McGrath may be reluctant to acquire a utility that would further
depress his company's stock price and dilute its earnings. But
Northeast has put a lot of its troubles behind it and has seen its
earnings recover. It plans to reinstate its dividend in December
and also plans to sell its nuclear plants, which are now operating
well.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have faced criticism recently.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-hour blackout on July 6 and 7 in the Washington Heights
section of Manhattan, the worst blackout to hit the city in 22
years, left 200,000 people without power and raised a political
storm. The city has sued Con Edison, contending that the blackout
was caused by the company's failure to properly design and maintain
its network of cables that distribute electricity. The state is
also investigating the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast had losses in 1997 and 1998 because of problems at its
Millstone nuclear plant, which is owned by one if its subsidiaries,
Connecticut Light and Power Co. Unit 1 of its Millstone nuclear
plant is being retired and decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   Long failures at Unit 3 of Millstone also plagued the company,
which had to buy expensive replacement power and do costly
maintenance. The plant has resumed operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also settling lawsuits over its nuclear
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are heading in the right direction,'' said Robert Rubin,
a utility analyst for Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its troubles, the company, under its chairman, president
and chief executive, Michael Morris, has been preparing for
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   As Con Edison is, his company is under orders by state
regulators to auction off its power-generating plants as part of
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Northeast has created an unregulated
subsidiary that has aggressively bought other power plants as they
have come on the market, including making a winning bid for 13 of
its own hydroelectric plants.
</P>
<P>
   It has built up a pool of power plants that can provide cheap
power, which is being sold to customers throughout New England by
another subsidiary, Select Energy.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing arm has been able to win some big customers in the
region, offering long-term contracts to sell power and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that a merger would give Northeast an edge in selling
to Con Edison's customers.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers, who have so far been reluctant or indifferent to
attempts by outside marketers to persuade them to switch over and
buy cheaper electricity, may be more willing to do so from the
combined utilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
