<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: CUTS IN COMMISSIONS STING TRAVEL AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Ill.)  (Eds: Also moved in ``f'' category) 
(lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three more airlines cut travel agent commissions to 5 percent
from 8 percent on Monday, making the latest reduction in
commissions all but a fait accompli.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts by Delta Air Lines, Northwest Airlines and KLM Royal
Dutch Airlines, following the lead last week by United Airlines and
American Airlines, left the agent community shaken. ``It's going to
be devastating for lots and lots of travel agencies,'' said Mary
Berry Murphy, the owner of Berry World Travel in Omaha, Neb.,
echoing a concern widespread within the community.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines' success with electronic ticketing and Internet
booking capability has periodically emboldened them to reduce
commissions, but most travel agents have demonstrated surprisingly
strong survival skills.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, 49 percent of travel agencies now have World Wide
Web sites of their own, compared with 37 percent last year,
according to the American Society of Travel Agents, and 76 percent
of the trade group's members have online capability, up from 61
percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, these figures show that travel agents are using the
Internet to get the best deals for their clients,'' said James
Ashurst, a spokesman for the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Studies also suggest that many people who surf the Internet for
deals then turn to travel agents to make the bookings. For example,
a study this summer by NPD Online Research, which tracks consumer
buying and behavior, found that while more individuals are booking
travel online, ``56 percent of online travelers reported having
completed travel reservations with a traditional travel agent after
visiting a travel-related Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, NPD found, was ``the need for human contact and
assurances that reservations are correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Joe Galloway, the society's president, said, ``Despite the
doomsday forecasts by many industry `experts,' the Internet is not
carving away at travel agency profitability _ in fact, the exact
opposite is occurring.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is likely that some of the almost 1,800 retail travel
locations that went out of business in the first seven months of
this year did so at least in part because of the drop in revenue
from lower commissions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to lowering the rate, five airlines _ United, a unit
of UAL Corp.; American, owned by AMR Corp.; Delta; Northwest and
KLM _ like most other major airlines have imposed a $50 maximum
commission on round-trip domestic tickets and $100 on round-trip
international tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recently wrote a $3,000 ticket for a corporate client who
likes to travel first class,'' said Joy Wittmann, the owner of the
Joy In Travel agency in Metairie, La. ``A few years ago we would
have made at least $300 on that ticket. Now it's $100.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, travel agents have turned to other sources of
income _ in particular, cruises, which with commissions averaging
about 15 percent are the second-biggest source of agent revenue and
the fastest growing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many travel agencies now charge fees averaging
between $10 and $15 for writing or rewriting tickets, booking
hotels or rental cars and processing refunds. Already 75 percent of
agencies charge fees, compared with 64 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Murphy's agency, for example, charges fees of $10 and has
managed to reduce its reliance on the sale of airline tickets from
90 percent of the business to about 55 percent. To pick up the
slack, she sells more cruises and tours.
</P>
<P>
   Even with fees, a recent survey of 450 travel agencies found
that 90 percent of agencies that charge fees say they have retained
at least 81 percent of their clients; three-quarters say they have
kept at least 91 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, many travel agents believe that the combination of
commission cuts and direct online bookings has cut into their
revenues and profits _ and would have cut even deeper if the strong
economy of the last nine years had not emboldened people to keep
traveling.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Murphy said that she had been aided by participating with
about 375 other Midwestern travel agencies in MAST, a consortium in
Hinsdale, Ill. The group's collective strength helps independent
agencies receive favorable rates on business items like computer
rentals and marketing programs.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines hope to reduce their costs by cutting commissions.
United, for example, said that its commission cut is expected to
save about $150 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   American and Delta are not saying how much they expect to save.
Indeed, the releases announcing the cuts said that the carriers
would not offer any public comment about them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
