<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL CROSSING BUYING A TELECOMMUNICATIONS UNIT IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Global Crossing Ltd. said Monday that it had acquired
the telecommunications business of Racal Electronics PLC of Britain
for 1 billion pounds, or about $1.65 billion, in cash. The deal
signals an aggressive push by Global Crossing into Europe, even as
it absorbs the Frontier Corp. of the United States, a provider of
long-distance and local phone service.
</P>
<P>
   The move surprised some analysts, who had expected that Energis
PLC would acquire Racal, after reports in the British press and
briefings by executives at Energis that said a deal was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite surprised,'' said Mark Davies Jones, electronics
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney here. ``They kind of came from
nowhere with considerable rapidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the deal said the two companies began
talking for the first time two weeks ago and signed the agreement
on Sunday night. Global Crossing, a communications start-up concern
with headquarters in Bermuda, hopes to build and operate a
worldwide fiber optic telecommunications network rivaling AT&AMP;T and
MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The acquisition of Racal is a catalyst for accelerating our
European operation,'' said Thomas J. Casey, vice chairman of Global
Crossing, in an interview. Speaking of the pressure to outbid
Energis, he added: ``We knew we were in a competition, but it
didn't dictate the price. Our valuation dictated the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Energis is said to have bid about 790 million pounds, or $1.3
billion in cash and stock. A spokesman for Energis acknowledged:
``Racal would have been a very attractive acquisition for us at the
right price. But for us, the right price is a lot less than 1
billion pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   While Global Crossing paid considerably more for Racal than
Energis was prepared to pay, analysts said the price tag reflected
pricing more representative of an American company than a British
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a reassessment in the U.S. market ab
much these things are worth, and it has begun to spill over to
Europe,'' said James Ross, a telecommunications analyst at ABN Amro
here.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing said that the acquisition would allow it to cut
costs by $420 million and that it would increase its income by
2001. The acquisition gives it control of a modern 4,500-mile
network that is built along the British rail system into major city
centers, making it less reliant on renting phone capacity from
British Telecommunications PLC than some of its large competitors
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Racal's network is built very deep into the
local exchange network allows Racal to interconnect to customers at
the lowest level of charges,'' Jack B. Grubman, an analyst with
Salomon Smith Barney in New York, wrote in a report issued to
investors Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Global Crossing fell $1.4375 Monday, to $35.0625,
in NASDAQ trading of more than 30 million shares. Racal rose 16.25
pence here, to 4.6625 pounds; Energis gained 33 pence, closing at
18.25 pounds. The deal was reported Monday by The Wall Street
Journal, The Financial Times and others.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts do not expect Energis or a third party to
re-emerge with a competing bid. Executives close to Energis said
the company did not plan to make a counteroffer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
