<HEADLINE>
EVOLUTION CONFLICT CONTINUES TO SIMMER AT KANSAS BOARD OF EDUCATION
MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
 EVOLUTION-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evolution was a done deal in Kansas in August, but don't tell
that to the half-dozen persons who spoke Monday before the state
Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   They all wanted to talk about it some more.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the six condemned the board for voting 6-4 to downplay
the teaching of evolution. The two others _ a Hare Krishna leader
and Celtie Johnson of Prairie Village, a member of an area
creationist group, told the board that it was on the right track in
deciding that local school districts should determine whether
evolution should be taught.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has taken a bold and brilliant step in rejecting
Darwin's evolutionary theory as a scientific principle,'' said Hare
Krishna leader Danavir Swami, who was accompanied by several other
Hare Krishnas, all dressed in pale orange robes.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin provides ``no experiments and no intermediate forms
between species to back up his guesses'' that various species
evolved one from another without the need for an intelligent
designer, Swami said. ``Darwin bluffed the world with his
speculation and double-talk, but the Kansas Board of Education has
called his bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   Swami, who is director of the Hare Krishna college in Kansas
City, said later that he does not support any teaching of evolution
in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The board is holding its monthly meeting Monday and today at De
Soto High School. It is scheduled to take up the question today of
how to rewrite its new science standards, which are based on
wording from three national science groups. Those groups, upset at
the decision to downplay evolution, decided recently to deny Kansas
permission to use the wording.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairwoman Linda Holloway said Monday during a break in
the meeting that she was not sure how the board would resolve the
copyright issue or who might rewrite the standards. She said she
hoped to learn more about the board's options today.
</P>
<P>
   As for the comments from the public Monday, she said: ``I'm glad
we live in America and can have free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who criticized the vote on evolution were Ken
Bingman, a biology teacher at Shawnee Mission West High School, and
Douglas Ruden, an assistant science professor at the University of
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Ruden presented to the board the 1999 Ig Nobel Prize for Science
Education, a ceramic green iguana. The spoof prize was awarded to
the board recently by four Nobel Prize laureates in a ceremony at
Harvard University. The award is sponsored by a science humor
magazine for work that ``cannot or should not be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway told Ruden to leave the iguana with a person at the end
of the table. He did.
</P>
<P>
   One critic of the board vote tried to make his point outside the
high school. Dave Raffel of Shawnee wore a gorilla costume and
carried a sign that said the board ``has made a joke of science.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffel said he was starting a group called ``Save Our Schools.''
He said he planned to work to oust members of the board who voted
in favor of diluting the teaching of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-COLUMN-CHASS-NYT &LR;      10-11 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-COLUMN-CHASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES ARE FAN PROOF, JORDAN SAYS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brian Jordan laughed at the suggestion that the Mets'
manager, with some fairly outrageous comments on Sunday, was trying
to induce the Shea Stadium fans to assist the Mets by taking the
Atlanta Braves out of their game this weekend, when their pennant
playoff goes to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not at this level for nothing,'' Jordan said Monday.
``Gee.'' Then he added, ``The fans won't have any effect on our
play _ unless you jump out on the field and hit one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   As intelligent and as talented as the Braves right fielder is,
he was probably not too wise in raising that idea. One or more of
Manager Bobby Valentine's fan followers may actually try that
tactic.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have to come up with something different in their
attempt to beat the Braves one more time in the next week than they
did during the season, but mayhem doesn't seem like a good idea.
Stop Chipper Jones, all right; neutralize Jordan, for sure. But do
it with sliders and changeups and fastballs on the black, not with
cross-body blocks across the back of the knees of an unsuspecting
player minding his own business on the outfield grass.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves beat the Mets 9 of the 12 times they played this
season. The Braves won five of the six games the teams played in a
pivotal 10-day period late last month. The Mets can't afford to
allow the Braves to continue that pattern in the National League
Championship Series. If the Braves win four of seven or fewer
games, the Mets' march to the World Series will end prematurely. So
what to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some good information on them,'' John Stearns, the
Mets' advance scout, said at Turner Field Monday as the Mets went
through a brief round of batting practice. ``But you can get all
the information in the world; the guys still have to go out and get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Stearns had come from Houston, where he had watched the Braves
complete their division series victory over the Astros. In that
series, he watched Jordan rip Houston pitchers at the rate of .471.
He also saw Jones, who devastated the Mets here three weeks ago,
hit only .231.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chipper was more impatient than he was earlier,'' Stearns
said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor, the Braves' batting coach, had made the same
observation. ``They were pitching around him and he came out of his
way of hitting,'' Baylor said. ``He became so impatient that he
swung at a 3-0 pitch, swung at a first-pitch changeup. Normally he
doesn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the Mets didn't pitch around Jones, and he
banged four home runs and drove in 7 of the 13 runs the Braves
scored in their three-game sweep. In New York the following week,
however, the Mets pitched much more carefully to Jones, the Braves'
third baseman, and he collected only three singles and knocked in
two runs in 12 at-bats. But Jordan assumed the offensive load in
that series, showing the Mets the difficulty of the task they face
in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to not let Chipper Jones beat us,'' Darryl
Hamilton said. ``When we played here, he basically single-handedly
put us away. We can't let that happen anymore. But Brian Jordan is
hot now. With those two guys in the lineup, it's going to be tough
pitching around both of them. But we have to find a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets should not expect to see the impatient Jones the Astros
saw. Baylor said he planned to talk with him before Game 1 Tuesday
night and tell him to be aggressive and not be lulled into thinking
the Mets will pitch around him. Baylor, however, wasn't planning to
say anything to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets a man on,'' Baylor said, ``when he gets two
strikes, I'm at ease. I know one thing. He's going to put the ball
in play somewhere, off the end of the bat, off the knob, he's going
to put it in play and try to get that run in. ``He gets into that
bunker mentality. Not too many times he's not going to put a good
at-bat on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was hit on the right hand by a pitch in June and was not
much of a factor in the Braves' lineup for weeks. He was in so much
pain swinging the bat at one point that he wanted to call it quits
for the season. ``I was in so much pain, I basically had given up
on myself and it affected me mentally,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   But a method of treatment he called cross-friction, a painful
procedure, restored the hand and wrist to game-ready status. ``Now
I don't even think about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So this is what the Mets will confront, the tandem of Chipper
and Jordan, either one of whom can dominate a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got to make their choice and make their pick who they
want to pitch to,'' Jordan said. ``If Chipper and I don't do it,
Ryan Klesko and some other guys are going to do it. We play great
as a team. It's not Brian Jordan's and Chipper Jones' team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a team that will be affected by anything Valentine has
said or the New York fans may do this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's him,'' Jordan said, talking about Valentine's comments.
``It's not going to have an effect on one player in this
clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had a message for the fans, too. ``They'll be better off
not getting on me,'' he said. ``At this point it's not going to
make a difference. I'm so motivated, so pumped up. I love playing
in the limelight. I love when fans get on me. It motivates me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
