<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY IMMUNIZATIONS DROP AS NATIONAL AVERAGE INCREASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As the national immunization rate for
America's toddlers climbed to a record high of nearly 80 percent
last year, the statistic for Kansas City area children took a dive.
</P>
<P>
   In Jackson County the immunization rate fell from 90 percent in
1997 to 68 percent in 1998, according to statistics being released
today. Wyandotte County had the lowest percentage of five metro
counties, at 49 percent, down from 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clay, Platte and Johnson counties recorded slight declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed,'' said Bill Schmidt, administrator of the
Jackson County Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt and other public health officials blamed high turnover
at health agencies, inconvenient times for immunization clinics, a
failure to mail reminder cards to parents, and societal complacency
_ there is no raging disease to promote urgency, as polio did
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also pointed to a new culprit _ the growing
anti-vaccine lobby that uses the Internet to spread its message
that infants and toddlers can suffer permanent injury, illness and
even death from childhood shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movement is very vocal, and they are putting out a lot of
misinformation. The public is at a disadvantage,'' said Rosie
Howlett, a registered nurse and division head for preventive
clinical services for the Kansas City, Kan., Wyandotte County
Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the effect of the Web sites is difficult, because the
immunization rate for the country is at a record high. Still,
officials here say the movement could grow into a threat to public
health.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more visible Web sites is the National Vaccine
Information Center, which is based in Vienna, Va. Its home page
shows full-color photos of four toddlers _ two killed and two
permanently injured by adverse reaction to vaccines, said
co-founder Barbra Loe Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   She does not summarily denounce vaccines but staunchly
criticizes public health policy, which she says is designed to
protect society from disease while ignoring the knowledge that some
children will have adverse reactions from the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The message is that some are expendable for the good of the
many, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mother doesn't give birth to a child to sacrifice for the
good of society,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts acknowledge that adverse reactions to vaccines do
occur and may cause serious harm. But they say the incidents are
rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line _ the vaccine is safer than the disease,'' said
Leanne Glenn, maternal and children division manager at the Kansas
City Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   The new immunization statistics are to be released today by the
Partnership for Children as part of its 1999 Report Card, which
grades the well-being of Kansas City's youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   The rate is for children who have been fully immunized by age 2
for tetanus, pertussis, diphtheria, polio, mumps, measles and
rubella. The data are for children seen by public health providers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no strict accounting for immunization of children seen
at private clinics, but surveys indicate the rate is a few
percentage points higher than for public agencies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the National Institutes of Health recently
estimated Missouri's overall immunization rate at 86 percent, three
points higher than the partnership's 83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Childhood immunization was a key focus of the partnership in
1991, when it began its mission to improve the well-being of
children in the area. The advocacy group sponsored clinics,
encouraged health providers to mail reminder cards to parents and
pushed for an immunization registry.
</P>
<P>
   The rate rose. From 52 percent in 1990, it increased each year
to a high of 84 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson (of this year's drop) is you can't let up _ every
year brings new parents,'' said James Caccamo, partnership
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The group takes some of the blame for the low rate, Caccamo
added. Perhaps there was a nonchalance attributed to the series of
increased rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He faulted health providers, too, saying they failed to
consistently mail reminder cards to parents and were not being more
``family friendly'' by offering clinics in evening hours. Reminder
cards, which are sent to a child's home to tell parents when a shot
is due, are key to immunization efforts, Caccamo said.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is likely to explore ways to increase the
mailings, even perhaps bringing private doctors into a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, at the Jackson County Health Department, blamed high
clerical turnover for failure to mail reminder cards, and he agreed
with Caccamo that more evening clinics might be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said the department was also burdened by the new state
requirement of hepatitis B shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got behind and could never catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said the rate at the Kansas City Health Department held
steady at 79 percent, but she had a theory for declines elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immunization is a victim of its own success,'' Glenn said. ``I
remember children with measles and meningitis. Most people don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Howlett said there needed to be a more concerted immunization
effort by day care operations, churches and health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   She predicted that the anti-vaccine movement on the Internet, if
not met with a strong response, could mean an even lower rate next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who runs the vaccination Web site, says that is not her
goal. What she wants, she said, is for public health officials to
adopt a new policy that would consider each child individually. She
said children who were prime candidates for adverse reactions
frequently could be detected in individual screenings and family
histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they don't want to take the time to do that,'' according
to Fisher, who said her son suffered permanent brain damage from a
DPT shot in 1978. ``They just want to line these kids up and treat
them all the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she said, a more individual method would take more time and
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``But isn't that the role of a humane and civilized society?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
