A3748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-VANDY-COX     10-11 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VANDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vandy gives fans money's worth
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It's not often that you find money-back guarantees
in college football _or anywhere in sports _ but that's exactly
what Vanderbilt University did for its new football season ticket
holders.
</P>
<P>
   The Commodores made an announcement prior to the 1999 season:
Buy season football tickets and, if after the first three games
you're not satisfied with the ``Vanderbilt football experience,''
your money will be refunded.
</P>
<P>
   There were approximately 250 takers. And as of last Friday, the
deadline for refunds, only two ticket holders had asked for their
money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were probably Alabama fans, who just bought them to
insure they got tickets to that game,'' said Hunter Yuracheck,
Vanderbilt's assistant AD for marketing and promotions and the
brainchild behind the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt's 4-2 record has helped. With NHL and NFL franchises
now in Nashville, Yuracheck knew the Commodores were competing for
the local entertainment dollar. He needed some way to let people
know Vanderbilt football was a good product.
</P>
<P>
   The Commodores, who play host to Georgia Saturday at 2 p.m. at
Vanderbilt Stadium in Nashville, are coming off their most lopsided
win in 47 years, a 58-0 victory over The Citadel. The Commodores
already have knocked off one ranked team this season when they beat
Ole Miss 37-34 in overtime in Oxford on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt's other wins were a come-from-behind thriller over
Northern Illinois 34-31 and a 31-14 victory over Duke, which upset
Virginia recently. The Commodores lost to undefeated Mississippi
State 42-14 on Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept our 4-2 record, but I was looking for a little better
than that,'' said coach Woody Widenhofer, who's 9-19 in three
seasons at Vanderbilt. ``We had Alabama and Mississippi State at
home and I thought we had a shot at (winning) both of those. I
thought the toughest game would be at Ole Miss and that's the one
we won.
</P>
<P>
   ``But any time you're on track to win more than you lose, you've
got to feel good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially at Vanderbilt, which hasn't enjoyed much success in
the 1990s. In fact, it hasn't had a winning season since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Commodores, always good on defense under Widenhofer, are
suddenly getting it done on the other side of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 142 points all of last season, Vanderbilt has
scored 191 this season and is fourth in the league in scoring
offense. After starting three different quarterbacks last year, the
Commodores committed themselves to Greg Zolman this year and he has
responded with 1,143 yards passing, just 307 yards shy of the
school record for a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt has solid running backs. Sophomore Rodney Williams
had 127 yards and four touchdowns before being pulled at halftime
against The Citadel. Williams, with 354 yards and seven touchdowns,
is second on the team in rushing. Junior Jared McGrath leads with
376 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
