<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: EXECUTIVES STRESS IMPORTANCE OF BRAND NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. _ Famous brand names, of people as well as
products, were the name of the game on Monday at the second general
session of the 1999 annual conference of the Association of
National Advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   At the general session, held at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel here, top
executives of two consumer-product companies offered case histories
to illustrate the theme of the conference, ``Brand Building for the
21st Century.'' And a round table of network radio personalities
discussed _ to paraphrase the jargon of the self-help movement _
how to be your best brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have a strong brand,'' said David Vermylen,
president of the Keebler Brands division of Keebler Foods Co.,
``the retailer will dictate your strategy _ and your
profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermylen, named a Marketer of the Year by the trade publication
Brandweek during a dinner Saturday that opened the conference,
outlined how new management at Keebler is seeking to increase sales
and shelf space in stores by ``leveraging the power of the Keebler
brand'' as embodied by the company's longtime symbols, the cartoon
elf characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Keebler strategy is that as adults, we may not believe in
elves,'' Vermylen said, ``but we can believe in the spirit of
elves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is defining what is your brand essence,'' he added,
``what it is about the brand that creates that connection with the
consumer and the retailer.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Keebler cookies and crackers, Vermylen said, the
brand essence, or essential attributes, includes perceptions of
``uncommonly good quality, caring and fun,'' which become the focus
of advertising, promotions, packaging, store displays and other
marketing initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Elf Grahams, a line of bite-sized snack cookies
now being introduced, is being brought out in stand-up resealable
bags in elf shapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the bag is empty, you can reseal the top, cut off the
bottom and turn it into a hand puppet for kids,'' Vermylen said,
adding that he personally presented prototypes to heads of large
supermarket chains who ``think we're nuts'' _ but ``they love it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Cheez-It line of crackers, acquired when Keebler bought
Sunshine Biscuits in 1996, is being advertised for the first time,
Vermylen said, with sassy commercials by the Keebler agency _ Leo
Burnett Co., a unit of Leo Group _ that underscore the brand
essence as ``a bold, eat-them-by-the-handful snack.''
</P>
<P>
   The results? Cheez-It sales are expected to climb to about $360
million this year, Vermylen said, from $125 million in 1996, while
total Keebler sales should reach $2.5 billion, up from $1.6 billion
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Building very different types of brands _ toys and games _ was
the subject of remarks by Herbert Baum, president and chief
operating officer of Hasbro Inc., which sells products as disparate
as Monopoly, ``Star Wars'' figures, Furby dolls and Pokemon trading
cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get one shot at the brass ring,'' Baum declared, urging
the audience to become experts in ``fast-lane marketing for fast
times'' as trends accelerate ``at twitch speed'' in selling
name-brand products to increasingly sophisticated consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six-year-olds don't aspire to be 12-year-olds,'' Baum
asserted. ``They're already there. And 3-year-olds are playing with
CD-ROMs instead of dolls.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fast-lane marketing to capitalize on trends offers ``high
potential market share in a short time,'' Baum said, ``but it's
hard to maintain momentum'' and ``year two can be a cold shower''
as a hot trend fades.
</P>
<P>
   And there are unforeseen risks, he added, like the recent
earthquake in Taiwan threatening the supply of chips for a Furby
based on the ``Star Wars'' character Yoda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many we presold,'' Baum said, but now
``we're not sure we'll get them out for Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, there are benefits when the trends are in your
favor: ``I carry packs of Pokemon cards. I can get to the head of
any line, see any show, with Pokemon cards.''
</P>
<P>
   The radio round table was part of the sponsored portion of the
general session, paid for by five national radio networks. The
network executives were joined by five familiar radio
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all brands,'' Charles Osgood of CBS Radio Network, part
of Westwood One Inc., said of the five, ``in the sense that we have
a certain identity, have to maintain a certain quality and have to
bring something to the affiliates they can't bring to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Kasem, the longtime proprietor of top-40 countdown shows,
said, ``One word is more important than any other word:
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was starting out in radio in Detroit,'' Kasem recalled,
``there were DJs that were not very good, but they had an audience.
It was because these people were always bad, not good one or two
days a week.'' The audience laughed heartily.
</P>
<P>
   Kasem, who works for AMFM Radio Networks, and Osgood were joined
by Tom Joyner of ABC Radio Networks, a disc jockey in the ``urban
radio'' format; the talk-show host Rush Limbaugh of Premiere Radio
Networks; and April Ryan, White House correspondent for American
Urban Radio Networks.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is part of Walt Disney Co. AMFM is part of AMFM Inc., which
agreed last week to be acquired by Clear Channel Communications.
Westwood One is managed by Infinity Broadcasting Corp., a division
of CBS Corp. Premiere is a unit of Clear Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The conference also featured the presentation on Monday night of
the fourth annual Casie Awards for outstanding interactive
advertising and Web sites. ``Casie'' is derived from the Coalition
for Advertising Supported Information and Entertainment, founded by
the Advertiser Association and the American Association of
Advertising Agencies. The presentation was a curtain-raiser for the
general session on Tuesday, devoted to e-business.
</P>
<P>
   For best interactive ads for products, the winners were Kraft
Foods, part of Philip Morris Cos., and Modem Media.Poppe Tyson,
part of True North Communications. For best interactive ads for
communications, the winners were IN2 and Star Media.
</P>
<P>
   The award for best Web site for products went to Procter &AMP;
Gamble Co. and Grey Interactive, part of Grey Advertising, for the
Cover Girl cosmetics line. The award for best Web site for services
went to Continental Airlines and Blue Marble Advanced
Communications Group, part of MacManus Group.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is the 90th annual gathering of the Advertiser
Association, the trade organization representing the United States'
biggest marketers. It began on Saturday afternoon and is scheduled
to end Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
