<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TREATY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FIGHTING FOR THE TEST BAN TREATY  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Oct. 12:
</P>
<P>
   Despite the important contribution it would make to a safer
world, the nuclear Test Ban Treaty stands virtually no chance of
mustering enough support to win Senate ratification this week.
Proceeding with the vote under those circumstances would deal a
damaging blow to the foreign policy and military security of the
United States. The wiser course is to delay Senate action for at
least a few months, as President Clinton requested Monday, giving
the White House more time to overcome the arguments of treaty
critics.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican senators are recklessly insisting on an immediate
vote unless Clinton agrees to withdraw the treaty for the rest of
his term. That is something that he should avoid, because it would
signal to the rest of the world that the White House, not just the
Senate, is edging away from the Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refuses to be bound by such conditions. Nevertheless
some Senate treaty supporters, including Daniel Patrick Moynihan of
New York, are trying to put together a deal under which Clinton
would not give up on the treaty, while Senate Democrats would
refrain from pushing it in this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The message that Washington sends to the world matters a lot.
One audience consists of countries like India and Pakistan, which
are still trying to decide whether to sign the treaty and would be
unlikely to do so if the Clinton White House gave up on eventual
Senate ratification. For these countries to remain outside the test
ban would encourage a dangerous nuclear arms race in South Asia
that could easily draw in nearby countries like Iran and China. It
could also fuel the ambitions of other intermediate powers, like
Saudi Arabia and Taiwan, to join an expanding nuclear club.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of countries includes established nuclear nations
such as China and Russia. Like Washington, Beijing and Moscow have
signed the treaty but not yet ratified it, and are observing a
voluntary moratorium on nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Clinton continues to campaign for the Test Ban Treaty
and there remains a reasonable chance that Washington will someday
ratify it, these countries are likely to refrain from further
testing. But if hopes for eventual U.S. ratification recede, China
or Russia might be tempted to test again in an effort to improve
their bomb designs and narrow America's present lead in nuclear
weapons technology.
</P>
<P>
   These considerations argue strongly for delaying the vote rather
than giving up on it for this Congress. The treaty is backed by
America's military leaders, public opinion and Washington's main
allies. Good answers are available to the objections so far raised
by Senate critics. True, the election-year political calculus is
not favorable, and ultimately it may be necessary to wait until a
new president and a new Senate take office early in 2001. But U.S.
interests are best protected if in the interim Washington does not
disavow the treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SCHOOLS-FUNDING-NY     10-11 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-FUNDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT CHALLENGES N.Y. STATE'S WAY OF FINANCING PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state judge will hear opening arguments Tuesday in
a case that poses the most serious challenge yet to New York
state's method of financing public schools. The case mirrors
lawsuits around the nation that have often forced states to
allocate more money to poor schools.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in state Supreme Court in Manhattan and which
has already cleared several court hurdles, argues that the state's
school financing formula has deprived city students of their right
to a ``sound, basic education'' under the state constitution. The
plaintiffs, a coalition of advocacy groups called the Campaign for
Fiscal Equity, also accuse New York state of engaging in racial
discrimination by giving a disproportionate share of school aid to
districts outsiYork City. The city's student body is
overwhelmingly nonwhite.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the lawsuit could end the state's tradition of
meting out almost $13 billion a year to schools based largely on
political deal-making. It could force the state to raise taxes to
provide more money for schools in New York City and other poor
districts, or to find another way to sharply increase state aid to
those school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current formula, the city receives 35.5 percent of the
state's education aid, even though it enrolls 38 percent of the
state's public school children, according to the suit. The
difference of two and a half percentage points equals $318 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether all children are entitled to a decent
education in this state, and that means whether poor and minority
children are entitled to the resources necessary to provide them
with an adequate education,'' said Joseph Wayland, a lawyer for the
Campaign for Fiscal Equity. ``We know what it takes, we know they
don't get it, and the state is responsible for that shortfall.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in 1993, is similar to cases in other states
that seek to define an adequate education and force the state to
provide it. In New Jersey, a 28-year school financing battle ended
last year when that state's highest court accepted Gov. Christie
Whitman's plan to improve curriculums and school buildings in urban
districts. The court also ordered Mrs. Whitman to end a spending
disparity between the wealthiest and poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   And in Connecticut, the state's top court ruled in 1977 that the
school finance system was unconstitutional and ordered the state to
come up with a more equitable formula. A more recent suit charging
that inequities still exist is now in court.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the school financing suit that goes to trial
Tuesday follows a 1982 case in which the Court of Appeals, the
state's highest court, dismissed a similar challenge brought by a
Long Island school group. That group based its suit on spending
disparities between poor and wealthy school districts, and the
court ruled that such disparities did not violate the state
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The current case, however, focuses on whether the state has
failed to insure that students in poor districts receive the
minimally adequate education required by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The state tried to have the Campaign for Fiscal Equity's suit
dismissed, but the Court of Appeals ruled in 1995 that the case
could proceed in the lower courts and laid out an unusually
detailed blueprint to help the trial court determine whether the
current system is unconstitutional. A ``sound, basic education,''
the court wrote, ``should consist of the basic literacy,
calculating and verbal skills necessary to enable children to
eventually function productively as civic participants capable of
voting and serving on a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   But while many school financing suits have charged that the
education in poor districts is inadequate, New York's case is one
of only a handful that also include a civil rights claim. In its
1995 ruling, the high court said the state's school financing
system could be found in violation of the federal Civil Rights Act
of 1964 if the plaintiffs could prove two things: that the system
had a ``discriminatory effect'' on minority students and that other
``less discriminatory alternatives'' were available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
