<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     10-11 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES CENTER: WHAT A PLACE!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ L.A. might tumble, fumble and bumble when it comes
to building a new football stadium, but, oh, has it made up for its
legendary foot-dragging when it comes to erecting a new sports
arena.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, L.A. soon will unveil the most modern, the most
luxurious, the most aesthetically-pleasing entertainment edifice in
America when The Boss himself, Bruce Springsteen, performs the
opening show at the Staples Center on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   As I donned a hard hat and walked through the $375 million
building the other day, I felt the same feelings of awed rapture I
had the first time I walked through the Superdome in New Orleans,
the Sky Dome in Toronto and even the Pond in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. has two dilapidated football sanctuaries in the Coliseum
and Rose Bowl. It has two other athletic places, the Forum and
Sports Arena, destined for the junk heap. And its 37-year-old
baseball outlet, Dodger Stadium, soon will be undergoing serious
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   But now, finally, L.A. has something it can gloat about.
</P>
<P>
   It possesses the creme de la creme of modern sports arenas.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the Staples Center would be state of the art, but it has
turned out to be even more impressive than what I had envisioned, a
roomy, 150-foot, 11-story-high structure with 1,200 TV monitors, a
$1.5 million sound system, 55 restrooms, 11 escalators, 10
elevators, 160 luxury suites and 14,000 seats with pleasing views
of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you can't see what is unfolding on the floor, or ice
from those 5,400 seats in the upper reaches of the arena. It's just
from that faraway vantage point Shaquille O'Neal will look small
enough to be riding a horse at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   The lobby area is immense, and there will be six minority-owned
fast food outlets---two McDonald's, two Pizza Huts, a Panda Express
and a Camachos---catering to hungry customers along with the
Staples Center's own culinary outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will starve, or get thirsty in this place,'' said
Michael Roth, the Staples Center's publicity director.
</P>
<P>
   When you first venture into the Staples Center, two features
immediately catch your attention---its architectural beauty and
sheer size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two and a half times bigger than the Forum,'' says Roth.
</P>
<P>
   It looks big enough to house a football team, which it will do.
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. Avengers of the Arena Football League will play their
home games at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, will the Lakers, Clippers and Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have 200 dates filled up for our first year in
existence,'' says Roth.
</P>
<P>
   The Staples Center has only four luxury boxes still unsold, with
the other 156, 8 to 14-seat suites having been purchased by various
corporate entities and wealthy individuals for anywhere between
$197,000 to $307,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those with tickets to luxury boxes and premier seats will have
access to the Arena Club, a high-end bar-restaurant that will be
off-limits to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Still another exclusive refuge will be the Grand Reserve Club,
restricted to a membership of 200 with annual fees at a cool
$10,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place will have its own wine cellar and cigar room,''
says Roth.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-sided scoreboard is another sight to behold, with four
Mitsubishi video screens and four message boards.
</P>
<P>
   It also looks to be at least four times larger than that dinky
one at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Natch, the Staples Center is abundant in high-tech gimmickry,
with something called the Pacific Bell Wireless Fan Access Hotline
available to the patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say a baby-sitter wants to get hold of you at the game,
she pages us with your seat number,'' says Roth. ``And we'll take a
cell phone to your seat for you to make a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Journalists attending Kings' game will sit in the Bob Miller
Pressbox, named after the Kings' long-time announcer.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be a Chick Hearn Press Room, named after the
venerable voice of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The imposing downtown arena, located at 11th St. and Figueroa
next to the Convention Center, figures to present a traffic
nightmare for its clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll probably take people a year, but I'm sure they'll find
short-cuts on how to get in and out of here,'' says Roth.
</P>
<P>
   The Staples Center already has proven to be a stellar attraction
for the downtown professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of attorneys, stock brokers and other business
types in the city buying season tickets,'' says Roth.
</P>
<P>
   As I sat in one of the purple-colored seats in the upper
concourse, a Mark McGwire home room from the floor, a young
construction worker laboring near the top inquired about the price
of tickets for Laker games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top ones go for $150 and the lowest are $10,'' said Roth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I guess this is where I'll be watching the games,'' said
the young construction worker. ``I'll just bring my binoculars. But
I'll be coming. I wanna be part of this place.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the strong feeling here that a lot of people around L.A.
are going to want to be a part of this dazzling new monument.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
