u f BC-RUSSIA-INVEST-NYT &LR;      10-11 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN COURT ANNULS U.S. INVESTORS' STAKE IN A PORCELAIN FACTORY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's shaky foreign-investment reputation weakened
further Monday when a court in St. Petersburg ruled that the
255-year-old Lomonosov porcelain factory be renationalized,
annulling a majority stake held by executives of a prominent Wall
Street buyout firm and an American-financed investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Alistair Stobie, vice president of the $440 million United
States-Russia Investment Fund, said it planned to appeal the ruling
that voided the ownership interests of his organization and those
of executives in Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co..
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision on a case brought by the Russian Ministry
of State Property against the porcelain factory is the latest in a
series of disputes over the last year that have eroded foreigners'
investments in Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Dart Group, for example, is struggling to prevent a share
issue by the Russian oil conglomerate Yukos that would dilute
Dart's stake in a Yukos subsidiary. BP Amoco PLC is trying to save
a half-billion-dollar investment in a now-bankrupt Russian oil
company, Sidanko.
</P>
<P>
   and other, smaller deals gone awry have supported the
widely held view abroad that Russia's market is a volatile one
unworthy of significant investment because most major Russian
companies, and perhaps even the government itself, flout
shareholder rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work with start-ups who understand the importance of sound
corporate governance,'' Stobie said. ``But 90 percent of the
factories that existed under the Soviets still don't understand it.
They think an equity investment is a no-interest loan.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund was capitalized by Congress in the early 1990s to
encourage direct investment into the Russian economy, and so far,
it has invested about $240 million. The fund has spent about $4.25
million since September 1998 to purchase slightly more than 25
percent of the Lomonosov plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Kohlberg Kravis executives, through a holding company called
the International Porcelain Co., invested about $4 million of their
own money and acquired a similar-size holding. The rest of
Lomonosov is owned by current and retired employees and by two
offshore companies.
</P>
<P>
   The factory, Russia's oldest and most famous porcelain works,
was purveyor to the imperial court and, in modern times, the maker
of china praising the achievements of the Soviet state. During its
heyday, Lomonosov was regarded highly enough that museums all over
the world carried its porcelain sets. ``We invested because of the
brand name,'' Stobie said. ``There are very few high-quality
porcelain brands in the world, and this is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Soviets, however, and recent ragged years of reform,
the quality of Lomonosov china had steadily declined, Stobie said,
and the factory today is unprofitable. The investment fund had
planned to invest in new equipment, he said, to improve the quality
of the porcelain being turned out.
</P>
<P>
   But since their initial investment late in 1998, the fund and
the International Porcelain Co. have had severely limited access to
the plant and its books, mainly, they say, because of a hostile
management that, like many from the Soviet era, view outsiders as a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in June, the Ministry of State Property filed suit against
the Lomonosov plant to annul the privatization, based on what it
called an error in the factory's original incorporation in 1993.
Fund officials have said they suspect the suit was initiated at the
request of Lomonosov management to fend off the foreign investors.
Officials at Lomonosov and the property ministry could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stobie, the three judges hearing the case
deliberated for 15 minutes before repealing the privatization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
