<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GINGRICH-DIVORCE-COX     10-11 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-DIVORCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich seeks to depose wife's friend
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: Ohio editors.)
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Newt Gingrich wants to question one of his wife's Ohio
friends who served as a witness to the couple's 1987 separation
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Villio of Warren, Ohio, and Marianne Gingrich have been
friends since before she met Newt Gingrich in the late 1970s.
Marianne Gingrich, 48, grew up near Warren, in the small town of
Leetonia.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the 56-year-old Gingrich filed a motion asking a Cobb
County, Ga. judge for permission to depose Villio, 54. The motion
was not specific about what Gingrich hopes to learn from Villio.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for both Gingriches did not return phone messages left
at their offices Monday afternoon asking for comment. Efforts to
contact Villio failed.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Gingrich already has received permission to depose a
number of her husband's friends and associates, including his
closest adviser, Joe Gaylord. Callista Bisek, a 33-year-old
congressional aide, also has been subpoenaed to testify about her
relationship with Newt Gingrich. A judge will make a final ruling
next week on Bisek's motion to toss out the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Villio signed her name as a witness on the Gingriches' 1987
separation agreement that split everything from bank accounts to
furniture. Under the agreement, Marianne Gingrich was to be paid
$12,000 in alimony over six months. The agreement was drafted by an
attorney in Ohio, where Marianne Gingrich had gone after splitting
with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich and Marianne Gingrich first met in Ohio and
married there in 1981. Marianne Gingrich was a planner for Trumbull
County. She moved with Gingrich to Jonesboro, Ga., then part of
Georgia's 6th Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's divorce lawyer, Tom Browning, said the couple's 1987
separation lasted six years. The Gingriches reconciled about a year
before Gingrich became speaker of the U.S. House in early 1995,
Browning said.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Gingrich and her attorneys won't confirm the length of
the separation. But during that period, the Gingriches made several
high-profile appearances together, including at a 1988 campaign
debate and at the 1992 Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1998 book, ``Lessons Learned the Hard Way,'' Gingrich
writes of leaning on his wife for support in May 1988, when he
filed ethics charges against then U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright:
``Maybe the loneliest day of my career was the day when Marianne
and I walked hand in hand down the corridor to the Ethics Committee
to file charges against the incumbent speaker. She stood by me when
it seemed no one else would.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Gingrich would still have been paying alimony to
Marianne Gingrich under their separation agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Duane D. Stanford writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
