<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A LABOR LIFT FOR GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Oct. 12:
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO endorsement of Vice President Gore, which is
expected tomorrow, will give him a badly needed boost in his battle
against Bill Bradley. Indeed, had Gore failed to secure the backing
of organized labor this week, his campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination would have been heavily damaged. But the
lift comes with a cost, because it reinforces the vice president's
problems as an insider too friendly with the Washington
establishment and too eager to please Democratic constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the labor endorsement is important in the Democratic
contest. That is why Bradley and his aides worked hard to try to
head it off. He argued that both he and Gore had good labor
records, except for the fact that both endorsed the North American
Free Trade Agreement, and that there was no reason for labor to
choose one candidate over another at a time when it was not clear
which one would get the nomination. Even with his outsider stance,
Bradley will have a hard time denigrating the endorsement after
working so hard to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are enjoying the Democratic fight, hoping to tie the
eventual winner to the traditional Democratic interest groups. Yet
among many Americans, labor may not be the demon it once was. Labor
lost heavily in trying to combat trade agreements early in the
Clinton administration. But it has come back with some big
victories since then, most notably on the minimum wage, using the
budget surplus for Social Security and Medicare and, most recently,
pushing for a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Many moderate Republicans sided with Democrats on these issues,
and a strong bloc from both parties has prevented Republican
leaders from enacting anti-labor provisions in campaign finance
reform and other legislation. Gore's alliance with unions could, in
fact, portend that for all the talk about the ``new Democrats'' and
President Clinton's centrist approach on welfare and fiscal policy,
the coming election could well turn on the traditional cleavage of
many recent American elections: Republicans favoring tax cuts for
business and the wealthy and less government for everyone else, and
Democrats favoring more spending for health, education and the
environment. If that is the general-election agenda, either Gore or
Bradley will be happy to have labor in his corner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
