<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PFIZER SAYS IT GAVE TO GROUP THAT PAID FOR 2 PATAKI TRIPS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another large New York-based corporation with
significant interests in Albany said Monday that it had contributed
to a nonprofit trade group that paid for two trips by Gov. George
Pataki to Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation, Pfizer, the pharmaceuticals conglomerate, said
it had given $5,000 to the group, the Hungarian-American Chamber of
Commerce of New York and New Jersey, shortly before the governor's
first trip in 1995. ``We did make a contribution back then to the
trip,'' said Bob Fauteux, a spokesman for Pfizer. ``We were happy
to support the governor in his outreach to Hungary.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer, which owns factories in New York and is closely
regulated by state environmental officials, is the fourth
corporation to disclose its involvement with the chamber and trips.
The others are another drug company, Bristol-Myers Squibb; Philip
Morris, the cigarette maker, and Pepsico. All four companies were
also big donors to the private corporation that Pataki set up to
pay for his 1995 inaugural.
</P>
<P>
   During an appearance Monday at the Columbus Day parade in
Manhattan, Pataki defended the trips, saying the one in 1995 had
led to the construction of a new glass factory in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a more than $300 million investment, the largest
industrial investment ever upstate, from Guardian glass company
because of that trip _ hundreds and hundreds of new jobs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Ethics Commission is considering whether to
investigate the trips, which took place in September 1995 and
October 1996. Pataki aides have said he and others in the
administration were not aware of any corporate donations to the
chamber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
