<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3765 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-STRANGE-HNS     10-11 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-STRANGE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The quietly driven, history-laced leadership Ben Crenshaw
brought to the U.S. Ryder Cup team last month will be replaced soon
with the fiery personality of Curtis Strange, several sources said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Strange, 44, has agreed to be the U.S. captain for the 2001
Ryder Cup team, which will play the Europeans at the Belfry Golf
Club in Sutton Coldfield, England.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of 17 PGA Tour events in his 23-year career, Strange
will be charged with leading the Americans into what no doubt will
be a hazardous road trip to the Europeans' turf. It is that
daunting task that had one notable PGA Tour player, speaking on the
condition of anonymity, applauding the choice of Strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great contrast this is going to be in the U.S.
captain,'' said the player. ``Ben was so reverent and led with a
quiet passion. Curtis is going to be more like a football coach
leading his team out of the tunnel onto the field. He's going to
create a great atmosphere for the American players, especially
because they'll be playing in really hostile territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtis is absolutely pumped about it. And the players will
have a different sort of respect for him once they see those fiery
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the PGA of America, which selects the U.S. Ryder
captain, are expected to formally announce Strange's appointment
soon. No PGA representatives could be reached for comment Monday.
Traditionally, they announce their captain for the next Ryder Cup
in the first month or two after one is played.
</P>
<P>
   Until the PGA has named Strange, nothing is official. But
several executives in the golf world said Monday that Strange is
the only name on the PGA's list.
</P>
<P>
   Strange's personality is a feisty one, and that defiant attitude
should bode well for the American team he will lead across the
pond. He also is well-respected among the crop of players who will
compose the 2001 team.
</P>
<P>
   One of Strange's hobbies _ Harley Davidsons _ should give fans
an insight into the sort of captain he might be. He walks, or
rides, a little on the wilder side than does Crenshaw, who prefers
a John Deere tractor to a motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   Following Crenshaw as captain will be no easy task. Crenshaw
used historical frames of reference and his own good vibes to stoke
the Americans to a record comeback during the Sunday singles Sept.
26 at The Country Club. The Americans trailed 10-6 but won eight
matches and halved another on Sunday to pull out a 14{-13{ victory,
reclaiming the Ryder Cup for the U.S. after Europe had won it in
1995 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the U.S. won in Europe was at the Belfry in '93.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw already has removed himself from consideration for
leading the U.S. team a second time. Other players, such as Payne
Stewart and Mark O'Meara, still are in the prime of their playing
careers and likely will be future candidates for the captaincy.
</P>
<P>
   Strange, who won the U.S. Open in 1988 and '89, has reduced his
playing schedule in recent years to devote more time to his work as
a television analyst for ABC. He has been the network's lead golf
analyst since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He has won more than $7 million in his career and was the tour's
leading money-winner in 1985, '87 and '88. He was the first player
to earn more than $1 million in a season, doing so in '88.
</P>
<P>
   Strange played on five Ryder Cup teams and had a 6-12-2 match
record. But lack of success in the event doesn't have any bearing
on success as a captain, as Crenshaw proved. He was 3-8-1 as a
player in four Ryder Cups but pulled out the biggest comeback in
Cup history as a captain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GENERIC-DRUGS-595&AMP;ADD     10-11 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERIC-DRUGS-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERIC DRUG MAKERS IN A `HUNKERING DOWN' CYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, the chief executives of the United States' largest
generic drug makers seemed almost giddy.
</P>
<P>
   Generic versions of popular drugs were coming to market with
ease, and investors clamored for shares of the tiny companies. The
stocks of two prominent ones _ Watson Pharmaceuticals, best known
for its estrogen-replacement therapies, and Forest Laboratories, a
maker of the popular anti-depressant Celexa _ each roughly doubled
in value in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the group has had a rapid descent recently. A raft of legal
troubles from lawsuits to inquiries by the federal government have
scared away investors, while the number of drug introductions has
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Standard &AMP; Poor's Drug index has slipped 6 percent
this year, the stocks of the generic companies have in some cases
lost a third or half of their value.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executives are hard pressed to explain the sudden
reversals of fortune. ``Not a lot of drugs have come off patent
this year,'' said Fred Wilkinson, chief operating officer of Watson
Pharmaceuticals. ``Everybody is just hunkering down. But within the
next two years, more drugs will come off patent. That may change
the business cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   William Fletcher, chief executive of Teva Pharmaceuticals
U.S.A., one of the largest makers of generic drugs, said,
``Everybody is suffering from a lot of lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mylan Laboratories struck exclusive deals last year with
suppliers of raw materials necessary to make two anti-anxiety
drugs, the Federal Trade Commission accused the company of trying
to monopolize the market. The company asked a federal court to
dismiss the case but got nowhere. Analysts now worry that Mylan's
mounting legal bills could dent the company's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Other generic makers face some serious court challenges over the
deals they have made with the drug giants. At issue is the practice
of accepting a payment from a branded drug company to delay the
introduction of a competing generic or to avoid patent litigation.
</P>
<P>
   People with knowledge of its investigations say the FTC is
considering filing a complaint against Hoechst Marion Roussel and
Andrx Corp., a maker of specialty pharmaceuticals and generic
drugs, over a deal they made to delay a generic version of
Hoechst's Cardizem CD, a treatment for high blood pressure, from
entering the market.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is investigating similar agreements between
Zeneca Pharmaceuticals, part of the giant Astra-Zeneca global drug
concern, and Barr Laboratories, a generic company, over the
breast-cancer drug tamoxifen, and between Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. and
Sepracor, a specialty pharmaceuticals company, to develop an
improved version of Prozac, according to people with knowledge of
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, Mylan's case with the FTC has put the company's
shares under pressure,'' said David Saks, a managing director of
Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``But I don't think the FTC investigations will
change anything. This may be more for a warning.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Mylan Pharmaceuticals are off 41 percent this year,
closing Monday at $18.50. For the quarter ended in June, Mylan's
earnings fell 6 percent from a year earlier, and analysts have
forecast a slide of more than 6 percent in the next quarterly
report.
</P>
<P>
   Since the FTC's investigation of Andrx was disclosed late last
month, the company's stock has tumbled 23 percent, to $46.0625,
well off its $78 high in June. Even the stock of Watson
Pharmaceuticals, which has not been reported to be the subject of
an FTC investigation, fell 54 percent this year, to $28.9375.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Litigation has long been a cornerstone of the generic industry.
To get a generic drug to market, companies must sometimes fend off
a patent infringement suit.
</P>
<P>
   Such courtroom quarrels sometimes amount to David vs. Goliath
battles. Andrx has been sued by Glaxo Wellcome and Hoechst, among
others. Andrx had $8 million in earnings last year; Glaxo, $1.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher and Wilkinson complained in recent interviews that
their annual legal expenses had swelled to about $4 million each.
For Watson, that amounts to a 200 percent increase from two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   With litigation fears depressing the stocks, some stock pickers
now consider them undervalued. Analysts expect Andrx earnings, for
example, to jump 221 percent from the year-earlier period to 45
cents a share in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, generic drug companies point to a better pipeline
of new products. Drugs worth some $13 billion in sales over the
next three years are coming off patent in that period. Last year,
drugs with just $1.4 billion in sales came off patent, virtually
the same as is expected this year, according to Gruntal &AMP; Co. The
generic drug companies will record a combined $9 billion in sales
this year, up 9 percent from last year, by Gruntal's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Some expect the FTC investigation to eliminate exclusivity deals
and ultimately open the market wider for generics. Even if it does,
it will crimp some companies' revenues along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Andrx, for example, was to receive $100 million a year from
Hoechst to keep its generic version of Cardizem CD off the market.
The deal was scrapped in June, but only after Andrx had earned most
of that amount, when the companies settled their patent dispute.
</P>
<P>
   A more open market could put more pressure on the generic
companies to continue merging in hopes of better economies of
scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to drug volume, the generic makers are going to
do quite well,'' said Sergio Traversa, a pharmaceutical analyst at
Mehta Partners. ``But there is so much competition within the
generic industry, that it is always going to be difficult to make
money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
