<SLUG> BC-NY-DEAD-BABY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD NEW BORN FOUND IN MIDTOWN GARBAGE CAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A newborn baby was found dead in a garbage can on one
of New York City's busiest corners Monday, leading the police to
canvass the streets and hospitals of midtown Manhattan in search of
the mother.
</P>
<P>
   The infant girl, who had been stuffed inside a black plastic
shopping bag, was found by a maintenance worker at 9:40 a.m. as he
began to empty the can on the southwest corner of Broadway at 32d
Street, the police said. Inside the bag, the worker found the baby
wrapped in a multicolored quilt, which featured Disney characters,
and a pink blanket with the word ``Baby'' embroidered in white
stitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the top off and there it was,'' said the worker, Robin
Toppin, who empties the can as part of his normal rounds for the
34th Street Partnership, a business improvement district that helps
keep Herald Square clean.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said they did not believe that the baby had
been there very long because Toppin had emptied the can only 90
minutes earlier, at 8:10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Chief William Taylor, the commander of detectives in
Manhattan, said the baby was about 12 hours old and appeared to
have died before it was been placed in the garbage can. He said
there were no signs of trauma, visible wounds or blood on the baby
and that the umbilical cord was still attached when it was found.
``The body appears to have been kept clean,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the City Medical Examiner's
office, said the coroner would not offer an opinion until an
autopsy had been completed today.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators closed the busy commercial stretch of Broadway on
which the baby was found, just a block from Pennsylvania Station,
and questioned store owners and passers-by in their effort to track
the mother. Detectives checked with area hospitals to see if a
woman had come in requesting postpartum care without a baby, and
they dusted the shopping bag and garbage can for fingerprints. They
also used a bloodhound to search Greeley Square, sniffing for
anything that might have revealed the baby's trail to the garbage
can.
</P>
<P>
   But the police had few clues to go on, except that the shopping
bag had come from a clothing store on Fulton Street in Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
