<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3768 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-COLUMN-LADN-(SLAN     10-11 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS HOCKEY A LUXURY ITEM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now for something completely different.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? How different is hockey, the passion of the great
white North and about 10,000 zanies in Los Angeles, from baseball,
our national pastime?
</P>
<P>
   After making the move from one sport to the other about 10 days
ago, I have concluded the answer is: not that much.
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance down the Kings bench shows Canadians, Swedes,
Slovaks and Finns. Not much change from the Dodgers clubhouse,
which has Americans, Dominicans, Mexicans and a Korean. There used
to be a pitcher from Japan and now the top minor-league prospect is
from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza once said he thought the Dodgers chemistry problems
stemmed from having so many players from different cultures. This
is a situation hockey has faced for many years. The Detroit Red
Wings won two Stanley Cups with a heavy Russian population. But
around the sport you still hear that European players are soft, not
big on going into the corners to get pucks or opposing players.
</P>
<P>
   When the Staples Center opens for sporting events Oct. 20 with a
game between the Kings and Boston Bruins, know that the Dodgers
will be watching closely to see how the city responds to luxury
boxes. They've never been available in this town, a town that was
happy to see its team on warm summer nights or through basic cable
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is a sport that has a lousy television contract and needs
ticket money to stay afloat. Despite its almost unlimited
resources, Fox is desperate to find new ways to make the Dodgers,
who claim they have lost $45 million in the last four years,
self-contained.
</P>
<P>
   They want to dive into the revenue stream of luxury boxes. But
will it work in L.A.?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it will be interesting to see whether new Kings coach
Andy Murray becomes the next Tom Lasorda or the next Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Kings love Murray's structure and attention to
detail. He has rules and a schedule. But he never played the game
at this level.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda was a career minor-leaguer who had just a few games with
the Dodgers and Kansas City in the 1950s. As a manager, he won two
World Series and went to the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Collins had structure and attention to detail during his years
managing the Angels. He had rules and a schedule. He also had a
midseason mutiny with his players, who did not respect him because
he hadn't played in the majors. They didn't think he could relate
to their problems, so he became the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Collins resigned in September, knowing he would get fired. So
did general manager Bill Bavasi. Bavasi didn't play the game
either. But neither did his father Buzzie, who was GM for the
Dodgers during four World Series championships.
</P>
<P>
   Murray has an impressive resume as an NHL assistant and as a
head coach for Canada in international competition. Kings captain
Rob Blake played for Murray and his endorsement helped Murray get
the job.
</P>
<P>
   But spliced among the victories in the team's season-opening
road trip were a loss and a tie that showed flaws in the club.
Players are rarely good at looking in the mirror. If the team
doesn't make the playoffs during its first year in the Staples
Center, somebody will be responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Will Murray be viewed as the ``Little General'' or an
overbearing control freak?
</P>
<P>
   As Terry Collins well knows, the answer can depend on the day.
</P>
<P>
   __ And another thing: Obviously the big difference between the
two sports is popularity in this country. When baseball decided to
clip the power of the umpires union by firing 22 of its members, it
was painted as the decline of Western Civilization.
</P>
<P>
   When Dallas Stars forward Mike Modano was nearly paralyzed after
getting cheap-shotted into the boards by the Ducks' Ruslan Salei on
opening night, the story was buried outside hockey circles, even
though it easily represented the biggest issue in the sport:
</P>
<P>
   How do you clean up hockey when the fans it so badly needs love
fights and violence?
</P>
<P>
   The NHL walks a tightrope between selling a fast and extremely
physical game and protecting its marquee players, who are the
primary targets of overly aggressive play. During games, the teams
run video highlights of the best hits of the week, many of which
are grounds for suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two teams played without incident Friday night at
the Pond, Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg has been portrayed by some
people around the league as leading a dirty team.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Hartsburg, who walks with a limp from a
cheap-shot incident during his playing career, would have been
teammates with Modano if he hadn't retired prematurely from the
injury. Hartsburg left the Minnesota North Stars in January 1989
and Modano played his first game with the same team during the 1989
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players needed: Colorado center Adam Deadmarsh is back after
suffering a hip pointer in the final exhibition game and the
Avalanche is hoping left wing Shjon Podein (knee surgery) returns
Wednesday when the club opens its new arena, the Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   Top center Peter Forsberg is out until December after undergoing
shoulder surgery, but getting back Deadmarsh and Podein certainly
will help. The club also signed left wing Dave Reid last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deadmarsh, who has 98 goals the past four years, will center a
line with Chris Drury and Milan Hejduk. Drury played center during
the first week because Deadmarsh, who was going to play center in
Forsberg's absence, wasn't able to play.
</P>
<P>
   __ No frauds allowed:Edmonton became the first NHL team to put a
microchip in its uniform tops for identification purposes. This was
because of the retirement of former Oiler Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   `The collectibles market is getting so big that there are some
sweaters being sold that aren't the real thing,'' Oiler equipment
manager Barrie Stafford said. ``We had a fellow put the microchip
in, with the date of the game, the player's identity and number.
He's also worked with dogs and cows for identification.''
</P>
<P>
   Several game sweaters, which had a special autograph from
Gretzky inside on the hem, will be kept for posterity by the Oilers
organization.
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky left the Rangers after last season, he gave a
trainer and equipment manager each $5,000 to say thanks. Gretzky
wore five sweaters his last day in New York in April. He kept one
for himself, gave one to general manager Neil Smith, one to his
agent Mike Barnett, one to the Hall of Fame, and one to an
anonymous friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3769 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      10-11 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FALSE IDENTITY CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - There are days when Phyllis Malkiewicz simply hates her
self. She can't believe the things Phyllis Malkiewicz does, the
wild spending sprees, the callous disre gard for others, the lies,
the lawless ness. It bothers her so much that she's made calls and
written letters to banks and businesses warning them about Phyllis
Malkiewicz. She's even printed fliers and handed them out to local
retailers, so they won't sell anything to Phyllis Malkiewicz.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a month, she's tried to put a stop to herself, but
she can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I have been a responsi ble person,'' she said.
``Now, I have collection agencies after me. I'm afraid to buy
anything, anywhere because they might recognize my name. I feel
like I've lost control of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In late August or early September, someone got a hold of the
bank account numbers for Phyllis and her husband. The thief then
made or purchased some form of false identi fication _ a driver's
license, maybe _ with the name Phyllis Malkiewicz on it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the newly created Phyllis or an accomplice used a
computer to print a book of checks featuring the real Phyllis' bank
account number, then went shopping. &QL; 
The beginning &QL; 
``Our first clue came when Bank One called us and asked if I had
written a $857 check to Circuit City,'' Phyllis said. ``It was a
fraud, of course. But it was also just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a week or two, checks in the name of Phyllis and her
husband were used to purchase a gold watch, a computer, a
refrigerator, furniture for both a dining room and a living room
and more.
</P>
<P>
   They showed up in stores in Phoenix, Glendale, Peoria, Sun City,
Scotts dale and Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis did everything a person in her position is supposed to
do. She had all her accounts ``flagged'' by banks and credit-card
issuers. She canceled existing accounts, contacted credit bureaus
and, of course, called the police.
</P>
<P>
   Who ignored her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I tried to get someone out to my house to take a
report I was told, `You're not the victim,' '' she said. ``They
said the stores being ripped off are the victim, and that I
eventually would get my money back.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she wondered, what about my good name? And what about the
fraud?
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Arizona has had a law making it a felony to assume
the identity of another person for any unlawful purpose. Phyllis
contacted Assistant Maricopa County Attorney Jerry Landau, who
helped get the law passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least he told me that, yes, I was a victim,'' Phyllis said.
``But it hasn't yet helped to resolve my problem.'' &QL; 
Struggle to find help &QL; 
Phyllis has lost time at work, watched a $5,000 savings account go
to zero, and struggled to get the attention of four different
police departments, none of which has helped her.
</P>
<P>
   She's written to the offices of U.S. Sens. John McCain and Jon
Kyl, as well as Congressmen John Shadegg, Matt Salmon, J.D.
Hayworth and Jim Kolbe.
</P>
<P>
   The only response she received was from a staffer in Shadegg's
office, who referred her to someone in the Arizona Attorney
General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like no one wants to catch the criminal,'' she
said. ``They all tell me, `Don't worry, eventually, you'll get your
money back,' and I say, `It's not just about money. It's about
crime. It's about my good name being taken from me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As of Oct. 11, no police department had taken an official report
from Phyllis. She did have some luck with the state Department of
Transporta tion, where an investigator is search ing for someone
with a false license in her name.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she went to the state motor vehicle office to
get a new, digital license. She also bought a paper shredder. When
she called me recently she identified herself as ''the real Phyllis
Malkiewicz.''
</P>
<P>
   How do I know for sure? she was asked. There was a time when
Phyllis, who has a good sense of humor, would have laughed. But not
now.
</P>
<P>
   She's not been herself lately. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0438 </DOCNO>
