<HEADER>
A3771 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      10-11 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ACTION' DESERVES MORE ACTION IN TV RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Appropriately, Richard Burgi (right) plays an
action-movie star on Action, which also stars Jay Mohr. The biting
new series takes on Hollywood. 
Micheal Lavine/FOX 
Jay Mohr stars as Peter Dragon, an unscrupulous movie producer, in
Action. 
A s fans of the Mike O'Malley Show can attest, it's never too late
to start trying to save your favorite low-rated television show.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actually, if you were a fan of the Mike O'Malley Show, which
distin guished itself only by becoming the first new show of the
fall season to get the ax, you've got bigger prob lems. Like
finding yourself a good spot on the humor-transplant list.
</P>
<P>
   More discriminating viewers are con cerned with Action, Fox's
hilarious Thursday night comedy about an unscrupulous movie
producer named Peter Dragon who is willing to do anything _
anything _ to get his next film made. The show uses bleeped-out
cursing and ``adult situ ations'' _ code for sex _ to portray as
realistically as possible today's Hollywood. It says something
about the place that the only person Dragon can trust is a
child-star-turn ed-prostitute named Wendy Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to say the show is like a snapshot of the current
moment in Hollywood,'' Action's executive pro ducer and movie
honcho Joel Silver said last week in a conference call promoting
another of his shows, UPN's The Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation is necessary be cause, even though critics have
gone through barrels of ink praising Ac tion, millions of viewers
are studi ously avoiding it. What's worse, Action is getting
trounced by the awful new NBC comedy Stark Rav ing Mad. True, that
show lives in the rarefied air time between Frasier and ER, but
this is supposed to be the Age of the Remote.
</P>
<P>
   You've got one. Use it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Fox executives are promising patience as Action takes a
break during the baseball playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys at Fox could not be more supportive of the show,''
Silver said. ``That doesn't mean that we won't wake up in the
morning and read in the paper that it's canceled, but they're not
acting that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Action's very premise sets up an intriguing dilemma.
Most save-our-show efforts are spent on heartwarming dramas like
Touched by an Angel or Seventh Heaven.
</P>
<P>
   How does one defend a show whose characters are designed to be
inde fensible?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't,'' Chris Thompson, who created Action, said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You defend that only by saying, `Is that the tyranny
ultimately of televi sion, in that everyone must be beloved? Do we
have to agree with everyone's motives? Do we only want to watch
people whose moral positions we admire? Is it about admiration and
role-modeling or is it about entertainment?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually it's about being funny, which Action is. In a season in
which most of the new network sitcoms go to great lengths to avoid
making you so much as chuckle, laughs _ no matter how crudely
gotten _ forgive a lot. Though not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it _ and I've only seen the pilot, and it did not
appeal to me enough that I went back to it a second time _ the
characters, other than Wendy Ward, just did not appeal to me,''
said Dorothy Swan son, the founder of Viewers for Quality
Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have to be lovable. They don't have to be likable.
But there have to be some redeeming qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   How about humor? That's a redeem ing quality. And Swanson admits
she thinks the show is funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly one of the few, if not the only, sitcom
anybody's even talking about,'' she said, ``and I think that's
important. There should be a sitcom that's worth discussing.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that Action is worthy not just of discussion
but of watching. Thompson is scheduled to meet with Fox bigwigs
today to discuss how to attract more viewers; likely scenarios
include moving Ac tion to a different night or time. If all else
fails and Fox cancels the show, perhaps it could be revived on
cable (Action was originally devel oped for HBO), where its content
might be a better fit.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, for his part, sounded reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may indeed be true that everyone needs to be likable in
television,'' he said. ``I don't know if that's true or not. I
would hope not, but I may wind up doing 12 episodes and that was
it, and maybe next year some body can do a show where some body's a
little edgier than a normal lead in a sitcom would be because I
opened that door a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or not. Or everybody in television will be a ballerina. I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   No one does. But if you haven't already, at least give Action a
try. Let's keep TV's dancing shoes on the shelf a little longer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
