<SLUG> BC-NET-WORKER-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net company sued over planned sale
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A shareholder of Net-Worker Inc., an Internet
company that alerts subscribers to career and networking events, is
suing the company's founders to prevent its sale to Agillion Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bruneman, former executive publisher of the company's Web
site, Networker.com, is also seeking $4 million in damages,
according to the lawsuit filed in Travis County District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Named as defendants are Agillion, which provides Web-based
software services, Steve Guengerich, Net-Worker's chairman and
chief executive, and Steve Papermaster, a director in Net-Worker
and chief executive of Agillion.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims that if Net-Worker is folded into Agillion _
as Guengerich and Papermaster are planning _ that no cash will
change hands and that stockholders will not get any equity from the
deal. It also accuses Papermaster and Guengerich of stealing
Net-Worker trade secrets and of failing to obtain bids from other
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Papermaster and Guengerich declined to comment, citing pending
legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Papermaster and Guengerich acquired the Net-Worker software from
Civic Pride Inc. in March and created Networker.com. Net-Worker is
backed by the Powershift Group, a venture development group whose
principals are Papermaster and Guengerich.
</P>
<P>
   After the sale, Bruneman, who helped create the software at
Civic Pride, moved to Net-Worker and received 10 percent of the
company's stock, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Agillion, whose chief executive is Papermaster, is also backed
by Powershift.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Hawkins writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
