<HEADER>
A3773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DNA-NYT &LR;      10-11 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JOHN DOE'S DNA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Oct. 12:
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor in Milwaukee has found an intriguing new use for
DNA evidence. With the six-year time limit for filing charges in
three rape cases about to expire, he filed rape and kidnapping
counts last month against an unknown man implicated by semen tests
in three 1993 assaults, identifying him only by his DNA code. The
warrant refers to the alleged assailant as ``John Doe, unknown male
with matching deoxyribonucleic acid profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the novelty of this approach, it is really just a new
twist on the long-established practice under state laws of allowing
``John Doe'' warrants that cite an alias, last known address or
other information that identifies the accused with ``reasonable
certainty.'' As courts are likely to find, a person's DNA code
easily meets that standard.
</P>
<P>
   But lurking in the case is a bigger issue for the future use of
DNA evidence. Chances are the prosecutor of this John Doe case
would not have been racing to beat the statute of limitations had
Wisconsin moved more quickly to test the vaginal and cervical swabs
of semen collected right after the 1993 attacks. As it is, the
samples waited at the police evidence room until last year, along
with 2,300 other unexamined rape kits, owing to a severe shortfall
in crime lab capacity.
</P>
<P>
   A survey commissioned by the National Commission for the Future
of DNA Evidence found that about 180,000 rape kits sit unexamined
in police departments across the nation. There are 12,000 in New
York City alone. In some places, the police still test DNA samples
only when a suspect has already been apprehended _ a Luddite
approach that fails to exploit DNA's usefulness for solving crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of DNA databanks now makes it possible to match
DNA evidence collected in rape, burglary and other cases against
DNA profiles of convicted offenders or of suspects in other open
cases. But absent more resources to collect and test DNA samples, a
lot of violent criminals who could be apprehended by DNA science
are destined to remain John Doe forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
