<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BAYLOR-DEATHSFOLO-COX     10-11 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYLOR-DEATHSFOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University grapples with death of students
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Jennessa Reed and Bonnie Saha are resident
assistants at Baylor University's Russell Hall. They're experienced
problem solvers, helping the young women living there settle
disputes with roommates or adjust to being away from home for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of three residents Sunday, however, left them
grasping for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us was prepared for it,'' Reed said. ``We just want to
be here for the girls. That's our main goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women have seen and heard a lot of crying in the wake of
the deaths of Emily Hollister, 18, a freshman pre-medical student
from South Bend, Ind.; Erika Lanham, 18, a freshman pre-nursing
student from Fort Collins, Colo.; Tricia Lynn Calp, 18, a freshman
business major from Houston; and Dolan Walter Wostal III, 22, a
junior biology major from Santa Fe, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The four Baylor students and two other people were killed when
struck by a Ford Ranger truck driven by Brandon Michael Kallmeyer,
a Texas A&AMP;M student who fell asleep at the wheel. His pickup veered
off Farm-to-Market Road 60, about two miles west of the A&AMP;M campus,
shortly after midnight Sunday. Eight people walking to a party at
the Tau Kappa Epsilon house were hit, including Baylor graduate
David Gamradt, 22, who suffered only minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor students were in College Station for the Bears'
football game against Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, when something like this happens, I don't think we
know why,'' Saha said. ``I think it's just something we have to
learn how to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Reed and Saha wore white ribbons on their blouses Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sunday night the students got together and talked about
wanting to show our love and respect for those who died,'' Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hindering them was the fact that the three Russell residents had
been at Baylor only a little more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know if they had a favorite color,'' Saha said.
``But we thought white was a peaceful color.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Russell residents helped create makeshift memorials outside
the three students' dorm rooms, leaving behind such things as
notes, cards and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said she was still at the point of trying to match the
names and faces of the freshmen together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless, it still hurts,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths Sunday were the second tragedy to strike Baylor in
less than two months.
</P>
<P>
   Three Baylor upperclassmen died Aug. 19 when their Acura smashed
into a tree and flipped several times just south of College
Station. The driver apparently fell asleep as the students headed
back to Baylor, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Former chaplain Milton Cunningham said the deaths Sunday hit
students harder because of the timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous deaths were at the end of summer,'' said
Cunningham, now special assistant to the vice president for student
life. ``The students had been separated. It wasn't like they had
just seen them the day before or that afternoon. That's why these
deaths are having such an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than 70 years since Baylor lost so many students
so suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Ten members of the men's basketball team were killed in 1927
when their bus was hit by a train in Round Rock as they headed to a
game against the University of Texas. Among the dead was James
Clyde Kelly, the captain of the team, who pushed his friend Weir
Washam out a window to safety just before the collision. To Baylor,
the dead became known as the Immortal 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since that time I don't believe we have lost so many students
in such a short period of time,'' said Baylor President Robert B.
Sloan Jr. ``It's on everybody's mind today. It's such a sobering
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Several professors have canceled quizzes this week to give
students time to grieve, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements for the four Baylor students who died
Sunday will probably be released today, officials said. Students
were told Monday that a campus memorial service will probably be
held the first week of November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still working with the families,'' Cunningham said.
``They are planning memorial services in their respective towns. We
won't even begin planning our service until those local services
are concluded.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said he met with about 150 students at Russell on
Sunday, including men from the Tau Kappa Epsilon fraternity, of
which Wostal was a member. The students did most of the talking,
Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Counseling is not a matter of telling,'' Cunningham said.
``It's a matter of listening. They were not there to find out what
I thought. They were there to talk to someone who is concerned
about them. There are no magic answers that will make all this go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell's Saha said counseling came from a lot of sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had quite a few parents come by,'' Saha said. ``More
than you would normally see in the lobby on a Monday. This affected
some students more than they expected it to. I think the parents
wanted to offer a shoulder to cry on. I also think it was
reassurance for the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Faulkner, who lived three doors down at Russell from
Lanham and Calp (who were roommates), took comfort Monday in
gaining perspective on how fleeting life can be.
</P>
<P>
   After learning of the deaths, Faulkner realized that she had
dropped off a roll of film to be developed containing pictures of
Lanham and Calp rollicking in the Freshmen Follies, an annual event
where dorm residents have food fights and engage in other
horseplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely makes you not take life for granted,'' Faulkner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark England writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail:mengland(AT)wacotrib.com. The Associated Press contributed
to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New Yos News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
