<HEADER>
A3892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-TELECOM-465&AMP;AD     10-11 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-TELECOM-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCI'S PURCHASE OF SPRINT COULD AFFECT BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ MCI Worldcom Inc.'s planned acquisition of
Sprint Corp. could send a jolt through Brazil's telecommunications
industry, which has emerged as a battleground for many of the
world's largest communications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. merger partners are competitors in Brazil's
long-distance business, since MCI Worldcom owns Embratel, the
country's dominant national long-distance company, and Sprint has a
25 percent holding in Intelig, a start-up venture with partners
that include National Grid Group of Britain and France Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Since Brazilian law prohibits one company from controlling a
single sector of the telecommunications business, like
long-distance, wireless or fixed-line service, one of the holdings
will have to be shed.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say the most likely outcome is the sale of
Sprint's stake in Intelig.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the obvious choice given Sprint's commitment to the
Brazilian market hasn't been as great as MCI's,'' said Andy
Castonguay, head of the Sao Paulo office of Pyramid Research, a
telecommunications analysis firm. ``The interesting thing will be
how they find a buyer and if they can do it quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The MCI-Sprint deal announced last week is only the latest
development to shake Brazil's telecommunications industry, which
has undergone a huge transformation since the government sold the
national telephone system, known as Telebras, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Telefonica SA of Spain has carved out the largest
presence in Brazil, buying the telephone companies in Sao Paulo and
Rio Grande do Sul, two prosperous states, in addition to several
cellular-telephone companies. European companies like Portugal
Telecom and North American companies like BellSouth Corp.,
Telesystem International Wireless Inc. and MCI have also made
significant investments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the end of the state monopoly has created a basis for
intense competition to begin in only one area, cellular telephones.
Meanwhile, start-ups are quickly building or renting networks to
compete with existing fixed-line companies and with Embratel, the
long-distance company acquired by MCI last year for about $1.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Intelig was hoping to be up and running by the end of the year.
But that plan is now in doubt since Sprint has been providing much
of the company's technological expertise. Even if France Telecom or
National Grid acquires the U.S. company's stake in Intelig, they
may have to search later for another partner that could provide
advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intelig has to be troubled by the possibility they could lose
much of their brain power,'' said Nilton Tuna, editor of RNT, a Sao
Paulo-based telecommunications magazine. ``Luckily there is a lot
of new technology _ and players _ in the market they could work
with.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brazil's size, covering an area bigger than the continental
United States with a population of 165 million, and the relative
backwardness of its communications infrastructure have actually
worked to its advantage in creating a competitive and
technologically astute market.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the lack of financial resources that Telebras had
before its privatization meant that Brazil was almost a clean slate
for newcomers. So the country has become a kettle of new
technologies and techniques transplanted from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Intelig is a case in point. The company is largely depending on
``right of way'' technology, which enables existing fuel pipelines,
sewage lines and electricity grids to piggyback telecommunications
equipment. The advantage of the system is that is it cheaper and
quicker than building an entirely new network to compete with that
of Embratel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991011.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASH-VALENTINO-UNGARO     10-11 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASH-VALENTINO-UNGARO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ungaro, Valentino get ruffled
 &HT;    By Robert Janjigian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The print factor at the Emanuel Ungaro spring-summer
2000 collection radiated as high energy as the disco soundtrack.
Models vamped in slinky ruffled crepe and georgette concoctions.
There was plenty of leather and lace. Floaty dresses rather than
rigid separates were the emphasis, which indicates the designer's
return to a more feminine silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   Asymmetrical skirts reached ``up to there,'' though no doubt
when these exuberantly patterned and polka-dotted pinafores make it
to boutiques, they'll have a slightly less showy and revealing cut.
But for the moment, the sounds of Donna Summer moaning ``I love to
love you, baby'' and ``do it to me again and again,'' or Dan
Hartman pleading in song to ``relight my fire,'' only translated as
a return to the disco aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   Ungaro did it again and again, capturing in cloth a freer and
easier, less analytical time, when colors were pretty and bright
and a party atmosphere prevailed. The clothes were made to move.
And that kinetic quality was catchy.
</P>
<P>
   Ungaro's collection was lighthearted, but not completely
oriented to the disco babe. In addition to the sexy slips,
one-shoulder dance dresses and tie-dyed tights was the clear
signature of the master of the mix, who seemed to be tossing away
any darker side that had emerged during previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   His spring-summer collection was seductively upbeat. Any Goth or
gypsy references were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Valentino
</P>
<P>
   The mood at Valentino was both frothy and elegant. The power of
the flower, as at Ungaro, was emphasized. Ruffles and fringe,
embroidery and bows, indicated an anything-but-pared down approach
by the Rome-based couturier.
</P>
<P>
   But there were sleek tailored elements to the collection,
successfully reviving the polished, yet always feminine, Valentino
look that has attracted style-setting clients from the late '60s
and early '70s until the present.
</P>
<P>
   He even reprised an ivory wool-cashmere coat that was originally
designed for Jackie O.
</P>
<P>
   In the handsome, ladylike focus of the clothes, there was no
evidence of any falling into The Gap or celebrating the mundane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reliable chic'' is an apt way to describe Valentino's
offerings for next spring and summer. Think of Claudia Cardinale or
Sophia Loren in their heyday, and you'll get an accurate picture of
Valentino's vision. The collection represented ready-to-wea
indeed was ready to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Janjigian writes for The Palm Beach Daily News, Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
