<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-717-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING'S 717 LOSES TO AIRBUS IN BRITISH AIRWAYS COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After turning its back on Boeing last year to buy
planes from Airbus Industrie for the first time, British Airways on
Monday again hurt the aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   This time it landed a haymaker on Boeing's slow-selling 717.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing was believed by some to have a slight edge in
the hard-fought competition, Europe's biggest airline rejected the
717 and announced it would buy a model from Airbus Industrie to
meet its requirements for a fleet of smaller jetliners.
</P>
<P>
   The order for as many as 24 A318s is worth nearly $1 billion at
list prices, though the carrier likely received a sizable discount.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. put the best possible face on the news, saying it
remains fully committed to the 717, a plane it inherited from
McDonnell Douglas that has so far failed to firmly establish itself
in the marketplace for smaller jetliners.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said the latest blow from British Airways,
while not a knockout punch for the 717, underscores the fact that,
in more than four years since its launch, the 717 hasn't won a
single order from a top-tier airline. The British Airways
competition represented what would have been a breakthrough order
for the 717, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long before Boeing throws in the towel? I'd give them
maybe a year,'' said Richard Aboulafia, senior aviation analyst at
the Teal Group, a market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia has long been a vocal critic of the 717, arguing that
it is a very good airplane, but one without a market.
</P>
<P>
   Other industry analysts say Boeing still has time to find a
market for the 717, perhaps in Asia, but they pretty much agree the
plane's long-term future is in doubt, perhaps more so with Monday's
announcement by British Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Boeing is clearly committed to the 717 and trying
to get more orders,'' said Peter Jacobs with the Seattle firm of
Ragan-MacKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, within a certain time if Boeing does not see
additional interest, they will have to make a decision whether to
commit to the program long term or just wind it down. I don't know
what that time frame may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing so far has landed 115 firm orders for the 717.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, Hawaiian Airlines announced it intended
to buy at least 13 of the jets. That broke a yearlong order
drought. Because the sales agreement has not yet been inked with
Hawaiian, those orders are not yet counted as firm.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Pembroke Capital Ltd., an Irish leasing firm, has
said it intends to buy another 15 of the 717s and take options on
25 more. Those orders also are not firm. Pembroke previously placed
a firm order for 10 of the planes.
</P>
<P>
   But what Boeing has needed most to stimulate sales, according to
analysts, is a large order from a major airline, which in turn
could lead to orders from one of the large leasing companies such
as International Lease Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Although TWA ordered 50 717s in Decemeber 1998, and took options
for 50 more, the St. Louis-based carrier is hardly a model of
financial health. It ranked 24th in the world last year based on
1998 revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was hoping that British Airways would be that big,
healthy customer.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's flagship carrier wants to replace some of its bigger
757s with smaller and cheaper jets in a move to maximize profits on
short European routes by focusing on better-paying business
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   It had been evaluating offers by Boeing for the 717 and by
Airbus for the similar-size A318 that is now in development. As
part of any deal, British Airways had said it first had to trade in
its Boeing-built 757s. That happened last week when Boeing said it
would buy back 34 of the used 757s and convert them into freighters
for lease to DHL Worldwide Express.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that deal, and because the A318 won't enter
service until 2002, some published reports had speculated Boeing's
717 would win the British Airways competition.
</P>
<P>
   But the carrier announced it placed 12 firm orders for the A318,
and took options for 12 more. The first planes will be delivered in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, British Airways said it chose the Airbus plane
``for its superior economics, flexibility and commonality with the
rest of our short-haul fleet.'' The British Airways A318s will seat
about 100 passengers in a two-class configuration.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus said it now has won 157 firm orders and commitments for
the A318. Its Web site puts the number of firm orders at 45.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing 717 spokesman Warren Lamb said the company was
disappointed in losing the British Airways order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never like to lose a sales campaign, but we are committed
to increasing shareholder value at Boeing and we will only sell
airplanes at a price to meet that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb would not elaborate, but his comment suggested Boeing lost
the competition on price.
</P>
<P>
   While Airbus may have offered British Airways a better deal,
industry analysts said, airplane commonality was likely the
deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, British Airways ordered 20 Airbus A320s and 39 Airbus
A319s. The A318 is a shortened version of the A319, which itself is
a smaller version of the A320.
</P>
<P>
   Commonality is an important consideration for airlines when it
comes to buying new planes. Pilots can be more easily trained when
cockpits of different models are similar. There are maintenance
cost savings, too.
</P>
<P>
   The 717 does not have commonality with Boeing's 737. The 717 was
developed by McDonnell Douglas as a replacement for the DC-9. Until
the 1997 merger with Boeing, McDonnell Douglas called its new plane
the MD-95.
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia, the industry analyst, said that given the importance
of aircraft commonality, no one should have been surprised British
Airways chose the A318 over the 717.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are asking a major airline with a lot of Airbus
narrow-body planes to take a limited number of orphan planes,'' he
said. ``Why don't they also pull their neckties until it hurts?
What's the advantage of having 10 or 20 orphan aircraft?''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analyst Paul Nisbet of JSA Research agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They already have the A320 on order,'' he said. ``What would
have been a surprise is if they had decided to buy the 717.''
</P>
<P>
   The 717 was launched as the MD-95 in October 1995 with an order
for 50 airplanes and 50 options from ValuJet, which later changed
its name to AirTran after the horrific crash of one of its jets in
the Florida Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those planes went into service with AirTran this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing builds the 717 in California at its Long Beach plant,
where it is ending production of all other McDonnell Douglas planes
_ the MD-11, MD-90 and MD-80.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Aboulafia is convinced the future of the 717 is
bleak, he doesn't think Boeing will axe the program anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killing the last Douglas program is politically unacceptable
or at best undesirable,'' he said. ``With the elections approaching
and all that. ... You don't want to throw a lot of people out of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   So for now, Boeing is continuing to talk with a number of
potential customers about the 717. Late last week, Boeing flew a
new 717 to Asia as part of what has been all-out marketing campaign
in recent months. The plane made a sales swing through Europe
earlier this summer after the Paris Air Show, where it was Boeing's
featured attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big market Boeing is looking at is China,'' said Nisbet,
the analyst. ``If that pans out, it could be a very good omen for
the program. ... It's too soon to write this off. ... I think
Boeing will go forward until they find the markets they are looking
at do not exist. ... If those don't work out, then they will give
the program a second look.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
