<HEADER>
A3886 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CLIFT-AZR &LR;      10-11 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL JOURNALIST IN WOMEN'S CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
As Newsweek correspondent Eleanor Clift listened to Geraldine
Ferraro addressing the 1984 Democratic con vention, the hardened
reporter had tears in her eyes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York's congresswoman had just become the first female
vice-presi dential candidate nominated by a major political party.
It was a historic moment and a moving one for many American women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She represented the hope and the dream,'' Clift says.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mondale-Ferraro cam paign ended that year with a
whim per, losing to the Ronald Reagan juggernaut, don't blame
Ferraro, Clift says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone he (Mondale) picked would have taken him
across the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro's ill-fated run for the vice presidency will be the
opening chap ter in Madam President, a book being written by Clift
and her husband, Tom Brazaitis, Washington bureau chief for the
Cleveland Plain Dealer. The book explores the past 15 years of
women in politics, culminating with the current cam paign in which
Elizabeth Dole has become the first woman with a serious shot to
win the presidency _ or at least her party's nomination. &QL; 
At the same time, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton has her eye on
the U.S. Senate seat once held by Robert Kennedy and Patrick
Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Women running for high office are no longer tilting at
windmills.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 29, Clift, now a contributing editor for Newsweek and
regular panelist on public television's politi cal tongue lashing,
The McLaughlin Group, will be keynote speaker at an event sponsored
by the National Museum of Women's History.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Virginia-based mu seum named White House corre
spondent Helen Thomas as the first recipient of its Women Making
History Award.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a gala banquet at the Arizona Biltmore will honor an
entire slate of Arizona public offi cials, including Gov. Jane
Hull, Secretary of State Betsy Bayless, Senate President Brenda
Burns, At torney General Janet Napolitano, Treasurer Carol Springer
and Super intendent of Public Instruction Lisa Graham Keegan.
</P>
<P>
   Also honored will be Supreme Court Justice Sandra O'Connor,
former Arizona Gov. Rose Mofford, Gila River Indian Community Gov.
Mary Thomas and former state legislator Polly Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Clift would seem the perfect person to introduce the honorees.
Her book will devote a chapter to the historic all-female
administration as part of a Western tradition in which such states
as Arizona, California and Washington offer some of the best
opportunities to women running for office.
</P>
<P>
   Brazaitis has already traveled to Arizona to interview the women
dubbed the ``chicks in charge,'' and Clift is eager to meet them as
well, saying their administration is not just a blip on the
political radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's very significant,'' she says from her home in
Washington, where she is on leave from her regular Newsweek duties
to follow the campaign trail. Her assignment: Glean juicy tidbits
about the presi dential candidates to include in the magazine's
special post-election edi tion and subsequent book. Offers optimism
</P>
<P>
   Clift's own book is due out next spring. It will focus on such
issues as the 1991 Anita Hill-Clarence Thomas hearings and the
hopes raised by 1992's so-called Year of the Woman, a boom time for
female candidates. Those hopes fizzled somewhat in subsequent
elections, although the era brought a new face into Congress: the
conservative woman.
</P>
<P>
   Clift offers optimism for voters hungry for gender equality in
public office. A Ms. Foundation poll found that 76 percent of those
surveyed said they would elect a woman president. The bad news was
that respondents could name only two likely female candidates: Dole
and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clift, whose liberal female voice often cuts through the
conservative male fracas on McLaughlin, can do better than that.
She names Califor nia Sen. Diane Feinstein, Texas Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchinson, New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, New Hampshire
Gov. Jeanne Shaheen and Maryland Lieutenant Gov. Kathleen Kennedy
Townsend as those most likely to take aim at the presidency in
coming years.
</P>
<P>
   To acquaint the public with the array of women qualified for
high office, the White House Project, backed by the Clinton
administration, was launched, Clift reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get out of the novelty stage,'' she says, ``you have to
have more than one woman running.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, she notes, finished a respect able third in this summer's
Iowa straw poll by playing to her obvious base _ women, especially
Republi can businesswomen.
</P>
<P>
   ``She showed she can motivate essen tially moderate women who
have not been politically involved,'' Clift says. ``She's got a
good shot. . . . We're in the realm of having a woman
(candidate).''
</P>
<P>
   Though she has chronicled other women's successes, Clift's own
story is a remarkable one. Raised in Queens, N.Y., she landed a
secre tarial job at Newsweek in 1963, when she was 22, shy and
known mostly for her typing skills. In 1972, she was assigned as a
reporter in the maga zine's Atlanta bureau. Covered Carter
</P>
<P>
   Her big break came when she began covering Georgia politician
Jimmy Carter in 1974 and scooped her colleagues by doggedly
pursuing the candidate behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Brazaitis is her second husband. Her first was Brooks Clift,
brother of the late Hollywood star Montgomery Clift. She has three
grown sons by Brooks, who died in 1986, four years after they
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a one-year stint in the Washington bureau of the Los
An geles Times, Clift, 58, has spent her journalism career at
Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   She's been a regular on The McLaughlin Group since 1983, hold
ing her own in what usually amounts to a quadraphonic verbal
slugfest among moderator John McLaugh lin's vituperative cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Clift has been married to Brazaitis for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Exit question: What's it like collabo rating on a book with your
spouse?
</P>
<P>
   Clift laughs, admitting to some ``tense moments'' as one writes
and the other edits.
</P>
<P>
   She says she's not satisfied unless her anxiety level wakes up
Brazaitis in the middle of the night and infects him, too.
</P>
<P>
   And when she takes a break from writing and heads for the
kitchen, husband and cat are sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, she says, ``It seems to work out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
