<SLUG> BC-FEDEX-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDEX CHIEF WILL RETIRE AT 55 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theodore Weise, the president and chief executive of Federal
Express Corp., will retire in January, the package-delivery company
announced Monday. He will be succeeded by David Bronczek, the
executive vice president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The move came as a surprise because Weise is only 55 and has
worked at Fedex, the world's largest air-express delivery company,
since its founding nearly 28 years ago. But analysts who follow the
company said that his departure would have little effect on Fedex,
which has been hurt lately by rising fuel costs and slowing
domestic sales growth.
</P>
<P>
   FDX Corp., parent of Fedex and of several ground-delivery
companies, will still be run by its chairman, Frederick Smith, a
hard-driving, ex-Marine aviator, who pioneered the overnight
delivery business in the 1970s and who also is 55. ``This is a very
deep management bench,'' said Edward Wolfe, an analyst at Bear,
Stearns in New York. ``I don't think operationally it should be a
setback.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bronczek, 45, has worked at Fedex for 23 years. He began
his career there in 1976 as a courier, and held top jobs in Canada
and Europe before returning to headquarters in Memphis, Tenn.,
early last year to succeed Weise after he was promoted to succeed
Smith. Bronczek is currently responsible for the company's global
operations, as well as sales, e-commerce and customer service.
</P>
<P>
   After stepping aside on Jan. 31, Weise will continue to sit on
the Fedex board and to act as a consultant to its air operations.
He said in an interview Monday that he had no plans to work outside
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Several people who spoke with Weise in recent months said they
had received no indication that his retirement was imminent. But
Weise said he and Smith had been planning to elevate Bronczek to
run Fedex since the umbrella FDX was formed early in 1998, after
Fedex bought Caliber System Inc., the owner of several trucking
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exhausting,'' Weise said of his 28 years at Fedex.
``I'm just, quite frankly, ready to step aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Weise took a lead role in the company's confrontation with its
pilots last year. On the brink of a strike, the independent pilots
union ultimately backed down after Smith threatened to dismiss
several hundred pilots. Until then, Weise had issued most of the
threats and was widely resented by many pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, FDX failed to meet already diminished earnings
expectations for the fiscal quarter that ended on Aug. 31. The day
the earnings were announced, FDX stock dropped 13 percent, the
steepest one-day fall in 12 years. Analysts said that high fuel
prices and increased domestic competition had slowed Fedex's
growth. FDX stock closed Monday at $42.75, up 43.75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Kauffman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch in New York, said
he did not believe that the weak results had any connection with
Weise's departure. ``The company's problems are macroeconomic,'' he
said, citing a slowdown in manufacturing. ``Every other player in
this market has not had the robust volume growth domestically as
they had in the last two years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
