<SLUG> BC-SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLULAR BIOLOGIST WINS NOBEL PRIZE FOR MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 13th graf to capitalize Nobel Prize title) (ART ADV: Photos NYT10, NYT11 have been sent to NYT graphic
clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Gunter Blobel, a cellular and molecular biologist
at Rockefeller University in New York City, won the 1999 Nobel
Prize in medicine on Monday for discovering that proteins carry
signals that act as ZIP codes, helping them find their correct
locations within the cell.
</P>
<P>
   The research that Blobel has conducted for 30 years has had an
``immense impact'' on studies of the cell and helps explain the
molecular mechanisms behind diseases like cystic fibrosis, a
condition that creates a certain type of kidney stone in young
children, and other hereditary illnesses, the Nobel Assembly of the
Karolinska Institute in Stockholm announced.
</P>
<P>
   There are a billion protein molecules in an average human cell.
Cells are constantly dividing or being repaired to replace those
damaged or lost to everyday wear and tear. The mystery that Blobel
helped solve was learning how the cells regulate internal traffic
so the protein molecules ``go to the right address,'' he said in an
interview in his office at Rockefeller University.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Klausner, the head of the National Cancer Institute,
said many advances in recent decades, including his own research,
was in some way derived from Blobel's findings. ``Gunter's work in
many ways initiated the whole modern era of what we call molecular
cell biology,'' Klausner said in an interview. ``It began to merge
the observational approaches of cell biology, looking, describing
structure'' and so scientists could ``figure out how molecular
information underlies the structure and functioning of the cell.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the 20th Nobel Prize awarded to scientists associated
with Rockefeller University, reflecting its strength in basic
science.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel, who recalled witnessing the bombing of Dresden as a
child, said he was donating most of the $960,000 in prize money to
the Friends of Dresden, an independent American group that supports
the reconstruction, restoration and preservation of Dresden's
artistic and architectural legacy. The group is helping rebuild the
Frauenkirche, a bell-shaped church that was a fixture in pre-war
Dresden. Blobel, who is not Jewish, said he is also donating part
of the award to reconstruction of a synagogue in Dresden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the firebombing destruction of Dresden from very near,''
Blobel said, ``only a few kilometers away; for an eight and a half
year old, this was all very impressive. The bombing was so bright
that you could read the newspaper by the red sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three days earlier, Blobel's mother had shown him the
architectural beauty of Dresden, a scene that stimulated Brobel's
life-long interest in architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel's father was a veterinarian who had one of the few
functioning cars in the area, which the family used to pass through
the rubble. In the last days of the war, one of his sisters was
killed, and the seven surviving siblings were left under Russian
occupation in the East German state of Saxony.
</P>
<P>
   Young Gunter graduated from high school ``with highest grades,
although he never studied very much,'' his oldest brother, Dr. Hans
Blobel, said in a telephone interview from his home in Geissen,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he couldn't continue to study because he didn't want _
none of us wanted _ to join the Communist youth parties,'' he said.
In the early 1950s, Blobel escaped to the West through Berlin. He
became a U.S. citizen in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel is a tall, kindly man with an impressive shock of white
hair, an appearance that ``has lent an air of authority to his
lectures,'' Klausner said.
</P>
<P>
   It was among the reasons that colleagues had long told him that
he deserved the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine. Initially,
Blobel said he believed them. ``But as the years passed and I
didn't get a phone call, I didn't believe it anymore,'' Blobel said
at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel learned of his Nobel award shortly before 5 a.m. on
Monday. His wife, Laura Maioglio, who is accustomed to the phone
ringing at odd hours as the owner of Barbetta's restaurant in
midtown Manhattan, said she told the caller: ``Dr. Blobel is
sleeping.'' The caller responded: ``We have to speak to him. Wake
him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Blobel knew the award was being announced on Monday, and when he
took the call, he first thought it was a prank. Then he realized
none of the many foreign scientists in his laboratory was Swedish
or could mimic a Swedish accent well. He quickly recognized the
voice of Nils Ringertz, the secretary of the Nobel Committee, and
knew the award was real, recognition of his three decades of
doggedly pursuing a line of research that many scientists,
including colleagues at Rockefeller University, told him was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel was born in 1936 in Waltersdorf, Silesia, Germany, now
part of Poland. After earning a medical degree from the University
of Tubingen, he interned at a small hospital where he said he
``realized that treatment of disease was irrational and not based
on profound knowledge'' and that his interest was in research.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the time, his brother, Hans, was on the faculty of the
University of Wisconsin on a Fulbright Scholarship. Hans advised
Gunter that his medical training was insufficient to do research,
that American universities were ahead of their German counterparts
because of the war, and that he should come to Madison. Gunter
Blobel did, and earned a Ph.D. there in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Blobel moved to Rockefeller University as a
post-doctoral fellow largely because he wanted to work with Dr.
George E. Palade, a pioneering cell biologist. ``My work was a
direct extension of the work Dr. Palade had started at
Rockefeller,'' Blobel said of Palade, who went on to win a Nobel
Prize in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, scientists had used the electron microscope and
other techniques to describe the structure of the cell, Blober
recalled. They learned that a cell contains many different
structures known as organelles that carry out different functions.
Each organelle is surrounded by a membrane.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists did not know how the cell worked. A particular
mystery was how large proteins could get through the tightly sealed
membranes surrounding the organelles.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel reasoned that proteins have to be transported either out
of the cell, or to the different organelles. Such transport had to
be highly regulated, or the cell would be wide open to damage from
things entering from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Blobel and Dr. David D. Sabatini, who now heads cell
biology at New York University School of Medicine, proposed a bold
idea known as the signal hypothesis. It was that ``proteins
secreted out of a cell contain an intrinsic signal that governs
them to and across membranes,'' the Nobel Assembly said in its
citation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 30 years, with support from the National
Institutes of Health and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute,
Blobel and his team have conducted experiments to prove the
existence of programmed steps that allow molecules to move from one
part of the cell to another, and directed to their proper location.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel Prize was awarded not for a single major discovery,
but for the series of findings in the decades that it took to prove
the hypothesis, Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Blobel's team found the intrinsic signal they were
seeking, in a protein found in one organelle known as the
endoplasmic reticulum.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel found that each newly made protein has an
organelle-specific address, a stretch of the protein called a
signal sequence, that is recognized by receptors on an organelle's
surface. His team showed that in the endoplasmic reticulum, the
binding of the signal sequence to its receptor opens a watery
channel in the membrane through which the protein can travel.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel also characterized in detail the molecular mechanisms
underlying the processes and showed that they were universal,
operating similarly in yeast, plant and animal cells.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at Rockefeller University on Monday, Blobel
said there were many disappointments in the 30 years of research
``such as when your grants and papers are rejected because some
stupid reviewer rejected them for dogmatic adherence to old
ideas.'' His remarks drew thunderous applause from sympathetic
colleagues and younger scientists who packed the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``What keeps you going are the little blips of excitement every
three to four years,'' Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists know that the cell works because it sorts its
proteins and directs them to the right places to carry out various
functions. Some proteins become building blocks for constructing
the cell. Others function as enzymes catalyzing thousands of
specific chemical reactions. Without the little signals Blobel
hypothesized, the cell would cease to function. Scientists also
know that a number of hereditary diseases are caused by errors in
these signals and transport mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel is still working, trying to unravel the trafficking of
signals between the cell's nucleus and cytoplasm. A knowledge of
how such communication goes on in normal cells is necessary to
understand what goes awry in cancerous cells, Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   His research has contributed to the development of a more
effective use of cells as ``protein factories'' for the production
of important drugs such as erythropoeitin. It helps stimulate the
production of red blood cells in the bone marrow and is used widely
in many kidney and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel said that with more research he expected that scientists
would unravel the mysteries of how brain cells are damaged by
Alzheimer's disease, blood cells are destroyed by the AIDS virus
and other infections, and normal cells become malignant.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``As long as we do not know how the cell works we don't know the
kind of havoc the AIDS virus creates in the cell,'' Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel said his work has not found any cures and that there will
not be specific treatments for many cancers and other diseases
until scientists gain that fundamental understanding. ``We are very
far from it,'' Blobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Blobel credited Rockefeller University's focus on basic research
for the last century in providing him the teaching and work
environment to make his discoveries. He thanked his his wife, Laura
Maioglio, for ``tolerating my long hours in the lab.'' ``Our
schedules meshed because she worked late at the restaurant and that
gave me the opportunity to come home late from the lab.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
