<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TRIANGLE TEST TIME AS LAKERS HIT ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ The calendar was marked clearly:
!ital!Camp ends. Fly to Arkansas for exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the Los Angeles Lakers training camp is over,
concluding mid-day Monday. Tonight, the Lakers unleash the triangle
offense on an opponent for the first time, playing the Washington
Wizards in Little Rock (6:30 p.m., Channel 9).
</P>
<P>
   But no one is foolish enough to believe the training itself is
over. Not where coach Phil Jackson's offense is concerned. Jackson
is encouraged by the progress he saw in one week at UC Santa
Barbara, but he didn't exactly heap praise on his pupils as the
Lakers broke camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't offering to take us out to lunch,'' Rick Fox
quipped. ``But at the same time, I think he saw enough to let us
out of the gym, instead of delaying the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, the Lakers will try to compete against the Wizards
on back-to-back nights, concluding Wednesday in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult even for the Lakers to say whether they're on
pace for picking up the nuances of Jackson's system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I don't know. I don't know where we're supposed to be.
We can only do what we're being asked of, but we don't know how
good that is,'' Fox said with a laugh. ``I wasn't in Chicago, but I
think it took them more than one week to become proficient at the
offense. I think he's consistently going to challenge us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson acknowledged the Lakers weren't necessarily ready for
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had another week before we started, but this is it,
so we play it,'' he said. ``I think (the players) got an air for
what we're trying to say. They're willing and I think sometimes
they're responding. I think they have that determination as a group
to try to become a better team, and I think all those things are
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now when the contests actually begin and conflict happens
out there on the court, we'll see how (able) we are to stay with
our newfound stuff and to forsake our old habits. And that's what
basically this process does _ it gives us an opportunity to build
new skills and new habits as a basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will offer a glimpse into Jackson's rotation and he
hopes to give starters and other key players up to 20-25 minutes.
He plans to use all 18 players, but winning is still a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important,'' he said. ``We don't expect to have
players out there at the end-game situation, to try to win the
games for us down the stretch, because that's not the way I work.
But we want people to show they want to do things to be on this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Homecoming: No one will be more excited tonight than guard
Derek Fisher, who will have hundreds of friends and family members
on hand to watch him play in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   His parents received a key to the city and other honors Monday
on his behalf. Fisher had to admit, even amid the electricity of a
new season under a new coach, playing in Little Rock ``is at the
top of the list right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we win that championship that we're shooting for, I
don't think I'll be able to put (tonight) up against anything. It
will be a special feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendinitis that flared in Fisher's left knee, meanwhile, is
not considered serious, and he was able to practice fully Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
