<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME IS BEST PART OF DEVILS-SENATORS 2-2 TIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario _ The Devils and the Ottawa Senators had their
first experience Monday with the National Hockey League's new
overtime format, which produced the most exciting hockey of the
afternoon after three periods of mediocre play had produced two
goals by each team.
</P>
<P>
   There was no scoring in the five-minute overtime, with just four
skaters on each side, and the game ended at 2-2, with each team
earning a point. But the extra session was the only time the Devils
(2-1-1) and the Senators (4-0-1) played with any kind of rhythm and
intensity at the Corel Center here on Canada's Thanksgiving Day.
The overtime produced three shots, two by the Devils, but it was a
wide-open affair.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik tied the score for the Devils with 2 minutes 41
seconds left in regulation after second-period goals by Marian
Hossa and Rob Zamuner had given the Senators a 2-1 lead. Krzysztof
Oliwa scored the first goal for the Devils with 3:57 left in the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overtime was very exciting to watch,'' said Oliwa, who sat
on the bench during overtime because the teams used their fastest
players. ``It was back and forth, and everyone enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliwa has been working extra hard with Slava Fetisov and Larry
Robinson, the assistant coaches, on improving his skating and
stick-handling, and his extra work has paid off handsomely four
games into the season. The towering Oliwa scored the first goal for
the Devils in their season-opening victory at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Both of his goals came with crafty moves and were vivid proof
that Oliwa can be more than just the Devils' biggest pugilist.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Oliwa's score came on a backhander from close
range on the right side after he took a pass from Scott Gomez.
Defenseman Sheldon Souray, who played his second game after missing
the first two because of a hip flexor injury, started the sequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gomez made a great play,'' Oliwa said, giving credit to the
rookie for his goal. ``He moves the puck so well. All I wanted to
do was put it on net and hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliwa also had a marvelous scoring chance early in the third
period but hit the post.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tugnutt, Ottawa's goaltender, had little chance to stop
Holik's score. Standing at the top of the right face-off circle,
Holik one-timed Brian Rafalski's pass into the net for his fourth
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Holik and Petr Sykora had 29 goals each last season, the closest
any Devils player has come to reaching the 30-goal mark since John
MacLean, now with the Rangers, and Stephane Richer, now with Tampa
Bay, did it in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
