<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-COACHCOMMENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OSU coach not exactly brimming with confidence
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ For weeks Ohio State coach John Cooper
carefully tried to protect the psyche of his young team,
acknowledging its mistakes but refusing to criticize players'
talent or ability.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, after a demoralizing 42-17 loss to Wisconsin, he
criticized several of his veteran players in a team meeting. A few
days later, after a 3-point comeback victory over Purdue, he
acknowledged this OSU team isn't as talented as past Buckeye
squads.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as his players prepared for a road trip to No. 2 Penn
State (6-0, 2-0 Big Ten) this week, Cooper made his most startling
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty obvious that if we play our best game and
they play their best game and neither team makes any mistakes,
they'll probably win the game,'' Cooper said. ``We've got to play
lights out for 60 minutes. And if we do that, we'll get a break or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been awhile since Cooper has deferred a talent advantage to
an opponent and acknowledged that his team would need ``a little
help'' to come away victorious. It's an about-face from his
defensive bunker mentality just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But after six games in which the No. 18 Buckeyes (4-2, 1-1)
frequently have been outplayed, Cooper said he's not acknowledging
anything his players don't already know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our players are realistic enough to know that we're
going to have to play fanatically better to go win that game'' at
Penn State, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Though several OSU players agreed they're going to have to play
great to beat the Nittany Lions, they weren't willing to concede
their opponent has superior talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to shortchange coach, but I don't believe that,
personally,'' strong safety Donnie Nickey said. ``We lost two
games, people are going to challenge the talent level. They're
going to question our abilities as a football team. But I don't
feel our talent level has dropped enough to be noticeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Kevin Houser said Cooper's scenario simply isn't
practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter who's playing, no matter how good a team is, no
one's going to play a perfect game,'' he said. ``So I'm going to
disclaim coach Cooper's comment. Football is a game where mistakes
are made and we're going to try to make fewer mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Houser, Nickey and several of their teammates said maybe
Cooper's comments are simply another way to motivate the team, to
challenge them. His challenge last week produced a squad that
coaches and player said played with a lot of heart and fought for
four quarters to defeat Purdue, 25-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever the coach tells you the other team will win, we have
to go out and work harder and show, on national television, that we
can win,'' defensive end James Cotton said. ``It's just motivation.
We don't play the game on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Penn State is clearly the superior team. From win-loss
record to offensive and defensive statistics, the Nittany Lions
rank ahead of the Buckeyes in almost every category.
</P>
<P>
   But junior linebacker Na'il Diggs said that was the case with
Ohio State and Michigan State last year and the statistically
inferior Spartans won the game.
</P>
<P>
   OSU was the No. 1 rated team in the country when unranked
Michigan State came to Ohio Stadium. The Bucks had one of the best
defenses in the nation and their offense routinely collected 500 or
more yards per game. But somehow, someway the underdog Spartans
came away with a 28-24 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing, just like us last year against Michigan
State,'' Diggs said. ``They came in our house and beat us. So it's
not impossible for us to beat (Penn State).''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
