<SLUG> BC-LINUX-DEBIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES JOIN TO PROMOTE A LINUX OPERATING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to nudge Linux software into the mainstream of computing,
three companies are joining in an unusual collaboration to promote
Debian, a Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Two computer makers, VA Linux Systems and Silicon Graphics Inc.,
and the specialist book publisher O'Reilly &AMP; Associates are linking
up to sponsor a broader distribution of Debian, which was created
and is supported entirely by a volunteer corps of nearly 500
programmers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsorship agreement will pay for the commercial
distribution of Debian, which has been distributed free over the
Internet. The commercial version will include the operating system
on a CD-ROM; a copy of O'Reilly's new book ``Learning Debian GNU
Linux,'' and a coupon for a copy of the Star Office productivity
suite by Sun Microsystems. The bundle of products will sell for
$19.95, available directly from VA Linux and some retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate customers, in particular, often prefer commercial
versions of free software, so they get written documentation
explaining the software and are assured of technical support if
they have problems.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat Software, Caldera and other companies market commercial
versions of Linux, the operating system created by a Finnish
programmer, Linus Torvalds. Debian will still be supported mainly
by its network of volunteers, but VA Linux Systems also plans a
commercial support service for new users.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the three corporate sponsors is also a nod to making
a contribution to the open-source community of engineers whose
volunteer work has created the commercial opportunities that the
companies are now exploiting.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux Systems, which recently changed its name from VA
Research, has just registered with the Securities and Exchange
Commission to sell shares to the public. The Silicon Valley maker
of computers running Linux is growing at a rate of more than 200
percent a year. Because of its rapid growth and direct-odel,
some analysts have called it the ``Dell Computer of the Linux
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting requests for Debian from customers,'' said Brian
Biles, vice president for marketing at VA Linux. ``But we're also
doing this now because we're now in a position to offer support for
Debian, to give something back to the open-source community.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of Linux _ a free version of the powerful Unix operating
system _ has grown significantly in the last couple of years
because of the Internet. It is particularly popular as an
operating-system environment in the powerful server computers that
send out Web pages to desktop users.
</P>
<P>
   The different flavors of Linux, like Debian and Red Hat, are
varying implementations of the same underlying operating-system
software, or kernel. What differs are the software tools for tasks
like installation and systems management.
</P>
<P>
   Debian was created in 1993 by Ian Murdock, who was then an
undergraduate at Purdue University. The name comes from putting
together the first name of Murdock's wife, Debra, and his own first
name.
</P>
<P>
   Profits from the commercial distribution of Debian will go to
Software in the Public Interest, a nonprofit group that supports
open-source software projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
