<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-TRAGEDY-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR STUDENTS GRAPPLE WITH DEATHS FROM CRASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC BERGER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Baylor University coped with its second major
tragedy in as many months Monday as students struggled to
understand why four classmates were struck down in an automobile
accident over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here is pretty much in a state of shock,'' said
Jennessa Reed, 21, a resident assistant in the dormitory where the
crash's three female victims lived.
</P>
<P>
   In all, six college students died early Sunday when the
18-year-old driver of a pickup fell asleep and fatally struck three
men and three women as they walked to a fraternity party on FM 60
in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   Three women, all freshmen who lived on the same dormitory floor,
and a junior were from Baylor. The accident was especially jarring
to this 13,000-student campus because three other students
returning to school died in a car accident Aug. 19 during the
school's welcome week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, students also recalled a 1927 accident when 10
students were killed when their bus collided with a train en route
to Austin for a college basketball game. They are now known as the
Immortal Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Students are told about the incident during freshman orientation
and a candlelight vigil is held the Wednesday before homecoming
each year to mark the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reminds everybody of that,'' said Dawn Maple, a sophomore
photographer who works for the student newspaper, The Baylor
Lariat. ``I think it's made everybody pretty cautious. It's made us
all realize our own mortality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor students killed Sunday were: Tricia Calp, 18, of
Houston; Emily Hollister, 18, of South Bend, Ind.; Erika Lanham,
18, of Fort Collins, Colo.; and Dolan Walter ``Tripp'' Wostal III,
22, of Santa Fe, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Also killed were William Flores, 22, a Southwest Texas State
student from San Marcos, Texas, and Ted Bruton, 21, a Texas A&AMP;M
student from San Angelo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After word reached the Baylor campus Sunday morning, Wostal's
fraternity brothers at Tau Kappa Epsilon held a service Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers at North Russell Hall, where the three women lived,
sponsored a memorial later, attended by about 250 students. The
university's chaplain, Dr. Milton Cunningham, who spoke at both
events, said he was struck by the students' love for their lost
classmates and their difficulties rationalizing the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things you learn as you grow older is that life
takes away your answers, and that you just don't have all the
answers,'' Cunningham said Monday afternoon. ``And I told them it's
OK to say, `I don't know,' and `I don't understand.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But some of their friends saw them just hours before they
died. They have vivid mental pictures of them. It's going to take
them a long time to get over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Calp, Hollister and Lanham said the three were
seemingly inseparable, always happy and regular participants in
such sports as intramural volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were beautiful, beautiful girls,'' said Chrystal Ray, 19,
a freshman who lived two doors down from Calp and Lanham, who were
roommates. ``They were friendly. Every time I saw them, they had a
group of people around them.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, flowers, cards and poetry were stacked around Calp
and Lanham's second-floor room as a shrine to the women, Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Saha, a resident assistant on the floor, said she was
collecting similar materials for Hollister because putting them
outside the room would only further upset her roommate.
</P>
<P>
   At the family's request, the rooms have been undisturbed, so
relatives can see how the women left them.
</P>
<P>
   Staff at the residence hall plan to prepare scrapbooks for the
women's families as well.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 470-plus students who live in the all-female
residence hall wore memorial ribbons Monday, choosing white because
of their lost potential and as a way to remember their happiness, a
dormitory staff member said.
</P>
<P>
   A residence hall described by its occupants as vibrant and full
of life was quiet Monday. The spacious lobby was silent except for
the occasional hug or soft tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somber would be the word,'' said Saha, 20. ``People are
talking, but it's not like it was. My hall used to be lively, you
know, the music up loud. Not today.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is feeling the hurt, Ray said. ``You can see it in
their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wostal, who traveled to College Station with the three women for
a barbecue and to watch the Baylor-Texas A&AMP;M football game, was a
junior studying biology who planned to become a doctor, said Tau
Kappa Epsilon's Baylor chapter president, Brian Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternity was planning another memorial for the Baylor
victims and sent flowers to each family, Garcia said. Baylor
officials also were planning a schoolwide memorial but set no date
because the service will be after the four funerals.
</P>
<P>
   Like the women, Wostal was active, winning his weight class in a
recent school power-lifting competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tripp was a small guy with a big heart,'' said Garcia, who
wore sunglasses that failed to hide his tears. ``He's the kind of
guy who anyone would want as the best man at their wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he would have become a great doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
