<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER TO SIT VS. CAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One step might have cost UCLA so tailback
DeShaun Foster several games.
</P>
<P>
   Foster aggravated his sprained right ankle making a cut on his
only run of the Oregon game. He won't play Saturday against Cal and
is questionable for the Oct. 23 game at Oregon State. Most likely,
he'll return for Arizona the following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing that could have happened to me happened, the
turf gave out from under me,'' Foster said. ``I'm trying to stay
positive, but it's hard because I want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster has three carries in the two games since suffering a high
sprain (above the ankle bone) at Stanford on Sept. 18. Despite
daily treatments and minimal practice, the weakened ligaments gave
out on Foster's 11-yard, second-quarter run. He spent the rest of
the night on the bench with his ankle on ice.
</P>
<P>
   Without Foster, the Bruins will rely on senior Keith Brown and
junior Jermaine Lewis. Brown rushed for 182 yards at Arizona State
and the duo combined for 105 yards against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a missing link,'' Brown said of Foster's injury. ``When
one of us is down, it hurts the rotation. Me and Jermaine just have
to fill in for DeShaun and try to make all the big plays he makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's OK. I'm a senior. There's supposed to be pressure
on me. I go into every game thinking I'm going to be a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   __ He'd like to thank: Receiver Danny Farmer was named Pac-10
Offensive Player of the Week for his seven-catch, 196-yard
performance against Oregon. He's the first Bruin honored by the
league this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great heart and he knows how to compete, how to
win,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``He has a lot of intangibles.
He's not the fastest guy, but he runs away from a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer owns the UCLA record for career receiving yards (2,847)
and is 33 catches from Kevin Jordan's school record for career
receptions (179).
</P>
<P>
   __ Throw long, young man, throw long: Toledo responding to fan
criticism of his decision to throw deep on third down with 1:20
left:
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they had to score a touchdown to beat us. Everybody was
thinking we were going to run it. My thinking was to go for a big
one and put the nail in the coffin. We were going to have to punt
anyway. I felt we were playing good enough defense to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the pass) had been one foot longer, coach Toledo would
have been a genius instead of a bum.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Tight end Bryan Fletcher (strained groin) is
questionable for Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ali Abdul Azziz (sprained shoulder) and offensive
tackle Brian Polak (knee tendinitis) are probable.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Jason Bell will miss his fifth consecutive game
because of a painful right heel.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Farmer was named UCLA Offensive Player of the
Game. Jermaine Lewis won the special-teams honor (three tackles).
The defensive award went to the entire unit, which held Oregon to
one scoring drive longer than 44 yards. . . . Cornerback Ryan
Roques and guard Oscar Cabrera will join season-long selections
Pete Holland and Farmer as captains this week. . . . The Bruins
have won 13 consecutive home games, the longest streak in the
Pac-10. They also have won 11 straight conference home games, one
short of the league record set by USC from 1986-89. . . . Kickoff
for the Oct. 23 game at Oregon State, initially scheduled for 1
p.m., has been moved to 3:30. It will be televised on Channel 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
