<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-FLAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THEATER, GOOD NEWS, IF EARLY, IS BAD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The review was a rave, but the reaction to its
publication was not.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of a forthcoming Broadway show were crying foul on
Monday after Newsweek magazine violated a longstanding, if
unwritten, rule of theater coverage by running a review of a show a
week before its opening night.
</P>
<P>
   The review, written by the theater critic Jack Kroll, was of
``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour,'' and arrived on newsstands Monday
morning. ``The Royal Tour,'' a one-man show at the Booth Theater by
the Australian actor Barry Humphries, does not open officially
until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And while Kroll's review was generally glowing, the decision to
run it early prompted concern from the show's producers _ who said
the critic had sneaked into an early preview _ and the League of
American Theaters and Producers, who are worried about what sort of
precedent it might set.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the league said the early review ``disrespects a
tacit agreement that has existed between the Broadway industry and
the media for close to 100 years.'' It also added that such reviews
did a ``disservice to the customer'' because preview performances
are often works in progress that do not resemble the finished
product.
</P>
<P>
   In general, producers offer two or three dates, and free
tickets, for critics in the final week of previews. But Kevin
McAnarney, a spokesman for the show, said Kroll had paid for a pair
of tickets and attended a performance last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack called on Friday and said, `I have good news and bad
news,''' McAnarney said. ```The good news is I liked the show; the
bad news is the review is running on Monday.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at the Newsweek offices Monday, Kroll had little to say
about the decision to run the review early, except that the
decision was not his but was made by his editors. Sarah Petitt, a
senior editor who oversees the magazine's theater coverage, did not
return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Brunett, a spokesman for the magazine, said he did not have
specific details of why the magazine had chosen to break the
embargo, but defended the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry they're upset over such a positive review,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the theater league, Kylie Robertson, said that
the organization was drafting a letter to the magazine to protest
the decision, but that it was highly unlikely any sanction would be
imposed on the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Other denizens of the Broadway scene said the move was
surprising _ but not particularly worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is a bad precedent,'' said Alexander Cohen, a veteran
Broadway producer, ``that involves a good notice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-99 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
