<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martinez sparkles in relief, O'Leary homers twice to sink
Cleveland
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Cleveland Indians didn't just dare Boston's Troy
O'Leary to put them out of their misery, they double-dared him. And
he obliged both times, crashing a pair of home runs to lift the
championship-starved Red Sox into the American League Championship
Series for the first time since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's grand slam in the third gave the Red Sox a two-run
lead, then his three-run rip in the seventh broke a tie and ended
with a dull thud Cleveland's hopes of qualifying for the ALCS for
the fourth time in five years, a 12-8 exclamation point to three
days of administering cruel and unusual punishment to the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   And what a dubious conclusion for the Tribe, a winner in the
first two games of the five-game series. Needing one victory to end
it, the Indians were assaulted for 44 runs over the final three
games to become the second team to lose the last three games of a
Division Series after winning the first two _ matching what the New
York Yankees did in losing to Seattle in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove was determined that American
League batting champion Nomar Garciaparra was not going to destroy
his team, so O'Leary did the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Both times Garciaparra was walked intentionally with first base
open, O'Leary drilled the next pitch for homers _ the grand slam
off starter Charles Nagy and the three-run game-winner off Paul
Shuey.
</P>
<P>
   After the Tribe assaulted Boston starter Bret Saberhagen and
relief pitcher Derek Lowe for eight runs in the first three
innings, Boston manager Jimy Williams tossed caution over the wall
and gambled by bringing in sore-backed 24-game winner Pedro
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   It was like drawing a window shade in front of a voyeur. The
Tribe saw nothing the final six innings _ no runs, no hits, three
walks, say good night to the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   All that was missing in the first three innings were bellies
sagging over belts and cut-off jeans. It was a perfect imitation of
a slow-pitch softball game at a church picnic.
</P>
<P>
   After three, 15 runs crossed the plate and not one runner was
left on base.
</P>
<P>
   It was Cleveland 8, Boston 7, with Jim Thome smashing two
two-run homers that covered 904 total feet, but Martinez turned off
the tap the final six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's reward is an all-expenses paid trip to New York
Wednesday to face the New York Yankees in the ALCS, the defending
World Series champions. Boston hasn't been to the World Series
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
