r a !dlim!!shead!Sophomorere listedasprobablefor   10-11 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 !dlim!!shead!Sophomore recovered from injury, listed as probable
for N.D. !dlim!!by1! By  Scott Wolf  
!by2!Staff Writer!dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; It seemed odd that USC did not take tailback Malaefou
MacKenzie to Arizona last weekend, after the sophomore appeared to
have recovered from his hamstring injury. Especially after Trojans
coach Paul Hackett said before the game that MacKenzie was ready to
be eased into the line.
</P>
<P>
   According to several sources, MacKenzie was left home because of
a team-rules violation.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie, who has not played since the season-opener against
Hawaii, is officially listed as ``probable'' for the Notre Dame
game.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Chin up:!off! Hackett said he is not worried the Trojans
will fall into a tailspin after losing two of their past three
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the maturity of the team. We've got Notre Dame
and a whole half of a season left,'' Hackett said. ``It's a team
that's very, very distraught over seeing the chance to go to the
Rose Bowl fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``But stranger things have happened. You've got to play it out
because there's no dominant team (in the Pacific-10 Conference).
You don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Grain update:!off! Right guard Jason Grain underwent a
magnetic resonance imaging test Monday on his injured knee. Results
were not available, but he is expected to be out at least a month,
and might miss the rest of the season if torn ligaments are found.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Hard to watch:!off! Among those watching the Arizona game
at home was quarterback Carson Palmer, who is recovering from his
broken collarbone. He was particularly frustrated watching the
offense slump against Arizona's supposedly porous defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough watching them struggle,'' Palmer said.
``Seeing plays you'd like to be in on.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said he won't feel worse over not playing against Notre
Dame. The Irish were his No.1 choice in high school, but he was
told he needed to raise his Scholastic Assessment Test score 100
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be difficult but no more difficult than last
week,'' Palmer said. ``It's a game and I'd give anything to play. I
want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means he still doesn't want to redshirt. Palmer is wearing
a harness over both shoulders to help his broken collarbone heal.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!No major changes:!off! Hackett said he didn't anticipate
any differences in the starting lineup, unless injuries dictate it.
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterback John Fox took most of the snaps in Sunday's
practice, but Hackett said he was just getting work because he had
not played against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Position change:!off! Freshman linebacker Troy Polamalu
has switched back to weakside linebacker after playing strongside
the past few weeks. It's the second time he has played the weakside
position this season.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Denmon's back:!off! Hackett said center Eric Denmon will
be back at full strength this week after being bothered with sore
knees that caused him to miss the Oregon game and play sparingly
against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   USC also gets left guard Donta Kendrick (ankle) back this week.
Linebacker Zeke Moreno said his arm was sore but that he would be
able to play.!dlim! &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
