<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACKENZIE BROKE RULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It seemed odd that USC did not take tailback
Malaefou MacKenzie to Arizona last weekend, after the sophomore
appeared to have recovered from his hamstring injury. Especially
after Trojans coach Paul Hackett said before the game that
MacKenzie was ready to be eased into the line.
</P>
<P>
   According to several sources, MacKenzie was left home because of
a team-rules violation.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie, who has not played since the season-opener against
Hawaii, is officially listed as ``probable'' for the Notre Dame
game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Chin up: Hackett said he is not worried the Trojans will fall
into a tailspin after losing two of their past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the maturity of the team. We've got Notre Dame
and a whole half of a season left,'' Hackett said. ``It's a team
that's very, very distraught over seeing the chance to go to the
Rose Bowl fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``But stranger things have happened. You've got to play it out
because there's no dominant team (in the Pacific-10 Conference).
You don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Grain update: Right guard Jason Grain underwent a magnetic
resonance imaging test Monday on his injured knee. Results were not
available, but he is expected to be out at least a month, and might
miss the rest of the season if torn ligaments are found.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hard to watch: Among those watching the Arizona game at home
was quarterback Carson Palmer, who is recovering from his broken
collarbone. He was particularly frustrated watching the offense
slump against Arizona's supposedly porous defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough watching them struggle,'' Palmer said.
``Seeing plays you'd like to be in on.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said he won't feel worse over not playing against Notre
Dame. The Irish were his No. 1 choice in high school, but he was
told he needed to raise his Scholastic Assessment Test score 100
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be difficult but no more difficult than last
week,'' Palmer said. ``It's a game and I'd give anything to play. I
want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means he still doesn't want to redshirt. Palmer is wearing
a harness over both shoulders to help his broken collarbone heal.
</P>
<P>
   __ No major changes: Hackett said he didn't anticipate any
differences in the starting lineup, unless injuries dictate it.
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterback John Fox took most of the snaps in Sunday's
practice, but Hackett said he was just getting work because he had
not played against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   __ Position change: Freshman linebacker Troy Polamalu has
switched back to weakside linebacker after playing strongside the
past few weeks. It's the second time he has played the weakside
position this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Denmon's back: Hackett said center Eric Denmon will be back
at full strength this week after being bothered with sore knees
that caused him to miss the Oregon game and play sparingly against
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   USC also gets left guard Donta Kendrick (ankle) back this week.
Linebacker Zeke Moreno said his arm was sore but that he would be
able to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
